<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SIDEWALK RHETORIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere in the west 30s, in Manhattan's sequin and applique
district, a taxi idles, trapped in a box canyon of double-parked
trucks. There is not much to see from the taxi's windows except an
inaudible conversation taking place between two men standing on the
curb. The tall man is making a point. The short man is taking it.
The tall man's point is so forceful that it bends him forward at
the waist. The short man bends backward to avoid being toppled by
gusts of the tall man's rhetoric. A forefinger prods the air and
then the short man's breastbone. Being prodded, however, causes the
short man to stand up straight, causing the tall man to stand up,
too. The taxi moves on.
</P>
<P>
   This is a city full of the lecturing and the lectured, the
hectoring and the hectored, a city that loves to get things off its
chest and onto someone else's. To tourists _ soft-spoken people
raised in hushed surroundings _ the volume of New York's unceasing
colloquy often seems a little too high, the posturing that
accompanies it a little too dramatic. Dickens read it, in `Martin
Chuzzlewit,'' as the national braggadocio of a still-young city in
which there was no private discourse, only public perorations of a
kind that seemed both immodest and orotund.
</P>
<P>
   But the city has aged, and its conversation has become less
grandiloquent. It is fairly rare, these days, to come upon someone
in the street speaking, as it were, in the agora to an audience of
all comers. There is now a more intimate kind of declamation, which
must have existed in Dickens' day as well _ a man or woman pouring
words of bitterness or counsel, warning or contumely, into the ears
of a rapt or fearful or dismissive listener. There is a
familiarity, a peculiar neighborliness about such scenes that most
New Yorker recognize.
</P>
<P>
   For one of the things that characterizes a city is the timbre of
its speech, not only its accent but its force. New York is a
voluble place, as most of its mayors and many of its cab drivers
have proved. Many New Yorkers would never say boo to a mouse, of
course. But some days, when you watch a crowd of New Yorkers
shuffling impatiently past the visitors at Rockefeller Center on a
sunny lunch hour or striding up Eighth Avenue toward Port Authority
at the end of another day, it is hard to envision them without the
thought balloons cartoonists use bobbing above their heads,
balloons full to bursting with great swarms of ink-black words just
waiting to be loosed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
