<HEADLINE>
ROBERT S. BURGER, 84, JOURNALIST AND TEACHER OF CONCISE WRITING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert S. Burger, a former journalist and professor who later
spent more than three decades teaching business executives how to
write, died on July 5 at Chester County Hospital in West Chester,
Pa. He was 84 and lived in West Chester.
</P>
<P>
   Burger, who was a reporter for The St. Paul Pioneer Press and
The Courier-Journal of Louisville, Ky., early in his career,
entered the business of teaching concise, effective writing to
business people in the late 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, when he was teaching at the Amos Tuck School of
Business Administration at Dartmouth College, Burger was approached
by the American Management Association to create and give a writing
course for executives.
</P>
<P>
   Burger remained at Dartmouth until 1961, but demand for the
writing course became so great that he finally chose to leave and
form his own business, Burger Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 30 years, his clients included executives from
some 70 corporations and organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Burger encapsulated the course, which ran from one to three
days, in a book, ``How to Write so People Can Understand You'' (the
Management Development Institute), which was published in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very well-structured course,'' said Klaus Wagner, a
planning manager in the petrochemical division of Mobil Chemical, a
subsidiary of the Mobil Corp., who took the course a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one really said much about my writing except that it was
too dense,'' Wagner said. ``The course helped me to try and cut
down on that.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Burger taught the course by himself.
</P>
<P>
   But in the late 1970s he hired a friend of his son Robert Burger
Jr. as an instructor. The young teacher, Dave Barry, subsequently
went on to become a best-selling author and Pulitzer Prize-winning
columnist for The Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   In promotional literature for the course, Barry says it
``teaches techniques you won't find taught anywhere else,
techniques I use every day in my own writing.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of the Bronx, Burger enrolled in the City College of
New York at age 14 and graduated with a B.A. in foreign languages.
He subsequently earned a master's degree in journalism from the
University of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   A staff sergeant during World War II, Burger later joined the
Society of Friends and became a pacifist. He was active in the
civil rights and antiwar movements and remained involved in other
Quaker and human-rights causes.
</P>
<P>
   Burger is survived by his wife, Elisabeth, of West Chester; four
sons, Robert Jr. and Grant, of Thornbury Township, Pa., and William
and James, of West Chester, and 12 grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
