<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL KICKED IN THE CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France On the eve of the World Cup final, when talk
turned to who might make the greatest impact on the planet's
biggest stage, Mario Zagallo scoffed when Zinedine Zidane's name
was mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got lots of players like him,'' the Brazilian coach
said. ``France has got one Zidane, but Brazil has several
Zidanes.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, Zagallo was wishing he had just one, and one
was quite enough for the French, who used a pair of goals by the
midfield giant and another superb effort from their defense to make
history, routing the Brazilians, 3-0, to claim their first World
Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   Before an adoring audience of 75,000 at the Stade de France and
an estimated billion more watching on television France, by turns
brilliant and gutty, dominated the defending champions early, then
held on after losing its top defender, Marcel Desailly, to a red
card in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extraordinary,'' gushed Zidane, who headed home a corner
kick in the 27th minute and again nearly two minutes into
first-half injury time. ``It's fabulous. Words fail us to describe
our joy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after saying it 10 times, we can't believe it,'' added
reserve forward Christophe Dugarry. ``We could have won, 5-0 or
6-0. We played fantastic football.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a stunning defeat for Brazil, which expected an
unprecedented fifth World Cup crown, but instead endured a pregame
``trauma'' involving star striker Ronaldo, who apparently came down
ill before the clash but played because his teammates panicked when
they learned he wasn't in Zagallo's initial starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronaldo wasn't going to play he wasn't fit to play,'' Zagallo
said in a contentious postgame news conference. ``It wasn't a ruse,
it wasn't a trick. But the players were distracted and overwhelmed
when they found out he couldn't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think the team could overcome it, so I had to play
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo was on the field the full 90 minutes, but it didn't
help.
</P>
<P>
   With Franck Leboeuf proving an expert fill-in for suspended
sweeper Laurent Blanc, and the rest of the defense particularly
left back Bixente Lizarazu and defensive midfielder Didier
Deschamps closing off access to the French box, neither Ronaldo nor
his teammates provided much danger in what turned out to be a very
one-sided affair.
</P>
<P>
   France dictated terms from the start, and once Zidane was
through, the only mystery was what exactly was wrong with Ronaldo,
the acknowledged ``world's greatest player.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd had a nagging knee injury since the start of the Cup, but
Brazilian officials said his left ankle had forced him to seek
treatment at a hospital before the game Sunday. Then it was said he
had an upset stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates suggested the pressure confronting him caused a
breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was emotional,'' said wing-defender Roberto Carlos.
... ``At about four o'clock in the afternoon (five hours before
game time), he suddenly got ill. It was like a malaise had come
over him. It was strange.''
</P>
<P>
   How much impact it truly had is debatable. With Deschamps and
Emmanuel Petit winning nearly every 50-50 ball in midfield, and
playmaker Zidane weaving his magic, the French created myriad
chances and failed to score more primarily because of Stephane
Guivarc'h's inability to finish. Guivarc'h, who has epitomized
France's offensive struggles through the tournament, was provided a
trio of superb scoring chances, blowing all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``France dominated it completely,'' admitted Zagallo, who
Saturday said it would be a ``disaster'' if Brazil did not win.
``Through the first half, I was watching, thinking, `It's got to
end, it's got to end.' I just wanted it to stop, so I could make
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time that opportunity arrived, it was 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   On the first goal, from a Petit corner kick from the right wing,
Zidane stepped into an open chunk of space at the near post about
nine yards from the net, sharply nodding the cross past goalkeeper
Claudio Taffarel and into the net.
</P>
<P>
   The second was nearly identical. It came from the left, from a
Youri Djorkaeff corner kick; Zidane's header, from seven yards,
split Roberto Carlos' legs at the left post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to score a goal in this World Cup, and I scored two.
It's amazing,'' said Zidane, who had been indispensable for France
but hadn't found the net in the first six games. ``In the final,
too, and with my head, of all things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not very good with my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil tried to make a game of it in the second half, with
Zagallo bringing on Denilson, whose tricky ball handling sparked
several waves of attacks. Few led to anything concrete, and when
they did, goalkeeper Fabien Barthez was flawless. His best save was
on a Ronaldo blast at the right post from a Roberto Carlos throw-in
that got through the box in the 56th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Desailly's explusion in the 68th minute, after picking up his
second yellow card for a late tackle on Cafu, should have empowered
the Brazilians, but instead bolstered the French. Petit moved back
into Desailly's spot, and Patrick Vieira's appearance seven minutes
later, in place of Djorkaeff, regained France control of midfield.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil had just one more chance, a Denilson lob that kissed the
top of the crossbar, and then Petit put the finishing touches on
the victory, finishing a counterattack more than two minutes into
injury time.
</P>
<P>
   It made France the first new World Cup champion since Argentina
won in 1978, and the first host country to win since then, too. And
it rewarded an effort that, for once, had unified France, given the
country an identity that was real, that was current.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fabulous dream,'' Coach Aime Jacquet said. ``When I
think about all we've gone through, all the work done by this team.
A whole group of players has decided to make France happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
