<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLER KEYS QUICK START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Sparks got exactly what they needed Sunday: a fast start and
a solid finish.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Toler was responsible for the good beginning, scoring 16
of her career-high 22 points in the first half, and defense made
the difference in latter part of the game as the Sparks routed the
Cleveland Rockers, 87-66, before 7,032 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks (4-8) exploited the Rockers' zone defense by making a
franchise-high eight of their 14 3-point attempts. Toler, a former
All-American guard from Long Beach State, made 4 of 5 from behind
the arc, all in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found myself wide open,'' said Toler, who also had a
season-high nine assists, one short of tying her career mark. ``It
was like the parting of the Red Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Leslie had 18 points, 11 rebounds, and a career-high six
assists, while Tamecka Dixon contributed 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland was really testing us to see if we had some
shooters,'' said Sparks coach Julie Rousseau. ``We had some
wide-open gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penny Toler was aggressive tonight. She looked for he shot,
and when Cleveland went with the zone defense early in the game,
everyone stepped it up on the perimeter. Lisa adjusted to the zone
after a while also.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks never trailed since early in the first half (3-2),
and had a 42-36 advantage at the half. The Rockers (6-7) went on a
12-2 run to pull within 57-55 on basket by Michelle Edwards with
12:13 to go. But that's as close as they would get, as they Sparks
played great defense down the stretch, and outscored the Rockers,
30-11, the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks got quality production off the bench from Jamila
Wideman, who came in to score a season-high nine points and played
great defense late in the game against the Rockers' Suzie
McConnell-Serio. Another key was reserve 6-foot-3 Eugenia Rycraw,
who was matched up against against 6-5 Isabelle Fijalkowski. Rycraw
scored only four points, but had four rebounds and two blocks in 12
minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``However I can contribute to the team,'' said Rycraw, a former
All-American from Cal State Fullerton. ``Tonight, it was defense,
blocking out. It was a physical game, but we practice physical.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks forced the Rockers into 20 turnovers, while they
minimized their mistakes to 15. They shot 48 percent from the
field, including 57 percent from the 3-point line, and 83 percent
from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockers shot 49 percent from the field on the strength of
Janice Braxton (13 points), Fijalkowski (12 points), who has been
fighting the flu, Edwards (10 points), and McConnell-Serio (nine
points). But they were scoreless after McConnell-Serio scored with
2:22 to go.
</P>
<P>
   `They picked up their defensive intensity,'' Cleveland coach
Linda Hill-MacDonald said about the Sparks. `I have to give them
credit for that, particularly in the second half which caused us to
turn the ball over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks Notes: Pamela McGee gave an emotional spill to the fans
after the game, proclaiming, `The drought is over.'' The Sparks are
0-1 against the Phoenix Mercury (9-3), after losing 70-60 on the
road. The teams split last year. `Now we have to momentum going
into the desert tomorrow,'' Rousseau said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
