<HEADER>
A1664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BO     07-13 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX CAGED AGAIN BY BIRDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ So, after being swept in a four-game series in Charm
City for the first time in 37 years, in the same year (1961) that
JFK delivered his inaugural address, the Red Sox boarded a plane
for Florida, hoping to find refuge under the roof of a St.
Petersburg dome.
</P>
<P>
   Which, it should be noted, is less drastic than jumping off the
roof of the nearest tall building.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Sunday's 11-7 loss to the Baltimore Orioles, Mo
Vaughn said he is making it his personal mission to squelch any
hint of panic in the Red Sox clubhouse. First order of business
Monday, he said, will be to call a meeting in which he very well
may be the keynote speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Ask not what your team can do for you, but what you can do for
your team?
</P>
<P>
   ``We put ourselves in a good position,'' Vaughn said, alluding
to the Sox' one brief shining moment Sunday, when they scored more
runs in the fifth inning (six) than they had in the previous three
games combined (five).
</P>
<P>
   ``We got ahead,'' said Vaughn, whose two-run home run followed a
two-run double by Darren Lewis and a two-run single by Nomar
Garciaparra to give the Sox a 6-4 lead. ``We wanted to settle the
whole thing down, but it didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles worked out against Korean rookie Jin Ho Cho and a
cast of scatter-shooting Sox relievers, seizing the lead back in
the bottom of the fifth with four runs and taking advantage of
eight Red Sox walks and a wild pitch to pull away in the only game
in this set that wasn't decided by a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got to regroup,'' Vaughn said. ``We're gonna sit
down in the clubhouse and maybe have a little talk.''
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to Hong-Koo Lee, South Korea's ambassador to the
US who thought it important enough to come up from Washington to
see native son Cho make his second start for the Red Sox, the less
said about this one, the better.
</P>
<P>
   The Kid from Jun Ju City gave the ambassador something to brag
about at his next Beltway cocktail party when he struck out the
first two batters he faced, Robbie Alomar and Brady Anderson, and
set down six in a row. But Cal Ripken, like most of the other
Orioles as foreign to Cho as the room service menu in the team's
hotel, opened the third with a single, Chris Hoiles followed with a
surprise bunt single, and Cho was suddenly as vulnerable as any kid
who walked off a college campus one day to find himself in the big
leagues three months later.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis made a terrific running grab of Mike Bordick's bid for
extra bases for one out, and Alomar was caught looking again at a
third strike. But Anderson walked to load the bases, and Eric Davis
followed with a grand slam that ripped Lewis's glove off his hand
as he tried to make the catch at the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the ball hit my glove, but it was over the fence so
I couldn't see it,'' Lewis said. ``My shoulder hit the wall, and it
just jammed my glove off. But I did feel the ball hit my glove.''
</P>
<P>
   But even after the slam, Cho was three outs from qualifying for
his first major league win when the Red Sox put their six spot up
against starter Doug Drabek and reliever Norm Charlton, who threw
the hanging slider that Vaughn hit over the Mason-Dixon line to
make it 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Sox manager Jimy Williams sensed trouble, however, as soon as
Bordick drew a walk in the bottom of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball wasn't coming out of his hand the same way,''
Williams said. ``Our long inning might have had something to do
with it. I asked the umpire if Cho could throw a few extra warmups,
which he did, but I don't think he was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar doubled, Anderson singled off the glove of diving rookie
second baseman Donnie Sadler to score Bordick, and Davis accounted
for his fifth RBI with a sacrifice fly. That tied the score, and by
the time Ron Mahay was done with his three batters, the Orioles led
for good, as Mahay went walk, intentional walk, and two-run single
by B.J. Surhoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relievers didn't throw a lot of strikes,'' Williams said
dryly. ``You get behind in the counts, the walks hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles added a run off Derek Lowe in the seventh on three
singles and a sacrifice fly by Hoiles, and touched up Dario Veras
for two more in the eighth. Boston's only scoring outside the fifth
came on Vaughn's RBI single in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   So now it's on to a two-game set with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays,
the bottom-feeding expansion team that has lost 10 in a row after
being swept by the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Lost weekend? ``We move on and we're gonna play the schedule and
go to Tampa,'' said Williams. ``We can't look back. We've got to
look ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   And wait for Mr. Vaughn to take the floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1666 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-JIFFYLUBE300-BOS &LR;      07-13 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JIFFYLUBE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIFFY WIN FOR BURTON IN JIFFY LUBE 300 
</HEADLINE>
 300-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Jeff Burton, after just a bit of a rough start,
had worked his way up near the front and was following Winston Cup
points leader Jeff Gordon closely around New Hampshire
International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Burton gave chase for 10 laps, then 10 more. Stuck himself to
Gordon's backside and followed him another 10.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 80 laps into Sunday's Jiffy Lube 300, Burton made his
move. Gordon gave him just a little bit of room and Burton roared
past and pulled way.
</P>
<P>
   And that was that. End of race.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there were still 220 laps to go before Burton crossed the
finish line in his No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford ahead of Mark Martin
and Gordon and Rusty Wallace and collected his first victory of the
season and the $128,575 that went with it. It was a couple of hours
before he dusted them all by 7.439 seconds that might as well have
been 7 1/2 minutes and picked up first-place points in the race for
a season championship.
</P>
<P>
   But when Burton blew past Gordon _ barring a crash, a flat tire
or some other serious misfortune _ it was only a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   Martin knew it. Wallace knew it. Chances are everyone in the
field and most of the 90,000 auto racing fans in the stands and
suites and infield knew it.
</P>
<P>
   When Martin and Wallace and others talked about what they could
have done to improve their stock in the race, they usually didn't
even bother to think about catching Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff Burton was in his own field,'' Wallace said. ``He whipped
everyone's butt. He smoked 'em. No doubt about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Martin: ``We had a good day, we're chasing points. We just
couldn't beat Jeff. The last set of tires was loose and I just did
what I could with them. I saved 'em because I knew we couldn't race
with the 99.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton became the first driver to win back-to-back Jiffy Lube
300s, doubling up on his win here last July. He won with an average
speed of 102.996 miles per hour in a race slowed by six caution
flags covering 40 laps.
</P>
<P>
   He led the last 84 laps and 191 total and only lent out the lead
a couple of times when he went in for pit stops. Being dominant
felt great.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say it that often, but today, boy, things just went
right,'' Burton said. ``Four laps out of that last pit stop (with
about 90 laps to go), when we put on four tires, it was like we've
got it made.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Stoddard, the crew chief, and Buddy Parrott, the manager
for the Jack Roush-owned team, followed along on the radio from the
pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy and I kept prodding him to just be smart,'' Stoddard
said. ``I thought the computer was broken. He kept running lap
after lap after lap at the same speed. That was an impressive
performance by Jeff Burton. He's a super smooth race car driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton returned the compliment. He praised the work of Stoddard
and Parrott. He noted how he enjoys working for Roush, whose
expectations for the team are high.
</P>
<P>
   This was a win born of those high goals. A win born of what
might have been a season-saving race at California in early May,
with what might have been a weekend-turning assist to John Andretti
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Burton won three races last year and finished fourth in the
points and much was expected of this season.
</P>
<P>
   The team went to California a furstrating 16th in points and was
10th in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ugly,'' Burton said. ``What we did in California was
disgusting. It was well below expectations of what we want for
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   A meeting was scheduled for Tuesday morning and the gathering
went long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our heads back together,'' Burton said. ``Jack didn't
panic. Frank didn't panic. Buddy didn't panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton finished fifth or better in the next five races before
handling problems left him 39th at Sonoma coming here. He climbed
from 16th to eighth in points.
</P>
<P>
   They came here and thought they were running pretty well in
practice Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then John Andretti came up behind us and passed us,'' Burton
said. ``Frank and I got together and decided we had some work to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   They made some changes before and during the race.
</P>
<P>
   Their race started inauspiciously with Burton missing a gear on
the first lap and then tangling a little with Kyle Petty and
bumping with him down the backstretch. It ended gloriously.
</P>
<P>
   Burton stayed in eighth place in the points race, but solidified
his hold on the spot. Gordon held onto first and Martin and Dale
Jarrett slipped past Jeremy Mayfield _ who lost his brakes and hit
the wall with six laps left _ into second and third.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace strengthened his hold on fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're real happy with the race,'' he said. ``We gained some
points and that's what it's all about right now. We're trying to
win a championship. We're working at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
