<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERSS GET THAT SINKING FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-MARINERS-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By Ronald Tillery  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariners are trying their best to hang on. By the
looks on their faces, though, the strain of riding high one day and
low the next is killing them.
</P>
<P>
   Some days the Mariners look vastly better than a team with a
39-53 record. Then there are days like Sunday, when they suffered
an 8-5 loss to the Anaheim Angels before 32,797 at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the M's do these days, they can't escape that
sinking feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't (help) as far as the standings, but we're starting
to play better baseball,'' said Ken Griffey Jr., who went 2-for-3
and stole a base but did not hit a home run. ``That could lead to
turning the season around. We've got to do everything we can.
There's not one guy in this locker room who likes the position
we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had hoped to win their four-game series with
Anaheim before starting a two-game series with the Texas Rangers
Monday night. However, Sunday's loss earned them only a split. Even
though the defense is markedly better and the team's pitching has
stabilized, the Mariners are no better off than they were five days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   They stand 13{ games behind first-place Anaheim and 13 games
behind Texas in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   To a man, the Mariners realize that the later it gets in the
summer, the ``chances of making up that ground are not very good,''
said first baseman David Segui.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hole we're in (right now) is not insurmountable,'' Segui
said. ``We're very capable of (climbing into the race). We just
have to do it. That second game ... if we win that game, we've got
some momentum. Everything would have been different _ especially
after Randy (Johnson) came out and dominated (last Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson put the M's in position to win the series with a
15-strikeout performance. The M's won 2-0. However, they lost 5-3
on Friday night after coming back to tie the game and force extra
innings.
</P>
<P>
   That game served as another example of how the M's are running
in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're behind, a split doesn't do you very much,'' M's
manager Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey sat at his locker Sunday, clearly dejected by the
situation. He is left to ponder what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can do is go out and play,'' Griffey said.
``I can't call a meeting and just say `You guys are (terrible).'''
</P>
<P>
   M's starter Bill Swift (8-5) lost his first decision since June
16. Despite yielding seven earned runs, he suffered through just
one horrendous inning.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim sent eight batters to the plate in the second and scored
five runs on four hits. The most damaging blow came when Dave
Hollins sent a 1-0 fastball into the bleachers in right-center
field for a 3-run homer and a 6-1 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the Mariners nibbled away at the deficit. Rico Rossy
led off the third inning with a double and came around to score on
Alex Rodriguez's sacrifice fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners made the score 6-3 in the fourth when Dan Wilson
blasted his sixth home run to straightaway center.
</P>
<P>
   Swift allowed the Angels to manufacture a run on two hits in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, I thought I was throwing hard,'' Swift said. ``I
made the one bad pitch to Hollins and it turned out to be the
game-winning runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Buhner got the Mariners within 7-4 with his fifth homer of
the season in the M's half of the sixth. Then, second baseman Joey
Cora flexed his muscles in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Cora belted his fourth homer off reliever Shigetoshi Hasegawa
with one out, and the Mariners trailed 7-5. The Mariners scored
four runs off Anaheim winner Jason Dickson (9-6), who was chased in
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Swift lasted six innings before yielding to relievers Paul
Spoljaric and Heathcliff Slocumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swifty hadn't been out in a while. He was up with the ball
early, but he pitched well in the middle innings,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will send Ken Cloude to the mound Monday night
against the Rangers, who will counter with Todd Van Poppel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing better,'' Piniella said. ``We need to get on a
roll, though. We need to put together a little streak and go from
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
