<HEADER>
A1669 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      07-13 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MR. SNAPPER' PERPLEXED BY MR. SNAPPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ No fences were mended Sunday. There was no clubhouse
group hug, despite Ken Griffey Jr.'s playful but earnest request:
``Can't we all just get along?''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after their clubhouse scuffle, David Segui and Randy
Johnson still are not talking _ so forget the theory that Friday's
pre-game shoving match between the two Mariner stars released all
kinds of pent-up tension, especially for Johnson, who has been
riding a roller-coaster of emotion all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, it's created more tension,'' said Segui, himself
a highly charged sort of individual prone to his own fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, I'm a snapper,'' Segui said recently. ``I've never
broke any body parts, but there are guys I really admire. Paul
O'Neill. He's a good snapper. My favorite was Kirk Gibson, I loved
the way he played.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the scuffle, Segui missed Saturday's game _ which
Johnson won in Cy Young, 15-strikeout, shutout fashion. Segui
sprained his wrist, he said while lifting Johnson away from him and
sending the 6-foot-10 lefty into Segui's locker.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Segui spent the morning getting treatment on his sore
wrist. He then talked his way back into the lineup after manager
Lou Piniella had left him out, thinking another day off was in
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I mad? Hell, yeah, I'm pissed,'' Segui said, adding that
Johnson has not offered an explanation or apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't make a difference anyway,'' said Segui, who denies
saying or doing anything to provoke Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson has another side to the story, we won't hear it.
Johnson has refused all media interviews since mid-June, when the
Mariners pulled out of a deal that would have sent him to the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Segui envisioned about playing for the Mariners before
he signed his free-agent deal last winter, some of the luster and
wonder has worn off.
</P>
<P>
   Segui has had an All-Star-quality season. He leads all AL first
basemen in fielding percentage, carries one of the best batting
averages and RBI-to-at-bat ratios, too. But the season has twisted
into a knot of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been done,'' Segui said once about players-only meetings
that attempted to clear the air and create momentum for win
streaks. ``We're not going to talk about it, but it's something you
take care of in the clubhouse. You don't talk about it in the
newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   The altercation with Johnson is just the latest and most
publicized bit in a season marked by an enormous sense of under
achievement. And it is the thing that has raised questions about
just where the fire and leadership is coming from inside the
Mariner clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Even Griffey tried to respond to this issue. Sunday, Griffey
made an emphatic point that he tries to lead by example on the
field. He is adamant that as the most talented player, he feels
awkward demanding that his teammates turn it up a notch.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Griffey did intervene in the Johnson-Segui clash,
separating the two men, who still haven't resolved the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't understand the whole situation,'' Segui said
about the tiff with Johnson. ``If you want to fight, let me know
and we'll go somewhere and fight. But to just walk up and shove me.
I've always had quite a bit of respect for him. I understand his
frustration, in general about the season, but otherwise . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Although Segui denied that his wrist bothered him during the
game, the M's 8-5 loss to the Angels sorely lacked Segui's usual
productivity. Segui went 0-for-4, ending three innings (two fly
balls and one strikeout) that left five Mariner runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Segui's wrist didn't hurt him Sunday, the price of any
clubhouse burst of emotion is too high right now.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, who split the series with the Angels, wanted to
win at least three of the four games. This is crunch time. This is
about reclaiming some measure respectability and the Mariners have
barely a week or so to demonstrate some whiff of contending in the
AL West. It is no time for a breakdown or a flare-up, especially
between any of the team's best players.
</P>
<P>
   Segui said Johnson was one of the reasons he wanted to play for
the Mariners, since Johnson has been all but a guaranteed win to
this team in years past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this guy has done a lot for this franchise,'' Segui
said. ``He took this ballclub somewhere it never went before. I
respect his stance on that. And I always felt I wanted to play
extra hard when he's pitching. ... I wanted him to have a great
year and show the organization that by not signing him they made a
big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's win on Saturday only proved what Segui has known all
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the Randy Johnson I remember. All that talk about him
losing his stuff. That's all a bunch of bullcrap. I just think it's
the situation. He's letting it affect his play,'' Segui said,
adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he can step up. He's the kind of guy a lot of guys
look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of '98, emotions have been at a slow boil for
the Mariners. Now, the heat is on and there are two ways for the
M's to handle it: Fighting each other or fighting together. Only
one of the ways does justice to the level of talent in that
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 0122EDT &QL; 
