<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BECOMING A MATTER OF NATIONAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Think things are bad in Brazil today? There's
another country with a flag at half mast.
</P>
<P>
   Take heart, you citizens of Brazil. Red Sox Nation shares your
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing truly equates with losing the World Cup final, but the
followers of the Red Sox are frustrated and nervous.
</P>
<P>
   And now Mo Vaughn has called for a team meeting to stop the
bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Lost Weekend ended the only way it could end Sunday _
with another loss to the Orioles, this time by a count of 11-7. Sox
watchers now must deal with the fact that the purportedly
playoff-bound Townies have come out of the All-Star break with four
straight losses. It was Boston's first four-game sweep in Crabtown
since July 25-27, 1961. That would be Carl Yastrzemski's rookie
year, when Jim Gentile was Lord of Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a team that did not need a break, it was the
pre-All-Star Game Red Sox. The Sons of Jimy Williams were rolling
before the midsummer stoppage, and Vaughn says he'll address the
team before Monday night's game in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna sit down in the clubhouse and maybe have a little
talk,'' said the first baseman. ``We've got to put it all together
and get one win and take it from there. The main thing is not to
panic.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Vaughn's All-Star break contract news (he turned down
$37 million over four years) will be cited as the start of this
slide. When Vaughn was asked if he thought he'd get blamed for the
slump, he said, ``I really don't know how to answer that question.
I don't think anyone who's out there working, playing nine innings,
is thinking about my contract situation.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some hope Sunday might be the day the Sox turned it
around. They had Korean righthander Jin Ho Cho making his second
major league start. Cho's birthday is Aug. 16 _ the same date that
Babe Ruth and Elvis Presley died.
</P>
<P>
   The stars were improperly aligned. It's always a bad sign when
your center fielder loses his glove over the fence trying to snatch
an opponent's grand slam (see Darren Lewis).
</P>
<P>
   The Sox locker room had an international flavor after the game
as an interpreter translated Cho's remarks. We should have asked
for the Korean word for ``panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if Vaughn was auditioning for the Orioles for next
season, he couldn't have had a better series. Sunday he hit his 23d
homer, an opposite-field double, and an RBI single. Mo's homer was
his 13th at Camden Yards, more than any opposing player except
Albert Belle, who also has 13.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn has family in Baltimore, you know. And Orioles first
baseman Rafael Palmeiro is in the final year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but back to the business of preserving a wild-card spot. The
Sox will send Steve Avery to the hill Monday night against the
immortal Julio Santana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We move on and we're gonna play the schedule and go to
Tampa,'' said Williams, the Sox' cliche-driven manager. ``Good
things will happen. We can't look back. We've got to look ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   And like they say, Jimy, you can lead a horse to water, but you
can't make him drink. And only time will tell. Stay tuned. That's
life. Play 'em one at a time (yeesh, it's kind of exhausting trying
to talk like Jimy).
</P>
<P>
   The inimitable Jim Corsi, a Newton guy, advises Sox fans to
remain calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only had one bad game here,'' said Corsi. ``In three games
we had good pitching and we'll go as far as our pitching takes us.
It could be worse. We could be 10 games under .500. We've lost four
in a row before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy,'' added Darren Bragg. ``No one said we were
gonna run away with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   And Monday night Vaughn will try to calm everybody down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through this situation,'' said the slugger. ``I
just want to make sure everybody goes out and plays and does their
job. You can't play with pressure. I don't know if that's the
attitude, but you've got to make sure that we have the right
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox lost six in a row in May and bounced back with a pair of
wins against the Yankees. Now they've got two games in Tampa to get
straightened out before they come home to the place where regional
baseball panic was invented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
