<SLUG> BC-CAR-JIFFY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIX WASN'T IN FOR UNLUCKY CRAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
 LUBE 300-CRAVEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Ricky Craven had the pole position when the Jiffy
Lube 300 started at New Hampshire International Speedway Sunday,
but he knew there were problems early on with his Chevrolet when
oil leaked to the back of the car.
</P>
<P>
   He led for the first 13 laps before giving way to Jeff Gordon,
who was beside Craven at the race's start. Craven, who was born in
Newburgh, Maine, and has homes in Greenville, Maine, and Concord,
N.C., then dropped steadily. When the race was over, the
32-year-old placed 29th in going 295 of the 300 laps, worth
$46,950.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pretty much knew by looking at the tire wear that it was
going to be a long day,'' said Craven, who never has won a Winston
Cup race but qualified for the pole with a lap of 128.394 miles per
hour. ``We weren't going to fix it under caution. We're going to
have to rebuild the car.''
</P>
<P>
   First there was the oil leak, then trouble with the right rear
tire, and then the right suspension became faulty. ``It's something
that we had to live with,'' Craven said. ``It couldn't be fixed, so
we lost a lap in the pits (on laps 131 and 132). There was more
testing than racing. We battled some problems the first 25 laps on.
It was an education and we learned a lot. You can't rebuild a race
car on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Craven said the troubles could not have been predicted. ``It's
just a day where we had our struggles, but in the scheme of things
it wasn't bad,'' he said. ``Cars run like (his did Sunday), and
that's as hard as it gets. It's just another example of how
difficult this is.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Craven's first race in 3 1/2 months; he had been
suffering from post-concussion syndrome, the illness building up
over time. He said he felt fine Sunday, with the temperature on the
cool side for racers, at 80 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were really hot, it would have been an issue, but I feel
great, I really do,'' said Craven, who picked up $5,000 for winning
the pole. ``There's no question, though, that I'm a bit rusty.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't had many races with Tony Furr, his crew chief, just
five since Furr came over from the Cale Yarborough team last year.
``It's never predictable, but there's still a period of
transition,'' Craven said. ``It takes time to get used to each
other, to determine what we exactly need.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday was outstanding, however. On that day he gained the pole,
his third in 98 career starts. ``I had a wonderful weekend. I had
fun,'' Craven said. ``In some respects, Friday was the highlight of
my career because of how difficult it has been the last 3 1/2
months and how quickly things turned around in my first day back in
a Bud car. It was a big boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been about poles and wins, and we got a pole, but
we sure didn't have a good day (Sunday). But that comes with the
business. I'll guarantee there'll be some other days like this. You
never ever prepare for them. I was disappointed in the day, but we
have a pretty good understanding of where we're at and why we
didn't run that well. Then again, we shouldn't be judged by one
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Craven's next race in New Hampshire is Aug. 30, the New
Hampshire 300. He hopes not only to gain the pole, but earn the
checkered flag as well. ``I know what I'm going to say when I get
to Victory Lane,'' Craven said. ``I'm just going to have to save
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
