<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-HALLOFFAME </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAES WINS FIRST PRO TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ Once again the Newport Casino is Indian country,
and the new chief is Leander Paes.
</P>
<P>
   That's Indian as in sub-continent, from which the whirring
Calcutta Clipper, 25-year-old Paes, took off 15 years ago. Sunday,
on a grass runway, he finally landed at a long-sought destination:
a professional tennis championship. He was doubly delighted to take
the crown thrice worn by countryman Vijay Amritraj, the event's
most prolific champ (1976, '80, '84).
</P>
<P>
   In a sunny, sea breeze-tormented struggle of have-nots, Paes
became a have at last, in his 52d tournament start. He won the Hall
of Fame Championship over the tourney's escape artist, goateed
South African 23-year-old Neville Godwin, 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man had graced a final before, and Godwin, ranked No.
170, was worn and shaky after coming through three successive
three-setters. He had squelched a match point against American
Justin Gimelstob in the quarters and next removed top-seeded Aussie
Jason Stoltenberg in a third set tie-breaker. But Paes was
escape-proof.
</P>
<P>
   Lone American among three Aussies, Doug Flach of Atlanta,
grabbed the doubles in the company of Sandon Stolle, 6-2, 4-6, 7-6
(7-5), over Scotty Draper and Stoltenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of nervous, my first final,'' said Godwin. He
double-faulted eight times, volleyed erratically, and was ever
apprehensive of the swift patter of Paes's net-rushing sneaker
steps. Since chip-and-charge is Paes's curry and chutney, Godwin
knew that if he didn't serve well Paes would be at his throat. He
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Paes, a semifinalist the last two years, losing to the champs
Nick Perreira and Sargis Sargsian, had strong approval from the
gallery of 3,398 in his fourth visit to the Casino. His appealing
smile and demeanor, blended with a daring nature, have won him
friends across the world and charmed Atlantans as he seized an
Olympic bronze in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Victory lifted him from No. 120 to 103 in the world rankings.
``It had an extra benefit that I really wanted _ entry into the US
Open without having to qualify,'' Paes exulted. He also hopes it
will get him a wild card for the MFS Pro Championships Aug. 24-30
in Boston. His smarts and volleying have carried him much higher in
the other precinct, doubles, where his status is No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Paes, a compact 5 feet 10 inches, mixed foot speed with offspeed
backhand returns, crisp volleys, and forceful forehand passers to
keep the shorter Godwin reaching. Paes lost serve to 1-2, broke
back immediately and again to 4-2, ducked two breakers to 5-2, and
cruised.
</P>
<P>
   He thought back to his very first title, 1983 in Hong Kong.
``First time I left India. I was 10 and won the Rice Bowl
12-and-unders. The trophy, which I value, was a silver pendant, an
angel. A long way from that title to this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An angel, he said, may have been on his shoulder _ where he
landed _ in diving for a winning volley against David Dilucia (3-6,
6-3, 6-4) in the first round. ``I was down a set and a break point.
If I hadn't saved it with that volley, I'd have probably been
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   What a kick the day was for Paes, who wears a miniature silver
soccer shoe in his left ear, a good luck gift from India's national
captain Dai Chung Bhutia. He has done better than they, losing
early in World Cup qualifying to Korea.
</P>
<P>
   As a recognized name and face at home, one of his country's few
internationally prominent athletes, Paes was awakened much earlier
Sunday than he would have wished by phone calls from eight national
newspapers. ``I asked them to please let me sleep, and call after
the match. I'd try to have good news.''
</P>
<P>
   He had the best possible news _ that the
green-white-and-orange-striped flag amid those atop the Casino
seemed to be fluttering at its proudest because Newport was again
Indian country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
