<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1673 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TECH-HNS &LR;      07-13 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TECH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Tech let WR play 
in spite of memo
<TEXT>
<P>
   Readmittance violated rules, said NCAA
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DANNY ROBBINS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Texas Tech administrators allowed receiver Malcolm McKenzie to stay
on the field even after they were made aware of an internal NCAA
memorandum asserting he was readmitted to the university in 1995 in
violation of NCAA rules, newly released documents show.
</P>
<P>
   Tech administrators were made aware of the memo, written by a
senior official in the NCAA's membership services department, a
matter of weeks before the Red Raiders played Iowa in the Alamo
Bowl on Dec. 29, 1996, the documents show. Despite the memo, Tech
allowed McKenzie, then a junior, to play in the game. The memo also
did not dissuade the university from letting McKenzie play last
season, when he caught 42 passes for 462 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie's eligibility is perhaps the most contentious issue
under review by the NCAA Division I Committee on Infractions in its
deliberations regarding alleged impropriety within the Tech
athletic program. The committee heard the Tech case April 24 and 25
in Cleveland. Tech officials expect a decision to be announced
before the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   Tech has imposed a variety of penalties on its athletic program,
including three years' probation and scholarship cuts in six
sports, but the committee could decide additional sanctions are
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Tech chancellor John Montford, interviewed last week, said he
and others at the university were aware of the NCAA memo regarding
McKenzie at the time it was written but did not believe they were
bound to act as a result of it. Tech should not be viewed as having
acted irresponsibly, he said, because the memo was not an official
interpretation by the membership services staff and because the
university believed strongly that no violations occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you there may have been wrong decisions made at the
time, but I believe they were good-faith decisions based on
evidence and advice of counsel,'' Montford said. ``I don't think
there was any flagrant disregard of a memo or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The memo was included in the case summary prepared by the NCAA
enforcement staff prior to the hearing in Cleveland. Such a summary
is used to lay out the issues involved in a case and highlight the
areas in which the enforcement staff and the school under scrutiny
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   The enforcement staff included the memo in the case summary to
buttress its argument that NCAA rules were broken when McKenzie was
readmitted to Tech in the fall of 1995 and that the university
failed to properly deal with the matter when it came to light later
that year.
</P>
<P>
   The case summary was provided to the Chronicle by Tech on June
23 as a result of a request for the document under the Texas Open
Records Act that was made April 16. Names of current and former
student-athletes were deleted from the copy provided to the
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter of official inquiry submitted to Tech last October,
the NCAA enforcement staff described 18 areas of alleged
wrongdoing. The letter included two matters developed largely
through Tech audits _ widespread mistakes in eligibility
certification and calculating financial aid _ and 16 stemming from
a lengthy investigation by enforcement personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The university's response, made public April 14, showed Tech
agreed with all or portions of 10 of the enforcement staff's
assertions, including the charge tying former Raiders assistant
coach Rhudy Maskew to academic fraud involving defensive lineman
Stephen Gaines and the contention that Tech lacked institutional
control in the operation of its athletic program. The charge
relating to the McKenzie matter is among those disputed by Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's view of Tech's actions in the McKenzie matter
could be crucial to whether the university receives additional
penalties. Committee decisions typically are harsher when schools
are found to have been lax in dealing with potential rules
violations. Acting contrary to a memo from a representative of the
NCAA's membership services staff could be a factor in such a
decision, according to several administrators involved in NCAA
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Membership services, until recently known as legislative
services, is the branch of the NCAA that interprets the
association's complex set of rules. Some rules interpretations are
official staff opinions and meant to be binding. Others are
unofficial, intended only to serve as guidelines for those who
request them.
</P>
<P>
   The McKenzie memo was written by Steve Mallonee, an NCAA
director of membership services, and dated Dec. 16, 1996, 13 days
before the Alamo Bowl. It was directed to Dirk Taitt, the NCAA
enforcement director who has overseen the Tech investigation. Taitt
requested the memo.
</P>
<P>
   The case summary includes portions of the transcript from an
NCAA interview with Tech faculty athletic representative Robert
Sweazy on Jan. 29, 1997, in which the memo was discussed by Sweazy,
Taitt and Mike Glazier, Tech's lead attorney. During the interview,
Taitt acknowledged he had provided the memo to Glazier. He said he
believed the memo, while not intended to put Tech ``on notice,''
might help ``folks deal with the matters that we've all been
reviewing for some time now.''
</P>
<P>
   Responded Sweazy: ``We certainly disagree with Steve's
assessment of the situation, and if that's what the enforcement
staff is going to come forward with, we will disagree with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallonee's memo took the same view of the McKenzie matter that
NCAA enforcement personnel would take 10 months later in the letter
of official inquiry _ that Tech's handling of the situation
violated a variety of NCAA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie, placed on scholastic suspension by Tech in the spring
of 1995, was readmitted to the university that fall as a result of
an A for a summer American History course at San Antonio College
when he had earned a B. Because he had failed American History
during the first summer session, the A enabled him to complete the
summer with a 2.0 grade-point average, the minimum necessary for
his readmission to Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The professor, Thomas M. Settles, agreed to give the A based on
an arrangement in which McKenzie would do extra-credit work during
the fall. A Raiders assistant coach, David Moody, was aware of the
plan and helped facilitate it.
</P>
<P>
   When McKenzie did not complete the assignment, Settles rescinded
the grade and sent a letter to the Tech registrar's office in
December 1995 detailing the situation and stating his belief that
he had been ``conned'' by McKenzie and the Tech coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Sweazy and other Tech athletic administrators were aware of
Settles' letter before the Raiders played Air Force in that year's
Copper Bowl, but a review of the situation by Sweazy led him to
conclude there was nothing about it that should keep McKenzie from
playing in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tech withheld McKenzie from the first game of the 1996 season
but allowed him to return the following week. He continued his
career without interruption.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA alleges that McKenzie's A in American History
constituted special treatment based on his athletic reputation and
that Tech failed to follow its readmission policy in allowing his
return to the university based on a grade he had yet to earn.
Further, Tech stands accused of compounding the matter by failing
to act when confronted with evidence of possible infractions.
</P>
<P>
   Montford last week declined to discuss specific student-athletes
involved in the infractions case but spoke in general terms about
Tech's response to the Mallonee memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, that was not intended for us, and I'm not sure
we were supposed to receive it,'' he said. ``But when we did
receive it, it was reported to me that Sweazy or one of our
representatives talked to Taitt about it and that he indicated the
memo was not meant for us and we were not obligated to adhere to
it. I think I had that discussion with Glazier, as best I can tell
from my notes, and, based on the advice of counsel, we decided to
go ahead and allow the player to play because we felt like our
position was correct all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Montford said the issue was revisited last summer by Glazier and
Bob Burton, who became Tech's associate athletic director for
compliance in August 1997 and has since taken a job in the
University of Nebraska athletic department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you I have confidence in Burton and the
recommendation he and Glazier made,'' Montford said. ``I think Bob
went through that program like Roto-Rooter. I believe he made some
calls that were unpopular and against the grain. We supported him
all the way. This call was no different. We stuck with our position
based on his decision and the advice of our hired attorney.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
