<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-1STLD-     07-13 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO OBVIOUS ALTERNATIVE TO HASHIMOTO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 2nd graf to update with Hashimoto's resignation) (With JAPAN-eLECTION) 
(lh) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto may have angered his
own citizens and the rest of the world with his reluctance to
tackle Japan's economic problems, but if he seems lackluster, the
alternatives could be worse.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Hashimoto has resigned after his party's dismal
performance in parliamentary elections on Sunday, the leading
candidate to replace him is Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi. Obuchi
has never been tainted by scandal and has generally avoided
missteps, but analysts describe him as someone who could make
Hashimoto seem dynamic by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States and many Asian countries are desperately
hoping that a fresh face will emerge _ someone who will take charge
of the government and begin tough steps to revive the economy, no
one in Japan seems to see such a person in the wings. Obuchi
certainly does not fit that description, for even in a country that
has specialized in faceless leaders, Obuchi has had a career that
has not been memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obuchi has all the pizazz of a cold pizza,'' said John F.
Neuffer, a specialist in Japanese politics at the Mitsui Marine
Research Institute in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't be calling the shots,'' Neuffer added of Obuchi,
if he were to become Prime Minister. ``He'd simply be a puppet for
the party elders.''
</P>
<P>
   This is also true to some extent of Hashimoto and other
candidates who might replace him, but even by comparison to his
peers, Obuchi seems unusually colorless and malleable. He is
relatively little known in Japan and has never been associated with
major policy initiatives _ and it is unclear what he stands for.
</P>
<P>
   While Obuchi helped carry out some of Hashimoto's diplomatic
initiatives, such as warmer ties with Russia, Obuchi has been
largely a figurehead who made few decisions himself. Diplomats say
that he generally allowed the career bureaucrats in the Foreign
Ministry to make the crucial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of Obuchi serving as prime minister raises some
intriguing questions about the Japanese political system. Polls
indicate that people want leadership, but the governing party may
replace a prime minister who has exhibited little leadership with a
Cabinet minister who has demonstrated none.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this puzzle, say Japanese politicians and
analysts, is that in a virtual one-party state like Japan, the key
to rising in politics is seniority and congeniality. And Obuchi,
61, is extremely senior and congenial.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He succeeded his father in a parliament seat in 1963 and has
been there since, working his way up the leadership ladder. A
gentle, low-key figure, he has often played the role of a mediator
and now heads the largest faction in the governing Liberal
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   While Obuchi's lack of both charisma and obvious leadership
skills might add to the party's problem with voters, the
fundamental problem that it faces is that while Hashimoto is
unpopular, there is no one else in the party who seems a clear
improvement. Indeed, the lack of alternatives is what has kept
Hashimoto in office in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you take care of the situation after him?'' asked
Kiichi Miyazawa, a former prime minister, in an interview last
week. ``Without knowing that, they can't get rid of him. Who can
succeed Hashimoto under these circumstances? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, someone will have to succeed Hashimoto, and talk is now
turning to Miyazawa as a possible emergency replacement. It would
be highly unusual to turn to a former prime minister, and he is not
the kind of fresh face that the party would like. But he is
recognized as an expert on finance and economics.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa's term as prime minister was not memorable _ except to
Americans, who remember President Bush throwing up in Miyazawa's
lap during a state visit to Tokyo in 1993 _ but his expertise in
finance would bring some credibility to efforts to grapple with
Japan's economic troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Another contender is Seiroku Kajiyama, a veteran Liberal
Democratic Politician who has called for more aggressive efforts to
tackle economic problems. Kajiyama suffers, however, from an image
of an old-style political horse-trader _ just the image that the
Liberal Democrats are trying to shed.
</P>
<P>
   Kajiyama caused an uproar in 1990, when he was justice minister
and told a news conference that prostitutes were taking over and
harming a district in Tokyo. He said this was ``just like in
America, where blacks move in an area and whites are chased out.''
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate for the prime minister's job might be Yohei
Kono, a former party leader who has a fresher image than some of
his rivals but who like Obuchi appears to have more friendliness in
his belly than fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
