<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-REDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KONERKO CONNECTS FOR REDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If France could win the World Cup on Sunday, certainly
Diamondbacks pitcher Brian Anderson would finally win a game at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Oui?
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson took a 3-2 lead over the Cincinnati Reds into the
eighth inning and gave up a game-tying home run to Barry Larkin, a
past All-Star and present Superman, at least during this series.
Then, in the ninth, Alan Embree served up a two-run homer to
Scottsdale's Paul Konerko, and suddenly, the Diamondbacks lost
their fourth straight (and seventh in eight games), 5-3, at Bank
One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds have won seven in a row and 12 of their last 13, all
this coming off an 11-game losing streak that included a three-game
sweep by the Diamondbacks at Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 6-3 on the road but 0-5 at home, has never been more
upset with himself than he was after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one thing that I can't stomach in sports, and that's a
guy who chokes,'' the left-hander said. ``When you get to the
eighth inning with a lead, you finish it. I absolutely choked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not anything that makes my blood boil more than
choking, and I am A-No. 1 at the top of the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin, the veteran shortstop and a nine-time All-Star, led the
Reds' three-game sweep in their first trip to BOB. He had seven
hits _ three homers, three doubles and a triple _ and drove in
seven runs. His defense was equally as damaging to the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson didn't want to hear about anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horrible,'' he said. ``Absolutely horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitch to Larkin ``wasn't anything close to being a strike,''
Anderson said. ``But there's still absolutely no excuse for that.
It makes me want to puke.''
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed Embree came in after Anderson gave up a single
to Dmitri Young to lead off the ninth. The next hitter was the
right-handed Konerko, the Scottsdale Chaparral High School graduate
just obtained from the Los Angeles Dodgers. Diamondbacks Manager
Buck Showalter said that despite the lefty-righty percentages,
Embree was the right man for the job.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Konerko homered off Willie Blair, but Embree got
him out. This time, Konerko smacked a 1-0 fastball deep into the
left-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   Embree said was trying to pitch Konerko away to set him up for
something in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't hit my spot,'' said Embree, who was as down as
Anderson. ``It ran back over the middle of the plate. Good hitters
hit it out. I could have hit it out, for gosh sakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson pitched like he did early in the season, struggling
early and then getting sharper. Reggie Sanders led off with a
double in the top of the first. Chris Stynes sacrificed, and
Sanders scored on a double by Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Pokey Reese singled with one out, and backup
catcher Brook Fordyce doubled to make it 2-0. It was just Fordyce's
ninth RBI of the year. But then Anderson toughened up, holding the
Reds until the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring in just one of the previous 21 innings against the
Reds, the Diamondbacks tied the game in the fourth on a two-out
double by Tony Batista, who started at shortstop to give Jay Bell a
rest.
</P>
<P>
   In his next at-bat, leading off the bottom of the seventh,
Batista hit a solo homer to give the Diamondbacks a 3-2 lead. Which
could have been more, but the Diamondbacks, as during the entire
series, squandered an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   After Jorge Fabregas grounded out, Karim Garcia and Anderson
singled, putting runners on first and third with one out. Yamil
Benitez, pinch-hitting for Andy Fox, hit a short fly to right, and
Garcia tried to make it home. Stynes' throw to Fordyce was perfect,
and Fordyce and Garcia collided. Garcia accidentally kicked the
catcher in the head and shoulder, but Fordyce held on and Garcia
was out.
</P>
<P>
   Then Larkin and Konerko blasted the Diamondbacks into another
loss. That's what hurt, Anderson said, not that he has yet to win
at home. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
