<HEADER>
A1688 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ANNOUNC-BRENNAMAN     07-13 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANNOUNC-BRENNAMANS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLING IT LIKE IT IS RUNS IN THE FAMILY  
 BRENNAMAN VOICES ECHO IN PRESS BOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There are times when the most unpopular person in the
Cincinnati Reds clubhouse is Marty Brennaman. That's because the
veteran broadcaster tells the fans the bad along with the good, and
many players don't like his honesty.
</P>
<P>
   His son, Thom, the Diamondbacks play-by-play man, also isn't
hesitant to criticize when the situation calls for it.
</P>
<P>
   The two, who say they are more like very good friends than
father and son _ Marty was divorced from Thom's mother when he was
a youngster _ were able to spend some time together during the
weekend when the Diamondbacks played the Reds in a three-game
series at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``My style has changed a lot,'' said Marty, celebrating his 25th
year with the team, whose most-memorable moment came when Pete Rose
got his 4,192nd hit. ``I was a cheerleader because that's what they
expected. But I wasn't comfortable doing that. I remember talking
to (pitcher) Jack Billingham once, and I said, `We played well
today.' And he says to me, `What the hell did you do?'
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I adopted a philosophy. If it's praiseworthy, you
say that, but you also have the right to criticize. A lot of
players don't like me, but that's OK. I don't like all of them,
either. I don't want to be liked. What everyone needs is a degree
of credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   His honesty, he said, almost cost him his job in 1983, when he
was at odds with General Manager Dick Wagner. But it was Wagner who
got fired instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wagner told me to say it and forget it, but if a play in the
second inning determines a game, I'm not going to forget about
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thom's situation is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfair to beat up young players,'' he said. ``But you
can't accept it forever. You can say things like `will he be here
three or four years from now?' I'm not a homer, either, and even
with a young team you can be critical, and we have been critical at
times of some of the veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty, 55, has had numerous opportunities to leave Cincinnati,
but he says he plans to finish his career there, in less than 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Thom, 34, who came to the Diamondbacks from the Cubs, likewise
hopes for a lengthy stay in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   They have worked together only once, in 1995 on the Baseball
Network, when the Cubs beat the Reds, 1-0. (``That game stunk,''
Marty said.) They took turns doing play-by-play and color analysis.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't critique each other that day, and they say they
never will.
</P>
<P>
   Father and son share a pet phrase, ``Um, um, um,'' when things
go wrong, either at the ballpark or elsewhere. And the like-father,
like-son bond extends beyond baseball.
</P>
<P>
   In January of 1991, Marty developed polyps on his vocal chords.
That's when he quit smoking. Thom, taking a belated cue, quit
smoking a number of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That put the fear of God in me,'' Marty said. ``The doctor
said two things could happen. One, they could remove my voice box,
and I would never work again, or two, I could get cancer and die. I
quit smoking, and I'm more proud of that than anything else I've
ever done.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm just thrilled that Thom quit. But you know, he used to
steal them from me all the time. When Lou Piniella was the manager
of the Reds, he was the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Thom, who played high school basketball in Cincinnati, took care
of himself as a teenager, recalls Denise Seomin, a classmate who is
now media relations director for Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't know that Thom is an accomplished singer
and actor,'' Seomin said. ``He was a tenor in the chorus, and he
performed in school musicals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brennamans are one of a handful of families in the
announcing business on the big-time level, along with the Alberts,
Bucks, Carays and McDonoughs.
</P>
<P>
   Second-generation announcers, much like second-generation
ballplayers, aren't necessarily pushed into their fathers'
footsteps, but they often get there by assimilation.
</P>
<P>
   Thom says broadcasting was never in his plans when he was
attending Ohio University, but that the bug hit him one day when he
realized he didn't want to go a whole day without knowing all the
baseball scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no pressure from me at all,'' Marty said. ``But I do
view it as a tremendous compliment to me and my life's work. I've
seen way too many parents push their kids into things they didn't
want to do, whether it was being a doctor, a lawyer, or a
ballplayer. Kids should do what they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Thom remembers an early lesson: ``He taught me and my sister
(Dawn) to first be good citizens, and then be happy in whatever you
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
