<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-SPARKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY WARY OF SPARKLESS LA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If the Los Angeles Sparks played half as well as their
opponents speak of them, they wouldn't be in this fix. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Even after beating Cleveland, 87-66, on Sunday, the Sparks (4-8)
are eight games behind Houston (13-1) in the WNBA Western
Conference and five behind the second-place Mercury (9-3) going
into a game at 6 tonight at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks' home attendance dropped to a franchise low 4,851
last week, then rebounded to 7,032 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed inconceivable that Los Angeles, which finished so
strong in 1997 and almost bumped Phoenix from the West title and
the playoffs, could start this season like the last one. But the
Sparks actually are a game worse than in '97, when they were 5-7
after 12 games en route to 5-10 before closing with a 9-4 rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when they're going to wake up,'' Mercury center
Jennifer Gillom said.
</P>
<P>
   The wake-up call seemed to come six days ago, when the Sparks
came off a four-day break to beat Eastern Conference leader
Charlotte, 86-79. But they lost to Sacramento for the third time
this season, 76-71, the next night before taking three days off and
regrouping for the victory over Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Sparks' four wins are over New York and Charlotte,
which are a combined 3-0 against the Mercury. That and the
simmering rivalry between the clubs _ five games, all decided by 10
points or less, two extending into overtime _ creates a healthy
respect for a team that, despite its struggles, is only 2{ games
out of the fourth and final playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles is a great team, I don't care what their record
is,'' Mercury Coach Cheryl Miller said. ``They have too much talent
for us to think we're going to steamroll them. They have too many
weapons to look at and say we can't get beat. They're not a
Washington,'' which is 2-11.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks' arsenal, however, is depleted. First down was
first-round draft pick Allison Feaster, who fractured her right
foot three games into a pro career. The nation's collegiate scoring
leader remains in a cast and will be fortunate to return this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Three games later, 6-foot-8 Haixia Zheng tore cartilage in her
right knee that required arthroscopic surgery. Her return is two or
three weeks away. Zheng has not been a force against the fleet
Mercury, but she can be effective in half-court games, as in her
19-point effort in a victory over New York.
</P>
<P>
   All-WNBA first-team center Lisa Leslie and shooting guard
Tamecka Dixon are near the top in league scoring, and Leslie has a
league high nine double-doubles. But the supporting cast is
inconsistent, be it veterans Pam McGee and Penny Toler or
21-year-old Mwadi Mabika. Toler stepped up Sunday with her WNBA
career high of 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury, six games over .500 for the first time in its brief
history, spurted to a 39-23 halftime lead and won, 70-60, when the
teams played here June 14. Toni Foster, now out with a stress
fracture, played just 13 minutes because of an ankle sprain and was
scoreless in that game, throwing newcomer Michelle Griffiths into
the fire against Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths responded with 16 points in 31 minutes. The Australian
now has seven starts and ranks among the league's top 20 in
free-throw percentage and steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Sparks) can be 0-20, and you'd better be ready,'' said
Foster, whose buzzer beater won a game at Los Angeles last season.
``They are a dangerous and a good team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
