r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-FRAUENHE     07-13 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-FRAUENHEIM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG GAIN, NO RISK STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Criticism of Oscar De La Hoya's opposition goes to the heart of
boxing's remaining credibility and it also raises questions about a
manager's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has been credibility's last refuge in a game that
would embarrass Jerry Springer, who might as well be a matchmaker
these days.
</P>
<P>
   But his victory over Patrick Charpentier belongs right there in
the garbage with Mike Tyson-Peter McNeeley and the projected Larry
Holmes-George Foreman bout, a Viagra special.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, De La Hoya's drawing power suffers no erosion. A more
significant number than the 45,000 people at El Paso's Sun Bowl for
the Charpentier demolition is Home Box Office's 12.0 rating, a
network high that amounts to 3 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   Those are convincing factors, especially if you happen to be De
La Hoya's manager/promoter``'' Bob Arum. The business-based credo
is simply this:
</P>
<P>
   Maximum profit for minimum risk.
</P>
<P>
   Still, De La Hoya is ripped for not fighting the best
welterweights _ Felix Trinidad, Ike Quartey and Jose Luis Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, he can make nearly as much money in fights that are
perceived to be less of a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at all of this, I know I don't need any other
fighter,'' De La Hoya said. ``Personally, I want a Trinidad or a
Quartey, but I don't need them.''
</P>
<P>
   The counter is that De La Hoya needs the fans, many of whom will
inevitably tire of their favorite fighter against one punching bag
after another. Fair enough.
</P>
<P>
   The other argument is that he owes something to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   If the payback is in scrambled brains, boxing never quits
paying. It's also easy and cynical for some fans to say fighters
are in their debt. HBO or pay-per-view is cheap compared to the
risk of one day living with a head that works like cauliflower.
</P>
<P>
   The choice ultimately belongs to De La Hoya. He, and Arum, are
wealthy, regardless of the decision.
</P>
<P>
   But great?
</P>
<P>
   Only if he chooses to take that risk, says longtime Valley
manager/promoter Steve Eisner, who is guiding the young careers of
heavyweight Paea Wolfgramm and cruiserweight Sione Asipelli.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a right to be careful on the way up,'' Eisner said.
``But once you're champ, isn't the public defrauded when you don't
have tough fights? You can have an easy one. But where's the tough
one?
</P>
<P>
   ``De La Hoya fought second-rate fighters to be a champion and
second-rate fighters to stay a champion.'' &QL; 
A cancellation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The traveling sales job by De La Hoya and``'' Julio Cesar Chavez
for a Sept. 18 rematch was KO'd last week. An eight-city tour was
scheduled to stop Thursday at the Valley's Celebrity Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Money was a factor. The journey would have cost $500,000. Each
fighter would have traveled in separate jets at $84,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, one jet wasn't enough. De La Hoya and Chavez
genuinely dislike each other. At 30,000 feet, De La Hoya would have
bloodied Chavez just as surely as he will at sea level. &QL; 
Briefly &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An interesting pro debut by Phoenix bantamweight Homero Sierra
is planned for Tuesday night at Midnight Rodeo, a club near 32nd
Avenue and Indian School Road. Sierra was runner-up in the national
Golden Gloves. Opening bell is scheduled for about 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _De La Hoya echoes: Evander Holyfield is hearing doubts about
his willingness to face a taller opponent. Why? He is asking for
$25 million to fight Lennox Lewis, who possesses some of the
Riddick Bowe-like reach and height that often troubles Holyfield.
HBO's current offer is $20 million. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Norm Frauenheim can
be reached at 444-8259 or norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
