<HEADER>
A1692 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTES-AZR &LR;      07-13 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWALTER'S COLLEGE COACH PAYS A VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 and MARK ZUCKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The 1998 USA National Baseball Team visited Bank One
Ballpark on Sunday prior to leaving for the World Championships in
Italy on July 19-Aug. 3. Arizona State's Willie Bloomquist and
Arizona's Keoni DeRenne are on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Polk is the coach. Polk for many years was head coach at
Mississippi State, where in 1977 he had a player named Nat
Showalter, who later became known as ``Buck.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter played just one season but owns the highest lifetime
average in school history (.459).
</P>
<P>
   ``He tells people that (Will) Clark and (Rafael) Palmiero are
2-3 in hitting at Mississippi State,'' Polk said. ``He just waits
for someone to ask him who's number one.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter ``looks the same,'' Polk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't changed that much. He was a very intelligent
baseball player. He came back and got his degree. He made that
commitment. He was very serious about the game.'' &QL; 
Don't ask, don't tell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showalter gave shortstop JayBell and All-Star center fielder
Devon White the night off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Devo's All-Star break,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was another reason _ Reds starter Pete Harnisch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to tell him that he's 0 for 17 against
Harnisch,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   We won't, either. &QL; 
Musical chairs &QL; 
With rookie Danny Klassen now looking like a permanent fixture at
second base, Andy Fox is a man without a position. That doesn't
mean, however, that Fox is not still a regular in Showalter's book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough making out a lineup without him in there,''
Showalter said. ``We're going to try to find a spot for him in
there.'' &QL; 
Streak rolls on &QL; 
Tony Batista's fourth-inning double extended the Diamondbacks'
streak of consecutive games with at least one extra-base hit to 78,
tops in the National League. Only Cleveland's string of 89 is
longer in the majors. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
