<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-KONERKO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KONERKO SHOWING SIGNS OF PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - He came, he saw, he conquered, which was a far cry
from Paul Konerko's visit to Bank One Ballpark earlier this year
with the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Then, his family and friends were in attendance, but a
struggling Konerko was a no-show except for pre-game batting
practice.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the case Sunday night, however, as the former
Scottsdale Chaparral High School star treated the 50-strong
contingent of family and friends to a big show.
</P>
<P>
   The first baseman went 3 for 4 and stroked a game-winning
two-run homer deep into the left-field seats in the ninth inning as
the Cincinnati Reds completed a three-game sweep of the
Diamondbacks with a 5-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The homer, his second in two nights since being traded to the
Reds by the Dodgers, came off reliever Alan Embree. It raised
eyebrows because Diamondbacks skipper Buck Showalter bucked
baseball's sainted percentages by bringing in the left-handed
Embree to face the right-handed Konerko.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't surprised,'' Konerko said. ``He's a good pitcher
who's in the big leagues because he throws in the mid-90s (mph).
When a guy throws that hard, it pretty much takes the lefty vs.
righty thing out of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell the truth, the homer was probably more him than me. I
didn't swing that hard at it. He supplied the power. When a guy
throws that hard, you know it's his pitch. I just looked for it in
an area, and he got it right there.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade sent closer Jeff Shaw to the Dodgers for Konerko and
southpaw pitcher Dennis Reyes. Now Reds Manager Jack McKeon has to
figure out what to do with Konerko.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles didn't know what to do with him, either,'' McKeon
said. ``He played first, third and outfield for them. We don't know
where we're going to play him, either. He'll probably play third
base (today) against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose we'll audition him all over until we figure it out.
He's a good young player, but I don't think anybody is ready to put
Paul Konerko into the Hall of Fame yet. He's going to struggle at
times, but he's a good player, and we'll find a place for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Konerko, baseball's Minor League Player of the Year after
battling .323 with 37 home runs with Albuquerque last season,
doesn't care where he plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whichever one gets me into the lineup,'' said Konerko, who
upped his average to .229 with Sunday's solid showing. ``I'd like
to settle down and play one position because that's the way you get
good at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for now, I'm willing to bounce around and do whatever they
want. I'm under a mind-set to just swing the bat well and produce
as a hitter. If I do that, they'll find a place for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Konerko put so much pressure on himself in Los Angeles to live
up to the ``can't miss'' label that he had trouble hitting his
weight (211) early in the season. He came to Cincinnati with a
different outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought before I came here that if I didn't get off to a
good start, not to press because I'll probably get my at-bats here,
regardless of how I'm doing,'' he said. ``It's probably why I had
such a good series. I knew if I didn't do well, it wouldn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two games doesn't make a season for a team or a player, but
first impressions are important in baseball. I got off to a bad
start in Los Angeles, and I think because I struggled at the
beginning, they didn't want to give me that good second chance.
Hopefully, I won't have to worry about second chances here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
