<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-ARENA-RATTLERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATTLERS CONFRONT 2 GAMES IN 4 DAYS  
 ALBANY'S 3-LOSS STREAK MISLEADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rattlers' weird and wacky schedule will continue tonight
with a rare Monday game in Albany, N.Y., then a Thursday game at
home against the New York CityHawks.
</P>
<P>
   They've had 11 days to get ready for this. That worries Coach
Danny White, even though his wounded warriors needed the rest.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they've done better on the shorter weeks, easily winning
two Thursday games on the road after playing on a Saturday or a
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more adversity they face, the better team they are,''
White said. ``We're starting to see that. You always wonder what
kind of personality your team will have. When we have a full week,
everyone is rested. That's when we struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go on the road after three days rest, all beaten up, we
don't have a fullback, and we blow a team out. How do you explain
that? It forces you to focus more.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened July 2 in Grand Rapids, where the Rattlers
(8-2) got a ton of breaks and whipped the Rampage, 69-27, for their
largest rout of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Now they face a team similar to the one they played June 20,
when they lost at home to the Orlando Predators, 42-40. Orlando
came in having lost three of four but put together one of its best
games.
</P>
<P>
   Albany's three-game losing streak is its longest in six years.
Its offense is almost as potent as the Rattlers', with quarterback
Mike Pawlawski and offensive specialist Eddie Brown putting up
similar numbers to the Rattlers' Sherdrick Bonner and Calvin
Schexnayder.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had some weird things happen to them in games,'' White
said. ``They should have won two of the three games.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those lost opportunities was last week, when the
Firebirds (6-4) blew a lead in the final minute, then came up a
yard short of the goal line as time expired in a 55-48 loss to
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a danger playing a 6-4 team,'' White said. ``You think
6-4, so they must not be one of the top teams. But they're better
than that. We thought they had the best pass rush in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's the third-best, with 16 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   That presents a challenge to the Rattlers' line, which hasn't
allowed a sack of Bonner in two seasons. Bonner's quick reads and
mostly three-step drops keep him from getting dumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot you can to do to rush that, but you can try
to deter it,'' Firebirds Coach Mike Dailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner passed just 18 times against Grand Rapids. The Rattlers
ran the ball 17 times for a team record 94 yards. The big lead
allowed them to keep the ball on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have that kind of yardage against every team, but it
helps your confidence to know you can run the ball,'' White said.
``The line is starting to develop a rapport.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers know they can't count on another wild array of
breaks. In Grand Rapids, they scored a touchdown off the net on a
kickoff, another on an interception and a third on a fumble
recovery, all in a matter of two minutes, to break open a close
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got all the breaks,'' White said. ``I was kind of sitting
there and hoping, `Let's not use them all up in one game. Let's
save some of those turnovers. Those will be critical against a
really good team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Good teams, however, don't usually make so many mistakes. And
White doesn't expect Albany to be so generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hungry for a win, and we'll have our work cut out,''
he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
