<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Congressional fix: Save the flag, burn the First Amendment
 &HT;    ATTN: Editorial, Op-Ed Page editors
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hey, kids, I've got a swell idea. Let's get a lot of people to
burn American flags. Then we can have a bunch of political trials
and send people to prison and then there'll be protest rallies to
free, like, the Austin 3 or the Washington 7 or Dayton 4 and _
well, wow, it'll be just one long show.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, yes, I know the problem. Almost nobody is burning flags. As
near as anyone can tell, only five did all last year, and when they
do, nobody makes a big deal out of it, so the show-offs quickly go
the way of their own smoke.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a surefire way to get a lot of new flag-burning
going: fix the U.S. Constitution so the free-speech thing in the
Bill of Rights won't cover it any more. Then the states can begin
making flag-burning a big-time crime. You can bet they will, and
maybe Congress will even make it a federal crime, so the FBI can be
called in.
</P>
<P>
   That will raise the stakes way up and make flag-burning a major,
major political act. All you'll have to do to call huge attention
to yourself or to your cause is fire up a flag, stand back and let
the fame pour in.
</P>
<P>
   Well, good news. It looks like the U.S. Senate is getting ready
to set all that up, maybe this fall. The House has already approved
an amendment and 49 states have passed resolutions begging for a
chance to ratify it. Getting two-thirds of the Senate to nail the
deal shouldn't be tough in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment is real simple: ``The Congress shall have the
power to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   You know, that might set off even more fun than Congress
imagines, since nobody knows just what desecration means, legally.
The dictionary says desecrate means ``to treat irreverently or
contemptuously often in a way that provokes outrage on the part of
others.''
</P>
<P>
   So those kids who sew flag patches on their ratty jeans could
find themselves going up the river, and you folks who plop barbecue
on paper-plate flags on the Fourth of July could wind up doing a
little time, too, though I'm sure you won't mind because it will
make you more patriotic.
</P>
<P>
   And the courts can have a lot of sport figuring out what a flag
is. Is it only the cloth version you buy at a store? Or what if
somebody draws a big paper picture of a flag and burns that? And
what will the courts make of the ``Flag-Burning Page'' on the
internet, where you can burn a virtual flag? Will you go to virtual
jail?
</P>
<P>
   With luck, taking this first-ever nick out of the First
Amendment will be just the start of some real changes. Patriotism
deserves all the help politics can give it. Shouldn't there be a
law to stop comedy groups from writing parodies of the National
Anthem and singers from rocking it or giving it a soul twist or a
Latin turn? Is this a nation or a mosh pit?
</P>
<P>
   And there are few more sacred symbols of our nationhood than the
Statue of Liberty, but over the years, editorial cartoonists have
done the grossest things to our Lady Liberty. Does anyone seriously
doubt the nation would be better off if it were swept clean of
editorial cartoonists?
</P>
<P>
   By the way, there's a ``Burn the Flag Burners!'' web page, too.
I'm afraid freedom is sometimes messy, and will be till Congress
cleans it all up for us.
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail:teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
