<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     07-13 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDING ON GREED AND ANTI-ENVIRONMENTAL SENTIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1998 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the '40s, a person learned that to ride the rails
successfully, he must be quick and quiet lest a railroad bull crack
his skull and toss him off the moving freight. Quick and quiet are
also the hallmarks of a rider successfully attached to an
appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   There are 13 appropriations bills that will be signed into law
by the end of September in order to keep the government open for
business.
</P>
<P>
   They're sure bets.
</P>
<P>
   A bill that must be passed _ like an appropriations or a highway
spending bill _ is called ``A train'' in the vernacular of those
who work the halls and floors in both houses of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A rider attached to a ``must pass'' bill doesn't go through the
usual hearing process that a proposed piece of legislation faces.
</P>
<P>
   The normal legislative process is designed to be deliberative.
Passing a bill into law takes time. Hearings are held. Concepts and
language are debated. Those who object to the proposed legislation
are purposely brought into the debate. A bill may successfully pass
through subcommittee hearings, then full committee debate, and
finally to a floor vote in one of the houses of Congress and yet be
defeated because of inherent weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate can each pass a separate version of a bill.
A compromise bill is then hammered out and voted on again.
</P>
<P>
   Other versions of an unsuccessful bill may come back the
following year, and the year after that _ until it has eventually
accommodated some of the criticism, ideas and language of those who
opposed it. Or it may be dropped altogether. It often takes five or
six years to create an effective piece of legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative process is supposed to allow time for debate in
both houses of Congress. The process responds to special interest
groups and watchdog organizations. Most importantly, it allows time
for the public to let its feelings be known. Dialogue is essential.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for riders. They may not face any debate, merely a
cursory vote.
</P>
<P>
   Throw a rider onto a fast moving train. An appropriations bill
moves relatively quickly. Many riders aren't subject to any
scrutiny _ either by the public or by our elected representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriations bills are huge, hundreds of pages long _ a rider
can be easily secreted.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason that some of these riders are kept hidden from
the public _ they smack of smarmy deceit. They couldn't stand up to
open debate; they'd shrivel up like snails in a salt storm.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the House GOP leadership pushed to attach an anti-gay
rider to the Treasury-Postal Appropriations bill, and later
attached a rider to the agricultural spending bill that would block
the Food and Drug Administration from using federal funds to test,
develop, or approve any drug that would induce an early abortion,
including the French pill, RU-486.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these riders concern issues that should have been
debated on their own merits and been introduced in the proper
committee where hearings could be held. The riders bypassed the
more democratic pathway.
</P>
<P>
   Public scrutiny was sidetracked.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Appropriations Committee attached a rider to the
Interior Appropriations bill that will delay new federal and Indian
oil valuations regulations until Oct. 1, 1999. The regulations
would help ensure that the American taxpayer receives a fair market
value for oil taken from federal lands. This little tactic _ unless
the rider is stripped from the bill _ will cost the taxpayer more
than $66 million per year in royalty payments and cost state public
school systems a large portion of that. Indian tribes will lose an
estimated $4 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   The oil valuations rider was proposed by Sens. Kay Bailey
Hutchinson, R-Texas, and Pete Domenici, R-N.M., _ both receive a
huge hunk of their campaign contributions from the oil and gas
industry. They pocket the dough; our children's schools suffer. The
Interior's Minerals Management Service estimates that Wyoming
public schools will lose $770,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Avarice rides again. Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., attached a rider
to the Interior bill to halt the review of current hardrock mining
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   It would effectively delay mining reform. No surprise: Reid
receives a large chunk of his campaign funds from the mining
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Riders are stealth legislation. No debate. No time for the
public to react. No time for those who oppose the rider to mobilize
their forces.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes riders are attached to a bill at 4 in the morning.
Who's watching our elected representatives at that hour? The rider
process can be intentionally, resolutely anti-democratic.
</P>
<P>
   A peek at the 20-plus anti-environmental riders attached to
either the House or Senate Interior Appropriations bills shows no
real surprises.
</P>
<P>
   It's deja vu all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska's entire congressional delegation, Sens. Frank Murkowski,
Ted Stevens, and Rep. Don Young, are once again attacking the
Tongass National Forest, wilderness and wildlife refuges in their
state with road construction, helicopters, timber sales and
giveaways of federal lands.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., attached a rider that would block
the reintroduction of grizzly bears into the Selway-Bitterroot area
of Idaho and Montana _ an important species recovery plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., is once again attacking American
Indian tribal sovereign immunity and self-determination. Sen. Mike
Enzi, R-Wyo., is once again pushing to limit a tribe's right to
establish gambling on its lands. And Rep. Ernest Istook, R-Okla.,
is using a rider to force tribal governments to pay state and local
sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Stream beds are sensitive to grazing cattle. One rider forces
the Bureau of Land Management to automatically renew grazing
allotments in 1999 whether or not poor land-use practices cause the
destruction of fish habitat, or riparian areas.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of these riders reveals a congressional leadership
driven by anti-gay, anti-Indian, and anti-environmental sentiment.
They leave the president with no choice but veto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
