</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1950 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDWARD-BURNS-INTERVIE     07-13 1629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDWARD-BURNS-INTERVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST EDDIE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine _
the rate is not prohibitive _ contact one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     (-----They also have information on how to subscribe to ``HIGH
STYLE AND MORE,'' a complete lifestyle and entertainment package
composed of stories _ with accompanying B&AMP;W and color art _ from
numerous publications issued by Fairchild Publications.-----) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``e'' entertainment news files.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: One color slide and one B&AMP;W photo are available FREE OF
CHARGE.)  
 &HT;    
 By JULIE L. BELCOVE 
 c.1998 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When Edward Burns arrived in Ireland last summer to begin
filming ``Saving Private Ryan,'' he was feeling pretty good _ if
not downright cocky.
</P>
<P>
   Who could blame him? He had just wrapped his third movie as
writer, director and star, and Steven Spielberg had cast him in the
World War II epic without an audition.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Burns had landed the part of a wisecracking soldier
without so much as taking a meeting with the most powerful man in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   His first day on the set went off without a hitch. It was the
second day that knocked the wind out of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, it was absolutely terrifying,'' Burns
remembers. ``It was this big, long scene with me and Tom Hanks
going toe to toe. I had to sort of get in his face. We did a bunch
of takes, and it was great, and I felt really good, and then Steven
said, `I want to try one more angle.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing the take, and it's going great, and I forget my
line near the end of the scene, and I think, 'Oh damn,''' he
continues. ``We do it again, and I screw up the line. Now, I see
Steven's concerned because we're running out of light, and then it
hits me: Oh my god, that's Steven Spielberg, this is Tom Hanks, and
I'm screwing up.''
</P>
<P>
   On take three, Burns choked again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hanks was just like, 'Eddie, calm down. You can do this,''' he
says. ``And then it was fine. I got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns likes to joke that watching Spielberg at work on ``Saving
Private Ryan'' was his graduate degree in film.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was feeling like I knew anything about filmmaking,'' he
says, ``that sort of woke me up to how much I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   In the three years since he became an instant sensation at the
Sundance Film Festival _ shocking the movie industry by taking home
the Grand jury Prize for his debut film, ``The Brothers McMullen''
_ Burns has parlayed the hype into a career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brothers McMullen,'' shot for a paltry $25,000, went on to
gross more than $10 million, making it, percentage-wise at least,
the most profitable movie of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the 30-year-old actor has filmed ``She's the One,''
a kind of McMullen redux with one fewer brother and a $3 million
budget, and ``No Looking Back,'' about a 30-ish diner waitress
trapped in a small Northeastern shore town and torn between her
sweet-tempered boyfriend (Jon Bon Jovi) and her no-good ex (Burns).
</P>
<P>
   Edward Burns grew up on Long Island, the son of a New York City
cop. (He's Eddie to his friends _ Screen Actors Guild has been on
his back about press references to ``Ed Burns,'' a name already
phonetically spoken for by 1960s TV actor Edd Byrnes of ``77 Sunset
Strip.'')
</P>
<P>
   When his NBA dreams didn't pan out _ he still has the thin,
squeaky voice of a kid calling plays in a schoolyard game _ Burns
enrolled in SUNY Albany, thinking maybe he'd become a sportswriter.
</P>
<P>
   Never a movie buff, he was hooked by a film-appreciation course
he took for an easy A. Burns later transferred to Hunter College in
New York City, unable to afford the more prestigious film schools.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a tale that has become modern-day movie lore, he spent
four years doing grunt work on ``Entertainment Tonight'' while
writing screenplays in his down time and piling up rejection
letters from agents and producers.
</P>
<P>
   He was close to quitting when his dad offered the seed money to
make ``The Brothers McMullen,'' which he shot over the course of
eight months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack (Mulcahy, who played the oldest brother) was the only guy
who had been in front of a camera before,'' Burns says.
</P>
<P>
   What followed were more rejection letters, this time from film
festivals.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate, he thrust a tape into the hands of Robert Redford _
the godfather of indie films _ after an ``ET'' interview. It was
the only time, Burns says, that he hit up a celebrity at work. Even
that approach failed.
</P>
<P>
   But by coincidence, Redford's Sundance accepted Burns'
submission. Only later _ after Burns won the top prize, Fox
Searchlight bought the picture and Redford called to congratulate
the young filmmaker _ did Burns remind the venerable actor/director
of their earlier meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Redford has since become his mentor, serving as executive
producer on his last two movies.
</P>
<P>
   For ``No Looking Back,'' Burns had a budget of $5 million _ more
than he was used to, but still far less than what your average
mega-star commands for one picture.
</P>
<P>
   He says he spent the extra cash on ``five more days of shooting,
my first crane shot and a rain machine for an afternoon. That's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I made less than half of what I made on `She's the One,'''
he adds.
</P>
<P>
   But Burns says that was an easy price to pay for the opportunity
to make the ``tough little drama'' he wanted. Besides, he says,
``When you make a film for five, they leave you alone. Working with
a lower budget just gives you more freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as shooting was to begin on his next film, ``No Looking
Back,'' Burns split from his girlfriend of eight years, Maxine
Bahns. Their relationship had become part of the Burns mythology:
They met working in a restaurant in the Hamptons, lived in his car
that summer and had been inseparable ever since. He had even cast
her, with no acting training, in his first two movies.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit for their breakup, he says, was not success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just Max and I were together such a long time, and it
was a case of, was either of us ready to get married?'' he says.
``I certainly wasn't ready to say OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Bahns left the picture, Holly entered it. But
Burns denies having an on-the-set romance with his leading lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' he smirks, ``Jon and I were having the affair.''
</P>
<P>
   He remains cagey about his relationship with Holly, calling the
two of them ``really good friends, underline really.''
</P>
<P>
   Since finishing ``No Looking Back,'' Burns has been working on
the script of ``The Long Blue Line,'' the story of an
Irish-American cop family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm passionate about my heritage,'' he says, admitting he's on
a quest to become the Irish-American Martin Scorsese, Francis Ford
Coppola, Woody Allen and Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Again he intends to direct and star in the movie. At heart he
considers himself a writer, but he has always been afraid ``to
surrender (a script) to someone and let them potentially massacre
my vision,'' he says. ``I wanted control of it. So directing was
just an extension of my writing.''
</P>
<P>
   He began acting for the same reason _ to maintain control of his
own work. ``Saving Private Ryan,'' in fact, was ``the first time I
ever uttered a line of dialog that I didn't write.''
</P>
<P>
   He has never taken an acting class and doesn't have a coach. But
with his strong features and easy manner, he seems a natural for
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``My approach is from the gut,'' he says, ``and I guess it's
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns says he would gladly act again in someone else's movie,
particularly if it pays well _ eliminating the need to earn money
from his own films.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has already made more money than he expected to earn
in a lifetime, Burns insists his daily fife hasn't changed much. He
still rents an apartment _ he swears it isn't much bigger than his
last one _ and he hangs out at the same neighborhood bar and plays
basketball with the same guys.
</P>
<P>
   But he does eat out more often.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the clout he has gained, allowing him to hobnob
with his heroes, from Spielberg, Redford and Hanks to Tom Petty and
Bruce Springsteen, and to form Irish Twins Productions with his
younger brother, Brian. They co-created a sitcom, ``These Are the
Days,'' for ABC and are now developing a one-hour drama for NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Keenly aware that he is only three short years removed from his
peonship at ``Entertainment Tonight,'' Burns is savoring every
minute of his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't work _ I make movies,'' he says. ``Ten years from now
I might be working in a diner.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Julie L. Belcove is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
