</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, July 19.)  
 (HLW)  
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BENJAMIN'S CROSSING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jay Parini. Owl/Holt, $15.
</P>
<P>
   This elegant biographical novel probes the life, death and
paradoxical character of the social critic Walter Benjamin, who was
both the beneficiary and the victim of the theorist's exile from
reality before his suicide in 1940. ``Parini's story is at once
painstakingly researched and dramatically recounted,'' Robert
Grudin wrote in the Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WHOLE SHEBANG: A STATE-OF-THE-UNIVERSE(S) REPORT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Timothy Ferris. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14.
</P>
<P>
   As the title suggests, the author of this arresting status
report on cosmology, which was selected by the editors of the Book
Review as one of the best books of 1997, has a lot on his mind.
Starting with the Big Bang theory and finishing with reflections on
God and humanity's role in the grand scheme of things, he works on
a breathtakingly wide canvas, offering chapters on everything from
the shape of space, the riddle of dark matter, quantum weirdness
and the inflation of the universe and all that implies. ``A skilled
and experienced popular writer, Ferris serves as one of the best
guides for the curious reader,'' Owen Gingerich wrote here last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNTOUCHABLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By John Banville. Vintage International, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator of this antic hall-of-mirrors novel, which explores
the compulsive appeal of communism for Britain's upper classes in
the 1930s, is based on the distinguished art historian Anthony
Blunt, who was named as a Soviet spy during the Thatcher years.
``Contemporary fiction gets no better than this ... extraordinary
book,'' Patrick McGrath said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAN CRAZY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Joyce Carol Oates. Abrahams/Plume, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid Boone is a sociopathic serial victim who is dehumanized
by a satanic motorcycle cult and its monstrously charismatic
leader. The violence in this perverse coming-of-age novel is
unrelenting, but ``there is no gainsaying the effectiveness of
Oates's writing,'' A.O. Scott wrote in these pages last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WAIT TILL NEXT YEAR: A MEMOIR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Doris Kearns Goodwin. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The author recalls her feisty girlhood in the prefeminist,
prosperous 1950s on Long Island, and how she grew up in love with
both her family and the Brooklyn Dodgers. ``For
self-esteem-building female role models, for baseball lore and
inning-by-inning action and for a lively trip into the recent
American past, you could hardly do better,'' Ann Hulbert said here
last year. A classic account of those same Dodgers,  &UR; THE BOYS OF
SUMMER &LR; , by Roger Kahn (Harper Perennial, $15), has been reissued
with a new epilogue by the author, who covered the team when the
lineup boasted guys with names like Reese, Robinson and Hodges. In
1972 our reviewer, Grace Lichtenstein, called this ``a very stylish
piece of '50s nostalgia that puts us back in touch with our
heroes.'' In  &UR; CREATING THE NATIONAL PASTIME: BASEBALL TRANSFORMS
ITSELF, 1903-1953 &LR; , by G. Edward White (Princeton University,
$14.95), a historian describes the various factors -- including the
fortunate foolishness of many team owners -- that turned a marginal
urban sport into a national institution. In 1996 in these pages,
George F. Will praised the author as ``an affectionate but
agreeably dry-eyed student of the game.'' Meanwhile, down on the
field, the player who broke Lou Gehrig's record of 2,130
consecutive games played reveals a refreshingly old-fashioned,
team-spirited attitude in  &UR; THE ONLY WAY I KNOW &LR; , by Cal Ripken Jr.
and Mike Bryan (Penguin, $12.95). ``Cal Ripken provides one of the
best reasons for even the most jaded fan to keep on rooting,''
Diane Cole wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FALLING BOY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By David Long. Plume, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   When a young carpenter marries one of four sisters in a small
town in postwar Montana, he unwittingly adds fuel to a smoldering
sibling rivalry with disastrous results. The author of this ``love
poem for an era, a place and a people'' displays a ``calm capacity
for warmth and gentle humor,'' Robert Houston said here last year.
Big Sky country is also the setting for  &UR; NOTCHES &LR; , by Peter Bowen
(St. Martin's, $5.50), the latest mystery featuring the brooding
lawman Gabriel Du Pre, who here tracks down a couple of serial
killers who may have murdered thousands of young women over a
20-year period. Last year in these pages, Marilyn Stasio called
this a ``mesmerizing series ... informed by Western legend, steeped
in Indian superstition.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SISTERS IN ARMS: CATHOLIC NUNS THROUGH TWO MILLENNIA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Jo Ann Kay McNamara. Harvard University, $18.95.
</P>
<P>
   This mammoth history is both a lament for the sad state of women
in religious orders over the centuries and a positive record of
their formidable achievements in administration, nursing and
education. The result is an ``engrossing and challenging work,''
Antonia Fraser wrote in the Book Review in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAIL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Mameve Medwed. Warner, $11.99.
</P>
<P>
   Katinka O'Toole is a youngish wannabe writer living alone in
Cambridge, Mass., whose spirits are lifted when a handsome new
mailman takes over delivery of her rejected short stories. Last
year our reviewer, Fran Handman, called this an ``off-the-wall
sendup of the take-charge-of-your-life novel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
