<TEXT>
<P>
   A Long-Running Battle Over Breast Implants  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning Corp. and lawyers representing the tens of thousands
of women who claimed injury from silicone breast implants agreed to
a $3.2 billion settlement, bringing to a close one of the nastiest
disputes in corporate history.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative agreement has enticements for both sides. The
170,000 women who filed claims against Dow Corning could recover
damages as early as next year. Dow Corning, forced into bankruptcy
by injury lawsuits in 1995, can now emerge from Chapter 11 without
admitting any liability over its silicone wares.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID J. MORROW &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Misconduct at the Top  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As deputy inspector general of the Army, Maj. Gen. David Hale
oversaw investigations of sexual misconduct by Army brass. Problem
was, Hale was facing some of the same allegations himself. Yet he
was still allowed to retire in February, with the investigations
unfinished.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon report last week found that he had engaged in a
pattern of ``inappropriate behavior'' or adulterous affairs with
the wives of four officers under his command in an earlier
assignment. The report fueled charges of an Army double standard,
in which senior officers accused of misconduct are allowed to
retire quietly while enlisted personnel or juniors officers are
prosecuted and jailed. Hale denied the misconduct charges.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PHILIP SHENON
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: Starr  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a string of legal setbacks, the Whitewater independent
counsel Kenneth Starr won one last week.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court rejected the Clinton administration's
claim that Secret Service agents should not have to testify about
what they knew of the president's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky. The Secret Service has argued that if its agents were
compelled to testify about the private life of the president, they
would be pushed away and unable to protect him.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ms. Lewinsky's former colleague, Linda Tripp, made
two more appearances before a federal grand jury in Washington,
just as another investigation was beginning. A Maryland prosecutor
announced that he had convened a local grand jury to examine
whether Ms. Tripp broke a law when she secretly recorded her
telephone conversations with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN LABATON &QR;
</P>
<P>
   HMOs Pull Out of Medicaid And Medicare in Some States  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Employers give health maintenance organizations the credit for
stopping inflation in the cost of their workers' health benefits,
and Congress and the Clinton administration want them to do the
same for their big benefit programs _ Medicaid, for the poor, and
Medicare, for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   But blaming inadequate reimbursements for their services,
leading HMOs have been pulling out of at least 12 states. Aetna
U.S. Healthcare has dropped Medicaid programs in Connecticut and
New York, leaving only New Jersey with one. Medicare beneficiaries
are losing programs in 10 California counties and 22 in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The move is more a trickle than a flood, with most of the
managed care organizations still operating their programs. But
President Clinton called the trend ``disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   The abandoned elderly have no choice but to return to more
costly fee-for-service medicine, and the poor to ``Medicaid mills''
that provide inferior care.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER T. KILBORN
</P>
<P>
   Wages for Former Slaves
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because it just bought Rolls-Royce, but Volkswagen is
suddenly feeling a bit more expansive _ more like meeting its moral
obligations. It had once insisted that in employing 15,000 mainly
Jewish slave laborers during World War II, it was, to use that
chilling excuse, ``just following orders.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, in an about-face, the company will set up a fund to
compensate those workers, many of whom now live in Israel. As
usual, though, justice delayed will often be justice denied: Many
of the workers are dead.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Bully Pulpit
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the government would no longer do
business with any health insurance company that flouts a 1996 law
intended to guarantee access to coverage for people who change or
lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you violate the letter or the spirit of the
Kassebaum-Kennedy law, we will, if necessary, terminate your
contract to provide health insurance to federal employees,''
Clinton said. ``If you say no to people with pre-existing
conditions, the federal government will say no to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurers insisted there was no evidence of abuse. The Health
Insurance Association of America called the president's
announcement an election-year stunt _ ``a frivolous misuse of his
bully pulpit.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT PEAR
</P>
<P>
   A Gain for the Palestinians At the United Nations
</P>
<P>
   A large majority of United Nations members, concerned about the
lack of progress toward peace between Israel and the Palestinians,
voted with a group of Arab and developing countries to expand the
Palestinians' rights in the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority has
administrative functions over real territory, the General Assembly
granted its delegation a special (though nonvoting) observer
status, with the right to take part in debates as well as United
Nations conferences. Washington opposed the move.
</P>
<P>
   Some U.S. diplomats sense that the lopsided vote for the
resolution reflects the plummeting position of the deadbeat United
States in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Masters Regained  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The thieves who stole two Van Goghs and a Cezanne from a Rome
museum in May were real pros, one investigator said, ``but they
didn't know too much about art.'' In their grand plans to sell them
for millions, they forgot that no one would touch such famous
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   And they also ignored this: While Italy has Renaissance art on
every street, these were its only Van Goghs. An irate Italy
assigned more than 100 law-enforcement officers to the case,
recovering all three paintings in predawn raids.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   More Money, Please  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Russia's economy hanging in the balance, the International
Monetary Fund has offered to give a helping hand to the government
of President Boris Yeltsin. But last week Russian officials and
Western investors were asking whether the fund was providing too
little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's initial suggestion was to provide $5.6 billion in new
financing, a small part of the $20 billion or more the Kremlin is
looking for. As the dance between the fund and the Russians went
on, the Kremlin was trying to prod the fund to double its
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kremlin was not simply waiting for the fund to get the
message. On Friday, Yeltsin decided to go over the head of the fund
and telephone world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MICHAEL R. GORDON
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Bond That's Pegged To Inflation  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration rolled out a new type savings bond
that it billed as inflation insurance for small investors _ or just
folks searching for the right birthday/wedding/new baby gift.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds' returns will rise and fall with consumer prices,
eliminating the risk that inflation will wipe out the value of a
30-year security.
</P>
<P>
   The new securities, which have all the tax benefits of
traditional savings bonds, are to be sold in eight denominations
from $50 to $10,000. Most of them, bearing the likenesses of such
people as Helen Keller ($50) and the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King
($100), go on sale this September.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES BENNET
</P>
<P>
   A Bouquet for Pepe Le Pew &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Given both the shape and the scientific name of the
Amorphophallus titanum, the Viagra jokes were inevitable. And so
Carolyn White, the security guard who stood sentinel last week
beside the world's largest flowering plant, was amused but not
particularly surprised when visitors wondered aloud whether the
potting soil had been fertilized with a monster dose of the
anti-impotence drug.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, in the horticultural event of the decade at the
Atlanta Botanical Garden, the 6-foot-2-inch tall plant began to
bloom. It was only the seventh time that the rare and unpredictable
plant from the Sumatran rain forest had flowered in cultivation in
the United States. During the next four days, until the bloom
wilted and shed, thousands of visitors jammed the normally tranquil
botanical garden like gawkers at a carnival freak show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting sucker, that's for sure,'' said an
admiring Carl Beck, a 72-year-old retiree. ``It's a wonder what
nature can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Amorphophallus, which is also known as the Titan arum, is
not only a sight to see but also to smell. In order to attract
pollen-carrying insects on the first day of its brief bloom cycle,
the plant gives off a stench that is often compared to that of
rotting flesh.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the Amorphophallus seedling four years ago from
a botanical garden in Sarasota, Ron Gagliardo, curator of tropical
plants for the Atlanta garden, began nurturing it with bone meal
and chicken manure. It sprouted leaves but never showed signs of
blooming until June 12, when a bud first emerged from the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Gagliardo, 33, was justifiably proud when the vast, vaselike
spathe, which is the color of dried blood, began to unfurl.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first walked in the room and looked at it I was just in
awe,'' he said. ``It made my heart stop.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEVIN SACK
</P>
