<HEADER>
A1990 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-YORKER-REVIEW-NYT     07-13 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-YORKER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW YORKER AFTER TINA BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We raised a quizzical eyebrow on hearing that Tina
Brown had abruptly, insouciantly sashayed her way out the front
door of 20 W. 43rd St. after six buzzful years as the editor of the
New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   This was rare news indeed. Resign? From The New Yorker? In the
past, editors either died or were forced to walk the plank, their
pockets weighted down with bullion. The restless Ms. Brown simply
left, rather than commit to a five-year contract. She signed on
with the film company Miramax to run a new company that will
produce a new monthly magazine, books, films and television
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something's perfect, it always seems like a good time to
leave,'' she told The Washington Post, applying a nifty gloss to
her tenure at what Fortune magazine recently called ``one of the
biggest money pits in American magazine history.''
</P>
<P>
   Strolling past the New Yorker's offices, and stopping in for a
haircut on the ground floor, we pondered the meaning of it all, as
Frank, our favorite barber, applied his sensitive hands to the
complex topography of our skull. Surely, life will be a shabbier
thing without Ms. Brown, we thought. No longer will it be possible
to speculate on our favorite conundrums. Is it S.I. Newhouse, the
owner of Conde Nast, who's fed up with Ms. Brown, or is it the
other way around? Which Florio does she work with, and how does she
know which one is which? Does she truly understand the damage that
a fused participle can wreak?
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a Tina-less New Yorker dampened our mood. Ms.
Brown ran the magazine as though she were giving a party in a
deconsecrated church. Readers felt a guilty thrill at the
brazenness of it all, grabbing a glass of champagne as they
circulated among the guests. Here was Norman Mailer, jabbing a fat
forefinger as he engaged in spirited debate with Queen Latifah.
There was Jeffrey Katzenberg, deciding the fate of empires, as
Richard Avedon clicked away with his camera.
</P>
<P>
   What larks! No more treatises on tectonic plates, Letters from
Washington that read like a VCR manual, langorous ruminations on
the fate of the earth, nattering Reflections or twitty Talk of the
Town observations in the first-person plural. No longer did we have
to worry with Bill McKibben in the Adirondacks. Away, dull care!
The new New Yorker was a kaleidoscopic swirl of power people,
synergists, media moguls, publicity pashas, superstars, and
megamodels. It was more fun than E! and sometimes nearly as deep.
When things got a little too giddy, there was always a report from
the latest trouble spot to provide some moral ballast, and darned
if writers like Simon Schama, Ken Auletta and Anthony Lane couldn't
be just as long-winded and boring as the great ones.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally _ well, more than occasionally _ some mauvais types
slipped past the velvet rope. We confess to a certain perplexity at
the thought of Roseanne Barr as a guest editor. That woman over in
the corner with the spiked dog collar and the cat o' nine tails?
Was she invited? And shouldn't someone have taken the drink out of
Ms. Brown's hand before she started going on about Princess Di, or
threw herself at Bill Clinton in an article that should have been
titled ``The Sexiest Man Alive''?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, we thought, with an indulgent smile, Harold Ross' New
Yorker was a bit raffish in its own way, and William Shawn's New
Yorker, as decorous as a Sunday service, has spent so much time
spinning in its grave that by now it's drilled a tunnel halfway to
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Autres temps autres moeurs,'' we murmured, slipping an
emolument into Frank's waiting hand. With a cheery wave, we
sauntered off to catch up with the buzz about the buzz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
