</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNALISM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZOMBIES AND OTHER CREATURES OF THE MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a curious new genre that seems to be emerging in
American journalism: the media obituary. In the hushed, somber
tones used for that most solemn of news accounts, reporters have
been busy churning out virtual death notices for the careers of
disgraced colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the recent chronicles of Stephen Glass' New Republic
exploits, in which he concocted parts or all of 27 of the 41
articles he wrote for that magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Or consider the reports of Patricia Smith's fabricated Boston
Globe columns, in which more than a few of the people quoted were
phantasms of her imagination. Or review the coverage of April
Oliver, the producer of a CNN report that the U.S. military used
poison gas in Laos, which both the network and its collaborator on
the story, Time magazine, have now repudiated.
</P>
<P>
   Much like actual obituaries, these accounts include paragraphs
detailing, in an already distant past tense, the decedent's career.
There is often a mention of parents, perhaps an aside to upbringing
and educational background. Also included are survivors _
producers, fellow columnists, editors. In the case of Glass, who
would not talk to reporters, the reporting sounds airless,
unleavened by any self-scrutiny or a whisper of personal
psychodrama. Ms. Smith left a misty apologia last month in one last
abject Globe column.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Greene, a former editor of Newsday and recipient of two
Pulitzer Prizes for his work as an investigative reporter, said he
had noticed the media-obit trend in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've also seen this in the past,'' he said from his office
at Hofstra University, where he teaches journalism. ``We wrote
about Janet Cooke in that past tense, I think rightly,'' he said,
referring to the Washington Post reporter who falsified an article
about an 8-year-old inner-city heroin addict, for which she won the
Pulitzer Prize in 1981 before the hoax was discovered. ``But we
have such an onslaught of victims right now that it seems new. It
becomes more stylized and sophisticated as we keep _ there's no
other way to say it _ piling up the bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   The media obit evolved because post-Watergate journalism depends
on a kind of professional schadenfreude, said Jerry Nachman, a
former editor of The New York Post. ``The sad thing about our
business,'' he said, ``is that as these journalists step out on a
ledge warily and appear to be attempting suicide, it's terrifying
to see how many of our brethren are standing below, yelling
`Jump!'''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, an obituary announcing the premature death of a
career signals an opportunity to try a more creative venture _ a
chance to write a novel that may become a movie. After the
journalist Clifford Irving was sentenced in 1972 to 17 months in
federal prison for a hoax involving his fabricated autobiography of
Howard Hughes, he wrote mysteries and a play titled ``Versus the
IRS,'' which was based on his own experience suing the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Mere weeks after Glass' doom was sealed as a reporter, editors
at Simon &AMP; Schuster and Random House bandied about the idea of
enticing him into writing a novel, according to editors at both
houses. Eventually the publishers concluded that his pattern of
deceit was a shade too morally ambiguous _ this judgment from the
people who paid $2 million for the memoirs of Dick Morris, the
former strategist for President Clinton who left the White House in
a scandal involving his relationship with a prostitute. Ms. Smith,
who is already an established poet, surfaced at the 17th annual
Taos Poetry Circus in June, where poets dueled and their verses
were judged by a cocktail waitress, a master carpenter and an
elementary school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are those who return like the phoenix, their sins
forgiven and their careers resilient. Michael Daly resigned from
his job at The Daily News in 1981 after admitting that a British
soldier he quoted in an incendiary article about Northern Ireland
was a composite; his departure was noted with funerary aplomb. But
weeks later, New York magazine hired him. He has since returned to
his post as a Daily News columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast news has a similar ratio of phoenixes to ghosts. In
1993, Michael Gartner resigned as president of NBC News after
acknowledging that the team behind a ``Dateline NBC'' report had
rigged a General Motors truck to explode for a report on truck
safety. Gartner retreated to Ames, Iowa, where he edits the Daily
Tribune (circulation 10,000). Last year, he won a Pulitzer Prize
for editorial writing.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Cooke now lives in Ann Arbor, Mich., where she was
studying for a fine arts degree until recently. Years after her
downfall, she received a little help from her friends. Mike Sager,
a former Washington Post reporter who dated her at the time of her
dismissal, turned the situation to their mutual advantage by
writing an article about their relationship for GQ magazine in
1996. He sold the film rights to James L. Brooks, the director of
``Wag the Dog'' and ``As Good As It Gets,'' for reportedly as much
as $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the victims themselves have resorted to the language
of death. Jack Smith, the CNN senior producer who was fired along
with Ms. Oliver, remarked to the Associated Press that ``the
bloodlust for another body was rising'' when CNN president Tom
Johnson issued a reprimand, rather than a vote of support, to the
correspondent Peter Arnett last week. (The New York Post reported
that a senior executive producer, Pamela Hill, also ``walked the
plank.'')
</P>
<P>
   But why do some journalists re-emerge and others sink forever
under the waves? When will Marv Albert surface again? And why is
Ms. Cooke never heard from?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about the most basic, driving motivation,'' Sager
said. ``Are these people who are struggling and just barely
treading water? Do they make these dramatic gestures in order to
save themselves, or do they do it to get caught? Or is this a
person who actually makes a mistake, carries it through, then
realizes it and is a person of some talent and credibility? The
well-balanced writer can carry out this tack and survive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
