<SLUG> BC-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVE YOUR OWN SKIN 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a 300-word sidebar 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By GALE HAYMAN  
 c.1998  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look around at the stars today who have paid attention to the
warnings about overexposure to the sun. Madonna, Sharon Stone and
Kim Basinger, among others, are preserving their beauty by
carefully protecting their skin.
</P>
<P>
   How, once and for all, do you really protect yourself against
the sun?
</P>
<P>
   Ultraviolet-A and ultraviolet-B rays are the sun's harmful rays,
the ones that cause skin cancer and premature wrinkling, and you
can't look for them, because they're invisible. They emanate
directly from the sun, they're reflected from water, sand and snow,
and they're a threat even on cloudy summer days.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, you can attract rays and harm your skin simply
by sitting unprotected under a beach umbrella. To protect
themselves, many people follow the conventional wisdom that says a
sunscreen with an SPF (sun protection factor) of 15 will screen out
these harmful rays.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with sunscreen lotions, however, is that they do
just that: screen the sun. They cannot effectively provide a
barricade any more than a window screen will keep out a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   For true protection, what you want instead is a sunblock, the
only true barrier against the sun. Read the label. If a sunblock
contains either titanium dioxide or zinc oxide, it's a sunblock
that will effectively block the sun. If it doesn't, it won't.
</P>
<P>
   Sunblocks have come a long way since the white pastes that you
used to see plastered over lifeguards' noses. Today, the better
brands blend into the skin, look natural, and provide great
coverage--all the criteria you need.
</P>
<P>
   For best results, apply a thin layer carefully, using a makeup
sponge to blend. (Important: don't forget to apply carefully to the
backs of your hands, one of the first places to reveal those age
spots caused by the sun.) Reapply, in general, every couple of
hours you're out in the sun, and definitely after swimming or
perspiring heavily, after gardening, say, or tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Among the great brands available at most drugstores are Bain de
Soleil's All Day Waterproof, Johnson &AMP; Johnson Sundown, Blockout by
Vaseline Intensive Care, A-FIL cream total block and Oil of Olay
Dily UV Protectant Beauty Fluid, which has an SPF of 15, contains
titanium dioxide, and is also a moisturizer.
</P>
<P>
   You can use the same sunblock on both face and body, although I
myself prefer to use the heavier blocks on the body, and the
lighter cosmetic blocks like Oil of Olay on the face.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, you'll want to ``accessorize'' for the sun. Sun
visors in vibrant colors are a protective must for playing tennis,
biking, gardening. J. Peterman makes a great Panama hat; the
``Gauguin'' model, very wide and floppy, is available by calling
1-800-231-7341.
</P>
<P>
   Any tightly woven, oversized cotton shirt will deflect the sun
some, but Travel Smith catalog (1-800-950-1600) offers terrific
``air conditioned'' protective shirts for both men and women.
They're lightweight and cool enough for swimming in. (Be sure to
tie at the waist first, for a sleek look.)
</P>
<P>
   Any tightly woven cotton shirt worn at the beach protects--and
presents a classic Katherine Hepburn image. Turn up the collar to
protect your neck, and leave the cuffs long to protect your hands.
 &UR; Help for Hair &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can also protect your hair before going to the beach by
using a hot oil treatment such as Alberto VO5, sold in any
drugstore, or the Super Luxurious Intense Hydrating Oil Treatment
by Phytogie.
</P>
<P>
   A home alternative is a 20-minute application of warmed
vegetable or olive oil, washing well afterward since these oils
aren't water soluble. With any treatment, be sure to wrap a hot
towel over your head to keep the heat in.
</P>
<P>
   For further protection, Phytogie also offers a fabulous product
called Sun Protection Oil, which does just that. Apply before
sunning or swimming. And where a hat whenever you can.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is to dress as carefully for the sun--summer and
winter--as you would for the bitter cold. And start your children
on the same thoughtful sun-protective regimen as soon as they're
exposed. You can definitely have your sun, as long as you protect
yourself against it, too. &QL; 
 &UR; (Gale Hayman is the author of ``How Do I Look?'' and co-founder of
the Giorgio boutique in Beverly Hills.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ---------
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR: SUMMER MAKEUP
</P>
<P>
   To layer makeup for summer, always start by applying your sun
block first--even if your makeup has an SPF factor. Apply it on
clean, dry skin, and give it ample time to let it dry.
</P>
<P>
   The next layer is your moisturizer. If your skin is oily to
begin with, it will be oilier in the summer, so one trick is to
dilute your foundation with your moisturizer for a lighter feel.
Dry skin needs its own layer of moisturizer, always.
</P>
<P>
   Next curl your eyelashes with an old-fashioned eyelash curler
from the drugstore, whether or not you're planning to wear mascara.
This will open up your eyes, actually lift the face, and it's a
step far too many women skip.
</P>
<P>
   (Another way to make your eyes look bigger is to apply a dot of
concealer in the corner of the eye socket and pat it in, which
brings the eye out where otherwise it tends to recede.)
</P>
<P>
   To create your own bronzing makeup, test your favorite
foundation in a shade three or four times deeper than your natural
color, blending it well with a damp makeup sponge. Blending is
key--be sure to ease the sponge into hairline, chin, neck, and--as
the pros do in Southern California--over the earlobes; white
earlobes against a glowing face are a giveaway every time!
</P>
<P>
   If you choose to go with a bronzer, they're available in powder
form or, my favorite, creme powder form, which is applied with a
damp sponge just like foundation and covers quickly and well. (The
powders are applied like blush, with a big fat brush all over the
face, under the chin, and over the eyelids.) Choose a tone that's
neither too red nor too orange, and apply it in bright natural
light to check the color.
</P>
<P>
   As for lip color, start by defining the lips with a nude-colored
lip pencil. For a natural look, fill in the lips with the same
pencil, then add a touch of lip gloss--long lasting and utterly
carefree. For a dressier occasion, go with brighter lip color, a
light, clear red, pink, or coral offsets a golden tan beautifully,
even if it's a tan from a bottle. --Gale Hayman
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
