<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2060 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESTAURANT-SECRETS-LI     07-13 1706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-SECRETS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETS OF A RESTAURANT CRITIC 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes photo of Julia Roberts in a scene from ``My Best Friend's
Wedding.'' Photo is also available by computer on NewsCom. 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By JOHN MARIANI  
 c.1998  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The call came in while the lingering effects of the
Romanee-Conti '59 let loose its grip on the back of my neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julia Roberts needs your help,'' said the voice. ``Thursday?
2:30?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to cancel some overdue knee surgery, but I guess I
can be there,'' I said, rubbing the last of the Romanee away.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know what the call was about then, but I had my
suspicions. Somebody in my racket has to read the entertainment
pages now and then. I knew Roberts, who had come off a few bombs,
was trying for a comeback with a movie in which she would play a
New York restaurant critic. I guessed she wanted to pick my brain,
but I don't work cheap.
</P>
<P>
   I gave the woman on the phone my price, telling her, ``I could
always go ahead with the knee surgery instead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she said, with a grudging resignation in her voice.
``Just make sure you're here for the full hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts was five minutes late for the meeting. Dressed in
bluejeans and a tank top that fit her like paint on a Corvette, she
had a handshake as determined as any Hollywood studio head, but
softer around the fleshy part of the palm.
</P>
<P>
   She showed me into her office, lit a cigarette, and said, ``So
you're the guy who's going to spill the beans on how I should act
like a restaurant critic. You know, I already played a waitress in
`Mystic Pizza.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see that one,'' I replied, ``But I'll tell you what I
can tell you. You tell me about this movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said it was called ``My Best Friend's Wedding'' and she
played a New York restaurant critic out to sabotage her best
friend's upcoming wedding in Chicago. I told her she didn't look
like any New York restaurant critic I knew. ``Well,'' she shrugged,
``things are different in the movies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, first thing, you shouldn't be smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do it to keep my weight down,'' she replied, blowing smoke
over her pretty left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe so,'' I said, ``But it'll kill you. More important,
it'll screw up your taste buds. What you can't taste, you can
criticize. And in New York the law says you can't smoke in a
restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take it under advisement. Here's the script. Give it a
look- see.''
</P>
<P>
   She tossed the blue-covered script on my lap, I opened to the
first page and started reading. It soon became clear that Roberts
was only required to act like a restaurant critic for the first two
minutes of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``O.K., well right off the bat there are a few things wrong
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what?'' she asked, coming around the desk and leaning
over to look at the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, right here you tell the captain hovering over
you what you're going to write about the food. They're not even
supposed to know you're there much less inquire what you think of
the place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``O.K., what else?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tools of the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What tools?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the first thing you do as a restaurant critic is to go
out and buy one of these pen flashlights. Two reasons for that:
Some restaurants are very dark and you can't see the color and
presentation of the dish. Second, you may want to take notes as
soon as you get outside and into a dark taxi.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good point. What else?''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the same key chain, carry one of these.'' I held up a
small, two-inch long thermometer I picked up at a sporting goods
store.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do with that, check out the temperature in the
refrigerator?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you never go into the kitchen, although you might pass it
by and peek in on one of your two, deliberate trips to the rest
room. A woman can make three trips, as long as you come back with
fresh lipstick. The reason you carry a thermometer is to check the
temperature in the dining room. Anything over 75 degrees is too
hot-- which most restaurants are--and anything under 70 is too
cold. That way, you can prove to a captain or maitre d' that the
place is too hot or cold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're getting somewhere,'' she said, with that huge smile
of hers showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so. OK, now a restaurant critic is a person paid to be
finicky and to challenge the staff, as long as you back it up. So
you specify every dish you order to be cooked to a certain degree
of doneness, like medium-rare for lamb chops, almost translucent
for a fish, al dente for pasta, tender but not soft for vegetables,
and so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should ask where the ingredients come from. Lobster tails
and shrimp are always frozen, so ask about them and try to trip the
waiter up. Question whether they think a particular vegetable or
fruit is in season, and, if you know it's not, ask where they're
shipped in from. Ask if the salmon is smoked on the premises, and
if not, what ocean it swam in from. Atlantic salmon is always
better than Pacific salmon, but I'm sure you knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, sure,'' she muttered, as a slight sweat broke out on her
brow. ``What about wines?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the wine list, check the highest and lowest
priced bottles on the list. If there are more wines above $40 than
below, the place is trying to coerce you into buying a big buck
bottle, which are probably marked up outrageously. Matter of fact,
it's good to keep a slip of paper in your pocket with some familiar
wines written down with their retail prices, then compare.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a reasonable markup?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Figure this: A restaurant pays about half of what you pay at
retail for a bottle of wine. You pay $20 at a wine shop, the
restaurant bought it from a distributor for $10. The price on the
wine list is $40. Now, that's a 100 percent markup on the retail
price, but it's actually 200 percent above his price. Most
restaurants charge 200, some even 300 percent, above retail, which
is 600 percent wholesale. Go figure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My God,'' she said, placing her hand on my wrist. ``That's
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is crazy, Ms. Roberts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Call me Julia,'' she said. Then, ``Go on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine glasses must be inspected,'' I said. ``When you're paying
top dollar for a good wine, you should be drinking it in a good,
thin wineglass. They should, er, ping! when you flick them with
your finger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean like crystal Baccarat?'' she purred, trying to show
some savoir faire about things she could easily afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't need to be,'' I countered. ``A restaurateur can pick
up great, hand-blown very thin glassware for three or four bucks a
pop. Don't let them tell they can't afford good glasses because the
dishwasher is always breaking them. Get a new dishwasher.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're pretty tough,'' she said breathlessly. ``I like that in
a restaurant critic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Same with silverware. Pick up the fork, feel it in your hand,
see if it has some heft to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a golf club.''
</P>
<P>
   The light through the Venetian blinds crawled across the script.
``I haven't much time left,'' I said, ``but there are a few things
more I'd like you to keep in mind.'' She just nodded, very slightly
and bit her lower lip a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ever let them shunt you to the bar if your table's not
ready, unless they offer to buy you a drink. Otherwise, just stand
right next to the maitre d's desk and don't budge. They'll seat you
pronto.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What if they give a lousy table?'' she asked, like someone who
had never been given a lousy table in her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask for a better one, but you don't throw your weight
around. See, here on page two, where the maitre d' says to your
character, `How does it feel to have your ass kissed by every
maitre d' in New York?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that's a funny line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never happen,'' I shot back. ``Even if they know you, they'd
never make a crack like that. I'd take it out of the script.
Pronto.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Consider it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a sap I believed her, and I said good-bye, receiving the
same firm handshake as when we'd met an hour before, only this time
there was something more familiar in it.
</P>
<P>
   I forgot about the movie, but not about Julia Roberts, in the
months that followed, then all of a sudden I started seeing the ads
for ``My Best friend's Wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   I bought a ticket to a late screening and took a seat to the
rear. The movie opens, there's Julia Roberts striding into a dining
room, with shots of the kitchen staff--filmed at Charly Trotter's
in Chicago--going nuts because they know she's there to review
them. And, jeez, damned if she hadn't cut out that dumb line I
objected to. But she kept on smoking throughout the movie.
</P>
<P>
   I smiled to myself, watched the rest of the movie, and got up to
leave. Then I turned halfway around to watch the credits roll by.
Past the assistant directors, past the make-up guy, past the grip
and best boy, even past the ``Lenses by Panaflex,'' and the thanks
to the city of Chicago. I know I didn't miss my name going by,
because it wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   I shrugged, murmured to myself, ``Some dames. You tell 'em all
your secrets, they use them, then they don't even thank you.'' So I
tossed the rest of my Junior Mints in the wastebasket and walked
out of the theater into the rain. &QL; 
 &UR; (John Mariani reviews restaurants for Diversion, and lives in New
York.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) &QL;
