<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEVEN-SPIELBERGS-SAVING-PRIVATE-RYAN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVEN SPIELBERG GOES TO WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Steven Spielberg directing a scene from
``Saving Private Ryan.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Imagine that you're a film director so uniquely successful that
not one, not two, but four of your films were included on the
American Film Institute's recently released honor role of the 100
best American films ever.
 &HT;    Would you high-five your cameraman? Slam-dunk your director's
chair? Declare yourself king of the world?
 &HT;    Steven Spielberg tried to give two of them back.
 &HT;    It seems that a couple of his favorites _ a Preston Sturges
comedy and a Marx Brothers romp _ had been omitted.
 &HT;    ``I was honored to be on the list,'' he says, ``but I
immediately called the AFI and volunteered two of my films back in
exchange for two others. I told them they could have `Jaws' (1975)
and `Raiders of the Lost Ark' (1981) back in exchange for
`Sullivan's Travels' (1941) and `A Night at the Opera' (1935).''
 &HT;    Well, he'd still have ``ET'' (1980) and ``Schindler's List''
(1993) _ not a bad double play in anyone's book.
 &HT;    Best of all, and unlike such AFI peers as Alfred Hitchcock,
Frank Capra and John Ford, Spielberg isn't even dead. At 51, in
fact, he's at the peak of his career, wrapping up a period of
remarkable productivity that has produced three movies back to
back, including ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park'' (1997),
``Amistad'' (1997) and ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the World War II
epic that stars Tom Hanks and opens on July 24.
 &HT;    Oh, and he has his own movie studio, Dreamworks SKG.
 &HT;    All this, and it's still a hobby. As a father of seven, he's
bound by the terms of a longstanding deal with Kate Capshaw, the
lovely actress who is his wife,
 &HT;    ``My job is that I do carpool and I make breakfast every
morning,'' he says. ``You know, those two things are my real
careers. Then I go to work.''
 &HT;    Currently, work brings him to Los Angeles' Ritz Carlton Hotel,
where he's doing a rare round of interviews to promote ``Saving
Private Ryan.''
 &HT;    He doesn't look much like a Hollywood powerhouse, however, in
his jeans, black-and-white tennis shoes and a tattered
brown-leather jacket. In fact, with wire-rimmed glasses framing a
warm, kind face, he looks rather like a college professor.
 &HT;    The topic of today's seminar is World War II, the setting for
``Private Ryan'' as well as several other Spielberg films,
including the disastrous ``1941'' (1979), the epic ``Empire of the
Sun'' (1987) and, of course, the Oscar-winning ``Schindler's
List.''
 &HT;    Oh, and one more: ``Fighter Squadron,'' a low-budget affair he
directed at age 15.
 &HT;    ``That was my first air-to-air-combat film,'' Spielberg says,
laughing. ``The budget was about a hundred dollars. I remember for
the bomb explosions, I got firecrackers. My mother wanted to kill
me.''
 &HT;    He acknowledges that maybe it was strange for a young boy
growing up in Phoenix to be so obsessed with war, even if his
father, Arnold Spielberg, was a veteran who had fought on Guam as a
sharpshooter.
 &HT;    ``My Dad is 82 now, and he fought in World War II,'' the
director says. ``I didn't know who to believe _ my Dad and his
friends, or the war movies Hollywood was making? I chose to believe
the war movies. My Dad's stories were so outrageously harsh to me.
 &HT;    ``He would tell me about the freezing cold and just the
suffering and how they had to endure watching their friends die,''
Spielberg recalls. ``War always fascinated me because, I think, at
the core of every war is this question of how far we can be pushed
and how deep you can reach down in your soul to walk those extra 10
miles in the morning. It still amazes me how the human spirit is
endless.''
 &HT;    This isn't the prettified war of 1940s films, in short. ``Saving
Private Ryan'' was reportedly involved in a ratings controversy,
rare in that it was about extreme violence, not sex or nudity.
Ultimately the film received an R rating, though some observers
whispered that a less influential director would have drawn the
commercially hazardous NC-17.
 &HT;    ``That whole thing is not true,'' Spielberg says heatedly. ``I
didn't get any special favors. We got the R rating. We were never
going to get an NC-17.''
 &HT;    The director freely admits that the film is very violent.
 &HT;    ``It's a war movie,'' he says with a patient sigh. ``I really
wanted to give the audience a physical experience.''
 &HT;    So important was it to him, he insists, that if he'd been hit
with an NC-17 rating, he'd have still refused to make cuts.
 &HT;    ``I would have taken the NC-17,'' he says. ``I would have taken
the rating without protest.''
 &HT;    This isn't the kind of movie that the young Spielberg grew up
watching. Lonely as the only boy among four children, he was drawn
to movies from an early age.
 &HT;    As a child, he recalls, he would stage his own horror movies by
pulling off the heads of his sisters' dolls, carefully placing them
on a dish and garnishing them with lettuce and tomato. Bigger
budgets _ and an indulgent mother _ led him to ``Fighter Squadron''
and, seemingly inevitably, to ``Private Ryan.''
 &HT;    His own children _ 13-year-old Max, his son with ex-wife Amy
Irving, Capshaw's 21-year-old Jessica and the couple's own five
children, 9-year-old Theo, 8-year-old Sasha, 6-year-old Sawyer,
2-year-old Mikaela and 1-year-old Destry _ don't seem to share his
interest in moviemaking, despite gifts of video cameras and such.
 &HT;    ``None of them cares about it, and I have seven kids,''
Spielberg laments.
 &HT;    Then he brightens.
 &HT;    ``The two babies don't know about it yet,'' he says hopefully.
 &HT;    Spielberg's passion for movies has led him to be one of the most
productive filmmakers of his generation, and he has a long list of
projects in mind, from a Tom Cruise film to a fourth Indiana Jones
picture. But the repercussions of fame have led him to plan a
couple of years off in the not-too-distant future.
 &HT;    ``I've heard I'm part of a government conspiracy to make America
and the rest of the world conducive to accepting an alien
neighbor,'' Spielberg says, laughing, ``and that's why I really
made `ET' and `Close Encounters of the Third Kind' (1977).
 &HT;    ``I love it, but the answer is no.''
 &HT;    More seriously, he recently was forced to testify in court
against a stalker who had threatened his family.
 &HT;    ``I don't really want to talk about it,'' the director says,
``except to say that I'm glad it's over.''
 &HT;    Spielberg has long been noted for his childlike imagination, a
sense of wonder which has fueled many of his most successful films.
But when he turned 50 last year, with ``Schindler's List'' and
``Amistad'' behind him and ``Private Ryan'' underway, many wondered
if their more serious tone meant that Hollywood's wunderkind was at
last feeling his age.
 &HT;    ``Turning 40 was really hard for me,'' he recalls. ``I had all
my midlife concerns. It was a terrible, terrible birthday where you
start to feel like you're getting old.
 &HT;    ``You know what? Fifty sucked, too.''
 &HT;    In retrospect, he says, he finds himself facing the question
that Private Ryan himself grapples with: Have I been a good man?
 &HT;    ``I think everybody asks that question at one time or another:
Have I been a good person?'' he says. ``It's a question we should
ask ourselves, not when we're really old and standing in the
cemetery. It's the kind of question we need to ask ourselves every
day of our life.''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
