<HEADER>
A2068 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTINA-APPLEGATE-I     07-13 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTINA-APPLEGATE-IN-MAFIA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTINA APPLEGATE IS LOOKING FOR A `MAFIA' HIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Christina Applegate with Lloyd Bridges
and Jay Mohr in a scene from ``Mafia.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Goodbye blue-collar bimbo, hello Madam President. That's one way
to sum up the career of actress Christina Applegate.
 &HT;    As the blond, bare-bellied Kelly Bundy on the long-running Fox
series, ``Married ... With Children,'' Applegate won legions of
fans _ as well as an image as a trashy, empty-headed beauty. In the
year since that series was canceled, the 26-year-old has been busy
on film sets trying to change that image.
 &HT;    Her latest effort is ``Mafia,'' a spoof of gangster classics
such as ``The Godfather'' (1972) and ``Goodfellas'' (1990), in
which she plays a Mafia moll who becomes the president of the
United States. The film is directed by Jim Abrahams, the master of
the big-screen parody, with hits such as ``Airplane!'' (1980)
``Naked Gun'' (1988) and ``Hot Shots!'' (1991) to his credit.
 &HT;    Applegate's character Diane is the WASPish girlfriend of Anthony
Cortino (Jay Mohr), son of the crime boss Vincenzo Cortino,
portrayed by the late Lloyd Bridges. While Diane may be more than
vaguely reminiscent of Diane Keaton's character, who married into
the mob in ``The Godfather,'' Applegate wants to make it clear that
she's not doing an impression.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't trying to be Diane Keaton any more than Lloyd Bridges
was imitating Marlon Brando,'' she says. ``We all loved and
respected `The Godfather' and all those other great mob movies, so
we weren't making fun of them _ we were just making light of
them.''
 &HT;    Still, Applegate readily admits that one of the biggest
challenges she faced was trying to play it straight while gags flew
on the set.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes they had to kick me out of a scene because I was
laughing so hard,'' she says. ``I quickly discovered the key to
this kind of parody: The actors can't try to be funny. In fact, Jim
Abrahams, the director, wanted me to get dramatic.''
 &HT;    The actress recalls playing one scene in which her character
breaks down in tears.
 &HT;    ``I remember saying to Jim, `I thought I signed up for a comedy,
not a melodrama,''' Applegate says. ``I ended up acting my heart
out, even though the audience will end up laughing at me.''
 &HT;    She took many of her cues from Bridges, a veteran of the genre.
 &HT;    ``Lloyd was an inspiration to all of us,'' Applegate says of the
actor, who died shortly after the film was completed. ``He was the
master of this kind of satire. His timing was always so perfect.
We'll miss him, just as all of his fans will.''
 &HT;    When asked to explain how her character progresses from Mafia
girlfriend to U.S. president, Applegate smiles.
 &HT;    ``All I can tell you is that she's on a quest for world peace
and it leads her to the presidency,'' she says. ``I must admit I
felt a little weird being the first female chief executive.''
 &HT;    If she had the chance to run for the highest office herself,
what would she propose?
 &HT;    Applegate flashes a sly grin.
 &HT;    ``I think mandatory meditation would be the key,'' she says. ``I
think everyone should get out and have that mandatory moment of
daily silence so they could kind of get in the zone.
 &HT;    ``Actually, I think I'd make a really fabulous president,'' she
adds with a laugh, ``but I'm not planning on pursuing a career in
politics. I'm too much into this acting thing.''
 &HT;    Applegate has been into ``this acting thing'' since she was 3
months old. She made her debut in the arms of her mother, actress
Nancy Priddy, playing the baby of one of the characters on the
television soap opera ``Days of Our Lives.''
 &HT;    She went on to become a regular on the series ``Heart of the
City'' as a teen-ager, and made numerous guest appearances on other
shows before she was cast as the Bundys' daughter in ``Married ...
With Children.''
 &HT;    During the popular series' run, millions of fans seemed
convinced that Applegate was just as vacuous and boy crazy as Kelly
Bundy.
 &HT;    ``I sometimes wondered if I might be labeled as Kelly for the
rest of my life,'' the actress says. ``But I'm a fighter, and I was
determined not to let that happen, because I'm really nothing like
her.''
 &HT;    Applegate says she has no regrets about her years as Kelly
Bundy.
 &HT;    ``In a lot of ways she was a wonderful character to play,'' the
actress says. ``It was fun to come in and just be sort of vacant
all week _ I got to turn my brain off.
 &HT;    ``And for 11 years we got to make people laugh every week,'' she
adds. ``I think laughter is so healing, and I loved taking it into
people's living rooms. But I was worried that I wouldn't get a
chance to play other kinds of roles.''
 &HT;    It turns out that Applegate had nothing to fear. She was
recently seen as a ``Jewish American Princess'' in ``The Big Hit''
(1998), opposite Mark Wahlberg, and she plays a motel laundress who
moonlights as a stripper in the low-budget feature ``Claudine's
Return,'' which has not yet been released.
 &HT;    The latter film gave Applegate a chance to stretch her acting
muscles.
 &HT;    ``It's a very dark piece,'' she says of the offbeat drama in
which her character falls in love with an Italian drifter. ``I had
some of my darkest hours as an actress doing it. It's a very heavy
film _ a tragic love story.''
 &HT;    The love story was scripted to include a nude love scene for
Applegate, but the actress had other plans.
 &HT;    ``I convinced (director Antonio Tibaldi) it wasn't necessary,''
Applegate says. ``I don't know if I'd ever do nudity. I just see so
much of it in films that is really unnecessary. After the love
scene in `Claudine's Return,' even though I didn't take my clothes
off, I felt violated. I actually broke down and cried.''
 &HT;    Her next project is much more light-hearted. This fall,
Applegate will return to prime-time television in the NBC sitcom
``Jesse,'' playing a single mother, not unlike her own mother, who
raised Applegate alone after a divorce.
 &HT;    ``In a way, this series is going to reflect my mother,''
Applegate says. ``I respect what she did for me totally on her own.
She went through a lot of trials and tribulations when money was
tight. As I look back, I just wish she could have had more of a
life, instead of sacrificing for me.''
 &HT;    Applegate remains close to her mother, and the two spend a lot
of time together. But she also has time for an active social life.
When asked if she's getting tired of the dating game, she grins
before replying.
 &HT;    ``I'm starting to get older,'' she says, ``and I know that at
some point I'm going to have to stop having silly little flings and
think about getting married. I'm interested in a long-term
relationship. I'm definitely looking for that in my life.
 &HT;    ``The things that I pray for are a lot different than they used
to be,'' she adds. ``I pray that I'll find joy and happiness in
whatever comes my way, rather than being totally focused on getting
the thing that will advance my career.
 &HT;    ``It's not that I'm less ambitious,'' she hastens to add. ``It's
just that I used to feel that if my life wasn't a certain way I
wasn't going to be happy. Then I discovered that being happy with
what you have is what makes your life more beautiful.''
 c.1998 Jeanne Wolf  
