<HEADER>
A2069 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURTNEY-THORNE-SMITH     07-13 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURTNEY-THORNE-SMITH-IN-ALLY-MCBEAL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTNEY THORNE-SMITH: ALL ABOUT `ALLY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Courtney Thorne-Smith in a scene from
``Ally McBeal.'' 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles is humming as Courtney Thorne-Smith settles in for
an interview during a break from taping on ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorne-Smith, the fresh-faced blonde who dazzled on ``Melrose
Place'' before making a splash on ``Ally McBeal,'' isn't
responsible for most of the day's buzz. The night before, both
``Seinfeld'' and Frank Sinatra signed off, and this morning brought
word that the city's most popular athlete, the Dodgers' All-Star
catcher Mike Piazza, had been traded to the Florida Marlins. (He
would later move on to the New York Mets.)
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Thorne-Smith is ready to put in her two cents'
worth on two of the three developments:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to live up to the hype,'' she says diplomatically
of the ``Seinfeld'' finale.
</P>
<P>
   She has more to say about Sinatra, having recently watched his
1956 musical, ``High Society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing,'' she says. ``He was so profoundly cool, and
he knew it. It would have been wild to be in the Rat Pack, to be
literally the coolest people in the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Piazza, though, Thorne-Smith has to take a
pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this one, I claim total chickdom _ don't care,'' she says
with a laugh. ``Call me when he designs a clothing line.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza has announced no such plans, which is probably just as
well _ Thorne-Smith doesn't have time to ponder him, even if she
were so inclined. She's moved from the trashy romp of ``Melrose
Place,'' in which she played the alcoholic Alison and struggled
with abuse, blindness and carjackings, to the tonier environs of
creator David E. Kelley's ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally'' surprised the critics to become one of 1997/98's few
breakout hits. Among the most popular characters, of course, is
Thorne-Smith's lovable Georgia, who gets to go home with Gil
Bellows _ who plays her husband, Billy _ every night while Ally
(Calista Flockhart) seethes and whimpers. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: What kind of reaction have you been getting from fans
this year? Have they been along the lines of ``Stand by your man,''
or more like, ``How dare you stand between Ally and Billy?''
</P>
<P>
   COURTNEY THORNE-SMITH: People who talk to me probably have a
different take. They say to Calista, ``You guys were meant to be
together,'' while to me, they take the party line: ``How can you
let her do that?''
</P>
<P>
   Now I think the triangle's done. One of David's strengths as a
writer is he gets bored with a story line before the audience does.
I think he finished with that a while ago.
</P>
<P>
   With the triangle fading, they're discovering Billy and
Georgia's relationship, and that's fun. They had spent time and
thought a lot about why Billy and Ally couldn't be together, and
they thought about why Ally and Georgia should be friends, but they
sort of forgot why Billy and Georgia should be together. Now we're
starting to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You had decided to sit out 1997/98, until David Kelley called
to ask you to be in ``Ally McBeal.'' How difficult was it to hop
back into things?
</P>
<P>
   THORNE-SMITH: It was tough. For one thing, I wanted a year off
because I was tired _ so tired. And here I was, coming on a new
show, everything was new.
</P>
<P>
   As an actor, you have either no hiatus or a four-year hiatus _
you have to be grateful for what you have.
</P>
<P>
   But this first year was an extraordinary experience in the
writing, the energy and the friendliness of the cast, the unity of
the crew.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think I would have made it if it hadn't been for that.
That made up for my lack of physical energy _ it was intellectually
stimulating and emotionally challenging, and that made it easier
for me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've gone from ``Melrose Place,'' a show where the writing
...
</P>
<P>
   THORNE-SMITH: (Laughing) Careful ...
</P>
<P>
   Q: ... wasn't considered one of its strong suits, to this highly
acclaimed show. How would you compare the atmosphere on the
respective sets?
</P>
<P>
   THORNE-SMITH: They're extraordinarily different in every way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melrose'' does what it does extremely well. We looked for ways
to make it light and fun _ we knew what we were making. We were
playing, creating this surreal world.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Ally,'' we're doing that as well, while we're searching for
the tone. It gets exaggerated in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melrose'' was melodrama, ``Ally'' is comedy and straight
drama. ``Melrose'' had 15 very separate story lines _ once you
would see one to the end, something would explode and people would
die. Here we work as a group more, which is more fun.
</P>
<P>
   I love that. There were some times on ``Melrose Place'' where
you'd have scenes with just one other actor for weeks and months at
a time. In this first year of ``Ally,'' we were all playing off
each other, getting the tone of scenes.
</P>
<P>
   It's fun, and creates a sense of unity among the cast. People
would come on ``Melrose'' _ like Lisa Renna, I don't think I ever
had a scene with her. I can't say that about anyone on ``Ally.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was your favorite subplot involving your character on
``Melrose?''
</P>
<P>
   THORNE-SMITH: I had the most fun. I liked when she was drinking,
because I got to go hysterical _ she got mad and had some backbone.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, she just whined a lot. And who wouldn't? Look at her
life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Georgia is certainly a switch from your last role in a Kelley
production, as the Laker Girl on ``L.A. Law.''
</P>
<P>
   THORNE-SMITH: I was told she was an aspiring actress. Then the
first day I walk into wardrobe, and there's this tiny leotard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' they told me, ``she's a Laker Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   I had no idea, but there I was.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And you didn't even make the cheerleading squad in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   THORNE-SMITH: Yes, thanks for bringing it up.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, it was dramatic and terribly important _ everyone
else was on the squad, but I wasn't. But I ended up in the drama
department.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has been the reaction of the cast and brain trust to the
endless deconstruction of ``Ally McBeal'' in the media?
</P>
<P>
   THORNE-SMITH: It's hysterical to us.
</P>
<P>
   David writes what is interesting and funny to him. There's no
committee _ he just puts it out there. And suddenly there are all
these people discussing the show, like why she wears such short
skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Calista looks great in short skirts. There have been all
these articles. She has great legs _ there's no sinister plot.
</P>
<P>
   Then I got a haircut. David had a whim, so I got my hair cut.
Now I can't walk down the street without people demanding to know
why I did that.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd _ we're just going to work and doing our jobs, and all
these people are analyzing and psychoanalyzing. I wonder if David
thinks it's as funny as we do.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is a Los Angeles-based senior writer for Canadian
TV Guide.) &LR; 
