<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADAM-BEACH-IN-SMOKE-SIGNALS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADAM BEACH: `SIGNALS' OF RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Adam Beach in a scene from ``Smoke
Signals.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's all just a bit overwhelming for Adam Beach.
 &HT;    Beach, the Native American star of the acclaimed art-house hit
``Smoke Signals,'' can't believe he's at the Soho Grand,
Manhattan's trendiest hotel. He can't get over seeing his face on a
poster plastered on the wall of a building just a stone's throw
from the hotel. He can't comprehend that journalists want to
interview him, and is amazed that everyday people are beginning to
recognize him on the street.
 &HT;    ``I can't believe how everything has worked out,'' the
soft-spoken 25-year-old says, as he settles into a chair in the
hotel's bar. He's dressed casually in black running shorts and a
gray tank top, and his thick black hair flows over his shoulders.
``I came to New York to audition, and on my second reading they
offered me the part.
 &HT;    ``The whole thing _ my getting the film, actually making the
film, it coming out even better than we could have imagined,
Miramax picking it up _ happened so fast,'' he says. ``I'm one to
go with things as they go down in life.
 &HT;    ``I kind of sensed that something special might build with
`Smoke Signals' from the day I first read the script,'' Beach adds.
``You can never be sure, but I felt good about this experience from
the start of it.
 &HT;    ``It's all just flowed beautifully.''
 &HT;    Billed as the first feature film written by, produced by,
directed by and starring Native Americans, ``Smoke Signals'' casts
Beach as Victor Joseph, a young Native American who travels to
Phoenix from his reservation in Idaho to claim the ashes of Arnold
Joseph, his late, estranged father. Joining Victor on his journey
is Thomas Builds-the-Fire (Evan Adams), whom Victor's father
rescued from a fire when Thomas was an infant.
 &HT;    Together, through laughter, tears and old stories, Victor and
Thomas learn about each other, themselves and the enigmatic Arnold.
 &HT;    ``You have to let go of some of the baggage you carry in life,''
says Beach, who was born in Asher, Manitoba, and raised ``on and
off'' a reservation near a small Canadian village called Vogar.
 &HT;    ``Everybody carries traits of their parents,'' he says, ``and
everybody hides a part of themselves, their vulnerability, their
anger, their happiness.
 &HT;    ``People need to live their feelings, whatever they are, and let
them go,'' the actor says. ``I would love people to see `Smoke
Signals,' feel it, relate to it and enjoy it.''
 &HT;    Upon reading the ``Smoke Signals'' script, which Sherman Alexie
based on his own book, ``The Lone Ranger and Tonto Fistfight in
Heaven'' (Grove-Atlantic, 1993), Beach instantly related to Victor.
 &HT;    ``My own life was more complicated than Victor's, because I lost
both parents,'' he says quietly. ``My mother was eight months
pregnant when she was hit by a drunk driver, and my dad drowned two
months later.
 &HT;    ``I was adopted by an aunt and an uncle, then by another aunt
and uncle,'' he recalls. ``So, even though I was with my two
brothers and even though we were close, my life was all sorts of
shifting around.
 &HT;    ``I felt that nobody wanted me around, and I blamed all of my
mistakes on my parents,'' the actor says. ``So, even though my
personal story was a little more dramatic, I could relate to Victor
and get into his head.''
 &HT;    The actor says that most Native Americans who see ``Smoke
Signals'' love it, that they find in it an accurate, realistic
portrayal of their people and of their lifestyle. Those elements,
he adds, are vital because there are so few works of entertainment
that ever reflect the Native American experience, and what few
there are rarely do so in an honest, authentic fashion.
 &HT;    ``That `Smoke Signals' is in theaters and is being well received
is important,'' Beach says. ``It's strengthening us as a people, as
artists, as storytellers.
 &HT;    ``The story crosses over,'' he adds. ``Everyone can relate to it
in some way. We live a different lifestyle, but we share a lot of
the same experiences.
 &HT;    ``The film doesn't beat anyone over the head with the lifestyle
differences, but it's good that people see those differences,'' the
actor says. ``We, as a people, are very nonchalant. We're not in a
hurry.''
 &HT;    Beach hopes ``Smoke Signals'' catches on with audiences, that it
makes money for everyone who kept the faith and got behind the
picture. But he knows it's not ``Armageddon,'' and he's actually
quite happy about that.
 &HT;    ``I'd rather 100 people at a time sit in a small theater and
watch our film, then leave with a good feeling about themselves and
Native Americans,'' he says. ``That would be better than a million
people going, `Oh, yeah, that was good,' and walking away with
nothing.
 &HT;    ``I think success for us with `Smoke Signals' will be a
different kind of success.''
 &HT;    Beach's own success has come slowly but steadily. After his
parents' deaths, he drifted for a while, directionless and lonely.
He eventually found solace in sports and then, after working as an
extra in a film, discovered that he could escape into other
characters via acting.
 &HT;    ``I said, `This is what I want to do. I want to re-enact a
moment, release what I have inside, express myself,''' he says.
``Now I can't imagine doing anything else.''
 &HT;    Beach counts among his credits the films ``Cadillac Girls''
(1993) and ``Squanto: A Warrior's Tale'' (1994), a Disney family
adventure, as well as guest shots on such television series as
``Lonesome Dove,'' ``Touched By An Angel'' and ``Walker, Texas
Ranger.'' He also spent a year as one of the stars of ``The Rez,''
a recently canceled Canadian television series.
 &HT;    Next up is ``Mystery Alaska,'' a big-screen hockey comedy
starring Burt Reynolds and Russell Crowe.
 &HT;    ``I'm a hockey nut, so that was great,'' Beach says. ``It's not
a big role, really _ I'm just one of the hockey players. I got paid
to play hockey for three months, so I didn't care.''
 &HT;    Now, however, Beach has to care. Coming off the success of
``Smoke Signals,'' he's got some serious choices to make.
 &HT;    ``I've got to decide on where I want my career path to go,'' he
says. ``Do I want to be an actor who sticks to roles that are
meaningful, that can impact lives, or do I want to be an actor who
wants to do important movies, but knows he has to work, to pay
bills, and may not always be able to be in movies that have
something to say?
 &HT;    ``I'm an actor who wants to work, and good films that have
something to say don't come along very often,'' Beach admits. ``So
I really have to think this through.''
 &HT;    And then he smiles.
 &HT;    ``Maybe I can find a middle ground.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
