<HEADER>
A2077 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALMOST-VEGETARIAN14-C     07-13 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALMOST-VEGETARIAN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More people making meat a shrinking presence on their plates
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Northside Hospital in Atlanta offered a seminar
called ``Almost Vegetarian'' on its roster of health classes this
summer, folks such as Cheryl Whitten made it an immediate sell-out.
</P>
<P>
   Whitten, 52, is watching her weight and her overall health and
thinks eating more meatless meals is a way to stay fit and well.
``I know meat has a lot of calories and fat, so I'm trying to limit
it,'' Whitten said. ``I probably won't eliminate it altogether _ my
husband wouldn't let me _ but I am going to eat less meat.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, when the Marietta, Ga. couple order pizza, she makes her
half veggie only. And Whitten is eating more pasta and salads and
sneaking ground turkey into the chili instead of using ground beef.
</P>
<P>
   Whitten is like a growing number of Americans who don't want to
swear off indulging on a steak occasionally, but they are trying to
work more meatless meals into their daily diets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a trend. I'm seeing more and more clients who
are cutting back on meat, but they don't want to cut it out,'' said
Page Love Johnson, a nutritionist with Nutrition Solutions Inc. in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Polls vary on how many Americans consider themselves strict
vegetarians, meaning they eat no meat, fish or fowl. A Roper poll
sponsored by the Vegetarian Resource Group last year showed only 1
percent of Americans say they fit that description. But 46 percent
said they were trying to reduce their red meat consumption, and 24
percent said they were eating more meatless meals than the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   There are other signs that vegetarian options are in demand.
Many airlines, including Delta, report that vegetarian meals are
the No. 1 special request. And more foods that used to be found
only at health food stores, such as tofu and veggie burgers, are
showing up in the mainstream grocery stores. The Vegetarian
Resource Group this year surveyed 12 major grocery chains
representing 1,800 stores and found that several items are more
available. For instance, veggie hot dogs were sold in 42 percent of
the stores, compared with only 9 percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   College and school cafeterias are offering more vegetarian
meals, and so are restaurants. Ciboulette, an upscale restaurant in
the Atlanta area, has offered special five-course vegetarian meals.
And vegetarian restaurants, such as Cafe Sunflower, say business is
brisk.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, steakhouses are hot, too. Diet books touting
``eat-all-the-meat-you-want'' high-protein diets are top sellers.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the barrage of warnings on the health effects of
diets rich in red meats, the average U.S. consumption of beef has
held steady the past three years at about 64 pounds per person.
(That compares with 50 pounds for chicken.)
</P>
<P>
   So it's not that we are letting go, but rather seeking a
balance, nutritionists say. ``I've cut meat out of breakfast and
lunch, but still include some kind during dinner,'' said Darlane
Coulter, 28, a client of Love Johnson's. ``But I love eating
vegetables and trying out all the veggie burgers, and Cafe
Sunflower is one of my favorite restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Denkinger, manager of Cafe Sunflower in suburban Atlanta,
said a good number of customers there aren't vegetarians. ``They
just want interesting food, and I think that's great. Even if they
don't go strict vegetarian, it's wonderful they are becoming more
conscious of healthy eating,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And despite persistent myths about the poor health of
vegetarians, vegetarian diets can be very healthy. Recently, after
several years of study, the American Dietetic Association adopted a
position paper favoring vegetarian diets as a sound alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetarians do need to get enough protein, calcium, iron and
zinc, but a vegetarian diet can provide those nutrients, and
there's mounting evidence that vegetarians are healthier than meat
eaters.
</P>
<P>
   That's because vegetarian diets tend to be higher in fiber and
lower in saturated fat and cholesterol. The ADA position paper
notes that vegetarians have lower morbidity rates from several
chronic diseases such as diabetes, heart disease, colon cancer and
high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Can part-time vegetarians reap some of those benefits? ``Yes, if
they are actually bringing more high-fiber and nutrient-rich
vegetables and fruits into their diet,'' said Chris Rosenbloom,
professor of nutrition at Georgia State University. ``But not if
they are simply living on french fries and Coke.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbloom said her biggest caution is to learn more about
vegetarian eating before trying to shift to more meatless meals by
attending a seminar such as the one at Northside Hospital, working
with a nutritionist or reading books on vegetarian eating. Too many
cut out the meat, but don't replace it with healthful alternatives,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Love Johnson agreed. ``I've had some clients, especially teens
and young women, who are all ready to cut out meat,'' she said.
``But then you learn they don't like beans or garden vegetables and
are scared of tofu.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
