<HEADER>
A2078 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN14-COX     07-13 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newt Gingrich's ``Yankee'' manners
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -Political style counts, especially in the South.
</P>
<P>
   When I told my 94-year-old south Georgia aunt that House Speaker
Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) did something good this week_ unveiled a plan
for 48 miles of greenbelt along the Chattahoochee River _ Autrey
Lewis Randall huffed over the phone. ``He still has Yankee
manners,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ungracious'' is the way she termed Gingrich's name-calling of
the first woman secretary of state. (Gingrich recently accused
Madeleine Albright of being an agent of the Palestinians.)
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Autrey's favorite Georgia politicians include the
chivalrous Sam Nunn, former U.S. senator, whom she says ``has solid
small-town values.'' She likes Georgia Gov. Zell Miller because he
credits his mother and his North Georgia upbringing with his
success. The only politician she ever sent money to, though, is
former President Jimmy Carter, whose mother she knew when she was
living in Dawson, Ga. close to Carter's hometown of Plains.
</P>
<P>
   ``In south Georgia,'' Autrey says,'' we were always fond of
Jimmy, though the boys used to call him 'sissy' for hanging around
with Miss Lillian and the womenfolk so much.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same aunt who reminded me ``to take galoshes'' when
I hiked part of the Appalachian Trail a few years ago _ no question
her political observations are slightly dated.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's not just my aunt who feels Southern politicians
should be _ well, Southern.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich isn't, by birth or manners. But I once listened to him
address a group of conservative doctors about the Clinton health
plan. He pounded the podium about ``the road to socialism'' like a
Baptist preacher might do. He seemed very in sync with a mostly
Southern male audience.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling that someone who's homebred can represent home best
isn't limited to the South, though it seems a stronger factor here.
Having spent many years in Colorado politics, I remember when Bo
Callaway, whose family is known for Georgia's Callaway Gardens, ran
unsuccessfully for a U.S. Senate seat in Colorado. (Of course, he
missed by only a hair becoming Georgia's first Republican governor
when the 1966 race was thrown into the state Legislature and Lester
Maddox was elected.) But in Colorado, no matter how often Callaway
posed against the snow-capped mountains of Crested Butte, the
western Colorado ski resort he started, his Southern accent
reminded more of watermelon and black-eyed peas than cowboys and
ski slopes.
</P>
<P>
   Though we all like to think we assess candidates on the basis of
the issues we care about, I hold the unscientific belief that if
two candidates seem equally appealing , voters go for the one they
feel most comfortable with rather than the one who's the best
qualified or the most articulate on important issues.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's gubernatorial candidates this year nearly all qualify
as to Southern credentials, by birth or length of residence. They
have different styles, though. Republican Guy Millner tells moving
personal stories instead of answering hard issues questions; Mike
Bowers, also Republican, despite his adulterous affair, presents
himself like a deacon on Sunday morning, laying down black and
white principles for making decisions, at least in the
public-policy arena. Democrat Roy Barnes can create the passion of
a tent revival at a political meeting or on the floor of the
Georgia House.
</P>
<P>
   The element of comfort with voters remains a problem for women
and minority candidates, homegrown or not. Though polls and pundits
predict which issues are the hot-button ones for the upcoming
election, there's precious little research to tell candidates that
how they speak and act is as important as what they say.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
