<HEADER>
A2079 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN14-COX     07-13 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: How to parent a college student
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ We have been oriented.
</P>
<P>
   My college-bound son and I recently spent two days discovering
everything we wanted to know about his chosen school but didn't
have enough sense to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Given the 100-degree weather, I had only one question: Do we
have to leave this nice air-conditioned auditorium and walk clear
across campus to sign him up for classes?
</P>
<P>
   It was a well-planned and executed orientation. We had
materials, folders, booklets, brochures, course catalogs, resources
and name tags out the wazoo.
</P>
<P>
   If we walked out of there after two days without knowing every
possible detail about the university, it wasn't because every
possible detail hadn't been printed, illustrated, demonstrated or
otherwise conveyed to us.
</P>
<P>
   We learned about meal plans, bus shuttles, dorm room
measurements, campus security, financial aid, the health center,
computer access, degree programs and bookstore lockers. We learned
the school song, colors, motto, logo and history.
</P>
<P>
   One particularly helpful bit of information was for parents
only. It was an article in the orientation booklet titled
``Parenting a College Student'' _ a do and don't list for parents
of incoming freshmen. Some of the advice:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask them if they're homesick.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is they will be so busy during those first few weeks
with classes and new friends, they won't give a thought to their
parents back home. Well, that's comforting. I really didn't need to
hear that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Write (even if they don't write back).''
</P>
<P>
   That will be no problem for me. The fact is, though, all of my
sons probably wish I would quit writing ... at least about them in
this column.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask questions (but not too many).''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, come on. How do you define ``too many''? If I call daily and
ask if he took his multivitamin, is that overstepping? I'm a
mother. It's who I am; it's what I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expect change (but not too much).''
</P>
<P>
   After a two-hour session on financing your child's education,
this bit of wisdom may be referring to coinage. Yes, I am confident
there will be some changes in our son's life. For instance, during
the next four years he will not find clean, folded clothes waiting
for him in his dresser. He will not have all four of his family
members to help him look for his keys, billfold or glasses. Nor
will he have home-cooked meals. Well, as the article states, some
change is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry (too much) about manic-depressive phone calls or
letters.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't think my son will. After 18 years, he's used to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visit (but not too often).''
</P>
<P>
   Who are these people and why are they telling me when I can see
my son?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not tell your students that `These are the best years of
their lives.'''
</P>
<P>
   Just because you're getting to attend the college of your
choice, living with your best friend, meeting new people, learning
exciting new things, socializing and partying ... no, believe me,
these are the tough days. Wait till you graduate, get a job and
work 60 hours a week. Those will be the good days!
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust them.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as I can call and visit daily, no problem.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, this going to college is really traumatic ... for the
parent. The university also offers a program ``to help parents of
college students focus on the opportunities and challenges they
will face as their sons/daughters begin the transition from home to
adult life.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as I quit crying, I'm going to sign up.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
