<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: The secret society of tourist photographers
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Lane
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   My work as a photographer has been displayed around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask me to be more specific. I seldom find out. I suspect
some of my photographic renderings have found their ways into
private collections in Europe, Japan, England, Brazil and the
Greater Disney Area.
</P>
<P>
   I do not accept money for my work. But I knew from an early age
this would be a lifelong avocation. The first time a sunburned
traveler wandered up a sand dune and said to me, ``Hey, kid! Could
you take a picture of us and make sure the ocean's in it, too?'' I
knew my path was set.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I am one of those people who are regularly called upon to
practice random acts of photography and senseless acts of
documentation. I am one of those people to whom tourists
instinctively turn when they must trust a bystander, a stranger,
anyone to take their photograph in a new place before it all
disappears into the abyss of memory.
</P>
<P>
   I have been tossed disposable little cardboard cameras and
gingerly handed pricey single-lens-reflex cameras with lenses the
size of oatmeal cartons and hieroglyphics flashing inside their
viewfinders. I have listened to suggestions about taking the shot
that have ranged from a gesture made toward a landmark to
mini-seminars on effective use of depth of field.
</P>
<P>
   I have been implored to take photographs by travelers speaking
20 forms of English as well as Spanish, Portuguese, Japanese and a
language that sounded like somebody spinning a radio dial but which
turned out to be Finnish.
</P>
<P>
   I have made hikers say ``cheese'' by secluded mountain vistas.
Commanded bathers to smile on beaches pink and paradisiacal. I've
told foreigners on busy city streets to step closer together using
the universal two-handed move-closer-together sign. Recorded the
doomed love of entwined young couples who someday will tearfully
tear up my work or else find themselves sheepishly explaining it to
their eventual spouses and children.
</P>
<P>
   They all find me wherever I go.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what?'' the casual reader might ask. (Despite their
comfortable clothing, casual readers are crotchety as a group.) I
would respond to the casual reader -- and any critical reader
trying to hide his harping under the transparent pose of casualness
-- that these requests do not arise from coincidence or chance.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who are regularly called upon to record the
vacations of strangers are part of a brotherhood. We are people
with the ingrained faculty of looking as though we can work a
camera. And, just as important, we do not appear to be the kind of
people who kill, rob or sell time-share condominiums to innocent
travelers
</P>
<P>
   You must be born with it. It cannot be learned. You have The
Gift.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists often are vulnerable people, acting on their instincts
in a strange place. They can sense the ones who can photograph them
and return their cameras undamaged.
</P>
<P>
   They can find us in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   No scientific study has been undertaken on this phenomenon.
Statistics are not available on which strangers tourists pick to
hand their cameras to.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect, though, that an average appearance helps. I, for
instance, am a person of average height, average weight with an
average smile that is only moderately reassuring. I look vaguely
like someone everyone thinks they know but isn't sure. I used to
imagine I had a double running around meeting people, but I now
chalk it up to extreme averageness.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in a strange town, you would rather hand your camera
to a man who looks a little like your cousin's idiot husband than
someone who looks exotic or scary or smarter than you.
</P>
<P>
   That's one theory.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer the mystical gift theory myself. Travelers are more in
tune with The Force. It draws them to someone of my skills to be
photographed in front of marble arches, ancient fortresses and
swaying palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever noticed the strangers you encounter never act
surprised when you ask them to take your picture? Isn't that a
little odd in a suspicion-filled society like ours? Huh?
</P>
<P>
   That's because we expect it. You found us again. We have been
waiting for you.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-10-98 1533E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
