A2083 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN14-COX     07-13 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: When the whole world was a green sofa . . .
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Today I find myself wondering whatever
happened to the old green sofa - the one we had in the living room
when I was a little girl. Odd thing to think of but I guess it's
because I've spent most of the day on the dining room floor leaning
against another old sofa. One with brown velvet upholstery and
carved feet.
</P>
<P>
   There's a good reason I'm here instead of in my upstairs office
or on the porch (my summer writing spot of choice). It's too hot!
It's too hot upstairs, downstairs, on the porch, and even here in
the dining room with the little fan right next to me. It's too hot
to clean up the house or work in the yard. It's too hot to pack my
suitcase for a trip I'm taking next week and it's too hot to run
errands.
</P>
<P>
   The basement is cool but there's nothing to do down there but
wash and iron and I've already done that.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, due to circumstances well within my control,
nothing I own is air conditioned. The house (radiators and no
duct-work) never was, and the old Bronco used to be but hasn't been
for quite some time. About four summers ago it started blowing hot
air which I knew was not a good sign. The Ford folks looked it over
and wrote up an estimate which was about fifty bucks higher than
the blue book value of the car. I politely declined but had to pay
for the estimate anyway. I came out $35 poorer and still hot.
</P>
<P>
   That's the story of how I came to be spending most of this day
in the dining room leaning against the sofa and watching the big
ficus by the window drop its leaves. It's getting a little scary
because I think I'm beginning to identify with that tree.
</P>
<P>
   Why don't I remember it being this hot when I was a kid and
hanging out on that old green sofa? I can remember everything else
about it.
</P>
<P>
   I recall lazy summer afternoons when my girlfriend Tootie and I
would choose up ends, plunk our heads down on an armrest, fling one
leg over the back and read Wonder Woman comic books. When my mother
wasn't around we'd sneak in a couple of Birely's orange drinks.
</P>
<P>
   One winter I had whooping cough on that old green sofa and had
to miss my own birthday party. Another, it was chicken pox. My
mother slid the sofa into the dining room so she could keep an eye
on me from the kitchen to be sure I didn't scratch and make scars.
</P>
<P>
   Summer evenings I would lie on it listening to ``Gangbusters''
and being scared stiff. One night an evil character named ``The
Blonde Tigress'' really got to me and by bedtime I was terrified. I
stalled with the old ``I'm hungry, thirsty, and whatever'' routine
in an effort to buy time to outsmart that half-human, half-wildcat
whose bloody claws awaited the reckless stair climber.
</P>
<P>
   Strange how quickly my father caught on and offered to walk
upstairs with me, checking along the way for any killers who might
be lurking behind toy chests or under doll beds.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, the old green sofa became a launch pad for my
movie-inspired adventures. Once, the back of it was the open door
of a C-46. I bailed out over enemy territory and crawled among the
furniture seeking cover from snipers.
</P>
<P>
   Another time it was the stage for a hula recital complete with a
grass skirt that I had made from cut-up newspapers - including the
one my father had been looking forward to reading when he came home
that evening. His reaction was somewhat short of thrilled and my
dance played to cool reviews.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of my 8th Christmas, I recall curling up on the old
green sofa in my chenille bathrobe - the one with the ducks around
the hem - and eyeballing a suspicious looking package with my name
on it under the tree. I suspected it might be the Sonja Henie doll
I'd been driving everybody crazy for since Thanksgiving. It was.
</P>
<P>
   Sonja and I set up housekeeping on the old green sofa, and when
she wore her fur-trimmed skating costume, the middle cushion became
an ice rink. The scenario shifted with each change of the doll's
clothes. It became Westminster Abbey when she marched the length of
it in a white satin bridal gown trailing a cathedral-length veil
behind her. For a day, the old green sofa became an entire world.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later I had a first boyfriend. His name was Harry
and he sat on the edge of the old green sofa, making polite
chitchat with my eagle-eyed father who thought 16 was too young to
date. He was holding out for 30.
</P>
<P>
   After a decent interval, Mother dragged my father off to another
room. Harry and I played records and cooked french fries. We danced
a few and sat out a few on the old green sofa. Whenever it got too
quiet, my father coughed.
</P>
<P>
   And then one day the unthinkable happened. I came home from
school and it was gone. Just like that - no ceremony, no warning -
nothing. It was just gone. My whole history wiped out in the blink
of a Burdine's furniture truck and when I asked my mother where it
had gone, she cracked wise: ``Probably to sofa heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Boy, I'd sure like to think so. If a piece of furniture ever
deserved it, it was my old green sofa.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
