<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2085 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRE-SURVEY14-COX     07-13 1830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-SURVEY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida fire survey shows apathy among residents
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In 1989, state foresters visited the
woody lots of Palm Coast and asked its residents: exactly how
afraid of wildfire are you?
</P>
<P>
   Going door to door, they handed out 200 surveys to homes most
likely to burn if a blaze broke out. Only 94 bothered to answer.
Those who did conceded fire was their biggest natural enemy. But
the chance of a fire actually occurring over the next 10 years,
they wagered, was less than fifty-fifty.
</P>
<P>
   The survey came just four years after a deadly wildfire season
killed two firefighters, burned 443,816 acres and destroyed 131
houses in Palm Coast, a subdivision carved out of forests in rural
Flagler County.
</P>
<P>
   Less than half quizzed even knew about the fires.
</P>
<P>
   So is there a lesson to be learned here?
</P>
<P>
   ``It don't take long to forget things,'' said Victor Buckles, a
retired timber man who managed 90,000 acres of forest in Volusia,
St. Johns and Flagler counties for the St. Regis paper company _
now Champion International Corp. _ until retiring in 1996 after 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the Memorial Day fires that scorched over
495,000 acres and destroyed or damaged 337 structures, state and
local officials say they'll examine how to better predict, control
and fight wildfires. Technology has improved considerably in the
last decade, with computers to forecast fire and formulas to
determine how it burns. Meteorologists are more accurate and
foresters are getting creative, even using goats to tame their
woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   That said, most _ timber men, firefighters, even the scientists
_ agree wildfire is one force that will never be completely
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nature wants it to burn, it's going to burn,'' said Karen
Terrill, information officer for the Department of Forestry and
Fire Protection in California, the epicenter for wildfires in this
country. ``Nature is more powerful than we are. However, we can
have isolated successes by using what we know works.''
</P>
<P>
   Fires burn because of three elements: fuel, oxygen and heat.
This summer, Florida found itself with an abundance of all.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal year, summer rains help counteract the thousands of
fires ignited by lightning, trash burning and other things. But as
early as April, foresters realized they were in for a tough
wildfire season. The rains hadn't come and the drought index had
climbed to an alarming level in central and north Florida, one
usually reached in August when thunderstorms are more scattered,
said Greg Thayer, a spokesman for the U.S. Forest Service stationed
at the command center set up for the Florida wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem was something weather forecasters call the
Atlantic ridge, a weather system that typically blankets the state
in spring and leaves in time for June rains, Thayer said.
</P>
<P>
   When the ridge persisted, foresters started worrying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started to watch the Atlantic ridge. It would stay for
five, six, eight days and break down, then come back again,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Crews with the division of forestry alerted to normal lightning
fires got a special warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (told) field units, out of 15,000 normal lightning strikes,
you're going to get a large percentage that will actually cause a
fire. And we were right,'' Thayer said.
</P>
<P>
   On Memorial Day weekend, thunderstorms ignited dozens of fires.
Fanned by high winds and feasting on dry vegetation, they streaked
across the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went instantly into fire threat situations,'' Thayer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Perry area and Osceola and Apalachicola National Forests
burned first and fastest, he said. Waldo came next, forcing the
evacuation of most of the town's 1,000 residents. Then fires in
Brevard, Volusia and Flagler counties intensified, erupting in
fierce blazes that chased more than 70,000 people from their homes
last week, including all of Flagler County.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was with woods and fields so dry, foresters were
getting the worst kinds of fires.
</P>
<P>
   Brush fires spread to woods where thick ground cover created
ladders for fires to climb into trees. Once in the crowns, fighting
the fires is virtually impossible because they create their own
firestorm. The intense heat builds wind that whips the fires
around, one time shooting a fireball across a four-lane divided
highway. Worse, the kinds of pine that fill Florida forests have
highly flammable resins. So sometimes the trees just heat up until
they explode.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters finally got the upper hand this week when winds
died and they had enough trenches dug to contain them. (Fires won't
burn soil stripped of vegetation.) And Saturday, the drought index
finally fell, dropping more than 100 points. At its peak, it was
near dessert level.
</P>
<P>
   Now many want to know what exactly happened.
</P>
<P>
   On some levels, the answer is simple.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, state foresters and timber men set their own winter
fires to rid areas of palmetto shrub, thick layers of pine needles
and other fuel that feed fires. The fires also leave behind
nutrients that help the forests thrive.
</P>
<P>
   But heavy rains in October and November made many fires useless.
In March, Flagler County commissioners authorized state foresters
to burn their county's overgrowth, said county commissioner George
Hanns.
</P>
<P>
   The drought, however, made conditions too dry there and around
the state, Thayer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The approval (for burning) was in place, but only for perfect
conditions and we were far from that,'' Hanns said.
</P>
<P>
   The more complicated answer to controlling wildfires is how to
strike a balance in developing a state where fire is a beneficial
part of its ecology.
</P>
<P>
   Before the early 1980s, large tracts of land were routinely
burned, Buckles said. In fact, controlled fires go back to the time
American Indians used it to raze woods for planting or clear out
brush for easier hunting.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Everglades routinely burned every two years and some
forests even evolved to survive fire. Longleaf pine, for example,
concentrates growing its roots during the first five years so it
can survive when leaves are consumed by fire.
</P>
<P>
   Civilization, however, has put an end to much burning.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Palm Coast. When ITT purchased the land it was a
42,000-acre managed pine forest. ITT began building roads and
sewers and by 1982 was selling off houses, targeting out of state
buyers, according to the division of forestry study. The area was
planted with pines expected to mature before and during
construction. Before the fires, most were about 30 years old and
had not been thinned. Likewise, most houses had just 30 feet
separating them from heavy, flammable brush.
</P>
<P>
   Controlled fires in the past always prompted complaints from
residents, Hanns said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In sunny Florida, they decide they don't want to be
inconvenienced by smoke unless it's from a barbecue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laws have also become more strict for conducting fires, said
Rep. Kelley Smith, R-Palatka, a timber man for 30 years. Less than
10 percent of the forests once burned now get cleared by fire, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules and regulations have become so stringent and
liability so great that many fear controlled burning. And the cost
has increased,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Private landowners who want to burn their land must be certified
and follow state notification laws of nearby landowners. Foresters
have their own set of complicated guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually write a contract and provide a prescription and we
don't set it if the prescription isn't right,'' said Terrill, of
the California forestry department where 40,000 acres were
intentionally burned last year. Officials in Florida said Saturday
they are still researching the number set here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has to be right and some contracts are many, many
pages long. The first one I saw was 72 pages long,'' she said.
``It's very much a science and if we show up and conditions
changes, the wind, we go home. We don't set it.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are other problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are running into difficulty in many places . . . due to air
quality regulations and laws that have been passed for rare and
endangered species,'' Thayer said. ``It's shrinking down our window
of opportunity. You might go out and just in early, early spring,
it's moist and cool and a preferable time, but it's the nesting
time for some animals. What would happen if during the nesting
season of our birds we had those fires? We would have wiped out a
whole year's worth of nesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who helped write legislation in 1992 to ease rules for
burning permits, said legislators will probably look at changing
laws in the aftermath of the Memorial Day fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then (in 1985) the fire was kind of localized in the
Flagler area and it now runs across central Florida, the
Apalachicola Forest and into the Panhandle. So I think more members
of the legislature will have an interest than before. Plus, the
cost.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the cost of fighting the fires has reached $104 million
with damages estimated at $276 million, most due to timber loss.
</P>
<P>
   Hanns said he will suggest hiring more firefighters to help the
nearly all-volunteer brigade in his county that has only 18 paid
members. He also wants brush trucks at every station.
</P>
<P>
   Besides setting fires, there are other ways to protect homes.
The city of Malibu, plagued by severe fires in 1993, keeps a herd
of brush goats that eat star thistle and other thick undergrowth
called chaparral, Terrill said.
</P>
<P>
   California also has strict building regulations in fire-prone
areas that require fire-resistant roofs and guards on chimneys.
Brush must be kept trimmed within 100 feet of houses and trees
planted at least six feet apart. Also, golf courses and parks are
used like moats to protect communities. Herbicides can also be used
to kill brush.
</P>
<P>
   Some western states use roads as barriers to fire, building them
perpendicular to prevailing wind patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the biggest difficulty is putting houses in the middle of
wildlands where fire can and should burn because it is part of the
natural cycle, foresters say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, a lot of people just don't think about it,'' said
Dave Tippets, public affairs officer for the U.S. Forest Service's
Rocky Mountain Research Center. ``They buy a home in a beautiful
forest environment, they love the trees and the vegetation and they
don't think what it's going to mean if a fire gets started.''
</P>
<P>
   What it will mean, at least for the next 30 years is a different
environment, Thayer said.
</P>
<P>
   Without a canopy of trees, different kinds of plants will grow
and young plants will attract more rodents, he said. Forests can be
replanted, but it is difficult and expensive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through this in many parts of the U.S.,'' he said,
``and we have a big job ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
