<SLUG> BC-HANDS-REVIEW14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movie review of Hands on a Hard Body
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ In S.R. Bindler's fascinating documentary ``Hands on a
Hard Body,'' to place a hand on the sturdy gleam of a factory-fresh
pickup truck _ a ``hard body,'' in East Texas argot _ is to rub the
genie bottle of cramped limbs, imminent dementia and unchecked
agony.
</P>
<P>
   It's to forfeit reason and stand firm with one hand on the
candy-apple blue vehicle for more than 70 hours straight. It's to
sweat, ache, cry real tears and marinate in impossible tedium. It's
about all of these factors wiping out your opponents and leaving
you the last person standing. All in the name of winning the spiffy
Nissan truck, the truck on which 23 exhausted paws rested for so
long with so much iron resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're suffering; we're hurtin'.''
</P>
<P>
   That's contestant Benny Perkins, a whip-smart man who serves as
the film's wise and gnomic elder, for Benny won Hands on a Hard
Body two years before this bruising bout.
</P>
<P>
   Benny is a simple man. And he and his 22 rivals compose a richly
compelling gallery of regular folks who want something we all want.
Director Bindler _ a native of Longview, where the film was shot in
1995 _ crafts a frank, funny and massively entertaining survey of
human quirks and values that opens worlds to the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Bindler's camera scours emotional terrain most documentaries
only skim and produces a textured microcosm of the human
experience. A war of attrition whose sole weapon is unblinking
will, the competition is much like the marathon dance contests of
yore and a bit like the Donner party: It's a not-so-pretty petri
dish of how we behave under the most unforgiving conditions. ``You
have to realize it's a human drama thing. It's more than just a
contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Hands on a Hard Body was a human drama thing held by the local
Nissan dealer, with contestants picked by lottery. Bindler weaves
precontest interviews with the 23 players throughout the film,
striking wonderful juxtapositions between bright-eyed declarations
(``I can't picture myself walking away,'' says one. ``That's just
something I won't do.'') and moans of doubt in the withering heat
of battle.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the desire to own a truck in Texas, competitors have
disparate reasons for doing this. Young Kelli Mangrum wants to win
the truck and sell it to pay bills, go to school and get braces.
Russell Welsh had a rough winter on the farm and had to hawk his
pickup to pay the bills. He needs this truck.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Norma Valverde, a deeply religious woman who finds
strength listening to sermons and church music on a Walkman and by
laughing hysterically at apparently nothing at all. (``That
uncontrollable laughter will take you down,'' warns Benny.)
</P>
<P>
   Several families are praying for her on the sidelines in the
dealership lot, and, indeed, cheerleading pit crews composed of
family and friends await each contestant with restorative
provisions during the five-minute breaks allotted every hour. Here,
feet are rubbed, cigarettes smoked, bellies filled and endurance
strategies formulated.
</P>
<P>
   Contest rules are strict, and we see a player disqualified after
two days because he leaned on the truck. Another contestant quits,
charging people are cheating under the unwary eyes of the judges.
She even admits to taking her hands off the truck. This makes for
high drama, and Bindler catches it all, even the glints of delight
in the eyes of those left standing. ``When they drop off, it's an
exhilarating thing. Like killing a deer.''
</P>
<P>
   Using a hand-held, Hi-8 video camera, Bindler shoots in true
ve(accent)rite(accent) fashion, chasing the unscripted drama as it
unfolds in unforeseeable bursts. ``So-and-so left!'' you hear far
off, and there goes Bindler dashing with shaky camera to see who
has bailed out and why, followed with often moving, tear-stained
interviews. The documentary ripples with impromptu emotional
charges like this.
</P>
<P>
   As the 20th, 40th, 60th hour ticks by, physical transformation
wracks the participants. Half-mast eyes, matted hair, nascent
beards, not to mention unintelligible muttering and swaying bodies,
signal encroaching delirium in this pilgrimage through boredom and
displeasure. We feel the pain. ``There's extreme boredom . . . Your
mind is looking for input. Anything. Something.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a whiff of condescension mars Bindler's exploration of a
slice of Americana. Any humor in the film is inherent in the
subject, a quotation straight from the ongoing human comedy.
</P>
<P>
   What Bindler captures in this amazing document far transcends
the importance of a good pair of tennies, the ills of a hamburger
and the power of prayer. He captures the bare essence of being
human: desire, the root of unhappiness and something some people
will go to incredible lengths to satisfy.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Garcia is a freelancer for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
