<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LETHAL-REVIEW14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest 'Lethal Weapon' misfires with tired routines
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Lethal Weapon 4' Starring: Mel Gibson, Danny Glover, Rene
Russo, Chris Rock, Joe Pesci, Jet Li Director: Richard Donner MPAA
rating: R for violence, language
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ `Lethal Weapon 4'' looks and feels like it was made 10
years ago. Ten looong years ago. The broad, dumb, retrograde
action-comedy reunites Mel Gibson and Danny Glover with a thousand
cop-flick cliches that once, in the days when Howie Mandel and Guns
'N' Roses were peachy, seemed so invigoratingly hip.
</P>
<P>
   Cliche(accent)s like: The villains are Ruthless Foreigners who
ply their sinister trade in a warehouse in America. The Heroic,
Funny Cops insult the bad guys with borderline racist gibes. A guy
gets thrown through a plate-glass window. A truck drives off the
end of a pier and goes headfirst into the ocean. A road
construction site serves as a perfect car jump.
</P>
<P>
   Wheezing along, the shockingly uninspired movie reveals a
franchise past its prime. There's a scene in which Gibson and
Glover's detective duo chant mantralike, ``We're not too old for
this (expletive)!''
</P>
<P>
   Correction. You are too old for this (expletive). The stars
aren't even trying, and wasted co-stars Rene Russo, in the waiting
girlfriend role, and Joe Pesci, in the hapless short-guy role, add
nothing to the insipid mix. Even tart-tongued comedian Chris Rock
and the chop-socky gymnastics of Jet Li can't generate enough sass
and spice.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Weapon'' movies were once hybrid action-comedies, but
what's lethal here is the extravagant lack of anything very funny.
Gibson and Glover are wretched comedians clearly tired of the
bullets-and-banter s htick. They painfully remind us of Jack Lemmon
and Walter Matthau getting back together in ``The Odd Couple II''
for patently mercenary motives.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson has never been more charmless (unless seeing Gibson
feigning a stereotypical Chinesying.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years since the series' zesty first installment, cops
Martin Riggs (Gibson) and Roger Murtaugh (Glover) are still a
bickering team. This time they're out to stop a Hong Kong triad
that's smuggling slave labor into America and printing piles of
counterfeit Hong Kong currency. It's as simple as that. It even
ends with the mandatory shootout in the bad guys' warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The other story threads concern Murtaugh's chronic aversion to
his pregnant daughter marrying a cop (enter Rock's wisenheimer
officer) and Russo and Gibson expecting a baby.
</P>
<P>
   In 12 years, Glover's Murtaugh hasn't changed much. He's still a
warmly gruff family man, with one eye on keeping his sitcom-happy
brood safe and the other on keeping his renegade partner in line.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Riggs has changed. The combustible cop, a
wounded, wild-eyed soul, has grown up. Originally, Riggs was a
suicidal, vaguely psychopathic officer who'd eagerly risk his life
to quash a crook. He was human TNT, an attractive character
withetic Hong Kong action idol, here reduced to a cipher _ is
exploited solely for his pin-wheeling legs. (Series director
Richard Donner hasn't a clue how to shoot a martial arts scene.)
</P>
<P>
   No fewer than five screenwriters pounded ``Lethal Weapon 4''
into a witless, rehashed pancake. You've seen it all before, and
better. Even with Gibson's massive Richard Marx 'do shorn, the
movie feels weirdly passe(accent).
</P>
<P>
   Like many summer blockbusters, it's trash and it knows it. But
it's not fun trash; it's recycled trash. Chris Garcia is the film
critic for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-10-98 1344E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
