<SLUG> BC-MILNER-BOOKREVIEW14-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMN: Autobiography sheds light on supporter of Kerrville Folk
Festival
</P>
<P>
   By Jay Milner
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Want a good coffee table book that people will actually pick up
and look through, at the pictures if not the text, although they'll
probably find time for the text as well?
</P>
<P>
   ``Music from the Heart,'' Rod Kennedy's autobiography, (Eakin
Press, $29.95 paper; $39.95 hardback), a 400 page book filled with
photos and illustrations on almost every page _ more than 500 in
all, tells the remarkably story of one man's dream and the people
who helped him achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   You've probably heard of the Kerrville Folk Festival, and maybe
you've attended one or more event over the course of the 25 years
that the festival has been around. But helping to organize Kerville
is not by any means all that Rod Kennedy is noted for.
</P>
<P>
   From a historical standpoint, the book reveals some interesting
twists in Texas history. It tells of Kennedy's fledgling FM radio
station, Texas's first radio stereophonic broadcast station.
Kennedy's company also built Austin's second television station _
Lyndon B. Johnson's competition.
</P>
<P>
   The book is liberally sprinkled with references to the author's
friends and acquaintances, including Cab Calloway and Carmen
Miranda. Kennedy's early belief in their careers _ and the talents
of Nanci Griffith, Riders in the Sky, Tish Hinojosa, Robert Earl
Keen, Lyle Lovett, Ray Wylie Hubbard, Townes Van Zandt to name a
few _ helped start their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's interests spread beyond music into car racing and his
collection in the late 1960s, which culminated in his Lancia team
winning the 1970 Sebring International Twelve Hours of Endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy tells of the first 25 years of the Kerrville Folk
Festival, spotlighting Michael Martin Murphey, Carolyn Hoester and
Jerry Jeff Walker. During the initial Kerrville festival, Kennedy
describes how he tried just about everything to provide cash to
support the event. It's all told and illustrated in this book, a
book that Pete Seeger called ``a remarkable achievement.'' Fred
Koller, writing in Performance Songwriter Magazine said, ``This is
the best book on the folk scene in America since David Gahr's long
out of print 'The Face of Folk Music.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
