<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROAD-ALBUMS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Highway to heaven? It can be a shorter trip with the right
tunes.
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As one who listens to music in a professional capacity _ namely,
as a critic for The Post _ I find that when I hit the road, I just
want to relax. I also factor in what my 6-year-old son will
tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in no particular order, are 10 of my favorites:
</P>
<P>
   1: Jimmy Buffett, ``Songs You Know By Heart'': When I moved to
Florida, my boss told me to pack some Buffett. I took her advice
and bought this delightful greatest hits collection. Whenever the
weather's just right, it makes for the quintessential tropical
listening. Warning: If you've got kids in the car, you may want to
turn the volume down on a ``Why Don't We Get Drunk and . . .''
(well, you know).
</P>
<P>
   2: Dave Matthews Band, ``Under the Table and Dreaming'': Rock
that truly rocks. This first album by Matthews and company finds
them at their most limber. The songs stretch on for minutes _ and
encourage you to take on the open road.
</P>
<P>
   3: Fleetwood Mac, ``The Dance'': If you grew up in the '70s, the
band is already woven into your past. This new live album preserves
the memories and adds to them a nostalgic bittersweetness. It's
music that takes you back and forward at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   4: The Bangles, ``Different Light'': No-frills pop from my
younger days. Every time I hear ``Walk Like an Egyptian,'' I have
to resist the temptation to let my hands off the wheel and do the
Babylonian boogie.
</P>
<P>
   5: Louis Prima, ``The Wildest'': Thanks to the recent swing
revival, everybody's starting to jump, jive and wail. But I've been
listening to this album in the car for years. Prima's wild-man
growl brings out the cool cat in anyone.
</P>
<P>
   6: Lou Reed, ``Walk on the Wild Side: The Best of Lou Reed'':
Maybe this ground-breaking New York rocker isn't most people's idea
of easy listening, but I find his edgy humor lightens any car ride.
And who can resist the spacious, string-laden ``Walk on the Wild
Side''?
</P>
<P>
   7: Spice Girls, ``Spice'': I'm not ashamed to admit I bought
this bubblegum-pop album for myself, not my kid. Then, he
discovered it and it shot to the top of our playlist. Even after
listening to it at least a dozen times straight on a trip to Fort
Myers Beach, I find the dance-pop grooves irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   8: The Beach Boys, ``Endless Summer'': I once put this greatest
hits collection on during the long haul to Key West. Listening to
such songs as ``I Get Around'' and ``California Girls,'' I found
the blue-green water seemed to sparkle even more.
</P>
<P>
   9: John Denver, ``The Wildlife Concert'': I consider the
unfairly maligned Denver the quintessential folkie in that his
songs were meant to be sung by everyday people. Put this two-album
live set on during a slow drive and you'll find it hard not to join
in the chorus of ``Rocky Mountain High'' and ``Country Roads.''
</P>
<P>
   10: Bruce Springsteen, ``The River'': Almost any Springsteen
will do for me on a car ride, but this classic double album
combines the best of Bruce: his blue-collar beat and his streetwise
lyricism.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
