<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2091 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROAD-BREAKDOWNS14-COX     07-13 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROAD-BREAKDOWNS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking the worry off the road: how to cope with breakdowns, pets
 &HT;    By Janis Fontaine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever you're getting ready to leave on a road trip, there are
worries, concerns _ questions. We did some research and took our
questions to some experts. Here's what we found out:
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IF I BREAK DOWN?
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Pembrook Burrows of the Florida Highway Patrol recommends
these tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ Look for a call box: Florida's Turnpike has call boxes every
mile. A computer tells the dispatcher exactly where you are when
you pull the switch. When walking to the box, walk against traffic
so you can see what's coming. Get as far off the highway as you
can. Carry a flashlight at night.
</P>
<P>
   When there are two adults, only one person needs to go. But if
you're traveling alone with kids, don't leave them. Raise your hood
to let people know you're having trouble. If you have a cell phone,
dial FHP toll-free. You'll need to know approximately where you are
_ what city, county or mile marker.
</P>
<P>
   If no one comes in an hour, call again. The dispatcher can give
an anticipated time it will take to respond. If there is a major
problem, the Highway Patrol gets assistance from the county
sheriff's office or local police.
</P>
<P>
   _ When your gas tank reaches one-quarter full, fill it up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use caution at rest areas: Most turnpike rest areas have
security. If you're on a different road, stick to rest areas with
lots of people. Don't leave your car running or unlocked.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you are traveling alone, plan your trip so that you arrive
by nightfall. Tell someone the route you're taking. Stick to it. If
you change your mind, call and let the person know.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ABOUT THE RECENT BRUSH FIRES?
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Lt. Burrows said:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fire: Monitor your car radio for information about any detours
you might encounter. The broadcast frequencies change depending on
where you are, so watch for signs along the turnpike. If you see a
fire, and there are no emergency workers call the FHP.
</P>
<P>
   _ Smoke: Depending on how thick the smoke is, you can drive
through it, but drive with caution. If workers are there, they will
stop you or wave you through.
</P>
<P>
   Should you need to detour, Burrows says signs and flares will
tell you where to go.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S THE BEST TIME TO TRAVEL?
</P>
<P>
   Early morning. It's cooler than midday, for one thing. Try to
avoid the rush hours of 7-9 a.m. or 4-6 p.m. especially around
large cities. And you'll likely find less congestion on the
turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IF I'M TRAVELING WITH SOMEONE WHO HAS SPECIAL NEEDS?
</P>
<P>
   Travelers who have medical needs can get help from Home Care
Medical Services Traveling Patient Care Program and programs like
it. People who need oxygen, walkers, wheelchairs or other medical
supplies can arrange to have the equipment waiting for them when
they arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We carry everything from gauze pads to full ventilators,''
said Phil Von Kahl of the patient-care program. ``Many of our
clients are people coming down from the north to go on cruises. We
meet them at the airport with the equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Check with your insurance company to see whether it covers these
expenses. And check the deductible, too. Call (800) 330-7738. Or
visit the Home Care Web site: www.healthtology.com/hcms/.
</P>
<P>
   WHICH PLACES ALLOW PETS?
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a quarter of the families who travel bring the family pet
along. Here are some resources that might help you find lodging:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Florida Dog Lover's Companion'' by Sally Deneen and
Robert McClure (Foghorn Press; $19.95) is available at bookstores
or by calling (800) FOGHORN. The 542-page guidebook lists cottages,
seasonal houses and inns along with a few chain hotels that accept
dogs. A new edition is being published in August.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another good guidebook is ``Vacationing With Your Pet''
($19.95 plus $3.95 for shipping; Pet-Friendly Publications), which
is available at bookstores or by calling (800) 496-2665. It lists
more than 23,000 hotels, motels, inns, ranches and bed and
breakfasts in the United States and Canada that welcome pets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
