</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROAD-PACKING14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pack with purpose
 &HT;    By Janis Fontaine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Medications. In addition to any prescriptions, don't forget
children's pain reliever and fever reducer. Keep your pharmacy's
number handy, too.
</P>
<P>
   Extra prescription glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency phone numbers such as your pediatrician's and the
number for poison control.
</P>
<P>
   Insect repellent.
</P>
<P>
   Sunglasses and sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   Roll-up sunshades for the back windows.
</P>
<P>
   First aid kit.
</P>
<P>
   Childproofing products, especially if you stay in a place with a
kitchen. And don't forget safety gates to keep children off
balconies and stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANCE PLANNING: DON'T LEAVE HOME WITHOUT IT
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, when Hurricane Andrew threatened to destroy South
Florida, I was visiting New Hampshire, enjoying the cool air, green
leaves and an ice-cold lake. I had made no storm preparations, so I
was panicked when I heard the weather report. I called some
neighbors, who tried to protect my personal belongings, but had the
storm come farther north, I would have lost everything.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some general precautions from Sentry Group,
manufacturers of fire safe security chests, for things to do
whenever you leave home:
</P>
<P>
   _ Have a plan. Ask a neighbor or friend if they will secure your
home if a storm is coming while you're away.
</P>
<P>
   Take photographs or make a videotape of your possessions
(computer, stereo equipment, TV, jewelry) for insurance purposes.
Keep the receipts, or copies of them, with the photos. And don't
store the records at home.
</P>
<P>
   _ Suspend mail and newspaper delivery. Nothing screams
``vacation!'' louder than newspapers piled up in the driveway or a
stuffed mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy a timer to turn your lights and a radio on and off. But
unplug your TV, computer and major appliances. They can be a fire
hazard. Plus, a lightning strike can harm them even when they're
turned off.
</P>
<P>
   PREPARE YOUR CAR:
</P>
<P>
   Your car is going to be ``home'' to you and your kids for at
least part of the trip. AAA Auto Club recommends that you give the
car a thorough checkup before you leave. Here are some things to
check:
</P>
<P>
   _ Examine tires for excess wear. Make sure all are properly
inflated. Check your owner's manual for proper tire inflation _ in
addition to being safer, properly inflated tires improve gas
mileage. Don't forget to check the spare tire, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check the oil, both the level and condition. You may want to
have the oil changed before you leave. And if you're traveling in
very hot (read, Florida) weather or you plan to haul a trailer,
switch to an oil with a higher viscosity. Again, check your owner's
manual for recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check the car's belts, looking for worn or cracked belts, and
hoses, or for blistered or soft hoses. Do this while the engine is
OFF.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check all fluid levels, including coolant and windshield
washer fluid. Fill them if they are low. Nearly half of AAA Auto
Club South's emergency road service calls are for overheated
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stock your car emergency kit. At a minimum, include these
items: two flashlights with extra batteries; warning devices such
as flares or reflective triangles; jumper cables. Carry a cellular
phone to summon help. It's the best emergency device.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCH YOUR TRIP:
</P>
<P>
   _ Plan your route. If you're a member of AAA, they'll provide
detailed maps of your route. If you're not a member, plan your trip
thoroughly. Use a highlighter to mark your route, a big help when
navigating busy roads or complicated interchanges.
</P>
<P>
   _ Call ahead to local visitors' bureaus or chambers of commerce
for information on interesting (and often inexpensive) local
events.
</P>
<P>
   _ Build your schedule around your kids' habits and routines,
says author Christine Loomis in her book Simplify Family Travel
(Reader's Digest, $17.95). When you stop for meals, avoid sit-down
restaurants, where the kids will be further confined. Instead,
choose a picnic area and make sandwiches. The food might not be
four-star, but the mood will be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
