A2097 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSPERITY-TAXES14-CO     07-13 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSPERITY-TAXES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big tax breaks benefit very poor and very rich
 &HT;    By Scott Shepard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton came to office promising to put
people first by ``honoring and rewarding those who work hard and
play by the rules.'' And in the current push for tax cuts on
Capitol Hill, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott repeatedly
characterizes GOP proposals as ``relief for working Americans and
their families.''
</P>
<P>
   But working Americans who have prospered _ particularly those
who have climbed into the ranks of those earning $75,000 to
$200,000 a year _ are finding that the rules don't work in their
favor.
</P>
<P>
   These Americans, who pay nearly half of federal income taxes,
are unable to take advantage of many tax breaks available to poorer
and richer Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tax income, we don't tax wealth,'' said Jeff Gates, an
Atlanta-based investment banker who was chief counsel to the Senate
Finance Committee in the 1980s and is the author of a new book,
``Ownership Solution,'' which promotes the idea of employee stock
ownership to combat America's growing income inequality.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in many ways high-earning Americans are hit harder under
the current federal tax structure than those with substantial
``unearned income'' from millions, or even billions, of dollars
worth of stocks and property obtained through employment or
inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   For example, multi-billionaire Warren Buffett has structured his
investment company in such a way that its more than $14 billion in
increased stock value has yet to be taxed by the federal
government. And it won't be taxed until it is sold, or
``realized.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 Taxpayer Relief Act, ballyhooed as a tax break for
middle-income earners, was nothing more than a Trojan horse to
reduce truly wealthy Americans' tax liabilities on their fortunes,
said Robert S. McIntyre, executive director of Citizens for Tax
Justice, a liberal public advocacy group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's centerpiece was a cut in capital gains taxes, paid on
the profits made when assets such as stocks or real estate are
sold.
</P>
<P>
   The tax on capital gains was cut last year from 28 percent to 20
percent. Under the old rate, it constituted $63 billion of the $737
billion in income taxes collected by the federal government last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Under tax proposals advanced this summer by House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., the top rate on capital gains would be further
reduced to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich characterized the capital gains cut as a ``powerful
motivation for every American to save and invest,'' noting that
``nearly half of all Americans own stock.''
</P>
<P>
   However, critics point out that the richest 1 percent of
American households own nearly 50 percent of the nation's net
worth, meaning a large part of the benefits of capital gains tax
cuts go to a fortunate few.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's proposal may not be enough to satisfy some in
Congress. A flat tax, sponsored by House Majority Leader Dick
Armey, R-Texas, would lower the top federal tax rate to 17 percent
and abolish federal inheritance and capital gains taxes altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
