</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROAD-AUDIO14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Listen up! Audio books make road seem shorter
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a driving vacation, a good audio book or three can save your
sanity, save your marriage and save you from wondering what you
could have been thinking when you decided to have kids. These books
on tape may end up being better than the trip.
</P>
<P>
   But kids may be the problem. Grade-schoolers won't be interested
in these subjects and parents certainly won't be interested in kids
listening to ``Lolita.'' The following tapes are for adults.
</P>
<P>
   But don't forget the kids. Most public libraries and every big
bookstore has an audio books section of classics such as ``Tom
Sawyer`` and ``Treasure Island.'' The classics make for great
listening no matter how old the traveler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela's Ashes'' by Frank McCourt, read by the author,
abridged, 4 1/2 hours, Simon &AMP; Schuster, $24. Note: an unabridged
version is also available.
</P>
<P>
   This book won everything for author McCourt and deservedly so.
This is a warm, funny recounting of growing up dirt-poor in Ireland
with an alcoholic father. From Depression-era Brooklyn to Limerick,
Ireland, this is an unforgettable story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruising Paradise, Tales by Sam Shepard,'' read by the author,
unabridged, two hours, Random House Audio, $16.
</P>
<P>
   This collection of stories about men and women living on the
fringes is as good as it gets for the written word. And Shepard's
reading of his own work ensures classic status. The border town
story ``Opuestos'' and the two-character story ``Just Space'' are
unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's stories, painted with details, trigger the
imagination. You can see rundown motels, smell the whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord of the Flies,'' by William Golding, read by Tim
Pigott-Smith, abridged, three hours, Faber-Penguin Audio, $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   Classic literature that's classic literature not only because
your teacher told you so. Mr. Pigott-Smith takes you to the coral
island where Piggy, Ralph, Jack and the other British boys create a
society with no rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds Like Murder.'' Mystery series from Random House Audio,
all unabridged, each two hours, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   This is the best idea since audio books. The ``Sounds Like
Murder'' mystery series opens with six tapes, each two hours and a
bargain at $12.95. The stories range from Ed McBain's ``Driving
Lessons,'' about a dangerous 16-year-old in love to the New York
Chinatown story ``A Tale About A Tiger'' by S.J. Rozan. ``Clean
American Fun'' is a murder in Branson, Mo. These are short-trip
books that are each worth the drive.
</P>
<P>
   June Thomson's ``The Case of the Scottish Tragedy'' is a mystery
that begins in Colombia and ends at a resort in Scotland. ``The
Sedgemoor Strangler,'' by Peter Lovesey, will have you guessing,
along with Sherlock Holmes and Dr. Watson, who solve the mystery of
who's killing off British barmaids. Stephen Solomita's ``The Poster
Boy'' has a veteran cop on the wrong end of a murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lolita'' by Vladimir Nabokov, read by Jeremy Irons,
unabridged, 11 1/2 hours, Random House Audio, $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   Even for the very long drive, you're going to tell yourself
there's no way you'd listen to Humbert Humbert's story about his
obsession with dangerous Dolores, Lolita. But this is writing that
makes it a deep regret to load in the last tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moby-Dick'' by Herman Melville. Read by William Hootkins,
abridged, six hours, Penguin Audiobooks, $23.95.
</P>
<P>
   Another classic that's also a great adventure and you can listen
to it without the high-school dread of writing a paper about the
symbolism. What it comes down to in the final analysis, students,
is that Captain Ahab was as weird about the great white whale as
Humbert Humbert was about Lolita. Ishmael's tale will live forever
and so will Lolita in the minds of every middle-aged man driving
his crabby wife and ingrate kids on another family vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
