<SLUG> BC-ROAD-LEAD14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Does your backseat look like a jungle?
 &HT;    By Janis Fontaine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're packed up and ready to roll out. Or are you?
</P>
<P>
   Have you crammed enough games in the back to keep the kids from
screeching all the verses of It's a Small World (aren't all verses
the same)?
</P>
<P>
   Do you have your prescriptions, phone numbers and SPF 30
sunscreen?
</P>
<P>
   Boy, do we have some tips for you.
</P>
<P>
   It might help to know you're not alone. There's a record number
of moms and dads on the road this summer (and some brave ones in
the air). More than 26 million Americans will take to the highways
for vacation this year. Half of those road trips wil will include
kids, according to AAA Auto Club South.
</P>
<P>
   So, we've decided to offer help (if not a Mickey Mouse bandage).
Let's hit the road!
</P>
<P>
   TAME GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Toobers&AMP;Zots, a wacky flexible foam construction game, comes
with a 20-piece set and a book of ideas and funny stories. (For
ages 5 and up; $14.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Koosh Color Change Markers (For ages 5 and up, $5 from Oddzon,
Inc.) My son likes these because you can use the white marker to
change the color of the other markers. And they have funny names,
too, like Oh My Black Eye and Plum Tuckered Out.
</P>
<P>
   Treasure Chests Knights kit lets you make your own catapult and
bomb the cardboard castle, too! The kit also contains materials to
make a signet ring, a book about medieval times and other goodies,
all locked inside a case. (For ages 5 and up, but probably more
appropriate for older kids; $19.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A plastic, see-through carry-all, ($11.95 from FeltKids Play
Systems) lets you keep all your stuff in one place. They also offer
bags that hang on the back of the seat with lots of pockets to keep
toys and games organized.
</P>
<P>
   Bedtime for Bunny Blue: This cute-as-can-be kit with travel
bunny, two books and music box in a traveling case can help make it
seem like bedtime no matter where you are. (For ages 3 and up;
$7.97.)
</P>
<P>
   Books on tape: Bring along your child's cassette player and
headphones and let him or her read along with the tape. My son
loves Star Wars stories and tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Baby-Sitters Little Sister Photo Scrapbook: This kit includes a
camera and scrapbook, but you can do the same thing with a notebook
and a disposable camera. (Ages 7 and up, $9.99, Scholastic.)
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry-making kits: The African Trade Bead Bracelet Kit
includes lots of beads, nylon and rubber cord, and an instruction
book. (For ages 8 and up, $10 from Curiosity Kits.) The Jewelry
Book kit contains beads, wires, clips and instructions and a
special keepsake box. (For ages 8 and up, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   Kids MagnePoem ($11.99) comes with more than 250 magnetic tiles,
plus a folding magnetic travel case. Have everyone write a poem and
read it out loud, or pass it around and take turns writing lines
for the same poem.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
