 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, July 14, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ Brief insights from the editor-in-chief
of Cox Newspapers. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ In Cincinnati Thursday July 9,
nearly 4,000 mourners paid their respects at a public visitation
service for Mary Jennifer Love. A neighbor in her Colerain Twp.
apartment complex, Ralph Lynch, 48, has been charged with rape and
murder in her strangulation death. In Santa Rosa, Calif., Tuesday
July 7, the body of Michael Patton was found dangling from a
redwood tree, a suspected suicide. The deaths forced me to confront
my profound ambivalence about Megan's Law, which requires the name
and address of convicted sex offenders to be open to the public.
(McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ I am one of those people who are regularly called
upon to practice random acts of photography and senseless acts of
documentation. I am one of those people to whom tourists
instinctively turn when they must trust a bystander, a stranger,
anyone to take their photograph in a new place before it all
disappears into the abyss of memory. (Lane, Daytona Beach
News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Today I find myself
wondering whatever happened to the old green sofa - the one we had
in the living room when I was a little girl. Odd thing to think of
but I guess it's because I've spent most of the day on the dining
room floor leaning against another old sofa. Elizabeth Schuett, a
teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio, is a regular contributor to
the Cox News Service. (Schuett, Cox News Service) (k)
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA -Political style counts, especially in
the South. When I told my 94-year-old south Georgia aunt that House
Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) did something good this week_
unveiled a plan for 48 miles of greenbelt along the Chattahoochee
River _ Autrey Lewis Randall huffed over the phone. ``He still has
Yankee manners,'' she said. (Ezzard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
