<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL BLACK ARTS FESTIVAL Moving in the (e) entertainment
category.
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-DRUMMER _ A feature that focuses on Chicago drummer Hamid
Drake, a new name to most but easily regarded as one of the world's
most in-demand percussionists on the jazz/improv/new music front.
Hamid will be performing the 16th and 17th as part of a three-day
jazz summit featuring European and American players whose lineage
stretches from the 60s to the 90s. Hamid is, in many ways, the one
degree of separation between various worlds (generational, racial,
national, etc.) represented by the music. (Dollar, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-DRUMMERSIDE _ A sidebar guide to the other artists could
accompany this, with selected discs, bio details, historical notes,
etc. (Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-VIDEO _ Under the heading ``Black At The Movies,'' cultural
critic/Vibe magazine contributor Harry Allen and musician/ Village
Voice columnist Greg Tate offer up their individual takes on music
video. Tuesday Allen screens his selection of the best music videos
in the history of hip-hop. And the next day Tate presents music
videos which in his opinion elevate the genre to storytelling art.
A talk with both beforehand about videos' reflection of and impact
on urban culture. And what part they play, if any, in the dearth of
rap live shows. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MONICA _ Interview with Monica, who's new album comes out July
14. (SoMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COILUMN _ Update from TV critics convention previewing
the new fall season in California. News from PBS. (Harris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Not expected to move until after 9 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   MILNER-BOOKREVIEW _ Want a good coffee table book that people
will actually pick up and look through, at the pictures if not the
text, although they'll probably find time for the text as well?
``Music from the Heart'' by Rod Kennedy (Eakin Press, $29.95 paper;
$39.95 hardback), a 400 page book filled with photos and
illustrations on almost every page _ more than 500 in all, tells
the remarkably story of one man's dream and the people who helped
him achieve it. (Milner, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ My college-bound son and I recently spent two
days discovering everything we wanted to know about his chosen
school but didn't have enough sense to ask. Given the 100-degree
weather, I had only one question: Do we have to leave this nice
air-conditioned auditorium and walk clear across campus to sign him
up for classes? (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GREIG-COLUMN _ AUSTIN _ Q: Couldn't we save trouble and time by
endorsing checks on the front, lower left? This would make it
easier to compare the information with the signatures. It would
also save the great difficulty in copying the back side, which
could be used as a deposit slip, saving tons paper and storage
space. What do you think? (And other questions compiled from the
week's consumer Q &AMP; A. (Grieg, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA FIRE
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-SURVEY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In 1989, state foresters
visited the woody lots of Palm Coast and asked its residents:
exactly how afraid of wildfire are you? Going door to door, they
handed out 200 surveys to homes most likely to burn if a blaze
broke out. Only 94 bothered to answer. Those who did conceded fire
was their biggest natural enemy. But the chance of a fire actually
occurring over the next 10 years, they wagered, was less than
fifty-fifty. (Staletovich, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   ALMOST-VEGETARIAN _ ATLANTA _ When Northside Hospital in Atlanta
offered a seminar called ``Almost Vegetarian'' on its roster of
health classes this summer, folks such as Cheryl Whitten made it an
immediate sell-out. Whitten is like a growing number of Americans
who don't want to swear off indulging on a steak occasionally, but
they are trying to work more meatless meals into their daily diets.
(Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY SERIES
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-RICH _ DAYTON, Ohio _ He drives a Mercury Sable
wagon, with three hubcaps and probably some junk in the back. His
designer label is more likely to be Levi than Armani, and for
lunch, the $5 salad, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Burton R. Saidel, the millionaire next door.
(Shepard/Gulliver, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-TAXES _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton came to office
promising to put people first by ``honoring and rewarding those who
work hard and play by the rules.'' But working Americans who have
prospered _ particularly those who have climbed into the ranks of
those earning $75,000 to $200,000 a year _ are finding that the
rules don't work in their favor. (Shepard, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-US _ How we have changed. Today's subject: The rich.
How many true millionaires do we have in the Miami Valley and how
are they spending their money? Are we reliving the 50s or have we
surpassed it? (Gulliver, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
