 &HT;    
 By THE EDITORS OF DISCOVER MAGAZINE  
 c.1998 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   In most species, the rules are pretty simple: Males try to mate
as often as possible; females, who must bear and provide for
offspring, seek to limit their mates to the best candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Mating systems have evolved over millions of years, as males and
females try to achieve their conflicting agendas. But what if all
members of a species have the same agenda?
</P>
<P>
   For hermaphrodites, says zoologist Nico Michiels, love is war.
</P>
<P>
   Michiels, who works at the Max Planck Institute for Behavioral
Physiology in Starnberg, Germany, studies hermaphroditic flatworms.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the literature on behavior and sexual conflict
focuses on species with separate sexes and there's very little
known about hermaphrodites,'' he says. ``People had assumed that
hermaphrodites are simply the sum of a male and a female. But the
conflicts hermaphrodites have are very different from those of
species with separate sexes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some hermaphroditic flatworms mate hypodermically _ that is, a
flatworm must jab its penis into its partner and inject sperm.
</P>
<P>
   The sperm courses through the loose tissue of a flatworm's body
until it reaches the ovaries.
</P>
<P>
   This mating method is not uncommon in flatworms, but researchers
didn't realize that mating could escalate into a violent contest.
</P>
<P>
   Michiels and Leslie Newman of the Smithsonian Institution's
National Museum of Natural History observed matings between 17
pairs of flatworms.
</P>
<P>
   When two flatworms meet, ``they rear up in this spectacular
posture, stick out their penises and try to stab each other,''
Michiels says. The flatworms feint and parry in a duel that can
last an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Michiels calls this behavior penis fencing. The flatworm that
successfully stabs its mate gets to fertilize eggs, while the worm
being stabbed has to bear the cost of healing its wounds and
producing offspring _ hence the fencing match.
</P>
<P>
   Flatworm mating, Michiels says, is ``a sexual conflict that has
almost gotten out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Michiels recently found another flatworm species with sperm so
aggressive that it eats its way through tissue, leaving gaping
holes in the body of the unlucky mate. A worm can lose up to
two-thirds its body mass in this manner.
</P>
<P>
   Penis fencing has been seen only in flat worms so far, but
Michiels suspects that other hermaphroditic species have also
evolved violent mating systems. ``Due to the identical but not
compatible interests of two mating partners,'' he says, ``you can
have sexual conflicts that escalate in a violent way, to an extent
that is not known in species with separate sexes.''
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
