<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2146 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZAPRUDER-JFK-FILM-NYT     07-13 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAPRUDER-JFK-FILM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE SEE IT ALL SO CLEARLY ... TOO CLEARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The bouquet of yellow roses. I never noticed the yellow roses
before _ tumbling around the presidential limousine as Jacqueline
Kennedy scrambles over the back seat and onto the trunk in a
panicked attempt to find pieces of her husband's brain and somehow
repair the horrific damage just done to him by the bullets that
exploded from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   We've all seen images from the Zapruder film; with the possible
exception of man landing on the moon, it may be the most famous
footage in our history. Yet we've never seen it like this. Never
seen the images in such gruesomely clear detail as the presidential
motorcade follows its fateful path through Dealey Plaza, while an
unseen Lee Harvey Oswald takes aim from the sixth floor of the
Texas School Book Depository.
</P>
<P>
   Some 35 years after dressmaker Abraham Zapruder stood near the
top of the grassy knoll, pointing his Bell &AMP; Howell 414PD Director
series, 8mm camera directly at President Kennedy's limo as the
shots rang out, his legendary film has been digitally enhanced and
showcased in a new 45-minute documentary, ``Image of an
Assassination: A New Look at the Zapruder Film,'' which goes on
sale today (July 13) and is expected to sell hundreds of thousands
of units.
</P>
<P>
   I obtained an advance copy from the MPI Media Group, the Orland
Park, Ill.-based company that produced the video. While the
documentary is padded somewhat with interviews and
less-than-riveting footage of the lab wizards working on the
project, it also includes fascinating details about what happened
to the film in the hours after the assassination and the decades
since then.
</P>
<P>
   And of course there's the improved edition of the Zapruder film
itself, shown several times. That alone is worth the $19.98 retail
price.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned, though: Frame 313, when that second shot hits Kennedy
and tears off so much of his skull, is more shocking and graphic
than the pretend-schlock you see in fictional drama, or even the
violent images on the evening news or in documentaries. It is not
for children or the squeamish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Image of an Assassination'' does a thorough job of chronicling
Zapruder's moves from the morning of Nov. 22 through the following
week. After the assassination, a semi-dazed Zapruder was walking
back to his office in the Dal-Tex Building across the street from
the Book Depository when he ran into a reporter for the Dallas
Morning News and told him about the footage he'd taken.
</P>
<P>
   They brought the film to WFAA, a local TV station affiliated
with the paper, thinking there might be facilities to develop it.
Zapruder was snagged for a live interview with the anchor on duty.
</P>
<P>
   While the anchor smokes a cigarette and listens to a hand-held
earpiece, Zapruder says, ``I heard a shot. He slumped to the side,
like this ... then I heard another shot, or two, I couldn't tell if
it was one or two. I saw his head practically open up, blood and
everything. I kept on shooting (film) ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV station couldn't develop the film so it was taken to
Kodak. In a move of astonishing clarity and calculation, Zapruder
obtained affidavits from Kodak and from the lab that developed the
film on the spot, stating that only three copies would be made.
Zapruder gave two copies to the government and kept one for himself
_ and in a matter of days, he had sold all rights to Time Inc., for
a total of $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Life magazine published still-frame photos, but the chairman of
Time Inc. didn't think the American public should see the film, so
it was out of circulation for years. The first time it was shown in
public was at the 1969 trial in New Orleans when Jim Garrison tried
(and failed miserably) to prove there was a conspiracy to
assassinate the president.
</P>
<P>
   Zapruder's widow and children regained the rights to the film in
the 1970s; they occasionally made copies available for a fee, and
are now negotiating with the government, which has offered $3
million for ownership of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, a deal was made to produce ``Image of an
Assassination,'' which has received tremendous hype in the last few
weeks. The images on the film were not altered in any way, but the
digital process removed scratches and hairs _ and the viewing area
is enlarged considerably because for the first time we can see the
section of the film between the sprocket holes. (Paranoid alert: A
few frames, damaged by previous archivists, are missing from the
original and thus are missing again here.)
</P>
<P>
   The ``new'' Zapruder film is shown once, twice, three times. In
slow motion. In close-up, focused just on Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   He waves to the crowd. A sign obscures our view for an instant _
and the next time we see the president, he is clutching at his
throat as his wife becomes aware that something is wrong. She is
tending to him with her white-gloved hands as the second shot rings
out.
</P>
<P>
   We see it all so clearly. Too clearly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
