earpiece, Zapruder says, ``I heard a shot. He slumped to the side,
like this ... then I heard another shot, or two, I couldn't tell if
it was one or two. I saw his head practically open up, blood and
everything. I kept on shooting (film) ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV station couldn't develop the film so it was taken to
Kodak. In a move of astonishing clarity and calculation, Zapruder
obtained affidavits from Kodak and from the lab that developed the
film on the spot, stating that only three copies would be made.
Zapruder gave two copies to the government and kept one for himself
_ and in a matter of days, he had sold all rights to Time Inc., for
a total of $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Life magazine published still-frame photos, but the chairman of
Time Inc. didn't think the American public should see the film, so
it was out of circulation for years. The first time it was shown in
public was at the 1969 trial in New Orleans when Jim Garrison tried
(and failed miserably) to prove there was a conspiracy to
assassinate the president.
</P>
<P>
   Zapruder's widow and children regained the rights to the film in
the 1970s; they occasionally made copies available for a fee, and
are now negotiating with the government, which has offered $3
million for ownership of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, a deal was made to produce ``Image of an
Assassination,'' which has received tremendous hype in the last few
weeks. The images on the film were not altered in any way, but the
digital process removed scratches and hairs _ and the viewing area
is enlarged considerably because for the first time we can see the
section of the film between the sprocket holes. (Paranoid alert: A
few frames, damaged by previous archivists, are missing from the
original and thus are missing again here.)
</P>
<P>
   The ``new'' Zapruder film is shown once, twice, three times. In
slow motion. In close-up, focused just on Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   He waves to the crowd. A sign obscures our view for an instant _
and the next time we see the president, he is clutching at his
throat as his wife becomes aware that something is wrong. She is
tending to him with her white-gloved hands as the second shot rings
out.
</P>
<P>
   We see it all so clearly. Too clearly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
