<HEADLINE>
PERCEPTION PERSISTS TEXAS JUSTICE IS FOR SALE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The more things change, the more they stay the
same. Or do they?
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years ago, when a national television program questioned
whether justice was for sale in Texas, the alleged buyers were
plaintiffs' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   They were making millions of dollars in eye-raising _ but
perfectly legal _ political contributions to Texas Supreme Court
justices and candidates and cashing in on court decisions that made
it easier to win big damage judgments for their consumer-clients
and lucrative fees for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that same TV show, CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' is getting ready to
take another look at justice, Texas-style, reportedly for airing
this fall. Producers already have been in Austin, asking more
questions about campaign contributions to judges and judicial
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican and civil justice revolution has transformed the
state's highest civil court and much of Texas' judicial system
since the previous ``60 Minutes'' segment was produced. But our
judicial campaign finance system remains as troubling an ethical
question _ and fodder for national entertainment _ as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys, doctors, insurance companies and other
business interests have long since replaced plaintiffs' lawyers as
the major fuelers of judicial races. And they have succeeded in
electing high court justices who have made it more difficult for
consumers to win large damage awards against doctors and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The same contributors also have convinced the Legislature to
enact major ``tort reform'' laws putting the brakes on plaintiffs
and their attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   All nine members of the Texas Supreme Court were Democrats and
most were philosophically aligned with plaintiffs' lawyers when the
``60 Minutes'' program aired in 1987. Now, seven of the nine are
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier ``60 Minutes'' program sharply criticized Texas law
for allowing elected judges to accept large campaign contributions
from lawyers who practiced before them. Some people have given that
program credit for spurring the widespread changes that were soon
to take place in the faces and political philosophies of Texas
judges.
</P>
<P>
   Such credit, however, may be overblown.
</P>
<P>
   The program certainly beefed up some campaign ads for Republican
judicial candidates, but its overall significance may have been a
matter of timing more than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   The show aired just as Republicans were beginning to make
significant inroads in the lower Texas courts and campaign
contributions from civil justice reformers were beginning to make
their mark in judicial elections.
</P>
<P>
   It also aired on the eve of some of the most critical elections
ever held for the Texas Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Three Democrats, including Chief Justice John Hill, resigned
from the Supreme Court in 1987 and 1988, giving then-Gov. Bill
Clements, a Republican, the opportunity to replace them with
Republican appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Those appointments broke the solid Democratic hold on the high
court and gave the Republicans a headstart on the 1988 judicial
elections. The GOP won three of the six court seats on the ballot
that year and has never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   But, despite the political and philosophical transformation, the
overriding problem persists:
</P>
<P>
   Texas judges and judicial candidates still run in partisan
elections and still take large amounts of campaign contributions
from lawyers and other interests with high stakes in the
judiciary's decisions. Only now, the shoe is on the other foot.
</P>
<P>
   According to recent reports by consumer and campaign finance
reform advocates, the Texas Supreme Court now heavily favors
business defendants over consumers and justices receive significant
contributions from sources with interests in pending cases.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court justices and their supporters say the reports are
flawed and unfair and deny that the court's decisions are
influenced by political donations. They say that none of the
court's critics have been able to link a campaign contribution to a
specific decision.
</P>
<P>
   And supporters point out that most, if not all, of the current
justices favor dumping the partisan election system in favor of
gubernatorial appointments with retention elections. But they have
been unable to convince the Legislature to do that _ or to persuade
Gov. George W. Bush to join their reform effort.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Legislature imposed campaign contribution
limits in judicial races, but they are too weak to make much of a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   The names, faces and labels may have changed since the ``60
Minutes'' cameras first focused on the Texas judiciary, but the
same perception _ that some people may be trying to buy and sell
justice in Texas _ persists.
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions can't replace integrity, but they can destroy the
public confidence that integrity deserves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
