<HEADLINE>
PETS ARE SAFE ALOFT BUT MISS THE FUN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even when the old bones are creaking in the midsummer heat, I
can always depend on a reader to elicit a chuckle, albeit on a
serious subject.
</P>
<P>
   Texas resident Wanda Odom's recent letter, for instance: ``My
husband and I would like to take our little pet poodle with us when
we travel by plane,'' Odom wrote. ``But because of the terrifying
stories we hear of pets dying in the heat or extreme cold or
getting out of their cages and being lost, we hesitate to take
Rusty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please try to find out the real truth for us,'' she continued.
``Maybe even ride down in that compartment to see how the situation
really is!''
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness Wanda added a ``just kidding'' to that last
request. I'd hesitate giving up my assigned seat on the wing where
I can check for any engine malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, Odom and countless others who cherish exploring the
world with their dogs can take comfort in knowing that Rusty likely
will be well cared for on airplanes. Most folks who load and unload
carriers love pets, too. And a few common-sense precautions can
ease the journey, according to Eileen Barish, author of several
books that focus on pet travel, including ``Vacationing With Your
Pet and Doin' Texas With Your Pooch'' (Pet-Friendly Publications,
each $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   Among Barish's recommendations:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Ascertain individual airline policies _ including allowable
carrier size _ well in advance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Book nonstop flights.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Select early-morning or late-evening flights in summer and
afternoon flights in winter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Don't feed your dog for at least six hours prior to
departure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Don't give your dog any medications not prescribed by a
veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Fill the water tray in the dog's carrier with ice cubes, not
water, to prevent spillage during loading.
</P>
<P>
   It is a shame that Rusty, according to Odom, ``is a little too
big to fit under the seat.'' Not because of any dangers in the
cargo hold, though, but because he'll miss out on all the
excitement in passenger cabins these days.
</P>
<P>
   First came several much-publicized revelations of fisticuffs at
35,000 feet. Then, a Wall Street Journal report concentrated on
passengers confusing their aisle and window seats for a boudoir.
(``It's uninhibited up there,'' a former United Airlines flight
attendant said.) Another passenger sought a different form of
mile-high entertainment: He tried to board carrying a bowling ball.
</P>
<P>
   Are air travelers confused? InsideFlyer magazine reports the
following ideas have been suggested to Houston-based Continental
Airlines: glass-bottomed aircraft for better viewing, roll-down
windows so passengers can feel the breeze, and soundproofed
children's sections. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Only the pilots seem serene. Alas, so serene that recent
studies conducted by NASA and federal aviation experts indicate
that one in seven pilots has nodded off in the cockpit,
particularly on overnight international flights.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Asiana Airlines has the right idea about keeping pilots
awake. And maintaining passenger control.
</P>
<P>
   For Asiana's new onboard entertainment program on flights
between Los Angeles and South Korea, according to Business Traveler
magazine, 16 flight attendants with musical and artistic talents
have been selected to perform live magic shows, sing and play
instruments, lead stretching exercises, coordinate birthday
celebrations and entertain children with face-painting and cartoon
drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't Rusty have a blast?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
