<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2158 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-13 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME MAGNOLIAS CAN TAKE YEARS TO BLOOM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: I have a magnolia that is 13 years old. It seems
healthy and grows well but never bloomed until last year, when it
produced two blooms. Is there anything I can do to induce
flowering?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some magnolias, especially seedlings, can take years to
bloom. Those planted in sun flower best. Magnolias prefer an
acidic, loose soil. Add organic matter to enrich the soil. Apply a
12-24-12 fertilizer in early spring to encourage blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was given a plant without a name. I've given several people
a start. It multiplies quickly but can be kept under control by
pulling the plants up where I don't want them. Before the flower
opens, it looks like many dark purple seeds all over the top. They
burst open to a lilac color, so it is pretty in the different
stages of bloom. It is 4 to 5 feet tall in good soil.
</P>
<P>
   A: You have one of the clerodendrums. Match yours to one of the
following descriptions: ``Clerodendrum bungei,'' or cashmere
bouquet, is a shrubby perennial that has clusters of red-purple to
deep pink flowers in summer. It matures to about 5 feet and spreads
by suckers. The large, serrated, heart-shaped leaves have a bad
smell if crushed.
</P>
<P>
   The similar fragrant glorybower, ``Clerodendrum fragrans
pleniflorum,'' tolerates various soils and produces large,
hydrangealike clusters of small pinkish blooms. Some dislike the
odor. The leaves are large, up to 10 inches, and look like those of
``C. bungei.'' This plant also spreads by root suckers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: &UR;  &LR; This spring I bought my first gazania daisy and planted it
in a barrel with several other bedding plants. It's in full sun
through noon with shade in late afternoon. It bloomed profusely and
was a great delight. I was away and let the barrel dry out for two
days. The gazania died while nothing else even looked stressed. I
was in nurseries in June and saw dozens of gazanias dying.
</P>
<P>
   Did my gazania die from lack of water? Is this the natural time
of year for it to die? Is this climate unsuitable for a gazania no
matter what you do? Is it an annual or a perennial? I would like to
have more next year if possible.
</P>
<P>
   A: Gazania daisies come in bold yellow, red and orange as well
as pink, bronze and bicolors. Blooms generally appear well into
fall, but I don't see much action among mine in this insufferable
heat. Those blooms that might open are smaller than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Gazania flowers close at night. Foliage is narrow and is green
above and gray below; some varieties have silver leaves.
</P>
<P>
   It took me awhile to find the right spot in our garden for these
South African natives. The key, I found, to growing these
drought-tolerant plants here is excellent drainage. Given this, the
plants may prove short-lived perennials. Those that have done best
are planted on the sloping side of a bed and around rocks. They are
watered when the rest of the bed is watered, but the excess
moisture drains quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hurd at JJL Greenhouse, a wholesale company in Houston,
says he's found that gazanias dislike competition and organic
mulch. He suggests mulching with gravel. If you plant more next
spring, do not crowd the gazanias with other bedding plants.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some of the above factors contributed to the sudden
demise of your gazanias. Quick death is not uncommon with these
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the nursery stock you saw was overwatered as workers
tried to compensate for the heat and drought. Add that extra water
to high humidity and the plants may have drowned. Or the small pots
may have parched in the scorching heat, and the plants were not
watered in time.
</P>
<P>
   Gazania flowers are so striking, I would give them another go
when healthy plants are again available. Morning sun and shade in
the hot afternoon is ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have two plum trees, a Methley and a Santa Rosa, that are 3
years old. Both are about 10 feet tall. To this date neither has
produced fruit. This year I got a few blooms on one tree.
</P>
<P>
   A: Plums usually take three to five years to begin fruiting, so
yours may be a little young yet. `Santa Rosa' produces quality
fruit and is said to be a good pollinator for other varieties.
However, keep in mind that it can fall victim to bacterial canker
within 10 years. The `Methley,' too, is a good-tasting plum and is
disease-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a dilemma as to what pest is eating my photinias. All
the leaves look like lace or have been chewed, no matter how tall
the plant is. I have sprinkled snail bait around the plant and
sprayed, but nothing helps. I cannot see a pest.
</P>
<P>
   A: &UR;  &LR; If the leaves are skeletonized, a beetle or the larva of a
beetle or moth may be at work. Leaf beetles will leave only the
skeleton of a leaf; caterpillars, the larvae of various insects,
will do the same. Flea beetles are tiny, hopping black insects that
eat holes in leaves. Beetles can be hard to spot as some move
quickly when they know you're coming.
</P>
<P>
   When you approach a shrub, run your hand over the branches and
watch for escaping pests; maybe you can see what's at work. If it's
a small beetle, look for an insecticide that targets these pests.
</P>
<P>
   If you see caterpillars, use ``Bacillus thuringiensis,'' or Bt.
</P>
<P>
   Lace bugs, which look like their name, will suck the juice from
leaves, leaving white or yellow stipling on the tops of the
foliage. The pests leave black excrement on the undersides. Spider
mites cause similar damage, but these are difficult to see. Hard
sprays from the water hose, directed to the undersides of the
foliage, will discourage both pests. Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   There are pesticides such as rotenone that help control these,
too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. Due to the bulk of mail,
unpublished letters cannot always be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
