<HEADLINE>
AVOID CONSUMER CREDIT-PROPERTY INSURANCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If you bought an appliance using credit, you may have
purchased insurance you never knew you bought.
</P>
<P>
   It's called consumer credit-property insurance and it pays if
property, such as a computer, refrigerator or stereo, is stolen or
damaged while the loan is being paid off.
</P>
<P>
   The coverage is generally sold by department stores and
specialty stores marketing such goods as electronics, furniture and
appliances.
</P>
<P>
   This is one form of insurance you should avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible stuff,'' said J. Robert Hunter, former Texas
insurance commissioner and now director of insurance at the
Consumer Federation of America in Washington, D.C. ``It's
high-priced, and it was my experience in Texas especially that it
tends to be poor people down in the Valley who end up buying all
this stuff because people don't even know they're buying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers normally don't even have a chance to say no because
they are not told they are buying the insurance. But that should be
changing soon. Starting in January, rates and policy forms will
fall under the eye of the Texas Department of Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found was that there was a very low claim total on
this type of policy, which made us suspect that a lot of people
didn't know what they were purchasing when they purchased it,''
said Jim Davis, spokesman for the insurance department.
</P>
<P>
   The measure of claims paid for credit property insurance, known
in the industry as ``loss ratios,'' range from as low as 2 percent
to as high as 50 percent. A ratio of 2 percent means that for every
dollar you pay in premiums, the insurance company returns 2 cents
to you in the form of benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the property/casualty marketplace, what we like to see are
loss ratios around 75 percent,'' said Rod Bordelon, head of the
Office of Public Insurance Counsel in Austin, a state agency that
represents consumers on insurance matters.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the low-claims level is that this coverage
duplicates the protection in a homeowners or renters insurance
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, retailers will have to tell consumers
clearly that credit property insurance may duplicate coverage on
their homeowners or renters policy.
</P>
<P>
   They'll also have to tell you how much the insurance costs, that
you have the right to cancel the policy at any time, and that this
insurance is supposed to pay for any covered property before your
homeowners coverage kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that makes this insurance a bad deal is that
frequently the premium payments for credit-property insurance are
tacked on to a consumer's loan, which often goes on a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   But as you buy other items on your credit card, your balance
goes up, which increases your premium. This is a bad deal since
credit-property coverage will only pay off if the item you bought
is damaged, Bordelon said.
</P>
<P>
   Credit-property insurance can be called several names, including
a ``buyer protection program.''
</P>
<P>
   The way to make sure it's not on the tab is to ask whether
you're paying for something in addition to the item you bought. But
that's easy to forget because you're often distracted when paying
for something.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're focused on whatever it is you're buying, and they slide
this thing in with usually inadequate disclosure,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   That's how three insurance companies owned by Montgomery Ward
got in trouble with Texas insurance regulators earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators said the insurers encouraged customers to buy a
``Credit Security Plan'' by signing a line on charge account slips,
without informing them that they were buying insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Montgomery Ward insurers, without admitting wrongdoing,
consented to an enforcement order by regulators and agreed to
refund as much as $5 million to consumers who unwittingly bought
the insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the premium you pay for the coverage is split up as money
for the insurance company and a commission for the retailer that
sold you the insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a rule at the Consumer Federation of America: Don't
ever buy insurance from somebody who's trying to sell you something
else,'' Hunter said. ``There's usually a huge kickback to whomever
is selling you the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   If a retailer sold you the coverage without your knowledge, you
can complain to the insurance department by calling 800-252-3439.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
