<SLUG> BC-INVEST-MORALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS BOARD JOINS TREND OF OPTING FOR `FEEL GOOD' INVESTMENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When the Texas Board of Education decided to dump $43
million in Walt Disney Co. stock last week because of moral
concerns, it joined a growing trend in the investment world.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend some say is being fueled in part by aging baby
boomers who grew up in the world of civil rights and environmental
sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, it's a trend supported by investment managers
who have shown that they can invest responsibly without having to
sacrifice strong investment performance, financial analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money invested in socially screened investment
portfolios between 1995 and 1997, for example, more than tripled
from $162 billion to $529 billion, according to the Social
Investment Forum, a nonprofit organization of investment
professionals dedicated to responsible investing.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more investors and consumers are realizing the link
between their money and many of the social problems we face,'' said
Ross Gaskin, managing director of the Social Investment Forum in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who opt for ``feel good'' investments use a fairly
complex set of benchmarks to evaluate a company's practices,
including its commitment to the environment, labor relations,
diversity and the community.
</P>
<P>
   But social consciousness must be balanced against financial
common sense, said Peter Kinder, president of Kinder, Lydenberg,
Domini &AMP; Co. in Cambridge, Mass., which provides social research on
U.S. and foreign corporations to investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, you must be socially responsible, but I must also be a
responsible investor, and if you're going to apply social screens
to your investments, you should not reduce the quality of your
financial screens,'' he said. ``You really don't have to give up
performance in order to have social screens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Domini 400 Social Index, created by Kinder's firm, consists
of the stocks of 400 corporations that have passed a socially
responsible test of sorts. The index was up 5.2 percent in June,
beating the 4.1 percent gain of Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should divest blindly and without regard for what the
financial implications are,'' Kinder said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney stock has been on a tear. It rose a whopping 45 percent
in the last year, zooming past the 29.7 percent return of the S&AMP;P
500.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Disney shares split 3-for-1 Friday, rising 1 1/8 to
close at 38 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were advising my clients, I would recommend that they not
sell the stock but that they use the weakness in the price to add
to their positions,'' said Linda Bannister, an analyst who follows
Disney for the Edward Jones brokerage firm in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   In evaluating the social conscience of companies, investment
firms that engage in ethical investing apply thorough methods.
</P>
<P>
   At the Calvert Group in Bethesda, Md., for example, money
managers submit the names of financially attractive stocks to the
company's analysts, who then examine the companies' performance in
such areas as environmental responsibility, labor relations,
discrimination and community responsibility, said Elizabeth
Laurienzo, Calvert spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The company also won't invest in firms in the alcohol, tobacco
and gambling industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't like to think of it as a moral issue,''
Laurienzo said. ``It's more of a quality-of-management issue. We
feel that companies that have managements that pay attention to
these types of issues,'' and care about their employees, ``are
going to be successful in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
