<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM'S MYTHIC DEFECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOB ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Time magazine and CNN have retracted their joint
story claiming a U.S. Special Forces unit dropped sarin nerve gas
at an encampment in Laos in order to kill American military
defectors.
</P>
<P>
   Based on an eight-month investigation, the repudiated report
relied heavily on one source: former Lt. Robert Van Buskirk, who
claimed he killed two of the ``beaucoup roundeyes'' when they
slipped into an underground tunnel system.
</P>
<P>
   There were about 20 defectors at the camp, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When this hit the news in early June, I thought the nerve gas
allegation plausible. Given the use of napalm, defoliants and B-52
carpet bombing runs during America's longest war, the clandestine
use of nerve gas would be within the realm of possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But I was struck that any journalist could buy the notion that
20 American military defectors would somehow show up at the same
secret place.
</P>
<P>
   How would they know where this sanctuary was located? Did they
walk through the war zone in Vietnam to Laos? What was the place
called, the Peace &AMP; Freedom Hotel? Did they check in with Tom
Hayden at the front desk?
</P>
<P>
   Van Buskirk's account sounds to me like a soldier's tale that
has grown richer over time. And April Oliver, the producer for CNN,
bolstered the lieutenant's credibility with additional amazing
snippets and soundbites neatly edited to fit her predetermined Gas
&AMP; Traitor agenda.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, Van Buskirk's story reminded me of a famous
defector I heard about when I served as a photographer in 1966 with
the Third Marine Division in Vietnam. I was attached to a photo lab
in Da Nang, but spent a lot of time out in the boonies snapping
pictures of the war.
</P>
<P>
   I was regaled with all sorts of wild rumors while sitting in a
circle with a bunch of grunts eating C-rations and smoking free
cigarettes supplied by the patriotic tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Tales of medical supplies found with Berkeley, Calif., postmarks
in a Viet Cong stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   Lurid details of genital mutilation on Marines overrun by the
enemy. Resentment over another company's supposed access to more
than two beers a man at an enlisted men's canteen.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the rumors circulating in the Asian mudhole, the one I
heard most often concerned the ``White Cong.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemed everybody in the ``Crotch,'' as it was lovingly called by
Marines, had heard about this guy. Although a traitor, this mythic
Marine fit the Iwo Jima image: macho, brave, willing to take great
risks.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't hiding out in Laos. He was with the Viet Cong shooting
back at us.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knew his name or what outfit he supposedly defected from.
He was said to be a big guy with blond hair. (Van Buskirk's
``victim'' also had blond hair: ``Looks like he was running off a
beach in California.'')
</P>
<P>
   I wanted more details. After a few days out with an infantry
company, I'd make an inquiry if the story of this elusive character
didn't come up in conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Some guys had heard about him. If not, my bringing it up was
grist for the mill. I may have done more to perpetuate the myth of
the White Cong than anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, when I did hear about him it was always second-hand or,
more likely, sixth-hand. On two occasions I spoke with Marines who
claimed they had seen the blond gunner in black pajamas pop out
from behind a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them could give Van Buskirk a run for his money. As the
White Cong story unreeled, the gleam in their eyes _ along with
rolling eyes of their comrades _ confirmed it was all smoke.
</P>
<P>
   I heard about the White Cong in the ancient imperial capital of
Hue near the Demilitarized Zone separating South and North Vietnam,
in the hills and jungles around Da Nang, and in the rice paddies
that seemed to stretch clear to the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The White Cong crisscrossed more terrain than I did. But I
jumped from place to place by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   How he did this on foot remains a mystery. Well, not really. I
suppose he rode on a magic carpet, an M-16 in one hand and in the
other a Viet Cong flag, rippling in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in my grimmer moments, I kind of wanted to believe the
blond traitor was out there, like some spirit of Death &AMP; Fire
reeking revenge on the Crotch. And what a photograph that would
have been!
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Armstrong is the editor of Exotica, a San Francisco adult
entertainment magazine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
