<HEADLINE>
MODERN IRONING BOARD THE BRAINCHILD OF A FORMER SLAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ To achieve a properly ironed look for bed, table
or garment, it's essential to have a proper ironing board and not
to use a bed or a folded towel on a countertop for ironing.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Seymour Housewares Corp. in Indiana,
approximately 5.7 million ironing boards are purchased each year in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Early ironing boards simply consisted of a wooden plank placed
across two chairs or a plain table top.
</P>
<P>
   The early collapsible-leg, padded, wooden ironing board was the
brainchild of Sarah Boone, a former slave, who patented her idea in
1892. Soon, the ironing board was modified and tapered at one end,
to accommodate delicate garment pieces and shapes. Because of damp
or wet clothing, the boards would often warp from moisture
absorption. By the late 1920s, boards were lacquered to seal them.
</P>
<P>
   Solid metal ironing boards of the 1950s eliminated the problem
of warpage, but they sometimes buckled under the heat and tended to
collect condensation under the padding. Today's wire mesh surfaces
allow the moisture to dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   A deluxe ironing board with an expanded mesh metal top, 100
percent cotton cover and extra thick steam-permeable felt pad,
built-in cordminder, four legs for stability and dual position iron
rest costs approximately $69.99.
</P>
<P>
   Other metal ironing boards without all of the bells and whistles
cost from about $19.99 without a cover to $49.99.
</P>
<P>
   Ironing boards with a stable T-leg design (instead of four legs)
cost about $14.99.
</P>
<P>
   If you hate lugging the ironing board out every time you have to
use it, then a space-saving over-the-door model may be for you.
This one costs $29.99. It installs quickly and folds up and down
instantly, like models that were built into narrow wall closets in
some older homes.
</P>
<P>
   For quick touch-ups, there's a table/counter top model for $4.99
with legs that fold for easy storage.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there's a small padded folding board for $10.99 that's
just for sleeves and collars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
