<SLUG> BC-TEENAGE-DRIVERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PUTS TEEN DRIVERS' LIVES IN HARM'S WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VERONICA FLORES  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Is a teen-ager prepared to drive?
</P>
<P>
   As more teen-agers die in traffic accidents, I'm convinced the
answer is no. But tell that to the Texas Legislature, which last
year turned back a proposal for a graduated license system. It was
one that would impose restrictions, then ease them as teen-agers
gained more experience behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers ignored the bloody facts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, motor vehicle accidents became the leading cause of
death for Texas teens, surpassing deaths by handguns and drugs. The
national auto death rate for 16-year-olds, meanwhile, doubled
between 1975 and 1996, from 19 per 100,000 licensed drivers to 35
per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers point to a pattern in behavior that strongly
suggests many teens may not be prepared to handle the
responsibility of driving.
</P>
<P>
   _ The invincibility factor: Teens often believe no harm can come
to them, an attitude that safety experts say is reflected in
seat-belt use. The Texas Department of Public Safety reported that
58 percent of teens killed in car accidents in 1996 weren't wearing
their seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other young people in the car: Studies indicate that a car
filled with teens is a recipe for disaster, raising the likelihood
of an accident by up to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speed: After laws raised the speed limit on highways to 70
mph, traffic fatalities among teens increased 38 percent in Texas,
from 373 deaths in 1995 to 514 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen states now have some limits on teen drivers, with
California, Florida, Georgia, Michigan, North Carolina and Ohio
cited by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety for including
critical elements of a ``proper'' three-step program.
</P>
<P>
   Those include prohibitions against nighttime driving and a ban
on carrying other teens in the same vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But not in Texas. Permissive laws make it easy for teens to
drive. Too easy. Driver's education now largely is handled by
private enterprise with little oversight to ensure teens are
getting proper instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, the dreaded driving test with the uniformed state trooper
isn't even part of the rite of passage as it was for me and many
others. Nothing like a state trooper sitting next to you to make
you drive the speed limit and wear your seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at my own experience as a teen-age driver _ marked
by two memorable wrecks _ I wish I had waited. Then I might have
known better than to follow so closely behind the car I wound up
rear-ending when it stopped abruptly on the highway to avoid
hitting a dog. And I could have known to turn the wheel in the
direction of a skid that, on one drizzly day, caused me to
sideswipe a parked car.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, even adult drivers may not know how to control such
situations. But state lawmakers now are leaving teens' lives to
chance. That's not a risk parents should let them take with their
children.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Veronica Flores is a columnist for the San Antonio
Express-News, P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
