<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2195 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-COURSE-BOS &LR;      07-13 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COURSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PLAYING IT SAFE DOWN THE BACKSTRETCH OF HIS TENURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ Full of energy, intensity, and maybe even
mischief, Bill Clinton has all the characteristics of the classic
risk-taker in his personal life. But as he approaches the midpoint
of his second, and final, term, the president is seeming
risk-averse.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton clings to safe issues: the struggle against drugs, the
effort to keep guns out of schools, the fight to preserve Social
Security. He shies away from confrontation with Congress _ a
quality more dramatic than ever since he was stung by his failure
to win approval of his tobacco bill.
</P>
<P>
   The president who came to office as an apostle for change has a
political style that whispers, ``Stay the course.'' The president
who promised an activist approach now mostly reacts.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this is strategy; politicians naturally gravitate toward
popular issues. Some of it reflects reality; leaders of the
Republican Congress cooperated with Clinton last year only to see
him steal the thunder _ and the applause _ and they aren't eager to
give the president a break now.
</P>
<P>
   But some of it is also cold calculation: There's a strong belief
inside the White House this summer that the president shouldn't
risk his political capital at the moment because he may need it
later to battle new revelations, developments, or twists in the
investigations being conducted by independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Popularity is like capital,'' says Abraham Zaleznik, professor
emeritus of leadership at Harvard Business School. ``Sometimes you
don't spend it, and sometimes you only spend it when you get back
even more _ greater prestige, more willingness to suspend
disbelief, the ability to get people to listen and pay attention to
the next initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   Under scrutiny from an office examining his private and
financial affairs, under criticism from Republicans eager to
protect their congressional majorities in the fall midterm
elections, under siege from reporters and commentators, President
Clinton nonetheless remains remarkably popular. The latest CNN/Time
Poll shows that more than three out of five respondents approve of
the job he is doing as president. His ratings are higher now than
they were last October, before Monica S. Lewinsky became a
household name.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking inside the White House today: We may need 10 or 20
of those popularity percentage points if Lewinsky makes a deal for
immunity, or if new damaging disclosures emerge, or when Starr
makes his long-awaited report to Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not crazy not to want to take risks that might lead to
big mistakes,'' says Geoffrey Garin, a Democratic political
pollster who nonetheless adds: ``Generally there's a bigger risk in
standing still than in moving forward. Even in good times there's a
political downside to not having a clear agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, moreover, no guarantee that such a strategy _
political capital conservation, you might call it _ will work.
</P>
<P>
   Popularity isn't fungible; it has a modest shelf life and can't
be put in cold storage for periods of time. Clinton should know
these properties of popularity; his own ascension to the White
House was built on a challenge to an incumbent president who tried
to conserve his popularity and live off it as times changed rapidly
_ and as perceptions of him changed irrevocably.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush enjoyed stratospheric approval ratings in the
months after the 1991 Gulf War, and then he embarked on a concerted
strategy to preserve those ratings. For a while, it worked; so
great was Bush's popularity that many of the leading Democrats,
including Senators Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and Al Gore of Tennessee
and Representative Dick Gephardt of Missouri, declined to enter the
presidential race in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Bush cobbled together a modest domestic agenda after the war.
His big initiative in spring 1991: a highway bill so unremarkable
that it prompted catcalls of derision in the capital. Those
popularity rating points evaporated like dew at midmorning. He was
defeated decisively by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush did, Clinton faces a Congress of the opposite party, and
the Republicans who rule Capitol Hill, so compliant in the spring
of 1997, have made no gestures of hospitality to the president in
1998. ``Clinton is working against a very retrogressive Congress,''
says Sherman Lewis, a political scientist at California State
University at Hayward. ``Much of politics is practicing the art of
the possible, and Clinton is trying to do what's possible. If more
were possible, he'd be even bolder. If less were possible, he'd be
even more wimpish than he is now.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's supporters argue that his trip to China itself
represented a foreign policy risk. It is true that many Republican
critics urged the president not to go. But it is also true that
American presidents seldom are criticized while they play the
statesman role abroad, and Clinton could count on stunning visual
images everywhere, from the terra-cotta warriors to the Great Wall
to Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the prevailing political culture gives little impetus
for risk-taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are huge hedges these days against risk-taking,'' says
Maury Klein, a historian at the University of Rhode Island who
specializes in 20th-century American politics. ``A hundred years
ago presidents went with what a small group of people around them
and his own gut told him. Today you don't do anything without a
statistical consensus. ... Today you don't approach a decision, but
you look for a certain reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's reluctance to mount bold proposals is no
character flaw. At the end of the month, the John F. Kennedy
Library and Museum will hold a remarkably celebratory retrospective
on Calvin Coolidge; the 29th president will be saluted for his
reluctance to offer the very sort of new departures that Clinton is
resisting in the waning days of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Coolidge, who didn't cultivate an image of a creative
innovator, Clinton campaigned as an activist.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Clinton possesses many traits of the classic risk-taker.
Psychologists have found that such people are motivated by
intensity, variety, novelty, and ambiguity _ a crisp, serviceable
description of the lifestyle and political style of a man like
Clinton, who studies hard, moves from subject to subject, and isn't
a slave to clear policy positions. Risk-takers, moreover, often are
high-energy personalities, and Clinton has a higher energy level
than any president in history.
</P>
<P>
   That the president seems risk-averse may not be as much of a
contradiction as it seems. ``Risk-takers have inner control,'' says
Frank Farley, a psychologist at Temple University. ``And they may
be able to turn off the risk-taking _ particularly when they want
to live for another exciting day. Clinton may be worried about
blowing it and may have throttled back his risk-taking propensity
for another purpose: survival.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, his advisers agree, like most presidents at the
end of a second term, is running for a place in history. But they
aren't won by campaigns. They're won by action, or vision, or
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a writer saying that he's going to write a
bestseller,'' Kleinsays. ``It doesn't work that way. You don't get
a historical reputation with just rhetoric or by trying too hard to
be appearing to be doing something.'' That's why a policy of risk
aversion may be the highest-stake policy of all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David M. Shribman is chief of The Globe's Washington bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
