<HEADLINE>
RECLAIMING, RECASTING CALVIN COOLIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Calvin Coolidge attended college in Massachusetts. He
spent a career in the Massachusetts bar. He rose through the
state's political ranks to become governor. After serving as
president, he retired to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge liked Massachusetts. But Massachusetts, in the years
since his 1933 death, has happily abetted the notion that the 30th
president, at heart, never really left his birth state of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Proud of its progressive past, and its Quincy-through-Camelot
connection to the presidency, Massachusetts regards Coolidge like a
conservative virus that wafted down from the north, claimed some
victims, and then vanished from the atmosphere without ever
touching down.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the state is reclaiming its misbegotten stepson in
a surprising way: by suggesting that he was really a progressive at
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy was part of all the progressive initiatives in this
state from the turn of the century until he left as governor,'' in
1921, declared former governor Michael S. Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   Added Sheldon Stern, historian at the John F. Kennedy Library,
``Coolidge actually had a remarkably pro-labor record in
Massachusetts, and was liked by labor,'' despite his famous
clampdown on the 1919 Boston police strike when he was governor.
</P>
<P>
   Stern is the organizer of a two-day Kennedy Library conference
on July 30 and 31, ``Calvin Coolidge: Examining the Evidence,'' an
event endorsed by the Coolidge family and hailed as a moment of
historical resuscitation. At the conference, Dukakis will deliver a
major address on Coolidge's career in state politics.
</P>
<P>
   No ``Silent Cal,'' Coolidge was the first president to use radio
as a bully pulpit, Stern says. And the two brittle epigrams that
cemented his reputation for cold-heartedness _ his insistence that
``there is no right to strike against the public safety by anybody,
anywhere, anytime'' and that ``the business of America is
business'' _ are misleading quotes that don't begin to describe
Coolidge's true feelings, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The conference sets out to offer a lesson in the shifting tides
of history: the way the image of a historical figure can be torn
from the context of his times, and distorted for political purposes
by succeeding generations.
</P>
<P>
   But, some conservatives ask, will Massachusetts liberals be
practicing some of the same revisionism they condemn?
</P>
<P>
   For while Coolidge's image moldered in Massachusetts' attic, it
was dusted off and hung on the wall of the White House Cabinet room
by Ronald Reagan. And libertarians have adopted Coolidge as an icon
of political rectitude, remembering his pared-down administration
as a golden era of small government.
</P>
<P>
   Why, ask some conservatives, are Massachusetts liberals so
intent on claiming Coolidge for the progressive camp? Are they
trying to rescue Silent Cal's reputation, or sink the current-day
conservative movement that calls him a hero?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the Kennedy people are doing, but I
certainly am not aware of Mr. Coolidge's progressive aspects of his
public life,'' said Richard Viguerie, the conservative fund-raiser.
``Before Ronald Reagan came along, when people asked who you most
admired among 20th-century presidents, it was easy to answer Calvin
Coolidge _ and hard to find a second and third.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Coolidge story doesn't meld with any political
fable. As related by conservative biographers and liberal academics
alike, it is a saga of idealism, success, tragic loss, and even,
some claim, clinical depression.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, the historian, conceives of the conference as a search
for the objective truth. Dukakis, the ex-politician, sees it as
something of an object lesson in the ups and downs of a life in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a guy who grew up in the Massachusetts political
system, developed great skills and abilities, got talked into the
whole national thing, and was not exactly over his head, but very
uncomfortable in a whole different universe,'' Dukakis said, with
sympathy in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 92, John Coolidge, the late president's son, still
occasionally trundles from his home near the family homestead in
Plymouth Notch, Vt., to collect his mail. Often, residents report,
he's charming and outgoing; sometimes he's not.
</P>
<P>
   The legend endures that a neighbor once confronted him about his
shifting moods: ``Some days I take after my mother,'' he explained,
adding darkly, ``Some days I take after my father.''
</P>
<P>
   In the living theater of American history, even old John
Coolidge is playing a role, slyly mocking the stereotype of his
famous father.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that Calvin Coolidge was, in his youth, a
straight-laced model of Victorian propriety. Serious of mien,
perhaps because of the death of his beloved mother when he was 12,
he was more diligent than brilliant in his early schooling in
Vermont; more respected than beloved by classmates at Amherst
College; and, into early adulthood, more noted for dry wit than
blazing charm.
</P>
<P>
   But upon entering Massachusetts statewide politics, Coolidge
cast himself as a progressive Republican fully in tune with the
``bully'' politics of Theodore Roosevelt. He rose to become a state
representative in 1906, mayor of Northampton in 1910, state senator
in 1912, president of the Senate in 1914, lieutenant governor in
1916, and governor in 1919.
</P>
<P>
   ``He exerted a measure of leadership and spoke out on the issues
_ on which he was by no means conservative, even by today's
standards,'' wrote historian Robert Sobel in ``Calvin Coolidge: An
American Enigma,'' a new biography from the conservative-leaning
Regnery Press.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Coolidge's ascendency was capped by his role as drafter
of the 1917 state Republican platform, a landmark document that
embraced the progressive creed, calling for government intervention
to cure the social ills that attended a state in economic
transition.
</P>
<P>
   As lieutenant governor, he endorsed statewide comprehensive
health insurance. As governor, he increased workers' compensation,
approved women's suffrage, applied rent controls, raised salaries
of teachers and other public employees, and imposed government
regulations to protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having been called upon to mediate strikes in the past,
because of his reputation as a moderate trusted by both labor and
management, Coolidge's signature moment came when he crushed the
Boston police strike in 1919, uttering his famous injunction.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Stern argues, Coolidge was privately sympathetic with the
police, believing they should have received the pay raises they
sought; after the strikers were fired, he helped many get other
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
