<HEADER>
A2202 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-OPERA-BOS &LR;      07-13 1775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OPERA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARGAIN OPERA RECORDINGS CAN MEAN GOOD STUFF CHEAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The classical-music recording industry is in deep trouble, and
some would say that it deserves to be.
</P>
<P>
   One dimension of the business seems to be thriving, though, and
that's the low-price end represented by the numerous historical
reissue projects of the major labels, the emergence of the budget
label Naxos as an international market force, and RCA's recent
introduction of its budget line, Arte Nova.
</P>
<P>
   Naxos and the new kid on the block, Arte Nova, are operating
very much the way the smaller labels like Vox, Remington,
Westminster, and Urania did back in the '50s, in the early days of
LP. They license recordings from the archives of European radio
stations or make new recordings of standard and unusual repertory,
usually in Central Europe, and using performers who do not command
high fees and demand prima donna or primo tenore amenities.
</P>
<P>
   I've always enjoyed budget recordings because you never know
what to expect, and celebrity recordings seldom bring surprises.
Budget operas often reflect the knockabout world of real
performance more accurately than slick studio jobs, offering
exhilarating highs, as well as slipping to hilariously
un-acceptable levels. Not that studio recordings with superstars
aren't capable of reaching comparable heights or sinking to lower
depths (like Placido Domingo's computer-sustained high C in Sony's
``Il Trovatore''). When I was a kid, cheap records were all I could
afford; my first part-time job started off at 40 cents an hour, and
it took a long time to save up for my first luxury set _ RCA's
``Aida'' with Zinka Milanov and Jussi Bjoerling, which cost $11.95.
To this day I remain fond of some operatic performances I
encountered and learned by heart on recordings that cost anywhere
from 99 cents to $1.98 a disc: the Mimi and Butterfly of Da-niza
Illitsch on Remington, the Rigoletto of Ivan Petroff, also on
Remington, the Sophie of Adele Kern and the Che-rubino of Pilar
Lorengar on Vox. At the other end of the spectrum, Remington's
``Tosca'' has long held cult status as the worst complete opera
recording ever made, so it's worth holding onto, too.
</P>
<P>
   After some uneven early efforts, Naxos has matched or
outperformed the major labels in at least three of its operatic
efforts: ``The Barber of Seville,'' ``La Sonnambula,'' and ``The
Flying Dutchman,'' which blows the Metropolitan Opera's subsequent
effort for Sony Classical right out of the water. Some other Naxos
recordings remain enjoyable for individual elements rather than for
the excellence of the entire performance.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Arte Nova entered the market with a dozen operatic
recordings, most of them featuring singers you never heard of, some
of whom sound better than singers we have heard too much of
already.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most interesting sets come from the Novosibirsk State
Opera in the former Soviet Union, a theater that boasts a
first-class orchestra and chorus, some important voices, and a high
standard of performance. Tchaikovsky's ``Eugen Onegin'' sounds
thoroughly idiomatic and persuasive under the direction of
conductor Samuel Friedmann. Bolshoi Opera soprano Yelena Zelenskaya
travelled to the Siberian city to sing Tatiana; her opulent, darkly
dramatic tones aren't really suitable to the character, but this is
a fabulous voice. The resident company holds up its end, and it is
perhaps even more impressive in Arte Nova's pairing of
Tchaikovsky's touching ``Iolanta'' (the opera that shared a double
bill with the first performance of ``The Nutcracker'') with
``Aleko,'' the astonishing graduation opera by the 19-year-old
Rachmaninoff.
</P>
<P>
   Two standard Verdi operas were recorded in Vienna by the Europa
Symphony, whatever that is, under the direction of Wolfgang Groehs,
who clearly knows his way around ``La Traviata'' and ``Rigoletto.''
Carmen Gurban is the fifth soprano from Romania to record Violetta
and a pupil of one of the better ones, Ileana Cotrubas; she has a
lovely voice, sufficient technique, and sensitivity to character
and situation. Baritone Georg Tichy may be a little past his prime,
but he's honorably held down the major Verdi roles at the Vienna
State Opera for a quarter-century, and he still makes a more
satisfying Germont than some of the younger competition (he does
omit his cabaletta; the score is otherwise heard complete, and
Gurban sings both stanzas of both her arias). Russian emigre tenor
Sergei Komov presents an agreeable Alfredo. Komov and Tichy
reappear to reasonable effect in ``Rigoletto,'' but this recording
would have profited from some retakes that weren't in the budget.
The American soprano Doreen DeFeis, who once offered a
well-received song recital here in the Pro Musicis series, sings
intelligently, but she doesn't have either the weight of voice or
the virtuoso coloratura Gilda requires.
</P>
<P>
   Four recordings come from the Putbus Festival on the island of
Ruegen, off the northern coast of Germany; the festival was founded
in 1993 by the conductor Wilhelm Keitel, an alumnus of the
Tanglewood Music Center. The orchestra consists of former players
from the Minsk opera and ballet; in its new formation it has won
the favor and patronage of Sir Yehudi Menuhin. Only one of the
Putbus recordings is a loser, Rossini's ``William Tell,'' and even
it is well-conducted and played, with some nicely sung supporting
roles. But the tenor cast in the high-flying role of Arnoldo is in
way over his head, and the soprano offers more wobble than tone.
Recordings of Paisiello's ``The Barber of Seville'' and the version
of the same story by Rossini that banished it to oblivion feature
the same singers (onstage they presumably featured the same sets
and costumes). Mozart admired Paisiello's opera, whose influence
can be heard in his sequel, ``The Marriage of Figaro,'' but after
Rossini, Paisiello's seems a predictable, professional, and
somewhat boring opera. The Putbus singers do better in the
Paisiello, where they do not have to withstand comparison to the
greatest bel canto singers of our century. But at least they seem
to be enjoying themselves, which is a critical element missing from
too many recordings of Rossini's opera. The Rosina, Marina Ivanova,
has sung at Glyndbourne; many of the others have been well-trained
and coached by that grand veteran of countless opera buffa
performances, Sesto Bruscantini. Only one singer is inadequate, the
bass Ezio Maria Tisi, who is faced with notes he doesn't have in
Rossini's aria for Don Basilio.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the Putbus recordings is Donizetti's ``Don
Pasquale,'' which features a full-blooded portrayal of Norina by
soprano Paola Antonucci. Tenor Patrizio Saudelli, who appears in
all four recordings, sings Ernesto with style and charm in an
unusual timbre that recalls Alessio de Paolis on the aria
recordings he made on 78s in Italy before he moved to America to
become the Met's most beloved comprimario tenor.
</P>
<P>
   Arte Nova's recording of Mozart's ``The Abduction from the
Seraglio'' hails from the Mozartean city of Linz, where the opera
house boasts a soprano who can sail through the impossible role of
Konstanze, Ingrid Habermann. The others are competent; the bass
Franz Kalchmair sings Osmin not only in Linz but all over Europe
because he can negotiate a role even less cast-able than Konstanze.
The Bruckner Orchestra plays deftly for Martin Sieghart.
</P>
<P>
   An Arte Nova surprise is a recording of the world premiere of
the challenging ``Gesualdo,'' by Franz Hummel, the work
commissioned for the 1996 opening of the new opera house in
Kaiserslautern, Germany. Elisabeth Gutjahr's libretto is drawn from
the unsavory life of the composer Carlo Gesualdo, whose music
fascinated Stravinsky; in the 16th century Gesualdo quite literally
got away with murder. The opera is a music-theater collaboration,
so it is hard to judge the work's effectiveness on the basis of a
recording alone. The formal intricacies and fever-pitch intensity
of ``Gesualdo'' do demonstrate that the tradition of German
expressionistic opera that began with Strauss's ``Salome'' and
``Elektra'' and continued through Berg's ``Wozzeck'' did not end
with Zimmermann's ``Die Soldaten.'' The audience responds with
hearty applause at the end.
</P>
<P>
   At another extreme is a recording of Johann Strauss's ``Die
Fledermaus'' made with the forces of the famous outdoor operetta
festival, which takes place on a floating stage in Moerbisch Lake
in Austria. The male singers are not outstanding, but nostalgia
will be evoked by the casting of two sons of the noted Viennese
bass Otto Edelmann (Peter sings Eisenstein and Paul Armin, Dr.
Falke) and by the presence of tenor Waldemar Kmentt as the jailer
Frank; Kmentt has been singing various roles in ``Die Fledermaus''
since 1950, so he knows his business. The women are terrific. Ute
Gfrerer offers a spunky, agile Adele, and Silvana Dussman sounds
funny, sexy, and infinitely glamorous as Rosalinde; she can sing
the dickens out of the unsingable Csardas. Casting a countertenor
as Prince Orlofsky is a fashionable idea today, and usually a
terrible one, but Artur Stefanowicz manages the aria better than
most mezzo-sopranos. The dialogue has been omitted for the
international market, so the work comes in at about 80 minutes,
spread over two CDs.
</P>
<P>
   The Verdi Requiem is operatic but not an opera, and Arte Nova's
recording differs from most of its other offerings by presenting
name performers in the solo roles. Sharon Sweet, Francisco Araiza,
and Simon Estes have all sung at the Met, and Jard van Nes has made
a lot of recordings. They appear in the context of a committed but
un-idiomatic performance by the Saarbruecken Radio Symphony
Orchestra and the Munich Bach Choir under the direction of
Hanns-Martin Schneidt. One does wonder why anyone would want to
record these particular singers in the Verdi Requiem, especially
now. The answer is, no one did: This recording was made 10 years
ago. Van Nes, so often so bland, summons some passion on this
occasion, but the vocal preening of Estes is preposterous, and
Araiza is a disaster waiting to happen. The surprise is Sweet, who
isn't quite on top of her part, but deploys a resplendent voice
that would never again sound this beautiful and powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The bill for all 12 of these recordings would add up to less
than the price of one $200 orchestra ticket at the Met. That ticket
would not come with an ironclad guarantee you would hear a better
performance than some of these Arte Nova bargains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
