<HEADER>
A2204 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-AIDS-TREATMENT-AR     07-13 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-TREATMENT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING WAYS TO HELP THE POOREST NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The theme of the world AIDS conference two years ago in
Vancouver was supposedly ``One World, One Hope.'' But the real
motif _ the amazing effectiveness of the then-new and costly
triple-drug ``cocktails'' to treat AIDS _ rendered the slogan
hollow.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise of this year's AIDS conference here was how much it
embodied its official theme, ``Bridging the Gap.''
</P>
<P>
   In every plenary session, press conference, and interview, and
often in the most abstruse virology and immunology presentations,
experts fretted and plotted about narrowing the treatment gap that
separates prosperous, largely northern societies _ where
triple-drug treatment has reversed AIDS mortality and emptied
hospital beds _ from the achingly poor, southern hemisphere
countries that are home to 90 percent of those who carry the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
</P>
<P>
   Another empty promise? Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question truly universal access to state-of-the-art
HIV treatment is a pipe dream. The global price tag would be $36.5
billion, at a current yearly cost of more than $10,000 per patient,
a Canadian group estimates. That's $6 for every man, woman, and
child on the planet, but an impossible $41 for every citizen of
sub-Saharan Africa, the region hardest hit by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In the AIDS-ravaged countries of Malawi, Mozambique, Uganda, and
Tanzania, the cost of universal access would exceed half of each
nation's gross national product.
</P>
<P>
   But developing nations differ enormously in their ability to
mount HIV treatment programs of one sort or another. Westerners
need to recognize this diversity, experts said, if they are to
shake off the paralyzing notion that treating AIDS is beyond all
but industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   A few developing nations have made considerable inroads.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil stands out. With nearly 600,000 HIV-infected citizens,
that country has pledged to provide triple-drug antiviral treatment
to everyone who needs it. The $250 million Brazil is now spending
represents only a fraction of the need, but it amounts to nearly 5
percent of the nation's health budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is spending more on HIV care than the rest of the
developing world is spending on prevention and care together,''
notes Daniel Tarantola of the Harvard AIDS Institute, which is
launching a $3 million project to enhance care in five developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Such foot-in-the-door efforts generate political pressure, both
within the nations attempting them and on international funding
sources such as the United Nations, the World Bank, and wealthier
nations. Drug companies in particular are feeling pressed to slash
HIV drug prices for the developing world and to forego patent
protections there _ a prominent topic in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Triple-drug HIV therapy, however, is not the only treatment that
could extend lives and diminish misery in poor nations.
</P>
<P>
   The opening wedge for all such interventions is the newly proven
use of short-course AZT, the original anti-HIV drug, to prevent
transmission of the virus from mother to infant. By the end of this
year, the UN agency UNAIDS plans to be running pilot programs in
Africa, Asia, and Latin America to identify 30,000 pregnant,
HIV-infected women and provide them with AZT in late pregnancy,
followed by infant formula to prevent viral transmission through
breast feeding.
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies in Thailand show that short-course AZT can reduce
mother-to-infant infections by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond AZT, a number of studies show that simplified drug
regimens to prevent tuberculosis among HIV-infected people could
have enormous impact in the developing world. Similarly, a
relatively cheap drug called Bactrim could prevent many thousands
of HIV-associated pneumonia cases in poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   Even less fancy care, such as over-the-counter Imodiumfor
AIDS-related diarrhea, could have important impact. One study from
Burkina Faso in West Africa, one of the world's poorest countries,
showed that lives can be extended (and made less miserable) by a
program costing just $20 a month per person.
</P>
<P>
   But for cost-effectiveness, nothing beats the vitamin
``treatment'' that Wafaie Fawzi of the Harvard School of Public
Health and his colleagues successfully tested among HIV-positive
pregnant women and children in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   For less than five cents a day, giving pregnant HIV-infected
women a multivitamin tablet reduced fetal deaths, low birthweight,
and premature births by 40 percent, while boosting the women's
immune systems for months after delivery. Among HIV-infected
children, daily vitamin A supplements cut mortality by nearly half,
and eliminated diarrhea-related deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Such successes ``challenge the stereotype that AIDS treatments
are only for wealthy nations,'' Tarantola said in an interview.
``We're shifting the emphasis from drugs for the rich to drugs for
the poor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
