<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-RELEVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP EAGER TO POINT ITS FIGHT OUTWARD AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Against the backdrop of this city of black pride and
progress, Julian Bond, in his first major address since taking over
as board chairman of the NAACP, said Sunday that the organization
would work to build a world where ``private prejudice doesn't
become public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond's speech punctuated the opening of the 89th annual
convention of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, and brought him home to a city where he established
his reputation as a respected civil rights leader and savvy
politician.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged the confusion and skepticism about the
organization's role in the aftermath of financial and leadership
setbacks _ turmoil that hindered the NAACP's effectiveness and
caused some to question its relevance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us are confused about what our next step should be,''
Bond said to the delegates. ``The task ahead is enormous _ equal to
if not greater than the job already done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise that you are going to read about the NAACP because
we are fighting for civil rights and not because we are fighting
with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the more than 3,500 delegates present frequently
interrupted Bond's speech with applause and standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have turned the corner,'' said delegate Leonard C. Alkins,
president of the Boston branch of the NAACP. ``We are not looking
backwards, we are looking forward, because we know where we come
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, much skepticism remains about the fate of the nation's
oldest and largest civil rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the jury is still out on whether the NAACP can and
will make an impact on resolving some of the urgent problems and
being a participant in the policy process in the way that it should
be in Washington,'' said Mary Frances Berry, chairwoman of the US
Commission on Civil Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Walters, director of the African-American Leadership Program
at the University of Maryland, said that, with the NAACP proposing
to get involved in such areas as literacy and fighting AIDS in
black communities nationwide, he wondered, ``What is the difference
between the NAACP and the Urban League, a social service provider?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a whole lot of other agencies out there, public and
private, who can deliver services. We need a fighting
organization,'' Walters said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the NAACP's biggest fight has been just to stay
afloat and hold on to its reputation. Three years ago, it was mired
in a debt of $4.8 million. Its leadership was in turmoil when in
1994 its director, Benjamin F. Chavis Jr., was forced out after he
admitted using $332,400 in NAACP funds to settle a sexual
harassment lawsuit filed against him by a former staffer.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, William Gibson was voted out as chairman by one
vote in a bruising campaign for board leadership against Myrlie
Evers-Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gibson and Chavis ran the organization into the ground,'' said
Roger Wilkins, a history professor at George Mason University in
Fairfax, Va. and chairman of the NAACP's magazine, The New Crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But now there are signs of life in the nation's oldest and
largest civil rights group. Its leaders say it has half a million
paid members and a $2.1 million surplus. It has a new president and
chief exective officer, Kweisi Mfume, a former congressman from
Maryland. In February, it also got a new board chairman in Bond, a
former state senator in Georgia and lieutenant of slain civil
rights leader, the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very dynamic duo,'' said Lenneal J. Henderson,
professor of government and public administration at the University
of Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some delegates say they are not ready to exult just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our troubles are completely behind us,'' said
Russell Williams, president of the Greater Hartford branch of the
NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have as many branches and as many board members
as we have, you are always going to have to deal with internal
issues and personalities,'' Williams said. The NAACP has 2,200
branches and a 64-member board.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that delegates are eyeing the chemistry between
Mfume and Bond, which he calls ``an interesting mix,'' as well as
the tone they will set for the organization. There have been rumors
of tension, which both men and their associates have either denied
or downplayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both have specific gifts that have yet to be completely
and succinctly identified,'' Williams said. ``I think there is a
period of evolution taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   Some delegates say that as the leadership is a work in progress,
so too is the group's focus. Although the NAACP will maintain its
advocacy roots in civil rights, the delegates say it will also
engage in coalition politics with other groups while charting a
course that mixes social justice and social service.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bond, in his address, said, ``At all times we must be
careful not to confuse social service with social justice. Social
justice is what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The civil rights issue will always be the common link,'' said
Alkins, the Boston chapter president.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Norvel Goff Sr., president of the Rochester, N.Y.,
branch of the NAACP, put it this way: ``We are now going to the
next level. We are prepared to fight the fight we have fought
traditionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we are poised to not only take on other issues, but also
stand in the forefront and lead, not react, but lead on major
issues that are confronting not only black America, but America,''
Goff said. ``We're not going to let the tail wag the dog.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1315EDT &QL; 
