<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2208 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-13 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN CRISIS MAY BEGIN TO CLOUD US PROSPERITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The US economy's smooth ride on a dangerous wind
from the East is about to get rougher. Maybe a lot rougher, though
there still is no direct evidence that a decade that rivals the
1960s in prosperity will end with a cessation of economic growth or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   The last several days have highlighted a different picture from
the uniformly positive news of the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   _Employment and industrial production growth are flattening, and
unemployment may be trending higher from the lowest level in a
generation as firms dependent on exports feel the impact of Asia's
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the announcement by Internet powerhouse Yahoo
Inc. of second-quarter profits that exceeded Wall Street's
expectations served as a reminder that a new economy continues to
churn forward.
</P>
<P>
   _Federal Reserve estimates showed a contraction in the growth of
consumer borrowing during May, the slowest pace since last
November. And that news can be a hint of what is to come in
consumer spending, which remains the source of two-thirds of the
economy's juice.
</P>
<P>
   But the announcement by Folgers of a second cut in its list
price of coffee this year, in the face of the biggest Brazilian
coffee crop in more than a decade, is a reminder of how good
inflation news remains. That is in turn a key cause of low interest
rates that are crucial to continued overall growth.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, Americans will begin to see how much the
economy's pace is slowing, particularly when the Commerce
Department makes a preliminary estimate of total output of goods
and service for the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   There is universal agreement that the extraordinary pace of the
first quarter, a 5.4 percent annual rate, cannot be sustained. The
real question is how much the growth rate dropped. To most
Americans that's just a number. More important is a narrative of
the underlying developments, of which there are primarily two.
</P>
<P>
   The first is a change in how the Asian crisis is affecting this
country. At first, it was more beneficial than harmful. With the
dollar trending higher against the major Asian currencies, above
all the yen, there was a rise in imports from the countries
involved that was noticeable in prices paid by Americans before the
loss of exports was felt in lower production and employment in
affected businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, movement of money to these shores, above all to the
government bond market, in search of security had the effect _
along with the stability at long last in US budget policy _ of
keeping long-term interest rates low.
</P>
<P>
   That is now changing. The lost export business and diminished
future prospects are being felt now, and the impact is likely to
continue for at least the next six to nine months.
</P>
<P>
   The second development is somewhat technical, but probably more
important to the upcoming estimate of the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   The huge growth figure in the first quarter turns out to contain
the largest addition to business inventories in the history of
statistics about them. The change, worth slightly more than $100
billion at an annual rate, accounted for fully 1.7 percentage
points of the total rate of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Ain't gonna happen again, and it definitely did not happen in
the second quarter. Because what counts in measuring the economy is
the change in inventories from quarter to quarter, as opposed to
their absolute level, they were at best a zero last quarter and
more likely a negative.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in a less vibrant industrial sector generally, and weak
Asian exports in particular, and it is difficult to see how the
growth rate could have been much above 2 percent, if that.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, that is no surprise. The relentlesssly conservative
Clinton administration, in drawing up its budget documents early
this year, projected growth at 2 to 2.5 percent this year, as well
as in 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As the months pass, however, that assumption will be tested by
four major questions:
</P>
<P>
   _Will Asia stabilize? The engine of recovery will have to be
Japan. In the wake of parliamentary elections, the world will find
out whether Japanese recovery policies are credible or
inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   _When will the General Motors strike end? So far, it may cost
the economy a half-point in growth for the year, but if the worst
GM strike in 28 years goes past Labor Day, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   _Will US policymakers goof? One danger would be a premature
tightening of monetary policy by Alan Greenspan's Federal Reserve.
The other would be a loss of budgetary discipline by the Republican
Congress. The former is unlikely, the latter a slight danger.
</P>
<P>
   _Will the Asian bug spread? The potential danger areas are Latin
America and the Middle East, but it is only potential at the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing view remains that the United States will slow
down a good bit for the next half-year or so, but then gradually
speed up. But where near-euphoria once reigned, some very health
concern and skepticism now hold sway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASS-COOLIDGE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     07-13 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-COOLIDGE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... other jobs.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The police strike greased his entry into national politics.
Party bosses, finding his law-and-order reputation an appealing
tonic for the rollicking '20s, nominated him for vice president
under Warren Harding. And when Harding, straining under the weight
of scandal, died during a speaking tour in 1923, Coolidge became an
accidental president.
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge moved swiftly to consolidate power. And his early
initiatives _ twice-weekly press conferences, regular radio
addresses, and a flurry of legislative proposals _ pointed toward
an activist agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But once elected on his own, on a ``keep cool'' platform of
peace and prosperity, Coolidge seemed more content to allow the
booming economy to raise all boats. Very popular in his time, he
declined to run again in 1928, turning over the keys to the White
House to Secretary of Commerce Herbert Hoover.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, noting the sharp difference between Coolidge's
progressive stands as governor and his more muted actions as
president, suggests that Coolidge was, at heart, a federalist,
believing in activism at the state level only, with a limited
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis found the shift even more profound. He endorses
Northeastern University professor Robert E. Gilbert's theory that
the death in 1924 of Coolidge's 16-year-old son, Calvin Jr.,  &UR;  &LR; 
plunged him into a clinical depression, and wreathed his presidency
with morbidity. Calvin Jr. died of blood poisoning from a blister
he got after playing tennis on the White House court.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``The Mortal Presidency,'' Gilbert depicts the
president in a series of plaintive images: capturing a small brown
rabbit on the White House lawn and taking it to his dying son's
room; staring numbly at young Calvin Jr.'s hospital window from the
street below; and, later, talking of looking forward to being
reunited with his son in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend who visited him in the Oval Office reported that
Coolidge wept openly, the tears running down his face, while he
kept repeating, `I just can't believe it has happened. I just can't
believe it has happened,''' Gilbert wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge's ``sustained depression,'' Dukakis said, ``certainly
would explain a lot of his presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Viguerie, of course, has a different explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calvin Coolidge didn't do a whole lot,'' he acknowledged.
``But for us (conservatives), that's the whole objective. And
that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Within a year of Coolidge's departure from office, the
chicken-in-every-pot prosperity promised by his administration
vanished into the maw of the Great Depression. A new president,
Franklin D. Roosevelt, had just been elected, and his Democratic
liberalism would define the era.
</P>
<P>
   History turned against Coolidge. Roosevelt assumed the role of
savior, and New Deal historians demonized the Republican presidents
of the 1920s as the bringers of the plague that Roosevelt cured.
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge's alleged complacency, his willingness to allow the
wheels of business to churn unimpeded, took on the look of
negligence. Journalist H.L. Mencken declared, ``He will be ranked
among the vacuums.''
</P>
<P>
   And, to a great extent, he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calvin Coolidge has been characterized as a complacent, lazy
and humorless man and an extreme reactionary _ hostile to
government and progressive legislation, oblivious to the needs of
working Americans and devoted only to the material wealth of the
nation and the interests of business,'' declares the opening
statement of the Kennedy Library conference literature.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Coolidge is even less well remembered than
elsewhere. To some, the state's treatment of Coolidge borders on
insulting. Boston Brahmins bearing the Coolidge surname are quick
to declare themselves no relation to the president _ though they
probably share a common ancestor, Stern says. Historians visiting
Amherst College are sometimes surprised to find that Coolidge is
not more honored at his alma mater, though a dorm bears his name.
</P>
<P>
   And among police unions, the word Coolidge still draws clenched
fists. &UR;  &LR; ``He was the person who broke the Boston police strike and
fired a number of police officers,'' declared Frank McGee,
long-time counsel of the Boston Police Patrolmen's Association.
``He was a vicious anti-union person who heaped a lot of misery on
a lot of police families.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   History, however, is always subject to change, and Coolidge
spent only a few decades in disrepute before being reassessed.
</P>
<P>
   When Ronald Reagan strolled into the Cabinet room of the White
House in 1981, he saw portraits of Jefferson, Lincoln, and Harry
Truman. The curator offered to make a change. And Reagan, eager for
a historical metaphor for his ambitious budget-cutting plans,
replaced Truman with Coolidge, an emblem of parsimonious good
sense.
</P>
<P>
   Thus was born a conservative icon.
</P>
<P>
   For liberals, however, the road to the Kennedy Library
conference has been more twisted.
</P>
<P>
   It began in a theater in Cambridge in 1975, when Dorchester
actor Jim Cooke played the title role in a forgettable,
post-Watergate farce called ``The Calvin Coolidge Follies.'' In the
play, Coolidge was meant to be a perplexing figure, but Cooke found
himself being drawn deeper and deeper into the character.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he was cutting and pasting his way through Coolidge's
writings, developing a one-man show. Cooke has taken the show to
theaters throughout New England, playing Coolidge as a man of dry
humor and straight-talking Yankee wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did what he thought should be done,'' said Cooke. ``He did
what he thought was right. He didn't care if he ruined his
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern, who has been at the Kennedy Library since its inception
and proudly boasts of ``never having voted for a Republican,'' saw
Cooke's show and enjoyed it.
</P>
<P>
   He was stunned, however, to learn that the entire script was
culled from Coolidge's words. Thus, he decided to take his own
fresh look at this conservative icon, and discovered that the
Reaganites were praying to a false God.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Reagan admired Coolidge for the wrong reasons,''
Stern said. ``Those reasons were not accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Stern had a conversation with Dukakis, and found that the
former governor had a longstanding curiosity about his famous _ and
infamous _ predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he (Dukakis) feels Coolidge has been misunderstood and
that he himself has been misunderstood, so he identifies with
Coolidge,'' said Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis maintains that his primary interest is in better
understanding the lively Massachusetts politics of the first two
decades of the century, but he allows that he and Coolidge were
``probably the only two governors to ride the trolley car.''
</P>
<P>
   He offers a story of an official greeting party waiting for the
governor's entourage, only to discover that Coolidge, having taken
the trolley, was already inside staring at the paintings on the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis believes a tragic ending is often preordained in
politics, as anyone who seeks national office must surrender to the
crude judgment of history as the price of entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you decide to play in that larger pond you're going to be
judged by what you do there,'' he said. ``Sadly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
