<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHARACTER TEST CLINTON PASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the late Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. once said, a man should
be judged not by the color of his skin, but by the content of his
character.
</P>
<P>
   Apply King's credo to President Clinton, say his critics, and
the president fails. They point to Clinton's relationship (whatever
it may have been) with Gennifer Flowers to his much-publicized
connection to Monica Lewinsky, from his involvement with Whitewater
to charges of illegal fund-raising. Indeed, they say, Clinton may
have the lowest character of any US president in history.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are other ways in which a president's character
can be judged. One of them is how he handles difficult public
issues _ such as race.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could have easily avoided any direct involvement with
the controversial _ and, politically speaking, no-win _ issue of
race relations in these United States.
</P>
<P>
   Race and racism have long been employed in negative ways in
American politics. Only a few elected officials have ever run on a
platform that promises to establish a real dialogue with the
purpose of improving race relations. No chief executive since
President Lincoln, including presidents in their last term, has
raised the issue of race to the level Clinton has in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   With foreign policy successes such as his recent trip to China,
and with a domestic economy still booming, Clinton had no need to
get involved in an issue that could lose him more support than he
could gain during these last two years of his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   But in the year since he established his President's Initiative
on Race, along with his national advisory panel, Clinton has
demonstrated beyond question that he is giving the issue real
significance, not just dismissing it with a gesture of political
tokenism.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither Clinton nor the panel can boast any real
achievements or breakthroughs, the fact that he has kept the issue
alive and well enough to be aired on PBS tonight in Boston and
other cities is noteworthy.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial last week in a Florida newspaper said, for example,
``President Clinton deserves credit for at least trying to focus
attention on the nation's racial problems. Not only did he appoint
a committed group of individuals as panel members, but he also lent
his considerable communication skills to promote the race
initiative commission and its work.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Clinton and the panel were criticized; some said
they were making too much of the race issue, while others said they
were not doing enough. Even members of the panel, as well as
Clinton himself, acknowledge that a lot more has to be done before
America can completely unite.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton nicely understated, ``unique and still unresolved
issues'' exist between black and white Americans, even as our
society becomes more complex, more multiracial, multi-ethnic, and
multi-religious. And, as Clinton and the panel members know, there
is hardly a consensus on such an emotional issue as affirmative
action, on which opinion remains largely divided along racial and
political lines.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked the audience during a town meeting in Ohio, ``Do
you favor the United States Army abolishing the affirmative action
program that produced Colin Powell? Yes or no? Yes or no?'' There
was no simple ``yes'' or ``no'' answer from the audience, according
to reports from the session.
</P>
<P>
   And while he is on record as supporting affirmative action,
Clinton still faced criticism from some black members of the panel
for being ``reluctant'' to deal with the issue. In addition, his
panel selection was criticized, legitimately, for not initially
including a Native American.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the three public discussions that have evolved from the
race initiative have produced more questions than answers about how
to resolve America's race problem. A measure of the problem's
complexity is reflected in how difficult it has been getting people
to open up and talk honestly about race.
</P>
<P>
   While the president's race initiative commission will officially
end on Sept. 30, and a series of recommendations from the
commission is expected by the end of this year, the issue of race
will not be resolved any time in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   But, at the very least, this initiative suggests a need for more
public discussion _ which in turn could lead to more effective
policies for resolving at least some of the issues related to race.
</P>
<P>
   As the O.J. Simpson trial documented, and as the recent dragging
death of a black man in Texas, allegedly by three white men,
brutally portrayed, there is still a chasm between the races.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's race initiative, as it comes to a close, was at least
an effort in the right direction _ an attempt to deal with the
problem of race rather than avoid its reality.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton may remembered for his jousting with
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr over Whitewater and Lewinsky,
let us not forget his willingness to tackle the tough issue of
race, with an eye toward healing the nation's painful divide. That
part of his character should not be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
