<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLER REGIMENS COMING IN THE AIDS DRUG QUEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ When it comes to AIDS treatment, timing and luck are
still as important as virology, immunology, and clinical research.
But that may be changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of the lucky ones,'' AIDS activist Mark Harrington
told a rapt audience at the 12th World AIDS Conference here.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Harrington's AIDS began to worsen ominously two years
ago, a process specialists call disease progression, researchers
came up with a potent triple-drug cocktail, a regimen that has all
but eliminated the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) from his
system and rescued his dying immune system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have progressed at a better time,'' Harrington
said, flashing a slide of his rejuvenated lymph node tissue. ``My
immune system is coming back to life.''
</P>
<P>
   A 49-year-old Rhode Island woman we'll call Christine is lucky
too, in a less dramatic way. Unlike Harrington, she couldn't defer
AIDS treatment until the triple-drug therapy came along. ``She was
progressing so rapidly that we had to layer in each new drug as it
was available,'' said her AIDS physician for the past 10 years, Dr.
Kenneth Mayer of Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   Usually HIV responds to that kind of sequential drug treatment
by developing resistance to each drug in turn, eventually using up
all options. But thankfully, and for reasons no one can explain,
Christine's virus did not become drug resistant.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, she has begun developing the abnormal fat
deposits that are cropping up in about 20 percent of patients on
long-term triple-drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   In a more precarious situation is Spencer Cox, a colleague of
Harrington's in the New York-based Treatment Action Group. Like
Christine, he has been heavily treated for HIV _ but now he's
resistant to most of the available drugs. Last December he took
himself off treatment to wait for researchers to come up with a
recipe for a new cocktail that will suppress the HIV in his system,
now hovering at a worrisome 230,000 viruses in each milliliter (1/5
teaspoon) of his blood.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he's hopeful. ``I tend to find the gray cloud in
every silver lining, but I came away from Geneva feeling pretty
optimistic,'' Cox said last week.
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone. Physicians who treat HIV patients and search for
better therapies say they feel optimistic too _ even though nothing
that came out of the Geneva conference tips the balance away from
timing and luck in AIDS treatment and toward reliable, sure-fire
options for individuals at every stage of HIV disease.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there's a case for pessimism, too.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, new drugs in the pipeline appear at least as
potent as current drugs, but they may not come in time to help
those whose current therapy is failing them _ about half the most
intensively treated patients. Also, no imminent drugs represent a
truly new class capable of attacking HIV at a different point in
its life cycle. Thus, it's possible that patients whose virus is
resistant to current drugs will be resistant to new versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my disappointments was that there wasn't more about new
treatments that would benefit those with advanced AIDS,'' said Dr.
Harvey Makadon of Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It is also still a matter of luck which patients will respond to
current anti-HIV cocktails as dramatically as Harrington did. All
the world's virologists cannot explain or predict why some people's
HIV can be suppressed indefinitely (so far) to a tiny residuum,
while in others the virus roars back.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can the cleverest immunologists say why treatment returns
some patients' ravaged immune systems to virtually normal, like
Harrington's, while others' appear beyond redemption.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the frustrating unknowns, many see the glass as
half-full. ``For the individual, there's still a certain amount of
caprice,'' Mayer acknowledged. ``But in the aggregate, we now can
treat HIV as a chronic, difficult, but manageable infectious
disease. That's real progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the positive new signs:
</P>
<P>
   --Much simpler HIV regimens. Instead of the onerous 20 to 30
tablets that patients are now told they must take without fail
morning, noon, and night, it will be possible to swallow three or
four pills a day, split into morning and evening doses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a massive reduction in the number of
pills,'' said Dr. Julio Montaner of the University of British
Columbia. ``We have nearly a half-dozen drugs that lend themselves
to once-daily dosing.''
</P>
<P>
   Easier regimens make it more likely people will take their
medicine faithfully, lowering the risk of treatment failure. That
should also diminish the risk that people will develop
omni-resistant viral mutants that, scientists now know, can be
transmitted sexually.
</P>
<P>
   --More choices. Drugs in the pipeline, and others not far
behind, introduce the possibility of effective regimens that don't
require protease inhibitors, the potent antivirals that made the
big difference two years ago in combination with older drugs. If
so, protease inhibitors can be held in reserve for those whose
virus rebounds after first-line therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Such ``protease-sparing'' regimens may also provide an
alternative for patients like Christine who suffer lipid
abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will soon have some really intriguing new choices _ for
beginning therapy or switching therapy _ that look equal or better
in potency to the current gold standard,'' said Dr. R. Scott Hitt,
a Los Angeles AIDS doctor who chairs President Clinton's Advisory
Council on HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   --Immune reconstitution. Researchers are heartened by signs that
current treatments allow patients' immune systems to recover more
completely than they expected. Even many whose virus rebounds seem
to benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first conference in which there was any optimism
about the immune system's ability to kick in,'' said Dr. Calvin
Cohen of the Community Research Initiative of New England. ``There
was always this feeling that the immune system was doomed to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are rushing to exploit and augment this immune
recovery, so that even if HIV cannot be eradicated from every last
cell in most patients, it might be controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington articulated the question in many people's minds:
``Are we willing to settle for lifelong therapy, or treat until the
immune system can control whatever residual HIV remains? Do we need
to delete every last...infected cell?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
HIV DRUGS IN THE PIPELINE &QL; 
 &QL; 
Clinical trial results on four new drugs promise additional options
soon. But all work in the same ways as existing drugs, so patients
who have developed resistance to standard drugs may also be
resistant to these. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Efaverenz (Sustiva)  &QL; 
DuPont Pharmaceuticals  &QL; 
Non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor  &QL; 
Potent HIV suppression, even in two-drug combination; Works in
cocktails without a protease inhibitor, saving those drugs for
later. Side effects similar to standard drugs; can alter mood.  &QL; 
Only once daily  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
--1592 (Abacavir)  &QL; 
GlaxoWellcome  &QL; 
Nucleoside analogue reverse transcriptase inhibitor  &QL; 
Potent antiviral in three-drug cocktail, even without a protease
inhibitor. Promising in children failing current treatment. May get
into central nervous system. Side effects resemble standard drugs,
but 3 percent suffer allergic reaction that can be fatal if 1592 is
restarted.  &QL; 
Twice daily, no food/water restrictions  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Adefovir (Preveon)  &QL; 
Gilead Sciences  &QL; 
Nucleoside analogue reverse transcriptase inhibitor  &QL; 
Preliminary studies suggest antiviral efficacy, though perhaps less
potent. As a nucleotide, may work against virus resistant to
nucleosides. Some patients suffer kidney toxicity.  &QL; 
Probably once daily  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Amprenavir  &QL; 
GlaxoWellcome/ &QL; 
Vertex Pharmaceuticals  &QL; 
Protease inhibitor  &QL; 
Potent effect in two-drug combination with Abacavir in small
trials. Three-drug combination with nucleosides showed durable
effect. Penetrates into central nervous system. Side effects
similar to other drugs in this class.  &QL; 
Probably twice daily, no food/water restrictions  &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOURCES: Respective pharmaceutical companies, presentations at 12th
World AIDS Conference, interviews with conference participants &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
