<HEADLINE>
`GOOD WILL HUNTING' PUTS SOUTH BOSTON ON THE MAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES:  &UR; ``Good Will Hunting''  &LR; _ South Boston's great
home movie _ it does for the alphabet streets what Thomas Crown and
Banacek did for Beacon Hill _ loses nothing on the small screen.
Matt Damon's fine performance survives Robin Williams's overrated
one. The miracle is that Damon and Ben Affleck had the fortitude to
resist alterations in their script, and that the story survived
intact from paper to screen to Oscar night. That means the story of
the making of the movie is actually rarer and better than the film
itself _ but this one is well worth renting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Boxer''  &LR; _ Is there any better actor working today than
Daniel Day-Lewis? He takes chances (both with his roles and his
pocketbook) in low-budget art movies. In this one, set amid the
most recent Irish troubles, he's as good as ever, in a tough-minded
movie that tells a compelling story in an unflinching style _ an
approach that's missing from most films.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Six O'Clock News''  &LR; _ Ross McElwee, the autobiographically
iconoclastic documentarian, sets his sights on an easy target this
time: television news. But the good news is that it's mostly about
his personal evolution. McElwee has the uncanny knack of being able
to document his own life without an overriding ego, making his
insights and imagery more universal than narcissistic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS:  &UR; July 14:  &LR; ``Phantoms,'' ``The Winter
Guest,'' ``Plato's Run,'' ``Nil by Mouth,'' ``The Night Caller,''
``The Call of the Wild: Dog of the Yukon,'' ``French Exit,''
``Swept From the Sea,'' ``Illtown,'' ``Chairman of the Board.''
 &UR; July 21:  &LR; ``Great Expectations,'' ``Four Days in September,''
``Krippendorf's Tribe,'' ``Two Friends,'' ``The Education of Little
Tree,'' ``Kissing a Fool,'' ``Prince Valiant,'' ``Children of the
Corn V: Fields of Terror.''  &UR; July 28:  &LR; ``The Gingerbread Man,''
``The Peacekeper,'' ``Paperback Romance,'' ``Dark City,'' ``A Kid
in Aladdin's Palace,'' ``Live Flesh.''  &UR; July 31:  &LR; ``Cousin
Cousine.'' &UR; Aug. 4:  &LR; ``Jackie Brown,'' ``Deceiver,'' ``Meet the
Deedles,'' ``Preston Sturges Collection,'' ``The Swan Princess
II.''  &UR; Aug. 11:  &LR; ``The Man in the Iron Mask,'' ``Mr. Nice Guy,''
``Senseless,'' ``John and Julie,'' ``I Love You, I Love You Not,''
``The Informant,'' ``The Big Lebowski,'' ``The Substitute 2:
School's Out,'' ``Hamsun,'' ``Merlin.''  &UR; Aug. 18:  &LR; ``The Apostle,''
``Kundun,'' ``An Alan Smithee Film: Burn Hollywood Burn,'' ``Summer
Fling,'' ``The Borrowers.''  &UR; Aug. 25:  &LR; ``Men With Guns,'' ``The
Last Way Out,'' ``Sub Down,'' ``Naked Lies.''  &UR; Sept. 1:
 &LR; ``Titanic.''  &UR; Sept. 15:  &LR; ``Lady and the Tramp,'' ``The Last Don
II.''
</P>
