<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 (FU)!!! ``Passion in the Desert''  An unusual story about the bond
that develops between a French soldier in Napoleon's army and a
leopard he encounters while lost in the desert. It beats the odds,
compelling us to believe in the way the boundaries of the rational
world dissolve for the soldier once he's cut adrift and the leopard
allows him to return to an elemental world. (PG-13)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! ``Dear Jesse''  &LR; Tim Kirkman's autobiographical memoir doesn't
bash Sen. Jesse Helms (R-N.C.) because it doesn't have to. Given
Helms's pro-tobacco, anti-arts, and anti-gay-rights stance, Helms
indicts himself in this documentary, which chronicles his thus far
successful appeals to ignorance. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! ``Madeline''  &LR; Those who fondly remember the Ludwig Bemelmans
books about the free-spirited orphan who keeps breaking out of the
genteel propriety enveloping her Parisian boarding school will
smile upon this charming and carefully wrought film. Britain's
Hatty Jones takes the title role; Frances McDormand is the 12
little girls' mother figure and guardian angel, Miss Clavell. (PG)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ! 1/2 ``Lethal Weapon 4''  &LR; Mel Gibson and Danny Glover peddling
more mayhem. This time their LA cop characters are chasing down a
Chinese triad smuggling in immigrants as the first stage in
establishing a crime empire. If it weren't for shameless appeals to
sentimentality between the set pieces, there'd be no plot at all.
The only breath of freshness comes from Jet Li, making his
Hollywood debut as the explosively proficient young ganglord. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! ``Small Soldiers''  &LR; The smart-gimmick movie of the summer. It's
a toy story with attitude, as macho mercenary action figures come
to malevolent life after real battlefield microchips are inserted
into their musclebound, commando-gear-clad plastic bodies and they
set about leveling a hitherto peaceful Ohio town. Gregory Smith and
Kirsten Dunst are the teens who try to cram these evil genies back
into the bottle. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (FD)!! 1/2 ``The Land Girls''  &LR; David Leland's evocation of a trio
of young British women working on a farm during World War II, so
that men will be free to fight, is gorgeously and evocatively
detailed. But its love stories don't equal the impact of its
splendid atmospherics. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
