<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, YOU, IT'S A GOOOAAALLLL! 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a soccer announcer shouts GOOOAAALLL!, will anyone in this
country hear it?
</P>
<P>
   A generation after soccer started gaining popularity in the
United States (more youngsters now play soccer than any other team
sport but basketball), the American public is turning its back in
astonishing numbers on the planet's most popular sport.
</P>
<P>
   In June, when the monthlong World Cup competition began, the
government of Tunisia gave everybody in the nation the day off so
they could watch their team compete against Colombia. On Tuesday,
when Holland and Brazil were playing what had been in the most
dramatic match of the competition _ which ended Sunday when Brazil
France for the title _ most Americans seemed to register a
collective yawn.
</P>
<P>
   TV ratings in the United States for the World Cup are down 53
percent on ESPN from the cup of four years ago. Ratings on ABC went
from 5.3 in 1994, when the United States hosted the World Cup, to
2.3 for this year's version of the quadrennial event, which is
being played in France. That will come as a surprise to most
Americans. According to a Harris poll, only 25 percent of the
people surveyed could identify France as the host country for the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more shocking: Only half _ 52 percent _ knew that the
World Cup was a soccer competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is there remains an enormous gap between the
global importance of the World Cup and the importance of the event
to the non-ethnic American population,'' says Matt Scheckner,
director of sports and entertainment practice for Louis Harris &AMP;
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those numbers are dismal,'' says Scheckner about the poll.
``Should they set off alarm bells? You bet. Is there anything
soccer can do in the near term to reverse this? Probably not. It is
just not part of our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that nearly 14 million Americans between the ages of 6
and 18 play organized soccer _ and ``soccer moms'' are sought after
by both politicians and marketers _ yet the game languishes in
roughly the same purgatorial television tier as beach volleyball
and arena football?
</P>
<P>
   ``America's kids love to play soccer, but America loves pro
football, pro basketball and pro baseball,'' says Scheckner, adding
that despite the millions of Americans who play soccer, the game's
nuances are not understood well enough for people to appreciate all
the subtleties in a 0-0 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Fredrick, executive director of national broadcast for J.
Walter Thompson advertising agency in New York, said his children
played soccer and he once thought the sport would eventually rival
the big three. ``Kids love to play it, but then they leave it and
watch football,'' he says. ``One of the problems for soccer is that
to be really big as a sport, sports fans have to talk about it
around the water cooler. If you talk about soccer, it is kind of
arcane, and you keep it to yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The US team's pathetic performance _ it was ousted in the first
round _ did little to spark either patriotic fervor or a deep
interest in the game. And in a country where instant gratification,
fast-food restaurants, and MTV quick-cuts abound, the pace of
soccer is as foreign as the game itself. Consider that in the two
semifinal games last week, both hard-fought dramas, the teams
averaged a shot on goal every 7 minutes. To many Americans, that,
apparently, is as exciting as watching C-Span.
</P>
<P>
   The athletic diversity of American youth and soccer's low
profile make rare the child whose dream is to score the winning
goal in the World Cup finals. Rather, most want to hit the home run
that wins the World Series, or to be the next Michael Jordan. In
contrast, the fantasy of youngsters around the world is to be the
next Pele, to score the goal that brings glory to their country.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Americans miss out on a passion that brings the
rest of the world to a standstill. The World Cup, after all, is the
culmination of two years of preliminary matches that winnow the
field of 144 countries down to the qualifying 32. It is sports'
quintessential definition of delayed gratification.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no secret that right now, everywhere else on the planet,
things have stopped. Traffic lights are blinking and there are no
cars on the road, signs in shop windows say they are closed for the
game,'' says Dick Johnson, curator of the New England Sports
Museum. But, he says, unlike other countries, the United States is
not a single-sport country.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike some countries, the ever-dominant United States does
not feel the need to win battles on the soccer field as a way to
retaliate for losses on the battlefield. Not so elsewhere. Earlier
in the competition, when Iran beat the US team, effectively
eliminating us from advancing from the first round of 32 countries,
Iranians were jubilant. Those Americans who were paying attention
shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is an automatic nationalism that partly fuels the
popularity of the game everywhere in the world except here. But
more than nationalism makes the World Cup so popular. It is the
world's common denominator. Unlike the Olympics, which has its
share of esoteric sports, the World Cup is just soccer. And soccer
_ or football as the rest of the world calls it _ is what the world
plays.
</P>
<P>
   It creates in spectators feelings toward the athletes that range
from affinity to envy, from rage to joy. Soccer analyst Seamus
Malin notes that not everyone can relate to an athlete skiing
through the snow and then firing a rifle at a target, but everyone
in the Stade de France, and the billions around the world watching
on television, understand soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there are hot spots of interest in the United States.
The Boston area's Brazilian community is already out in force, and
the Crimson Sports Grille in Harvard Square was standing room only
Wednesday with foreign students watching France defeat Croatia, and
more people standing on the sidewalk of JFK Street watching the big
screen television through the bar's plate glass front window.
</P>
<P>
   But for every person who can identify Ronaldo and Rivaldo (the
former, one of the world's most recognized sports figures and the
star attacker of the Brazilian team, the latter is his midfield
teammate), there are countless others who could care less.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the discouraging Harris poll (which, for the record, a
US Soccer Federation spokesman says must be ``bogus'') and the drop
in ratings, television executives say they are thrilled by the
World Cup, which is being televised in its entirity, live and _
most un-American _ without commercial interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted,'' says ABC's Sports Jon Litner, senior vice
president for programming. ``We think it has been a terrific
tournament, competetive, and great for marketing. We think it
(soccer and the World Cup) is healthy and has a bright, long-term
future, and we will continue to work towards that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, whatever lack of passion the US continues to display,
the rest of the world will probably make up for it, sometimes for
the better _ like the spontaneous parties and parades that often
follow victories _ and sometimes for the worse. Defeat has, in the
past, led to desperate acts. For example, when Uruguay stunned
Brazil in the 1950 contest, dozens of despondent Brazilians
commited suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Victory or defeat can also bring out ugly displays of violence.
British soccer hooligans are known and dreaded the world over. And
their mayhem has spawned other acts of violence _ like the severe
beating last month of a French policeman by German fans, believed
to be neo-Nazis, who went wild after a game.
</P>
<P>
   And one cannot forget the most astonishing example of the
extreme behavior, which occured in 1994. In a game against the
United States, Colombian player Andres Escobar accidently scored a
goal into his own net, a pivotal error because Colombia was upset,
2-1. Colombia was eliminated from the competition, and shortly
after Escobar returned to Medellin, he was shot 12 times.
</P>
<P>
   As his murderers fired away, they reportedly shouted, ``Goal!
Goal! Goal!.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
