<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN CRISIS MAY BEGIN TO CLOUD US PROSPERITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The US economy's smooth ride on a dangerous wind
from the East is about to get rougher. Maybe a lot rougher, though
there still is no direct evidence that a decade that rivals the
1960s in prosperity will end with a cessation of economic growth or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   The last several days have highlighted a different picture from
the uniformly positive news of the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   _Employment and industrial production growth are flattening, and
unemployment may be trending higher from the lowest level in a
generation as firms dependent on exports feel the impact of Asia's
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the announcement by Internet powerhouse Yahoo
Inc. of second-quarter profits that exceeded Wall Street's
expectations served as a reminder that a new economy continues to
churn forward.
</P>
<P>
   _Federal Reserve estimates showed a contraction in the growth of
consumer borrowing during May, the slowest pace since last
November. And that news can be a hint of what is to come in
consumer spending, which remains the source of two-thirds of the
economy's juice.
</P>
<P>
   But the announcement by Folgers of a second cut in its list
price of coffee this year, in the face of the biggest Brazilian
coffee crop in more than a decade, is a reminder of how good
inflation news remains. That is in turn a key cause of low interest
rates that are crucial to continued overall growth.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, Americans will begin to see how much the
economy's pace is slowing, particularly when the Commerce
Department makes a preliminary estimate of total output of goods
and service for the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   There is universal agreement that the extraordinary pace of the
first quarter, a 5.4 percent annual rate, cannot be sustained. The
real question is how much the growth rate dropped. To most
Americans that's just a number. More important is a narrative of
the underlying developments, of which there are primarily two.
</P>
<P>
   The first is a change in how the Asian crisis is affecting this
country. At first, it was more beneficial than harmful. With the
dollar trending higher against the major Asian currencies, above
all the yen, there was a rise in imports from the countries
involved that was noticeable in prices paid by Americans before the
loss of exports was felt in lower production and employment in
affected businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, movement of money to these shores, above all to the
government bond market, in search of security had the effect _
along with the stability at long last in US budget policy _ of
keeping long-term interest rates low.
</P>
<P>
   That is now changing. The lost export business and diminished
future prospects are being felt now, and the impact is likely to
continue for at least the next six to nine months.
</P>
<P>
   The second development is somewhat technical, but probably more
important to the upcoming estimate of the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   The huge growth figure in the first quarter turns out to contain
the largest addition to business inventories in the history of
statistics about them. The change, worth slightly more than $100
billion at an annual rate, accounted for fully 1.7 percentage
points of the total rate of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Ain't gonna happen again, and it definitely did not happen in
the second quarter. Because what counts in measuring the economy is
the change in inventories from quarter to quarter, as opposed to
their absolute level, they were at best a zero last quarter and
more likely a negative.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in a less vibrant industrial sector generally, and weak
Asian exports in particular, and it is difficult to see how the
growth rate could have been much above 2 percent, if that.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, that is no surprise. The relentlesssly conservative
Clinton administration, in drawing up its budget documents early
this year, projected growth at 2 to 2.5 percent this year, as well
as in 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As the months pass, however, that assumption will be tested by
four major questions:
</P>
<P>
   _Will Asia stabilize? The engine of recovery will have to be
Japan. In the wake of parliamentary elections, the world will find
out whether Japanese recovery policies are credible or
inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   _When will the General Motors strike end? So far, it may cost
the economy a half-point in growth for the year, but if the worst
GM strike in 28 years goes past Labor Day, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   _Will US policymakers goof? One danger would be a premature
tightening of monetary policy by Alan Greenspan's Federal Reserve.
The other would be a loss of budgetary discipline by the Republican
Congress. The former is unlikely, the latter a slight danger.
</P>
<P>
   _Will the Asian bug spread? The potential danger areas are Latin
America and the Middle East, but it is only potential at the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing view remains that the United States will slow
down a good bit for the next half-year or so, but then gradually
speed up. But where near-euphoria once reigned, some very health
concern and skepticism now hold sway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
