<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-CHARITABLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY IMPOSES NEW RESTRICTIONS ON ITS CHARITY FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fidelity Investments has imposed new restrictions on
the ways in which donors to its hugely popular charity fund can use
their contributions, putting a lid on disbursements that could seem
at odds with the giant philanthropic fund's do-good mission.
</P>
<P>
   The changes at Fidelity's Charitable Gift Fund, one of the
nation's largest public charities, come amid carping from
traditional not-for-profit outfits and officials that charities run
by commercial companies can allow donors to benefit themselves
rather than worthy causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all sorts of donor-advised funds that cover the
waterfront in terms of behavior and appropriateness,'' said Marcus
S. Owens, head of tax-exempt organizations at the Internal Revenue
Service, referring to a new breed of charities, like Fidelity's,
that allows donors to decide which organizations receive their
assets. ``We are taking a look at some donor-advised organizations
a bit more closely,'' he said. He declined to comment on
Boston-based Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity officials said last month that the IRS had reaffirmed
the $1.3 billion Charitable Gift Fund's status as a public charity.
The IRS had not audited the philanthropic activities of the
nation's largest mutual fund company, said Jamie B. Jaffee, who
heads Fidelity's gift fund.
</P>
<P>
   At the fund, donors with at least $10,000 can set up an account,
sometimes named after themselves and styled like a personal
foundation, and take an immediate tax deduction on the gift. Unlike
traditional charities, which give donors little or no say in how
their money or stocks are used, Fidelity lets customers decide when
and to which cause the assets are disbursed. Customers cannot draw
money out and receive no money back.
</P>
<P>
   But &UR;  &LR; Fidelity executives acknowledged that a few of the fund's
more than 11,000 donors had in the past misdirected contributions
to private foundations and other non-IRS-registered organizations
that then used the money to buy benefit tickets, pay off pledges,
and finance scholarships and college tuition payments. Such uses
are prohibited by the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffee characterized the incidents as small in number and minor
in sum. She declined to provide details but said Fidelity had gone
back to the donors and asked them to return the money to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   While Fidelity explicitly prohibits grant distributions from
being used to satisfy personal benefits, the company has introduced
new restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Under new rules, outlined in a letter to gift fund donors last
week, Fidelity will not allow new donors to make grants to private
foundations. But under certain conditions the fund will consider
existing donors' recommended grants to private foundations until
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity has also banned donors from directing money to foreign
charities. Instead, disbursements should go to a US organization
that makes grants to foreign charities. And Fidelity now promises
it will disburse at least 5 percent of the gift fund's assets each
year _ a symbolic gesture, since the fund currently disburses 20
percent of its assets annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reviewing the procedures that the gift fund follows, there
were a number of areas where if the object is to avoid questions,
we thought we could make some enhancements,'' said Fred Goldberg, a
former IRS commissioner whom Fidelity hired to review the fund
after allegations of impropriety were raised.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception in 1992, Fidelity's charity fund has been a
runaway success with customers, who have found the idea of being
miniature Rockefellers appealing in a booming stock market that has
stuffed their wallets. Fidelity argues that the gift fund, which
has spawned a host of look-alikes, marries glamorous philanthropy
with average Americans. But such funds have stirred up controversy
among charities run by churches, hospitals, and relief outfits,
which are also wooing dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charities are upset because it's competition,'' said Stacy
E. Palmer, editor of The Chronicle of Philanthropy, an industry
newsletter. But she added: ``There is concern that it's not a level
playing field, that Fidelity has a marketing machine (to attract
donors) that other charities do not.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Charitable Gift Fund, the nation's 12-largest
charity by assets, was the country's number-one grant maker among
public charities, according to The Chronicle of Philanthropy. The
fund gave out nearly $195 million to 16,000 charities in 1997, more
than the American Cancer Society and the March of Dimes Birth
Defects Foundation. Over its lifetime, it has dispersed $680
million to more than 50,000 charities.
</P>
<P>
   Once customers put money or stock into the fund, Fidelity earns
a fee for managing the assets, which are funneled into Fidelity
mutual funds to grow before being disbursed by donor request.
Fidelity says the fee it charges covers administrative costs and
that it takes none of the interest.
</P>
<P>
   Slamming critics who have said the Charitable Gift Fund makes a
profit for Fidelity, company executives said the fund had actually
lost money every year since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am satisfied,'' Goldberg said, ``that they have not made a
dime off of this thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
