<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-YOAKAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DWIGHT YOAKAM: THE REAL BEVERLY HILLBILLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Hollywood sophisticate by day, a hillbilly by night. That's
the duality of Dwight Yoakam's life. He's a Grammy-winning country
singer with Kentucky roots, but also a hot motion-picture property
thanks to his work in the Oscar-winning ``Sling Blade,'' which has
led to more movie roles and the possible filming of a new Yoakam
screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't ask for a better opportunity than `Sling Blade,'''
Yoakam says of his jump-start from the Billy Bob Thornton-penned
film two years ago. In it, Yoakam played a mean drunk who was ``an
outgrowth of an all-too-common behavior in families,'' he says. He
has since played a bomb expert in ``The Newton Boys'' and just
started filming an HBO movie, ``Minus Man,'' in which he plays a
cop chasing a serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   To Yoakam's credit, he has doggedly surmounted any Hollywood
stereotypes about his hillbilly roots and music.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hillbilly genre I was in was sometimes a hindrance,''
Yoakam admits from his Los Angeles home. ``You're characterized as
a certain type regionally and colloquially, and it's taken some
time to transcend that. It was hard for the casting people to look
beyond a low-brimmed hat and a guitar slung over my shoulders. It
took time for me to convey my sincerity.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam, of course, has conveyed his musical sincerity for years
_ ever since the smash honky-tonk album ``Guitars, Cadillacs,
Etc.'' put him on the map in 1984. He has released a potent series
of retro-rocking hillbilly discs since then, peaking commercially
with 3 million sales of ``This Time'' in 1993, which yielded the
Top Five country hits ``Ain't That Lonely Yet,'' ``A Thousand Miles
from Nowhere,'' ``Try Not to Look So Pretty,'' and ``Pocket of a
Clown.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam followed that with the creative, if not commercial,
brilliance of ``Gone.'' That led to his new release, ``A Long Way
Home,'' a more personal album in which he wrote all of the material
(without collaborators) for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cosmic cowboy music for the new millennium'' is how Yoakam
describes his latest album, which incorporates a timeless, Johnny
Cash-like twang with modern lyrics about relationships, both
endings and beginnings. As with previous discs, it was produced by
his longtime guitarist and musical partner, Pete Anderson. The
latter knows how to coax the best performances from Yoakam, a noted
individualist who likes to rec-ord his vocals in near-darkness in
the studio.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Standing in the dark in the studio is less distracting,''
says Yoakam. ``I like to drift away from visual distractions. And
if I'm not seeing the tile floor and the microphone stands too
clearly, I feel more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Given how busy Yoakam is these days, one would not expect him to
have written everything on the new album. But like fellow
musician/film star Harry Connick Jr., Yoakam has learned to write
during the long down times on movie sets. He wrote the new songs
while filming ``The Newton Boys'' in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film didn't have anything to do with it, but the isolation
did,'' Yoakam says of his songwriting. ``I didn't expect to be
writing an album, but it came from a natural place.''
</P>
<P>
   The album's title, ``A Long Way Home,'' and its first hit
single, ``Things Change,'' suggest the rapid transitions Yoakam has
experienced in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the midst of transitions in my life on `Gone,' and
also subsequently on `Sling Blade,' which crawled, then toddled,
then ran to the success it eventually realized,'' he says. ``And I
was being pulled by that in an auxiliary way. The music is about
how relationships changed because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam has no plans to tour to support the album this year, but
will go out next year. ``That will be a difference from the last
couple of tours, where I found myself introducing the new material
to the audience,'' he says. ``I'd like to go out next time and
share the material, rather than present it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Yoakam is trying to see his screenplay (his first)
produced. It's a gothic western titled provocatively ``South of
Heaven, West of Hell.'' He's reluctant to describe it for fear of
jinxing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to do it, but you never know in Hollywood,'' he
says. ``I had a 212-page script that was cut to 193 pages to 166 to
a svelte 146. It's a lean, mean, fighting script. Today, it looks
as if (Hollywood) will let us shoot the movie. We're just waiting
to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
