<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE PUTS THEIR BEST FACE FORWARD
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Image consultant. The job description has a superficial, even
slick, ring, but the actual work is practical, and very personal.
Trust is crucial, says image consultant Ginger Burr as she works on
client Ann Paquin's makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clients have to feel comfortable with me,'' says Burr, who has
been an image consultant for 11 years. ``They're not going to let
just anyone into their homes, their lives. I see them in their
underwear. I tell them: I've seen everything, you won't be
embarassed. I promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Burr, one of several Boston-area image consultants, has worked
with hundreds of clients, most of them professional women ranging
in age from their 30s to their 60s. Her usual fee is $75 an hour.
She does color analysis, makeup, wardrobe consultation, personal
shopping, advises clients about hair, glasses, jewelry. She helps
some pack for trips, she advises others on choosing the right
outfit for an important occasion. ``Whatever it takes to make a
client look good, I'll do it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Burr's business is a bit unusual in that it includes a number of
transgender clients who have completed or who are awaiting gender
reassignment surgery. She saw her first transgender client shortly
after she launched her business, and over the years, word-of-mouth
recommendations have brought her more, for whom she does much the
same work as she does for her other clients. ``The only difference
is that usually we're starting from ground zero,'' says Burr.
</P>
<P>
   The image consulting business is growing, as more women, and men
too, realize that the way in which they present themselves can have
a make-or-break impact on their careers, to say nothing of their
personal lives. The Association of Image Consultants International
has more than 600 members worldwide, 200 of whom, Burr included,
are meeting this week in Miami at a five-day conference for, among
other events, panels titled ``Feng-Shui _ the Image Consultants'
Way,'' and ``The Psychology of Appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   Image consultants advise clients on every aspect of their
personal style, from wardrobe and makeup to speech and body
language. They come from a variety of backgrounds and disciplines.
Burr's career path is typically atypical. She was a music major at
Mount Holyoke College, worked in Boston in arts administration and,
at MIT, word processing. ``I'd always had an interest in makeup and
fashion, although 15 years ago you never would have known it to
look at me,'' she says. ``And I always wanted to start my own
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Burr attended seminars conducted by Worldwide Images, a training
organization, and set up her business, Total Image Consultants, in
a studio in her Somerville home. Slim, fine-featured, impeccably
groomed, Burr, 42, is her own best advertisement. She likes to show
vistors a ``before'' photo of herself as she looks when she gets up
in the morning, with no makeup, her hair hanging limply, and ask
them to compare it with a glamorous ``after'' photo in which
resembles a CNN anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Richardson of Newburyport, Mass., author and business
coach, credits Burr with transforming her look, which boosted her
career. ``I did what a lot of women do, I completely underestimated
the importance of my image as a business-building strategy,''
Richardson says. ``I thought if people liked me it didn't matter
how I looked.''
</P>
<P>
   She found out how important image can be when, after Burr took
her in hand, she attended a meeting of influential business
executives whom she had tried, unsuccessfully, to impress on a
previous occasion. ``That day I had seven or eight people come up
to me, ask what I did, and give me their business cards,'' she
says. ``That one day really changed everything for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Burr's introductory two-hour session includes color analysis,
makeup application, and instruction and advice about hairstyle.
Most clients also want a wardrobe consultation, which means that
Burr goes through their closets, helps them weed out has-beens, and
organize what's left. She also shops with or for clients. One of
her favorite haunts is the Turnabout Shop in Wellesley, a high-end
resale boutique. ``I've seen Ginger in action for four or five
years and I've learned a lot from her,'' says owner Elaine
Sugarman. ``She helps her clients learn what looks good on them and
what doesn't and gives them the confidence to make choices without
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the women she works with, Burr's transgender
clients are working professionals who want help with makeup, hair,
and wardrobe and don't have the time or the expertise to do it
themselves. Some are afraid to shop for themselves, so Burr selects
clothing for them. She also has a few cross-dressers as clients,
men who enjoy dressing as women. ``They usually want a more
flamboyant look,'' she said. ``It's fun, but not for everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, her transgender clients want more conservative
clothes that they can wear to work. Many of them have high-powered
jobs. ``I've been reborn, but I don't have the benefit of having a
girlhood,'' said one, a 52-year-old woman who heads her own
technical consulting business. ``I have all these things to learn
about hair, makeup, clothing. I felt I had to go to someone who
would give me a complete education.''
</P>
<P>
   This client, who asked that her name not be used, underwent
gender reassignment surgery just a few months ago. ``When I
transitioned I had nothing,'' she said, from her Rhode Island home.
``I had to start from scratch. I'd never worn makeup. And men's
clothing choices are so much less complicated. You don't have all
the style and color and fabric selections, the different outfits
for various occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   Burr taught her how to apply makeup and took her shopping at
Saks and Filenes. ``Appearance is very important in my job because
I'm constantly meeting people,'' she said. ``I'm very pleased with
the results. I feel I have a long way to go, because I can't be
sure that everything I've accomplished in the past will be accepted
now that I'm a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Burr, she added, has been ``very supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very rewarding part of my business,'' Burr says. ``I
feel I'm making a big difference in their lives. On their part, it
takes a lot of courage. You have to be so sure of who you are, who
you want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Burr's job incorporates elements of therapy. She has to be a
good listener. ``I spend a lot of time talking with clients,'' she
says. ``I have to get a real sense of who they are and what they're
going for. It's very personal. If I take somebody shopping without
knowing about them, I don't know how to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Paquin of Boston says Burr helped her develop a casual but
businesslike look appropriate for her job as a national distributor
of Shaklee products. ``I want to look good, but I don't want to be
thinking all the time: How do I look?'' says Paquin. A longtime
client, Paquin visits Burr every so often for makeup and wardrobe
updates.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Burr's clients have body image problems. One told her
that she looked in her closet every morning and cried. ``They hate
their clothes, hate how they look,'' Burr said. ``Every woman who
looks into my mirror will start tearing herself apart. Every one.
She'll notice flaws that nobody else sees, or what she considers to
be flaws. It would be wonderful if all women could accept who they
are, how they look. When was the last time you heard a man talk
about the size of his thighs?''
</P>
<P>
   Often women will tell her that they'll call for an appointment
in six months or a year, when they've lost 10 or 15 pounds. ``I
wish I could convince them to do it now,'' Burr says. ``Because if
they do, they're going to feel better about themselves, even if
they don't lose weight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
