<HEADER>
A2255 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARITAL-BLITZ-ART-BOS     07-13 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARITAL-BLITZ-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEVIN'S GUIDE TO WEDDING SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Dan Zevin is not a man to miss an opportunity
to turn his life's milestones into comic prose and potential
bestsellerdom.
</P>
<P>
   Zevin, 33, burst onto the humor scene four years ago with
``Entry Level Life,'' a tongue-in-cheek, how-to book for recent
college graduates about surviving in the real world. At the time,
he was surviving in the real world by working as ``gear editor''
for the Boston-based Walking magazine, a job that entailed ripping
running shoes apart and examining the innersoles, all the time
contemplating the depressing disparity between his job hopes and
reality.
</P>
<P>
   His book dealt with ``the things career counselors don't tell
you,'' Zevin says of ``Entry Level Life,'' which poked wicked fun
at ``What Color Is Your Parachute?'' and other solemn career
manuals. ``Like making the transition from keg party to cocktail
party and how to decorate an apartment with milk crates.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ``The Nearly-Wed Handbook _ How to Survive the
Happiest Day of Your Life'' (Avon Books), a spoof of
wedding-planning guides that Zevin began writing just about as soon
as his honeymoon was over.
</P>
<P>
   Like his first book, ``The Nearly-Wed Handbook'' parodies an
entire genre of pretentious how-to books. In this case, he says,
``all those books with pink covers that supposedly tell you how to
have the perfect wedding but really just make you feel inadequate.
Like you don't know what you're doing _ which you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   A shrewd and witty observer of Gen-X mores, the 33-year-old
Zevin, who majored in journalism at New York University, says men
of his generation frequently don't even start thinking about
getting married ``until the day after attending the wedding of a
kid they used to baby-sit for.'' Marriage usually sneaks up on
these guys, he notes, when they aren't paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the typical unmarried woman, Zevin maintains, is an inner
bride trying to get out. Women are usually aware of this at some
level, he says, but single men are utterly dumbfounded to discover
that they have an inner groom. ``One day you're sitting in front of
the TV in your underwear watching ESPN and the next thing you know
you're down on your knees proposing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He insists (with a not very straight face) that ``Stan'' and
``Peg,'' the couple whose chaotic and costly progress from live-in
companionship to wedded bliss he gleefully chronicles, are not be
confused with ``Dan'' (Daniel Zevin) and ``Meg'' (Megan Tingley),
who got married in the Berkshires a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Zevin and Tingley met while students at NYU and moved to the
Boston area in 1986. She is a children's book editor. They live in
North Cambridge in a recently purchased two-family house.``We got
married on our 10th anniversary,'' quips Zevin. ``We needed new
kitchen appliances and you don't get presents if you elope.''
</P>
<P>
   After the publication of ``Entry Level Life,'' which has sold
about 40,000 copies, Zevin quit his magazine job to become a
freelance writer. He contributes to Rolling Stone (where he
interned as a student) and other national publications. ``I just
wrote an article for U.S. News &AMP; World Report about aging
Generation Xers like me who are getting married,'' he says, ``but
they edited most of the humor out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zevin has a prose style that's a blend of Dave Barry and P.J.
O'Rourke, and, happily, the editors who worked on the ``The
Nearly-Wed Handbook'' left the laughter in. ``Getting wedded is an
exhausting experience, and I'm trying to provide some comic
relief,'' says Zevin. ``You need a sense of humor to survive it.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Nearly-Wed Handbook,'' Zevin takes the prospective
bride and groom step by step through the wedding process _ which is
not to be confused with the marriage process. Getting married,
explains Zevin, means: ``You make the most mature adult decision of
your life.'' Getting wedded, however, means: ``You spend three
hours deciding whether to register for the sterling silver olive
pitter or the crystal margarita decanter with cactus theme swizzle
sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   Useful tips for nearly wed grooms include where to get an
engagement ring. ``The best place to go shopping for a ring is the
place your fiancee has told you to go. Make sure to bring the stack
of Polaroids she has taken of the ring she has selected.'' Also,
what kind of orchestra not to hire for the reception: ``The Tony
Cheesetone All-Bald Wedding Combo.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly wed brides, Zevin provides capsule descriptions of
various kinds of ``specialty'' bridal showers, such as the
bachelorette party. ``A favorite among gals who find male stag
parties so juvenile, so vulgar, so demeaning, they are forced to
have one themselves. Party antics include dressing up in toilet
paper wedding gowns, engaging in adult-themed scavenger hunts and
stuffing dollar bills down the athletic supporters of gyrating
Chippendale dancers.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; On the wedding day, Zevin advises the modern bride to reject
the sexist practice of having her father give her away. ``Tell your
patriarchal oppressor you won't let yourself be `given away.' For a
mutually agreed upon fee, however (for example, the outstanding
balance on the florist) you'll be happy to let him walk you down
the aisle.''
</P>
<P>
   Stressful as the wedding ceremony may seem, Zevin says, what
follows may be equally traumatic. Such as: the receiving line, a
spotlit solo dance performance (``the dance of fear'' ),
table-hopping at the reception (Everyone asks: ``So, how does it
feel to be married?''), and the bridal bouquet toss (``The bouquet
never lands on the floor but many of the women vying to catch it
do.'')
</P>
<P>
   His own wedding was actually a pretty happy occasion, Zevin
says. ``It was a nonreligious ceremony in an old farmhouse in
Western Massachusetts that's the kind of special wedding place
nobody else is supposed to know about but you have to book a couple
of years in advance,'' he says. ``I only recognized about 15
percent of the guests, but we had a 12-piece funk band.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides writing freelance articles, a happily married (as
opposed to wedded) Zevin keeps busy doing an occasional commentary
for National Public Radio and hosting a weekly call-in show on
WMFO-FM, Tufts University community radio. ``The show is called
`Every Day People,''' he says, ``and I interview plumbers,
electricians, dog trainers, and people like the guy who runs my
favorite sandwich shop.''
</P>
<P>
   He also still gets invited ``by career counselors with a sense
of humor'' to lecture about life at entry level to nearly graduated
college students. Then, there's the new book he's working on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about buying a first house,'' Zevin says, ``and is
tentatively titled `Surreal Estate.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
