<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRITIC-NONESUCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NONESUCH LIVES UP TO ITS NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of America's cultural institutions have decided that the
only way to survive in today's market-driven world is to follow the
lead of politicians. Instead of inviting the public in through the
force of artistic personality, the trend is to pander to public
taste. Classical labels and even a public-radio station follow this
path of least resistance.
</P>
<P>
   There are, though, still cases where a cultural institution,
even a commercial one, forges such a strong personality that
audiences are drawn by the continued excellence of its output. Take
``The Connection'' on WBUR-FM in Boston or the Kendall Square
Cinema in Cambridge, Mass. Not only do they not pander; they lead
their audiences to sample subjects people might not otherwise
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Under Robert Hurwitz, Nonesuch Records has been a similar oasis
of artistic excitement, since 1984. When one picks up a Nonesuch
CD, there is the sense of occasion, the feeling that the artists in
question have been assembled not as an exercise in star power, but
as an exercise in artistic exploration. Even when the results are
disappointing, there isn't a feeling of being shortchanged, because
the label has such a strong record of paying dividends, of opening
doors onto exotic musical landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   Nonesuch began life as a classical label in 1964, with twin
specialties in early music and contemporary composers. Joshua
Rifkin produced two '60s classics. ``The Baroque Beatles Book''
demonstrated the relationship of Beatles melodies to Bach and
Telemann, and ``Piano Rags by Scott Joplin'' sparked renewed
interest in Joplin and ragtime. William Bolcom and Joan Morris also
recorded for the label.
</P>
<P>
   Now both a profitable and prestigious arm of Time Warner,
Nonesuch's current classical roster is a who's who of minimalist
music _ Steve Reich, Philip Glass, and John Adams (though it has
been a pleasure to listen to Adams break out of that category with
his more expansive recent work, like the Violin Concerto and his
latest release, ``Gnarly Buttons''). The Kronos Quartet, which
performs only 20th-century music, records for the label; so does
Richard Goode, playing the traditional piano repertory. They would
seem to have nothing in common with each other, let alone with jazz
guitarist Bill Frisell, classical violinist Gidon Kremer, opera
singer Dawn Upshaw, and Broadway belter Mandy Patinkin.
</P>
<P>
   Or with all the artists in the world-music idiom: Cesaria
Evoria, the Buena Vista Social Club (Ry Cooder's Grammy-winning
mission to Cuba), Radio Tarifa, and one of its most recent
releases, Paolo Conte, a grizzled Italian singer who somehow merges
the sensibilities of Tom Waits, Jerry Lee Lewis, Edith Piaf, and
Frank Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a sensibility that unites them, one in which all
these musical categories dissolve not into a Pavarotti-meets-Sting
eclectic emptiness or a Sony Records all-star snooze, but into a
musical world where boundaries between genres stretch and snap.
Where a Gidon Kremer can go to new places with John Adams and then
make such a heartfelt case for tango master Astor Piazzolla as he
has on a pair of CDs. Or a Dawn Upshaw can move so effortlessly
from singing with Richard Goode to collaborating with Mandy
Patinkin.
</P>
<P>
   Hurwitz says that what unites the artists he's signed to
Nonesuch is ``their one-of-a-kindness. There was just one
Piazzolla. He was a complete original. Bill Frisell is the same
kind of an original. Steve Reich and John Adams have such a strong
identity. Those are the people who attracted me ... people like
Richard Goode and John Zorn, who have such a complete and utter
focus in what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect of Nonesuch releases that makes them almost leap
off the shelves is the handsome packaging. ``All of us who work at
Nonesuch take every detail very seriously,'' said Hurwitz. ``We
want the records to be memorable, that are works of art themselves
and reflect something that made the music special. And that 10
years from now will still look pretty good.'' Each of the CDs since
1995 is enclosed in a cardboard slipcover over the jewelcase, each
with striking artwork. There's Isabel Munoz's sexy
hand-on-bare-back photograph on Kremer's first Piazzolla CD, which
perfectly captures the sensuality of the music within. Roberto
Serra's photographs of Paolo Conte are so evocative you want to
find whatever club he's playing in and bum a cigarette from him.
The covers are so good they can lead you astray. Nonesuch's film
series, with photos from ``Rebel Without a Cause,'' ``A Streetcar
Named Desire,'' and ``Jules and Jim,'' makes you think the music of
Leonard Rosenman, Alex North, and Georges Delerue is going to be
better than it is. The CD of Toru Takemitsu's film music is more
successful.
</P>
<P>
   Heightening the sense that each CD is an event is the fact that
there are only 20 to 25 releases a year. Each is more a project
than a product off an assembly line. Aside from the film series,
most of the projects yield remarkable results. The Buena Vista
Social Club not only won a Grammy, but anchored a trio of releases
from Cuba, including the Afro-Cuban All Stars and, best of the
three, ``Introducing ... Ruben Gonzalez,'' an 80-year-old Cuban
pianist _ imagine a Duke Ellington of danzon and guaracha making
his first recording.
</P>
<P>
   Nonesuch also has been one of the stellar labels in terms of
Broadway music, restoring George Gershwin's piano rolls and
re-recording his lesser-known musicals like ``Oh, Kay'' and
``Strike Up the Band.'' The most successful Broadway project,
though, was the label's ``Leonard Bernstein's New York'' with
Upshaw, Patinkin, Donna Murphy, Audra McDonald, Judy Blazer, and
Richard Muenz singing music from Bernstein's shows set in New York,
along with selections from his underrated score from ``On the
Waterfront.'' The ``Balcony Scene'' duet between Patinkin and
McDonald (the Tony-winning actress of ``Carousel,'' ``Master
Class,'' and ``Ragtime'' who just finished her first solo CD) is
out of this world, as is Upshaw's ``Somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the individual projects already mentioned,
Frisell's ``Nashville'' is a particularly gorgeous blend of jazz
and country music, and Upshaw's solo CDs erase any barrier between
Broadway and classical music. Patinkin's ``Oscar &AMP; Steve,'' a
salute to Oscar Hammerstein and Stephen Sondheim, as well as his
recent Yiddish CD, ``Mamaloshen,'' are never less than, well,
really something. I still can't tell whether I love or hate ``Bali
Hai,'' and you haven't heard ``White Christmas'' until you've heard
it in Yiddish.
</P>
<P>
   As Hurwitz said, each of these artists has a unique voice and
each is allowed to take it, and us, to new musical places. The
dictionary defines ``nonesuch'' as a person or thing without an
equal. Under Hurwitz's direction, the label has lived up to its
name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
