<SLUG> BC-HUTCHESON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT TAKES MORE ENERGY TO HATE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If anyone has a right to hate, it's Renee Mullins.
In the early morning hours of June 7, her father, James Byrd Jr.,
was kidnapped, beaten, chained to a pickup and dragged along a
rural road in East Texas until his body disintegrated.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators in Jasper found Byrd's remains spread over two
miles. His severed head, neck and right arm were discovered about a
mile from his battered torso. Police believe that Byrd, 49, died
for one reason: He was black.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Mullins have to say about the three whites who have
been charged with the killing? She wants us to pray for them.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins, 27, appeared before the Senate Judiciary Committee this
week to endorse legislation that would expand federal jurisdiction
over hate crimes. But it was her emotional plea for racial
tolerance that left her audience spellbound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want all citizens to pray for these individuals, who have
such low self-esteem and who are so full of fear and hatred that
they are cut out from the happiness of life,'' she told the Senate
panel. ``I've learned from living 27 years _ it takes more energy
to hate than to love.''
</P>
<P>
   I saw the kind of energy that some people devote to hate once
during a college hitchhiking trip from Austin to New Orleans.
Somewhere near the Louisiana border, I got picked up by a Ku Klux
Klansman and his young son. The toddler could barely speak, but his
father proudly demonstrated how the boy's limited vocabulary
included the ``N-word.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we hate?'' the father asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``N__'' ... well, you know the rest. I couldn't wait to get out
of the car, but I've often wondered what happened to that kid. Is
he one of the men awaiting trial for Byrd's murder? Could he
possibly have overcome that kind of upbringing? It doesn't seem
likely.
</P>
<P>
   I've been doing a little reading on hate groups lately.
Klanwatch, an organization that monitors racist organizations,
reports that Texas has at least 18 white supremacist groups,
including chapters in Fort Worth and Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Fort Worth groups is the National Alliance, which
spells out its vision for an ``Aryan society'' on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``In specific terms,'' the alliance proclaims, ``this means a
society in which young men and women gather to revel with polkas or
waltzes, reels or jigs or any other White dances, but never to
undulate or jerk to negroid jazz or rock rhythms. It means pop
music without Barry Manilow and art galleries without Marc
Chagall.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm no fan of Barry Manilow either, but I don't think Lawrence
Welk is the answer to that problem.
</P>
<P>
   As if that isn't wacky enough, a short time later I got a chance
to read David Duke's views on golfer Tiger Woods. You might
remember Duke. He's the former Klansman who cleaned up his act to
enter politics as a Republican. Neither the Republicans nor the
voters wanted much to do with him.
</P>
<P>
   Duke seems to be spending his time these days worrying about
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the emphasis many put on sports heroes, Woods'
ascendancy in the golf realm will simply add to the myth that most
Blacks are just like us,'' Duke writes in a lengthy essay. ``A
number of White men will be suckered in by a wave of admiration and
emotion for one Black golf player into believing that the Black
race can fit in and do well among the White race. That is simply
untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm pretty sure Mullins would also want us to pray for Duke and
the gang at the National Alliance. In any case, it's pretty clear
who is talking sense and who is talking nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   (Ron Hutcheson is chief of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram's
Washington bureau. You can e-mail him at
rhutcheson &LR; krwashington.com or call him at (202) 383-6000. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
