<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMETICS-INFECTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDATED EYE MAKEUP CAN BE A SOURCE OF INFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DR. ELLIOT FINKELSTEIN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; c. Medical Tribune News Service &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Millions of American women stepped up to the bathroom mirror
this morning to apply their eye makeup without knowing that the
cosmetics that make those baby blues (or browns or greens) look
beautiful can also do them serious harm.
</P>
<P>
   Although most makeup is completely safe, contaminated or
outdated cosmetics have been known to cause infections capable of
damaging eyesight permanently.
</P>
<P>
   The moment cosmetics are opened for the first time, bacteria
move in and start growing. Most cosmetic products have
preservatives to slow that process, but the bacteria eventually win
out, and a meeting between bacteria and the surface of the eye can
have devastating consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The danger is greatest with mascara, because it's worn the
closest to the eye. Fortunately, protecting yourself requires
following only a few simple precautions recommended by the American
Academy of Ophthalmology.
</P>
<P>
   --First, if your eye makeup has been open more than three
months, throw it out and replace it -- especially mascara.
</P>
<P>
   --Second, never share cosmetics with anyone, because you could
be sharing an infection as well.
</P>
<P>
   --Third, opt for hypoallergenic products and disposable
applicators wherever possible.
</P>
<P>
   --And fourth, if you do develop an eye infection, throw out all
your old makeup -- contaminated cosmetics could re-infect you.
</P>
<P>
   Contact lens wearers need to exercise extra care when using
cosmetics, because some products can damage eyes and lenses. Use
only water-based mascara -- avoid mascaras labeled
``lash-building'' or ``guaranteed waterproof'' because they contain
rayon or nylon fibers that can fall into the eye, slip under a
contact lens and injure the cornea.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing can happen with frosted or iridescent eye shadows
-- they contain ground oyster shells and tinsel. Avoid them, and
generally speaking, don't buy makeup that may not have been
thoroughly tested for safety.
</P>
<P>
   Your morning makeup-and-lens routine can be critical, too. Use
hair spray and other aerosols first, and wait for the mist to clear
before inserting your contacts. Put your lenses in before applying
your makeup, and take them out before removing it.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful with eyeliner and don't apply it inside the lower
lashes. Apply face powder gently to keep it away from your eyes.
And throughout the process, wash your hands with a pure,
additive-free bar soap.
</P>
<P>
   One final safety tip -- don't put on your makeup in the car,
even if you're not driving. One abrupt stop or pothole could mean a
painful meeting between a mascara brush and your eye -- and a trip
to the ophthalmologist.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Elliot M. Finkelstein, M.D., is president of the American
Academy of Ophthalmology in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Distributed by New York Times Special Features
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
