<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY ARE GOLF BALLS DIMPLED? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why do golf balls have dimples?
</P>
<P>
   B.K., Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Thank the old Featheries and Gutties for the dimples on golf
balls. Featheries were the first balls used, 500 or 600 years ago.
They were little more than a two-seamed leather sack stuffed with
feathers. Around 1870, a natural gum discovered in Malaysia was
fashioned into the first Guttie, a smooth ball that sank like a
rock compared with the old Featherie.
</P>
<P>
   Discouraged duffers eventually discovered, however, that the
more nicked and scratched their Gutties got, the farther they
traveled. So manufacturers started making them with all kinds of
cuts and grooves and lumps. And then in 1908, businessman William
Taylor patented the Bramble pattern of dimples.
</P>
<P>
   Since then we've learned why the dimples work. A golf ball in
flight is doing a couple things to the air around it. It's making
air pass over and under it, but it's also creating a partial vacuum
in its wake as it displaces the air it's forcing out of its path.
And because the ball is moving so fast, the air traveling over and
under it can't immediately fill the vaccum just behind the ball.
That makes the pressure against the ball high at the front, and
lower at the back. The ball favors the path of least resistance,
which is backwards. That's called drag, and it slows the ball's
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Aoyala of the Titleist Company in Fairhaven, Mass. says
dimples stir up the air passing over the skin of the ball in
flight. That turbulence allows more air to tumble in behind the
ball, helping fill that partial vacuum and cutting the drag in
half.
</P>
<P>
   Aoyala proudly points out that the golf ball is the most highly
engineered ball in sports. Its dimple patterns include 20-faced
icosahedrons and cuboctahedrons, the shape you'd get if you cut the
corners off a cube.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the lava in lava lamps?
</P>
<P>
   J.D., Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. All those fascinating bloops and gloops are made of wax. But
not just any wax, says Garret Kaess, chief chemist for Haggerty
Enterprises, which refers to itself as ``Lava World.''
</P>
<P>
   The mix involves chlorinated paraffins with six ingredients, but
he won't say much more, because the formula is a trade secret.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  British scientist and inventor Walter Craven developed the
formula in the early 1960s. But he didn't know Jimi Hendrix was
right around the corner, and sold it to the Haggerty family in
1965. Then along came the drug culture and Lava Lamps became a
cultural icon.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the water in which the waxy blobs float around is a
special concoction as well. Chemicals called surfactants reduce
surface tension and let the blobs of melted wax break apart and
squish back together just right. They also keep the wax _ the
``lava'' _ from sticking to the sides of the bottle. Other
substances called chelating agents keep the water clear. Glycols
alter the specific gravity of the water to allow the wax to float
when it's heated by the 40-watt light bulb in the base and the
heat-transfer coil built into the bottom of the glass bottle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Kaess says the brew is nearly identical to anti-freeze, only
clear.
</P>
<P>
   The waxy blob moves around because heating it makes it less
dense, causing it to float. As it rises, away from the heat, it
cools, condenses, and sinks.
</P>
<P>
   Because the dyes for each of the 25 colors change the specific
gravity of the lava,subtle changes have to be made to the amount of
chlorines added to the wax and to the formula of the water, so each
color blobs around just right.
</P>
<P>
   Devoted Lava Lamp lovers (or people with enough time on their
hands to spend hours watching their lamps) might wonder why the
lava seems to go from a see-through translucent to a more milky
opaque after the lamp has been on for the first couple days. The
expanding and contracting wax slowly absorbs a little water, about
half a percent, which clouds things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on trying to cure that,'' Kaess says. The
milkiness seems to dampen the experience for the most hardcore lava
lamp fans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
