<HEADER>
A2270 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REWARD-KIDS-EFFORT-NY     07-13 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REWARD-KIDS-EFFORT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE CAREFUL WHEN YOU PRAISE KIDS FOR GOOD GRADES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By PETER MODICA  
 c.1998 Medical Tribune News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though parents often encourage their children by lauding good
grades and high test scores, such praise actually may leave
youngsters ill-equipped to deal with setbacks, new research
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 412 fifth-graders, psychologists at Columbia
University in New York found that children complimented for
intelligence rather than for effort when they performed well
academically tended to place greater importance on grades than on
learning or mastering new skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's believed that praising a child's traits _ such as
intelligence _ will create greater self-esteem and make them feel
productive and what we're showing is that [such praise] can
backfire,'' said lead study author Carol S. Dweck, a professor of
psychology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Praising children's intelligence, far from boosting their
self-esteem, encourages them to embrace self-defeating behaviors,
such as worrying about failure and avoiding risks,'' Dweck said.
</P>
<P>
   Children should be commended for hard work, which encourages
them to seek out strategies to enhance their performance, Dweck and
her colleague Claudia M. Mueller reported in the July issue of the
Journal of Personality and Social Psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Children in the study were divided into groups that were given
different forms of praise. For example, after a good performance,
one group was told ``you must be really smart'' after a good grade,
while the other group was told ``you must have worked hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Most children who had their intelligence praised wanted to
continue looking smart and were more reluctant to take on greater
challenges, Dweck said. However, nearly all of those given
encouragement for hard work and effort were motivated to learn new
things even when the tasks were highly challenging, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, children who concentrated on grades lost enjoyment when
learning new things that could potentially make them look ``dumb.''
Such learning remained enjoyable for those who did not concentrate
on grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone cares about grades and should to some extent. But the
question remains, is that all you should care about,'' Dweck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be some risk for children if the predominant
or only form of praise is for academic accomplishments. There can
be devastating results if they experience failure,'' commented
Peter Goldenthal, a clinical and family psychologist in Wayne, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea would be to do both. Praise your child for their
accomplishments, but when you do that make them know that failure
is possible and that they should learn from it,'' Goldenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Verbal praise is very powerful and one of the implications of
the study is if it is too narrowly focused or applied, for some
children it might be upsetting if they cannot perform to the
standards of that praise,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1345EDT &QL; 
