<HEADLINE>
CABLE INDUSTRY CONTINUES TO SPECIALIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: ``style.'' with lc s and . is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The cable industry has made it clear that the
future of television continues to be in specialization.
</P>
<P>
   TV critics here for the semiannual press tour ovr the weekend
were deluged with previews of new shows by everything from the
Travel Channel, Animal Planet, and the Golf Channel to the Game
Show Network, the Cartoon Network, and Home &AMP; Garden Television.
Lee Masters, the president and CEO of E! Entertainment Television,
took the weekend as an opportunity to introduce yet another new
corner of the TV universe called ``style.,'' a hip companion
network to E! that will restrict itself to fashion, dining out, and
home decorating when it launches in October.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of cable, what seemed like ridiculous hype
predicted that someday we would be able to choose from among a
thousand channels, each devoted to a narrowly defined subject. But
that possibility no longer seems far-fetched. And as Larry W.
Jones, general manager of Nick at Nite and TV Land, reminded
critics that Nick is strictly for classic sitcoms while TV Land
also programs old dramas like ``St. Elsewhere,'' the
thousand-channel future seemed to be waiting around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most promising cable programming due in the coming
months will be on the fast-growing VH1. The network began in 1985
as an older cousin to MTV, and by the early 1990s it was viewed as
a creative failure. But in 1994, with a savvy new president, John
Sykes, at the helm, VH1 began to find its identity as an
authoritative and yet playful channel for fans of rock 'n' roll
history. And now, with signature series like ``Behind the Music,''
``Storytellers,'' ``Pop-Up Video,'' and ``Legends,'' VH1 has
surpassed MTV as the place to look for exposure to and insight into
music culture. ``Music is really at the heart and soul of
everything that we do at VH1,'' Sykes noted, inadvertently pointing
up the problem with MTV's gimmick-heavy programming lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Forthcoming VH1 series includes a comedy called ``Vinyl
Justice,'' which follows the investigations of a pair of ``music
policemen'' who bust people _ some of them famous _ for bad taste.
Imagine an officer writing out a violation for driving under the
influence of Wham!, and you've got the picture. Another new series,
``Video Timeline,'' will illustrate music videos with archival
footage, interviews, and irreverent onscreen graphics in the manner
of ``Pop-Up Video.'' VH1 also announced the formation of a TV-movie
wing already developing a documentary by Oscar-winning director
Barbara Kopple called ``Trouble Girls: Women in Rock,'' as well as
a fictional film about an imagined meeting between Paul McCartney
and John Lennon in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   In order to promote ``Endless Harmony: The Beach Boys and Their
Music,'' a two-hour special premiering on Aug. 23, VH1 brought in a
tired-looking Brian Wilson for a question-and-answer session. The
former Beach Boy, famous for his personal ups and downs, was
particularly enigmatic when asked why he has been so fragile
through the years: ``I think the Christmas carol `Joy to the World'
must have bent me out of shape a little bit,'' he said, ``and of
course my whole life was given over to God as soon as I heard that.
So in a way I can't be blamed for being a little more sensitive
than usual.'' Wilson said he ``got in contact with that Christmas
carol'' in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   HBO introduced its new movies, most notably a pair of timely
biopics. ``Winchell,'' due in November, stars Stanley Tucci as the
man many blame for the dangerous power of gossip in the media.
``The Rat Pack,'' which airs August 22, stars Ray Liotta as Frank
Sinatra, Joe Mantegna as Dean Martin, and Don Cheadle as Sammy
Davis Jr.
</P>
<P>
   While Tina Sinatra refused to authorize the project or allow use
of Sinatra's music, John Matoian, president of HBO Pictures, said,
``Hopefully when Tina sees it, I believe she'll like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Matoian package the movie to air on the heals of Sinatra's
death? ``I'm not that good,'' he said. ``And I'm not that bad
either!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
