<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2272 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMEDY-ONEAL-BOS &LR;      07-13 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMEDY-ONEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRICE O'NEAL TRIES TO MAKE IT BIG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrice O'Neal is killing. The packed house at the US Comedy
Festival in Aspen is rolling with laughter as O'Neal punctuates the
smoky air inside the Aspen Sports Club with a delivery as crisp and
clear as the Rocky Mountains just beyond the door.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4, 350-pound African-American is doing a routine
about an Eastern European gymnast, in which he imitates the voice
of Nadia Comaneci. It's a hilarious piece, made all the more so by
the contradiction between O'Neal's very visible physical presence
and that of the young, tiny white girl he's playing. He segues to
the false presumption among obsese people that there's some kind of
bond between them because of their weight. He closes with the
following: ``I get a lot of fat strangers coming up to me thanking
me for representing them. Like we have some sort of fat bond.
Represent who? Fat people? I don't want to lead fat people nowhere.
What are we going to do? We going to have a march? A Million Pound
March. What are we going to do? We're going to march and we're
going to rest, like I'm some sort of Malcolm XXL.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though many of his jokes are funny, it's not the joke that
makes the comedy: It's the jokester.
</P>
<P>
   Patrice O'Neal _ named after the hero of Congolese liberation,
Patrice Lumumba _ was brought up in Roxbury, was one of just a
handful of comics, and the only one from Boston, invited to perform
at this year's festival in March. This is a setting where the
stakes are as high as they get for a comic. Kelsey Grammer, Dennis
Miller, Bill Maher, John Cleese and the Python crew, and the kids
from ``South Park'' are all here, all competing for attention. And
this crowd's attention is worth getting. There's Bernie Brillstein,
partnered with Brad Grey in Brillstein-Grey, producers of ``The
Garry Shandling Show.'' A few seats over is legendary comedy-club
owner and starmaker Budd Friedman. A talent scout from HBO lingers
at the back of the room. O'Neal has about 12 minutes to prove a
lot.
</P>
<P>
   He's already proven he's funny. People are laughing. But there's
more to this game than the laughs. Funny doesn't always do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a business,'' says O'Neal, 28, the next day. ``They are
businessmen looking for business. And comics are the commodities
for their business. You either fit as a commodity or you don't. And
I'm a 350-pound man in a business run by short white guys. That's
the way it is.'' O'Neal is a comedian, but he's not smiling.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 years ago, O'Neal was working as a bouncer at
Estelle's, a Boston nightclub, when he started getting into it with
a professional comic. The performer challenged O'Neal to come up
onstage if he thought he could do better. O'Neal did. He was. And
that's when the man who, by his own count, has held more than 70
different jobs found the one he seems born to.
</P>
<P>
   But as O'Neal expected, it hasn't been easy.
</P>
<P>
   O`Neal started in Boston, bouncing from club to club looking for
more than five minutes and $5.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I got to be better, many of the Boston club owners
continued to put me in with people I didn't belong with,'' he says.
``And when I got a bit better and was bringing in some people, I
would get screwed with the money. You know, promised $1,000 and get
$900. It just (ticked) me off.''
</P>
<P>
   Did it also have to do with race?
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal stares, suggesting only an idiot wouldn't know the
obvious answer to that question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say hello to all the black comedians in Boston,''
he responds. ``Hello, Dwayne'' _ referring to Dwayne Perkins, the
only locally based black comic of note.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying O'Neal's sense of frustration is a sense of justice
misapplied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was funny because the audience was laughing,'' he
says. ``I didn't need anybody to tell me things were going good.
But I couldn't get anywhere here. So I left. Sometimes you don't
get any respect unless you leave town and then come back.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who now lives in the New York area, is back home, with
his mother. ``Things are going along pretty much as I expected,''
says O'Neal, while sitting on his mother's couch, a few feet away
from a computer and a gold-framed copy of the lyrics to ``Amazing
Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be making more money if I wanted to play a fat guy
eating a hamburger in some commercial, or doing a sequel to `Fat
Albert' _ but what's that? Sure, I'd like the money to get my
mother some things. Move her to Arizona. But the money will come
eventually. Most of the money is in the TV and movie thing, but it
takes away from what I'm trying to do. They pimp you into what they
want you to be in movies and TV, but I'm not interested in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Was it worth going to Aspen, making contacts that could help?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he says. ``Everyone's always giving you
advice. The head of Fox wants this, and another guy says I swear
too much. I had TV material before I was ready for TV, and now that
I'm ready for TV, my material isn't suitable. It's too edgy. And
I'm not going to tone it down. I'm not going to pretend I'm someone
I'm not just to get on TV. Someone else says I could go further
this way or that way. If you listen to all that ... it'll drive you
nuts. What makes it even more difficult is that this is how you
have to make your money. But you have to stay focused. I could be
famous by now if I was eating hamburgers in commercials and
smiling. But the world is not a smiling world.''
</P>
<P>
   Many comics are in a hurry. They want big money and they want it
now. ``It's hard not to envy someone else when they've got $750,000
in the bank,'' says O'Neal. ``I've waited this long. If I have to,
I'll wait some more.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal pauses as his mother enters the room. He smiles. She
wants him to do the Malcolm XXL routine, but Patrice is not in the
mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about anybody can get up onstage and tell jokes,'' he
says. ``That's one thing. But I am my work. I am funny. I'm not
trying to be funny. I'm passionate about it. When I'm up there it's
my soul on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal recalls a recent show in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., where only
20 people showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great show,'' he says. ``I did an hour and 10
minutes and I could see it in their faces. I was moving people. I
didn't need any flutes or buzzers or balloons. Just talking. I
could see it in their faces. You can't want it and you can't plan
it. You just got to do your work.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal wipes the heat of the day off his forehead with a
washcloth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be put in the category of funny as much as I
want to be put in the category of respect,'' he says. ``I want to
be like (George) Carlin or (Richard) Pryor. The place where you can
be an artist and maintain your love for it and still make the
money. That's where I'll be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
