<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-JAPAN _WASHINGTON _ Monday's resignation by Japanense Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, nine days before a planned state visit
to the White House, left world stock markets and the Clinton
administration scrambling to assess whether Japan's next government
would accelerate reforms needed to lift Japan's lifeless economy
and prevent it from dragging down global growth. On first blush,
the White House said it expects the next prime minister _ as yet
unamed _ to move quickly to cut taxes, shore up the country's
ailing banking system and invigorate consumer spending, measures
long resisted by Tokyo. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 6 p.m. EDT in both the (i)
International and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECONOMY _ MOSCOW _ Russia and the International Monetary
Fund on Monday reached an ''agreement in principle'' on a bailout
package worth about $15 billion designed to prevent a collapse of
the shaky Russian economy. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 2 p.m. EDT in both the (i)
International and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-COKE _ TEHRAN, Iran _ Coca Cola might be an American icon,
symbol of what some people here still call ``Great Satan,'' but the
name has not turned them off from buying the drink _ or at least
the bottles. Despite three-year-old U.S. sanctions against trade
with Iran, Tehran is flush with Coca Cola ads and bottles. The
drink inside, however, isn't Coke. The bottles are a controversial
hold over from before the sanctions and Iranians are mixing their
own local mix. The bottles, the popular cola and the controversy
illustrate the love-hate relationship between this country an the
United States, as well as the complications that arise when
sanctions interrupt the world-wide thirst for American products.
Iranians know it's not the American drink, but they don't mind
asking for it by the brand name. ``We have been using Coke since
before the (1979) revolution,'' said restaurant owner Hassan
Alvandi, dismissing the court and political battles that have
swirled around the product. ``That's just politics. We have never
disliked it.'' Ironically, the company that brought Coke back to
Iran in the early 1990's is now in a legal battle with the cola
producer. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 2 p.m. EDT in both the (i)
International and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
