<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE ME OUT TO THE BALLGAME? NOT JUST YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Things are looking good for major-league baseball, the experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is improving; TV ratings are up; superstars such as
Mark McGwire, Ken Griffey Jr. and Juan Gonzalez are on pace to
shatter long-standing batting records. Even last week's All-Star
Game was an entertaining spectacle _ and baseball's All-Star Game
can be as boring an event as a big-league sport can inflict on its
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of great stuff happening on the field,''
broadcaster Bob Costas told USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   And off the field? Would you believe that the team owners
finally named a commissioner after nearly six years of
procrastination?
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is, the permanent commissioner is the same guy
who's been serving as interim commissioner: Milwaukee Brewers owner
Bud Selig.
</P>
<P>
   This is the very same Bud Selig who called off the 1994 World
Series because of the ``labor dispute'' that spurred so many fans
of the national pastime to seek out other forms of amusement. The
owners are apparently feeling so confident _ arrogant? _ that they
had no qualms about choosing as a figurehead for baseball a man who
personifies the greatest insult ever perpetrated by the game upon
its fans.
</P>
<P>
   Do you ever wonder how people this stupid got as rich as they
are?
</P>
<P>
   It was the arrogance, stupidity and greed of owners and players
alike that prompted many fans to turn their backs on baseball _
some of us going so far as to boycott the sport that we once
followed fervently. My own boycott dates back to a 1990 ``labor
dispute'' that disrupted spring training; the '94 strike merely
intensified my disgust.
</P>
<P>
   With all the exciting developments in baseball this season, I
guess it's lucky for me that I recently modified the rules of
engagement in my personal war against baseball. I still refuse to
attend games or contribute in any way to the bankrolls of owners
and players, but I now permit myself to watch baseball on
television and read about baseball in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   I simply decided that avoiding baseball telecasts and news
accounts wasn't punishing anyone but me, which seemed rather
self-defeating.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, now that I'm free to watch baseball, I find that
I'm not particularly interested in doing so. I've watched only two
games plus a few stray innings here and there.
</P>
<P>
   I'll probably watch more games as the season progresses and the
record-chases heat up. A Mark McGwire home run is an amazing thing
to see, no matter how fed up you might be with a sport that seems
to thrive on mistreating its devotees.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, McGwire seems like a decent guy. He's modest and
unassuming on the field _ he actually apologized to the fans for a
sub-par performance in the home-run contest held in conjunction
with the All-Star Game. Off the field, McGwire contributes
considerable time and money to the battle against child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey is likewise said to be a good citizen, although the fans
had to badger him into taking part in the homer contest _ which he
won, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to be booed,'' Griffey said.
</P>
<P>
   Good for him. Most of these overpaid, overpraised characters
seem to go out of their way to do things that provoke booing _ and
worse _ by people whose far more natural inclination is to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   Followers of baseball are unique among sports fans in their
willingness to endure abuse and disappointment. Many remain loyal,
year and year, decade after decade, to losing teams _ even to
losing teams whose management makes no apparent effort to turn them
into winners.
</P>
<P>
   For baseball fans to abandon the sport and the teams they love,
as they have in recent years, they had to be antagonized beyond the
tolerance of the most tolerant of constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the experts say, the fans are coming back. The
excitement of the game and the appeal of positive role models such
as McGwire and Griffey are erasing the disillusionment engendered
by the '94 strike and other insults.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, well, I'm not coming back _ not yet, anyway. I can't
shake this nagging feeling that some new insult might be just
around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
