<HEADER>
A2284 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN     07-13 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMING A DUO WITH A CHILDHOOD IDOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 30 years ago, when he was turning 8 or 9, Scott Moss
got a Peter and Gordon LP for his birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, who grew up in the Fort Worth area, was just another kid
smitten with the Beatles and all-things-British invasion, just
another dreamer who learned how to play an instrument (in his case,
bass) by listening to Beatles records over and over between bouts
of dad knocking on the door and telling him to turn that danged
noise down.
</P>
<P>
   Only difference is, Moss kept at it. Year after year after year
he kept on, in cover bands like the Werewolves in the '70s. And in
the '80s he was with the Slicks, who did originals.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other people put their guitars and their dreams away
for good.
</P>
<P>
   And one fine day about three months ago in Los Angeles, a mutual
friend introduced him to Gordon Waller, one half of Peter and
Gordon _ and suddenly Moss found himself sitting in Waller's garage
singing with one of his idols and playing a guitar John Lennon had
once owned.
</P>
<P>
   Ironies don't get much more delicious _ not if you're still a
staunch Beatles/Brit invasion fanatic, and not if you're
determined, at age 43, to still make it in the music business.
Which Moss is.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the odds, he just might. Already he has cut a
five-song demo tape of strongly melodic pop that often compares
favorably with the Beatles, Peter and Gordon and Badfinger.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he and Waller have teamed up to form Moss, which will
hit a number of Metroplex clubs in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And while they're in the area they'll go to a Dallas studio to
finish up nine more songs with an eye toward shopping the entire
14-song CD to labels.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, my head spins,'' says Moss, who
graduated from L.D. Bell in 1973 and whose other area bands in the
'70s and '80s included Wish, Flight and The Artist. ``It's like
getting on a train that's moving very fast. Gordon wanted to play,
and I said, `Let's go back to Texas.' We're going to do a set of my
material and a set of Peter and Gordon's hits, `A World Without
Love,' `Lady Godiva,' `I Go to Pieces,' stuff all the classic rock
stations play. He hasn't toured in 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   And Moss the man hasn't played live very much in a good long
while, either. By the mid-'90s, he had ``saturated the market'' in
the Metroplex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd done everything I could do here,'' he says. ``It was time
to move on, but I didn't know how or where.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he met Ashlie Rhey, a model/actress and longtime Los
Angeles resident. He moved to LA to be with her three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came with an acoustic guitar and 15 cassette tapes of
material,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He began to restart his career, looking for management and a
producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird in LA,'' he says. ``I've played live all my life,
but here your tapes and your resume do all the work.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago he hooked up with producer Scott Mathews and began
flying back to Texas to cut songs, with help from well-known local
guitarists Andy Timmons and Johnny Red.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's old yet new _ I don't want to put a label on it,'' he
says of his music. ``I've stuck to one sound, one avenue _ hooks
and melody and a lot of harmonies, keeping it pretty simple. The
more simple it is means the easier it is for people to adjust to it
and like it.''
</P>
<P>
   And, really, this stuff is pretty easy to like: Layers of
acoustic and electric guitars, bright production, sweet harmonies,
catchy choruses, and so on. One song, ``If You Don't Mind,'' is
particuarly Beatlesesque, but all five songs are impressive _
ageless-sounding, friendly and well-played. A Beatles fan looking
for something new to listen to could do a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   From here, Moss says, ``We want to finish the album and secure a
deal and go to the next phase _ take it on the road on a more
national level. I'm grateful for this _ not many people get what
they dream for. As far as stardom, that don't mean nothin' anymore.
It's about getting to do what you enjoy doing _ but this time,
getting paid for it. That's a nice change.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman writes on pop music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2288 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-IRAN-0714-COX &UR;      07-13 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-IRAN-0714-COX </SLUG>
    
 &HT;     COCA-COLA IMAGE, BOTTLES ARE POPULAR HOLDOVERS IN IRAN
 &HT;     With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server and available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;     By LARRY KAPLOW and MICKEY H. GRAMIG 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ It needed special permission from an Ayatollah,
overcame threats from anti-American hard-liners and faced a
three-year-old U.S. trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that icon of Americana, the Coca-Cola bottle, is a common
sight next to the kabobs and rice on Iranian dinner tables.
</P>
<P>
   The soft drink inside, however, isn't Coca-Cola _ a fact that
does not bother thirsty Iranians but has officials with
Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co. seeking relief in Tehran's courts.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy highlights the contradictions between the two
countries' opposing governments and the personal attraction
Iranians have to American products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been using Coke since before the (1979) revolution,''
said restaurant owner Hassan Alvandi, dismissing court and
political battles that have swirled around the product. ``That's
just politics. We have never disliked it.''
</P>
<P>
   This hot Iranian summer, the conveyor belts at the immaculate
Noushab bottling plant here are running overtime to turn out nearly
50,000 cases a day filled with Coca-Cola bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Limited by small production, it's a minor share of the market.
But many prefer Noushab's product over that served up from the
quasi-government owned Parsi Cola and Zam Zam.
</P>
<P>
   Finer restaurants and groceries have trouble keeping Coca-Cola
bottles in stock, even though the bottle caps and the delivery
trucks carry different names indicating that both Noushab and
customers could care less that the cola inside is not Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   The bottles _ 22 million Coke and Fanta bottles _ are left over
from Noushab's pre-embargo contract with Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Arsalan Namdar, chairman of Tehran-based Noushab, brought
Coca-Cola back to Iran in the early 1990s, after a lengthy absence
following the 1979 Islamic revolution and Iranian hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Returning such a classic western product was not easy in a
country where some officials call the United States the ``Great
Satan.'' Hard-line conservatives threatened to burn down the
bottling plant. Namdar eventually had to get special permission
from the late Ayatollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this, the Noushab relationship with the Coca-Cola
Co. soured quickly in fights over management and advertising _
Namdar said he wanted a low-key debut and Coca-Cola wanted glitz.
</P>
<P>
   When U.S. officials decided to isolate Iran for its support of
international terrorism in 1995, they imposed a strict trade
embargo that prohibited American companies from operating there.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola severed its relationship with Noushab, but, according
to Namdar, the companies fought over money and old promises that
had been agreed to in the contracts. Iranian courts are now looking
over Noushab's claims against Coca-Cola and the company's trademark
protest against Noushab.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, in compliance with the embargo, does not supply any
more ingredients. But Noushab still has the bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Namdar said the company will eventually replace the bottles with
its own. Meanwhile, an Iranian court allowed Noushab to continue
using the Coca-Cola bottles, but required it to run a media
campaign telling consumers that the soft drink in the bottles is
not really Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign seems to have worked. Several Iranian soft drink
consumers interviewed here recently knew they were drinking an
Iranian soft drink. They said they still liked it better, in part
because the new bottling plant has kept the bottles clean and free
of the bugs and dirt found in other drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co. officials in Atlanta, however, say that Noushab is
violating the soft drink maker's famous trademark. The company is
appealing the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we stand for is put at risk when you put something
other than Coca-Cola in one of our bottles,'' said Randy Donaldson,
a Coca-Cola vice president.
</P>
<P>
   He said a bad product could damage the company's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The fight has become nasty. Noushab has accused Coca-Cola of, at
one point, violating the U.S. trade embargo by shipping ingredients
to a rival bottler that had a part of the bottling contract.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola denies that, alleging that Noushab is passing around a
fake Coca-Cola company document.
</P>
<P>
   Namdar complains that Coca-Cola has not been so tough on the
other bottler, called Khoshgavar, which is also using old Coca-Cola
bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said company had no knowledge of Khoshgavar still
using the Coca-Cola name, and would inquire.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while the companies fight over the name, most
Iranians are not concerned. Far from their image as anti-American
zealots, they are a pragmatic people who get the U.S. products they
like, despite the embargo, through third countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care,'' 67-year-old Sadighe Karami said flatly.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the all-black cape and scarf required by Muslim
modesty laws, she was about to split four so-called Coca-Colas with
her family in a Tehran park. ``It's not a bad thing. We don't get
poisoned by it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2290 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-IRAN-0714-COX &UR;      07-13 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-IRAN-0714-COX </SLUG>
    
 &HT;     COCA-COLA IMAGE, BOTTLES ARE POPULAR HOLDOVERS IN IRAN
