<SLUG> BC-SOAK-THE-RICH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T GET RICH IN FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France's Socialist-led government is extending a wealth
tax, introduced a decade ago, to include the estimated value of
individuals' art collections and antiques.
</P>
<P>
   The rich also will no longer be able to write off bad loans they
or their enterprises make against their wealth-tax liability.
</P>
<P>
   The law declares that people with assets of $750,000 are
officially wealthy and those with that amount must pay yearly taxes
not only on their income but also on the capital they hold _
defined as savings, personal and real property and corporate shares
and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 200,000 men and women fall into the category of the
officially rich here. So the tax of 1.5 percent doesn't bring in a
great deal of money. A spokesman for the Finance Ministry said it
yielded $40 million in revenue in 1997, and there is no official
estimate of what the government will net from the extended tax.
</P>
<P>
   However, bringing in cash to the treasury is not the tax's real
objective.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Americans, most French people don't expect to emulate the
wealthy and become successful themselves. Instead, they want those
better off than they are to be brought down a peg or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an emotional issue,'' conservative member of parliament
Jean-Luc Vincent told the Paris newspaper Le Figaro. ``The French
are happiest when they see the rich being forced to pay stiff
taxes. Their instinctive belief is that the rich got where they are
by more or less illicit means, so they should be made to surrender
much if not all of their ill-gotten gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent noted that the 19th century French socialist
philosopher, Pierre Joseph Proudhon, argued that ``property is
theft.''
</P>
<P>
   Socialist Prime Minister Lionel Jospin has shown little
enthusiasm for extending the wealth tax, emphasizing that the
business community should not be frightened off at a time when
France is eagerly seeking investment to encourage economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But Jospin is in a corner. His government depends for its
majority on 40 Communist members of Parliament who demand the tax
in the name of social justice.
</P>
<P>
   ```Soak the rich' has always been a left-wing battle cry here,''
historian Olivier Weiner explained. ``It has been justified to the
extent that, historically, the French capitalist class has been
extraordinarily selfish and short-sighted. The problem is that the
left regards capital as a source for the redistribution of wealth,
not as a source for creating more wealth on behalf of the nation as
a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   The current campaign to impose the wealth tax more widely began
when it was revealed that financier Francois Pinault, rated among
this country's richest people, lowered his tax bill by using a
loophole in the law. It allowed him to write off a large loan made
by his company.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, Pinault owns a valuable art collection, which
will now be taxed annually as part of his fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Other art collectors face similar taxation, as do owners of
antique furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inevitably,'' Weiner said, ``a fiscal system is being built
that will make it virtually impossible for even a portion of
France's cultural heritage to survive outside of museums.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
