A2307 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSION-RESTORATION-H     07-13 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSION-RESTORATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK SERVICE TO GET SOME HELP IN RECONNECTING HISTORIC MISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It may take an act of Congress to ease problems
plaguing a centuries-old route connecting five missions that
Franciscan priests built along the San Antonio River.
</P>
<P>
   The river was a natural thoroughfare that linked the five
shelters and their communities. But 267 years after the last
mission was built, access to the historical sites is impeded by
streets and man-made impediments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of people who get lost,'' said Steve
Whitesell, superintendent of the San Antonio Missions National
Historical Park. To help clear up the confusion, lawmakers have
slipped $2.2 million into spending bills to improve access to the
park and provide a partial face lift for some of the artifacts at
the four missions the National Park Service administers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not pork. Not even a little bit,'' Whitesell said.
``Some of the oldest historic features in the state of Texas are
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians agree. The San Antonio missions, they say, are the
essence of the region and its culturally diverse heritage.
Franciscans spent 13 years building the stone shelters to protect
early pioneers from Indian attacks. The Alamo was built in 1718,
followed by Mission San Jose in 1720 and the completion of Espada,
Concepcion and San Juan in 1731.
</P>
<P>
   The Alamo, owned by the state and operated by the Daughters of
the Republic of Texas, is not part of the national park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The missions are really the beginnings of San Antonio. And
they represent what endures of the Spanish empire,'' said Gerald
Poyo, an associate professor of Latin American and U.S. Latino
history at St. Mary's University in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The missions were the catalyst for religious conversion to
Catholicism for regional Indians friendly to the early pioneers,
and provided shelter from hostile forces that helped nurture the
fledgling mestizo communities.
</P>
<P>
   Poyo said from the missions ``you get your first civilizations''
in southern Texas. And today, the missions serve as a history book
to explain the early origins of that civilization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those missions are wonderful places to take students. They get
a visual sense of how the early settlements were set up,'' Poyo
said.
</P>
<P>
   The four missions within the 850-acre national park survive as
parishes today. Nonetheless, Congress and the Interior Department
have grappled with fiscal constraints that have left the National
Park Service operating them on a bare-bones budget. Whitesell has a
staff of 41 and an annual operating budget of $2.2 million for more
than 250,000 square feet of ``masonry and historical materials.''
</P>
<P>
   To make improvements, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, tucked
$390,000 into a spending bill for the Interior Department to
``rehabilitate'' antiquities and structures at the Missions Park.
The funding wasn't included in the House version of the bill. A
House-Senate conference committee must iron out differences in the
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rep. Ciro Rodriguez, D-Texas, was instrumental in
placing $1.9 million into the federal highway bill to improve
access to the four missions. President Clinton signed that bill
into law.
</P>
<P>
   The highway funds would be spent under the direction of the
Texas Department of Transportation and would provide a continuation
of the Missions Trail and improve signage for ``one of the largest
tourist attractions in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Missions Park is the second most popular national park in Texas,
with 1.3 million visitors annually. It ranks behind Lake Meredith
with 1.7 million visitors, according to the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   The missions are the largest collection of Spanish Colonial
architecture in the United States, drawing tourists and history
buffs from coast to coast and abroad. With the improvements,
Whitesell said, the number of annual visitors could increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Mission Trail would begin at the Alamo. Once known as the
San Antonio de Valero Mission, the structure later was renamed the
Alamo and became the Shrine of Texas Liberty after the 1836 battle
that saw its Texas defenders wiped out by Santa Anna's Mexican
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Although many visitors know the Alamo's significance, Poyo said,
the cultural significance of the four other missions along a
13-mile stretch of the San Antonio River often is overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   From a practical standpoint, Whitesell said, improving access to
the park and spending funds to rehabilitate structures will
``improve the quality of experience'' for visitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
