r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-150     07-13 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-1500(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYNDICATED TV SHOWS GET NO RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Having made it 15 minutes or so into the news
conference without shifting the conversational focus to Pamela
Anderson Lee's breasts, the creator and producer of her new
syndicated drama, ``V.I.P.,'' blew it by gleefully pointing out
that Lee possessed ``two noticeable assets'' as her bankable
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a Freudian slip or an attempt at jazzing up the
otherwise who-cares proceedings, but as the gathering of TV
critics, publicists and other hangers-on burst into laughter,
producer J.F. Lawton tried desperately to correct the mistake, only
to bury himself more deeply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, what can you do?'' Lee said later as she stood in a hotel
lobby trying to gather enough strength to face hungry-looking
paparazzi circling her waiting limo. ``But at some point you'd like
to think that people will start taking your acting far more serious
than your looks or, for God's sakes, what you're wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   (A yellow, short, hip-hugging skirt, painted-on yellow top,
white sandals, since she brought it up.)
</P>
<P>
   International audiences couldn't care less about acting talent _
they made ``Baywatch'' the most-watched television series on the
planet, didn't they? So it goes without saying that Lee's
``V.I.P.,'' a humorous action series about a security agency and
its figurehead chief, has a better-than-average chance of becoming
a global phenomenon this fall even if it fails at home.
</P>
<P>
   Lee already has the fame thing down pat; now she's reaching for
fortune. If ``Baywatch'' star and inspiration David Hasselhoff
handed her any advice, it was ``to own a piece of the show.'' Lee
is listed as one of the producers.
</P>
<P>
   This is the netherworld of syndication, a kind of stepchild of
network television; if this were theater, it'd be an
off-off-off-Broadway production. These shows are usually tucked
away at odd times on odd channels, and you often stumble upon them
while flipping around looking for something else. Sexy, violent and
frequently stylistically risky, syndicated dramas are often
considered ``less than,'' even compared with network programs, in
which idiocy is often a prerequisite.
</P>
<P>
   Syndicated dramas (think ``Xena: Warrior Princess'') would never
be considered Emmy-level productions because so many are on the
``V.I.P.'' level: campy productions aimed at beer guzzlers with an
affinity for scantily clad women gripping firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a perception that it's violent and racy and has no
substance,'' said Peter Davis, one of the producers of
``Highlander: The Raven,'' which begins Sept. 14 and picks up where
``Highlander'' left off. ``But in many ways it has far more
substance than network dramas in the sense that we have the time to
build plots and deepen characters.''
</P>
<P>
   No one understands this world better than Lorenzo Lamas. He
showed up in Army fatigues to push ``Air America,'' in which he'll
play an ex-Navy SEAL and undercover agent running a commercial
airline and saving folk along the way. It didn't take long for
Lamas to move back into syndication when ``Renegade'' petered out
after five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't seem all that thrilled to be in the fatigues, though,
snapping at a reporter who asked why he showed up dressed in
character. Snarled Lamas: ``This was `their' idea,'' speaking of
his producers.
</P>
<P>
   A very lean, almost sickly looking Lamas seems to know that a
syndicated star's work is never done. ``You've got to sell it,'' he
said, shrugging. ``There's so much competition out there that you
can't just sit around and watch everyone else get the audience. But
for me, it's not the medium that's important; it's the material.''
</P>
<P>
   Polygram Television won't have to do much selling to get an
early sampling of ``The Crow: Stairway to Heaven'' with Mark
Dacascos as the beleaguered soul trapped on earth. Dark and moody,
the series, which premieres in September, will expand the Crow
legend, though executive producer Bryce Zabel says they'll stay the
course enough to keep the faithful audiences who flocked to both
``Crow'' feature films.
</P>
<P>
   Syndication is more synonymous with game shows and talk shows,
of which a few were presented here, though expectation for long
life isn't high. King World reps tried their best to talk up
``Roseanne,'' the new daytime talker from you know who, since
Roseanne failed to speak for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters expected a fiery session; the actress is known for
being feisty and intolerant of journalists. But the most noticeable
event was the bizarre seaweed sandwiches served for lunch. Roseanne
spent the entire hour with a blank look on her face, fielding every
question with vague answers. (''Can you give us an example of
topics?'' Answer: ``Things I believe in, things other people aren't
talking about.'' Question: ``Will you have sketches?'' Answer:
``Well, we might.'') She clearly wanted to be elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by her producers, Roseanne gave no indication of how her
daytime show will differ from, say, Rosie O'Donnell or Oprah
Winfrey, except that she'll cover edgy topics much like her sitcom
did.
</P>
<P>
   One breakthrough came when she admitted that the hardest part of
the job has been the actual interviews. Hey, it was something.
</P>
<P>
   The next biggest name to try syndication this fall is Whoopi
Goldberg, who, like Roseanne, seemed to see the news conference as
a waste of time. She spent her hour session snapping at questioners
who couldn't believe she had signed on as a regular on the new
``Hollywood Squares'' game show. Question: ``How long did it take
you to come to such a decision to leave your film career?'' Answer:
``About five seconds.'' Question: ``How did you happen to make this
career choice?'' Answer: ``I got a phone call.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Whoopi mentioned that she'd been offered $5 million a year
to spew jokes as the middle square, the exchange would have been
moot.
</P>
<P>
   As she left the stage, Whoopi was overheard muttering, ``Get me
outta here.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Maury Povich and Whoopi found one another in the hotel
bar. He, too, spent most of his session in defensive posture. And
for good reason. Critics drilled him on why he's revamping ``The
Maury Povich Show'' into ``The New Maury Povich Show,'' which he
claims will be more hard-hitting and newsy, with multiple guests
sounding off on single topics.
</P>
<P>
   But it sounds like any other talk show in which the topics
simply rotate between paternity tests and family scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Povich launched into a long-winded tirade about his wife, Connie
Chung, being network caliber and how he's hardly that kind of
goody-goody foot soldier, why their joint show wasn't bought,
(''station politics''), and how ``I don't do big-breasted women
well; Sally Jesse Raphael does.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensing a sinking ship, Povich's producer, Tamara Haddad, jumped
in. ``We're in business,'' she said. ``And if something works, why
wouldn't you go back and do it again?''
</P>
<P>
   The sentiments exactly for Donny and Marie Osmond, the epitome
of the kind of friendly, feel-good TV that appears to be overtaking
the ``Jerry Springer'' shock trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donny &AMP; Marie'' will be a variety and chat show, bringing
together this brother-and-sister duo after some 20 years. Marie
insists that audiences shouldn't expect the sugar-coated
teeny-boppers of a decade ago, that they are different people with
different ideas, and this alone will spice up their reunion.
</P>
<P>
   In front of reporters, Donny spent an hour calling his sister
``Ree,'' and she gently needled him while both broke into giggles.
It was enough to make you weak-kneed or simply want to kick them.
</P>
<P>
   Donny, clearly aging but looking no more than 30, told us that
``Donny &AMP; Marie'' will be part talk, part variety, all clean. ``But
it'll be hip,'' he promised. ``No smoke and mirrors. What you see
will be real. It will be us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, like Pamela Anderson Lee. After building a career fueled
by her sexuality (first on ``Home Improvement'' as the bouncy
``Tool Time Girl'' and later on ``Baywatch'' as the bouncy
lifeguard) she wants to reinvent herself as an actress who just
happens to be beautiful, cosmetic surgery notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   She said this while showing us clips from ``V.I.P,'' in which
she pranced around in various forms of undress, particularly from
the waist up.
</P>
<P>
   But as new talk show host Howie Mandel said, success ``is a
marathon, it's not a sprint. You have to keep picking at it,
knocking out any misconceptions people have. You won't achieve a
goal next week or two weeks from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as he explained how ``staying focused and steady'' is the
key, Lee glided by, catching Mandel's attention. Which prompted him
to end his discourse with ``and keeping your eyes to yourself won't
hurt, either.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
