<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NELSON-MANDELA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY BIRTHDAY, NELSON MANDELA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The world's greatest man turns 80 years old
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, it would have been deemed improbable that Nelson
Mandela would celebrate his 80th birthday while serving as the
first democratically elected president of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   His destiny, it seemed, was to die as the most famous political
prisoner in the world, a man lionized by millions worldwide who
looked to him as South Africa's messiah.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, already serving time for incitement, Mandela was
convicted of treason, a charge that England could have made against
George Washington and that any totalitarian government can level
against those attempting to overthrow it in favor of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's foe was apartheid, an instrument of hate that made
South Africa the most systematically racist country in world
history.
</P>
<P>
   Like Socrates on trial in Athens, Mandela used the courtroom as
a platform. He condemned the government of South Africa and the
immorality of apartheid while advocating justice and democracy.
Sentenced to life in prison, Mandela didn't disappear from the
conscience of his country or the world.
</P>
<P>
   As South Africa spiraled into what seemed an inevitable and
cataclysmic blood bath, three words became a mantra of hope: ``Free
Nelson Mandela.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mandela had died in prison, entombed in legend, he would have
been a tantalizing ``what if?'' to history while South Africa
consumed itself in its rage.
</P>
<P>
   But on Feb. 11, 1990, as he left prison, Mandela walked out of
the mists of mythology and onto the stage of history. From that
point on, the greatness that had only been heard and read about
became evident.
</P>
<P>
   For 27 years he was imprisoned as the most visible symbol of a
cruel and brutal regime, one that wouldn't allow him to attend the
funerals of his mother and oldest son. Yet Mandela didn't allow his
suffering to embitter him nor blur his vision for South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   He emerged from prison unbowed, a warrior still in possession of
his dignity and graciousness. He proved himself not to be a
fire-breathing demagogue, but a pragmatic statesman devoted to
nation-building.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the Czech Republic's Vaclav Havel, who
also journeyed from prison to the presidency, no head of state
comes close to matching Mandela's moral authority.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the dock during his 1964 trial, Mandela concluded
his address to the court with these words:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have cherished the ideal of a democratic and free society in
which all persons live together in harmony and with equal
opportunities. It is an ideal which I hope to live for and to
achieve. But if needs be, it is an ideal for which I am prepared to
die.''
</P>
<P>
   The ideals didn't die and neither has the man. Happy Birthday,
Nelson Mandela, and many more.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
