<SLUG> BC-FERRY-BUILDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO HOPES TO ADD SPIT AND POLISH TO FADING LANDMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Its glory days, when 50 million people a year
passed through it and 170 ferries plied the Bay, are a distant
memory, but the dream of a San Francisco Ferry Building restored to
its original magnificence lives on.
</P>
<P>
   The Port of San Francisco is again trying to arrest the slide
into shabby obsolescence of one of the city's enduringly famous
landmarks, this time with a planned $70 million restoration and
redevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ferry Building is one of the great icons of San Francisco,
and it would be not only exciting but a privilege to help restore
it to its original grandeur,'' said former city Supervisor Robert
Mendelson, who heads Mentmore Development Co., one of four
developers responding to the Port Commission's requests to renovate
the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project would draw strength from the qualities of the
city. It's quintessentially San Francisco,'' said David Malmuth,
senior vice president of TrizecHahn, another interested developer.
``It's an extraordinarily valuable piece of property. ... Our sense
is that it is potentially something great.''
</P>
<P>
   The city marks the centenary of the building on Tuesday. With
its 250-foot central tower and prominent location at the foot of
Market Street, the building has historically been regarded as a
home-grown San Francisco phenomenon, but the money to build it _ a
little less than $1 million _ was raised with a statewide bond
measure in 1891.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by architect Arthur Page Brown, who died before its
completion, the building received its first passengers 22 months
after construction began.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly half a century thereafter, the Ferry Building was one
of the two or three busiest passenger terminals on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   It survived the great earthquake and fire of 1906.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those San Franciscans who looked down a devastated Market
Street throughout the first months, the Ferry Building, a splendid
survivor, stood against the skyline as a solitary promise that San
Francisco would once again come to be,'' wrote California State
Librarian Kevin Starr.
</P>
<P>
   In 1915, the biggest neon sign on the Pacific Coast, mounted
atop the Ferry Building, welcomed visitors to the great Panama
Pacific Exposition: ``California Invites the World,'' it said in
letters 8 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 17, 1989, when the Loma Prieta earthquake struck, the
building's tower, with its clock stopped at 5:04 p.m., became an
enduring symbol of the city's resilience after a cataclysmic event.
</P>
<P>
   But the building had long since lost the utilitarian value it
had when ferries were the only means of cross-Bay travel.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the Bay Bridge in 1936 and the Golden Gate Bridge
in 1937 had radically diminished its importance. Ferry service from
the building ended in 1958 when Southern Pacific's ``Eureka'' made
its final crossing to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The intervening years have been hard on the old building, which
was at its most useful and vibrant when San Francisco wasn't a
tourist town, but a busy, blue-collar seaport and financial capital
of the Far West.
</P>
<P>
   The prospectus sent out to interested developers by the Port
Commission reflects changing times.
</P>
<P>
   Just as San Francisco has evolved into a tourist town, replete
with public amenities, so the commission wants to make the Ferry
Building fit gracefully into the new mold.
</P>
<P>
   With its commanding setting and graceful lines, it should become
``the centerpiece of our waterfront development,'' said Port
Director Doug Wong.
</P>
<P>
   The Ferry Building is exceptional in that it presents a dual
challenge, ``to restore its grandeur'' and ``to give it a new
economic life,'' said Chris Meany, retail director for William
Wilson &AMP; Associates of San Mateo, which has worked on redevelopment
projects at other historic landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Commission wants a project that ``enhances the historic
qualities of the Ferry Building, while providing both a focal point
on the waterfront and an integrating link with downtown,''
according to its formal request for proposals. The Ferry Building
is a national historic landmark.
</P>
<P>
   Port officials envision the building housing offices, retail
shops, restaurants, space for renewed ferry service and have given
the developers wide latitude to include other uses such as
entertainment, public markets, academic facilities and museums.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels, residential uses, nonmaritime private clubs and
wholesale and/or trade promotion centers will not be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The developer also will have to seismically retrofit the
building and show that its project can continue to provide the port
with $1.4 million in annual rent.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is expected to pick a developer sometime this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to restore the Ferry Building is the second in 20
years. The first, launched in 1980, fizzled when the commission
canceled its agreement with what it believed to be a nonperforming
developer. It was sued and settled in 1991 for $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the troubled track record of restoration projects for
the building, Port Commission Chairwoman Denise McCarthy is not
committing the commission to a timetable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has taken a long time, but with the economy like it is,
it seems like a good time to do it,'' McCarthy said. ``Certainly,
everybody would like to see it happen in our lifetime after all
these years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
