<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILIPINOS-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ACTOR OFFERS GENUINE PROMISE IN THE PHILIPPINES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DON PACIS  
 c.1998 San Franciso Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When the newly elected president of the
Philippines heralded his office as ``Ang araw ng masang Pilipino''
(Day of the Filipino masses), Joseph Estrada brought a lump to the
throats of Filipinos everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   No president of the island nation has ever done this before. His
inaugural address in Tagalog struck a chord that resonated far and
wide.
</P>
<P>
   The actor-turned-politician is wasting no time in setting the
tone for a country badly in need of change.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada might be the butt of jokes for mangling the English
language, but the Filipino masses love him.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he's begun to unite a country slowly shedding
its made-in-America image.
</P>
<P>
   After all, how better to talk to your countrymen than in your
own language? No gimmick, no platitudes. Just plain,
honest-to-goodness talk that's endeared Estrada to his countrymen,
especially the poor and downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder then that Filipinos, rich and poor _ ``Armani
or no money,'' as Estrada joked _ have embraced him as their new
president? True, there are skeptics, but Estrada has a chance. Six
years won't be enough, of course. Poverty and corruption are so
pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   So is the psychological trauma of centuries-old colonialism.
After all, who can undo overnight what the Spanish and Americans
did for so many years of domination?
</P>
<P>
   Not Marcos. He tried. It destroyed him. Neither could his
successors in the presidential palace, Corazon Aquino and Fidel
Ramos. It left them scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   A century earlier, the national hero Jose Rizal tried and was
executed by the Spanish. With America's Manifest Destiny lording
over its wards of ``little brown brothers,'' no one in the
handy-dandy list of Filipino heroes could.
</P>
<P>
   If it isn't the Western Father, it's the Filipino with no
memory, as a Filipino novelist once said. Meaning: Foreigners have
dominated the Filipino psyche for centuries, but Filipinos don't
seem to remember. If they did, the Philippines wouldn't be in a
such a mess.
</P>
<P>
   Is it cultural amnesia, then? Maybe. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Can Estrada turn things around? Too early to tell.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Estrada has rallied his people behind him.
That's what counts. Never mind the cynics who shrug off his speech
as another ``palabas'' (a grand gesture).
</P>
<P>
   It is noble. It is necessary. By speaking directly to the little
people, by speaking their language, he's cast off distrust and
suspicion. He's one of them. He's talking to them in a language
they can understand.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Don Pacis is a writer and poet who emigrated from the
Philippines 20 years ago.)
</P>
</TEXT>
