<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Ratings for the CNN news network soar during crises, scandals,
and big, breaking events. But when news becomes routine, viewership
slips sharply. Under CNN president Richard Kaplan, the network is
trying to attract more long-term viewers. In a two-part series,
Boston Globe writers Don Aucoin and Mark Jurkowitz explore the
status of America's ``hearth'' for breaking news. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; TV-CNN-I-SPCL (Atlanta) -- Over 18 years, CNN has carved out a
reputation for earnest journalism, despite occasional lapses. Now
CNN executives are trying to reinvent the network as a place of
``appointment viewing'' where news, entertainment values, and
personality mix in distinctive programming. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TV-CNN-GROUP-SPCL (Washington) _ The CNN programming that
Americans see derives from CNN/US, but that is only one part of the
sprawling entity that is the CNN News Group. 400 words.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CNN-II-SPCL (Washngton) -- CNN executives exult when their
programming generates headlines in the nation's newspapers and
magazines. Such pickups show the network's clout. But there is
another, more direct measure of its effectiveness: how many viewers
are watching? And on that score, CNN often falls short. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS
designator and move under the general national (a) and
entertainment (e) category codes.
</P>
