<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2370 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CACONGRESS-RACES-SFCH     07-13 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CACONGRESS-RACES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP, DEMOCRATS TO CONTEST 11 SEATS FOR CONTROL OF HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ Republicans believe history is on their side.
Democrats believe the issues are on theirs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever happens in the November congressional elections,
neither side believes that many seats will change hands. Experts
say less than 1 in 6 House races are competitive, which in most
years would make the election a bit of a snoozer.
</P>
<P>
   But with a 228-to-206 margin _ the narrowest majority in nearly
a half-century _ the Republicans' grip on the House is anything but
firm: A turnaround of just 11 seats would put the Democrats back in
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very legitimate chance of taking the House back,''
said Rep. Martin Frost of Texas, the chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee. ``I think (Republicans) will be
very, very fortunate if they regain control of the House. I think
our chances are 50-50.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost is more optimistic than most nonpartisan observers, who
note that only once since the Civil War has the president's party
picked up seats in a midterm election.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Walter of the Cook Political Report, which handicaps
congressional races, said the Democrats' chances are slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible, but everything has to fall perfectly into
place,'' Walter said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Republicans currently hold a 55-to-45 advantage,
and the balance is unlikely to change by more than several seats.
However in the House, a shift of the same proportion could
determine whether Republican Newt Gingrich or Democrat Richard
Gephardt holds the speaker's gavel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what (former GOP chairman) Lee Atwater used to call a
`small change election.' '' said Professor Jack Pitney of the
Claremont McKenna School of Government outside Los Angeles. ``No
big deals. No big transactions. But nickels and dimes could make a
big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is an intense focus on a handful of competitive races
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats see their best prospects in the West and Midwest. In
California, which once looked like it might be a great opportunity
for GOP pickups, Democrats will be fortunate to not lose a seat or
two. However, they think they can pick up seats in Washington, New
Mexico and Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the margin is 11 (seats), every district matters a lot,''
Walter said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hope that Republican opposition to recent legislation
on tobacco, health care, campaign finance reform and the emerging
influence of religious right organizations, will alienate enough
voters in key districts to end their majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the hard right turn that the Republican Party has
taken nationally in the House of Representatives is going to cause
problems for some of their more moderate candidates,'' Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, history suggests that the Democrats face an uphill
struggle. Since World War II, the average loss for a president's
party during the sixth year of his term is 46 seats. Republicans
steadfastly maintain that they will increase the size of their
majority by at least 10 seats.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the economy is booming and the nation is at
peace, incumbents are enjoying a surge in popularity. Many
Republicans appear unconcerned with the prospect of losing power
and are banking on their more ambitious accomplishments from
previous years, including legislation that overhauled the nation's
welfare system and produced the first balanced budget in a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first secure Republican majority since the
1920s,'' Gingrich wrote in the Washington Post last month. ``Both
the tide of history and the currents of today's politics are on the
Republican side in this election.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said a ``district-by-district review highlights the
negligible opportunities for Democrats to win any net House seats _
let alone a ridiculous eleven.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton One wild card is President Clinton. Earlier this year,
Republicans said that the controversy surrounding the Monica
Lewinsky scandal could cost De &LR; mocrats dearly. Instead, Clinton's
popularity surged, and he remains the party's most prolific
fund-raiser. Clinton has already attended more than three dozen
fund-raisers this year and has pledged to raise at least $18
million for the Democrats this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP's confidence is buttressed by a recent survey of 1,012
voters by the Pew Research Center. When likely voters were asked
which party they would support in their own House district, 48
percent said Republicans, while 44 percent said Democrats. The poll
showed that white women, who have voted heavily for Democrats in
recent elections, are now backing Republicans by a four-point
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Partisans on both sides say the election is not likely to be
framed so much by broad national issues as local concerns that will
vary from district to district. Strategists have identified several
dozen swing districts which hold the key to the election.
</P>
<P>
   The two closest California contests are in districts where
Democrats are retiring. In Sacramento, Vic Fazio is leaving after
20 years in Congress, and in Los Angeles, Jane Harman chose to run
for governor instead of defending her House seat.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are confident about picking up the Northern California
seat now held by Frank Riggs, R-Windsor, who is not seeking
re-election after a brief run for the Senate. Democratic State Sen.
Mike Thompson is the favorite in his contest with Napa County
Supervisor Mark Luce, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbents look strong in most Northern California races,
although Republicans insist they will contest the Contra Costa
County seat held by Ellen Tauscher, D-Walnut Creek. Tauscher, a
freshman, stunned Republican Bill Baker in 1996. She is being
challenged by Charles Ball, an analyst at the Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory, who has been circulating a poll that suggests
Tauscher may be vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The California race likely to attract the most national
attention is in Orange County, where Rep. Loretta Sanchez,
D-Anaheim, is being challenged by Republican Bob Dornan, whom she
defeated by just 984 votes in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Dornan, the bombastic and at times acerbic orator, accused
Sanchez of stealing the election with the help of illegal immigrant
votes. Democrats couldn't help from showing their glee when Dornan
won the June 2 primary, asserting that his presence will turn
Hispanic voters away from the Republican Party nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, the winning party is likely to hold a
narrow majority, making it difficult to pass legislation. Some
academics have even suggested that if nothing is going to be
accomplished, it might be advantageous to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frost bristles at the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell no,'' he said, noting that the majority party gets to
choose a speaker, name committee chairman, and bring legislation to
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the expression, `I've been rich and I've been poor,
and rich is better,''' said Frost. ``Well I've been in the
majority, and I've been in the minorit &LR; y, and being in the majority
is better, under all circumstances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1504EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
