<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2372 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATHPENALTY-THOMPSON     07-13 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATHPENALTY-THOMPSON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLER'S LAST CHANCE TO AVOID DEATH PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARRIET CHIANG and GLEN MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ Thomas Thompson's lawyers will file a final
appeal with the U.S. Supreme Court Monday in a desperate bid to
prevent the convicted killer from being executed in San Quentin's
death chamber.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The high court is Thompson's only hope that his life will be
spared before he is strapped down and injected with a lethal
chemical mixture at 12:01 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The condemned man's best chance of a reprieve was with the U.S.
Court of Appeals in San Francisco, which blocked his execution last
August. But late Saturday, the federal appeals court refused to
stay the execution, rejecting his plea for a hearing to bring in
new evidence that he says proves his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprising, lopsided 9-to-2 vote, the judges said that
Thompson, 43, had not raised ``clear and convincing'' evidence
proving that he should not be put to death.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's fate is now in the hands of the U.S Supreme Court,
which stayed his execution almost a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, he may not be as lucky.
</P>
<P>
   In reinstating his death sentence in April, the high court
accused the U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco of committing a
``grave abuse of discretion'' in stopping the execution in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to do real well up there,'' said Frank Zimring,
a criminal law professor at the University of California's Boalt
Hall School of Law in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, 43, was sentenced to die for the 1981 rape and
stabbing death of Ginger Fleischli at his Laguna Beach apartment.
</P>
<P>
   He would be the fifth person to be executed in California since
the death penalty was reinstated in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the previous four inmates, Thompson had no prior criminal
record and is not a multiple murderer.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers say they have uncovered evidence that they claim was
withheld by the state proving that Thompson is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, they pleaded with the U.S. Court of Appeals for a
hearing to bring in evidence that allegedly undermines the rape
conviction. Without that conviction, Thompson would not be eligible
for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers rely on transcripts from a 1995 parole hearing, in
which Thompson's accomplice, David Leitch, testified that he saw
Thompson and Fleischli having consensual sex on the night of the
murder.
</P>
<P>
   But in an opinion issued Saturday, Chief Judge Proctor Hug
called Leitch's statements ``minimal evidence'' that does not prove
Thompson's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's attorney, Andrew Love of San Francisco, said he would
immediately file an appeal with the U.S. Supreme Court. ``It's an
outrage that the state can withhold critical evidence of
innocence,'' he said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy District Attorney Mike Jacobs, the prosecutor in
Thompson's 1993 trial, denies that he withheld any information.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Leitch never said anything at the time of the trial
or at the 1995 parole board hearing that would have exonerated
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all fiction,'' the prosecutor said. ``It never happened.
Nobody who had anything to do with the case has any doubt about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Ross, a spokesman for state Attorney General Dan Lungren,
said the right man is being put to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in our minds that he is guilty of the crimes
that he has been sentenced to death for,'' he said. ``No doubt.''
While Thompson's lawyers fight to save his life, his scheduled
execution has been almost overlooked, compared to the barrage of
publicity he received last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's case is caught up in the morass of procedural rules
aimed at shortening death penalty appeals that can drag on for
years.
</P>
<P>
   The condemned man was unable to overcome a procedural hurdle
created by a 1996 federal law that limits state prisoners to one
appeal in the federal courts unless they have evidence proving
their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' Love said. ``The case appears to be coming
down to procedural technicality.''
</P>
<P>
   But legal experts say the rules reflect the public's growing
impatience with the endless delays that prevent the death penalty
from being carried out.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has repeatedly chastised the federal
appeals court in San Francisco for issuing last-minute stays of
execution, leaving it up to the high court to make the final
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty is a no-win issue for the U.S. Supreme Court,
Zimring said.
</P>
<P>
   If the justices allow a death penalty to be carried out, there's
blood on their hands, he said. If they stop an execution, the
justices are accused of delaying the process.
</P>
<P>
   What the courts want is to get out of the capital punishment
business, Zimring said. ``And they can't.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the death penalty, ``you can't have a fair and
fast system,'' Zimring said. ``You can have one that's fast or you
can have one that's fair. But you can't have them both.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jack Fleischli, Ginger's brother, believes that when
Thompson is executed there finally will be some sense of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's speculative whether it will provide relief or not, but
I'm looking forward to it immensely,'' said Fleischli, who said he
will witness the execution with his brother, Mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thompson has escaped justice for 18 years. If his time has
finally come, I'll be very gratified.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleischli, a former public defender, was practicing criminal law
as a private attorney when his sister was killed. He said the
incident was so traumatic that he changed professions. He has been
an actor for the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischli said he still thinks constantly of his sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were incredibly close,'' he said. ``When something like
this happens to a family, it's devastating, it's a day-to-day
assault, it's water torture. You wake up, and somebody in your life
is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then you have to wait 18 years or longer for justice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
