<HEADLINE>
BEWARE OF PESKY 401(K) MAINTENANCE FEES 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY DOAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Are administration fees pecking away at your retirement nest egg?
Money invested in 401(k) retirement plans is being swallowed by
rising maintenance fees, according to a booklet released by the
U.S. Department of Labor this month.
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to the booklet, fees range from 0.2 percent of an
account balance to 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The fees cover day-to-day expenses like record keeping and legal
costs and to pay for investment-related services.
</P>
<P>
   The high figures cited in the booklet are comparable to what
investors pay for maintenance fees for mutual funds. The
publication notes that most workers are paying higher 401(k) fees
than they did 10 years ago because a growing number of employers
are shifting a greater share of the costs to their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Plan administrators say they also have had a hard time figuring
out just what the maintainence fees are because they aren't
well-disclosed by the plans.
</P>
<P>
   You can get a copy of the free report, titled, ``A Look at
401(k) Plan Fees,'' by calling (800) 998-7542 or going to
www.dol.gov/dol/pwba.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE COSTS: A child born this year will need about $104,000
to cover the costs (tuition, room and board, books, etc.) of four
years at a public college, according to the College Board's latest
cost survey. That compares with an estimated $222,000 for a private
college eduction.
</P>
<P>
   T. Rowe Price Associates Inc. has a new college expense
forecasting kit that you can use to calculate the costs in your
situation. You can order the booklet by calling (800) 638-5660.
There also is an online version available at www.troweprice.com,
and it has an interactive cost calculator.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING ORGANIZED: Citibank Corp. has a new workbook titled,
``Getting Financially Organized,'' to help those who are just
starting their financial planning or who need to reorganize their
finances. The free packet includes worksheets on paying bills,
saving and investing. Call (800) 669-2635 for orders.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING ADVICE: Charles Schwab has published a new guide on how
to select a financial adviser. It defines financial terms like CPA,
CFA and CFP, and it lists questions that investors should ask
advisers who they may be considering. The publication is free and
available by calling (888) 889-4998.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle staff writer Amy Doan can be reached at
doana &LR; sfgate.com or by calling 415-536-5134.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
