<HEADLINE>
TEST SCORES AFFECT RESIDENTIAL REAL ESTATE PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Even if you don't have kids, even if you don't care about the
future of American education, you should take a close look at your
local school test scores just released by many Bay Area districts.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Chronicle reporter Lori Olszewski noted last week, home
buyers scrutinize the scores of schools and districts their
children will attend _ and that translates into higher property
values in neighborhoods that funnel children into schools of higher
perceived quality.
</P>
<P>
   That fact helps explain why the stakes are so high in reporting
the results of California's Standardized Testing and Reporting
(STAR) exam _ and why some districts with many below-average
schools, like San Francisco, have resisted releasing their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But just how big is the effect on real estate prices? Economists
have examined the issue since the mid-1970s and usually found it
large.
</P>
<P>
   A study published in 1996 by the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas
estimated that every 10 percent increase in a school's contribution
to sixth-grade math scores increased neighboring home prices in
North Dallas by 4 percent _ making school quality the most
important influence on residential real estate values other than
the size and age of property.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, a 4 percent boost would add nearly $12,000 to
the price of the average home.
</P>
<P>
   Similar results were reported last March by Sandra Black, an
economist at the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, who compared
homes in Boston on opposite sides of streets that divide elementary
school boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   She found that moving from a school ranked at the 25th
percentile to one ranked at the 75th percentile led to a 3 percent
increase in average house prices, enough to grab the attention not
only of home owners, but of city officials concerned about
maintaining their tax base.
</P>
<P>
   But should home buyers pay such premiums for higher scores? Many
experts question the popular assumption that good scores reflect
good schools. Just about every study shows that what matters most
to student achievement are family characteristics such as parental
education and income, not differences in school quality.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it's hardly fair to assume that schools in Portola Valley
deserve all the credit for the high STAR scores of students there
compared with relatively low scores of poor and minority students
in East Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly wrong to take an inner-city school with low test
scores and blame the teachers,'' said Julian Betts, an economist
and education researcher at the University of California at San
Diego. ``Demographics matter tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   But if peer pressures influence student performance, then
perhaps parents aren't so irrational after all in checking out a
school's average test scores when choosing where to move. The
average does tell something about the achievement of students with
whom your own kids may mix. If your kids rise (or fall) to the
level of their peers, their education could be profoundly affected,
regardless of the school's other merits.
</P>
<P>
   Sorting out the effects of peers on individual student
achievement is a thorny but vital task, raising significant
questions not only about school choice, but about programs to track
ability groups in classes and bus minorities to desegregate white
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to list something that was of fundamental importance
but under-researched in the economics of education, this is it,''
said Thomas Kane at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have been frustrated in trying to estimate peer
effects because cause and effect are hard to determine. If kids
were thrown together randomly in schools or neighborhoods, it would
be easy to study the effect of growing up with more affluent or
brighter peers.
</P>
<P>
   But because families choose where to live, the causality gets
murky. Parents who put special value on education, spending more
time reading to their kids and helping with their homework, may
choose to put their kids into some schools or neighborhoods and not
others. Researchers may attribute to peers or neighborhoods an
influence on education that is actually caused by differences in
parental commitment.
</P>
<P>
   One influential study, published in the Journal of Political
Economy in 1992, followed this line of argument and concluded that
peers in fact have no independent influence on student achievement.
But the bulk of evidence from other studies is that parents are
right to assume that who their kids associate with in school does
matter:
</P>
<P>
   _ A study of 7,000 school children in Montreal in the early
1970s examined achievement gains from grades one to three and found
that the average IQ of students in any given class had ``a
consistent and strong impact on the achievement of individual
students'' in the class.
</P>
<P>
   _ An unpublished study this year by Steve Raphael and Alejandro
Gaviria at the University of California at San Diego, based on a
national sample of 10th graders, shows strong effects of peers on
the likelihood that students abuse drugs, drink alcohol, smoke
cigarettes or drop out of school. Moving from a school where no one
drops out to one where half the kids drop out would increase an
individual student's chances of dropping out by 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Studies of academic tracking consistently find that low-track
students do better when put into mixed classes with high-ability
students. Unfortunately, some studies also show that high-track
students do worse in mixed classes, showing they can be dragged
down by less-able peers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two University of California at Los Angeles economists
reported in January an answer to the puzzle of why Head Start, the
preschool program for disadvantaged children, doesn't pay off in
long-lasting academic gains for black students. The reason: African
American Head Start graduates disproportionately end up in schools
with sub-par test scores. Rubbing shoulders with under &QL; 
achieving peers causes them to backslide after they enter school.
</P>
<P>
   _ Peer effects seem to matter a lot in college as well. Studies
show that, holding individual ability constant, students are more
likely to graduate from more-selective colleges. Students also earn
3 to 5 percent higher wages several years after graduating for
every 100 point increase in the average SAT score of their college
class.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot that researchers still don't know about peer
effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has disentangled whether what's important is your
immediate group of friends or (the quality of peers in) the class
you are in, the school or the neighborhood,'' said Dominic Brewer,
an economist at Rand, a think tank in Santa Monica. ``We don't
understand how they affect how kids do'' in school or in life.
</P>
<P>
   But Lawrence Katz, an economist at Harvard University, said that
despite all the uncertainties, there's little reason to suppose
peer effects are unimportant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on my knowledge, the average citizen who's willing to
pay a lot of money to have better peers (in their school or
neighborhood) is probably right. It's hard to believe, given
everything we know about how children develop and the time they
spend with peers, that peers won't make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Marshall can be reached by e-mail at
marshall &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
