<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2378 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREETSMARTS-COLUMN-S     07-13 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREETSMARTS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAREHOLDERS BEWARE _ AUTODESK BRASS LIGHTENING UP AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK VEVERKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Top executives at Autodesk have been unloading stock again, and
history tells us that it doesn't bode well for shareholders.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the biggest sellers is President Eric Herr, who has dumped
about 115,000 of his shares in the San Rafael software company.
Herr is slashing his position (including options and warrants) in
Autodesk by nearly 20 percent, according to CDA/Investnet
Technologies, an investment research firm in Rockville, Md. The
action was noted in filings between May 27 and June 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are large numbers. This kind of selling doesn't tell us
that the insiders see a lot of upside in the company's shares
during the immediate term,'' says Bob Gabele, editor of Investnet's
insider newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   All told, five company insiders sold or filed to sell about
157,225 shares at around $42 to $43 a share. Autodesk closed Friday
at $35.63, down about 31 cents.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, insider selling shouldn't warm the cockles of
shareholders' hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Autodesk, the nation's fourth-largest seller of software for
personal computers, makes software that is used by various
industrial concerns, from heavy manufacturers to architectural
firms to video production companies.
</P>
<P>
   Its exposure to Asia's sick economies is fairly substantial.
During the company's first fiscal quarter ending April 30, Autodesk
reported that about $29 million of its revenues, or 15 percent,
came from the across the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   That could be a considerable problem. And it has proven to be
troublesome for one of Autodesk's top rivals: Parametric Technology
of Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Parametric was a poster child for blown-up tech stocks earlier
this month. On July 2, Parametric plunged $8.75 in heavy trading
after it warned Wall Street that the company's third-quarter sales
and profits would be lower than expected. Parametric blamed much of
its financial woes on lost business in Asia. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Whether Asia will cause financial hiccups for Autodesk remains
to be seen. The company reports that North American and European
sales are robust. Herr, who was unavailable for comment, has said
he would be ``surprised'' if his firm would need to warn Wall
Street about missing earnings targets.
</P>
<P>
   An Autodesk spokeswoman would not speculate on Herr's motivation
for selling his shares. However, she does say the executive
exercised options to buy the shares. She notes that the options
were slated to expire last month.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that means Herr &LR;   &LR; would have needed to dip into his
personal cash to buy the shares and hold them. If he had done that,
it would have sent a more reassuring sign to shareholders than
unloading 20 percent of his position when Asia is economically
underwater.
</P>
<P>
   But would buying and holding the shares have been too much to
ask at this time?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, if you consider the precedent. This isn't the first
time Herr and compatriots have sold big chunks of stock. Last
November and December, Autodesk insiders sold about 294,000 shares
at prices ranging from around $37 to $42. That time, Herr lightened
his load by 165,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that insider sell-off, Autodesk shares plummeted
20 percent, according to CDA.
</P>
<P>
   And it looks like the same thing is happening to Autodesk shares
this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Veverka can be reached at 901 Mission St., S.F. 94103,
phone at (415) 777-8444, or e-mail at mveverka &LR; sfgate.com. He also
appears on KRON-TV's Daybreak program on Tuesdays and Thursdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
