<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-INVESTORS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND FOR YOUNGSTERS APPEALS TO ADULTS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY DOAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
When Stein Roe &AMP; Farnham's Young Investor Fund was launched four
years ago, it was designed to appeal to kids _ with investments in
companies like Coke and Hasbro, and cartoonish quarterly reports.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But to almost everyone's surprise, the fund is increasingly
popular with adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started, 100 percent of the shareholders were young
people or parents who were setting up custodials for their kids,''
said Dave Brady, senior portfolio manager with Stein Roe in
Chicago. ``Now, over 25 percent are adults who want their own
account.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason: Young Investor has posted some very grown-up
returns. The no-load fund has beaten the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 over
the one-year and three-year periods ending June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's minimum investment is low _ $100 if shareholders
agree to add $50 a month until their account reaches $1,000. That's
good for kids on allowances, but it's also ideal for adults who
can't come up with the steep minimums _ usually starting at $2,500
_ required by most funds.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, which now has assets of $776 million and 135,000
shareholders, has undergone other changes that suit aggressive
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The first prospectus promised that managers would only buy
shares in companies relevant to kids.
</P>
<P>
   But before long, the fund's managers realized that they needed a
wider range of options to achieve good performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make sure there was some room to pick small-cap
stocks because our investor profile _ young kids with very longtime
horizons _ is very aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund now aims to hold at least 60 percent kid-related
stocks. Its top-10 holdings now include companies such as Outdoor
Systems (a billboard company), Cisco Systems, Viagra-maker Pfizer
Inc. and Traveler's Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   That shift in approach has won over analysts, some of whom
nicknamed Young Investor the ``High Calorie Fund'' because of its
heavy weighting in companies like Coca-Cola, McDonald's and
Wrigley.
</P>
<P>
   ``At its inception, people may have thought it was just a
gimmick that would die away,'' said Laura Lallos, senior analyst
with Morningstar in Los Angeles. ``But they're not letting the
marketing drive their buys.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Morningstar gives the fund its highest, five-star rating.
</P>
<P>
   But some worry that the fund's stellar performance may mislead
young shareholders into thinking that 30 percent-a-year returns are
normal.
</P>
<P>
   Lallos cautioned that the fund ``has had the wind at its back''
and that kids might be getting an unrealistic impression of the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the same holds true for many other funds in this
prolonged bull market.
</P>
<P>
   Kids will ``eventually get their lesson'' when the stock market
turns, said Lallos.
</P>
<P>
   She said the fund's newsletter does a good job of explaining
risk in words that kids understand.
</P>
<P>
   The simple language also appeals to adults, according to Brady.
``I think there are a lot of adults out there who want to
understand the market and the companies they're investing in
better. This gives them a closet way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Each quarter, the newsletter features a question and answer with
an executive at a company owned by the fund.
</P>
<P>
   In last quarter's newsletter, a 13-year-old girl from Kansas
asked McDonald's chief executive Michael Quinlan why the chain
doesn't serve veggie burgers.
</P>
<P>
   His answer: ``We do serve a `veggie burger' in India, because
beef is not part of its cultural diet, and in a few other markets
outside of the United States. While we don't plan to add it to our
U.S. menu, we do offer several nonmeat items, including salads and
soups.''
</P>
<P>
   (Despite that comment, McDonald's is test-marketing veggie
burgers on the East Coast, according to Brady.)
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Horton, a 12-year-old from Rohnert Park with $6,000 in
the fund, looks forward to the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like knowing where my money's going and who the people are
running the companies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew is 53 years away from retirement, but he's already
socking away most of his $7 weekly allowance.
</P>
<P>
   His early savings ethic started in 1995 when his mom, Wendy, got
Andrew and his two brothers and sister started in the fund.
</P>
<P>
   She said she wanted to encourage her children to invest early
because she wishes her parents had done the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds crazy to have a 10-year-old saving for retirement,
but that's almost what you have to do now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Horton gave each child $1,000 to start them off in the fund. She
promised that when the kids saved up $500 to invest, she and her
husband would match them dollar-for-dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy worked a little too well _ I think I owe about
$1,000 right now,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
