A2386 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHR     07-13 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE BOSS DOESN'T REPAY EMPLOYEE'S LOANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 Q:  My boss often asks me for small loans _ usually about $5 for
lunch. Although he makes considerably more money than I do, he
never pays me back. I've tried to talk to him and have even told
him I'm short on cash, but he ignores all that. He's the top dog
here, and there's no one above him that I can complain to. Do you
have any suggestions?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Your manager is way out of line here. Your job description
may include everything from typing to arranging the office flowers,
but I doubt that it says ``provide a revolving loan for the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Take another look at whether you've expressed your concerns
directly enough. You may have been so polite that your boss didn't
get the message. And believe it or not, he may be so preoccupied or
insensitive that he just doesn't realize how all those $5 lunches
are adding up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen situations like this where the managers were
actually quite embarrassed when they realized what they were
doing,'' said Michelle Burke, president of Executive Counterparts,
a San Francisco firm that coaches administrative support staff.
``They didn't realize it was $5, then $10, $20, $30 _ that it was
adding up.
</P>
<P>
   If your boss continues sponging off you, Burke suggests, keep a
written tally of the loans and submit it to him for reimbursement
every couple of weeks. Or ask your boss to set up a petty-cash
drawer for the office, so that he can borrow from that fund rather
from you.
</P>
<P>
   You also could simply try giving him a polite ``no'' when he
asks you for a loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she thinks her boss will be angry because she won't lend
him money,'' Burke said, ``she needs to ask herself whether this is
the kind of person she really wants to work for.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; The president of my company has his secretary make coffee
for him. When she's not around, he asks other female administrative
staff like myself to do this. His secretary doesn't seem to mind,
but I do. It seems demeaning and unfair because he never asks the
male office staff. Can I be fired if I politely refuse to get him
his coffee?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; In the office of the '90s, it's not uncommon to see
everyone from the boss to the receptionist making their own coffee
_ or taking turns doing a Starbucks run on behalf of the whole
office.
</P>
<P>
   But many secretaries still do make coffee for their supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are happy to do it, while others find it
demeaning,'' said Lynn Taylor, director of research at Robert Half
International, a Menlo Park staffing firm. ``If someone has strong
feelings about this, they should find out what the corporate
culture is while job-seeking. When they're talking with the
company, they can ask if personal tasks are considered part of the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   In your case, you're in the job already and you want to keep it.
So see if the other secretaries share your feelings. Then approach
someone in management _ your own boss, a personnel manager or maybe
the president himself _ and politely explain why fetching coffee
bothers you.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a hard worker and a valued member of the team, the
company's likely to accommodate you. After all, do they really want
to alienate a good employee simply over a cup of coffee?
</P>
<P>
   But if the firm insists that you get coffee, you do have to
comply _ or risk discipline and even firing.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike providing the boss with constant $5 lunch loans, getting
coffee is a pretty reasonable request. It may not be in your job
description, but neither are a lot of other small projects that
managers ask their assistants to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Could you sue if you were fired for not fetching coffee? Maybe _
if you could prove that only the female office staff were put on
coffee duty. But it would be a pretty hard case to win, according
to Doris Ng, an attorney with Equal Rights Advocates in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Want more information on the legal rights of office workers?
9to5, the National Association of Working Women, runs a free job
advice hotline at (800) 522-0925.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I'm interested in finding out about COBRA. How can I get a
copy of the law?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; COBRA is short for the Consolidated Budget Reconciliation
Act of 1987. That's the federal law giving most employees the right
to continue purchasing health coverage through their company's
group plan for 18 months after they leave a job.
</P>
<P>
   (It also allows an employee's dependents to continue buying
group insurance for up to 36 months if they lose their coverage for
reasons such as graduating from college or undergoing a family
divorce.)
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to find out about COBRA is through your company.
Look in your benefits handbook or ask for a copy of the Summary
Plan Description for your health plan.
</P>
<P>
   You also can get a summary of COBRA from the U.S. Pension and
Welfare Benefits Administration. Visit their Web site at
www.dol.gov/dol/pwba/public/pubs/COBRA/cobra95.htm. Or call PWBA at
(800) 998-7542 or (415) 975-4600.
</P>
<P>
   If you want even more detailed information, Robert Burnett of
Buck Consultants in San Francisco suggests these sources:
</P>
<P>
   _ The COBRA law itself can be found in the section of federal
code called 29 USC 1161-1168. You can access it on the Internet at
law.house.gov/uscsrch.htm.
</P>
<P>
   _ The proposed COBRA regulations that appear in the Federal
Register aren't in electronic format. However, you can get a copy
of the Federal Register in most public libraries and look for the
section 52 FR 22716 _ June 15, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   _ The federal tax code relating to COBRA is Section 4980B(f) and
can be found at www.fourmilab.ch/ustax/us tax.html.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; _ The Internal Revenue Service publishes Notice 98-12,
``Deciding Whether to Elect COBRA Health Care Continuation Coverage
after HIPAA,'' which can be viewed online at www.irs.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Have a question about your workplace or career, your boss or an
employee? Send it to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San Francisco
Chronicle, 901 Mission Street, San Francisco 94103. Or send e-mail
to workways &LR; sfgate.com. Or call (415) 764-2815. We can't respond to
each query in person, but we will answer as many in print as  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
