r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-13 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     ADDING YOUR OWN PARTICULAR RAY OF SUNSHINE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing less than improving the cosmos is the aim of Weight
Watchers magazine, which advises: ``From the way you garden to the
way you order pizza over the phone, breathe radiance into this
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, &UR; Nicoletta Mantovani &LR; , 27-year-old love of &UR; Luciano &LR; 
 &UR; Pavarotti &LR; , told the London Telegraph about the difficulties of her
relationship with the Italian tenor:
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment of lunch and dinner was always a nightmare for
me,'' she said. ``We had very big fights. I was taking the plate
away. Everything would go on the floor. Oh, yes, a nightmare
situation! He thought I would never dare to do something like that
in front of guests, and he took advantage of that. So I started
even doing it with other people around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He became more mad and it was not nice. But after a lot of
fighting he understood. Now he knows he cannot eat everything, only
one portion. There is no drink anymore, no wine. He is very good,
and I am proud of him now.'' Pavarotti has lost 42 pounds, says the
New York Post. According to Mantovani, he ``is not enormous. The
legs are quite slim.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. &UR; Joe Waldholz &LR; , who is spending 37 months in Allenwood
Federal Prison for embezzling more than $4 million from the father
of his wife, former Utah Representative  &UR; Enid &LR; , has lost almost 120
pounds in the hoosegow, reports the Washington Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - More New Yorker editor possibilities, floated from near and
far: Knopf editor  &UR; Sonny Mehta &LR; , Salon founder  &UR; David Talbot &LR; , GQ
editor  &UR; Art Cooper &LR; , Conde Nast editorial director  &UR; James Truman &LR; 
and  &UR; Jon Carroll &LR; . Names that haven't come up yet:  &UR; Ginger Spice &LR; ,
 &UR; James Fallows &LR;  and  &UR; Dan Quayle  &LR; (who was unavailable for  &UR; Si &LR; 
 &UR; Newhouse &LR; 's call this weekend because he was playing in the Isuzu
Celebrity Golf Championship at Lake Tahoe).
</P>
<P>
   - San Franciscans shouldn't let People magazine's cover story on
 &UR; Barbra &LR; 's wedding overshadow the treasure within: A glowing
profile of Delancey Street founder and director  &UR; Mimi &LR; 
 &UR; Silbert &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   - Following last week's item about Web sites,  &UR; Jeff Pelline &LR; 
directed Personals' attention to www.sfchronicle.com, which an
entrepreneur _ who has nothing to do with this newspaper _ is
offering for sale, with the come-on, ``over 84,000 (unique)
visitors per year!'' And  &UR; Bob Lacey &LR;  remembers that  &UR; Will Durst &LR; 
once ``registered a Web site that's worth absolutely nothing:
www.amish.com.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Bob Treuhaft &LR;  credits the U.S. embargo for the toilet paper
origami in Cuban hotels: Baby-soft American-style stuff ``would
wilt in the hands of an origami artist,'' he writes; the use of
``crinkly European style paper'' makes this art possible.
</P>
<P>
   - The Irish band Boyzone has been hired by  &UR; Mohamed Fayed &LR;  to
perform at the opening of the summer sale at Harrods, and then
outside the department store at midnight on August 31, to
commemorate the anniversary of the death of  &UR; Dodi Fayed &LR;  and
 &UR; Princess Diana &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   - Postcard from day camp: At an SF/SPCA children's summer
``Introduction to Pet Care'' workshop last week, a little girl
having trouble making her voice authoritative enough to command her
dog to sit received some helpful advice from her sister: ``You can
say it meaner than that!'' she said. ``Think about if I just broke
your favorite Barbie doll!'' It worked.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; IN THE SUMMER &LR;   &UR; WHEN IT SIZZLES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Frank Viviano &LR; , The Chronicle's man in Paris, reports that
 &UR; Stuart Canin &LR; , former concertmaster of the San Francisco Symphony,
couldn't resist temptation when he came upon four street musicians
at the Place des Vosges. He joined in on a Beethoven string
quartet.
</P>
<P>
   - News that the French bank, Credit Foncier de France, which
indirectly is responsible for management of the Eiffel Tower, might
be sold to an American company owned by General Motors, created a
stir in Paris last week.  &UR; Philippe Domanati &LR; , a conservative city
council member, said it was ``inconceivable and unacceptable'' that
Americans have a major role in managing the tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   It took a formal reassurance by the French Ministry of Finance
that the City of Paris would always retain control to undo the ado,
said British newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
