<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2393 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOLFF-SFCHRON &LR;      07-13 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLFF-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Cyberspace Tell-All  
   
 By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR; New York &QL;  &LR;
<P>
   Michael Wolff speaks softly but wields a wicked pen.
</P>
<P>
   The writer-turned-Internet entrepreneur-turned writer has just
published a scathing tell-all that chronicles the early days of the
online Gold Rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burn Rate'' is Wolff's biting first-person account of how his
company, New York-based Wolff New Media, landed him in the inner
circle of Net pioneers, including Wired magazine founder Louis
Rossetto and America Online Chairman Steve Case.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The book rips new media, old media, Wall Street _ and Wolff
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most heinous deeds were committed by me. I was a guy in
business who would have done nearly anything to survive,'' says
Wolff, who lives in a spacious, nearly empty Upper East Side
apartment with his wife and three kids.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, he wrote that New York venture capitalist Alan
Patricof ``resembled a mental patient'' and described Case as ``an
affable, nondescript, chinos and button-down guy with a layer of
baby fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Like that other Wolfe _ Tom _ Michael Wolff practices ``new
journalism,'' nonfiction dressed up with quotes and color to
resemble a novel.
</P>
<P>
   In his preface, Wolff explains how he gathered his treasure
trove of trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``At conference tables, board meetings and industry gatherings,
while others were scribbling to-do lists on their legal pads, I
found myself recording observations and jotting down telltale lines
of dialogue on mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolff's irreverent take how companies that were losing millions
of dollars suddenly became worth billions hasn't gone unnoticed by
some executives.
</P>
<P>
   AOL executive Ted Leonsis, whom Wolff described as a ``fat man,
an ugly man, sweating like crazy,'' has blistered Wolff with
equally vitriolic e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are a loser _ and you are looked at as a whiner. ... Suck
it up _ what's next for you _ a guest spot on Geraldo or Jerry
Springer?'' Leonsis wrote in a message to Wolff.
</P>
<P>
   Others are also miffed &UR; .  &LR; ``I understand that ``Louis (Rossetto)
feels betrayed, (Cnet co-founder) Halsey Minor is furious and CMP
is apoplectic,'' Wolff says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Louis' case, that's unfortunate, because I think he made an
incredible accomplishment that was described in the book. But he
doesn't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys are threatening lawsuits against Wolff. And CMP Media,
a billion-dollar Long Island publisher of computer magazines,
blamed a stock dip on his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's seriously, off-the-charts reaction,'' says a bemused
Wolff. ``The industry is so bloodless and one-dimensional in how it
wants to be perceived. These people are funny, but they want to be
perceived as serious people, leading the most serious industry in
the world's greatest economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Burn Rate'' shatters that myth, in a series of caustically
comic vignettes that center around Wolff's attempts to raise money
and create a new media empire.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff New Media developed a series of best-selling books about
the Internet and operated one of the first online Web-site
directories.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Burn Rate refers to the amount of money a startup spends each
month that exceeds its income.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the tens of millions of dollars that Wolff had tried
to raise didn't materialize and his company closed shop in the
spring of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Wolff, 44, is back to writing, doing a weekly column for
the Industry Standard.
</P>
<P>
   His first job out of Vassar College was with the New York Times.
He has also free-lanced for Rolling Stone and Playboy and has
penned two critically acclaimed books _ ``White Kids'' and ``Where
We Stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Over pizza in an East Side restaurant, Wolff castigates AOL,
calling it ``the most dysfunctional company in America. The
underlying reason for their success is selling sex and fantasy
role-playing in chat rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that Yahoo's ``estimated $9 billion market value doesn't
make one bit of sense to me, there is nothing there.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Most of all, Wolff is scornful of Silicon Valley, which he
describes in an interview ``as a one-company town, it's
Detroit-like. Everyone knows someone in high-tech, everyone is
working toward the same goal, they're all on the same team. They
all work and eat together. And those company cafeterias _ they make
me want to stand up and scream.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolff says a chief complaint about his book is that it revealed
anecdotes that took place during confidential conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't believe this guy, a former journalist, was taking
notes in executive meetings. Their attitude was, `You can write
about us, but only on our terms.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The valley may hate ``Burn Rate,'' but Hollywood loves it.
According to Wolff, several film and TV studios have approached him
about bringing his book to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff calls ``Burn Rate,'' which took six months to write, a
`cathartic experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Among everything else, this is a very funny story,'' Wolff
says, ``I wanted to write a real story on the absurdity and chaos
theory that go into startups. If that means calling a buffoon a
buffoon, a cheat a cheat and a mental patient a mental patient, so
be it.`
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1516EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
