<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2394 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-IMPLANTS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-13 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-IMPLANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW CHEMICAL NOT LIABLE IN CALIFORNIA IMPLANT CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARRIET CHIANG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The California Supreme Court ruled Thursday that
the co-owner of silicone breast implant-maker Dow Corning Corp.
cannot be sued over illnesses that women in California suffered
from the product.
</P>
<P>
   The high court said Dow Chemical is not liable for any harm
caused by the implants made by its now-bankrupt partner, Dow
Corning.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1995 as a means
of legal protection from almost 20,000 lawsuits brought by women
claiming injury from the implants.
</P>
<P>
   In its 6-to-1 decision Thursday, the state Supreme Court said
Dow Chemical could not be held legally liable for its part in doing
research on silicone toxicology for Dow Corning in the 1940s and
1950s, before the silicone breast implants were produced.
</P>
<P>
   When Dow Chemical conducted and performed the research, ``any
risk of physical harm to plaintiffs from negligent performance of
that undertaking was unforeseeable,'' wrote Justice Kathryn Mickle
Werdegar in the court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning began making breast implants in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, women began filing lawsuits against Dow Corning
claiming that leaks in the implants had caused a variety of
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1992, the breast implant cases in California were
coordinated into one legal action.
</P>
<P>
   A San Diego trial judge threw out the lawsuits in 1994, a
decision upheld by a state appeals court in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In affirming that dismissal, the high court said there was no
evidence that Dow Chemical had undertaken any duty to ensure the
safety of the implants.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Chemical officials were delighted by the ruling, which they
said is consistent with decisions in Michigan and New York
dismissing similar suits.
</P>
<P>
   The decision ``is consistent with a growing recognition in the
courts that science, the facts and the law do not support
plaintiffs' claims in implant cases,'' said John Scriven, Dow
Chemical vice president and general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the decision will help facilitate the resolution
of these claims in Dow Corning's bankruptcy process.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said Thursday's ruling will have little, if any, effect
on a separate $3.2 billion agreement reached Wednesday between Dow
Corning and lawyers for tens of thousands of women across the
country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1516EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2395 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CNN-GROUP-SPCL-BOS     07-13 0306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CNN-GROUP-SPCL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MULTIPLE MEDIA, CNN SPRAWLS OVER THE WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 
(a and e coding)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN   AND MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the precision of a professor giving a lesson
in economics, CNN correspondent Wolf Blitzer described the division
of his daily labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I do a spot from the White House, it'll air on CNN,''
said Blitzer. ``Then it'll air on CNN Headline News. Then CNN
International. Then CNNfn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it'll air on CNN Radio. Then they'll give it to CNN
Newsource. Then to CNN en Espanol. Then our interactive Web will
use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Blitzer paused, not dizzied at all, apparently, by the specter
of one of his stand-ups on the White House lawn undergoing such a
multiple-media metamorphosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genius of CNN,'' he confided, ``is that they've amortized
the news.''
</P>
<P>
   The CNN programming that Americans see on their television
screens derives from CNN/US, which is but one part of the sprawling
entity that is the CNN News Group.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN News Group encompasses six cable networks (CNN/US, CNN
Headline News, CNN International, CNNfn, CNN/SI, and CNN en
Espanol), two radio networks, seven Web sites, the CNN Airport
Network, the Better Health Network, the College Television Network,
and the syndicated news service called CNN Newsource.
</P>
<P>
   It has 700 broadcast affiliates located all over the world,
enabling programming from CNN/US and CNN International to be
available in 190 million homes in nearly 220 countries and
territories.
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN is the best-known brand in the world,'' declared Richard
Kaplan, president of CNN/US.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a pointed reminder that beyond the tip lies the rest of
the iceberg, Kaplan added: ``The downside is people think they know
you, and they don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1516EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2397 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-COPPOLA-PINOCCHIO-SFC     07-13 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIO SNUB NETS COPPOLA $60 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-COPPOLA-PINOCCHIO-SFCHRON   By PETER STACK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oscar-winning director Francis Ford Coppola won $60 million in
punitive damages Thursday in his lawsuit accusing Warner Bros. of
thwarting his attempt to make a feature film about Pinocchio.
</P>
<P>
   That's on top of the $20 million the same Los Angeles County
Superior Court jury awarded in compensatory damages to the San
Francisco filmmaker, famous for his ``Godfather'' trilogy and
``Apocalypse Now.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola, who wept during the trial, said in Los Angeles after
the verdict: ``Warner Bros. has traditionally not treated its
creative people well. Hopefully, this will teach them to treat
creative people as an asset, not as serfs.''
</P>
<P>
   The studio, which the jury earlier found acted with ``fraud''
and ``malice'' in saying that it owned the screenplay Coppola
wanted to make into a movie, said through a spokeswoman that it
would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the jury in their verdict found that Warner Bros.
reasonably believed it had a contract with Mr. Coppola, there's
absolutely no basis for the jury's award of punitive damages, and
the $60 million amount is simply ludicrous,'' said Barbara
Brogliatti, senior vice president of corporate communications at
Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   If the appeal is denied, Coppola could collect his award within
18 to 24 months, his attorney, Robert Chapman of Los Angeles, told
The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the normal length of time, given the way the appellate
system is currently working,'' Chapman said. ``And we believe that
the jury's decision will be upheld all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola, head of the American Zoetrope production company, based
in San Francisco's North Beach, filed the lawsuit in 1995. He had
asked for about $23 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Coppola said, ``I feel vindicated in
the long struggle with Warner Bros. and encouraged that the
individual can stand up against enormous corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood at his Columbus Avenue office was ``jubilant,'' said
one employee.
</P>
<P>
   The case, closely watched by writers and other artists unhappy
with some aspects of Hollywood business manners, dates to 1991. In
court, Coppola and Warner Bros. disputed a $3,100 fee he got from
the studio for ``Pinocchio.'' Coppola said in court he considered
the amount too small to bind him in any way to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The studio then threatened to sue any other studio that tried to
produce it even though it refused to pay Coppola to develop the
film. The director had previously tried to sell the project to
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Coppola film was to be a live-action version of
``Pinocchio,'' with an estimated budget of $100 million, according
to industry reports. It was to be a modern musical version set
against the story of a band of children escaping from the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   The major dispute in the case was whether Coppola and Warner
Bros. ever made a legitimate deal for Coppola to produce his
``Pinocchio.''
</P>
<P>
   In the compensatory damages award, the $20 million was based on
the fees Coppola would have collected for writing, directing and
producing. The figure included a projection of gross profits had
the film been moderately successful. The jury used the box office
earnings of his 1992 ``Bram Stoker's Dracula'' to make its
calculation.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman said his client ``clearly touched the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extremely gratified, because he always wanted to tell
his story to a group of 12 regular people. He knew they would
understand. He was overwhelmed by the amount of the judgment, but
it is fair _ studios have to learn they are required to follow the
law and the rules just like everyone else,'' said Chapman. ``It's
an important day for artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. denied it prevented Coppola from proceeding with
his ``Pinocchio'' project at Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The project was one of three Coppola negotiated with Warner
Bros. A second, ``The Secret Garden,'' was made under the Warner
banner, and the third, ``Hoover,'' is still in development,
according to the studio.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
