<SLUG> BC-TV-CNN-II-SPCL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN STRUGGLING TO SHAKE IMAGE OF HO-HUM TV
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (a and e coding)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN AND MARK JURKOWITZ   
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With President Clinton out of town on a muggy
Monday in May, the White House was becalmed and newsless _ a
circumstance at which CNN correspondent Wolf Blitzer usually would
chafe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Blitzer wore a contented smile as he glanced at the front
page of The Washington Post, where the lead story was based on news
generated by ``Late Edition,'' his Sunday interview show. That sort
of ``pickup'' matters greatly in this political hothouse of a city,
where TV's ``Sunday talks'' are judged ruthlessly by how much news
they break.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another, more direct measure of a network's impact
than scoring a Beltway bull's-eye: namely, how many viewers are
watching? On that score, CNN fell short on that day, just as the
network falls short whenever there are no bombshell stories
riveting people to their TV screens.
</P>
<P>
   No news is bad news for an all-news network, and on its slowest
days, CNN's ratings sink to the neighborhood of the Home &AMP; Garden
channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN does wonderfully when there's a major news event, but they
lose momentum any time there's no major crisis or hugely
fascinating story,'' said Lawrence K. Grossman, former president of
NBC News. ``When their audiences are small or minuscule, they have
to worry a lot about their ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   By that standard, there is cause for significant worry these
days at CNN. Mark Twain once defined a classic as ``a book which
people praise and don't read.'' CNN is struggling to shake an image
as a network that people praise and don't watch.
</P>
<P>
   That is why new CNN/US president Richard Kaplan opted to
mobilize CNN behind a new ``NewsStand'' series _ the magazine show
whose debut was badly tarnished when the network had to retract the
``Tailwind'' story alleging that the US military used nerve gas in
1970 on defectors in Laos.
</P>
<P>
   That setback notwithstanding, there was a competitive impetus
for change. While CNN clung year after year to its identity as a
plain-vanilla news service, aggressive new players joined the
all-news game that CNN invented and began poaching its viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, around-the-clock competition for serious news viewers
comes at CNN from all directions, ranging from splashy national
upstarts like MSNBC and the Fox News Channel to the Internet and
local outlets such as New England Cable News.
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers are playing for keeps, and some of them see CNN's
leap into prime-time newsmagazines as another symptom of the
network's vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN is, in my view, trying to save itself from terminal
boredom,'' said John Moody, vice president of news at the Fox News
Channel, an all-news cable outlet that was founded less than two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've chosen an interesting route: creating huge
controversies about their reporting,'' Moody added, in a caustic
reference to Tailwind. ``It's not boring. I don't think it's what
they had in mind, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, CNN clearly had to do something. Its viewership (along with
general viewership of other networks and local stations) has
declined since the early 1990s. Just last month, a survey conducted
by the Pew Research Center found that only 23 percent of
respondents said they watched CNN regularly, down from 35 percent
in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   While CNN is less financially dependent on ratings than
broadcast networks, since cable operators pay a fee to carry its
programming, its chronic ratings woes underscore the oddly
precarious position the world's leading all-news TV network finds
itself in.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its vulnerability to news slumps, CNN is battling ominous
trends. For one thing, surveys show that American viewers are
tuning out foreign affairs in huge numbers. That's dire news for a
network whose calling card for the past 18 years has been its
no-dateline-is-too-distant coverage of international news.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the news environment has changed dramatically in
the post-Cold War era. As the nuclear threat receded, Americans
have developed what Bernard Kalb, host of CNN's ``Reliable
Sources,'' has described as ``a blissful indifference to the
urgency of news.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN Washington bureau chief Frank Sesno sees major implications
for his network. ``We have to be honest, that we are in an era of
bits-and-pieces news,'' Sesno said. ``We've got relative
prosperity, relative peace, and there's no epic story that
dominates the front page every day such as a civil rights struggle
or a recession. The news environment has changed, the interests of
our viewers have changed, and our storytelling has to change.''
</P>
<P>
   But as CNN tries to reinvent itself, the question arises: Has
CNN waited too long, and given its new competitors too much of a
foothold to stave its audience erosion?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there are three (all-news) cable networks ... and the
viewership for all of (television) journalism is in rapid
structural decline,'' said media analyst Tom Rosenstiel. In
revitalizing CNN, he added, Rick Kaplan faces ``a lot harder job''
than he would have had just five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   With CNN reeling from the credibility blow delivered by the
Tailwind fiasco, Kaplan's job may have just gotten harder still.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At CNN headquarters in Atlanta, not far from Kaplan's office,
hangs a telltale graph that vividly shows the 18-year history of
CNN's ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Four sharp points reach into the air like church spires,
reflecting the network's ratings spikes during the Gulf War, the
O.J. Simpson freeway chase, the verdict in Simpson's murder trial,
and the Al Gore/Ross Perot NAFTA debate. (Shortly after CNN
mesmerized sleep-deprived Americans with its nonstop coverage of
the 1991 Gulf War, CNN News Group chairman Tom Johnson ran into
American tourists while hiking in Peru. ``We came down here to get
away from CNN,'' they told him.)
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the ratings graph looks like a freshly mowed lawn _
reflecting CNN's flat numbers in normal, calmer times. Take May 3,
when Blitzer's ``Late Edition'' won the news race but lost the
ratings race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Edition'' drew 517,000 households for its first hour
before climbing to 708,000 households during its final half hour.
While that was a strong showing by CNN's standards, it nonetheless
represented only half as many as the number tuned into ``Fox News
Sunday,'' an interview show the Fox broadcast network launched just
two years ago. NBC's ``Meet the Press with Tim Russert'' drew 3.2
million households, ABC's ``This Week with Sam Donaldson and Cokie
Roberts'' 2.6 million households, and CBS's ``Face the Nation'' 1.6
million households.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the overall ratings numbers this year encouraging for
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   From January through March, as CNN joined the media frenzy over
allegations that President Clinton had an affair with White House
intern Monica Lewinsky, an average of only 507,000 households per
day were tuned in to CNN, according to Nielsen Media Research. From
April through June, as the Lewinsky story abated somewhat, CNN's
average numbers dropped still further, to just 348,000 households
per day, about as many viewers as watch Country Music Television.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 100 top-rated programs on basic cable in the first
quarter of 1998, CNN had two, a special on the Texas woman facing
execution and the State of the Union address.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
