<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2405 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-SPIN-HNS &LR;      07-13 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-SPIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG AUTHOR TAKES A `SPIN' IN CALIFORNIA'S POLITICAL CIRCLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ California Republicans have sex for fun. At
least that is what the author of a new novel, ``Spin,'' would have
you believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spin'' is billed as a trashy morality tale set amid the
``glamour, excess and power of California GOP politics,'' featuring
an Armani-clad Machiavelli with goals that reach far beyond
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   In this political potboiler, the likes of Michael Huffington and
former Assembly Speaker Curt Pringle _ both former bosses of author
Tom Lowe _ are not-so-subtly turned into fully functional sex and
scandal machines named ``Edward Winston'' and ``Brett Alexander.''
</P>
<P>
   Published by Pocket Books, ``Spin'' has gotten attention from
U.S. News &AMP; World Report and George magazine, which declared it:
``Sex Conservative Style: Republicans take cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Some California Republicans aren't taking ``Spin'' (304 pages,
$23) too seriously. ``It's so outrageous. It's a joke,'' said
longtime GOP consultant Jim Camp. ``People are just laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, 26, was a low-ranking campaign operative for Huffington,
an unsuccessful U.S. Senate candidate, and a former press aide to
Pringle. He insists he only borrowed backdrops from recent
California history for ``Spin,'' which went on sale last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I had a lot of good material for a novel,'' Lowe
said. ``What was important to me was to have a plot. A book like
`Primary Colors' (about President Clinton's 1992 campaign) doesn't
really have a plot because you basically know what happened.
Clinton got elected. I knew I couldn't count on Curt Pringle or
Michael Huffington to make this thing a best-seller. I knew I had
to have a really compelling story, a moral story.''
</P>
<P>
   The plot lines to ``Spin'' aren't just backdrops. Lowe has
lifted the entire tumultuous history of the Republican fight in
1995 to replace former Assembly Speaker Willie Brown, not the mayor
of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The fictionalized account is told by Jim Asher, speechwriter to
the eventual GOP speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The novel includes an episode in the beginning that Lowe insists
is true: A drunken Asher has carnal relations with two women on the
speaker's desk, breaking a framed picture of the speaker's son. It
was never reported because most of the police officers who guard
the Capitol are ``good Republicans,'' according to the novel.
</P>
<P>
   The Asher character later convinces another woman that he
doesn't need to wear a condom, even though she's worried. She
doesn't even know his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Jim. And don't worry _ I'm a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the real world, the clubby GOP political scene has
pretty much ostracized Lowe _ while feigning indifference to the
novel. They were particularly upset after reading an article he
wrote last summer for the alternative newspaper, OC Weekly. Lowe
says he regrets some of the things he wrote in ``I Was a Gigolo for
the GOP,'' which was billed as nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers me,'' Lowe said, ``is that some of the smaller
people in that article, the girls for example ... they would be
recognizable to the small group of people I was hanging out with. I
hurt some people's feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   In the novel, Asher works to recall GOP Assembly Speaker ``Bryan
Gentry'' after Gentry works a deal with former Speaker Willie
Black. Asher sets up a decoy Democrat to split the vote and gets
his guy, Brent Alexander, elected and eventually elevated to
speaker.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, in real life, Republican Doris Allen was elected
speaker with the help of Brown. Allen was eventually recalled, and
replaced with another GOP turncoat, Brian Setencich. Several
Republicans were accused of recruiting a decoy Democrat to split
the vote in Allen's recall race in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   In the novel, political consultant Bud Raper calls himself ``a
bar-brawling, cigar-stomping political gunslinger.'' GOP political
consultant Ed Rollins worked for Huffington and looks and acts a
lot like the Raper character.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe referred to Tolstoy and Hemingway in an interview. Jim
Asher read and absorbed Edmund Burke, Madison, Bloom, Strauss,
Plato and Olasky with ``astonishing greed and clarity.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to imagine Tolstoy writing this: ``I understood
how to play the game. That's why I now lived my life as an Alpha
male. I ate Alpha food _ filet mignon. I drove an Alpha male car _
the Hummer. I had an Alpha male physique _ muscular and athletic.
Whenever I had time to think over decisions in my life, I always
asked myself: What would an Alpha male do?''
</P>
<P>
   He'd write a book. Get an agent. Hang out in Tahoe. Wait for the
movie deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2406 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CNN-II-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     07-13 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CNN-II-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 WASHINGTON: ... Union address.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``When news breaks, people turn to us,'' said CNN's Johnson.
``When there is a quiet environment, they go back to soap opera and
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, NBC, ABC, and CBS _ the networks that Kaplan tells
the CNN troops are the real competition _ pull in 8 million
households apiece each night for their evening newscasts, week in,
week out, without regard to public interest in a particular news
story. During prime time, the broadcast networks draw even more
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Blitzer pointed out that CNN's ratings numbers do not
reflect the network's large international audience, which Nielsen
does not measure. ``We're seen in 220 countries around the world,''
said Blitzer. ``While we may have a smaller audience (in the United
States) than the broadcast networks, worldwide we're seen by many
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he noted, when it comes to domestic viewers, CNN
operates in the cable universe, which is smaller than the broadcast
universe of 98 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   But still, CNN's programming is distributed to 73 million US
households. It is an American network competing with other American
networks for viewers, yet the cold truth is that at any time only
around half a million Americans consider it must-see TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest disappointments is that after the Gulf War,
we went back to our pre-Gulf War audience,'' conceded Blitzer.
``Maybe we should have done the `appointment-viewing' approach
we're doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Appointment-viewing refers to shows that viewers remember to
turn on and watch week after week.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's Moody, however, pointed to CNN's Tailwind embarrassment as
an object lesson in the risks of grafting magazine-style,
``appointment viewing'' programs onto an all-news network.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to reconcile the concept of appointment viewing with
a news channel, for exactly the reason that has now caught CNN by
the butt,'' said Moody. ``There's too much of a push to put on
incredible stuff _ and in this case, literally incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Other rivals, while stressing their respect for CNN's
journalistic caliber and pioneer status, make clear that CNN now
inhabits a brave new world where its dominance is no longer
assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: Is there a large enough audience to sustain
numerous 24-hour cable news operations?'' said NBC's Russert, who
besides hosting ``Meet the Press'' has an interview show on CNBC
and makes regular appearances on MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that CNN had the luxury of avoiding when they
were the monopoly,'' added Russert. ``They could do the news wheel
as much as they wanted. Now, however, they realize they have to go
with programming rather than rehashing headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   John Higgins, assistant managing editor at Broadcasting &AMP; Cable
magazine, said CNN, while still dominant, is destined to weaken.
``CNN isn't quite on the defensive because of MSNBC and Fox,'' he
said. ``But the faster they get strong, the worse (CNN is) in the
long run. Eventually, (CNN) is going to get eroded by the other
cable networks.''
</P>
<P>
   While not conceding that as inevitable, especially since the
advent of its new newsmagazines, CNN staffers such as anchor Judy
Woodruff take that threat seriously. ``To survive, we've got to be
aware of who our competition is,'' said Woodruff.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for CNN is that the competition today takes so many
forms. For example, MSNBC, a joint venture of NBC and Microsoft,
boasts star power CNN cannot match, since it draws heavily on such
NBC celebrities as Jane Pauley and Matt Lauer.
</P>
<P>
   Sesno says of CNN's instantaneous transmission of news that ``we
were the Internet before the Internet was cool,'' but lately the
real Internet has come on strong as yet another news competitor.
The Pew survey found the number of Americans getting news from the
Internet at least once a week has more than tripled in two years.
</P>
<P>
   The balance of power among the all-news cable networks is so
delicate, one TV analyst said, that CNN's continued dominance would
be gravely threatened if MSNBC were the network that found the next
Larry King.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As competitors like MSNBC try to unseat CNN, though, they are
tackling a widely respected organization that has made news _ and
even history _ while reporting it.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters such as Blitzer and foreign correspondent Christiane
Amanpour are considered among the best in the business. CNN's
traditional reputation for trustworthiness is no myth: A May survey
by the Pew Research Center indicated that among cable and broadcast
outlets, CNN ranked highest in believability, ahead of CBS's ``60
Minutes'' and network and local news.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thistle, the former news director at WCVB-Ch. 5 in Boston
who is now director of broadcast journalism at Boston University,
said that reputation is well earned. ``When it comes to breaking
news, they're right on top of it. They set the agenda,'' said
Thistle. ``When I deal with CNN people, they don't know the word
`can't.' The enthusiasm level is very high; they're not arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, CNN has a direct impact on events, one that is unique
among television networks.
</P>
<P>
   A study of US press coverage of the 1989 uprising in China's
Tiananmen Square, published by Harvard's Shorenstein Center on the
Press, Politics, and Public Policy, quoted a rival reporter as
saying it was CNN's coverage of events that forced other networks
to increase their live coverage, bringing a global spotlight on the
crisis and ``setting an agenda for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   A host of foreign leaders, from Moammar Khadafy to Saddam
Hussein, have used CNN's airwaves as a bully pulpit. Peter Arnett's
stint as the lone Western journalist in Iraq sparked a debate about
his patriotism and journalistic neutrality. In the '80s, Poland's
Communist government agreed to include a half-hour of CNN on the
nightly newscast to mollify the Solidarity trade union. After the
United States invaded Panama in 1989, the Soviets used a statement
on CNN to register their reaction. According to Eason Jordan, CNN's
president of global news gathering, the old Soviet KGB established
a unit dedicated to monitoring CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (CNN) has had a very significant impact, probably much
more outside the country than inside,'' said Barrie Dunsmore, the
former ABC News diplomatic correspondent who has written about the
impact of television on geopolitics. Leaders like Boris Yeltsin and
Hussein make judgments based on the network's coverage, Dunsmore
added. ``There really isn't an equivalence to that in previous
times. ... It's very easy to misread the reality of a situation
based on a hiccup in attention from CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan acknowledged that ``clearly, at times, our reporting and
the pictures we show have driven policy. If that results in some
policy changes, that's only a natural process.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called CNN effect on geopolitics is the subject of much
scholarly discussion and plenty of think-tank manifestoes. But the
grim reality is that news may not sell: The Pew survey indicated
that only 16 percent of respondents followed international affairs
``very closely.'' And Yeltsin and Hussein don't get counted by
Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   The eyes of the world have often turned to CNN in times of
international crisis. Now, recognizing that that is not enough, CNN
is striking out in a direction with no clear signposts, in hopes
that new viewers will join them along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really are at a crossroads,'' acknowledged Judy Woodruff.
``We're rethinking: `What is news?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2410 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CNN-I-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-BO     07-13 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CNN-I-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (a and e coding)  
 ATLANTA: ... different niche.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the ill-fated nerve-gas story demonstrated, the CNN/Time
program (Sundays and Mondays) is intended to be an
attention-grabbing newsmagazine. The CNN/Fortune pairing
(Wednesdays) is business-oriented, looking at subjects ranging from
the popularity of corporate jets to the rise of Michael Dell's
computer company. The CNN/Entertainment Weekly effort (Thursdays)
is a showbiz program with some newsier edges. The first episode,
for example, featured a ``Spin City'' segment on the Hollywood
hired guns who help polish the images of wayward stars who have
ended up on the police blotter.
</P>
<P>
   The next major surgery on the lineup occurred on June 22, when
CNN's nightly ``Moneyline with Lou Dobbs'' was expanded into an
hourlong ``Moneyline News Hour'' (6:30 p.m. weeknights) that is
CNN's answer to its broadcast cousins' nightly news shows. The
program makes use of CNN's reporting resources and has morphed from
a Wall Street roundup into a hybrid of business and world news
where the crisis in Nigeria gets about equal billing with a surge
in Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, said Dobbs in a recent interview, is to broaden the
reach of his old show ``to the political economy. ... It's going to
be a very serious broadcast. ... I probably shouldn't acknowledge
this, but this is going to be very close to being news for the
know-it-all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kaplan strategy for CNN is to produce more provocative
programming without dumbing down the network, ``to make the
presentation worthy of the scope of the network,'' as he says. The
trick is to get viewers to think of CNN as something other than a
perpetual newscast. The blueprint calls for shedding the network's
faceless-anchor image and developing stronger personalities;
creating prime-time programming, like ``NewsStand,'' with clear
identities and themes; and pouring more energy into distinctive
long-form journalism.
</P>
<P>
   At Kaplan's prodding, CNN has produced a stream of nightly
specials on issues like campaign-finance reform and tensions with
Iraq. One day after The New York Times created a furor with its May
3 story suggesting major breakthroughs in cancer treatment, for
example, CNN was on the air with a prime-time special on the
subject. Early returns indicated that these specials were bumping
up CNN's ratings by anywhere from 50 to 200 percent for that hour.
</P>
<P>
   This past January, the network unveiled an ambitious Sunday
night documentary series, ``CNN Perspectives,'' which has tackled
such subjects as Holocaust survivors and life in war-torn Sarajevo.
Some of CNN's plans are epic in scope, including a 24-hour ``Cold
War'' series narrated by Kenneth Branagh, due to begin airing this
September.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of sprawling, cerebral programming that would
seem to present the most obvious conflict between CNN's
journalistic ambitions and its hopes for a mass audience. Still,
the bosses think the ``Cold War'' series can work on both levels.
In the most animated moment in an hourlong interview in May,
Johnson rose from his desk, clutched a handful of ``Cold War''
tapes, and announced that they contained evidence that the Cuban
missile crisis was even more dangerous than previously thought.
``In this,'' he exclaimed proudly, ``Fidel Castro makes
headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   At a network where the credo was ``the news is the star'' and
anchors like Shaw and Judy Woodruff are not considered breakout
personalities, Kaplan has made headlines by actively trolling for
flashier talent. He dangled lucrative offers before CBS's Rather
and NBC's Tom Brokaw, who both turned him down. Others, however,
said yes, including ABC's Willow Bay and Judd Rose, both of whom
are now hosting ``NewsStand'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaplan's biggest catch so far is senior analyst and
``NewsStand'' co-host Jeff Greenfield, who built a reputation as a
brainy and provocative commentator at ABC. The Greenfield
acquisition was ``huge for me,'' said Kaplan. ``When you make him
part of the bouquet, people pay more attention to the rest of the
flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield received a quick baptism of fire at CNN. &UR;  &LR; A week
after arriving in late January, he was hosting a prime-time special
_ called ``Media Madness'' _ that became an orgy of
self-flagellation over media outlets' performance covering the
Monica S. Lewinsky saga.
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN said `Come here and you can stretch,''' said Greenfield in
early June. ``This was a place where I could do more.'' Greenfield
acknowledged that his CNN role is ``still evolving'' and that being
a host is an adjustment. ``All of this is a work in progress, and I
think you have to come here with that at the center of your
assumptions,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield's already tricky transition has been complicated by
the Tailwind story, which he introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish it had not happened,'' he sheepishly declared on the
July 5 edition of ``NewsStand.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most visible indicator of how far CNN has come since it was
launched _ reaching a paltry 1.7 million homes, and known by the
derisive sobriquet of ``The Chicken Noodle News'' _ is the
network's headquarters near downtown Atlanta. It looks less like a
news operation than a huge theme park designed around a central
atrium that includes the set of CNN's ``Talk Back Live'' show; a
CNN studio tour; and the Turner souvenir store. Spiraling around
the atrium are the CNN offices, which house some of the 3,500 or so
full-time employees of its sprawling empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have eight independent networks,'' explained Kaplan several
months ago, while citing the advantages CNN has over competitors
like Fox News Channel and MSNBC. ``We have an assignment desk that
speaks 31 languages. We're talking about spending $700 million in
news coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   But CNN's power is not strictly in resources. The network has
affected _ some might say revolutionized _ the journalism business.
``In many ways, CNN has served as an electronic version of the
Associated Press,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point may have come in the first days of the Gulf
War, when Americans, awakening with dark circles under their eyes
after watching CNN into the wee hours, realized that their morning
papers contained nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   In a critical and widely quoted article on CNN for The New
Republic in 1994, media analyst Rosenstiel wrote that after the
Gulf War, ``suddenly, CNN was on in newsrooms around the country,
... changing the consciousness of the people who put out
newspapers. Editors who watched CNN all the time started to assume
that their readers were watching, too.'' That, he concluded, led to
more of the narrative and interpretive-style journalism that is in
vogue today, as newspapers seek to give readers something they have
not already gotten from CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hastened the trend among news organizations toward opinion
and interpretation over hard reporting,'' Rosenstiel wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Tailwind flap, some might argue that CNN had
fallen into a trap of its own making _ forsaking its immediate-news
mission for the kind of dramatic storytelling that would grab
viewers' attention for the new show.
</P>
<P>
   That is the view voiced by Nieman Foundation curator Bill
Kovach, who says of CNN: ``I don't think you can make a mistake of
this magnitude and not suffer consequences. At what point is it
going to be possible for journalists to resist the pressure ... to
compete for revenue dollars rather than focus on quality?''
</P>
<P>
   Others say that despite this misstep, CNN's best bet is on
Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a vision,'' said Blitzer, this past week. ``He needs
some time, obviously, to get it going. But I have no doubt that he
is the man who can lead us to the level of journalism we want to
get to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
