<HEADER>
A2413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CNN-I-SPCL-2TAKES-     07-13 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CNN-I-SPCL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAKING CNN PROVING DIFFICULT
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (a and e coding)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ AND DON AUCOIN  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On June 7, amid a cloudburst of promotion, CNN debuted
an ambitious program designed to usher in a proud new era at the
world's leading all-news network.
</P>
<P>
   As the cable network's first serious move into the prime-time
newsmagazine world that has produced such valuable commodities as
``60 Minutes,'' ``Dateline,'' and ``20/20,'' ``NewsStand''
represented an attempt to transform CNN's identity, to parlay its
longstanding reputation for fast, fair television news _ for being
the channel Americans turn to when a crisis erupts _ into more
stable, long-running viewership.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Shortly before the premiere of ``NewsStand,'' a program he
created, CNN/US president Richard Kaplan sat in his Atlanta office
and enthusiastically predicted that the new show ``will get us a
lot of different attention and a lot of different eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Kaplan may be pondering the wisdom of the adage: Be
careful what you wish for.
</P>
<P>
   The very first ``NewsStand,'' with its stunning allegation that
the US military used a deadly nerve gas during a secret 1970
mission in Laos dubbed ``Operation Tailwind'', has been a fiasco
for CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the night it aired, there were troubling doubts
about the Tailwind story. Less than one month later, the network
was forced to retract it, three producers were out the door, and
Peter Arnett, perhaps CNN's most famous reporter, was reprimanded
and nearly fired. Kaplan contemplated quitting. His boss, CNN News
Group chairman Tom Johnson, submitted his resignation to network
founder Ted Turner, who refused to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   But late last week, Turner indicated how much damage the episode
had caused. ``Nothing has upset me more in my whole life,'' he said
at a Television Critics Association news conference. ``I feel
horrible about it. CNN has been my baby from the very beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the Tailwind trauma simply added to the litany of
recent media disasters, including the dismissals of New Republic
writer Stephen Glass and Boston Globe columnist Patricia Smith for
fabricating material in their work and The Cincinnati Enquirer's
$10 million apology for improperly obtaining material for an expose
about the Chiquita Brands company.
</P>
<P>
   For this media outlet, though, it was a debacle with a
particularly cruel twist. Rather than savoring its most innovative
programming move in years, a shellshocked CNN was left fighting to
regain its hard-won credibility.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 years, CNN had carved out an enviable reputation for
earnest journalism. It had also become America's ``hearth'' for
breaking news _ the place where people flock in times when there is
information everyone's waiting for and everyone's talking about.
That place in our national life is reflected in the huge CNN
viewership for events ranging from the Gulf War to the freeway
chase of O.J. Simpson. Yet the network has had to face another fact
about its history: In less stressful times, viewers desert in
droves. No longer satisfied to watch its audience flow in and out
like the tides, CNN executives are trying to reinvent the network
as a place where news, entertainment values, and personality mix to
create distinctive programming and attract more viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're an underachieving network,'' said Kaplan in an
interview before the debut of ``NewsStand.'' ``We're averaging
about a 0.5'' rating, less than half a million households ``and we
should be getting a lot more. ... All of a sudden, we've come to a
fork in the road and there's only one path to go. And that's up.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, the Tailwind story hangs like a dark cloud over
the network's aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shaken by the setback, but we're moving quickly to get
over it,'' senior White House correspondent Wolf Blitzer told the
Globe last week. ``Are we over it? No. It will take some time. But
the best way to get over it is to show everybody we're going to
break stories and do in-depth journalism and regain whatever
confidence may have been lost due to this one mistake _ albeit a
big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters last week, Gerald Levin, chairman of Time
Warner, which is CNN's parent company, expressed his confidence in
the Johnson-Kaplan team.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the nerve-gas story fiasco, the big question was
whether stronger competition, embedded viewer habits, and changing
news technology would doom CNN's strategy. Now, Tailwind raises the
stakes, and a daunting question: Will CNN become a victim of its
own ambitions?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a corporate entity, the CNN News Group might be fat and
happy. It comprises 13 operations and 36 foreign and domestic
bureaus, and earns about $300 million in annual profits on total
revenues of about $1 billion, revenue split roughly 50-50 between
advertising and fees.
</P>
<P>
   The network has also amassed an impressive list of journalistic
accomplishments since its inception in 1980. It consistently tops
public opinion polls in terms of reliability and credibility. It
has become America's network of choice in moments of drama. It has
changed the way global leaders do business. And it has functioned
as a video wire service for the rest of the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe the public has been well served by the
presence of CNN,'' said Johnson in May, before the Tailwind story
was aired. ``I believe we have been there for them in Tiananmen
Square; ... in San Francisco'' for the 1989 ``earthquake; in
downtown Baghdad.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN's problem, of course, comes during calmer moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of an old story, the cyclicality of CNN's
viewership,'' said John Higgins, assistant managing editor at
Broadcasting &AMP; Cable magazine. ``So Kaplan is trying to organize
this into a better audience flow, particularly in prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the Tailwind episode could have resulted in
Kaplan's departure sent chills through the CNN boardroom. More than
any other personnel or programming change, the hiring of Kaplan _
the 6-foot-6 former executive producer of ABC's ``World News
Tonight'' and well-known friend of Bill Clinton _ is the linchpin
of the new CNN strategy. Before landing him last August, Johnson
actively pursued Kaplan, 51, for almost three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't until Rick was hired that they said they were going
to create a different sensibility, a `show' sensibility,'' said
media analyst Tom Rosenstiel. ``The only `appointment' programming
they had was `Larry King' and `Crossfire.' They never really had
anybody with that kind of network experience.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, ``appointment viewing'' has become the CNN mantra:
In a May interview, Johnson said ``appointment shows'' would help
mark the ``third major wave or cycle in the life of CNN.'' The term
refers to programming that viewers will make a point of watching.
NBC's ``Must-See TV'' on Thursday night is the most spectacular
current example.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects ``Seinfeld'' to be reincarnated on CNN. But there
is a heavy burden on Kaplan to juice up the prime-time lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``NewsStand'' is ``akin to what CNN launched on June 1, 1980, in
terms of magnitude and in terms of significance,'' said anchor
Bernard Shaw. ``Anybody who does not realize that we are evolving
into an entirely new era is missing the basic point of our
existence.'' Even the old familiar CNN studio is in the midst of a
$7 million renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``NewsStand,'' the most expensive startup in CNN history, was
meant to be a showcase for corporate synergy. The show is one of
three collaborations with magazines which, like the network, are
Time Warner properties: Time, Fortune, and Entertainment Weekly.
These collaborative programs air at 10 p.m., most nights after
Larry King. Each has a different niche.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1523EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
