<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2415 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-POPULARITY-BOS     07-13 1480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-POPULARITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK CAR RACING IS SPORTS JUGGERNAUT OF '90S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing; moved July 11; a and s coding; note
time references.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ All week long, they have been gathering near the
big oval track here, the 130,000 auto racing fans who will, again
this year, help make the stock car race at the New Hampshire
International Speedway the largest paid sports event in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at Sunday's Jiffy Lube 300 (TNN, 1 p.m. EDT) is just
part of the evidence that the National Association for Stock Car
Auto Racing is now years beyond its image as a provincial, niche
sport, a descendant of the good ol' boys who ran moonshine in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of NASCAR, stock car racing has become the
sports juggernaut of the 1990s. As the organization celebrates its
50th year, observers agree that it is the model of what sports, as
a business, should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of leagues ought to take a real lesson from how they
have marketed the sport,'' said Larry Moulter, president and chief
executive of Woolf Associates in Boston. ``It is a sport that is
really smart about how it sells its story.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation of stock car racing is its fans, whose intense
loyalty to their favorite drivers and to the sport is a marvel on
Gasoline Alley and Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because NASCAR wasn't on television for so many years, its
legions of fans had to go to the races in person,'' said Shaun
Assael, who spent two years on the circuit to write a book, ``Wide
Open: Days and Nights on the NASCAR Tour.'' ``What they came to
understand is that it is best experienced that way.''
</P>
<P>
   As the crowds gathered in Loudon this week, it was clear that
the experience is about camping and family, as well as racing. With
thousands of recreational vehicles and trailers, the site resembles
a family campground, without the litter, but with a race track
attached. A look at license plates suggests that all New England
states have embraced stock car racing, along with New York and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attraction is all about the drivers and the cars,'' said
Bruce Reed of Hinesburg, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they don't go on strike and they don't screw up,'' said
Tom Gadhue of Richford, Vt. ``And they don't charge $100 per
autograph.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what this is all about is that, I think, everyone who
has ever sat in a car wants to know how fast it will go,'' Reed
said. ``Not everyone wants to play football or basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   The track in Loudon was built with private funds and is
supported, to a great extent, by the two NASCAR races there every
summer, according to Bob Bahre, chairman of the board of the
speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The 83,000 ticket holders who actually get seats are offered the
first chance on renewals every October. Bahre said the renewal rate
is 96 percent, with 15,000 to 20,000 on a waiting list for tickets.
In other words, get on the waiting list now, and by 2003 you might
have a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Based on NASCAR numbers, Sunday's race and the New Hampshire 300
on Aug. 30 will generate at least $32.8 million for tickets,
lodging, food, and souvenirs alone.
</P>
<P>
   Total attendance in this decade has increased 47.4 percent at
tracks across the country, from 3.8 million to 5.6 million. It now
averages about 180,260 per event. During the same period, NBA
attendance increased by 17 percent, NFL attendance by 6 percent,
and major league baseball by 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   New state-of-the-art racetracks have been built recently in
Southern California, Dallas, Miami, and Las Vegas. There are plans
for new tracks in Denver and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's television viewership is up 106 percent since 1991, and
it now beats the regular-season coverage of major league baseball
and the NBA, according to Nielsen Media Research.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of NASCAR-licensed products climbed from $60 million in
1991 to $600 million in 1996, according to NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   But the most striking business statistic has been gathered by
the IEG Sponsorship Report in Chicago: NASCAR alone will account
for more than 10 percent of the $4.5 billion spent this year on
sports sponsorships by US companies. While $476 million will be
spent on NASCAR, the sponsorship of the four major professional
sports _ baseball, basketball, football and hockey _ totals $457
million.
</P>
<P>
   So sophisticated is NASCAR as a business that even enterprises
far removed from the rush and rumble of 200-mile-per-hour
straightaways should heed the lessons of the descendants of
back-road rum-runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opera and the symphony could learn a lot from NASCAR,''
said Lesa Ukman of IEG Inc., the Chicago-based leader in analyzing
commercial sponsorships and endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR has really been smart with its fans, and it's made very
clear, in a very overt way, the direct links between their
sponsors' money and the benefits that the fans get,'' Ukman said.
``The fans understand that the sponsors keep ticket prices down and
pay for the new engine for their favorite driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what the opera and the symphony should learn: For
NASCAR, sponsorship is less intrusive than just a big part of the
fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, sponsorships in sports are commonplace. But when
NASCAR started linking companies such as Ford and Chevrolet to a
250-mile race on a dirt track at the Michigan State Fairgrounds in
Detroit in 1951, it blazed a trail that other sports,
entertainment, and recreational activities have followed,
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years, other sports didn't think to do stuff with
commercial endorsements from companies,'' said William C. France,
the president of NASCAR and the son of its founder, William H.G.
``Big Bill'' France.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, for a while, we were ridiculed for doing that,'' France
said. ``But, you see, we didn't have television. Through the '50s
and and a lot of the '60s, it was our fans paying money at the gate
who would have been left to pay for everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, a lot of other sports find themselves in a similar
position, because television is not paying for all of the big
salaries,'' he said. ``So, now, they are all doing what we did long
ago, as a matter of survival.''
</P>
<P>
   The throngs who attend races and a burgeoning television
viewership is older, richer, and better-educated, and includes more
women than one might imagine. According to NASCAR marketing
studies, 82 percent of fans are 25 or older, 64 percent are
married, 38 percent are women. Almost one-third earn more than
$50,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between NASCAR and other sports is the amazing
loyalty of fans to sponsors, and it all proceeds from the fact that
fan and sponsor were linked from the very start. It is of little
surprise to companies such as Kellogg's, Kodak and K-Mart that
NASCAR marketing studies show that 72 percent of its fans are more
likely to buy products from NASCAR sponsors than from anyone else.
Who cares if it even costs a little bit more, if it helps pay for
your sport and your heroes?
</P>
<P>
   Such fan loyalty helps drive a massive corporate investment in
stock car racing, attracting fully one in seven Fortune 500
companies, several of whom spend $10 million annually to sponsor
NASCAR drivers, cars or events.
</P>
<P>
   While the relationship between fan and sponsor is an intrinsic
part of racing, the relationship between fan and driver is its very
soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR has done it from Day One, and the drivers realize from
their history that in order to survive, they had to appeal to the
fans,'' said Robert G. Hagstrom, an investment strategist and
author of the book, ``The NASCAR Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking among the RVs and family barbecues in Loudon this week,
one does not hear the complaints typical in other sports, about how
the drivers are cry-babies, increasingly separated from their fans
by fame and riches, and far less skilled and gallant than the early
heroes of the sport. Instead, one hears of a fierce loyalty to men
they can literally touch.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the campers have flagpoles, and they fly, in order, the
American flag, the flag of their state, and a flag bearing their
favorite driver's number and colors. NASCAR drivers are famous for
their generosity to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Petty is the Babe Ruth of stock car racing, a legend as
famous for his feats on the track as he is for establishing the
sport as a fixture in American society. In 1972, Petty told Stock
Car Racing magazine: ``The people who come to see me race pay to
get in. If they didn't come, there would be no racing, and hence
there would be no Richard Petty. The very least I can do in return
is be nice and receptive to them and spend time with them, whether
they root for me or against me.''
</P>
<P>
   That relationship has largely provided for NASCAR's ascendance
in an era of increasing cynicism about professional sports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
