<SLUG> BC-TV-CRITICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TED TURNED ON BY SAGA OF THE COLD WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ CNN founder Ted Turner, mortified by the
network's embarrassment over its report on the alleged use of sarin
gas by U.S. operatives in Vietnam, is delighted if anyone changes
the subject, even if it's to discuss the possibility of nuclear
holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Turner decided CNN should do the definitive
piece on the half-century after World War II to show how close the
world came to total meltdown. The result is ``Cold War,'' a 24-hour
series that Turner, in his own humble way, calls ``one of the most
important television projects of the last several years.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who said he is sometimes ashamed to be in the TV
business, promised TV critics in Pasadena that ``Cold War'' will
not be a waste of people's time. It premieres in September and will
run in weekly installments into April.
</P>
<P>
   While we're on the happy topic of global annihilation, let us
not forget ``Planet of the Apes,'' that classic 1968 polemic on
what might have happened if humans had gotten too frisky.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, American Movie Classics won't let us forget. The
film that spawned four sequels and two TV series between 1968 and
1975 returns in September when AMC presents all five ``Apes''
movies and a new two-hour special, ``Behind the Planet of the
Apes,'' to mark the 30th anniversary of the first movie. It
explores how producer Arthur Jacobs put the project together after
many rejections, and how it came to be a marketing phenomenon that
broke ground for dozens of science fiction/adventure films that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   Action figure Charlton Heston, who appeared almost naked in the
first two ``Apes'' films, cloaked himself in nostalgia over the
weekend. Meeting with critics via satellite, Heston said he thinks
interest in the ``Apes'' oeuvre continues because the original was
a fine movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of created a genre of the space opera, which still
thrives,'' Heston said. Even the current escape-from-doomsday film
``Armageddon'' fits the category, he said, ``except it doesn't have
any dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Liotta twice turned down an opportunity to play Frank
Sinatra in a TV movie _ once on CBS, once on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   HBO persisted, and Liotta finally gave in. ``I realized I'm
getting to play a guy who sings `One for My Baby,' sleeps with Ava
Gardner and goes sailing with JFK,'' he said. ``That's a great
part.''
</P>
<P>
   As to his qualifications for playing the chairman of the board,
Liotta joked: ``I'm from Jersey, I've got blue eyes. Close
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO's ``The Rat Pack'' (featuring Joe Mantegna as Dean Martin
and Don Cheadle as Sammy Davis Jr.) premieres Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Potts still steams over ABC's treatment of ``Dangerous
Minds,'' canceled last year after 17 episodes. This fall, Potts
stars with Lorraine Toussaint in another drama about race
relations, ``Any Day Now,'' on the Lifetime channel, and is more
hopeful about the show's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare when (network) shows are given a chance to dig their
roots in,'' she said. ``With Lifetime, we have a more secure
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
