<HEADER>
A2469 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWINGSET-1500(3Takes)     07-13 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINGSET-1500(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS ARE DANCING THE JITTERBUG AND THE LINDY HOP OF YORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In a Deep Ellum parking lot on a Wednesday night, a
couple is dancing hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
   They are serious. They are sweating. They are perfecting their
Lindy Hop.
</P>
<P>
   Backs hunched, knees bent, eyes locked, they begin: swivel hips,
step-ball-change, turn around and start again.
</P>
<P>
   A horn section bellows from the bar next door, summoning the
faithful to the dance floor. A guy in a fedora keeps the beat,
singing 'bout a girl with two left feet.
</P>
<P>
   It's swing, man. A blast from the past. Get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Kids these days: They're more and more like kids 50 years ago,
actually. At least in the way they're starting to dress, in the
styles they're beginning to emulate, in the bands they're making
popular.
</P>
<P>
   And in the way they're dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Swing music is back, albeit with a few '90s twists like tattoos
and Web sites. An ever-increasing community of kids under 40 is
resurrecting the big-band sound, the jump-blues of Louis Jordan,
zoot suits and saddle shoes.
</P>
<P>
   It's been happening for years in less geographically insulated
parts of the country _ San Francisco and LA spawned the movement _
but the Dallas scene has attracted national attention, and evenFort Worth is part of the cultural stampede.
</P>
<P>
   In April and May, swing surfaced at several unlikely Fort Worth
joints: the Aardvark, the Wreck Room, the 8.0, attracting kids as
young as 16. Before closing in January, the Split Atom Cafe had
drawn crowds with weekly swing lessons and bands like Mr. Pink.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, the swing scene consists of a few hundred dedicated
dancers and lifestyle adherents, not to mention an increasing
number of venues, say Mitch Baranowski and Elaine Hewlett. ``Mitch
and Elaine'' teach East Coast swing to the mobs packing the
highest-profile swing event around _ Thursday nights at the Red
Jacket, where Fort Worth's Johnny Reno and his Lounge Kings hold
court.
</P>
<P>
   The swing circuit includes about a dozen bars and clubs in the
Metroplex, and almost an equal number of bands, including imports
from Austin. On May 8, the first ``all swing, all the time'' club,
the Sand Castle Swing Lounge and Casino, opened its doors on
Northwest Highway in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we started playing the music,'' the kids started
showing up, says co-owner Craig Thompson. ``They're like rats. They
smell the music.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Jet Lounge _ the Deep Ellum club where the aforementioned
couple was Lindy Hopping in the parking lot _ the Lakewood Rats'
four-man horn section whips up a melodic tsunami. Guys in gabardine
shirts and suspenders toss gals in vintage '40s dresses over their
heads and throw them through their legs. Garter belts are a-flyin'.
(For swing girls, panties are as public as purses.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an ability in swing to be kind of campy and have fun
and make it more than just the tunes,'' says Lakewood Rats founder
and frontman Brian Hurley, 31. ``You don't have to be chock-full of
integrity like all these angst-ridden bands. People are sick of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream popularity has brought a bit of a swing backlash:
Some of the original converts in San Francisco apparently have
moved on (to what, we won't know for another five years). And with
1,000 people passing through Red Jacket on a recent Thursday, a few
regulars have decided to take a break from the club until the
curiosity-seekers fade out.
</P>
<P>
   But the hardcore swing kids contend the movement is no fad for
them. It's an aesthetic and a lifestyle defined by simplicity, an
``anti-mini mall mentality,'' and a desire to celebrate one of the
few truly American art forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swing is an alternative to the alternative,'' says Hewlett,
28, who drives a '66 Thunderbird, has dressed vintage all her life
and recently quit her day job to teach swing full time. ``It's a
way to look, a way to feel. It ties everybody together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good clean fun.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Originally, ``swing'' was a verb, not a noun. As the jazz
fathers of the 1920s knew, any music can swing: a waltz can swing,
Pearl Jam can swing. It's a matter of attitude and musical energy.
But nobody has ever really pinned down what swing is, not even the
great band leader Count Basie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think swing is a matter of some good things put
together that you can really pat your foot by,'' he once said. ``I
can't define it beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   The swing music of the '90s is an amalgamation of big band, jump
blues, rockabilly and western swing. Old recordings have definitely
energized the movement, but of the new swing bands very few
actually qualify as big bands, which traditionally had 14 to 16
players. And very few sound as symphonic. Instead, they've
introduced a more aggressive jump style than their earlier
counterparts. Think Dean Martin with a dash of Green Day played on
78 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   It's a toe-tapping, finger-snapping, horn-driven sound with
lyrics that still rely heavily on humor, kitsch and romance. The
old songs have titles like ``Knock Me a Kiss'' and ``I've Got a Gal
in Kalamazoo.'' The new songs go by names like ``Hell'' and ``Big
Tattoo.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend encompasses the Charleston ('20s), two-tone shoes
('40s) and rat-pack chic, a la martinis and cigars ('50s, early
'60s).
</P>
<P>
   But its boldest manifestation is dance: variations on the
jitterbug, or the Lindy Hop (the dance they're doing in that Gap
khakis commercial).
</P>
<P>
   The Lindy came out of Harlem, so the story goes, where
African-American musicians were writing big-band jazz arrangements
as early as the 1920s. In 1927, Charles Lindbergh flew his plane
from New York to Paris, prompting headlines like, ``Lindbergh Hops
the Atlantic.'' Dancers in Harlem took to calling their eight-count
jitterbug after the aviator.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a decade passed before big bands became universally
popular. When Benny Goodman toured in 1935, reception to his
swinging arrangements (many bought from black musician Fletcher
Henderson) was cool to downright hostile. The country was barely
out of the Depression, and the working man wanted music to soothe
his weary soul.
</P>
<P>
   But the kids were a different story. When Goodman's band reached
Oakland, Calif., that summer, the line to get into the gig
stretched around the block. For the next 10 years, the nation would
be heady about big bands.
</P>
<P>
   There was more to this revolution than musicians looking for a
new groove and kids searching for an alternative to the fox trot.
Jazz, an African-American art form at its roots, would become the
first frontier on which blacks and whites broke the color barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1939, bands with both black and white musicians were
still unacceptable, in some cases illegal. Club owners stretched
rope down dance floors to separate black and white patrons, or
restricted blacks to the balcony.
</P>
<P>
   But a few influential jazz figures pressed for integration _
including band leader Artie Shaw, who hired Billie Holiday in 1938.
By 1940, Goodman's band included African-American musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the '30s, there was a search for an American culture,''
says Lewis Erenberg, a professor of history at Loyola University
Chicago and author of ``Swingin' the Dream: Big Band Jazz and the
Rebirth of American Culture.'' ``I see swing as not only the
commercialization of jazz, but also a rediscovery of American
tradition, and, in this case, African-American traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Inherent in swing was a broader definition of ``American'': The
band leaders and musicians, pop-culture icons of the time, were not
only black, but also Jewish, Italian, Irish, etc. Plus, with
Prohibition over and the Depression waning, Erenberg says, swing
expressed the nation's youthful energy, its power to heal itself.
</P>
<P>
   So why in the world is it back?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, the swing rebirth has the punk movement to
thank. Punk rockers _ weary of cacophony, androgyny and a generally
bleak lifestyle _ grew up, says V. Vale, the San Francisco-based
editor and publisher of the book ``Swing! The New Retro
Renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They can transfer the same driving energy from punk to
swing,'' says 29-year-old Baranowski. ``There's that gangster-bop
appeal, zoot suits, wild plaids and pinstripes. And it's just more
challenging musically.''
</P>
<P>
   Vale traces swing's rebirth to two key events in 1989: the Los
Angeles formation of the band Royal Crown Revue, and the opening of
the Deluxe, an Art Deco-style bar in San Francisco conceived as ``a
refuge from rock music.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Reno stumbled onto Royal Crown Revue while touring with
Chris Isaak in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into (premier Los Angeles swing club) the Derby on a
Thursday and I just went, `Wow.' Here's a club full of 21-year-old
kids dressed to the nines, and this band on stage is wailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like lots of early swing disciples, Reno, a saxophone player and
stalwart on the local music scene, grew up listening to big band
and crooners. By the time Red Jacket owner John Kenyon opened the
club in 1996, Reno had already recorded a portion of his first
album of swing tunes (aptly named ``Swingin' and Singin.'''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   He convinced the club to turn Thursdays over to his new band.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the deal,'' Reno recalls saying. ``You've got to do it
every week and for at least a year. We'll start out taking
practically no money, and let's see if we can develop a scene.''
(Besides Red Jacket, Sons of Hermann Hall and the now-closed Lava
Lounge were also early supporters of swing in Dallas.)
</P>
<P>
   About six months later, kids familiar with the California bands
started showing up. When Reno recruited Hewlett and Baranowski to
teach dance lessons, the crowds shot up to 150 each week. When the
indy film ``Swingers'' found an audience, the Red Jacket numbers
doubled, Reno says. ``And the whole thing has kind of taken off
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great way to socialize and meet people,'' Reno adds.
``And that's a whole new experience for your under-30 crowd. You
can ask some girl to dance, and if you're reasonably courteous and
friendly, you can have a great time. And I think that really
appeals to these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the bands Royal Crown Revue and Big Bad Voodoo
Daddy, featured on the ``Swingers'' soundtrack, have won
major-label deals. And the rest of the music industry is scrambling
to catch up. ``Just about every A&AMP;R guy in every town is out there
looking for bands right now,'' Reno says.
</P>
<P>
   Is our hometown boy next? Reno will neither confirm nor deny:
``There are some great possibilities in the works.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The twist put partner dancing on the back burner in the early
'60s, and rock 'n' roll, disco and grunge kept it there. If kids
were dancing at all, they were dancing by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, social movements arise out of needs,'' says
publisher Vale. Mainstream music no longer satisfies the desires of
a growing number of young people, he believes, especially the
longing for community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It translates to all sorts of levels,'' Vale says of the swing
attitude. ``Like getting to know the name of your grocer down the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Romance, courting, manners, dapper duds: The swing lifestyle
emphasizes a sort of old-fashioned simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting to the point where they want something more
engaging in a club atmosphere,'' says Matthew ``Taps'' Edwards, 24,
the host of KAAM/620 AM's ``Swing Shift'' show (6-8 p.m. Fridays)
and a swing teacher at the Sand Castle. ``It doesn't just have to
be a meat market.''
</P>
<P>
   Among swingers, drugs are passe and even drinking is considered
an inconvenience; ice water is the beverage of choice. ``Serious
swingers won't drink alcohol because you do those aerials _ it's
dangerous,'' says Edwards, who came to the swing scene 10 months
ago after a visit to the Red Jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked in and they were playing `Sing, Sing, Sing' from the
soundtrack of `Swing Kids,' which I owned, and never thought
anybody would do that kind of dancing again,'' he says. ``And I
absolutely fell on my knees thinking, `I have found my home.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight at the Sand Castle, Edwards is teaching 25 beginner
couples the Lindy Hop, outfitted in a double-breasted zoot coat and
wide-brim fedora. ``I've always dressed the part,'' he confesses.
``I had the nickname Ducky in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Valentine's Day dance, Edwards met his future swing partner
and girlfriend, Mandy Hofer, who demonstrates the women's part of
the Lindy wearing a floral dress and ankle-strap heels. She ends up
icing down her left foot at the end of the lesson. ``Someone with
very large heels got me,'' Hofer explains, wincing.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards plans to open the first all-swing store in the Metroplex
in the coming months, complete with music and clothing. And when he
isn't at the radio station or the club, he's giving private lessons
in the roomy foyer of his parents' Plano home.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some of us,'' Edwards says, ``it's just a way to live
again.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
