<HEADER>
A2512 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDGE-JUSTICE-2000(3T     07-13 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-JUSTICE-2000(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LEGENDARY FEDERAL JUDGE, RETIREMENT MEANS NEW QUEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News service clients) 
By LINDA P. CAMPBELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When about 40 former law clerks met recently to
roast and toast veteran U.S. District Judge William Wayne Justice,
they surprised him with a gift of flowing optimism: a new black
robe.
</P>
<P>
   He can use it.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the 78-year-old Justice took senior status this
month after 30 years on the bench, the retirement system for
federal judges allows him to keep hearing as many cases as he
wants.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters are delighted that Justice's judicial career
continues, even though he has left his Tyler, Texas, courthouse
seat to a new appointee. He will hear cases for the Del Rio federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   His critics, however, would just as soon he swap opinion writing
for gardening or golfing.
</P>
<P>
   In his career, Justice has ordered schools desegregated, public
housing integrated, immigrant children educated and the state
prison system revamped, all to correct constitutional violations.
</P>
<P>
   He also sat on a three-judge panel that in the 1970s ordered
single-member voting districts for Tarrant and other counties,
forcing the Legislature to revamp its districting plan for the
statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   For his work, Justice has been lauded and lambasted, revered and
reviled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a very nice guy who did a lot of courageous things
in a pretty hostile environment over a long period of time,'' said
lawyer David Richards of New Mexico, a former Texas lawyer who has
tried voting rights cases before Justice.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, state Rep. John Culberson, a Houston Republican who
is trying to end the judge's continuing oversight of the prison
case, accused the judge of having ``a sort of instinctive
willingness ... to substitute his personal authority for the will
of the voters on many occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   To Justice, the criticism and kudos are all in a day's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't control the way people feel about me,'' Justice said
last week in an interview at his tidy new Austin office, where
he'll share the courtroom used by judges from the 5th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to follow the law as I find it. If there's a gap in the
law, I'll make up my own mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, he said, ``is supposed to be fair, just and decent. If
it's not, I'm always disappointed, but I follow the law, whatever
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Tooling around in his sporty black 1991 Mitsubishi 3000, Justice
said he enjoys his virtual anonymity in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   He has wanted to return to the capital since his law school days
at the University of Texas, but especially now, so he can see more
of his daughter and 16-year-old granddaughter. Justice said his
wife, Sue, is handling the house hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has many good friends in Tyler, Justice said he was
also aware of significant hostility in a small city where he
reshaped many ingrained habits. He received hate mail and ugly
calls over the years, although no one ever threatened him
personally.
</P>
<P>
   Biographer Frank Kemerer wrote about the time that several
workers remodeling Justice's house walked off the job in the
aftermath of his school desegregation order in the early 1970s.
Kemerer also wrote about a petition signed by thousands of people
who supported the judge's impeachment after the school decision.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, James Brady, who owns a coffee shop near the
federal courthouse in Tyler, said the judge's fans tried to get a
petition to prevent his leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't like him,'' Brady said. ``I respect him
immensely because he did his job. He was doing what he thought the
Constitution said to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the lore about Justice, ``the thing that probably gets lost
is, he is really a fun person,'' said Tyler lawyer Andy Tindel, a
family friend who has won and lost cases before Justice.
</P>
<P>
   A large photo of Sue Justice sits on the judge's desk.
Autographed pictures of the late Justice William Brennan and the
late U.S. Sen. Ralph Yarborough occupy nearby shelves, along with
an orange-and-white football inscribed ``To Coach Judge Justice.
1972. Texas 27, TCU 0.''
</P>
<P>
   Former clerk Amy Johnson, who practices environmental law in
Austin, called Justice ``the most kind person I've ever met for
anybody in power.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also a perfectionist.
</P>
<P>
   He's respectful in the courtroom and expects lawyers to rise
when they speak. He doesn't want flowery writing drawing undue
attention to his opinions. But because he is a lover of words,
always searching for just the right one, he keeps a thesaurus, or a
book of synonyms, and a Bible near his computer.
</P>
<P>
   He attracts clerks from some of the nation's top law schools,
including Yale, Harvard and Stanford. They remain loyal to him, as
witnessed by high attendance at periodic reunions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Justice flew to Wyoming to perform a ceremony at the
marriage of former clerk David Weiser, an Austin lawyer, and his
wife, Assistant Attorney General Mary Crouter. Because he doesn't
have jurisdiction in Wyoming, he advised the couple to have their
marriage formalized by a local official first. Justice, who loves
to dance, recalled that the reception featured a great band.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling like he's part of your family,'' said
Johnson, the former clerk. ``How many bosses would you travel
across the country to see? He really is a hero to a lot of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   A native of Athens in East Texas, Justice grew up in the heart
of the conservative region that he would later shake up with many
of his rulings.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, whom Justice described as ``a very gentle woman,
very principled,'' was active in the Baptist church and took her
son to Sunday school at an early age.
</P>
<P>
   His father, a lawyer, was ``a populist. He loved people and
always tried to help them out'' if he could.
</P>
<P>
   Justice toyed with becoming a journalist or an engineer, but his
career seemed preordained. When he was just 7, his name was
alongside his father's on the Justice law firm shingle.
</P>
<P>
   His name also seemed so fitting: In law school at the University
of Texas, Justice and classmate Tom Law toyed with the idea of
partnering in a firm of Law &AMP; Justice. When Justice went to work
with his father after a stint in the Army, the firm, Justice, Moore
&AMP; Justice, was jokingly called ``Justice and More Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   President Kennedy nominated Justice as U.S. attorney for the
Eastern District of Texas in 1961, and President Lyndon Johnson
named him to the federal bench in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   He donned his black robe during a nationwide wave of change,
when federal judges were being called on to enforce desegregation
rulings in recalcitrant communities and to provide the backbone for
other civil rights protections.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970 and 1971, Justice issued desegregation orders that
affected school districts across the state. And his decisions on
single-member voting districts led to the election of black
officials in various East Texas communities.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys familiar with Justice's work say that although he was
a major player in institutional reform, he was not out of step with
other courageous federal judges in Texas and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were breaking new ground culturally or socially, but we
were not breaking new ground legally,'' said Richards, the civil
rights lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Justice's rulings riled ordinary people as well as
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   As he was then, the judge remains unapologetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't regard my so-called activism as anything other than a
response to the needs of a particular case,'' Justice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court has said the extent of relief to be granted
is measured by the extent of the violation of the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   In cases where he ordered extensive remedies, he said, ``the
violations of the Constitution have been egregious and required
detailed remedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you couch your decree or judgment in vague terms, there'll
always be a plea that they didn't understand what was there.''
</P>
<P>
   In a case Justice calls his favorite, he struck down a Texas law
that let public school districts charge tuition for undocumented
immigrant children.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ultimately affirmed the ruling, 5-4, in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was absolutely no case law on it. I found no case, no
statute that covered the point of law that I had to decide. So I
guess I made my own little contribution,'' Justice said.
</P>
<P>
   No case in Justice's court has generated more attention or drawn
more fiery political rhetoric than Ruiz vs. Estelle, the prison
reform case.
</P>
<P>
   Started in 1972 as a complaint over prison conditions, the Ruiz
suit led Justice to conclude that the prison system routinely
violated inmates' constitutional rights against cruel and unusual
punishment. In 1980 and 1981, he issued comprehensive orders
requiring widespread changes to relieve overcrowding; improve
security, health care and sanitation; revamp disciplinary
procedures; and give prisoners better access to legal assistance.
</P>
<P>
   One of the primary results was a boom in prison construction to
ease overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   He later found the state in contempt for not living up to its
obligations, and he threatened stiff fines in a case that was
already costing the state millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1987, at the request of Gov. William P. Clements,
Justice met at the Tyler courthouse with the governor, Attorney
General Jim Mattox, plaintiffs' attorneys and other prominent
players in the Ruiz case.
</P>
<P>
   Weiser, a clerk at the time, recalled that coffee was served on
Sue Justice's fine china, and that the meeting was cordial and
diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, Judge Justice was simply as gracious and well-mannered
as he would be to any visitor,'' said Weiser, who suggested that
Justice's good nature may have impressed state officials and ``kept
them from demonizing him so much in their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, the parties eventually worked toward settling
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Clements and a prison official who subsequently spoke at local
business gatherings acknowledged that Justice had prompted
corrections that Texas prisons needed, according to lawyers who
were there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really a very sincere person. I have no doubt that he
personally felt very keenly about the problems he saw in that
prison system and some of the things the prisoners were being
subjected to,'' said law school classmate Law, now a Fort Worth
attorney and, like Justice, a member of the Philosophical Society
of Texas. Organized by Sam Houston and others, the society brings
together judges, college presidents and other state leaders once a
year for a weekend of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to go down in history as a villain at all. He
will be recognized as a very sincere visionary.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Although Justice signed a final judgment in the Ruiz litigation
in 1992, he didn't bring an end to his jurisdiction over the case.
In May, Attorney General Dan Morales asked the judge to formally
end his supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Culberson and state Sen. Buster Brown, R-Lake Jackson, are also
seeking 5th Circuit permission to intervene and press for an end to
Justice's control of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased he is in Austin, where he can witness firsthand
how capable the people of Texas are through the Legislature of
governing the prisons ... without him in his ivory tower,''
Culberson said.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for Justice in the Capitol galleries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the separation of powers,'' he said. ``I will not
be over there superintending their operations.''
</P>
<P>
   In his new role, Justice will handle two-thirds of the docket
for the Del Rio federal court, a heavy load of cases involving
illicit drugs and undocumented immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who have watched Justice in court said he gives criminal
defendants a fair trial, listening carefully to the evidence. But
once a guilty verdict is returned, he's known for tough sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the first Justice sentencing she witnessed involved
a defendant convicted of defrauding a bank. The man ``had a teacher
wife and a 6-year-old kid, and the wife was crying in the audience,
and he put him away.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Justice said he believes that the proliferation of
drug cases in the courts has squeezed criminal defendants' rights
under the Fourth Amendment, which protects against unreasonable
searches, and the Fifth Amendment, which guarantees due process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts are tolerating searches and seizures now that they
would not have prior to the surge in drug usage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Each Friday, he plans to hold sentencing hearings by video
conference, a practice already being used in Del Rio. He'll travel
the 200-plus miles to the border city the last week of every month.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've given me more than a full caseload,'' Justice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to enjoy this. It's a new challenge. ... I'm
stimulated by it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
