<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LITWACK-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK, WHITE ALL LOST IN `JIM CROW' ERA, AUTHOR SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  ``Trouble in Mind: Black Southerners in the Age of Jim Crow''; by
Leon F. Litwack; (Knopf, $35.) 
 
By CELIA MORRIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leon F. Litwack, of all people, will appreciate the irony of a
spiffed-up ``Gone With the Wind's'' reissue some two months after
his magisterial ``Trouble in Mind'' arrived to haunt the nation's
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the period Litwack covers here, roughly 1890 to
1920, is rather later than the time in this old warhorse of a movie
_ perhaps the most famous ever made. For the book is a sequel to
his ``Been in the Storm So Long: The Aftermath of Slavery,'' which
won both the Pulitzer and the Parkman prizes and focused precisely
on those years when Scarlett was conniving never to be hungry again
and the glamorous Rhett Butler was amassing his fortune. But ``Gone
With the Wind'' may have done more than any other text to exalt and
preserve the myth of the glorious Old South _ a ``land of Cotton
and Cavaliers ... of Knights and his fair lady'' _ a myth Litwack
shows to have been a fantasy and a cheat.
</P>
<P>
   The chilling task Litwack set himself was to examine exactly
what white Southerners who considered themselves superior to blacks
did in the name of civilization to other human beings _ and how the
people they despised then managed, when they did manage, to resist
and ultimately to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Not that blacks were merely victims or whites merely
victimizers. ``But the extent and quality of the violence unleashed
on black men and women in the name of enforcing black deference and
subordination cannot be avoided or minimized,'' Litwack writes.
``The details make for unpleasant reading, sometimes stretching our
credulity, numbing the mind to the full extent of the horror, but
they must be examined if we are to understand how normal men and
women could live with, participate in, defend, even reinterpret
such atrocities, so they would not see themselves or be perceived
as less than civilized.''
</P>
<P>
   As a white woman, I read ``Trouble in Mind'' not only as an
exhaustive catalog of unspeakable cruelties inflicted on black
people but as a withering testimonial to the way whites crippled
themselves in the doomed attempt to demonstrate their innate
``superiority.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Litwack's major themes, in fact, is that it was not the
scum of the white South that behaved so barbarously but indeed the
``best'' people among them. Similarly, it was not the scum among
the blacks who truly frightened the powers-that-be but instead
those men and women who were the most intelligent, hard-working and
respectable.
</P>
<P>
   For the surrender at Appomatox did not compel white Southerners
to rethink the assumptions of racial superiority that led to such a
disastrous end; it merely strengthened their defiance. They went on
to twist their minds and spirits, canker their hearts and squander
their worldly goods in ultimately futile attempts to assert their
own power and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   From the first ship captains who delivered slaves to the
overwhelming majority of leading citizens for the next 250 years,
nobody seems to have thought beyond what they conceived to be their
own self-interest. No one adequately calculated the resources that
would be required to subjugate an entire race _ resources
financial, managerial, social, intellectual and spiritual. ``We're
bound to keep the nigger down,'' said a North Carolina registrar.
``It's all that saves us.'' But the cost proved astronomical and
bankrupted the region for generations.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Jim Crow'' era is that period in the South from the 1890s
on when blacks were separated and subordinated according to code,
custom and habit _ some of which we live with still.
</P>
<P>
   Though Litwack often draws on the work of distinguished black
writers like Richard Wright, Ralph Ellison and Zora Neale Hurston
who grew up in the South, ``Trouble in Mind'' is primarily an
account of ordinary black people and ``the story of what they
confronted, how they struggled, worked, tried to educate
themselves, and found ways to temper their accommodation to the new
racial order.'' Packing his book not only with facts and figures
but also with luminous stories, Litwack writes about virtually
everything that affected them.
</P>
<P>
   The Morrison Professor of American History at the University of
California at Berkeley, Litwack methodically investigates an
economy based on share-cropping _ a system that caught blacks in a
tangle of financial indebtedness that in effect substituted peonage
for slavery _ and a convict labor system that trapped and exploited
black men jailed for the merest infraction of law and not
infrequently for nothing at all. (Employers who leased convicts
often worked them to death, but they were easily replaced. In 1870,
for instance, 41 percent of Alabama's convicts died.)
</P>
<P>
   He documents conditions of black children's schooling so
pathetic that they made a mockery of education as well as the
American credo that anyone who works hard and perseveres will
succeed. He describes not only the daily indignities black people
faced but also a reign of terror that culminated in lynchings as
barbaric as anything in the Roman Colosseum when Christians were
fed to lions. (``Justified'' commonly by the need to protect ``the
chastity of white women'' from black men who might rape them,
lynching became so prevalent that between 1890 and 1917, according
to a conservative estimate, ``some two to three black Southerners
were hanged, burned at the stake or quietly murdered every week.'')
</P>
<P>
   Writing of jazz and the blues as authentic expressions of a
despised people and a land where ``the betrayal of expectations
became a way of life,'' he evokes the blight of hunger and the
feeling of helplessness.
</P>
<P>
   Read properly, ``Trouble in Mind'' is a profoundly humbling
experience. Despite the fact that it is numbingly repetitive, I
wager no one can take it up with an open mind and put it down
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The even tone contributes to its cumulative power, for Litwack
rejects rhetoric in favor of quiet proof. A Jew who doesn't scant
the evidence of black anti-Semitism, he triumphs over the brutality
of his material by the courage and integrity with which he
confronts it.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, he implicitly honors Richard Wright for his
``conviction that the meaning of living came only when one was
struggling to wring a meaning out of meaningless suffering.'' And
along the way, he indirectly teaches the rest of us something about
how to live.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
