<SLUG> BC-CIDER-THEATER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG `CIDER' MAY BE YOUR CUP OF TEA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; John Irving's novel ``The Cider House Rules'' is
high-cholesterol literature, a big, thick slab of marbled fiction
chock full of wacky characters, bizarro Dickensian subplots and
protein-enriched themes.
</P>
<P>
   It's also an epic-size slice of theater _ six hours' worth, plus
a dinner break _ in its current state at the Mark Taper Forum,
where it's running in two parts through Sept. 27. If theatergoing
were bodybuilding, the Taper would be this summer's answer to
Muscle Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Lovingly adapted by New York playwright Peter Parnell and
directed with maximum enthusiasm by Tom Hulce and Jane Jones, ``The
Cider House Rules'' employs 22 versatile actors portraying 120
characters. With more passion than economy, it recounts Irving's
popular, picaresque tale of a principled Maine country doctor,
Wilbur Larch (Michael Winters), his beloved protege, Homer Wells
(Josh Hamilton), and the moral quandary over abortion that
threatens to come between them.
</P>
<P>
   It's a massively eager-to-please show, and through its first
three or four hours, it keeps the audience rooting for the heroic
Wilbur and Homer as if they were Dickens' own David Copperfield (to
whom Homer is repeatedly compared).
</P>
<P>
   But although the production has slimmed down from its original
eight-hour Seattle debut, it still becomes something of an
endurance test as it winds into its final 1{ hours. The dialogue,
an otherwise effective blend of first-person character-speak and
third-person Irving-speak, begins to repeat itself. Some episodes
wander down narrative cul-de-sacs. A couple of tertiary characters
make token appearances, then virtually drop out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   Most crucially, the play _ like the book _ can't disguise the
reality that what Irving has to say about abortion, medical ethics
and other highfalutin themes is ultimately far less interesting and
complex than what he has to say about family ties, fatherly love,
adolescent lust (an Irving specialty) and the orphaned Homer's
obsessive desire ``to be of use.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, the adapters and the large ensemble remind us
that the novel's claim on our attention isn't its impressive
command of gynecological procedures, nor its characters' earnest
deliberation on when a fetus acquires a soul.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the novel's appeal lies in Irving's eye for the pathos
and slapstick of everyday life and in his knowing evocation of the
rugged Maine lifestyle, circa 1920-1960, and the flinty New England
moral temperament personified by Winters' noble, irascible Dr.
Larch.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of Irving's story involves Homer's understated love
for Dr. Larch (and vice versa), his quest for identity outside the
desolate Maine orphanage where he's raised, and the near-tragic
menage a trois he enters into in Part 2 with apple-orchard heir
Wally Worthington (Patrick Wilson) and Wally's salt-of-the-earth
fiancee, Candy (Myra Platt). The play loses steam whenever it
deserts these points and starts to sermonize, as it does in a
Brechtian aside on how to use a condom.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``The Cider House Rules'' succeeds on a number of
fronts, perhaps most in conveying its affection for Irving's book
and in its passionate conviction that rich, voluble novels and live
theater can enlarge the imagination like no other art forms.
</P>
<P>
   This is made clear from the opening scene in which a
dazed-looking Hamilton pops out from between a woman's parted legs
and launches into his moving portrayal of the young Homer Wells.
Adult actors playing newborn babes? Wait _ you ain't seen nothing
yet. In this energetic ensemble, men play little girls and a nurse
doubles as a prostitute. When the wind whips up outside the old
orphanage, the effect is supplied by heavy-breathing actors. When
snow is required, a cast member sprinkles down a handful from on
high. These poetic effects _ occasionally strained but mostly not _
enhance the production's considerable charm.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine landscape is beautifully rendered here by James F.
Ingalls rustic lighting and John Arnone's no-nonsense set, an
abstract cutaway of a Victorian orphanage that becomes a loggers'
bunkroom, a whorehouse or an apple orchard with the addition or
subtraction of a few benches and chairs. Dan Wheetman's bluegrassy
original music, performed by cast members, adds a lyrical layer to
Parnell's adaptation, which is sturdy and elegant when it isn't
preaching.
</P>
<P>
   The large cast is skillful and effective, particularly Winters,
Brenda Wehle and Jane Carr as Dr. Larch's steadfast nurses and
Jillian Armenante as Melony, the butch female orphan who introduces
Homer to the parallel worlds of lust and deception.
</P>
<P>
   All this makes the play a grandly engaging tour of its
novelistic namesake. Does that make it worth giving up a summer's
afternoon of waxing your surfboard?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is probably yes, especially if you're still undecided
whether abortion is a painful necessity or an abomination _ ``God's
work'' or ``the devil's work.'' ``The Cider House Rules'' spins a
terrific yarn around that terrifying question. But it also leaves
you wondering whether even Charles Dickens would need six hours to
untangle Irving's unsurprising answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
