<HEADLINE>
TANGLED WEB SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a snapshot of the most common Web site management and
development mistakes, according to Jakob Nielsen, who was in charge
of Web site testing at Palo Alto, Calif.-based Sun Microsystems
Inc. and has written two books on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not knowing why you are creating a Web site in the first
place: Most companies should start their Web design project by
finding out ways in which they can provide true customer value on
their site. Give users benefits from spending time on your site,
allow them to do business with you, and their money will follow.
</P>
<P>
   _ Designing for your own bosses: Internally-focused sites cause
companies to end up with home pages full of mission statements,
photos of the chief executive, and corporate history _ all of which
can fit on a single ``about this company'' page. The average
Internet user doesn't care about these things.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not getting your Web site tested to make sure it is
user-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Making the Web an extension of the company's marketing and
advertising program: The Web is a new new medium. Marketing and
advertising drive the viewer or reader's experience. But the viewer
drives his or her experience on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   _ Long download times: About 15 seconds is an acceptable period
of time to wait for a page to download on a computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Excessive animation: Too many moving objects on the screen
make it difficult for users to read text on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   _ Complex Web site addresses: Avoiding these minimizes the risk
of typographical errors, which keep users from downloading the
site.
</P>
<P>
   _ Asking users to scroll down a page: Only 10 percent of users
scroll beyond the information that is visible on the screen. All
critical content and navigating options should be on the top part
of the page.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forgetting to budget for Web site maintenance: As a rule of
thumb, the annual cost to maintain a site should be at least half
of what the company spent on developing the site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
