<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2541 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0714-C     07-13 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IMF, RUSSIA AGREE ON $17.1 BILLION BAILOUT
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Facing the prospects of financial disaster, Russia
obtained a crucial agreement Monday for a new $17.1 billion bailout
package from the International Monetary Fund and other lenders to
bolster its frail economy.
</P>
<P>
   The loan assurances over the next 18 months should allow
President Boris Yeltsin and his government to make payments on the
country's foreign debts and avert a potentially calamitous
devaluation of Russia's currency, the ruble, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The financing package, larger even than Russian officials had
hoped, also should restore investors' confidence in the fledgling
market economy, reeling from massive losses in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's lead negotiator, Anatoly Chubais, said the package
``signifies a restoration of faith in Russia's ability to overcome
its difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia already has existing loan agreements with the IMF and
others totaling $5.5 billion this year and next, bringing the sum
of the international bailout to $22.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF has linked the support to Russia's pledge that it will
enact long-overdue reforms to improve tax collections and lower its
budget deficit -- a huge task given the problem-plagued economy and
a Communist-dominated parliament which has balked at government
proposals to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement the IMF will provide an additional $11.6
billion, the World Bank will give $4 billion and Japan will put up
$1.5 billion -- for a total of $17.1 billion over the remainder of
this year and 1999, Chubais said. Russia could receive the first
installment, $5.6 billion, after the expected approval of the deal
by the IMF board on Monday (July 20).
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the new economic program, Russia's fiscal position is
being strengthened markedly,'' IMF Managing Director Michel
Camdessus said in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But the relief will forestall a financial crisis only for
several more months unless Russia fixes once and for all the
country's deep economic problems, warned a leading member of the
Russian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Zhukov, chairman of the tax and finance committee in
the Duma, said: ``If we do not do anything radical, this money will
quickly run out and we will have to borrow again.''
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of grinding negotiations, the IMF announcement
clearly demonstrated the willingness of the United States and other
major donor nations to continue backing Yeltsin, despite Russia's
lagging market reforms seven years after the fall of the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The size of the package shows strong confidence in Russia's
reform commitments and reflects strong support from the world
community,'' White House spokesman Michael McCurry said in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Russian stocks and bonds climbed Monday on rumors of the
announcement, which came as trading ended. The Russian stock index
gained 9.2 percent, its biggest one-day gain since June 2. Russia's
Eurobond posted its biggest one-day gain since it debuted in
November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economy began to dive last fall following onset of the
Asian financial crisis. It faced further pressure this year as
world prices for the country's main export, petroleum, fell and its
own tax collections were dismally short of what was needed to fully
finance the state budget.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Russian workers have not been paid for months. In
Moscow and throughout the country, protesters have shut down mines
and blocked the Trans-Siberian railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Yet throughout the scare, most ordinary Russians have been
largely immune from the tumult as the ruble has remained stable in
relation to the dollar and consumer prices have remained constant.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent a currency devaluation, which would drive prices up
and threaten Yeltsin's push for economic reforms, Russia's Central
Bank has been spending its hard-currency reserves to support the
ruble, which is trading at about 6.2 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But as a result, investor confidence in the Russian market
plummeted and the stock market has lost more than half its value
since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners have withdrawn about $8 billion from the Russian
equities market and about another $10 billion from government
securities since October 1997, Mikhail Alekseyev, deputy executive
chairman of Unexim Bank, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   In a gloomy assessment, Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko warned
parliament on Friday that social tensions were rising in Russia and
financial markets had ``practically ceased to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyenko traveled to Tokyo on Monday for talks in Japan on its
efforts to ease Russia's economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian analysts had predicted that a protracted fiscal
crisis would force Yeltsin from office and create political chaos.
On Friday, Yeltsin enigmatically warned of extremists trying to
overthrow him. He telephoned President Clinton and other Western
leaders to ask for their help in supporting a favorable bailout
package.
</P>
<P>
   Key to the IMF agreement were Russian assurances that the
Communist-controlled lower house of parliament, the Duma, would
approve the bulk of government-proposed measures to improve tax
collection and narrow the budget deficit, said John Odling-Smee,
the IMF's chief negotiator in the Russia talks.
</P>
<P>
   Odling-Smee said the IMF board would be unlikely to give its
approval to the package unless the Russian legislature supports the
reforms. The Duma, which already has passed some of the
government's legislation but has resisted other reforms, is
scheduled to reconvene on Wednesday and Thursday to consider the
remainder of the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as it is impossible to get out of the financial crisis
without a loan,'' said Zhukov, the tax and budget chairman, ``so it
is impossible to solve all the problems with the help of the
loan.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
