   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Tuesday, July 7. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) _ The Russian government and international
lenders concluded a landmark agreement Monday to calm Russia's
teetering financial markets and restore confidence in its economy.
By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Washington) _ Its financial strength depleted by
the Asian crisis, the IMF said Monday that it will have to borrow
from its richest members to pay for the bailout of Russia. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ Senior Japanese politicians began
jockeying Monday for the chance to play chief surgeon to the
world's second-largest economy, after Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto resigned to take responsibility for his party's
disastrous finish in parliamentary elections. By Nicholas D.
Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   With: JAPAN-REACT; JAPAN-U.S.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ After a week of
Protestant violence over the issue of patriotic parades through
Catholic neighborhoods, and the death of three young Catholic
brothers in an arson attack, tens of thousands of Orange Order
Protestants walked peacefully Monday in several hundred parades
throughout Northern Ireland. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL (Poughkeepsie, N.Y.) _ The Rev. Al Sharpton and
two legal advisers to Tawana Brawley were found liable of
defamation Monday for accusing a former prosecutor of assaulting
the black teen-ager in November 1987.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Flint, Mich.) _ Developments in the General Motors
strike. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-YORKER-EDITOR (New York) _ The New Yorker names a new
editor, David Remnick. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
