<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-DRUCKENMILL     07-13 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-DRUCKENMILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUCKENMILLER LIKES RIDING ON THE EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The 49ers' coaching staff put together a special
calendar for Jim Druckenmiller. They color-coded it for film study,
physical drills and weightlifting. They kept track of his every
footfall.
</P>
<P>
   The young quarterback showed up at team headquarters on weekday
mornings at 7:30, just as it said on the calendar. He went home to
visit his parents in Pennsylvania. The trip was on the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller may or may not be the centerpiece of the San
Francisco team's future, but he was absolutely the focus of the
offseason. His intensive extracurriculars, combined with the
signing of Ty Detmer as Steve Young's immediate backup, can be
interpreted a number of ways.
</P>
<P>
   In the eternally peptic guts of 49ers fans, Druckenmiller's
private boot camp is likely to register as remedial training and,
therefore, a sign of the franchise's imminent demise. In the more
generous view of offensive coordinator Marty Mornhinweg,
Druckenmiller has refined himself in the last few months, possibly
into the best quarterback prospect in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Mornhinweg recently received a ballot from the magazine Pro
Football Weekly, asking him to rank the youngsters. The candidates
included Ryan Leaf, Peyton Manning, Steve McNair and Jake Plummer.
Mornhinweg, guaranteed anonymity in the poll, could have safely
raved about someone else's quarterback. He wrote in Druckenmiller's
name and rated him No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's come a long way,'' Mornhinweg said. ``He's quickened his
release up, and he's more consistent with his accuracy when he
throws the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also packed away his Harley-Davidson motorcycle,
foresworn further appearances on the Howard Stern show and vowed
never again to miss a team flight. At times during his rookie
season, the first-round draft pick behaved like a stray puppy let
loose in the 49ers' locker room, oblivious to the protocol of the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little bit nuts,'' Druckenmiller said. ``I think we
all realized Jim was being young and stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   He was on his cellular phone when he said that, taking a trip to
the beach with a friend in Florida. His coaches had let him go
until the start of training camp. He laughed a lot as he talked and
seemed to be having fun. Then again, Druckenmiller always seems to
be having fun. That quality cost him a lot of money in fines last
year, but it could also be an asset.
</P>
<P>
   Even when he irritated his coaches last year, he made them
laugh. They couldn't help it. He was so brazenly goofy. He was
never self-conscious or timid. He rode the Harley right onto the
set of a local sports television show.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing that was conduct detrimental to the team,''
coach Steve Mariucci said. ``And he was always working hard. I
don't want people to think he was a party animal. But you want to
nip these things in the bud. I was kind of happy that when he was
late for that flight, because he was out getting a pizza (on orders
from Steve Young and Jeff Brohm), that we just left without him. We
didn't wait one second.''
</P>
<P>
   Mornhinweg points out that he and Mariucci worked with Brett
Favre and Jim McMahon in Green Bay. They are accustomed to
quarterbacks with wild streaks.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller said he gorged on the freedom that came with being
a professional. He was accustomed to round-the-clock monitoring at
Virginia Tech, where players lived together, ate together, rode
buses to every destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, in the NFL, the attitude is: `You've got a mind,
you've got to use it,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At times last year, he couldn't do that. His mind had barely
been introduced to the 49ers' offense. During the St. Louis game,
which he won as an emergency starter, he threw some routes he had
never attempted in practice. The offseason training allowed him to
absorb more of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, I think I'm more attuned, and I think I look more
comfortable because of that,'' he said. ``Physically, I loosened
up. Before, I was a little tight. I think I was more robotic.''
</P>
<P>
   If he interpreted the Detmer signing as a slight, Druckenmiller
hides it well. Either he had learned advanced diplomacy in a hurry
or he really doesn't feel threatened. He talks about how much he
can learn from the new backup, a former Mariucci protege. In
minicamp, Young and Detmer were both allowed to leave early, but
Detmer kept coming to practices anyway, in street clothes, to watch
and advise Druckenmiller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ty's one of the smartest quarterbacks in the NFL,''
Druckenmiller said. ``Everybody says that.''
</P>
<P>
   The offseason training didn't faze him, either. He is not, he
said, easily frustrated. He expects his job to be difficult. It
always has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go to prep school for a year before college,'' he
said. ``Virginia Tech was the only college that offered me a
scholarship. When I got there, there were 11 quarterbacks on the
team. ... I'm used to adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The prep school that took Druckenmiller was Fork Union Military
Academy, hardly the kind of place that breeds Harley-riding guest
stars for Howard Stern. Druckenmiller hated the place, the
saluting, the uniforms. They took his civilian clothes and locked
them up for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I cried myself to sleep every night until
Thanksgiving,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the 49ers' calendar probably seemed comforting. He
felt a little isolated at times, working only with Mornhinweg or
assistant coach Greg Knapp, without teammates around him. He took
endless grief from the other players for missing the flight to New
Orleans, but he also leaned on certain veterans. On the flights he
did make, Druckenmiller always made a point to sit near linebacker
Ken Norton Jr., a valued mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Left with the coaches, Druckenmiller managed to have a little
fun. In the spring, he told them that his girlfriend, a model, had
helped set him up with agents who wanted him to appear in a Calvin
Klein underwear ad. He said the billboards would go up in San
Francisco about the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller winked at Mornhinweg as he told the tale, but he
let Mariucci believe that his second-year quarterback, with one
just win on his resume, had Broadway Joe on the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just put his head in his hands,'' Druckenmiller said.
</P>
<P>
   That was a great moment for him. It proved that he didn't have
to be tame to be in control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1633EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
