<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2586 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABIOLA-COMMENTARY-840     07-13 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABIOLA-COMMENTARY-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO WOULD HAVE BEEN KING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: What we do know about Moshood Abiola is that he
was a self-made millionaire and an amazingly talented politician.
What we will never know, in the wake of his death, is whether he
could have been Nigeria's Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Lagos airport was eerily efficient that February morning in 1993
when I returned to Africa after an eight-year absence. Customs and
immigration were a snap, and my party of three was ushered through
so quickly that a promised ride hadn't shown up.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, while standing on an outside curb, we were swept up in
an impromptu demonstration of people shouting, ``A-bee-oh-la!
A-bee-oh-la!'' And somehow we met the object of the chants: a
short, stout man with a wide grin who breezily shook our hands and
asked the reason for our trip. When told we were spending a month
giving seminars to working journalists around the country, he said,
``I'm president of the publishers' association, and I must give a
banquet in your honor.''
</P>
<P>
   That was our introduction to Moshood Abiola, a self-made
millionaire who was soon to be a presidential candidate. He kept
his promise and threw a luncheon for us; later, he took me on a
breathless, 19-hour tour of the country where, between audiences
with feudal nobles and soccer players, we talked at length about
his life.
</P>
<P>
   His remarkable journey ended this past week when Abiola, after
four years of confinement, died of what was described as a heart
attack while meeting with senior American diplomats. He was 60.
With his death, many analysts agreed, Nigeria lost a leader who had
the rare ability to appeal to all quarters of a land divided by
religious, ethnic and north-south rivalries. A Muslim from the
southeastern Yoruba tribe in a nation traditionally ruled by Muslim
northerners, his dynamic personality and decades of public
philanthropy won him support from all regions.
</P>
<P>
   In Zaria, a northern city where an emir still wields influence,
I watched Abiola pay his respects to the traditional Muslim elite
and to the turbanned horseman who succeeded to an old hereditary
title. He pointedly reminded northerners that he owns thousands of
acres of farmland in the region and therefore shares their
interests and concerns. On a continent rife with linguistic and
tribal antagonisms, Abiola sought to persuade them to see him for
what he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought 10,000 hectares here. I have given scholarships all
over the north,'' Abiola, up since 6 a.m., said at a stop shortly
before midnight. ``I have helped bury your dead, sang when you were
happy. I expect to be welcomed in every village in Nigeria. I am
one of you, isn't that right?''
</P>
<P>
   At another stop, I watched as he met members of his tribe
resettled in the north. After exhorting them to become active in
their adopted communities, Abiola led them in the Fatiyah, a Muslim
prayer, although many were Christian. Then, without missing a beat,
he led all in the Lord's Prayer. In my four years in Africa, I had
never seen a politician so adroitly ecumenical and charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from politics, Abiola had struck a chord across the
continent and many parts of the African diaspora by leading an
international campaign for reparations from former slave-owning and
trading nations, as well as for an apology from the United Nations
for centuries of bondage. In Nigeria, he had practically invented
large-scale philanthropy, underwriting schools, scholarships and
soccer organizations throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of American had known nothing of this man whose name
has been flashed on the TV screens, a man who has been compared to
South Africa's Nelson Mandela but never got the opportunity to
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Abiola had meant nothing to me before I landed that
day in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Moshood Kashimawo Olawale Abiola was the 23rd child born to a
produce buyer who had lost most of his offspring in infancy. This
led his father to name him ``Kashimawo,'' Yoruba for ``Let us see
if this one survives.'' Abiola worked his way through the Baptist
Boys School by selling firewood and leading a dance band in which
he played banjo and talking drums. Graduation required writing a
Baptist hymn. The Muslim youth not only wrote one but also penned
others for Christian classmates _ for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   An academic standout, he went on to Scotland to study. ``I
wanted accounting _ the science of moneymaking,'' Abiola joked
between renditions of Elvis songs and, incongruously or not, gospel
tunes. ``If you are a poor man's son, you want to identify the
jingling sound of money. From the age of 9, I've been working.''
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying as a chartered accountant, equivalent to a certified
public accountant in the United States, he worked for a hospital
and a drug firm. In 1967 he joined ITT, working his way up the
corporate ladder to vice president, responsible for Africa and the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The story behind his meteoric rise is that after collecting a
long-standing debt from the Nigerian army's signal corps, he
telephoned his foreign bosses with the good news. Back at the
office, he was shocked to find them partying to the point of being
hog-whimpering drunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a picture of everyone drunk and sent it to ITT
headquarters,'' he told me. The snapshot went off with a memo: As a
devout Muslim, how could he work with such men?
</P>
<P>
   Abiola then set up his own electronics business, signing big
contracts with the military, until ITT accepted his terms _ putting
him in charge in Nigeria and selling him a hefty stake in the local
subsidiary, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's how I became the first African managing director of
a multinational corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   From ITT Nigeria, he went on to become a major shareholder in
Volkswagen Nigeria; an oil-production firm; a large baking concern;
a mammoth corn and sorghum farm; an airline; and a publishing
house, which included newspapers, magazines and a chain of
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his life, he was hardly considered a critic of the
military. In 1992, he made a bended-knee apology to the ruling
general after the regime closed Abiola's news weekly, African
Concord, for saying that the military was badly managing the
economy, which was largely true. A crew of editors protested the
apology by quitting and then started a competing magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Some questioned the sources of his wealth. Apart from his
military links, Abiola's various other dealings have raised
concerns, said diplomats in West Africa. But compared with many in
Nigeria's civilian and military governments, Abiola was seen as a
``clean'' politician by ordinary Nigerians whom I randomly
interviewed five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   During his presidential race, he campaigned on an
anti-corruption theme, saying that because he was already rich, he
needed no favors, bribes or even the ``gift'' of a jetliner. He
flew in a craft built for Queen Elizabeth II that was considered
too big for the monarch. ``I don't owe any man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Abiola the apparent winner of the 1993 poll, the military
regime annulled the election result. He was arrested after
declaring himself president and had been kept for most of the past
four years in solitary confinement at a government guest house near
the capital of Abuja. His family says he was not given adequate
medical care for his high blood pressure. After one of his wives
publicly protested the conditions, she was assassinated on a Lagos
street.
</P>
<P>
   Born into poverty, Abiola acquired 140 honorary titles during
his 60 years, including field marshal of Ibadanland, a main Yoruba
area. He amassed a fortune and, according to a Who's Who of
Nigeria, fathered ``many children.'' But his empire had withered
during the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   And now we will never know how well Abiola might have led his
fractious but potentially rich nation.
</P>
<P>
   (Barry Shlachter is a reporter for the Fort Worth STar-Telegram.
He was a foreign correspondent who covered Asia and Africa for The
Associated Press in the 1980s. His e-mail address is
barrs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
