<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    US, BRITAIN SIGN DRUG INTERDICTION AGREEMENT FOR CARIBBEAN
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and Britain signed an agreement
Monday allowing the U.S. Coast Guard and the Royal Navy to
permanently collaborate on drug interdiction efforts in national
and international waters in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will allow U.S. Coast Guard and Royal Navy
personnel to serve aboard both country's ships for counter-drug
operations in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Once only a temporary arrangement between the two countries, the
agreement means drug traffickers will not be able to escape pursuit
by U.S. or British vessels by crossing into the territorial waters
of the other country.
</P>
<P>
   The signing ceremony was held in the ornate Treaty Room of the
U.S. State Department. Baroness Symons, parliamentary
undersecretary at the British Foreign and Commonwealth Office, said
that as the mother of a teenage son, she knows the dangers of drugs
and sees the agreement as a way of helping to fight them.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Anthony Tangeman of the U.S. Coast Guard said he viewed
the agreement as ``another step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, under the temporary arrangement between the two
countries, the Royal Navy's West Indies Guardship and the U.S.
Coast Guard confiscated drugs with a street value of $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
