<HEADER>
A2611 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HYPERTENSION-DIET     07-13 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HYPERTENSION-DIET-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MILD HYPERTENSION, HEALTHIER DIET MAY BE GOOD MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 (With SCI-HYPERTENSION and SCI-HYPERTENSION-FDR)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For people with high blood pressure who hate to take pills,
recent studies have offered good news: changes in daily routine can
lower blood pressure enough to let some people with mild
hypertension postpone the need for medicine or avoid it altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstering previous research, new experiments suggest that
people who can lose excess weight, exercise regularly and limit
alcohol to a drink or two a day can sometimes lower their readings
enough to stay off drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting salt may also help some patients. Blacks and older
people seem to be most sensitive to salt, but there is no simple
test to tell who benefits from abstaining. Most salt in the
American diet comes from bread and processed foods, and many
doctors advise patients to cut back and see whether it helps.
</P>
<P>
   Guidelines issued in November by the National High Blood
Pressure Education Program, part of the National Institutes of
Health, said people with mild hypertension should try life style
changes for six to 12 months and resort to drugs only if the
changes do not work.
</P>
<P>
   Research since then has supported that recommendation, at least
in the elderly, more than two-thirds of whom are afflicted by
hypertension. In a study published in the Journal of the American
Medical Association in March, some people age 60-80 got off blood
pressure medication by losing 8 to 10 pounds and limiting their
salt intake to 1,800 milligrams of sodium a day, instead of the
4,000 milligrams that most Americans eat (sodium is the ingredient
in table salt that is linked to higher blood pressure).
</P>
<P>
   After two and a half years, the study found, those who changed
their habits were 53 percent less likely to have high blood
pressure or need medicine than those who did not change. The people
who made changes also had fewer heart attacks and strokes. People
who either lost weight or reduced salt, but did not do both, were
30 percent less likely to need medicine. About 30 percent of those
who changed their habits were able to stay off medication after the
study ended.
</P>
<P>
   The study's director, Dr. Paul Whelton, dean of the school of
public health and tropical medicine at Tulane University, in New
Orleans, said the study's high rate of success was at least partly
linked to the age of the participants and their desire to avoid
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were older people, 60-80, and at that age range you're
seeing illness around you,'' Whelton said. ``They're well-motivated
to maintain sodium restriction and weight loss.''
</P>
<P>
   But some doctors wonder whether the findings can be applied to
real life, because people in the study received a good deal of help
from exercise and nutrition counselors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life style modification doesn't work for most people,'' said
Dr. Michael Alderman, professor of medicine and epidemiology at
Albert Einstein College of Medicine in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a nasty little secret,'' he added. ``Either they can't
do it, or they do it, and it doesn't work. You spend six months
beating them on the head, and it makes them feel that if they
either tried harder or were better human beings it would have
worked.'' Some patients get so discouraged that they quit treatment
altogether; others wind up needing medication anyway, Alderman
said.
</P>
<P>
   He prefers to start patients on medication right away, he said,
and if they want to avoid the pills and try lifestyle changes
first, he tries to talk them out of it.
</P>
<P>
   But even doctors who scoff at life style change seem willing to
give points to a plan known as Dietary Approaches to Stop
Hypertension, the first diet to be recommended by the National High
Blood Pressure Education Program.
</P>
<P>
   The diet does not require people to lose weight, avoid salt or
liquor or count cholesterol. It adds foods instead of taking them
away. Specifically, it requires eating eight to 10 servings a day
(about 5 cups) of fruits and vegetables and 3 cups of low-fat dairy
foods, about twice what most Americans consume. But the diet has
less fat than the usual American diet: 26 percent of its calories
come from fat, rather than the usual 37 percent, and all the
reduction is in artery-clotting saturated fat. It is the same sort
of diet that some experts believe helps prevent cancer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Alderman calls the diet doable but says it has not been around
long enough for researchers to determine whether it can prevent
heart attacks and strokes over the long run.
</P>
<P>
   The regimen was tested last year for eight weeks in 459 adults,
including 133 with mild hypertension. Researchers provided all
meals to make sure that everyone ate the correct diet. People with
normal blood pressure experienced a slight drop from the diet, but
those with hypertension had bigger drops, an average of 11.5/5.5
millimeters _ as much as treatment with a single drug usually
achieves. Results among blacks were better than those among whites.
</P>
<P>
   People with very high blood pressure who try the diet would
almost certainly still need medicines, but the diet could help
drugs work better and may allow doses to be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Why does the diet work? Dr. Frank Sacks, a professor of
nutrition at the Harvard School of Public Health who helped set up
the study, said: ``I think the high potassium content of the diet
pretty much explains why it lowers blood pressure. It's half or
more of the effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Calcium and magnesium also probably play a role, but potassium
seems especially important, Sacks said. Fruits, vegetables and milk
are all rich in potassium, and the diet provides 4,400 milligrams
of the mineral a day, about the amount in 11 bananas.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say they believe that potassium lowers blood pressure by
relaxing the arteries and by countering the effects of salt. And,
surveys show that blacks, who tend to have more blood pressure
problems than whites, consume less potassium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potassium might foster sodium excretion from the body,'' Sacks
said, adding that it also lowers blood pressure within the kidney.
In addition, some studies have shown that people who eat
high-potassium diets have fewer strokes than those who do not,
although people with kidney failure and those taking certain drugs
must avoid potassium.
</P>
<P>
   Whelton said, ``Potassium seems much more effective in people
who have more sodium in their diet. In people who have trouble
following sodium reduction, potassium gives you some backup.'' It
seems to help the body rid itself of excess water and salt, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For patients who will not eat vegetables, Sacks said, doctors
should consider potassium supplements. Yet few doctors prescribe
potassium to treat hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason,'' Sacks said, ``is that the science hasn't been so
firmly established until the last several years, and also not so
widely publicized.''
</P>
<P>
   A new study of the diet is trying to determine whether a
low-sodium version yields any added benefit. Because of their
higher sensitivity to salt, blacks will make up half the study's
participants. Results are expected in two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
