<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GAMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY'S MULAN GAME HAS 'EM CLICKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As sure as that big avalanche swept away the Huns
in ``Mulan,'' Disney has come up with a computer program based on
the hit animated film that should carry away your kids.
</P>
<P>
   Like every other major animated film Disney has released in
recent years, the company has come out with an ``animated
storybook'' for ``Mulan.'' And like many of those previous efforts,
it's well-done and should find favor throughout the 5- to
9-year-old set it's targeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan'' is based on a Chinese fable about a girl who disguises
herself as a warrior to replace her ailing father when a Hun
invasion forces the Chinese government to conscript soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The game centers around Mushu, the goofy supernatural dragon in
the film voiced by Eddie Murphy, as he tries to retrieve a series
of magic scrolls that he's accidentally dropped throughout the
film's main sites.
</P>
<P>
   The storybook tells Mulan's tale well enough, with lots of
small, interactive moments for children to play as they go.
</P>
<P>
   But probably the greater strength of the program, what allows
children such as my 6- and 7-year-old to keep playing and playing
are several other nifty features.
</P>
<P>
   There's a dress-up room where Mulan can try clothing,
hairstyles, shoes and accessories from various Chinese dynasties. A
click of a button allows children to print out clothing that can be
colored and used on two included paper dolls.
</P>
<P>
   The storybook also includes three playable videos of musical
scenes from the movie and displays the lyrics karaoke-style as they
play. For my children, that was big fun as they used the videos to
rehearse their own personal performances.
</P>
<P>
   And the storybook includes several games, including a matching
game using mah-jongg tiles similar to the longtime shareware
program Shanghai. Another game requires players to trace a route
across a mountainside, picking up gear before a length of rope runs
out.
</P>
<P>
   My children and a younger playmate gave the storybook two
decided thumbs up, and repeatedly asked to play it over several
days _ always a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   The game runs on both Macs and PCs and proved a breeze to set up
on either kind of machine.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. IN A BOX?: Care to monopolize the time of friends and
out-of-town visitors, and do it in an L.A. way that doesn't include
talking about how your latest script is in turnaround?
</P>
<P>
   Try Los Angeles in a Box, a Monopoly-based game from Late for
the Sky Production Co. in Cincinnati. If you know the old stalwart,
you basically know Los Angeles in a Box, though there are plenty of
cute, localized changes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Community Chest and Chance, the game has Big Fun! and
Contingency cards. Instead of Jail, it has a traffic-jam corner.
And instead of houses and apartments, it has Skyline sections and
Keys to the City. And instead of railroads and utilities, it sells
major thoroughfares such as Sunset Boulevard and vital
accouterments such as sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   In true Los Angeles-sprawl fashion, the game lets you plant
high-rises all over town as you acquire property. And the city of
Los Angeles is defined loosely, here including such regional
attractions as the Santa Monica Pier, Pasadena's Rose Bowl and
Inglewood's Great Western Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and for conspiracy-minded San Fernando Valley secessionists,
there's more reason for outrage at the downtown hegemonists: ``The
Valley,'' all of it, costs just $90 to buy. Spago, meanwhile, goes
for $190, and Hollywood, in all its faded, tinseled deterioration,
for $375.
</P>
<P>
   At least the La Brea Tar Pits go for less.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
