<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORIC-TREASURES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON TOURS HISTORICAL SITES TO PROMOTE PRESERVATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, starting a four-day tour to
promote historical preservation, announced Monday that designer
Ralph Lauren's company has donated $10 million to restore the Star
Spangled Banner, the flag that inspired Francis Scott Key to write
the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   The gift from Polo Ralph Lauren Corp. is the largest corporate
donation ever received by the Smithsonian Institution, which owns
the National Museum of American History where the flag is on
display.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren, chairman of the corporation, added $3 million of his own
money to help pay for education programs for Mrs. Clinton's ``Save
America's Treasures'' initiative that seeks to preserve American
history and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said Lauren gave the money in response to President
Clinton's 1998 State of the Union address asking for help in
restoring American historical artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   In thanking Lauren, the First Lady said: ``People say something
is very `Ralph Lauren' if it has a certain American style or
design. Perhaps after today, it will also come to symbolize ...
good citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   The president joined his wife at the history museum, the first
stop of her 10-site tour that is billed as a drive to restore
historical artifacts, buildings and monuments around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised the planned repair of the historic flag and
offered his encouragement to preservation efforts around the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every community in this country has a piece of itself that
must endure,'' he added. ``Americans need to know the stories.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-by-34-foot flag was made of wool bunting in 1813 by Mary
Pickersgill of Baltimore and was flown over Fort McHenry in
Baltimore, Md., on Sept. 13-14, 1814, during the War of 1812.
</P>
<P>
   During the British bombardment on the morning of Sept. 14, Key,
a lawyer, had gone out to the British fleet to obtain the release
of a prisoner but was prevented from returning to shore. At
approximately 7 a.m., he saw the flag flying from the fort and was
inspired to scribble the words to the poem that he would later set
to music. This song became the official national anthem in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   The flag will undergo repairs for the next three years at a
conservation laboratory in the museum at a cost of about $18
million to fix the damage from light, pollution and oxygen. The
restoration work will be visible to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew Charitable Trusts of Philadelphia announced a $5 million
gift for the project in February. Gifts from the John S. and James.
L. Knight Foundation and the Veterans of Foreign War will also
assist in the conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Describing her four-day tour of threatened historical sites,
Mrs. Clinton said: ``We are the caretaker's of our past. We have a
responsibility to future generations to be good ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   After the announcement ceremony at the Smithsonian, Mrs. Clinton
traveled to Baltimore where she announced a project to repair
outdoor monuments in Baltimore, including the Francis Scott Key
monument.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the rest of her schedule:
</P>
<P>
   _ TUESDAY: 9 a.m. Thomas Edison National Historic Site/Invention
Factory, West Orange, N.J. The site needs funds to preserve
artifacts and notes from Edison's laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   1 p.m. George Washington's Revolutionary War Headquarters,
Newburgh, N.Y. Washington stayed here for over 16 months during the
war. The site needs extensive repair.
</P>
<P>
   4:30 p.m. The Colonial Theater in Pittsfield, Mass. Once the
host to famous entertainers including Sara Bernhardt, John Philip
Sousa and Rachmaninoff, the theater, built in 1903, is currently a
paint store. The theater is in need of refurbishment so it can be
used as a performance space once again.
</P>
<P>
   _ WEDNESDAY: 9:30 a.m. Kate Mullany House, Troy, N.Y. Mullany
was one of the earliest leaders of the women's movement in the
United States; she organized an all-female union in the 1860s.
</P>
<P>
   1:50 p.m. Harriet Tubman's house in Auburn, N.Y., where Tubman
assisted runaway slaves in the Underground Railroad movement.
</P>
<P>
   4 p.m. Ganondagan State Historic Site, in Victor, N.Y. Buildings
here dedicated to the Iroquois heritage need to be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   6 p.m. McClintock House in Waterloo, N.Y. Mrs. Clinton will
visit the Women's Rights National Historical Park which contains
several houses important to the fight for women's rights.
</P>
<P>
   _ THURSDAY: Seneca Falls, N.Y. Mrs. Clinton will end her tour on
Thursday with a speech in Seneca, where women gathered in 1848 in
the Women's Rights Convention to proclaim their equality with men
in the treatise, ``The Declaration of Sentiments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
