<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN SHINES ON FRANCE'S NATIONAL HEROES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It rained here on Monday morning, and after France's
convincing 3-0 victory in the World Cup final the previous evening,
it was not surprising that some discouraged Brazilian fans
maintained that the precipitation in Paris was the tears of their
people falling from above.
</P>
<P>
   But by early afternoon the sky had cleared, and the members of
the French team, who had played with such precision and speed on
the field, took a more leisurely journey in an open bus up the
Champs-Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd estimated at 500,000 pressed as close to the vehicle as
police would allow as it crawled toward the Place de l'Etoile, and
on this joyous day it was difficult not to notice that the Arc de
Triomphe bore a certain resemblance to a soccer goal as it lay in
wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our biggest source of pride is to have created a sense
of communion with the French people,'' said French coach Aime
Jacquet. ``I think they identified with this team. We put France in
the street and for a good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than a million people in the streets of Paris on
Sunday night and millions more engaging in public displays of joy
and affection elsewhere in France, this was the biggest spontaneous
celebration in this nation of 58 million since Liberation in 1944.
There is no debating the relative importance of the two events, but
there is no question that the traditional Bastille Day celebrations
on Tuesday will seem like an anticlimax.
</P>
<P>
   France, no traditional sports power, now is in temporary
possession of the most prestigious trophy in sport. They won the
16th World Cup by outscoring the opposition 15 goals to two and, in
keeping with a competition that had no defining moment or player,
they relied on a different hero in nearly every match.
</P>
<P>
   France is the first host nation to win the Cup since Argentina
in 1978, but if it benefited from the snowballing support of its
usually reticent populace it did not benefit from favoritism from
the referees. Zinedine Zidane, who scored two goals against Brazil,
had to miss two games after receiving a red card for stepping on a
Saudi Arabian player. Star defender Laurent Blanc had to miss the
final after receiving a red card for a foul that Croatian defender
and part-time thespian Slaven Bilic made look like a crime against
humanity. Another vital French defender, Marcel Desailly, had to
miss the last 22 minutes of the final after being sent off with a
second yellow card.
</P>
<P>
   The referees in this World Cup often ruled with a heavy hand,
sending mixed signals but often deciding outcomes. New FIFA
president Sepp Blatter has made it clear that he wants to improve
their efficiency by making them professionals and using only the
best referees, regardless of nationality, in future World Cups. But
Desailly's departure on Sunday would not change the outcome of the
most lopsided World Cup final since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has stood in a line in France recently can confirm
that individualism still has a pride of place in this society, but
in the sporting arena the French clearly have learned to work well
together. The inferiority complex that used to afflict French
athletes with regularity on the biggest stages is becoming part of
the past along with the beret and bidet.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being content to have surprised their nation by
reaching the first World Cup final in French history, Jacquet's
team played with enough energy and sang-froid to make it seem as if
they not the disoriented Brazilians were the perennial soccer
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, it all felt very normal,'' said French
goalkeeper Fabien Barthez. ``On the morning of the match, we really
believed that nothing bad could happen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   That state of mind is a tribute to the fact that the top French
players, unlike some French companies, have thoroughly embraced
open markets, leaving home for better salaries to test themselves
against the best competition available in the Italian, Spanish,
English and German leagues. It is also a tribute to Jacquet and his
steady, consistently communicative leadership style. Jacquet was
widely criticized in France for his defensive mindset and lack of
charisma, but the man known as ``Meme'' ended up making nearly
everyone happy in France, even his least favorite newspaper
L'Equipe, with which he has clashed frequently but which had one of
its best-selling days in history the morning after the French
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Le Monde, in a front-page editorial on Monday, wondered whether
Jacquet and his emphasis on virtues such as inclusion,
industriousness and collectivism could serve as ``a parable'' for a
country reputed to be ``tired and sclerotic.''
</P>
<P>
   Reforming mentalities in France is certainly a bigger job than
leading 22 players, but Jacquet confirmed on Monday that he will
resign his post because he and his team had accomplished what they
had set out to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he showed all along the way that he made the right
decisions,'' said defender Bixente Lizarazu.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was to emphasize loyalty. Lizarazu missed much of
last season with a leg injury after transferring to Bayern Munich
in Germany, but Jacquet told him that if he could get back into the
Munich lineup, he would still have his place with the national
team. Lizarazu did so this spring, and was excellent in France this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Striker Christophe Dugarry struggled for the last two seasons
after leaving Bordeaux for AC Milan and then FC Barcelona, but he
kept Jacquet's faith and in spite of considerable criticism at
home, Jacquet included him on the team. Dugarry responded by
scoring the first French goal of the World Cup against South
Africa. Midfielder Christian Karembeu was out of action for nearly
all of last year because of a transfer dispute with his Italian
club Sampdoria, but after Karembeu finally managed to make his way
to Real Madrid in late December, Jacquet reinserted the fleet and
aggressive player in his lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Karembeu already had helped set one massive celebration in
motion in May after Real Madrid won the Champions' League title. On
Sunday, Karembeu helped ignite another popular explosion of joy,
but the place that probably took the most delight in his
performance was his home of New Caledonia in the South Pacific. The
age of traditional colonialism is over, but the sun did not set
easily on the French victory celebrations on Sunday. Along with New
Caledonia, there was Thuram's native Guadeloupe; Desailly's native
Ghana; and Zidane's humble community of La Castellane in the
northern reaches of Marseilles.
</P>
<P>
   There was also Clairefontaine, the French national team
headquarters south of Paris where the players returned at 3 a.m. on
Monday morning. They celebrated in private, but even those without
invitations who were standing outside the gates could see the
fireworks display the team had planned in case of victory. The 16th
World Cup was over, but the communion was not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
