<HEADLINE>
FIVE KEY ISSUES HEADING INTO 49ERS CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Six months after falling to the Green Bay
Packers in last season's NFC Championship Game, the 49ers face this
question as this season approaches: What's it going to take to
improve?
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers had established almost everything possible going into
their final game of the 1997 season _ home-field advantage, a
healthy Steve Young, a hungry veteran team. The only thing they
were missing was injured star receiver Jerry Rice.
</P>
<P>
   However, even his presence probably wouldn't have prevented
Green Bay's victory that day. The 49ers vanished from the Super
Bowl picture for the third consecutive year, and left knowing
something had to change. What they had clearly wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   The offseason, as a result, featured a flurry of changes. Key
veterans from last year's team (Gary Plummer, Brent Jones, William
Floyd) are gone. Younger established players arrived through free
agency while unproven ones will have their chances to contribute
more often this season.
</P>
<P>
   The faces have changed some on the 49ers. What hasn't been
altered is their attitude. They finished 13-3 in head coach Steve
Mariucci's first season, but what they remember most is how the
Packers knocked them around Candlestick Park in January.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of reasons to expect the 49ers to contend for a
Super Bowl spot again this season. But when they open their new
training camp in Stockton on Friday, the Niners will understand the
issues that must be resolved for them to maintain their place among
the NFL's best. These are the five biggest:
</P>
<P>
   KNEES: Until they play in a game, there will be endless
questions about the health of Rice, offensive lineman Harris Barton
and defensive end Gabe Wilkins, each of whom underwent knee
operations in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rice has said he'll be ready for this season, and his doctors
agree. If Barton, an 11-year veteran who missed all of 1997, can
return, he will add much needed experience and versatility to the
offensive line. Wilkins signed a $20 million free-agent deal in
February but his knee problem, which is similar to Barton's in
complexity, already has forced the team to keep Chris Doleman _ the
man Wilkins was supposed to succeed. The 49ers hope Wilkins will be
at full strength by the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSIVE LINE: The inside is solid here, with center Chris
Dalman flanked by Ray Brown and Pro Bowl selection Kevin Gogan at
guards. It's at tackle where the stability must be settled. With
the retirement of Kirk Scrafford, Derrick Deese moves from left to
right tackle. The team acquired Jamie Brown, a reserve in Denver
last season, and gave him Deese's old job. There isn't much proven
depth after the starting five, which is why quarterback Young said
he'll monitor this group's development.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE LINE: Dana Stubblefield took his 15 sacks and inside
dominance to Washington in February, leaving Junior Bryant, who
rotated with Stubblefield and Bryant Young last season, as the man
on the spot. He's about 15 pounds lighter than Stubblefield, but
he's also a fine fundamental player. The 49ers hope to find a solid
third tackle to take Bryant's old position. Wilkins' injury has
given Doleman a chance to keep his job, one he handled well last
season (12 sacks).
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING GAME: Garrison Hearst enjoyed his best year last season,
running for 1,019 yards and balancing out the offense. But there
will be more pressure on him this year. Terry Kirby is gone, and
there's no legitimate backup. Fullback is more of a question. The
team didn't re-sign Floyd, who moved on to Carolina, and Marc
Edwards is entering his second year. Mariucci already has indicated
one-back formations will be utilized more often this season.
</P>
<P>
   NEW FACES: For a team that didn't have much salary-cap room
entering the free-agent market, the 49ers operated like an
organization that missed the playoffs by one game instead of the
Super Bowl. They signed linebacker Winfred Tubbs from New Orleans
to replace Plummer. Wilkins came a few days later, around the same
time as another former Saint, tight end Irv Smith, who will try to
make people forget Jones' consistency. Add in cornerback Antonio
Langham, who takes over for Rod Woodson on the left side, and the
team has turned much younger in each of those positions. All they
have to do now is prove that youth translates into improvement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
