<HEADLINE>
ONCE ALMOST EXTINCT, FALCONS AGAIN FLY OVER NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Md., Wash., Mass., Ill., Ont.)  (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the canyons of Wall Street to the city's great
bridges, from the steeple of Riverside Church to one of the city's
most prestigious medical complexes, peregrine falcons, once near
extinction, are nesting, breeding and, most assuredly, endearing
themselves to Gotham residents.
</P>
<P>
   New York's 12 pairs of breeding falcons number more than any
other city's, and there appear to be at least three other pairs
that did not breed this spring. About 24 chicks were born this
year, 20 of which survive. They inhabit at least four buildings and
eight bridges.
</P>
<P>
   To say the least, New Yorkers are charmed. ``You hear these
truly joyful breeding sounds,'' said Adele A. Lerner, archivist at
New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center, where a ledge between the
24th and 25th floors of the main building has been home to breeding
falcons since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The city's peregrine falcons are one of the nation's happiest
environmental success stories, so successful that Washington plans
to remove the species from the endangered list. The pesticide DDT
and related compounds that were first used after World War II
altered the birds' calcium metabolism, making their eggshells
perilously thin. Other effects of these compounds were even more
sinister: in some cases, falcons ate their young.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1972, DDT was banned, and in the 1980s Cornell University
began the chancy process of reintroducing the species. Scientists
collected specimens from falconers and successfully experimented
with artificial insemination. They put up nesting boxes, first on
bridges, then buildings.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a perfect environment. The falcons, which
once lived on cliffs, adapted easily to man-made aeries. They loved
the open rivers as highways to glide at speeds clocked at more than
200 miles an hour. The former predators of the extinct passenger
pigeon acquired a taste for street pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   And they almost gleefully demonstrated their bloodthirsty
habits, particularly in mating competition among males, which are a
third smaller than the 20-inch-long females. ``We see a lot of
battling out there,'' said Christopher A. Nadareski, a biologist
with the city Department of Environmental Affairs who has studied
the species. ``Sometimes the birds will kill each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The reintroduction was replicated in other cities, including
Baltimore, Seattle, Chicago, Boston and Toronto. And the peregrine
falcons were only one of a number of raptor species to reappear in
the wake of the DDT dread. On one day last fall, a New York Parks
Department team counted 1,184 hawks, 54 osprey and 4 bald eagles.
The migrating hawks passed at the rate of 15 a minute.
</P>
<P>
   But the peregrines are year-round residents. They are returning
to a place that was the home for some as recently as the 1950s.
Nadareski said that, in addition to the damage done by DDT, they
were depleted by falconers and collectors of their rust-colored
eggs. Though he acknowledged that removing the birds from the
endangered _ and even threatened _ species lists demonstrates
success, he worries these behaviors could recur.
</P>
<P>
   ``They exist only at the will of humans,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
