<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun. July 19)  
 (JT)  
 By L.R. SHANNON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FINDING ATM'S ABROAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; www.mastercard.com/atm &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; www.visa.com/cgi-bin/vee/main.html &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Before a trip, or during one if you travel with a computer,
check one or both of these sites to find an ATM for when you run
short of cash. Each can be searched by region or airport. The
Mastercard site also has what it describes as a map for finding
ATM's in the United States. (I found three in my hometown, but
never saw a map.)
</P>
<P>
   The ATM's are regular ones that accept Mastercard or Visa;
whatever other services are available depends on the bank or
country. The Web sites are full of guides to shopping at places
that, of course, accept one of the cards. An index in the
Mastercard site, for instance, lists places to buy books, music and
jewelry, and how to assemble travel packages. The Visa site can be
switched to the native languages of China (including Hong Kong and
Taiwan), Germany, Japan, Korea and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GEARED TO STUDENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; www.sta-travel.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers can book domestic and international flights with
convenience (and probably savings) at the Web site of STA Travel,
set up in Australia in the 1970s primarily for students and others
under the age of 26. You don't have to be either to get a ticket at
a good price _ although it may not be as good a price as a student
would receive. The fares are the ones currently being offered to
students by the airlines, and they vary from time to time, but
tickets obtained through STA Travel have fewer restrictions, with
one-way fares, no advance purchase requirements, and refunds on
unused tickets. The site is so colorful it verges on illegible, at
least to these over-26 eyes, but it is worth a bit of squinting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You can now enter when and where you want to travel and get
back our latest air fare price,'' STA Travel promises. ``If you
like what you see, hold your seats and purchase your tickets, all
on-line, while you sit at home in your pajamas.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was wearing jeans and a T-shirt, but I did carry out most of
the steps to reserve a seat from Newark to Copenhagen Aug. 5,
returning on Aug. 19. I was asked whether I was a student and, if
so, at what school, my nationality and birth date. Posing as a
20-year-old student at Rutgers, I was quickly presented with a
choice of flights. On neither the first, on SAS for $732, nor the
second, Lufthansa for $841, was a seat available, at least for a
student. But KLM had seats on Aug. 5 and 6 for $844. A quick check
with a travel agent found that a regular ticket, on British
Airways, was $959.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from booking flights, which must originate in the United
States, you can get Eurail Passes, travel insurance and an
International Student Identity Card, which you must have to
complete the booking (I didn't have one, of course). There are also
sections helpful in planning trips and exchanging information about
them. The Show and Tell section featured nine forums when I checked
it: destinations, travel tips, hot places to go, great places to
stay, site feedback, jobs, backpackers international, help and
around-the-world travel. There were no hot places to go, as it
turned out, but there were seven great places to stay.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STA Travel has offices around the country for the Web-allergic
or Web-deprived. Call (800) 781-4040.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
