<P>
   US-JAPAN _WASHINGTON _ Monday's resignation by Japanense Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, nine days before a planned state visit
to the White House, left world stock markets and the Clinton
administration scrambling to assess whether Japan's next government
would accelerate reforms needed to lift Japan's lifeless economy
and prevent it from dragging down global growth. On first blush,
the White House said it expects the next prime minister _ as yet
unamed _ to move quickly to cut taxes, shore up the country's
ailing banking system and invigorate consumer spending, measures
long resisted by Tokyo. (Deans, Cox News Service).
