<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2723 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HYPERTENSION-ART-     07-13 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HYPERTENSION-ART-825(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS RETHINK TACTICS TO LOWER BLOOD PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 (See also SCI-HYPERTENSION-DIET and SCI-HYPERTENSION-FDR)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in 1972, when the National High Blood Pressure Education
Program was established, its public health message was simple and
compelling: Treating high blood pressure would save lives. It was
right. The program has been credited with substantially lowering
death rates from stroke and coronary heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, though, the news has been less encouraging. The
stroke rate has been creeping up again, and not just because
Americans are aging. The decline in heart disease, never as great
as experts had expected, seems to be leveling off, and kidney
disease and congestive heart failure, both linked to hypertension,
are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Dismayed, scientists have begun to re-examine the treatment of
high blood pressure, asking how much of the ominous trend can be
blamed on lackadaisical doctors and patients who do not take
hypertension seriously enough, and how much on the limitations of
treatment itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are struggling now with the concept that we are not doing a
good job,'' said Dr. Franz Messerli of the hypertension department
at the Ochsner Clinic in New Orleans. ``We know we can reduce blood
pressure, we know it's beneficial to do so, and still it's not
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that of the 50 million Americans
estimated to have high blood pressure, only 34 million know it.
Just 27 million seek treatment, and only half of them get their
blood pressure under control, which is defined as below 140/90
millimeters of mercury. Those figures, from a survey taken from
1991-94, show people to be worse off than three years before, when
awareness, treatment and control were all slightly higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We home in on the public and say they're not taking their
pills,'' said Dr. Marvin Moser, clinical professor of Medicine at
Yale University Medical School. ``But I think we should be paying
more attention to the problem of adherence to treatment guidelines
by the doctor.'' Many doctors, he said, are not following those
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   And that means many patients are not getting the best treatment
for their high blood pressure and its complications, other
researchers agreed. But experts also admit that their research has
not given doctors all the information they need to make the best
decisions about treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Two important issues have not been resolved. First, it is not
known whether all drugs that lower blood pressure also protect
against heart attack and stroke. Second, more studies are needed to
compare different drugs and determine whether some work better than
others in particular types of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Blood pressure is the force exerted by blood as it pushes out
against the walls of the arteries. When pressure surges too high,
it can damage the vessels and lead to arteriosclerosis, heart
disease, stroke and kidney failure. Doctors define optimal blood
pressure, associated with the lowest cardiovascular risk, as below
120/80 millimeters of mercury. The first number, the systolic
pressure, is measured while the heart is contracting, and the
second, the diastolic reading, is taken while the heart is relaxing
between beats.
</P>
<P>
   Once the pressure climbs past 120/80, the risk of cardiovascular
disease begins to rise. But the condition is not called
hypertension until the pressure exceeds 140/90, and then the goal
of treatment is just to get it below that cut-off number. Few
patients ever make it back into the charmed zone below 120/80.
</P>
<P>
   People with mild hypertension and no other risk factors are
often advised to try lowering it through exercise and diet for six
to 12 months. Others are given medicine. The first choice for most
patients, according to the national guidelines, should be diuretics
and beta blockers, though doctors can use other classes of drugs if
the first try does not work.
</P>
<P>
   But basing treatment decisions solely on the numbers read off a
sphygmomanometer, the familiar cuff used to measure blood pressure,
can be a mistake. Two people may have the same high blood pressure
reading for different reasons, and their odds of developing heart
disease may also differ, depending on other risk factors like
smoking, age, obesity, race, high cholesterol and triglycerides,
abnormal glucose metabolism, kidney problems and enlargement of the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who focus on blood pressure alone may neglect other
conditions that still pose risks for heart disease, said Dr.
Michael Alderman, professor of medicine and epidemiology at Albert
Einstein College of Medicine in New York. He labeled that approach
simplistic and said therapy should be tailored to individual needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more complicated than just measuring the blood
pressure and giving people pills,'' Alderman said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the most recent guidelines from the national program
recommend certain types of drugs specifically for people with
problems like diabetes, Alderman said more research is needed to
fine-tune such advice.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   CHOOSING TREATMENT: STUDY FINDS MERITS IN INTENSIVE THERAPY
</P>
<P>
   There are doctors who specialize in hypertension, and
enterprising patients who seek them out, but most people depend on
internists and family practitioners, who may or may not be well
versed in the 65 different drugs and 29 combination pills used to
treat high blood pressure. Hypertension is not an officially
recognized medical specialty, but those who devote their careers to
it think it should be, and their professional group, the American
Society of Hypertension, based in New York, announced plans in May
to try to make it one.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting research to address basic questions that remain
unanswered is among the group's goals. For instance, doctors have
debated about how far it is necessary and safe to go in lowering a
patient's blood pressure. Although readings below 140/90 are the
accepted goal of treatment, studies show that any reading above
120/80 increases the risk of stroke and heart attack. But studies
have not shown whether using drugs to get closer to 120/80 can
provide any added benefit.
</P>
<P>
   A new study suggests that more intensive treatment is
worthwhile. The study included almost 19,000 people in 26 countries
who started out with a diastolic blood pressure, represented by the
second number, between 100 and 115. The patients were divided into
three groups with different targets for diastolic pressure: 80 or
less, 85 or less and 90 or less. People with diabetes who reached a
pressure of 80 or less benefited most: They had 50 percent fewer
heart attacks than those whose readings were between 80 and 90. For
others, the study suggested that pressure should be reduced to
138/83 or lower because patients who met that target had the fewest
deaths from cardiovascular disease.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the June 13 issue of the journal Lancet,
provides evidence that doctors should be more aggressive in
treating hypertension, said Messerli, who was not involved in the
study.
</P>
<P>
   But there are differences of opinion over the best way to lower
blood pressure. Moser, for instance, said he has been trying for
years to convince his colleagues that diuretics should be used more
often, alone or combined with other drugs. Also known as water
pills, diuretics reduce blood volume and lower blood pressure by
increasing the excretion of water and salt through the kidneys.
They also relax blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in the June 10 issue of the Journal of the
American Medical Association, Moser noted that the use of diuretics
has gone down in the past 15 years, despite the national
guidelines. Some doctors avoid prescribing diuretics, Moser said,
because of exaggerated concerns about side effects like elevated
blood sugar and cholesterol. With small doses, those effects are
usually small, he said, adding that doctors can monitor for them
and change therapy if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Moser traces the decline in diuretic use in part to the
pharmaceutical industry, which he said influences medical practice
by advertising newer, more expensive drugs, promoting them at
medical meetings, handing out free samples and paying doctors to
give promotional talks under the guise of lectures at medical
conferences. The net effect, he said, has been to draw doctors away
from diuretics, which have been proven to prevent heart attacks and
strokes, and toward newer, more costly medications like calcium
blockers and ACE inhibitors, whose long-term effects are less well
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``When these other drugs came out and doctors stopped using
diuretics, we started getting a lot of resistant patients,'' Moser
said in a telephone interview, referring to people whose blood
pressure escaped control even though they were taking two or three
different drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than half of them at Yale became responders when a little
bit of diuretic was added and the other drug was reduced. The other
drugs are good, and thank goodness we have them, but if we used
more diuretics we'd have fewer resistant patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Messerli also said diuretics were underused, especially in
people over age 60. He recently reviewed 10 published studies
involving a total of more than 16,000 patients, and concluded that
many of the 6 million older people now taking drugs known as beta
blockers _ a practice in keeping with current treatment guidelines
_ would be better off taking diuretics, which have been proven to
reduce the risk of heart attack. His findings were published in the
June 17 Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   He said that although beta blockers work well in young and
middle-aged patients, in older people the drugs do not prevent
heart attacks, do not even lower blood pressure effectively and too
often cause side effects, including fatigue, depression and loss of
sexual function.
</P>
<P>
   Then why are so many older patients given beta blockers?
Messerli speculated that doctors are confused, because there is one
group of elderly patients in whom the drugs are essential: those
who have already had a heart attack. Even in patients who do not
have high blood pressure, beta blockers help prevent additional
heart attacks. It might seem reasonable to assume that if the drugs
can prevent second heart attacks, they can prevent first ones, too.
But there is no evidence that they can.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   COMPARING THE DRUGS: MONEY FOR RESEARCH IS SLOW IN COMING
</P>
<P>
   The information that doctors and patients want most _ data on
which drug really is best for which patient _ has been slow in
coming. Until recent years, relatively few studies were done to
compare drugs, largely because the pharmaceutical industry, which
finances much of the research on hypertension drugs, was not eager
to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were manufacturing a drug and it was selling like hot
cakes, why would you risk a study comparing it to other drugs?''
asked Moser. Drug companies sold about $9 billion in blood pressure
medications in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, they're doing the studies because there's pressure to do
them,'' Moser said, noting that about 30 comparative trials are
under way, with results expected in several years.
</P>
<P>
   Alderman cited a study published in March in The New England
Journal of Medicine as an example of what comparative studies can
reveal. In that study, 470 patients with Type 2 diabetes, the more
common, adult-onset form of the disease, were divided into two
groups, with 235 taking a calcium blocker and 235 a type of drug
known as an ACE (or angiotensin converting enzyme) inhibitor.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs lowered blood pressure equally well, but after five
years, an alarming difference showed up between the two groups:
there were 25 heart attacks in the calcium blocker group, but only
five in the ACE inhibitor group. The study, being conducted at the
University of Colorado, was halted early to give the people on
calcium blockers a chance to switch to an ACE inhibitor.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson, said Alderman, who was not involved in the study, is
that just lowering blood pressure does not wipe out all risk. ``How
you lower the pressure may make a difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the study said their findings needed to be
verified by larger studies. But in the meantime, many doctors are
taking the results seriously and steering people with diabetes
towards ACE inhibitors, which had already been recommended for
diabetics, because the inhibitors also seem to slow the progression
of kidney disease and some heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   Future studies are also expected to help determine whether the
difference in heart attacks occurred because calcium blockers
actually harm the heart in diabetics, or because ACE inhibitors are
better at protecting the heart. Dr. Curt Furberg, professor and
chairman of the department of public health sciences at Wake Forest
University of Medicine, who was not involved in the study, said he
thought calcium blockers would be proved harmful to diabetics,
because diabetes changes cell structure so that calcium blockers
bind to the cells more strongly. ``So you get a magnified effect,
sort of like having too high a dose,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To Alderman, the Colorado study was a reminder that blood
pressure is only part of a person's medical picture, and that
relying too much on the numbers can lead to false reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evidence that we're shifting away from the notion
that it's all about blood pressure to the fact that there's a
vascular disease out there for which high blood pressure is a
marker,'' he said. ``High blood pressure is a physical sign that
tells us about a system gone awry, but it doesn't tell us the
cause. Blood pressure is part of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   FINDING THE CAUSE: WHY SYSTEM FAILS REMAINS A MYSTERY
</P>
<P>
   People with high blood pressure who wonder ``why me?'' rarely
get the satisfaction of an answer. About 90 percent of cases are
labeled ``essential'' hypertension, and no reason is pinpointed.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate causes are the same ones that would boost the
pressure in any plumbing system. They include excess fluid in the
circulatory system, pushing too hard on blood vessels. Vessels may
also have constricted or become stiff. Or the heart may beat too
hard, pumping out extra blood with each beat.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying causes are harder to sort out. The sympathetic
nervous system, agent of the ``fight-or-flight'' response to a
threat, can drive blood pressure up or down by sending alarm calls
to the heart, blood vessels and kidneys. In some people, blood
pressure rises because the kidneys make too much of an enzyme
called renin, which leads to production of the hormones angiotensin
II and angiotensin III. Those hormones can make arteries constrict
and also stimulate the release of another hormone, aldosterone,
which makes the kidney retain salt and excrete potassium. The salt
(sodium) draws in water, expanding the volume of blood in the
circulatory system, increasing the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Why the systems that regulate blood pressure go awry in the
first place is not fully understood. Hypertension runs in some
families, probably the result of multiple genes. But the genes may
be just a predisposing factor, waiting for an environmental trigger
to set them off. In some people, gaining weight does it. Some,
especially blacks and the elderly, seem especially sensitive to
salt in the diet. Smoking, lack of exercise and drinking a lot of
alcohol can also contribute. But thin people who do not smoke or
drink sometimes become hypertensive, too.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four years, researchers in California have been
studying about 200 people with family histories of high blood
pressure, who are thought to have an inherited disorder called the
hypertension syndrome. They are probably a minority of all
hypertension patients, but their evolving medical histories may
shed light on the course of high blood pressure in other people as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The study is being led by Dr. Joel Neutel, director of research
at the Orange County Heart Institute and chief of hypertension and
clinical pharmacology at the Veterans Administration Medical Center
in Long Beach. He and his colleagues have selected people, many in
their mid-20s, who do not have hypertension but have at least one
parent with it.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers have found that many of these people already
have disorders often associated with hypertension, even though
their blood pressure is still normal: high cholesterol, high renin
levels and abnormally high levels of the hormone insulin, which
their bodies do not use efficiently to metabolize glucose. The
raised insulin levels may be brought on by excess weight, which is
a problem for many of the subjects. Excess insulin and renin can
cause stiffening of the arteries and enlargement of the main
pumping chamber of the heart, which have also been found in the
subjects. Heart enlargement can lead to dangerous rhythm
abnormalities and heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the things causing cardiovascular disease in these
patients may be there before the onset of hypertension, and may
cause hypertension,'' Neutel said. Stiffening of the arteries, for
instance, seems to occur several years before hypertension sets in.
</P>
<P>
   By the time blood pressure goes up, vascular damage may have
already begun, Neutel said, and hypertension may accelerate it. The
best way to help the patients will probably be to try to identify
and treat them early. Doctors suspect that ACE inhibitors may be
useful, but studies have not yet been completed.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Neutel said, ``the best thing we can advise them is to
be very diligent about diet and exercise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
