<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, July 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The beginning of a coast-to-coast heat wave will become more
evident Tuesday. High pressure moving off the Middle Atlantic coast
will merge with the Bermuda high and this will circulate hot and
humid air from the western Gulf states northward through the Plains
and then eastward across the Great Lakes and into New England.
Readings should reach 90 degrees for the first time this season in
sections of southern New England.
</P>
<P>
   A second center of high pressure will develop over the Four
Corners region and this fair weather system will transport desert
heat from the Southwest into the central and eastern Rockies. The
hot weather will advance into Idaho and Montana under mainly sunny
skies. However, the Northwest coast will be dull with a few
showers.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and thundershowers will dampen most of the Tennessee
Valley and parts of the Southeast. A large but weak disturbance at
15,000 feet over Arkansas will draw tropical air into the Gulf
States. The boundary between this tropical air and a rather warm,
but noticeably less humid, air mass over the Carolinas will be the
mechanism for triggering some large thunderstorms. Florida will
continue to see beneficial rains as thunderstorms form Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered thunderstorms are likely in the eastern Dakotas as
torrid air moves farther north. A cluster of storms will dissipate
in Wisconsin by afternoon. Several thundershowers will develop in
the Appalachians as sultry air rises over the mountains. The
Northeast coast will be hazy, but mostly sunny.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Famine to Feast
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms that signaled danger due to lightning strikes that
triggered brush fires along Florida's northeast coast have turned
more friendly. Melbourne, which had measured less than a half inch
of rain from mid-May through early July, received a daily record of
1.41 inches on Sunday. A slow-moving storm drenched Brevard county
and helped to douse remnant fires. In Melbourne, nearly six inches
of rain has fallen since last Tuesday. A weak disturbance will
settle over the Southeast the next few days, perhaps causing more
rain than is needed along the central coast of Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
