<HEADLINE>
FOR FDR, `FATIGUE' WAS LETHAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 (With SCI-HYPERTENSION and SCI-HYPERTENSION-DIET)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By LAURA CHANG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though wholly without glamour, hypertension has played a
noteworthy role in the course of human events, rarely more than in
the case of President Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt learned late in his third term that he had serious
hypertension but made enormous efforts to conceal his illness,
according to a new book by Robert H. Ferrell, a history professor
emeritus at Indiana University. By his final months, Roosevelt
could work no more than four hours a day, Ferrell says in ``The
Dying President'' (University of Missouri Press).
</P>
<P>
   Unable to concentrate for long periods, the president delayed
important decisions and was ``in no condition to govern the
republic,'' Ferrell writes. But he hid his illness even from his
family and Vice President Harry S. Truman.
</P>
<P>
   The sporadic data available from Roosevelt's early terms
indicate that his blood pressure was normal when he entered the
White House. But in late 1943, after returning from Tehran to
confer on war plans with the Allies, Roosevelt could not shake his
fatigue and fell victim to headaches, bronchitis and flu. His
daughter, Anna, insisted that a specialist be consulted, and on
March 28, 1944, Dr. Howard G. Bruenn, a cardiologist and lieutenant
commander in the Navy, made his first thorough examination.
</P>
<P>
   The president, Bruenn was shocked to find, was in an advanced
stage of cardiovascular disease, with an enlarged and weakened
heart. His blood pressure was 180/90.
</P>
<P>
   No beta-blockers or sophisticated diuretics existed then, and
Bruenn used the limited therapy available at the time. He gave the
president digitalis to stimulate his heart and ordered changes in
his diet.
</P>
<P>
   Though the President improved for a time, his hypertension never
disappeared. Roosevelt died from a massive brain hemorrhage on
April 12, 1945.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
