<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr takes stand on idea of national ID cardsBy Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Conservative Republicans, the Christian Coalition and
the American Civil Liberties Union are opposing a proposed federal
rule that they say would result in a national ID card.
</P>
<P>
   ''This proposed rule represents a major threat to the privacy of
individuals in America,'' said Congressman Bob Barr (R-Marietta).
''Practically every privacy rights and civil liberties group in the
country is opposed to it. Additionally, it imposes a huge financial
burden on individual states.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr, who hosted a press conference Monday at the State Capitol,
said he will introduce legislation today aimed at blocking the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the rule would simply offer employers a better
way to do background checks on prospective employees and provide
immigration authorities with an effective means of identifying
illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
   The national ID card, Barr said, would result from a rule
proposed by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration that
would require states to link driver's licenses with Social Security
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation passed by the Georgia General Assembly last year
allows state drivers to use their Social Security numbers on
driver's licenses but does not require them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Nelson, the executive director of the ACLU of Georgia,
said efforts to push a national ID card measure through Congress
several years ago failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a quick fix,'' Nelson said. ``We believe that not only
would it violate privacy rights but it wouldn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   She called the rule proposed by the NHTSA a ``back-door try'' by
the government, adding: ``They want to get the states to do their
work for them.'' Both Barr and Nelson said they believe the
proposal will draw broad bipartisan opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
