<HEADER>
A2752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-DAY14-COX     07-13 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-DAY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mfume names names on politicians with unfavorable voting records
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He made it plain, leaving the soldiers no room to
misinterpret the battle plan: Demand. Boycott. Oust. Work.
</P>
<P>
   In a tell-the-truth-shame-the-devil call to action, NAACP
president Kweisi Mfume pointed fingers and boldly named names in a
speech Monday designed to set the course for the organization's
members when they leave the annual convention being held here this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Before hundreds of delegates participating in the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People convention, Mfume
gave instructions on handling politicians who voted unfavorably on
civil rights issues.
</P>
<P>
   Call them in to a chapter-sponsored forum and tell them to ``sit
in a chair and explain how they did so poorly,'' he demanded. ``And
if they don't show up, put an empty chair there with their name on
it. ... And let them know we will do what we did in 1914 and throw
the rascals out!''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to economic empowerment within the black community,
Mfume told delegates to make use of the NAACP's report cards that
rate how well businesses provide opportunities to black people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't spend your money where you can't work,'' he said.
``Don't spend your dollars where you can't get a promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotels where black people can only carry bags, make beds and
empty trash need to know they don't deserve black people's
patronage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From this day forward, we are prepared, in a disciplined way,
to spend our dollars with those who have a sense of reciprocity,''
Mfume said. ``... Boycott those who boycott you!''
</P>
<P>
   Lest delegates forget who some of those companies are, Mfume,
without hesitation, cited Denny's, an event sponsor, and Texaco, an
exhibitor at the NAACP convention as perpetrators of recent racist
acts and reasons for continuing affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   But the specifics didn't stop there. Referring to the paltry
presence of black law clerks employed by the nation's highest
court, Mfume declared the U.S. Supreme Court a hypocrite and
singled out one justice in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice (Antonin) Scalia,'' Mfume yelled addressing the
justice as if he were present, ``you have never found it in you to
employ one black law clerk since you have been there (on the
Supreme Court since 1986), so we know why you make the decisions
that you do!''
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court spokeswoman Toni House said Monday ``...no one is
going to have a response to that comment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the motivating speech that brought hundreds of delegates to
their feet and left them talking on the street afterwards, Mfume
stressed that the NAACP must do its own work and serve its own
people.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he mentioned having attended a funeral for a
13-year-old black male who was killed by another black male in a
drive-by shooting and waiting in a hospital emergency room with an
elderly black woman who had been attacked by a black person.
</P>
<P>
   It is the NAACP's responsibility to address the pathology within
the black community that leads its members to shoot one another and
assault its elderly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to fix it. We are going to clean up our act,''
he promised.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
