<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH, PLAYER ABANDONED THE GAME PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Despite their best efforts and intentions, birth
coaches are _ let's face it _ like appendixes.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they're nice to have, but they don't really do anything.
</P>
<P>
   In my experience, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   You know the adage about how a coach can only teach his players,
that he can't get out there on the field and play for them?
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to birth coaching. The difference is that you can't
teach your wife what to do. She knows what to do.
</P>
<P>
   She's doing it, right there in front of your disbelieving eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Quite the transformation for your wife, labor. Like when Linda
Blair says, ``The sow is mine,'' in ``The Exorcist.'' One minute
you're watching an episode of ``ER,'' the next minute you're in
one.
</P>
<P>
   The calm, cool, collected woman you married, who earlier in the
evening casually mentioned a little grumbling in her stomach, now
has both feet planted on the dashboard of your car, pushing herself
so far into the seat you're afraid she's going to pop herself into
the trunk, all the while insisting in no uncertain terms that the
car CAN TOO go faster than this.
</P>
<P>
   The tricky part is that, what with all the excitement and
everything, you'd like to scream, too. But it seems somehow
inappropriate at a time like this. Sort of like complaining about a
bad case of jock itch while visiting a leper colony. Probably best
not to mention it.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't get the wrong impression. I heartily recommend that
all expectant fathers take birthing classes. Read everything you
can on the subject. Pay careful attention. Take copious notes. Ask
lots of questions.
</P>
<P>
   That way, when the professionals move you out of the way to get
down to business, you'll at least have an idea why.
</P>
<P>
   My experience as a coach began in earnest when, as I drove my
wife to the hospital, I encouraged her to ``breathe,'' breathe
right through those contractions. Recalling some snippet of
information I'd read somewhere, I breathed myself, loudly, to give
her an example to follow.
</P>
<P>
   The contraction subsided, and I was feeling pretty good about
things. This is going to be easy, I thought. Nothing to it.
</P>
<P>
   My wife looked at me with calm eyes. I was ready for a little
appreciation, a quick thank-you for my efforts. She spoke in even,
measured tones:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't
 &UR; ever breathe for me again.''
</P>
<P>
   Noted.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived at the hospital after hours, so we had to be buzzed
in by security. Not a big deal, except that when I hurried ahead
and opened the door, I looked for my wife and . . . there she was,
still shut inside the car. Her feet were on the dash again, and her
face was contorted in such a way that I was thankful it was a cool
night and the windows were shut. &QL; 
Remember the promo line for ``Alien,'' ``In space, no one can hear
you scream?'' Turns out the same is true in hospital parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   From there, things went predictably. I rubbed her back; she
asked me not to, in a way that made it sound as if I were wearing
gloves made from sandpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, no breathing, no back rubs. Unless I missed something
critical in birthing classes, this pretty much exhausted the extent
of my participation.
</P>
<P>
   For the remainder of the process, I mostly stood around and
offered the occasional ``good job'' or ``nice work.'' (I also
pulled one of her legs back during the ``pushing'' part, but I'll
spare you the details. Believe me, you'll be glad I did.)
</P>
<P>
   And you know what? Everything worked out just fine anyway.
Performing what by anyone's standard is the toughest physical work
there is, my wife actually ``apologized'' for not being more
``coachable.'' Latrell Sprewell, she's not.
</P>
<P>
   I laughed. She had the important job, after all, and she carried
it off beautifully. She produced, in my humble opinion, the cutest
baby ever born. (I know, everyone says that, but I have a mountain
of pictures to prove it.)
</P>
<P>
   The entire event reminded me of what broadcasters say when
they're talking about a player with particularly good innate
skills:
</P>
<P>
   Some things, you just can't coach. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
