<SLUG> BC-BBN-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COMMISH'S DAUGHTER TO DAD: BUD OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN SHEA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ When Bud Selig was elected permanent commissioner in
an owners' meeting in Chicago, the duties of running the Milwaukee
Brewers were handed to his daughter. With Cincinnati's Marge Schott
still under suspension, Wendy Selig-Prieb became the lone woman
running a major-league club.
</P>
<P>
   Selig and Selig-Prieb have a close relationship, but the
daughter had one message for the father: Bud out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have no involvement,'' said Selig-Prieb, shooting
down obvious conflict-of-interest fears. ``Like everyone else,
he'll have to read it in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers aren't about to undergo wholesale changes, it
appears. General manager Sal Bando and manager Phil Garner are
safe, and the payroll won't take a sudden reduction. As Selig-Prieb
said, ``I can tell you I'm not going to do anything different. ...
We're very fortunate to have Sal Bando as our general manager. In
my view, he's among the best when you look at what he's been able
to accomplish with a very restrictive budget.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers are a nice story. As the first team this century to
switch leagues, the Brewers started quickly before leveling off.
They entered the All-Star break with a winning record for the first
time since 1992, and they still think they're in the playoff hunt,
at least as a wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seems to think the Brewers' front office will change
much. Selig had always set the payroll and left the personnel moves
to Bando, and he gave most of the day-to-day operations to his
daughter after becoming interim commissioner in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Selig-Prieb, 38, attended ownership meetings and represented the
Brewers during the labor war and revenue-sharing debates. She was
handling most of the day-to-day chores until taking a recent leave
of absence after giving birth to her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Selig had to resign as Brewers chief executive, and Selig-Prieb
is expected to be appointed his successor Aug. 1. Selig will move
his office from County Stadium to downtown Milwaukee, mostly to
avoid charges of conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can speak with him about issues any other club can talk to
him about,'' Selig-Prieb said. ``As far as club-specific issues, he
would avoid it and I would avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows he's the heart and soul of the franchise.
Nothing has meant more to him than the Brewers. If he felt we
weren't on the right track, it would have weighed heavily in his
decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1739EDT &QL; 
