<HEADER>
A2770 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-BUSINESS-LADN     07-13 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-BUSINESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURSUING THEIR DREAMS IN A BIG WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEESUN WEE 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Summer can be a bummer for 12-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Driving is several years away, bicycling around town gets old
and television isn't always stimulating.
</P>
<P>
   But Kristin Sanchez, now all of 14, didn't succumb to boredom
that fateful summer. The self-proclaimed girl-on-the-go turned to
an old passion to pass the time _ baking.
</P>
<P>
   As the temperature rose in the Valley, so did the heat in her
family's Chatsworth kitchen as she prodded ingredients into tasty
cookies, cakes, breads and cinnamon rolls. Little did she know she
was on her way to starting her first business as a baker.
</P>
<P>
   Since that portentous summer, Sanchez has posted a total profit
of several hundred dollars from Cinnamon Cat's Baked Goods. She has
used the money to splurge on occasional treats such as clothes, but
more often than not, she has reinvested her earnings in more
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Costco seems to be my good friend lately,'' said Sanchez,
already sounding a bit like a weary veteran of the business ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Who said summers are boring and uneventful?
</P>
<P>
   While young entrepreneurs are nothing new, more teen-agers and
young adults are turning toward business ventures.
</P>
<P>
   According to Forbes magazine, 80 percent of an estimated 7
million Americans currently trying to start their own businesses
are age 34 or younger.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, resources for the swelling ranks of young
entrepreneurs are growing more sophisticated. We're talking
Internet-based virtual stock market simulation games for teen-agers
and summer camps that teach youngsters everything from how to write
a business plan to analyzing no-load mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   But not all young entrepreneurs have the luxury of outside
resources before setting up shop. Others rely instead on the
expertise _ and loans _ of family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   That's what brothers Desi and Robert Kepe of Burbank did in
December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Robert, then 18 and a high school senior, and Robert, then 21
and a junior college student, decided to try their hand at owning
and running their own sandwich shop. Armed with more than $200,000
in loans from their parents and an uncle, they opened Togo's
Woodland Hills on Victory Boulevard in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Although Robert Kepe, now 20, decided to pass on the college
experience, he said pursuing a paycheck vs. a diploma wasn't too
difficult a decision to make. ``Go to school for six years or make
money now? I'm a little impatient that way,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Although getting support from family members was challenging,
convincing the Togo's franchise to hand a store over to two very
young adults was even harder. ``But we were real persistent. We
argued out the point not to hold something against somebody because
of their age,'' Robert Kepe said.
</P>
<P>
   It worked _ and they made a bit of history along the way. The
Kepe brothers are the youngest Togo's owners in the company's
two-decade history, Robert Kepe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, people don't believe I'm the owner,'' added
Robert Kepe with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kepe brothers don't fuss too much about their age _
Robert is now 20, Desi, 23. They're too busy running the business
that includes supervising a staff of 22 employees, ordering meats
and making sandwiches during the weekday lunch crush when
professionals often twice their age order turkey-and-avocado or hot
pastrami sandwiches. Although they're still in the red, business is
good and the loan is getting paid off, Robert Kepe said.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers credit their business savvy to their parents,
immigrants from Slovenia who raised their sons in an
entrepreneur-friendly household. Both parents own real estate.
Their father also owns a construction business. The common question
around the dinner table was, ``So how's the business going?''
</P>
<P>
   While the Kepe brothers attribute part of their business
interest to their upbringing, some experts believe more young
people are turning to entrepreneurship specifically because their
parents rode the ups and downs of America's corporate boom and bust
in the 1980s _ and then made personal vows not to follow in their
parental footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   Many young people interpreted the decade as: ``Don't go to work
for corporate America. There's no loyalty. We can't trust anyone
but ourselves,'' said Jennifer Kushell, president and founder of
the Young Entrepreneurs Network, a Boston-based international
support group and resource center for young business people.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to avoid their parents' work experiences, they instead
are embracing the charmed success tales of business rebels who
decided to boldly go it alone _ among them technology giants Bill
Gates and Michael Dell.
</P>
<P>
   And that independent business philosophy coupled with the
home-office trend is making it possible for more young people to
transform business plans into profit-making realities.
</P>
<P>
   Kushell herself is a part of this latest generation of young
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   While growing up in Encino, she began selling painted T-shirts
when she was 13. By age 15, she had moved on to gift baskets. At
17, she organized safety and self-defense seminars for women.
</P>
<P>
   Kushell's entrepreneurial drive continued when she entered
college. She tried marketing video tours of colleges. That didn't
pan out either.
</P>
<P>
   Then last year, the now 25-year-old finally hit pay dirt when
she funneled her experience as a young entrepreneur into a book
about that very same topic, ``No Experience Necessary: The Young
Entrepreneur's Guide to Starting a Business'' (Random
House/Princeton Review Books; $12).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Kushell's multiple business ventures are not unique. A
1997 study conducted by the Young Entrepreneurs Network found many
entrepreneurs are veterans of several start-ups by their 30s _
about 2.3 businesses, defined as any registered or
income-generating enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   And more business ventures by young people means more acceptance
of green entrepreneurs. ``When people know about Bill Gates, they
don't laugh about a kid and a computer,'' Kushell said.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Liebeskind, 21, of Calabasas also is a young
entrepreneur based in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Liebeskind, who graduated from college this past spring with a
degree in acting and directing, began her cosmetics line just after
her first year there. She hopes her own business will allow her to
accommodate acting auditions.
</P>
<P>
   The business began with a simple observation: car-less college
students in need of fun yet practical and affordable makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Already having done makeovers for many girlfriends, Liebeskind
dipped into her $15,000 inheritance and began Dramatic Designs.
</P>
<P>
   She's not the only one. The Network study also found that 66
percent of the 200 entrepreneurs surveyed between ages 18 and 35
emptied savings to start their companies.
</P>
<P>
   Liebeskind, a sorority member, advertised her new business in
the campus sorority-fraternity directory. A few makeovers later,
her customers multiplied via word-of-mouth referrals.
</P>
<P>
   Now back at home in Calabasas, she continues to primarily target
young women who come to her home-office for beauty sessions and
products that feature sheer, luminescent colors. Popular products
include Shadow Shifter and Lip Lacquer that can be worn over other
eye shadows and lipsticks, giving old colors a fresh look.
</P>
<P>
   Liebeskind said she's slowly recording a profit. Through a
network of family and friends and referrals, she's accumulating new
fans in the Los Angeles area, including high school and college
students.
</P>
<P>
   While making money and being your own boss are good things,
being a young business go-getter does have its drawbacks. Aside
from the mountain of paperwork, including acquiring business
licenses, that come with being an entrepreneur, teens who choose
this route often run into one common problem: No one takes you
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought it was a hobby of mine. ... They thought it was
cute,'' said Kushell of her work. But she deftly responded: ``This
is a job. I work for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Liebeskind agreed. ``I felt like I had to prove something, let
everyone know I was no joke,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy for Sanchez either. Some of her peers
taunted her when, with the administration's permission, she first
brought her baked goods to Chaminade Middle School in Chatsworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think you're going to be a world-famous baker? How much
money do you think you can make?'' they asked. But a taste usually
was all it took to convert critics into customers.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly developed a loyal clientele of teachers, staff and
students. They're so hooked on her sweet treats that during summer
vacation, customers pick up their orders at Sanchez's home.
</P>
<P>
   And, while Sanchez may be young, she already has some business
advice to pass along.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a dream, I say go for it. Take risks, even if you
have doubts. Ignore (the naysayers) and go for what you want,'' she
says. ``If you want something bad enough, you can get it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
