<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT MACWORLD, APPLE TURNS OUT NEW PRODUCTS AND PLENTY OF PROMISES
</HEADLINE>
 700&AMP;ADD -NYT (The Science Times) 
(js) 
By PETER H. LEWIS  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The relatively sparse crowds and smaller exhibit
booths at last week's Macworld trade show in New York were tangible
evidence of the decline of Apple Computer in recent years. Visitors
to the show typically found that promises almost outnumbered actual
products. But while dazzling new products were scarce at Macworld,
no doubt many people were just as happy to take home some optimism
about the future of Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the show was an aqua and white beach ball of
a computer called the iMac. The iMac, which is the computer
equivalent of a new Volkswagen Beetle, was announced more than two
months ago and will not reach stores for another month.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 prototypes of the iMac (the ``I'' stands for
Internet) were dispersed around the show floor, where one of the
machine's admirers was Apple's former chief executive, John
Sculley. Wearing baggy corduroys and carrying a backpack, Sculley
was able to stroll largely unnoticed through the exhibits on the
show floor.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sculley who orchestrated the dismissal of Apple's
co-founder, Steve Jobs, more than a decade ago, and who was in turn
dismissed in what became a revolving door for Apple bosses that
ultimately revolved back to Jobs, who now holds the title interim
chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   In the only real surprise of the conference, Jobs made an
unexpected appearance at Macworld to deliver the keynote address.
During his two-hour presentation, he noted that it was almost
exactly a year ago that he rejoined the company. ``When I came a
year ago, all I heard was that Apple was dying,'' Jobs said. ``A
lot of people thought Apple was in a death spiral, which I think
there was some truth to.''
</P>
<P>
   Few experts expect Apple to climb back to its old heights, but
at least it has a chance now to stanch the 10 percent annual
defection rate from its current base of Macintosh users. Jobs
conceded that Apple had ignored its individual and educational
customers for several years, but now, based on hopes for the new
consumer-friendly iMac computer, Jobs said: ``We expect to see some
growth in the next six months.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Apple is also developing a less expensive Powerbook for
consumers and students, but it will not be ready until sometime
next year.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the computing world's attention has been on
Windows 98, but Apple's operating system is also scheduled for an
upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Mac OS 8.5, code-named Allegro and due this September, was given
a brief and limited demonstration at the show. Jobs and his
marketing chief, Phil Schiller, described Allegro as the most
significant upgrade to the Macintosh operating system in years,
even more significant than the jump from System 7 to System 8.
</P>
<P>
   Their enthusiasm for Mac OS 8.5 is evidently based on more than
just the two new features they selected to show to the audience: an
impressive new engine for finding information on the computer's
hard disk and on the Internet, and a feature that allows rapid
transfers of large multimedia files over computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   The file transfer demonstration, involving a 150-megabyte Adobe
Photoshop file, was a dud. In a staged demonstration, an Apple
computer running Mac OS 8.5 froze as it attempted to pass the file
to another Apple computer, while a Compaq computer running Windows
NT 4.0 easily transferred the same file to a Dell machine.
</P>
<P>
   On the second try, the Apple computers beat the Windows NT
machines by about four seconds. (As one might expect, there were no
oohs and aahs from the audience.)
</P>
<P>
   Far more impressive was the demonstration of Mac OS 8.5's
information searching feature, called Sherlock, which replaces the
feeble file-finding utility in the current Mac operating system.
Instead of searching for file names, Sherlock allows users to
search for content inside documents, using natural-language
queries. Files meeting the search criteria are then ranked by
relevance _ and here's the cool part that sets it apart from even
the best Web search engines _ the computer will analyze the
document and create a brief synopsis of the file's contents, not
just the first few lines of text. The new search engine can also
scan the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   It will be at least a year before Apple's next major operating
system version (Mac OS X) is made available to the public, Schiller
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Until recently, Macintosh users were accustomed to having new
features and technologies well ahead of their Windows counterparts.
But at this year's show, Mac users seemed pleased with promises for
a broad array of products that showed up first in Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Among the products and programs coming to the Mac in months
ahead are the popular ``Tomb Raider'' games that star the virtual
celebrity Lara Croft, coming in time for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The disk-based version of the Encyclopedia Britannica will soon
be ready for the Mac from Broderbund. Disney Online was given an
unusually large part of the keynote to demonstrate a Macintosh
prototype of its popular Blast web site for children
(www.disneyblast.com/mac) Peripheral products based on the
Universal Serial Bus connection scheme will soon be appearing for
Macintosh computers. Windows-based PC's have been equipped with USB
ports for more than a year, but in this case the Mac has not been
at a disadvantage because so few USB peripherals have reached the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Syquest was demonstrating a prototype of its one-megabyte Sparq
removable cartridge drive for Macintoshes, which has been popular
on Windows machines. The Palm Computing division of the 3COM Corp.
promised to deliver better versions of its Palm III organizer for
the Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   The head of Microsoft's Macintosh development group vowed that
never again will Microsoft treat the Macintosh as a second-class
citizen by simply retooling Windows programs to run on the Mac OS.
Instead, he said, the group will have a battle cry of ``first and
only on the Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof of all these promises is yet to be seen. But compared
to where the Mac was a year ago, promises are encouraging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
