<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIGHT BIGOTRY AT THE BALLOT BOX, CORETTA KING TELLS LAWYERS
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Coretta Scott King urged a lawyers' group Monday to
help use the 1998 elections to bring to office ``more men and,
especially, more women ... who will serve as champions of
diversity, affirmative action and other measures to promote
equality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The brutal killing of James Byrd in Jasper, Texas, provides a
tragic reminder that we still have a serious problem with hate
groups in America,'' said King, the widow of civil rights leader
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. ``We've also got to deal with the more
subtle and sophisticated forms of racism and bigotry. The best
place to begin is at the ballot box.''
</P>
<P>
   King was the keynote speaker at the awards luncheon of the
Association of Trial Lawyers of America, the national organization
of plaintiffs' lawyers whose six-day convention ends here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Honored on Monday were lawyers who have given the maximum $5,000
each to the trial lawyers' political action committee, which has
contributed $1.3 million to congressional members and candidates in
the last 18 months. Almost 90 percent of the campaign contributions
went to Democrats, but the trial lawyers are making a concerted
effort to reach Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional political activism of trial lawyers showed in
their applause Monday when King declared that ``We need a Congress
that legislates more and investigates less.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress is supposed to be about serving the people, not the
partisan agendas of the power-hungry careerists who turn their
backs on working people, the poor and the disadvantaged,'' King
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let 1998 be the year that we get commitments from candidates
to do something meaningful to fulfill the dream. And let 1998 also
be the year in which the American people turn out in massive
numbers to say no to the politics of polarization, no to the
politics of intimidation, gossip and vilification,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
