<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2785 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-13 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET CAUTION BE YOUR GUIDE ON WHITEWATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Toll-free information number is CQ.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hey, now I admit it: I was scared to death.
</P>
<P>
   Petrified actually, heart thumping in my chest, short of breath,
eyes about to pop out of my head, and suddenly converted to prayer.
</P>
<P>
   I was paddling an inflatable kayak, pointed downstream, about to
enter this sharp right turn with a high, granite wall along the
left side, sparkling with whitewater from a Class IV rapid. Right
at the turn, there was a big boulder at mid-current, so there was
no way to cheat the rapid on the inside of the current line. I had
to go through.
</P>
<P>
   Was I really ready for this? That is the exact question
thousands of vacationers ask themselves every year as they embark
on outdoors adventures. In the case of rafting, that question is
coming up a lot more this year, with high water from the meltoff of
the big El Nino snowpack and a few highly celebrated accidents, far
more than reported in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   The snowmelt has peaked, according to the Department of Water
Resources, and a recent aerial survey showed that most of the snow
had melted off in the north Sierra. The snow line is roughly 6,500
to 7,500 feet in Yosemite, and 9,500 feet in the south Sierra near
Mount Whitney, with the deepest pockets of snow remaining in the
highest terrain in the Trinity Alps, localized vicinity of Shasta
and Lassen peaks, and the central Sierra along the crest.
</P>
<P>
   That means two things:
</P>
<P>
   1. Conditions are now about perfect for whitewater rafting, with
good stream flows from snowmelt, yet hot summer temperatures in the
Sierra foothills. This should continue on most streams well into
August, and some rivers through September.
</P>
<P>
   2. At some point, you will likely say to yourself, ``Am I really
ready for this?''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among an organization of 50 outfitters called
California Outdoors is that the danger level of whitewater trips is
elevated by inexperienced individuals trying the sport without
guides, or when rogue guides without permits try daredevil runs on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best rafting in 15 years and we encourage the
public to enjoy their trips with well-trained professionals rather
than on your own in private parties,'' said Diane Strachan of
California Outdoors. ``Many private rafting parties do not have the
river experience and skills to safely enjoy this El Nino summer
season.''
</P>
<P>
   She said professional outfitters take roughly 335,000 people
rafting each summer in California, while another 165,000 try on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   Rafting danger has made the news this year because there have
been 13 deaths in California attributed to high water. However, 11
of those were on non-guided trips. In a typical year, such as 1996,
there were three fatal accidents on rivers, all non-guided trips;
in comparison, there were 17 fatal boating accidents on lakes in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   While there are many whitewater experts who can make safe trips
without guides, I've personally seen some near tragedies by those
trying the do-it-yourself method, from expert kayakers to kids on
inner tubes.
</P>
<P>
   At the Smith River, I watched a team of 10 expert kayakers
plundering down the South Fork at high water, coming around a bend,
one after another. Everything was perfect until the last kayak
arrived around the bend: It was floating down the river upside
down. All the others in the group were looking downstream, unaware
that the poor guy behind them was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   As fortune would have it, the force of the river spun him into
calm water by an eddy, where he managed an Eskimo roll to right
himself, then grabbed on to a rock, and stayed there for 15
minutes, trying to catch his breath. That was a close one.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, on the Sacramento River in Red Bluff, where the
flows are benign but cold, a group of youngsters was spending a day
rolling down the river on inner tubes. One problem: No life
jackets. They started horsing around, and a teen-age girl fell off
her tube and into the cold water; she started splashing about,
shocked by the temperature, and became separated from her tube.
From shore, it looked like a disaster about to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the current swept her to a support piling for a bridge,
and she was able to grab ahold of it and scramble out of the river.
But she was still stuck. An hour later, a rescue team got her to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   To keep whitewater trips exciting but safe, Strachan suggests
matching up the age and experience level with the difficulty of the
trips, interviewing outfitters, and if any doubts linger, asking
for references.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are over 20 excellent river trips in California,'' she
said. ``What makes it work is matching up with the one that is
perfect for you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On my inflatable kayak trip, looking at that Class IV right turn
and granite wall, I had scarcely asked, ``Am I ready for this?'' _
when suddenly, my boat was surging right toward the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, I was in a vortex of whitewater, plunging forward,
the boat full of water. I leaned left, toward the wall, and paddled
hard on the left side, just as guide Steve Lentz had told me to,
and the boat shot into the main current. But a cross-current hit
me, and in a split second, I flipped and dumped, and the cold shock
of water enveloped me.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, I popped up in quiet water, downstream of the
rapid, and Lentz was nearby in his raft, smiling. Later he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never let people get into something they can't get out of,''
he said. ``In 20 years, I've never had a client have a serious
water accident. Rafting is exhilarating, thrilling, and it can get
all your senses on fire, but there's no reason it has to be
dangerous. There should always be a way out.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For a free directory of 50 California outfitters and the rivers
they specialize in, phone 800-552-3625.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
