<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2789 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      07-13 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE WATCH: ADVICE FOR 1-DAY NONSMOKERS; RECIPE FOR QUICKIE
DIAMONDS; LIVING FOR NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Natural experiments are those in which nature designs the test
of some hypothesis and the only effort required of the scientist is
to figure out what experiment is being conducted in nature's
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   A well-known example comes from the practice of English
congregations of praying every Sunday for the long life of the
monarch; the geneticist Francis Galton reasoned that the power of
prayer would be proved if indeed English monarchs tended to live
longer than average, an eventuality which he determined was, alas,
not the case.
</P>
<P>
   Not Smoking Proves Point
</P>
<P>
   English public life has afforded another natural experiment, and
one that regrettably is also subversive of public virtue.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1984, the second Wednesday of every March has been
designated No Smoking Day. Some 2 million British smokers, whether
impelled by guilt or the opprobrium of their peers, give up the
noxious weed, or gasp in less of it, for at least one day.
</P>
<P>
   It is well known that in laboratory tests, when smokers suddenly
abstain from nicotine, for a few hours afterward their mental
performance falls and their bad humor rises.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Andrew Waters, of the Institute of Psychiatry in London,
realized that No Smoking Day provided the perfect opportunity to
test whether this was true in the real world, too.
</P>
<P>
   It was. Significantly more workplace accidents occur on No
Smoking Day than on the Wednesday before or the Wednesday after,
according to statistics collected by the British government agency
that monitors workplace safety.
</P>
<P>
   In noting this finding in the current Nature, Waters and
colleagues say they do not want anyone to infer that No Smoking Day
is a bad idea, but that maybe those one-day quitters should take
some nicotine substitutes instead of going cold turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Diamonds in the Rough
</P>
<P>
   On the avarice front, a simple recipe for cooking up diamonds
has been devised by Dr. Yadong Li and colleagues at the University
of Science and Technology of China.
</P>
<P>
   Take a spoonful of the solvent and former dry cleaning agent
carbon tetrachloride, add an ounce of sodium metal and a pinch of
nickel-cobalt catalyst, and cook in an oven at 700 degrees Celsius
for two days. The result is a lot of table salt (sodium chloride)
and a 2 percent yield of diamond, Li and colleagues report in
Science. The diamonds are not of gem quality. You need a microscope
to see them, but Li is working to improve the process.
</P>
<P>
   Live by Numbers
</P>
<P>
   To hear it for virtue, consider the Hungarian mathematician Paul
Erdos (pronounced AIR-dosh). To devote his life as purely as
possible to pure mathematics, Erdos forsook all other distractions,
including family, home and money. He lived out of two battered
suitcases, traveling from one mathematician's house to another. He
would show up on the friend's doorstep, announcing, ``My brain is
open.'' They would work together for a day or two, then Erdos would
move on.
</P>
<P>
   Erdos had a special vocabulary. He loved epsilons, his word for
children, after the Greek letter used in mathematics to denote a
small number. He endured much bureaucratic foolishness at the hands
of Joe (the Soviet Union) and Sam (the United States). He referred
to international news as the Sam and Joe show. When he said someone
had died, he meant that the person had left mathematics. When he
said they had left, they had died.
</P>
<P>
   Erdos left in 1996. Two biographies are about to appear. ``The
Man Who Loved Only Numbers,'' by Paul Hoffman, is published this
week by Hyperion of New York. In September, Houghton-Mifflin
publishes ``My Brain Is Open,'' by Bruce Schechter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
