<P>
   CEMENT-SHORTAGE (undated) Tight supplies of concrete could slow
the breakneck pace of home building and commercial construction in
some parts of the country, and suppliers in the Kansas City area
say spot shortages are expected soon. Two takes. By ERIC PALMER.
Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION-MAGIC-KANSAS (undated) When a new TV show gets off to
a less-than-auspicious start, it's customary for the producers to
tell the on-camera talent to ``ignore the critics'' and ``just go
out and do a good show.''
</P>
<P>
   Earvin Johnson, erstwhile basketballer and now host of a
late-night talk show, found himself unable to do either on the
night of July 2, when Howard Stern was his guest.
</P>
<P>
   Since Johnson's ``The Magic Hour'' signed on in early June,
Stern has made a morning ritual out of roasting the previous
night's broadcast on his nationally syndicated radio show. Yet
Johnson and his producers hatched the nutty idea that it would be
great TV to have Stern on the show. Commentary. Story by AARON
BARNHART. Story will move in the ``e'' category.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SILVA-KANSAS (undated) Jill Wendholt Silva, food editor for
the Kansas City Star, writes a column each week about nutrition and
cooking. Story will move in the ``l'' category.
