A2798 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN14-C     07-13 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As athlete defies odds, community rallies to help her meet goals
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Grandma was talking about her red-headed,
17-year-old granddaughter _ Erin Wiedemann _ one of the best
teen-age softball players in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's an all-around good girl,'' Alice Caldwell said Friday at
her Willamet Road home in Kettering. ``She would never even think
of doing something out of the question. She's wonderful, beautiful
_ quite a little athlete. She's the kind of girl everyone would
love to have as a daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Every parent, that is, but her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad? I think he might be somewhere in Florida. I really
don't know him,'' Erin said. ``He's a guy who never lived up to his
responsibilities. He left when I was just a couple of months old. I
know he has no idea who I am or what I've become.''
</P>
<P>
   And mom?
</P>
<P>
   ``She lives in Dayton somewhere. She was young when she had me.
She had a lot of problems _ still does I guess _ and it just didn't
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   When she was five months, Erin _ known in the family as Boo
because she was born on Halloween _ came to live with her
grandparents. So did her brother, Todd, who was 3.
</P>
<P>
   After raising six kids of her own, Alice suddenly had two more
under her wing: ``A couple of mine fell by the wayside and I wanted
to get involved so it didn't happen to Todd and Erin. They needed
someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Erin's dad had battled drugs and ended up in prison. Her mom had
similar problems. And if that wasn't enough, in June of 1992, Todd,
then 14, was hit and killed by a teen-age driver while
roller-blading on Grange Hall Road.
</P>
<P>
   With all of her immediate family gone, Erin could rely only on
her grandparents _ and herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since she was a little child, she's had all kinds of goals for
herself,'' Alice said. ``She got involved in the D.A.R.E. program
at school. I think underneath it was about wanting to be so
different than her parents. She wanted to make something of
herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into her senior year at Fairmont High, Erin said she has a
3.5 grade-point average.
</P>
<P>
   Athletically, she's won six letters in soccer, basketball and
especially softball, where last season she won first-team All
Western Ohio League honors and was named to the second team
All-State. She led the Miami Valley in triples, runs scored and
stolen bases and was sixth in batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the jobs she works. She's a resident caregiver at
a nursing home on Lamme Road. During the school year, she served as
an ice guard at the Kettering Recreation Center skating rink.
Weekends she worked 7 p.m. to 5 a.m. Friday and Saturday and all
day Sunday, too.
</P>
<P>
   She's trying to save money to buy a car and take care of other
needs. ``Both my grandparents are retired and have health
problems,'' she said. ``I don't want to make it any tougher on them
by asking for things, so I try to do as much as I can for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Erin Wiedemann can't do it all. She wants to go to college
_ specifically the University of Dayton _ and she needs help. ``I
want to stay around this area to take care of my grandparents, ``
Erin said. ``My grandmother has arthritis real bad. She just had a
knee replaced and needs the other one fixed. My grandfather has
emphysema. They did so much for me, it's my turn for them. I know
they'd try to help me get to college, but there's no way. Without a
scholarship, I won't be going to a four-year school.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's where the Miami Valley Sports Foundation _ which
sponsored The King and His Court in a celebrity softball game at
Welcome Stadium _ comes in.
</P>
<P>
   The Foundation is a local group made up of professional and
blue-collar men and women who four years ago set their sights on
bringing a minor-league baseball team to Dayton. Along the way,
they scrapped that idea, but kept their organization together and
decided to gear their efforts to helping some of the Miami Valley's
best athletes achieve excellence in sports and in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   The Foundation is in the process of converting an old K-Mart
store in Centerville, Ohio into a sporting facility that will offer
specific workout areas for several Olympic sports _ from softball,
baseball and basketball to the martial arts.
</P>
<P>
   According to Centerville attorney Richard Duncan, Foundation
president, there will be instructors, sports-medicine and fitness
programs, and a concentration on academics _ from preparing
athletes for SAT tests to helping them land a scholarship by
sending out resumes and videos and providing showcase athletic
events for the teenagers to be seen by college coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The Foundation currently has five softball and three baseball
teams competing in the area, including the Miami Valley Express _
for which Erin plays second base _ in the Greater Cincinnati
Fast-pitch League.
</P>
<P>
   Besides league play, the Express _ which includes girls from 10
area high schools _ plays weekend tournaments around the state.
Recently it was in Akron. And the GCFL will hold its All-Star game
to which, Duncan said, 68 college coaches have been invited:
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do whatever we can to get these kids in school, so they
can go after their dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   For Erin _ who idolizes Dr. Dot Richardson, the Olympic softball
player who is an orthopedic surgeon _ that means some kind of
medical studies: ``I'd like to be a CareFlight nurse, maybe even an
emergency-room doctor. When somebody's really in need, they need to
know someone is there who really cares.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, that's just what the Miami Valley Sports Foundation
will end up being for athletes like Erin.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Archdeacon writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
