<SLUG> BC-MCCOY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perez handles difficulty with class
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX, Az _ That afternoon, Eduardo Perez cleaned out his
locker in Cinergy Field _ lock, stock and baseball spikes.
</P>
<P>
   The next afternoon, Perez was sitting in front of his locker in
Bank One Ballpark, still wearing his Cincinnati Reds uniform.
</P>
<P>
   How bizarre, how bizarre, how bizarre. With the Cincinnati Reds,
things continue to get curiouser and curiouser and curiouser.
</P>
<P>
   True, curiouser is not a word but what is happening with the
Reds these days defies normal description.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday July 9, Perez thought his time with the Reds was up.
He was put on waivers and he cleared _ nobody claimed him. Perez
expected to be designated for assignment, meaning the Reds had to
trade him, release him or offer him free agency.
</P>
<P>
   So he cleaned out his locker.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen. The Reds kept him on the roster, even though
he is No. 4 on the first-base depth chart behind Sean Casey, Paul
Konerko and Dmitri Young.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Perez won't be traded. If a deal can be made,
it'll be made. If not, he may be released.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, Perez wore his normal ultra-bright, ultra-wide
smile Friday afternoon as he slipped into his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand. . .you can see what they're doing,'' Perez said.
``They're building toward a winner by 2002 or whenever the new
stadium is built and going with young guys who will be in their
first or second year of arbitration eligibility. Hopefully, the
Reds will have the funds to pay these guys as they build from the
bottom up.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez was one of the guys who stepped forward last season after
Ray Knight was fired and Jack McKeon was hired. McKeon gave Perez a
chance and he hooked it. So he began this season as the regular
first baseman, but quickly found himself on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   And to his credit, he didn't squawk, kick or fuss. He did what
was asked of him and did it with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be 33 years old in 2002 and I certainly wouldn't fit,''
Perez said. ``Baseball is a business and everybody has to realize
it and I realize I'm a victim of the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told they're looking to see if I fit with another
organization and I respect (general manager) Jim Bowden for doing
that,'' Perez added. ``We talked about that Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to be a Red and enjoy being a Red and I was
always proud to wear this uniform,'' he said. ``I'm just trying to
be a professional about it, not be a bad apple. I've kept my smiles
up and kept some of the young guys who struggled loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is so tough _ because I love this team so much _ to see
stuff going on with Barry Larkin, who has played for nobody but the
Reds, and to see Lenny Harris and Jeff Shaw and Dave Burba get sent
away,'' Perez said. ``But like I have to keep telling myself,
that's the business part of baseball. But it's a big family and
it's a family that is being broken up and everybody is going their
own way. It's sad. It's tough to deal with the realities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be here to see it or feel it, but the key
word for Cincinnati fans right now is, 'patience,' and that's with
a capital P.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez was speaking softly now and he laced on his red shoes,
perhaps for one of the last times. His name was not on the lineup
card, it seldom is these days. Nevertheless, they can rip the
uniform off his back, but they can't tear it out of his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, but what can I do? Nothing. I can't beg to stay
here,'' he said. ``I can't cry. I have to keep my chin up, as tough
as that is. I realize I am a good ballplayer and I have to continue
to believe in myself. Given an opportunity, I'll produce. That's
all I can ask. If they want me to stay here and be a stunt man
(extra player), as Lenny Harris called it, I'll do that. Lenny
thought that, too. And he's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
