 &HT;    Jane Greig's consumer column
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Q: Couldn't we save trouble and time by endorsing
checks on the front, lower left? This would make it easier to
compare the information with the signatures. It would also save the
great difficulty in copying the back side, which could be used as a
deposit slip, saving tons paper and storage space.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think? _Harold B.
</P>
<P>
   A: A provocative idea but the
</P>
<P>
   endorsement on the back of a check is a processing requirement
from the American National Standards Institute, adopted by the
American Bankers Association, says the ABA's John Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement by the payee is just the beginning of the
information that will grace the back of the check _ other payees
and several banking institutions will also use the back (and that's
just if the check does not bounce!). In addition, the magnetic
encoding on the front of a check is adversely affected by ink.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have an antique oak mirror that belonged to my great aunt.
The glass has become spotted and discolored in places over time and
I am thinking of having it reglazed. Whom would you recommend?
_Michael Grable
</P>
<P>
   A: Maxey Glass, 305 E. Fifth St., has been resilvering mirrors
for more than 40 years. The process removes the old silver, which
has been damaged by moisture, insects and chemicals. A new silver
layer, a new copper layer and sealer will be applied to the mirror.
The glass remains the same, so remember some scratches may be more
visible after the resilvering than before!
</P>
<P>
   Call ahead for price estimation. Resilvering is good economic
sense for beveled, etched or patterned mirrors. If the antique had
just a plain mirror, buy a new one. The job can be done in 14-20
working days.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a money belt. It looks like a regular belt
but has a zipper on its back. I wonder if anyone in Austin sells
them or is there a place I could order one?
</P>
<P>
   I am going to Vegas soon and need one to take money. Probably
won't need one for the return trip. _B.K.
</P>
<P>
   A: A web money belt is available in three colors at REI, 9901
Loop 360, for a mere $12. But for the look of Charles Grodin in
``Midnight Run,'' call TravelSmith at (800) 995-7010. They have a
few leather belts (the end of stock so they may go quickly!) with
the inside back zipper for $29.50 May Sky Masterson be with you!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
