<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2807 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SOUTHERN-KANSAS-     07-13 1510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SOUTHERN-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN COMFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The prune cheesecake at the Magnolia Grill in
Durham, N.C., wasn't selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be (that) anytime you put the word `prune' on the
menu, people would get to that point and they'd just look at each
other and laugh!'' admits pastry chef Karen Barker.
</P>
<P>
   So, using a bit of what chef Ben Barker refers to as
`menuspeak,' he renamed the dessert sun-dried plum cheesecake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, instead, we get all these people telling us how much they
enjoy those sun-dried plums!'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Barkers, one of a handful of high-profile husband-and-wife
chef teams working in cities across the country, were in Kansas
City recently to teach a cooking class at the American Restaurant,
which also features its own husband-and-wife chef team in Michael
Smith and Debbie Gold.
</P>
<P>
   The Barkers have appeared in Food &AMP; Wine's Who's Who of Southern
Cooking, have been named rising stars in Esquire and have been
James Beard nominees. Yet the culinary accolades sometimes leave
them wondering if disguising the prune's wrinkles from diners is
always such a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry that if you win that award (the James Beard Award),
then people come into your restaurant looking for something
different, looking for something other than what we are and what
we've done for the last 10 years,'' Ben says.
</P>
<P>
   What the Barkers have been doing for the last decade is turning
out rustic Southern fare _ with notable refinements. For instance,
Karen's silky, pecan-infused custard has a long history in Southern
cooking, dating to early English settlers. Meanwhile Ben's savory
short ribs served with grits has found a resurgence among a
fine-dining audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time we couldn't serve braised food, which is one
of the hardest foods to do. And, because of their inherent
rusticity _ read brownness! _ they don't photograph well, but they
sure taste good!''
</P>
<P>
   Ben grew up in the South. His paternal grandmother and a great
aunt were farm-raised cooks who served fresh bread, home-preserved
condiments and a variety of vegetables dishes with each meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Southern table was generally presented to us without much
fanfare,'' he says. ``It often wasn't so much specifically what was
on it, as the fact that you were there at the table with your
family or your friends. It was a moment for storytelling and
regaining the relationship that we don't get in our daily lives
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Although Karen's desserts display a fondness for the South, she
grew up in Brooklyn and comes from a Jewish family. She laughs as
she recalls a recent Passover celebration where Ben reigned in any
tendencies to create ``New Age'' gefilte fish. Instead, he played
it straight, and her family nodded its approval by taking home the
leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of us came from a family where the table was really
important,'' Ben says.
</P>
<P>
   The couple met on the first day of classes at the Culinary
Institute of America. They opened their restaurant in a converted
health food grocery in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many fine-dining restaurants, the Magnolia Grill does not
have a dress code.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we fine dining? Yes. There are tablecloths. We have
professional, although not stuffy, service,'' Karen says. ``It has
all the components of fine dining, but it's not so upscale that you
can't walk in there in a pair of jeans and have the most expensive
bottle of wine and foie gras.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Ben says he is complimented by those serious diners
who dutifully analyze a dish's flavors before passing it to the
left, but he prefers a more relaxed approach to his food.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's more important to me is people sit at a table and have
a glass of wine and enjoy the sociability of it,'' Ben says.
``That's really why we went into (the restaurant business) in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't often sit down with your family for dinner anymore.
Often the restaurant venue is one of those rare and infrequent
opportunities to recapture that thing that you don't have at
home.''
Smoked trout carpaccio with pickled ramp and roasted beet salad
Makes 8 servings Pickled ramps:
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Cheesecloth sachet (10 whole black peppercorns, 2 bay leaves, 4
whole cloves and 4 allspice berries)
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ramps, green tops and stems trimmed and washed in
several changes of water (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Smoked trout carpaccio:
</P>
<P>
   14 ounces skinless, smoked trout filet (available at gourmet
specialty stores, such as Dean &AMP; DeLuca)
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil spray
</P>
<P>
   Tarragon vinaigrette:
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup tarragon vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh horseradish, grated
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Red beet vinaigrette:
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces red beets, roasted, peeled and grated
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup tarragon vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salad:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound watercress, cleaned
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces gold or chioggia beets, roasted, peeled and sliced into
batons
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   For ramps: In a nonreactive saucepan, combine vinegar, water,
sugar, salt and cheesecloth sachet; bring to a boil. Add ramps and
return to a boil. Remove from heat and cool in pickling liquid.
Transfer to clean glass or stainless steel container. Refrigerate.
Best after two days. Keeps 3 to 4 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For trout: Divide trout into 1 1/2- to 1 3/4-ounce portions.
Lightly spray a sheet of plastic wrap with vegetable spray, place 1
portion of trout on wrap and cover with another piece of sprayed
wrap. Pound gently, working from the middle to the outside to form
a nearly translucent circle about 8 inches in diameter. Repeat with
remaining portions. Refrigerate up to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   For tarragon vinaigrette: Combine shallots, 1/4 cup tarragon
vinegar, horseradish and 1/4 cup olive oil. Season with salt and
pepper; reserve.
</P>
<P>
   For red beet vinaigrette: In a bowl, combine red beets, add 1/4
cup tarragon vinegar and mustard. Whisk in 1/4 cup olive oil.
Season to taste with salt and pepper; reserve.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Remove trout from refrigerator 30 minutes before
serving. Remove plastic wrap and place on a large 10-inch serving
plate. Toss watercress with gold beet batons, tarragon vinaigrette,
herbs and salt and pepper. Divide salad onto center of carpaccio.
Spoon red beet vinaigrette and pickled ramps around salad and onto
trout.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Ramp is a wild onion that grows from Canada to the
Carolinas. It resembles a green onion with broad leaves and has an
assertive, garlicky-onion flavor. Ramps are typically only
available at specialty produce markets from March to June. You may
substitute leeks, green onions or onions instead.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 376 calories (40 percent from fat), 17 grams total
fat (2 grams saturated), 29 milligrams cholesterol, 41 grams
carbohydrates, 19 grams protein, 907 milligrams sodium, 3 grams
dietary fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _ From Ben Barker, chef at the Magnolia Grill
Toasted pecan pot de creme with bananas brulee Makes 6 (1-cup)
ramekins
</P>
<P>
   2 cups toasted pecan pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar, plus additional sugar to caramelize
</P>
<P>
   8 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 medium perfectly ripe bananas
</P>
<P>
   Mint sprigs, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Place toasted pecan pieces in a food processor with a steel
blade and process until finely ground.
</P>
<P>
   In a heavy-bottomed saucepan, combine nuts with cream. Bring to
a simmer. Remove from heat and allow nuts to steep in cream at
least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a stainless steel bowl, combine sugar, egg yolks, salt and
vanilla; whisk together.
</P>
<P>
   Reheat cream mixture to just under a simmer. Strain through a
fine mesh strainer, pressing on nuts slightly to extract as much
cream as possible; discard nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Use a portion of the warm pecan cream to slowly warm egg yolks.
Gradually whisk in remaining cream. Strain custard mixture through
a fine mesh strainer and divide evenly among ramekins.
</P>
<P>
   Place ramekins in a hot water bath. Cover with foil and bake at
325 degrees until custards are just barely set (about 90 minutes,
but check often as this can vary enormously).
</P>
<P>
   Remove ramekins from water bath, cool, cover and refrigerate
several hours or up to 2 days.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, slice bananas approximately 1/4-inch thick
on the bias. Place slices, overlapping, on top of each pot de
creme, covering entire surface. Sprinkle bananas with additional
sugar using a torch to caramelize evenly. Garnish with mint and
serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (1 ramekin): 900 calories (77 percent from fat), 79
grams total fat (40 grams saturated), 501 milligrams cholesterol,
43 grams carbohydrates, 9 grams protein, 160 milligrams sodium, 2
grams dietary fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _ From Karen Barker, pastry chef at the Magnolia Grill
</P>
</TEXT>
