<HEADLINE>
JUST A TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Barbecue. It's not just for breakfast anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the Kansas City Barbeque Society's motto.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that smell?'' you ask as your cornflakes and milk turn
to mush. Why it's a whiff of KC barbecue on the ``Today Show.''
Co-host Matt Laurer will interview local 'que aficionados Carolyn
Wells, executive director of the KCBS, and Paul Kirk, the
award-winning Baron of Barbecue and cookbook author, for a segment
on regional barbecue styles. It's scheduled to air Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most wonderful opportunity to showcase barbecue _ and
particularly Kansas City barbecue _ for the rest of the world,''
Wells says.
</P>
<P>
   The call from NBC came shortly after Wells played host for the
KC leg of a BBC TV crew's series on American barbecue. Last spring
Wells and Kirk also were invited to cook for a Julia Child benefit
held in Portland, Ore., which was attended by the renowned cooking
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all this interest in barbecue is just too cool,''
Wells says.
</P>
<P>
   For their ``Today'' show appearance, Wells and Kirk will rise
with the roosters and head for the NBC studios where they will
explain how to prepare ``wet'' ribs, burnt ends, lamb chops and
brisket.
</P>
<P>
   The duo is scheduled to appear midway through the four-part
segment. Other guests will include John Willingham of Memphis; Jeff
Shivers of Arlington, Texas; and Jim Tabb of Tyron, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   After the live show the newscasters and crew will chow down on,
you guessed it, barbecue, that other breakfast of champions.
</P>
<P>
   Soggy cereal
</P>
<P>
   And it's back to that rather unappetizing bowl of soggy cereal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everybody's pet peeve, but nobody ever does anything
about it,'' says Kevin Shamy, the father of four and food broker
who lives and works in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of dumping his kids' half-eaten bowls of cereal down the
drain, Shamy has taken it upon himself to rid the world of limp,
milk-soaked mush by creating a slanted cereal bowl that allows
gravity to feed dry cereal into the milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple solution, but it really works,'' Shamy says.
``Besides, just about everybody eats cereal, and the cereal
companies spend a lot of money promoting crisp-this and Cap'n
Crunch-that, so obviously there's a market.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard plastic bowls retail for $14.95 for a set of three.
Shamy claims they can pay for themselves in 30 days and save up to
$300 a year in soggy cereal. They're available by calling
1-888-550-2695 or on the Internet at NewAngle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
