<HEADER>
A2810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPLIT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     07-13 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPLIT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPLIT: A COUNTERCULTURE CHILDHOOD': COMING TO TERMS WITH PROTEST
AND DIVORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., production notes are at the end of the review) 
 (HLW)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a college student at UCLA in the 1980s, Lisa Michaels recalls
in her affecting new memoir, she sported a tiny red and gold
Chairman Mao pin on her duffel bag. It was less a political
statement than an act of nostalgia, a tiny nod to her childhood as
the daughter of a radical activist.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 3, Ms. Michaels was photographed for Life
magazine, waving a Vietcong flag. By 8, she was playing at protest,
marching about the backyard with a bedsheet and broomstick flag,
shouting ``Ethiopia!'' Her father would have her evaluate her
summertime visits with him, applying a little of Mao's ``criticism,
self-criticism'' to the domestic sphere, while her stepmother
inscribed one of her birthday presents, a book on Chinese
revolutionary youth, with the exhortation ``Dare to struggle, dare
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it would be easy to caricature her '60s childhood or turn
her parents into cartoon radicals, Lisa Michaels, a contributing
editor at The Threepenny Review, does a beautifully nuanced job of
conjuring up her youth in both its anomalous and ordinary detail.
Her memoir, ``Split,'' is distinguished by its snapshots of
counterculture life (the author describes life on the road in a
mail van, and her visits to communes, labor meetings and protest
rallies) and by its sensitive evocation of her conflicted, loving
and sometimes tortured efforts to come to terms with her parents _
not just with their unorthodox life style, but also with their
divorce, their remarriages and their idealism and fervor.
</P>
<P>
   Although her mother's laissez-faire, hippie-style parenting left
the young Ms. Michaels as ``wild as a baby goat'' _ as a baby, she
recalls, she ``ate whole sticks of butter, bit anyone who crossed
me'' _ she longed for a more conventional upbringing. She remembers
asking her mother and stepfather to teach her table manners, and
later coaxing her mother to wear more makeup so she would look more
like her schoolmates' mothers, ``ranchers' wives who leaned toward
peroxide and blue eyeshadow.'' In college, when other students were
protesting the university's ownership of South African stocks, she
recalls, she remained ``more worried about my grade point average
than the school's investment portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Ms. Michaels' ambivalence toward politics stemmed in
part from the realization that her father's activism was
responsible for his absence from her early life. Her parents split
up when she was four months old, and her father began spending less
and less time with her, after he joined the Weathermen, a splinter
group of Students for a Democratic Society, in 1969. Later that
year, he was arrested during an antiwar protest and began serving a
two-year prison term for assault and battery.
</P>
<P>
   Though the teen-age Ms. Michaels would spend considerable time
with her father, he remained for many years ``a ghost presence'' in
her life, kept alive by the stories about him that she would tell
her friends.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Ms. Michaels writes, when she confronted her father
about his decision to put politics before family, he replied, ``I
felt terrible to leave you, but it was a very important moment in
history, and there was so much at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always tried to be conscious of you,'' he went on, ``but
I've been on my own trip, and I don't think that's a bad thing _ I
don't think the only positive value I can have as a parent is to
keep everything safe and stable. We're living in a very dangerous
time, families are falling apart under the strain, and I'm trying
to do something about that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of Ms. Michaels' affection for her parents _ and
her earnest, scrupulously fair-minded account _ that her father
does not emerge from this book as a self-absorbed scoundrel, but as
a passionate, if often misguided, man, who loved her despite his
preoccupation with politics. Yet at the same time, Ms. Michaels
makes palpable the emotional fallout of growing up with his
ferocious convictions: constant feelings of guilt about the modest
comforts of her life (``I did nothing to deserve them; I had come
to them by chance, and chance might take them away'') and a deep
longing to be more like others (``I wanted to slip into the bland
flow of passers-by; I wanted to live a life that aroused no
suspicion or trouble'').
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Michaels found herself internalizing her father's
paranoia and all his talk about wiretaps and the police. ``More
than my father ever did, I believed in a faceless governmental
will,'' she writes. ``His fears were concrete. He feared phone
taps; he feared inflated charges and prison, no doubt, having faced
them before. My fears were more vague than that, more high-flown
and Orwellian, though I hadn't read Orwell yet. I was a
pure-blooded conspiracy theorist at 12, the product of bad nerves
and little information.''
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Split'' grows somewhat fuzzy when it gets to the
author's college years _ too many pages spent chronicling the usual
adolescent problems about what to wear, whom to date, what to major
in _ it remains, for the most part, a lucidly written, highly
evocative memoir, a memoir that ratifies Ms. Michaels' observation
that she watched her parents ``far more closely'' than she listened
to them. It also demonstrates her eloquence as a witness to all
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   SPLIT: A COUNTERCULTURE CHILDHOOD.
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Michaels
</P>
<P>
   307 pages. Houghton Mifflin. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
