<SLUG> BC-RAZOR-MACH-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPE OR SHAVE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now here's something different: a new razor that promises
(gasp!) THE CLOSEST, SMOOTHEST, SAFEST, MOST TECHNOLOGICALLY
ADVANCED GEE-GOLLY UNBELIEVABLE SHAVE ON THE PLANET!
</P>
<P>
   Honest. Would Madison Avenue lie to you?
</P>
<P>
   Ho, ho! Don't make us laugh.
</P>
<P>
   So pay attention, America. Here come the ads. Here comes the
hype. Here comes the only $750 million, computer designed,
``revolutionary'' triple bladed ``shaving system'' the world has
ever known.
</P>
<P>
   Here comes (drum roll, please) The Gillette Mach3!
</P>
<P>
   Hailed in no less than The New Yorker as ``the billion dollar
blade,'' and a product that ``may make five-o'clock shadow a thing
of the past,'' the Mach3 is simply the most extensively (and
expensively) researched razor in the history of shaving. It was
developed over the last seven years with cutting-edge metallurgy
and computer imaging technology by shaving scientists at the Los
Alamos of razor research, a large Gillette lab near Reading,
England.
</P>
<P>
   Never heard of the Mach3?
</P>
<P>
   You will. Over the next few months Gillette plans a $300 million
marketing blitzkrieg, the largest in the company's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge,'' said Stephen East, a business analyst at A.G.
Edwards in St. Louis. Gillette is ``betting the farm on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   And how's this for a neat publicity stunt? When the razor was
shipped to stores late last month, Gillette chairman Alfred Zein
announced its availability at the New York Stock Exchange. Standing
beside him was exchange president William R. Johnston, who appeared
for the first time in 17 years without his beard. He had shaved it
moments earlier with _ you guessed it _ the Mach3.
</P>
<P>
   So what's so ``revolutionary'' about the Mach3?
</P>
<P>
   According to Gillette, it's not just the world's first
triple-bladed razor. It has the thinnest blade edges Gillette has
ever made, and its open-backed (for easier cleaning) cartridge lies
flat to the face and pivots in ways other razors can't.
</P>
<P>
   The result _ which Gillette says can be demonstrated by 3-D
computer images that provide 40 times normal magnification _ is a
closer shave with fewer strokes and less irritation.
</P>
<P>
   But wait a minute. Haven't we heard this before? Doesn't
virtually every razor on the market say it offers the closest
shave, too? And just how close can a razor get, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   More on that later.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to see how the Mach3 rated, we gave it to five
barbers and stylists in the Kansas City area to see what they
thought.
</P>
<P>
   - Damian Becerra, a stylist at Alfredo's Hair Design on the
Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shaver was sweet,'' he said. ``I shave almost every day.
(Currently) I use a Gillette Sensor Excel. But this one was better
because I just shave down, and when I brush my fingers up against
the way the hair grows it's not as rough. And I liked the way it
pivoted, like when it came down around my cheekbone the top of it
bent a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   - Darren W. Cole, barber at the Ivy League Barber Shop, 4438
Prospect Ave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was AS CLOSE AS YOU CAN GET WITHOUT ACTUALLY USING A
STRAIGHT RAZOR,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The best he's used so far?
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt,'' he said. ``It would run me away from my Bic
or any other kind of safety razor easily. It was comfortable. It
was just the glide. It moved right along my face. It was very
smooth. No irritation at all. I liked it a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   - Tom Alexander, a barber at the Grand Avenue Barbershop, 1817A
Grand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's closer (than a straight razor) and your face feels
better,'' he said. ``If a man hadn't shaved for a week it might be
a different story. But I tell you, you couldn't even feel the cut.
That's about as good a razor as I ever shaved with.''
</P>
<P>
   - Leslie Cavallaro, barber//stylist at the Plaza Executive
Barber Shop, 328 W. 47th St.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was very unusual and hard to get used to because
it has a flatter head to it. Then I noticed that by using that
flatter head it seemed to go over the skin a lot better. ... I
don't know if it's going to work with guys who have cleft chins or
a little sharper jaws if it would nick or cut easier. But I have a
little rounder face and it seemed to move real easy across my face.
I don't think it was the best shave I ever had ... but I guarantee
you it's a very comfortable shave.''
</P>
<P>
   - Sonny Noland, barber at the Brookside Barber Shop, 308 W. 63rd
St.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shaved without softening my beard up first, and it did a
great job. The only problem I had was the sideburns. Where to hit
them, because it was so big with the three blades that I didn't
know where to put it. But it worked out OK. I think it's great. It
sold me.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone. East, the analyst, said the Mach3 irritated
his heavily stubbled face.
</P>
<P>
   How do competitors view the Mach3?
</P>
<P>
   Jason Ford, a spokesman for Schick razors, said Schick won't
wilt under the Mach3's onslaught. After all, he said, that
company's been scoring well with its newest razor, the Protector.
That razor features a lubricating ``comfort strip'' and blades
wrapped in micro-fine safety wires to prevent nicks and cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Protector, Schick's second-quarter profits rose 31
percent to $32 million, Ford said. And recently, an author
reviewing Gillette's new entry pronounced Schick's razor decidedly
less irritating than the Mach3.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of hype about the (Mach3), but the bottom line
is does it give you a good shave?'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Ritchie Lowry, a professor of sociology at
Boston College, who just doesn't care. With all the other things to
worry about, he said, the idea of spending a billion dollars on a
closer shave is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just waste,'' he said. ``They have to tell you not to use
your old razor _ in many cases the same razor they told you just
last year was fantastic! _ because it's no longer good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the dilemmas of a capitalist society: You keep
needing more and more markets. But when it comes to a razor, how
close of a shave do you really need?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
