<HEADER>
A2813 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELEVISION-MAGIC-KANS     07-13 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEVISION-MAGIC-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S MAGIC TO DO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 AARON BARNHART  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a new TV show gets off to a less-than-auspicious start,
it's customary for the producers to tell the on-camera talent to
``ignore the critics'' and ``just go out and do a good show.''
</P>
<P>
   Earvin Johnson, erstwhile basketballer and now host of a
late-night talk show, found himself unable to do either on the
night of July 2, when Howard Stern was his guest.
</P>
<P>
   Since Johnson's ``The Magic Hour'' signed on in early June,
Stern has made a morning ritual out of roasting the previous
night's broadcast on his nationally syndicated radio show. Yet
Johnson and his producers hatched the nutty idea that it would be
great TV to have Stern on the show.
</P>
<P>
   They should've known better. As a guest, Stern is a handful even
for David Letterman _ and Letterman's a control freak. Three years
ago ``The Tonight Show'' got out of hand when Stern brought two
bikini-clad women onto Jay Leno's stage and had them perform TV's
``first lesbian kiss'' as the host squirmed in his seat.
</P>
<P>
   On ``The Magic Hour'' Stern may have done something worse.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the broadcast produced great ratings _ for one night.
``The Magic Hour'' doubled its normal audience that night, only to
fall back to its usual low levels the next. But Stern's appearance
exposed key reasons why the show must not go on:
</P>
<P>
   - Johnson has no control over his program. When Stern brought up
the firing of the show's unfunny house comedian, Craig Shoemaker,
the host should've deflected the subject. Instead, Johnson
confessed that he and Shoemaker ``weren't clicking.'' Yeah, that's
the kind of information I'd share on my program.
</P>
<P>
   As a condition for appearing on ``The Magic Hour,'' Stern
actually demanded that his band be allowed to perform a flatulent
version of ``Wipe Out.'' And Johnson's producers said yes! When it
was over, they had no one but themselves to blame for the debacle.
</P>
<P>
   - The show's bandleader, Sheila E., can't ad lib musically or
verbally. She played ``You Light Up My Life'' when Stern first
walked on but let the tune drag on one or two bars longer than
necessary. Then as the show went to commercials, she played the
song again. And every time Stern tried pushing her buttons
(suggesting at one point that more lesbianism on her part would
spice up the show), Sheila E. just stood and grinned, not daring to
say a word.
</P>
<P>
   - Above all, Stern correctly identified the central problem with
``The Magic Hour'': its pathetic desire to be all things to all
people. Johnson should be building a loyal core audience _ namely
black viewers who are already comfortable with him _ and then try
to increase the show's reach from there.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago the ``black demographic'' was being touted as the
most highly sought-after crowd in late night. Black viewers weren't
being served by Letterman, Leno or other white-bread performers, we
were told. Well, they aren't being served now, either. With the
exception of cable's ``BET Tonight,'' no late-night program books
the rap performers, the gospel artists or the African-American
luminaries that once graced the couches of Arsenio, Keenen and
Sinbad.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, who declared himself to be ``more black'' than Johnson
because Stern grew up in a mostly minority area of Long Island,
urged the host to fire his diction coach and speak in a more
comfortable dialect.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are anti-Ebonics,'' he told the host. ``I'm
pro.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson tried to deflect the criticism jovially, but the studio
audience (admittedly a pro-Stern faction) cheered it wildly.
</P>
<P>
   In the end the host and producers of ``The Magic Hour'' failed
to weigh the ratings and publicity boost they might have gotten
from Stern against the embarrassment of having Johnson's harshest
critic on national TV, cutting the show to bits.
</P>
<P>
   Damage control was attempted a few days later when the Rev.
Jesse Jackson was booked. Jackson and Johnson staged a bit in which
the guest upbraided the host for having Stern on the show. But it
was too late. The time to undo the damage was before the broadcast
with Stern ever aired.
</P>
<P>
   Years from now Stern's hijacking of ``The Magic Hour'' will be
recalled as one of the infamous moments of late night, right up
there with ``Tonight Show'' producer Helen Kushnick's canceling of
a broadcast less than an hour before airtime in 1992 and the
spectacular opening crash of ``The Chevy Chase Show'' in 1993. It
was great PR for Stern, who is about to launch alate-night program
of his own in August.
</P>
<P>
   For Johnson, however, it may have been the beginning of the end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
