<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Q&AMP;A: EXPLODING ELEVATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why is grain dust in elevators explosive?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Just about any organic material will explode if it is in
fine enough form, dry enough, in suspension in air and confined,''
said Ralph Regan, safety director of the Grain Inspection Service
of the U.S. Department of Agriculture. All it takes is the fuel,
oxygen and a spark, he and other experts suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar, coal dust, wood dust, walnut hulls, the ingredients of
children's modeling dough and some medications have also been
involved in recent dust explosions, Regan said.
</P>
<P>
   Organic particles vary in flammability, and wheat and corn
starch are more explosive than other kinds, said Robert Schoeff,
professor emeritus of grain science at Kansas State University and
a consultant on grain safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary explosion shakes the building, dislodging more
dust, which ignites in turn, and there is also a pressure wave
ahead of the flame front,'' which shakes loose still more dust,
Schoeff said.
</P>
<P>
   The stronger the elevator the greater the danger, he said,
because ``a stronger container lets pressure build up so when it is
released it does so with greater force.''
</P>
<P>
   One important safety measure is venting the elevator to release
pressure. Others are cleaning grain of foreign material and broken
kernels before storage, spraying edible mineral oil on conveying
equipment to control dust and installing pneumatic dust-collection
systems using bag filters. ``The dust is pulled into the filter by
suction and removed for use in animal feed,'' Schoeff said.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions about science to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New
York, N.Y. 10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
