<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEMENT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEMENT SHORTAGES PREDICTED TO STALL BUILDING PROJECTS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SHORTAGE 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... The cement industry is made up primarily of large companies
such as Holnam Inc., Lafarge Corp., Lone Star Industries and Ash
Grove Cement that own plants around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Cement makers sell primarily to concrete makers, generally known
as ready-mix companies. Some of the concrete companies are owned by
the large cement manufacturers, while others are locally based
independent companies.
</P>
<P>
   The answer for why there is a tight cement market can easily be
found in the numbers, according to Bill Toal, an economist with the
Portland Cement Association, a trade association in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. used 93 million metric tons of cement last year, up
from 73.4 million metric tons in 1992. That is a 21 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the most recent year for which figures are available,
the U.S. produced 76 million metric tons of cement, up from about
75 million metric tons in 1992, a 1.3 percent increase and about
the same amount the U.S. produced in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Imports of cement have nearly tripled since 1992, reaching 17.6
million metric tons in 1997. Imports have some domino affect on the
Midwest market, but because they are expensive to ship, they mostly
fill needs on the coast, according to Toal and others.
</P>
<P>
   Cement is made in kilns, or furnaces, that operate at about
2,700 degrees Fahrenheit. Turning them on and off is not cost
effective so they generally operate year-round, 24 hours a day. As
a result, the industry almost always runs at full capacity. It
requires new plants to add capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some plants are operating at over 100 percent of capacity
because they are not allowing for down days for maintenance,'' Toal
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cement plants are expensive to build, costing up to $200
million. They take years to get up and running, mainly because of
the process of obtaining air and water discharge permits. There are
118 cement plants in the U.S., down from 127 in 1988 and 163 in
1978. No new plants have been built for years because many cement
makers weren't making much money until the recent economic
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Improving market conditions have prompted some companies to plan
expansions but none of those have come online yet, Toal said.
Besides Ash Grove Cement's proposed new plant, Lafarge Corp., based
in Reston, Va., is expanding the only cement plant now operating in
the Kansas City area. It is adding 350,000 tons of capacity to its
plant in Sugar Creek.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino, of course, had to play a part in the shortage. Cement
makers usually build enough supplies in the winter to carry through
the construction season. With a mild winter, there were days in
December, January and February when concrete was poured, siphoning
off cement supplies, explained Ron Deleenheer, vice president of
marking for Ash Grove Cement.
</P>
<P>
   The wet summer has allowed cement makers to rebuild supplies but
it will compress the construction season, Deleenheer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into 1998 with thin inventories,'' Deleenheer said.
``We are getting delayed now because of weather but we may not be
able to get enough product through the shipping points to meet
demand. Some projects may just have to go into next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright with Heartland Cement said cement takes a back seat to
perishable products during this season, meaning rail delays of
product. Cement makers are also being asked to cut back on their
production to conserve electricity during the summertime heat. His
company's plant in Independence, Kan., cut its third shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cement production demands tremendous energy. Cutting one shift
stymies our production by up to 30 percent.'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, people shouldn't panic if their home or project is two or
three weeks late. It will get finished, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people relax and not drive the ready-mix people crazy, they
will get their concrete,'' Wright said. ``Chewing them out with
four-letter words is not going to help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2821 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEMENT_SHORTAGE2TAKES     07-13 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEMENT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEMENT SHORTAGES PREDICTED TO STALL BUILDING PROJECTS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SHORTAGE 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tight supplies of concrete could slow the breakneck pace of home
building and commercial construction in some parts of the country,
and suppliers in the Kansas City area say spot shortages are
expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   That means some consumers building homes and contractors on
small commercial jobs may see delays of days or weeks as bigger
customers get top priority. Homeowners who want a single load for a
dog pen or patio project may be unable even to get supplies this
construction season.
</P>
<P>
   Tight supplies have pushed up concrete prices for several years
and have added several hundred dollars to the cost of an average
home and thousands to the cost of bigger building projects.
</P>
<P>
   Don't panic yet. While there will be delays, concrete and cement
executives say consumers will eventually get their supplies.
There's even some disagreement in the building industry about
whether there is a real shortage of concrete.
</P>
<P>
   The wet summer has kept the problem from becoming more
pronounced among consumers and builders, but concrete manufacturers
say shortages could begin showing up soon and continue into the
winter. If the economy continues to expand, the tight market could
last for several years until new cement plants come on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be days when home builders or some of the smaller
guys down the line might not get the concrete they need. All the
cement plants in this area are at near capacity and there is still
not enough cement to meet the total demand,'' said Kent Sunderland,
vice president of Ash Grove Cement in Overland Park, the country's
fourth-largest cement maker.
</P>
<P>
   Ash Grove in June announced it will build a 1-million-metric-ton
capacity plant in the Kansas City area or expand a plant in
Chanute, Kan. The $150 million to $200 million plant won't be ready
until about 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Actually it is cement, the main ingredient in concrete, that is
in short supply. Cement is to concrete what flour is to bread.
</P>
<P>
   A raft of factors _ both short and long term _ have contributed
to a tight cement market nationally and a shortage of cement in the
Midwest. The simplest explanation, however, is that since 1994 the
U.S. has used record amounts of cement while cement production has
remained stagnant and actually declined from 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In this area, building construction has been on the rise thanks
to seven years of economic expansion. Moreover, Kansas and Missouri
have undertaken concrete-heavy road and bridge projects such as
Bruce R. Watkins freeway in Kansas City and interchanges on
Interstate 435 in Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   Some area home builders and heavy constructors say they have yet
to feel the pinch and not everyone is convinced there is a real
shortage. Some area home builders said talk of shortages always
precedes price increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard this with all kinds of building materials,''
said Darryl Rodrock of Rodrock Development, one of the area's
largest home builders. ``They jump prices 20 percent and there will
be plenty of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Concrete prices have gone to about $75 a cubic yard, up from
about $55 several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage, however, is no joke, said Bill Geiger, of Geiger
Ready-Mix. His cement supplier put him on an allocation budget that
is 10 percent less than what he sold last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we are playing games but this is not a game,''
Geiger said. ``Right now Kansas City is just moving so fast, we are
going to get caught short.''
</P>
<P>
   With the NASCAR race track planned for Wyandotte County, rapid
home building and new federal transportation money coming down the
chute, concrete supplies will be tight for several years, Geiger
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are positive things but the effect will be like going to
the grocery store and not being able to buy pop and bread. Cement
is a basic commodity. We are doing everything we can to get more
cement.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell Wright, a sales representative with Heartland Cement in
Gardner, cautions builders and consumers not to panic. They will
get what they need, although not necessarily on the day or hour
they might want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our opinion that it will be a temporary problem, off and
on all this year, anyway,'' Wright said.
-MORE-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
