<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2844 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIAPER-COX     07-13 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAPER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Diapers scant protection against fouling pool water
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the advent of disposable swimming diapers this season,
taking babies to the swimming pool has gotten easier than ever. But
many pediatricians think it's a lousy idea _ risking the health of
other swimmers and the babies themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the hype around special swimming gear for infants,
nothing can guarantee that fecal matter won't get into the water,
manufacturers say. ``Rubber pants, swimsuit, diapers, if the child
has any of these on (and has an accident) there's going to be
leakage,'' acknowledged Wendi Strong, spokeswoman for
Kimberly-Clark, maker of the Huggies diaper Little Swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   And that means those sharing the pool could be exposed to such
organisms as E. coli, as in the case of 25 children who became ill
after swimming in June at White Water park in Cobb County.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more commonly, swimmers could become infected with
intestinal parasites such as Giardia lamblia, which attaches itself
to the lining of small intestines, causing nausea, vomiting or
diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   Giardia can survive what's considered a safe concentration of
chlorine and can live for more than two months in cold water. The
Food and Drug Administration estimates that 2 percent of the U.S.
population has the parasite, with young children seen as the main
culprits for transmission.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I see toddlers in diapers swimming in the same public pool
I'm in, I get out,'' said Dr. Neil Izenberg, a pediatrician at the
Dupont Hospital for Children in Wilmington, Del., and editor in
chief of the e-zine KidsHealth
</P>
<P>
   .org. ``We have said for years that if a child does not have
bowel control, they should not be allowed in public swimming
pools.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing similar concerns, both the American Academy of Pediatrics
and the Canadian Paediatric Society have recommended that children
in diapers not be allowed in swimming or wading pools.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, most community pools _ including White Water _ allow
babies in if they are wearing gear deemed appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   At the Metro Atlanta YMCA _ a chain of 15 centers _ more than
250 babies are enrolled in the infant swim classes. Such classes
are important because they give parents and infants one-on-one time
and teach the basics of pool safety, says Marcia Humphrey, director
of the aquatics program at the Gwinnett YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   Those benefits, she says, outweigh the risks of contracting
diseases. At the YMCA, swim pants with elastic waists and legs are
required.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think babies should be kept out of the pool,'' said
Sabrina Morgan, a Garden Hills mother. ``A pool is a place for a
family and babies are a part of our family.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 packages of swim diapers have been sold each
weekend this summer at the Babies R Us in Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   And Little Swimmers - the newest Huggies _ was developed
precisely because there was such a consumer demand, Strong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this, diapers were made with gel so absorbent they
swell, they become huge _ many times their size _ and can explode
and clog the pool drain,'' she said. In contrast, Little Swimmers
are a one-piece disposable pants built with an absorbent liner that
does not swell in water.
</P>
<P>
   But like other swim gear, they do not provide 100 percent
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're designed to prevent urine and bowel movement leakage
before the child goes in the water, and they can help prevent
leakage of solid bowel movement once the child is in the water,''
Strong said.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to precisely assess the risk from diapers in the
pool.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported that 14
states had 26 waterborne-disease outbreaks associated with
recreational water in 1993 and 1994, the most recent years it
surveyed. More than 1,700 people were affected by the outbreaks,
and of those cases, half involved swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   The White Water outbreak is only the second time the CDC ever
has seen E. coli transmission through a chlorinated public pool.
The first time was also in Georgia, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the grand scheme of things, I think the risks of acquiring
infectious diseases from public pool facilities is just low,
period,'' said Dr. Harry Keyserling, an Emory University
pediatrician specializing in infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
   However, Keyserling did add a caveat: Chlorine levels have to be
maintained at a proper level. That's one of the factors being
examined in the E. coli outbreak at White Water. Pools need a
chlorine level of at least 1.5 parts per million to be considered
safe, and it's not clear whether the pool where the infection took
place was properly chlorinated at the time of infection.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstering the case against infant swimming is the general
agreement that chlorine is not a complete shield against infection.
If a large dose of fecal germs are introduced, some may survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of overwhelms the chlorination,'' said Peter Lee,
spokesman for the state Department of Human Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, pool managers will ``shock'' their pools with high
levels of chlorine when a bowel movement is discovered, but people
are exposed in the time it takes to clear the area, Lee says.
``Shocking the pool is done too late, because you have to wait till
there's no one in the pool,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Izenberg, the Delaware pediatrician, brings up one other problem
about children and public pools. If someone does get sick, folks
are likely to blame the foods _ not the pools _ of summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to the other public health dangers, I don't think
this ranks very high,'' he said. ``But that might be because the
problems are going unnoticed _ not that they're not occurring. So,
it's probably far more widespread than we think.''
</P>
<P>
   Holly Morris and Hadley RiCharde Kreiner contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
