<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2845 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MONICA-COX     07-13 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MONICA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Musically, things have gone well for Monica. Since releasing her
first album ``Miss Thang'' three years ago at the age of 14, the
College Park, Ga. resident born Monica Arnold has sold over a
million copies of her debut album. She's also become the the
youngest artist ever to have two consecutive No. 1 singles (``Don't
Take It Personal _ Just One of Dem Days,'' ``Before You Walk Out of
My Life'').
</P>
<P>
   But talk of Monica has rarely, solely, been about her music.
Even as a young teen, journalists asked her if she had lost her
virginity. And she and her family continue to hear rumors that she
was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 2 1/2 years people are still asking me about my baby,''
says the 17-year-old singer, who doesn't have any children, in a
recent interview at the Atlanta office of her label, Arista
Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just had too much to deal with other than my music,''
adds Monica, whose new album ``The Boy Is Mine,'' goes on sale
today. . ``And not only has it been unfair to me, but people don't
understand how unfair it is to my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has been trying from the start,'' adds her mother
Marilyn Best, who works in consumer affairs for Delta Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Thang'' came out 10 months after fellow teen vocalist
Brandy's debut. And while Brandy sang well about typical teen
topics - ``I Wanna Be Down,'' `` `Baby, Baby, Baby', don't your
know that you're so fine'' _ Monica wore the brashness of
adolescence on her sleeve, shouted it in her CD title, and sang it
with a spunk that drew instant and persistent comparisons with
Brandy.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the ``good'' girl versus ``bad'' girl thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brandy and I have talked about situations where people have
told her mother things that weren't true as well,'' says Monica,
effectively negating the rumor that the two singers who share the
country's No. 1 pop single for the past six weeks, ``The Boy Is
Mine,'' don't speak to each other. (The song is also on Brandy's CD
``Never Say Never.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like, I can't tell the people fast enough to mind their
business. Sweep around their own front doors. Maintain their own
households. And be adults. My 18th birthday is still not here and I
think my brain is so much further along than a lot of people who
are 30 and 40 years-old who work with my stepfather and work around
people in my family who call and make up these lies.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monica deals with it. ``Incredibly well,'' noted Vibe
magazine president Keith Clinkscales. ``I think the words `old
soul' are used to describe her quite often. But they're
appropriate. Her voice and spirit has a knowingness well beyond her
years.''
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because her father abandoned her mother when
Monica was just 4 years old. ``And to lose somebody you either lose
yourself or you gain a lot of knowledge as you deal with losing
them,'' explains Monica, speaking with an evenness that doesn't
waver as she recalls this turning point. ``We gained from the
experience. I saw (my mother) be strong. I saw her take care of me
and my brother (Montez, 14) . I saw her continue her life. I saw
her work extra hours and not eat for trying to do things to feed
us. And that's what made me so strong as a female.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the producer who Monica calls her father, Dallas Austin,
came along when she was 11. ``I thought I was getting a singer, but
I gained a daughter and what I could see, even then, was going to
be an incredible woman,'' says Austin. ``I don't know exactly what
made her this way. But people know it when they hear it.'' It's
that strength, that emotion crawling up your spine when you listen
to Monica hit the higher registers on ``For You I Will,'' or its
equal on her new CD, ``Inside.'' It's the kind of reserve you must
have at that age to deliver Dorothy Moore's classic ``Misty Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   One recent newspaper article touted Monica as a Whitney
Houston-in-the-making. ``And I can see that in a way because
Whitney had a great voice when she was young, and so does Monica,''
said Atlanta's Daryl Simmons, who produced Monica's ``Why I Love
You So Much,'' and ``I Keep It To Myself'' on the new CD. ``But she
connects to audiences in a different way than Whitney did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see myself hanging out with Monica,'' says 18-year-old
Tasha Moreland of College Park, one of Monica's fans. ``Whitney
seems too distant, too put together. She can sing and everything.
But she doesn't seem real. I think Monica is the same person on
record as she is out here on Old National Highway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I give people all that I am, especially on this
record,'' affirms Monica, who actually considers Houston and rapper
Mia X ``my two real friends in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm glad people, in the end, have been feeling and
understanding what they hear on my records and not in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
