<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nancy Reagan might have had more influence in the White House
than Hillary Clinton does
 &HT;    By Don O'Braint
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite what some Republicans think of Hillary Rodham Clinton,
Nancy Reagan actually may have been the most influential first lady
in the past four decades, according to many top-ranking officials.
In Part 2 of Vanity Fair's 25,000-word chronicle of the Reagans,
correspondent Bob Colacello says, ``Mrs. Reagan never tried to make
policy. But she had a tremendous influence.'' Colacello reports
that Mrs. Reagan worked behind the scenes in the White House to
pave the way for the four summits held with Mikhail Gorbachev. ``I
protect Ronnie from himself,'' she once told one head of state.
Today, as Reagan's primary caregiver, she protects him from the
world.
</P>
<P>
   NET PROFITS: Suburban malls revolutionized the way we shopped in
the 1970s and '80s. Now, says Time correspondent Michael Krantz,
the Internet has become a shopper's paradise. According to one
study, online consumer sales will reach $20 billion by 2000, an
increase of 233 percent over this year's estimated $6.1 billion.
Still, some skeptics doubt that virtual shopping will ever take the
place of hands-on browsing. Economist Stephen Roach notes that
e-commerce represents no more than 1 percent of the U.S.'s $8.5
trillion economy.
</P>
<P>
   HERE'S THE BEEF: The New Yorker ($3) features a fascinating
article by Lawrence Wright on the strange alliance between Clyde
Lott, a Pentecostal cattle breeder in Mississippi, and Chaim
Richman, an Orthodox rabbi in Israel. This December, 500 pregnant
Red Angus cows will be exported from Mississippi to Israel _ not
just for beef, but to fulfill a scriptural prophecy. The Jews
believe the advent of the ``red heifer'' means the Messiah may be
near; Christians believe it means the beginning of the end of the
world. The red heifer is also the key to the rebuilding of the
Temple destroyed by Romans in 70 A.D. Before it can be rebuilt,
Jews must be purified with the ashes of ``a red heifer without
spot, wherein is no blemish, and upon which never came a yoke.''
Rabbi Richman has found such a heifer: a cow named Dixie.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE AND GOD: Scientists and theologians often have been at
odds, but that is changing, reports Newsweek ($2.95) in its cover
story. ``Science and spirituality have a common quest, which is a
quest for truth,'' says Sister Mary White of the Benedictine
Meditation Center in St. Paul, Minn. Meanwhile, U.S. News &AMP; World
Report ($2.95) looks at our universe and ponders what came before
creation. Allen Sandage, one of the world's leading astronomers,
says that contemplating the majesty of the big bang helped make him
a believer in God, willing to accept that creation could only be
explained as a ``miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK READS: Lilburn's 19-year-old musical sensation Usher
Raymond IV talks to Ebony ($2.50) about his best-selling album ``My
Way,'' the influence of Michael Jackson and other entertainers, and
his budding film career. ... Spin's ($2.99) cover girl Christina
Ricci is one of the hottest young stars in Hollywood. At 18, she
has become the Anti-It Girl by shunning designer clothes and
refusing to play the Hollywood game. ... Icon ($3.95) profiles
three emerging actors _ David Arquette, Vincent Gallo and Ben
Stiller _ and concludes that achievement and recognition have
little to do with each other. ... The Spice Girls talk about Girl
Power and life after Ginger in Entertainment Weekly's ($2.95) cover
story. ... And, in case your invitation to the Barbra
Streisand-James Brolin wedding went astray, you can see what you
missed in People's ($2.79) 11-page photo spread.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
