<SLUG> BC-SOUNDSHOPPING14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Muzak teams up with others to bring a new kind of music
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As unlikely as it seems, elevator-music kingpin Muzak,
Footaction USA, Arista and Puff Daddy are pooling resources to
market ``Nothin' But the Hotness in '98,'' a compilation album.
It's a consortium that is on the leading edge of a trend uniting
retailers, record labels and artists, and one expected to be
particularly effective in the hip-hop/rap arena.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, as Robin Forman, project manager for Muzak,
notes, is to link brands with ``powerhouse leaders of urban music
and culture like Puff Daddy and his Bad Boy Entertainment label.''
</P>
<P>
   Other artists on the 10-track CD, available for $9.99 only at
Footaction stores, include Faith Evans, the late Notorious B.I.G.,
the Lox and Mase.
</P>
<P>
   -- Beastie Boys, ``Hello Nasty'' (Grand Royal/Capitol). Grade:
B.
</P>
<P>
   -- BR5-49, ``Big Backyard Beat Show'' (Arista). Latest from
crossover country act that's toured with Bob Dylan, Black Crowes
and George Strait. It includes Billy Joe Shaver's ``Georgia on a
Fast Train.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Monica, ``The Boy Is Mine'' (Arista). Grade: B+.
</P>
<P>
   -- P.A. (Parental Advisory). Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nancy Sinatra, ``For My Dad'' (DCC). Maxi-single featuring
duet with her father, ``Somethin' Stupid,'' and two other tunes
will benefit Frank Sinatra Foundation's charities.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lucinda Williams, ``Car Wheels on a Gravel Road'' (Mercury).
Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   -- Trisha Yearwood, ``Where Your Road Leads'' (MCA). Grade: A.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
