<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2849 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN14-COX     07-13 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN:Time's the best gift a child can give Dad on her big day
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For her birthday, our daughter suggested a few things that might
be nice for a girl of her age. There were about a dozen, actually,
and she printed them on a piece of white notebook paper with a lead
pencil. They included a turtle, a boom box, a certain Beanie Baby
whose going price would buy a set of tires and, last but hardly an
afterthought, a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a lot to shell out. The turtle, fortunately, already
comes equipped.
</P>
<P>
   Alex turned 8 years old today, 8 going on 12. When a girl is 8,
she is, of course, quite grown up. She is not of voting age or
drinking age or even driving age, but why split hairs? She's all
but there.
</P>
<P>
   Any child born on Bastille Day is bound to be a pistol. A trip
to France, in fact, was casually mentioned. Next year if not this
year. We could fly over on the Concorde, she said, take in Paris
and do it up right.
</P>
<P>
   Alex is our spunky one, certain of what she wants, given to
insurrection and exasperated by an old stick who's just running out
the clock. The ancien regime _ that's me.
</P>
<P>
   Already at seven and a half she had become too worldly for the
adventures of Sally O'Malley and Molly McGolly, fictional
characters in bedtime stories we told each other when she was still
a mere child. Not to be be immodest, but I thought those stories
had real possibilities. I thought of this once when reading her a
story by William Steig, a better writer than her father but
something to shoot for just the same. Elaborate a bit on the story
lines, sharpen the dialogue here and there, find us a good
illustrator and we're in business, kiddo.
</P>
<P>
   My chance to become a famous author, or at least co-author, has
gone by the boards. At the witching hour she hasn't time anymore
for Sally and Molly.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough that she has time for me, and I try to show my
appreciation. One way of doing that lately is by playing the number
game, a kind of roulette in which you win a quarter if you can
guess what number between 1 and 20 is hidden in the other person's
head. You get three guesses and she usually nails it by the third
one. The girl's got a knack for holding my head between the palms
of her hands, peering deep into my eyes (poking around in my ears,
too, if necessary) and, so to speak, reading my mind.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, it saddens me that the acquisitive impulse has
won out over storytelling. But she's up by $1.75 _ nothing to sniff
at.
</P>
<P>
   With luck I'll retain financial leverage for another 14 years.
But in time I'll have to let go, not as soon as she'd like and
sooner than I'll be ready for. ``A father's anxieties end only in
his grave,'' a friend of mine wrote when his daughter reached 20.
Until then, he clings to the illusion that the child can be molded
to his design.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, she's not a bad fit. I always liked a spirited woman
with a mind of her own, and I think she knows that a part of me is
silently applauding her resistance to paternal commands. I'm not
going to be a pushover, and I don't want her to be either. Just
don't whine.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know where the balance lies, but I hope that before she
goes her own way we'll have struck something close to it. Give me
the short end, if need be. I'll trade a measure of permissiveness
for the assurance of trust. Drugs, drinking, smoking, teen
pregnancy, the wrong crowd, boys too much like the ones I once knew
_ those are the nightmares that loom larger with every year.
</P>
<P>
   Has there ever been a worse time to raise kids? She already
knows too much while not knowing enough. When she starts dancing,
limbs and torso loosey-goosey, it scares me as much as it charms
me. The high school girls didn't even come on to me like that, and
_ come to think of it _ neither has anyone since.
</P>
<P>
   You can't expect Sally and Molly to be much competition for the
Spice Girls. I just hope Leonardo DiCaprio hasn't got so much over
Daddy that nothing I say registers.
</P>
<P>
   On a chest of drawers, there's a picture of her when she was
about 3. In it, I can see an intimation of the girl she's become,
sly and smart. I look at the girl she's still becoming and hold my
breath. Somewhere in there I think I see the dim outline of a woman
I'm going to like.
</P>
<P>
   I just don't want to see it too soon. I still want to see a girl
who could forget Leonardo DiCaprio for a box turtle and might even
turn off a cell phone to let her father tell her a story at
bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
