<HEADER>
A2850 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBAF-VIDEO-COX     07-13 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-VIDEO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 events explore images presented by music videos
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--We're talking about one guy who calls himself the Media
Assassin and another who describes himself as ``an anarchist and a
subversive.'' So you can expect the National Black Arts Festival
program that Harry Allen (Media Assassin) and Greg Tate (choose
your adjective) have assembled on hip-hop music music videos will
be a bit more than your daily BET or MTV countdown.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Allen's two-hour ``Hip-Hop Music Video Giga-Film
Festival'' deals with how hip-hop visualizes images of black men,
black women, power and race. It will end with a video countdown.
Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say the best, I don't mean music videos that promoted
popular songs,'' explains Allen, a contributor to Vibe and its
upcoming sister publication Blaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because a song was popular doesn't mean the video was
good,'' he continues. ``If a song conveys `positive' messages, (it)
doesn't automatically get (recognized). They won't make my list
just because they were popular videos or if they were the video
debut of influential or popular artists.''
</P>
<P>
   For a video to be considered for his list, Allen said it should,
among other accomplishments, set new and higher creative standards,
reflect a powerful synergy between sound and image, and affect
``the way hip-hop was seen, discussed or treated in a larger
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew. All this serious talk about a three-minute promotional
tool?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, the Media Assassin has always been serious about his
work,'' says Public Enemy's D, who boosted Allen's profile by
mentioning him in his song ``Don't Believe the Hype.'' ``And
videos, legitimately, should be taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Allen: ``Most people think of (music videos) disposable
form, but it is the largest mass of documented black popular
musical performances in this portion of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   As of this writing, Allen, who also serves on the advisory board
of the Race Relations Institute at Fisk University, still hadn't
come up with his ``best of the best'' list. Maybe Coolio's ``C U
When I Get There'' will be on it. Or Dr. Dre's ``Nuthin' But a `G'
Thang.'' He's already certain Bone-Thugs-N-Harmony's
``Crossroads,'' a dark video about afterlife, is ``the greatest
music video ever produced.''
</P>
<P>
   Tate is shorter on specifics about his ``Music Video As Film''
program the following evening. ``I'm going to be using a DJ and
we'll be using turntables and guitar to help tell the story,''
offers the 40-year-old author and Village Voice columnist who's
also in town for the Black Rock Coalition performance Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really necessarily accept this hierarchy of cinema
being art and video being a lesser form. There's really a lot of
imagination in some of this work which I hope to show. The
cheesiest r&AMP;b video is less offensive to me than these so-called
black comedy films.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
