<HEADER>
A2857 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AKINWANDE-COX     07-13 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AKINWANDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Results of tests may lead to rescheduling of Akinwande-Holyfield
bout
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The rescheduling of Evander Holyfield's heavyweight
title defense against Henry Akinwande is closer to realization
after Akinwande's most recent blood test showed Monday that the
residual strain of hepatitis B in his system is non-infectious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a situation where it has become more likely than not
that this fight will go forward as soon as it's practicable,'' said
Jim Thomas, Holyfield's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Don King and Showtime executive Jay Larkin had penciled
in Aug. 29 at Madison Square Garden as a potential resetting for
the fight. But the New York State Athletic Commission still may
refuse to license Akinwande, based on the fact that the virus
remains detectable in his blood. A positive test can occur even
after a person recovers from a virus.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the Garden, which has a right of first refusal, has
sent mixed signals on whether it wants to host the fight after the
original June 6 card was shaping up as a financial disaster.
</P>
<P>
   If either the commission or Garden officials say no, the fight
may go to Las Vegas on Sept. 5 _ possibly at the Mirage, which has
shown interest. The timing could bode well for ticket sales. That
date would be on Labor Day weekend and the first week of the NFL
season, when crowds flock to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   States often adhere to each other's conclusions on the medical
status of boxers. But Marc Ratner, executive director of the Nevada
Athletic Commission, said Akinwande can fight in Las Vegas if he is
approved by its doctors. Nevada, unlike New York, doesn't
customarily test boxers for hepatitis but would in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Since the postponement, Holyfield received an offer from HBO of
$20 million for a title unification bout against Lennox Lewis in
December. He said he would not commit to the offer until assessing
how he feels following an Akinwande bout. ``I have to listen to my
body,'' he said, adding he would prefer meeting Lewis in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who was recently quoted as saying he would demand a
$25 million guarantee against Lewis, says those comments were not
accurate. He now says a $20 million guarantee would be acceptable,
with more revenue possible based on sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm saying is I don't want anybody to put a cap on (my
purse),'' he said. ``If the fight does well (on pay-per-view), I
expect to get compensated for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
