A2858 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-ONDECK14-COX     07-13 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-ONDECK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: New York Mets
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Tonight at 7:40 p.m.; Wednesday at 12:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Radio/TV: Fox Sports South will broadcast both games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight: RHP John Smoltz (6-2, 3.77;
7-7, 3.96 lifetime vs. Mets) vs. RHP Bobby Jones (7-5, 3.88; 3-6,
5.40 lifetime vs. Braves). Wednesday: LHP Denny Neagle (9-7, 3.30;
4-3, 4.33 lifetime vs. Mets) vs. RHP Masato Yoshii (4-4, 3.65; 0-1,
3.00 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: The Braves trail the all-time series 197-201 and
are 6-13 at Shea Stadium the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The Braves swept a three-game series from New
York at Turner Field on July 3-5 just before the All-Star break.
The New Yorkers were outscored 10-5 and did not hold a lead the
entire series.
</P>
<P>
   Mets leaders: Avg: John Olerud (.328); HR _ Mike Piazza (14);
RBIs _ Piazza, Olerud, Huskey (50); SB _ McCrae (15). W _ Rick Reed
(10); ERA _ Al Leiter (1.86). Strikeouts _ Leiter (96). Saves _
John Franco (18).
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: The Mets opened a 12-game homestand by dropping two of
four to visiting Montreal during the weekend and still managed to
pick up a game in the NL East on the front-running Braves. The last
time the Braves saw them, the Mets were chasing the umpiring crew
off the field following Atlanta's 11th-inning victory on July 5, an
incident that prompted a three-game suspension for closer John
Franco. He continues to pitch until his appeal can be heard. . . .
The club's biggest news is the return of Todd Hundley, the
catcher-turned-outfielder who is 1-for-6 and starting in left. The
club has tried Bernard Gilkey in right field (where he last
appeared in 1993 with St. Louis), but Butch Huskey started there
Sunday. Good idea. Huskey is hitting .484 with eight RBIs in his
last eight games. . . . New York, which like the Braves had an
off-day on Monday, has won its last two, but is 4-9 dating back to
June 26. The Mets bullpen has five blown saves in the last 13
games. . . . Jones, tonight's starter, has rebounded from a 1-3
start to go 6-2 in his last 11 games. The Mets are 8-4 in his last
12 appearances, his last one coming Thursday against Montreal, an
11th-inning loss. Jones allowed four earned runs in five innings
that night but drew no decision. He was 0-2 against the Braves in
three starts last season, Atlanta pounding him for 25 hits and 16
earned runs in just 11 2/3 innings. . . . On the DL: 1B Matt Franco
(broken toe), RHP Jason Isringhausen (right shoulder surgery), LHP
Al Leiter (torn tendon, left knee), LHP Hector Mercado (left elbow
surgery), INF Craig Paquette (sprained left ankle), RHP Armando
Reynoso (right elbow strain), C Tim Spehr (broken left wrist) and
RHP Paul Wilson (right shoulder sprain).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: CF Brian McRae has six homers in his last 17 games
and has a .424 on-base percentage during his last 59 plate
appearances. 1B John Olerud's .328 average is sixth in the NL.
Light-hitting SS Rey Ordonez is hitting .400 with four runs scored
and two RBIs in his last five games.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: 3B Edgardo Alfonzo hit 3-for-16 (.188) in the weekend
Expos series. Closer Franco blew two saves in his first two
appearances of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
