</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-0PEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Els in search of old confidence at British Open
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Ernie Els played in Ireland mostly for
laughs and leisure last week instead of competing at the Loch
Lomond Invitational in Scotland, but also to get the feel of links
courses heading into Royal Birkdale and this week's British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Nice plan. Too bad there wasn't a spare wind tunnel to borrow at
Ballybunion.
</P>
<P>
   After a practice round Monday at Royal Birkdale, Els promptly
called the British Open venue ``the toughest par 70 I have ever
played. I would say it's even tougher than The Olympic Club if it
blows like this.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not particularly good news for Els, whose first two
majors of 1998 will not add too many pages to the scrapbook. He
tied for 16th at the Masters, then fell to a tie for 49th at the
U.S. Open in his defense after winning in 1997 at Congressional. A
sometimes aching back has not aided the process. He welcomes an
arrival by Columbus, Ga., physical therapist Tom Boers, who will
work with Fred Couples and Sea Island's Davis Love III. Admittedly,
Els ``has lost a little confidence'' in his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the bloody spasm,'' Els said. ``It doesn't want to
go away, doesn't want to release. ... I think I'm going to give a
really good go this week, play as hard as I can. If it's still
niggling a little bit by Sunday or Monday, I am going to take maybe
a month off and get it sorted out and come back healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen: Get used to me
</P>
<P>
   When Lee Janzen checked into the Royal Birkdale locker room
Sunday, an attendant asked, ``Are you a qualifier?'' With that, the
U.S. Open champion just smiled and said, ``No, I'm exempt. ... Get
used to my face. I'll be coming here the next 10 years.'' The
attendant's embarrassment only grew painfully when told by his
fellow workers the identity of the player he had just questioned.
``The other guys,'' said Janzen, ``gave him a hard time right
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Mize qualifies for spot
</P>
<P>
   Columbus' Larry Mize, who made the overseas trip without a spot
in the British Open, justified the effort Monday by securing a spot
through the local qualifier at Heskett Golf Club with rounds of
71-75_146. Considering the nature of Sunday's weather _ wind gusts
measured up to 55 mph and one qualifier suspended because of balls
blowing off the greens _ a 71 was the relative equivalent of a 66.
... Gary Nicklaus, son of Jack, won't be able to carry on the
family tradition at the British Open. Trying to qualify the past
two days, he bogeyed the last three holes Monday at Hillside Golf
Club for a 78 then lost in a playoff. ... American John Cook
withdrew for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Faldo says he's greatly improved
</P>
<P>
   England's Nick Faldo, who withdrew from Loch Lomond less than an
hour before his tee time last Wednesday, said his injured right
elbow is ``75 percent better'' and he's confident of playing in the
tournament. A soft cast that was placed on the pained elbow has
been removed and the inflammation reduced. Faldo walked the course
Sunday and planned to play a practice round Tuesday. He will use a
tee on every shot for a while to avoid jarring the elbow with a big
divot. ``There is no point taking any unnecessary risks,'' Faldo
said. ``Hopefully by Wednesday I'll be okay to play a proper
practice round without the aid of a tee. Right now I am confident
I'll be fit to play on Thursday.'' ... Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar
wants to maintain what has been a successful trend in the Masters
and U.S. Open. He played a pre-tournament practice round with
fellow Yellow Jacket Stewart Cink of Smyrna at both Augusta
National and The Olympic Club and tied for 21st and 14th,
respectively. ``Hopefully, we'll continue our tradition of doing
well,'' Kuchar said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
