<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2863 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-LOGOS-COX     07-13 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-LOGOS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Corporate sponsorship the name of the game in NASCAR
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He hasn't won a race in 247 tries, so when Rick Mast
climbs out of his No. 75 Ford Taurus after another Winston Cup
adventure, he gets right to the point. He describes how the car
ran, or didn't run. He remembers key moments in the three-hour
race.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes he forgets to plug Remington rifles, as in, ``The
Remington Arms Ford really gave it a good shot today.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Mast is waiting to get to victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   Remington, the manufacturer of rifles and ammunition, pays
Mast's race team between $3-6 million to remember why that big 'R'
is on the hood of his yellow Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem I have with this is that all the years I was with
Skoal (chewing tobacco), they never wanted me to say 'Skoal,'''
Mast said. ``On TV or radio or nothin'. Just wear the uniform and
hat. I kind of got in that mode. So I get with these folks, and
they're calling me up asking, 'When you gonna start saying
'Remington, Rick?'''
</P>
<P>
   It's a question more and more sponsors are beginning to ask.
Sponsorship is the driving force behind NASCAR, and as stock car
racing has grown into a major lifestyle sport, the cost of
advertising on the brightly painted 200 mph billboards has
increased dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Every inch of the car, except for the roof, is for sale. The
major sponsors get the biggest decal, on the hood. Associate
sponsors may pay up to $500,000 to be on the rear deck lid. NASCAR
controls the decals in the 36-inch space from behind the front
wheel to the driver's window.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the sponsorship varies with the success and
popularity of the race team and driver.
</P>
<P>
   Remington is delighted with Mast, because he's an avid
outdoorsman with a playful sense of humor who enjoys making his
obligatory three trips to the rifle factory and hanging out with
the employees.
</P>
<P>
   He even won the pole at Rockingham on the same weekend Remington
introduced its new model rifle by painting a picture of the gun
across the hood of the No. 75.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked with him on how and when to say Remington,'' said
Phil Murdock, the company's Manager of Sports Marketing. ``It means
a lot to us. We're involved in racing because we like racing, but
we're involved very much to promote our brand to outdoorsmen.
Rick's getting better. He's doing a good job with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Remington is just one example of how Winston Cup's sponsor base
has expanded from what once was predominantly automotive products
and beer. Of the 38 primary sponsors this season, 11 are companies
that either manufacture shelved goods or sell them. Kellog's, Tide
and Kodak have sponsored cars for more than five years. Other major
sponsors include a satellite TV company, financial-services firms
and Tabasco hot pepper sauce.
</P>
<P>
   They all want to buy into the loyalty factor: 71 percent of
NASCAR fans buy products of NASCAR sponsors, according to
Performance Research, a company that tracks that sort of thing.
Performance Research also found that 40 percent of race fans will
switch to a product if it becomes a NASCAR sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Firms such as Remington, which sees the NASCAR fan and the
outdoorsman as one and the same, and Midwest-based Thorn Apple
Valley Meats (yes, race fans like sausage) are proof that the
little guys, if they come up with the money, can ride with the big
guys, like McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn Apple Valley Meats has tied into Winston Cup this year in
an effort to turn around its financial situation. The company lost
$21.7 million in fiscal 1996 and $3.2 million last year. But
president Joel Dorfman asked stockholders to be encouraged by the
company's investment and growth potential that would come because
of its affiliation with NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sponsorships puts the Thorn Apple Valley brand in the
company of Tide, Budweiser, Winston, Kodak and other leading
brands, provides the broad, national exposure that had been missing
from our marketing arsenal and gives us a significant marketing
advantage over our competitors,'' Dorfman wrote in his annual
report.
</P>
<P>
   You can't buy Thorn Apple Valley sausages everywhere, but you
might be curious about the brand name if the Cale Yarborough-owned
No. 94 Ford is running well enough to get some TV exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The company wasn't even that concerned about buying into a team
that has won only once in 10 years, that victory coming last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In auto racing, there's one team that wins, and 42 that lose
every week, if you want to categorize it as losing,'' marketing
director Mike Farley said. ``It takes a long time to build a team,
as in football, basketball, baseball. We didn't think we were going
to be a Jeff Gordon and DuPont in the first year. But running a
Winston Cup car can achieve your objectives outside of winning,
like brand identification. People know who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   For their investment, the sponsors are paired with teams by
NASCAR and have a major say in who drives the car. ``It's like a
personal services contract,'' Mast said.
</P>
<P>
   There is one bottom line that makes the investment seem like a
smart one. The Joyce Julius Sponsors Report, based in Ann Arbor,
Mich., studies each race telecast frame-by-frame and feeds
information into a computer that calculates how much time a
sponsor's decal is on screen. Then it computes what it would cost
the sponsor to buy that much time at a non-discounted advertising
rate for that broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for the first time, sponsors accumulated more than $1
billion in comparable exposure value. The sponsors consider this
free advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to count the exposure it has to be clear and in
focus,'' said Eric Wright, vice president of the Report. ``It can't
be blurred or partially obscured. Our researchers are trained to
only tabulate what's clear and in focus. The larger sponsors that
are across the hood show up more frequently than those smaller type
decal sponsors. But that doesn't mean those smaller sponsors are
not receiving exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at a pit situation, where they're focusing on the
tire being changed. That's real prime time for them to pick up that
screen time. We're able to tell our clients where they're showing
up and for how long. We can tell them they appeared on the hood of
so-and-so's car for four minutes and 32 seconds and on a uniform
for another 25 seconds, on a billboard in Turn 3 for 15 seconds or
what have you.''
</P>
<P>
   So there is a reason for that suspension cam beneath the car.
``Lots of times you'll see decals down there, too,'' Wright said.
``The only people who are going to see that are the people sitting
at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrecks often can cost a sponsor credit in the Report. ``We fall
back on our methodology,'' Wright said. ``If it's a 10-letter
sponsor, and seven of the letters are mangled and you can't read
it, we're not going to count that.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't necessarily have to win a championship to win in the
Sponsors' Report.
</P>
<P>
   When last year's tabulations were complete, Mark Martin's
Valvoline-sponsored Ford led all sponsors in exposure. It was
captured on camera for 14 hours, 46 minutes, 10 seconds. Add in 270
sponsor mentions during telecasts, and Valvoline accumulated the
equivalent of $43,108,036 in air time.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 events this season, Martin's car was leading again with
$26,514,195 on six hours, 27 minutes and 35 seconds of air time. He
had 125 sponsor mentions.
</P>
<P>
   Points leader Jeff Gordon's DuPont Chevy was fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valvoline has been the No. 1-ranking team sponsor over the
last five years,'' Wright said. ``They've got a really nice V logo;
you can see it all the way down the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
