<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: WINNERS OF $110,000 IMPERIAL PRIZE ANNOUNCED; FILM
PRODUCER NAMED TO BRITISH POST; BRAND-NEW MOZART; BERGMAN TURNS
80 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Israel, Russia, Great Britain, Japan, Sweden)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the beautiful Prinzregentheater in Munich as the setting,
the Japan Arts Association announced the winners of the 10th
Praemium Imperiale, or Imperial Prize, for outstanding lifetime
achievement in the arts:
</P>
<P>
   In painting, Robert Rauschenberg of the United States; in
sculpture, Dani Karavan of Israel; in architecture, Alvaro Siza of
Portugal; in music, Sofia Gubaidulina of Russia, and in theater and
film, Sir Richard Attenborough of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The awards of approximately $110,000 are given annually in
artistic fields not covered by the Nobel Prizes, and each laureate
is to receive a commemorative medal from the Japanese imperial
family in Tokyo in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Capitalist
</P>
<P>
   David Puttnam has been named chairman of Britain's new National
Endowment for Science, Technology and the Arts. In announcing the
appointment Monday, Chris Smith, the culture secretary, described
the endowment as a ``national bank for talent'' that will receive
some $328 million from lottery funds to invest in promoting new
arts and science.
</P>
<P>
   Puttnam is now Lord Puttnam, one of Prime Minister Tony Blair's
life peers. Puttnam, a longtime producer whose credits include the
Academy Award-winning ``Chariots of Fire'' and ``The Killing
Fields,'' was also chairman and chief executive officer of Columbia
Pictures in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Partly Mozart
</P>
<P>
   In the mood for some Mozart _ Mozart you've never heard before?
Then mark the dates Oct. 30 and Nov. 1. That is when Boston Baroque
will present the first performances of the 1790 opera ``The
Philosopher's Stone'' (``Der Stein der Weisen'') since the time of
Mozart himself. The performances of the fairy-tale opera,
attributed to Mozart and four colleagues and discovered in 1996 by
the musicologist David Buch, will take place in Boston at Jordan
Hall of the New England Conservatory. In addition to this modern
premiere of the opera, written in Mozart's final year, Boston
Baroque will record the work on the Telarc label.
</P>
<P>
   Image Maker
</P>
<P>
   Ingmar Bergman turns 80 Tuesday, and though the great filmmaker
has often talked of retiring, he continues to write and direct. At
present, he is reported to have written a new film for the Swedish
actress Lena Endre. Titled ``Troloesa'' and translated unofficially
as ``Faithless,'' it is described by Bergman as ``a passionate
drama, almost a thriller.'' The director will be Liv Ullmann, the
star of many Bergman films.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
