A2887 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HBO-EARNINGS-COX     07-13 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HBO-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HBO &AMP; Co. reports 56% increase in earnings
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HBO &AMP; Co. continued its run of good financial results Monday,
announcing record second-quarter earnings that exceeded analysts'
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares hit a 52-week high of $38.37 1/2 after the
announcement, but closed at $36.12 1/2, down $1.37 1/2 in Nasdaq
trading. The health-care software and services company's stock
typically climbs in the days preceding earnings announcements, then
falls off, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Second-quarter profit rose 56 percent to $73.8 million, or 17
cents a share, from $47.4 million, or 11 cents per share. The First
Call consensus was 16 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   HBO &AMP; Co. cited strong sales growth, as well as improved
margins, for the quarter's performance. The numbers exclude a
non-recurring credit of $3 million in the latest quarter, and a
non-recurring charge of 5 cents a share related to an acquisition
in the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
   Second-quarter revenue was also a record, increasing 29 percent
to $376.7 million vs. $291.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a good solid quarter, pretty strong across the
board,'' said analyst Stephen Fitzgibbons of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, who
had a 16 cents estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The company leads the health care information technology sector
in revenues and profits.
</P>
<P>
   HBO &AMP; Co.' customers include 2,800 hospitals, 5,000 physician
practices, 600 insurers and 700 home care agencies. Software sales
increased during the quarter in each sector, and service revenue
climbed as well, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the quarter, HBO &AMP; Co. had almost $500 million in
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Monika Brown, director of investor relations, would not comment
on possible acquisitions. ``There's always a variety of things
we're looking at,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   For the six months, income was $138.7 million, or 32 cents per
share, vs. $85.8 million, 20 cents, in the year-ago period. Revenue
rose to $719.5 million from $554.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Charles Trafton of Adams Harkness predicted the company
would surpass $1.5 billion in revenue this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
