<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-JAPAN-425&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      07-13 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JAPAN-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JAPANESE TV SHOW THAT PAIRS BEAUTY AND PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japanese television is known around the world for its
outrageous, sadistic antics. There are game shows in which men
compete to see who can keep from going to the bathroom the longest
and in which women play games of Ping-Pong and the loser must
strip. Now, thanks to the hit weekend television comedy show
``Super Jockey,'' one more popular culture apparition can be added
to the list. And it comes not from a desire to see beautiful,
scantily clad women or to see men in pain, but to see beautiful,
scantily clad women in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Super Jockey'' is a comedy program disguised as a game show in
which Japanese celebrities are pitted against one another in
contests involving feats like eating disgusting flavors of ice
cream and playing charades, with bad hints punishable by electric
shocks. But somewhere along the line, the makers of the show
decided to give sponsors who couldn't afford air time another
option.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of paying for commercials, they could earn a spot by
bringing bikini-clad women (usually themselves or employees) onto
the program to be dunked into scaldingly hot water. The longer the
woman can stay in the water, the longer she is allowed to deliver a
commercial. Most women last three or four seconds in the heat,
after which they rub ice over themselves or jump up and down in
pain as the camera focuses on their reddened breasts and legs. Once
they have cooled off, they can advertise whatever product they want
for exactly the amount of time they were able to stay in the water.
</P>
<P>
   An added twist is that one host of ``Super Jockey'' is an
internationally known movie director, Takeshi Kitano, who has been
described by American critics as the decade's most important
Japanese filmmaker. Last year, he won the top prize at the Venice
International Film Festival for his movie ``Hana-Bi''
(``Fireworks''). Many Japanese believe that the more seriously
Kitano (or Beat Takeshi, as he is known in his stand-up comic
guise) is taken in the film world, the more outrageous he feels he
needs to become on television in order to prove that he hasn't
become stuck up.
</P>
<P>
   Like posed White House shots of President Clinton jogging and
frolicking on the beach, Kitano's antics are an effort to prove
that despite all his recognition, acclaim and responsibility, he
isn't any less of an average guy. The difference is that in
Kitano's world, there appears to be nothing the average guy loves
more than seeing beauty, and then seeing beauty humiliated or
destroyed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A simple explanation of such mass-entertainment misogyny is to
look at it as a need for men to overcome their feelings of
inadequacy around powerful women, especially considering the old
Japanese woodblocks and prints in which female sexuality is
depicted as threatening, demonic and life-destroying. As Ian Buruma
writes in his book on Japanese culture, ``Behind the Mask,'' the
``violent entertainment and grotesque erotica are still important
outlets in what continues to be an oppressive social system.''
While this offers a partial explanation for ``Super Jockey,'' the
culture's relationship to beauty is also more complex.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Japanese are not particularly keen to claim Yukio
Mishima as a spokesman for their heritage, he may have described
the attitude best in ``Runaway Horses.'' In the novel, the main
character, Isao, wants nothing more than to commit suicide at the
pinnacle of his youth, beauty and purity _ ``to die atop a cliff
swept by a breeze fresh with the scent of pine overlooking a sea
bright in the morning sun.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Mishima writes of a desire to destroy or subvert
beauty at its height, thus strengthening its appeal and preventing
its slow decay. It is not just a coincidence that this is to be
done in front of water. Water is a constant character in Kitano's
films, representing death and rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals are drowned by being held under water, and characters
whose lives have hit dead ends ritually make pilgrimages to the
ocean. As an element of pain in ``Super Jockey,'' hot water is an
ingenuous choice. It is pure and clear, enabling the audience to
see through the glass tank the destructive chemistry that occurs
when two beautiful and innocent forces, flesh and water, combine.
And though ``Super Jockey'' may seem to have nothing to do with
Kitano's films, both are hinged on a mutually dependent balance of
comedy and violence, albeit in different proportions.
</P>
<P>
   One difference between ``Super Jockey'' and Kitano's movies is
that in the films violence is sudden. It appears in a blinding and
irreversible flash, as it did in Kitano's life four years ago when
his face was disfigured in a motorcycle accident.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Super Jockey,'' however, violence is an eagerly anticipated
ritual, like a meal. The women, in fact, look as if they are being
cooked in the water, since during each show men stand behind the
tank, ladling hot water over the women's breasts as if they were
chickens in a pot. Making this sadomasochistic entertainment even
more disturbing is the habit Japanese women have of smiling and
laughing when they are embarrassed or humiliated, letting the
audience indulge in the fantasy that the women have reached Isao's
goal in ``Runaway Horses'': ``the peak of sensitivity where the
scarlet and white threads of ultimate pain and ultimate joy are
woven together.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the feminist outrage such a show would cause in the
United States, it is nothing too out of the ordinary in Japan. The
facet of Japanese culture that has probably most interested,
confused and frustrated Westerners is the sharp demarcation between
public life, where strict rules of formality and conduct apply, and
private life, where anything goes so long as it doesn't carry over
into the public life.
</P>
<P>
   Considering its content, ``Super Jockey'' belongs in the realm
of private life. Though television programs are of course on view
for the public, they, like theater, aren't real, and thus don't
rupture the delicate fabric of conformity and respect holding the
society together. Therefore, on shows like ``Super Jockey,''
breaking taboos isn't transgression. It's comedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
