<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release TUESDAY AMs, July 14, 1998  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-HASHIMOTO (Tokyo) _ Edgy financial markets and disgruntled
voters cheer the resignation of Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 1200 words. (i and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CANDIDATE (Tokyo) -- Whoever replaces Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto will have his work cut out for him.
Unfortunately, there may not be a politician in Japan who is up to
the task. By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) -- IMF and others agree on a $14.8 billion
loan package to help stabilize Russia's financial markets. But will
the move take effect in time to head off mass social discontent. By
David Filipov. 1000 words. (i and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-PARADE (Portadown, Northern Ireland) -- Orangemen will
commemorate their biggest holiday divided by the deaths of three
Catholic boys. By Kevin Cullen. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-GOALS (Atlanta) -- NAACP leaders are being forceful in
their defense of affirmative action, belittling critics of the
program and pledging to defeat any effort to curtail it in
Washington state. By Ann Scales. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   ZAPARUDER-Kennedy (Washington) -- Release of Zapruder film
causes stir 35 years after Kennedy assassination. By Bob Hohler.
700 words.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRO-SHARKS (Undated) -- Environmental groups accuse states of
shirking protection of sharks, a species important both for
medicinal uses and because of its role in the food chain. By Larry
Tye. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   YORKER-REMNICK (New York) -- David Remnick gets his first
editing job _ in charge of the New Yorker. By Fred Kaplan. 1000
words. (a and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IFM-STABILITY (Washington) -- IMF's decision to provide $11
billion for a Russia bailout package from reserve funds raises
questions about the financial stability of the IMF itself. By Aaron
Zitner. 800 words. (f and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REALTY (Undated) -- Microsoft to begin on-line real
estate listings, as well as mortgage origination, putting the
software giant into direct competition with the National
Association of Realtors Multiple Listing Service. By Jennifer
Babson. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-REDSOX-RAYS (St. Petersburg, Fla.) _ By Gordon Edes.
</P>
<P>
   CYC-TOUR (Undated) _ British rider Chris Boardman crashes,
fracturing his left wrist. So now he's not just out of the leader's
spot, he's out of the Tour de France. By Susan Bickelhaupt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
