<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2900 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-U.S.-HNS &LR;      07-13 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED STATES URGES JAPAN TO STICK WITH ECONOMIC REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration said Monday it hoped the
resignation of Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto would not
derail an overhaul of that country's economy, which experts say is
needed to shield the United States from the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important to the United States that the new
government, whatever its composition, move quickly to implement
concrete fiscal and banking measures to achieve strong domestic
demand-led growth in Japan and to restore confidence in Japan's
financial system,'' White House press secretary Michael McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think they will see it in their own self-interest to pursue
economic reform quickly,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   There is general agreement among economists that Japan must
deregulate its economy and, in particular, overhaul its banking
industry or risk an economic meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Japan doesn't get fixed, the Asian financial crisis has a
very good chance of going worldwide, and, then, the United States
won't be able to escape without serious harm,'' said Clyde V.
Prestowitz Jr., senior fellow at the Economic Strategy Institute, a
Washington-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto announced his resignation Monday after his Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) suffered a stunning defeat in Sunday's
parliamentary elections. The prime minister also said he was
canceling a scheduled meeting with Clinton on July 22 in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The electoral drubbing was unexpected. The LDP retained only 44
seats of the 61 it was defending in the upper house of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Because the upper house has little real power, Sunday's
elections were in large part symbolic. However, the results are
seen as a sign that the Japanese people want change.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto will remain in office until his party chooses a
successor later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP, which has dominated Japanese politics for 50 years,
still holds a majority of seats in the lower house of parliament,
which controls government policies, including banking and financial
reforms, and chooses the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said U.S. officials would work with Tokyo to schedule a
visit by Hashimoto's successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has a close and enduring relationship with
Japan, and the change in leadership does not alter the strong
nature of the relationship or the strong sense of a personal
connection of our two peoples,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economy is dominated by a handful of massive corporate
conglomerates, each tending to include a major bank. Because of the
strong ties between the bank and the other companies within the
conglomerate, loans often are made on the basis of personal and
professional relationships rather than the merit of applicant.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a massive number of bad loans, leaving some
financial institutions near bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Prestowitz said Sunday's vote showed the depth of Japanese anger
over the government's current economic course and their fear that
stagnation will not soon fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese people want change, but they haven't really
rallied around any one plan for that change,'' Prestowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese economy has declined for two consecutive quarters _
the definition of a recession _ and despite a large government
stimulus package announced in April, consumer and business
confidence remain low.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Hashimoto announced a plan to stabilize the
banking system. But there were doubts about whether the prime
minister would fully implement the plan in the face of political
pressure from big banks, which are major donors to the LDP.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Alexander, president of the Japan Economic Institute, a
Washington-based economic think tank, said the LDP should take the
election as a mandate to speed up their push to deregulate the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese people are willing to accept a stronger,
harder-line reform package than what the government has been
doing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said Hashimoto, who took office in January 1996 vowing
to overhaul the economy, was defeated because he failed to carry
through with his promises to change the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Hashimoto's election as a reformer and now his defeat for
failing to reform enough, the country is showing that it wants
faster economic change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen Cohen, a professor at American University's School
of International Service, said the United States should not expect
any major changes from the Japanese soon.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Japanese culture discourages quick actions,
preferring, instead, for the country to reach a consensus before
moving in one direction. While the elections may cause the pace of
reforms to increase slightly, he said, the changes will still take
many years longer than they would in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese are not Americans, and we shouldn't expect them
to act like we would,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
