<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAYSON-THEATER-REVIEW     07-13 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAYSON-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JAYSON': ROUTINE SHOW WITH UNMEMORABLE MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wine and wit are delicate travelers. And what makes
one or the other savory in one setting is easily lost in the
transition to another.
</P>
<P>
   So it is, for the most part, with ``Jayson,'' the syndicated gay
comic strip that has been turned into a musical comedy at the 45th
Street Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Taken in small doses on the printed page, the tart, keenly
observed humor of its author, Jeff Krell, is amusing. But in its
longer form, on the stage, ``Jayson'' becomes just another routine
sitcom, accompanied by some unmemorable music.
</P>
<P>
   The show, directed by Jay Michaels from a book by Krell, with
music and lyrics by Ron Romanovsky and Paul Phillips, isn't dull.
But its plot _ a ``boy meets hunk, boy wins hunk, boy loses hunk''
romance about true friendship and true love and personal honesty
and parental acceptance of gay children _ covers ground that has
been visited before and more tellingly. And pivotal moments _ the
gay Jayson's decision to marry his female roommate, Arena Stage,
for money and his well-built lover, Eduardo's, decision to drop
Jayson and medical school in favor of a Hollywood career _ seem
more arbitrary and out of character on the stage than on the page.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McNicholas contributes a set of Sunday comic strip
colorfulness, bathed in never-a-rainy-day brightness by Roger
Formosa, and Julia N. Van Vliet's costumes are a knowing complement
to character.
</P>
<P>
   Stealing the show in a display of queenly bitchiness, flamboyant
male and female attire and withering commentary is Craig Dawson as
Robyn Ricketts, a producer of gay porn films like ``Locker Room
Lust.'' Robyn energizes ``Jayson'' at every opportunity, from the
moment he turns up shortly after the action begins.
</P>
<P>
   Boyish, decent and unassuming as portrayed by Brian Cooper,
Jayson Callowhill, yearning for a career in advertising and true
love, is a recent college graduate, newly arrived in New York from
the confines of Farmville, Pa. In short order he finds himself with
a roommate in the form of his old college pal, the sometimes shrill
Arena Stage (Susan Agin), a dentist's daughter from Long Island,
and a neighbor in the form of Robyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jayson'' proceeds to have its fun with conflict between Arena
and Robyn Ricketts, the arrival of the appealing Eduardo (Mark
Haen) and the appearance of Jayson's ``American Gothic'' parents
and Arena's Jewish parents. Kenny Morris contributes a gallery of
comic characters in roles ranging from both fathers to a rabbi and
one of Jayson's bosses, and Jane Smulyan has a high time as both
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   But transferring ``Jayson'' from page to stage doesn't really
improve the content.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `JAYSON'
</P>
<P>
   Book by Jeff Krell, based on his comic strip; music and lyrics
by Ron Romanovsky and Paul Phillips; musical direction and
arrangements by Simon Deacon; directed by Jay Michaels; sets by Jim
McNicholas; lighting by Roger Formosa; costumes by Julia N. Van
Vliet; choreography by Kyle Craig; assistant choreographer, Lee
Wilkins; production stage manager, Joseph Mauro. Presented by
Ignite Entertainment Corp. At the 45th Street Theater
</P>
<P>
   With: Brian Cooper (Jayson Callowhill), Susan Agin (Arena
Stage), Craig Dawson (Robyn Ricketts), Mark Haen (Eduardo Rivera
and Feldman), Jane Smulyan (Bertha Callowhill and Stella Stage),
Kenny Morris (Armistice Callowhill, Stan Stage, Phelps, Rabbi,
Riverdale and DiCerchio) and D. Matt Crabtree and Alicia Litwin
(Ensemble).
</P>
