<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2917 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMF-BOS &LR;      07-13 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF-LED BAILOUT PACKAGE FOR RUSSIA ANNOUNCED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a dramatic show of support for the Kremlin's efforts
to avert financial collapse, the International Monetary Fund and
other lenders announced Monday a $22.6 billion rescue package for
Russia's beleaguered economy.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and other Western leaders praised the whopping
bailout, larger than the $10 billion to $15 billion Russia had
previously requested, as a vote of international confidence in
Russia's ability to put its fiscal affairs in order.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has vowed, and failed, to do this in return for aid many
times before. But Monday's loan could also be seen as a sign of the
West's concern over what economic meltdown could mean in a
politically unstable nuclear superpower, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The new cash, $6 billion of which could be available early next
week, will give President Boris Yeltsin's embattled administration
badly needed breathing room by allowing it to meet short-term debt
service obligations and protect the ruble from a politically
dangerous devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, should restore some investor faith in Russia's
stock market, which has lost 60 percent of its value since the
beginning of the year. Monday, Russia's leading index rose nearly
10 percent at the news of the loans.
</P>
<P>
   But the rescue package brought little good news to a nation that
has heard promises of better times to come for years, but has yet
to feel positive effects of market reforms. If anything, the tough
conditions imposed by the IMF and the World Bank for receipt of the
new credits augured even harder times in the short run for millions
of increasingly disgruntled workers who go months without
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Russian and Western officials Monday hailed the agreement as a
sign of faith that the government of Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko had the right recipe for fixing what ails Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decisions taken today signify a restoration of faith in
Russia's ability to overcome its difficulties,'' Russia's lead
negotiator, Anatoly Chubais, told a news conference after emerging
from three days of talks with officials of the IMF and the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which is spread over this year and next, calls
for the IMF to provide $11.6 billion, for the World Bank to add $4
billion and for Japan to give $1.5 billion in a World
Bank-sponsored program _ for a total of $17.1 billion. That, added
to $5.5 billion Russia will receive under existing loan
arrangements with all three, totals $22.6 billion, Chubais said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's crisis was ignited by outside factors, such as the
Asian economic collapse and low oil prices, but has been fanned by
a host of domestic woes, such as chronically poor tax collection,
corruption and misuse of funds at all levels, and the slow pace of
restructuring of Russian industry.
</P>
<P>
   To make ends meet, Russia has built up a mountain of short-term
debt that it must repay at interest rates as high as 150 percent.
Government officials say about 33 percent of total budget spending
goes toward debt service. Chubais Monday announced a plan to reduce
Russia's short-term domestic debt burden by replacing short-term
government securities with longer-term debt that would be
denominated in dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The critical question Russia now faces is whether it can
implement badly needed reforms in the grace period the bailout has
created. In the past, Russia has promised to improve taxation, cut
spending, and restructure inefficient industry in return for IMF
and World Bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   But those promises have faded, largely thanks to Yeltsin, who
tends to distance himself from unpopular but necessary measures,
which in turn reduces the chances that they will be enforced. For
example, promises to cut spending and improve tax collection went
right out the window in the presidential election year of 1996,
when Yeltsin needed to be able to offer tax breaks and increased
social benefits to woo voters.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether the government's austerity plan will
withstand growing social unrest. IMF official John Odling-Smee said
Moscow had vowed to cut its budget deficit to 5.6 percent of gross
domestic product this year and to 2.8 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   If the government fulfills the austerity program to the letter,
in the short run things will get even harder for unpaid miners and
state employees, some of whom are camped out in protest at
government headquarters in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The debt crisis produces stories that would be almost funny if
it were not for the looming danger they signal. Soldiers' laundry
is held up by cleaners who have not been paid; soldiers are fed dog
food instead of beef stew.
</P>
<P>
   The first test for the austerity program will come at the end of
the week, when the State Duma, the lower house of parliament
dominated by opposition parties, debates the tough new spending
cuts and tax reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do not do something radical, this money will quickly run
out and we will have to borrow again,'' said Alexander Zhukov,
chairman of the Duma's Tax and Finance committee. But Zhukov will
likely be in the minority of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF's board, which must formally approve the agreement at a
meeting scheduled for July 20 in Washington, will be watching. So
will Yeltsin, who has sounded an increasingly shrill note of late,
hinting at an extremist plot to unseat him, and warning he would
implement tough measures by decree if the Duma fails to pass them.
</P>
<P>
   But Kiriyenko's program faces an even more fundamental problem.
It is easy to talk about collecting taxes. But in Russia's economy,
most transactions are done by barter, not money. How does the
government collect on this?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, wage arrears are not caused by a lack of money, but
by the fact that directors of large enterprises are able to get
away with not paying their workers. What is needed, observers say,
is political resolve not economic bailouts. But that, too, has been
lacking over the years, said Andrei Piontkowski, a Moscow-based
analyst on Russian politics and economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things go as they always do, most of the new money will end
up stolen, while nothing in the country will change,'' Piontkowski
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most Russians would appear to agree. A recent poll showed that
61 percent of Russians are convinced the Kiriyenko government
cannot solve the country's problems. That attitude put a cloud over
the news of Monday's bailout package.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great news for Russia because it definitely puts off
anything like the meltdown we were facing for six months or maybe a
year,'' said Gleb Shestavkov of Global Fund Management in Moscow.
``But it doesn't really solve the problem in the long run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
