<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASHIMOTO RESIGNATION DRIVES BOND SELLOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Treasury securities suffered their worst one-day losses in more
than a month Monday on suggestions that Japan and Russia would
overcome their economic crises, which diminished the allure of U.S.
bonds as a safe-haven investment.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 30-year bond's price fell 31/32, or nearly $10 for
each $1,000 in the face amount, to 106 7/32. Its yield, which rises
when the price falls, increased to 5.69 percent from 5.62 percent
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The main force behind the bond selloff was the resignation of
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto of Japan, after weekend elections
that reduced his party's power and showed widespread
dissatisfaction with his Cabinet's handling of the country's
deepening economic problems. The drop in U.S. bond prices came on
speculation that the new Japanese prime minister, as yet to be
designated, might speed up tax cuts and other measures to stimulate
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The financial turmoil in Asia has been a major reason why U.S.
bonds have rallied in recent months, sending the yield on the long
bond as low as 5.56 percent last week, the lowest level since the
Treasury began regular sales of these securities in 1977. Buyers
have been acting on the belief that Asia's problems will hurt the
U.S. economy, keeping inflation and interest rates down.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds also weakened Monday on news of an agreement on new
international aid to Russia to help it avoid default. Russia's
worsening economic problems had also been an important force
driving up U.S. Treasury bond prices.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, bond traders should get more data on the possibility
of American inflation when the consumer price index for June is
released along with the report on June retail sales. Most
economists are expecting a gain of two-tenths of a percentage
point, both in the overall inflation index and in so-called ``core
inflation,'' which excludes food and energy prices.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Monday's bond market weakness, the weekly Treasury
auction of new three- and six-month bills met with strong demand.
Three-month bills were priced to yield an average rate of 4.98
percent, up from 4.96 percent a week ago, while the six-month bill
was priced to yield an average rate of 5.025 percent, up from 5.010
percent last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
