A2930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHULZ-CROCODILES-600     07-13 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHULZ-CROCODILES-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REBIRTH OF A WRITER MURDERED IN POLAND
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the sort of twist he might have found
paradoxically engaging, fate has finally turned kind to Bruno
Schulz decades after a Gestapo officer shot and killed him in 1942
as he crossed a street in Drogobych, the provincial Polish hometown
he hated but could never leave.
</P>
<P>
   The two short books of shimmering mythologized reminiscence that
this shy and often depressed high school art and shop teacher wrote
in the 1930s have by now been translated into many languages. With
every year their author is acquiring more and more distinguished
devotees eager to honor his work and spread his fame.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the second of those books, ``The Street of Crocodiles,''
has been turned into a theatrical piece that opens Thursday at the
John Jay College Theater as part of the Lincoln Center Festival
'98.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did we come to do it?'' asked Simon McBurney, the founder
and director of Theatre de Complicite, the innovative troupe that
despite its French name is based in England. ``Well, in 1990 a
Polish-born director, Helena Kaut-Howson, introduced me to Schulz's
two books saying that they were strange and extraordinary stories
and that she thought they might have something to do with the
theater but she didn't know how to make use of them.'' Speaking
from London, McBurney said he had read the books ``and found them
neither strange nor out of the ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I immediately recognized Schulz's world as the place of
childhood and his recognition of the openness of a child's
imagination,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McBurney, whose own childhood was spent in Cambridge as the son
of an academic, said the writing was ``a little like Proust, like
the images of Marc Chagall, like Dylan Thomas when he makes you
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect is, as Schulz himself wrote, `to mature into
childhood,' '' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Schulz stories, originally written in Polish, lack a
conventional narrative, so McBurney, whose experimental theater
relies on very physical and highly choreographed movements, merged
elements from Schulz's melancholy life with images drawn from his
poetic prose. These gave willful force to images like store
dummies, coagulating clouds, the curve of a servant girl's leg, the
oppressive miasma of small-town boredom.
</P>
<P>
   The production was last performed at the Young Vic in London in
1994, and McBurney decided to revive it when his company was
invited to this year's Lincoln Center Festival. ``New York is the
only place I wanted to revive it since there are probably more
people there who admire his work than anywhere else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz's work has been gaining respect all over the world since
the war, but New York writers have been among the most effective of
his champions. Philip Roth published Schulz's two books of poetic,
nostalgic prose as part of his Penguin series, ``Writers From the
Other Europe.'' John Updike has written several admiring critical
essays about Schulz and has called him ``one of the great writers,
one of the great transmogrifiers of the world into words.'' Cynthia
Ozick has attributed to Schulz ``one of the most original
imaginations in modern Europe'' and made the writer a central
presence in her novel ``The Messiah of Stockholm.'' In 1988 Jerzy
Kosinski held a Town Hall evening to honor the writer, announcing a
$10,000 prize in Schulz's name, to be given to writers who are
insufficiently well known. Elizabeth Hardwick and Susan Sontag
offered praise. Shortly before his death, Isaac Bashevis Singer
said of Schulz, ``He wrote sometimes like Kafka, sometimes like
Proust and at times succeeded in reaching depths that neither had
reached.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Europe, Danilo Kis, the Yugoslav novelist, had written,
``Schulz is my God,'' and Jerzy Ficowski, a Polish writer, spent
four years searching for drawings, letters and written fragments
that Schulz left behind. Neither Ficowski nor anyone else has yet
been able to find the manuscript of a large novel called ``The
Messiah'' that Schulz had placed in the countryside for safekeeping
before he and the other Jews of Drogobych were herded into the
city's ghetto by the occupying Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   But among the cult of Schulz enthusiasts no one has welcomed his
growing reputation with more delight than an 80-year-old retired
piano teacher named Renato Laufer who lives in Inwood, Manhattan.
Her feelings are deeply personal since Schulz had been her drawing
teacher when she was the teen-age daughter of well-to-do parents in
Drogobycz, a city now in Ukraine that grew rich when nearby oil
deposits were discovered early in the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 15 or 16 years old,'' said Mrs. Laufer. ``My parents
thought that I had some talent in sketching and so every Sunday I
would go with my girlfriend and we would draw for him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was already famous in Poland,'' she said. ``He had
published the first book, `The Sanatorium Under the Sign of the
Hourglass.' He had sent it to a famous woman writer, and she had
gotten it published and it was a sensation. It was read on the
radio, but he lived with two aunts and taught at the boys' high
school and could not leave Drogobycz. But for my girlfriend and I
he was very strange. He seemed so somber. He always wore a flannel
jacket and a scarf around his neck. He was afraid of colds and
worried about his lungs. We would tease him and laugh at him behind
his back. From some of his drawings you can see he was a foot
fetishist, and once I caught him secretly sketching my friend's
legs; she had very lovely legs. Later I read everything he wrote
and everything about him. I realized he was so far ahead of his
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In her apartment Mrs. Laufer keeps a portrait of her old teacher
not far from a sketch of Chopin.
</P>
<P>
   She remembered how she heard about Schulz's death while she was
in hiding. It was a day that the people came to call Black
Thursday, when another group of Jews hiding beyond the ghetto had
been discovered and one of them, a young man, fired at and wounded
a German. Reprisals were ordered. At the time Schulz, who had been
commissioned to paint frescoes in the house of a Gestapo officer,
had been given a pass by his patron and was walking in the town. He
was spotted by a Nazi storm trooper who had argued with the man for
whom Schulz was working. He stepped up to the writer and shot him.
``The way we heard the story,'' said Mrs. Laufer, who later
survived the war in the forests of southeastern Poland, ``the man
who shot him went to the man for whom he was painting and said, `I
have just killed your Jew.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
