<HEADER>
A2938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNTERTENORS-NYT &LR;      07-13 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTERTENORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: A SINGING VOICE ON THE SEXUAL FRINGE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grumblings go on about how we are living through a drought of
great singers. Recordings from two or three generations back are
forever being cited as evidence, though we ought to wonder whether
their simple existence does not half-prove the case. In no other
time have great dead performers lived on to challenge the living,
providing competition that is unfair in two ways. The old singers
are taken to set the standard and do not allow the art of singing
to change. Also, what may have been their very finest performances,
captured on record, become the measure for what happens on any
particular night at the Met.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever may be the rival claims of a recorded Rosa Ponselle and
a live Renee Fleming, there are kinds of singing in which the
present age has not been matched for a very long time. You probably
have to go back 800 years to find someone who was singing
troubadour songs with as much distinction and passion as Paul
Hillier, or 500 to find choirs as capable as the Clerks' Group or
the Tallis Scholars in the music of Ockeghem. But what is most
striking by far, and a glory of contemporary musical life, is the
abundance of outstanding countertenors.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the recent upsurge are clear. They include the
presence of inspiring models, from Alfred Deller through James
Bowman to David Daniels. But they also include the demand created
by the early-music revival for people to sing not only music
written for the countertenor voice but also the enormous repertory
of castrato roles in baroque opera. For these roles, countertenors
provide the best substitute for the castratos, because like them
they contradict customary specifications of the male. The
countertenor voice, utterly male in timbre but usurping female
territory in range, is hermaphroditic. And this sexual ambiguity
speaks loudly for the countertenor's modern desirability.
</P>
<P>
   At the Glyndebourne festival in England this summer, the triumph
of the countertenor is being acted out twice a week, for the
countertenor Andreas Scholl is making his operatic debut in
Handel's ``Rodelinda'' there, and he outshines everyone onstage.
The calm beauty of his singing in Jean-Marie Villegier's tenebrous
Fascist-period staging, suggests the moon: This is singing that
glows.
</P>
<P>
   Handel wrote the part of Bertarido in ``Rodelinda'' for his star
castrato, Senesino, and his librettist, Nicola Francesco Haym,
provided opportunities for a character who would express himself in
tones at once ardent and plaintive. Bertarido is a king who has
been exiled and separated from his wife and son. Having returned to
his former kingdom, he spends most of the first two acts in
disguise, and most of the third, once his identity has been
discovered, in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Disguise and prison: In both situations the hero is bereft. All
that remain are his emotions and hopes. He is often alone, and
though Handelian opera is everywhere an art of soliloquies,
Bertarido, in this piece, is the greatest soliloquist of them all,
delivering laments and love songs.
</P>
<P>
   Scholl's performance of them is gorgeous. His tone is pure and
perfectly made, yet at the same time highly expressive; his voice
moves with ease through the stately slow movements that are
Bertarido's forte, and with only a little less ease through the
much more ebullient aria in the second act. Sometimes his control
is breathtaking. On one long note he executes a steady loudening
and then softening, as if his voice were an instrument he was
handling.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the countertenor voice, which is no more unnatural than
any other operatic type but which has its own particular
artificiality, more easily suggests this kind of separateness from
the performer. At the Glyndebourne ``Rodelinda,'' it is as though
Scholl has a special advantage, shared only with another fine
countertenor, Artur Stefanowicz, in the role of Unulfo, Bertarido's
loyal follower and confidant. Paradoxically, the strange vocal
world in which they operate offers the most stable ground for
viewing the action. It is the rest of the characters, with their
more usual voices, who sound as if they are making pretenses, or as
if they are being perverse in staying outside the luminous sphere
around Scholl and Stefanowicz.
</P>
<P>
   Even as fine a singer as Kurt Streit, in the role of the tyrant
Grimoaldo, sounds tied by being only a tenor. He, his baritone
henchman (Umberto Chiummo) and two women (Anna Caterina Antonacci
and Louise Winter) circle the stage as if mystified, recognizing
the power that Scholl wields, but not knowing where it comes from.
</P>
<P>
   William Christie, conducting the Orchestra of the Age of
Enlightenment, knows. His partnership with Scholl, and with the
other singers, is very fine: He makes the orchestra wait on them,
and phrase with them. He and Scholl also keep the long evening
floating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rodelinda'' is one of those Handel operas that remain in a
state of permanent arousal, until a rapid denouement comes as a
merely mechanical necessity. This is opera mirroring the myth, at
least, of the castrato's sexual potency. You are to wish the night
would never end, and here you do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
