<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGNING FOR OSCAR NIXED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; What's good for beauty contestants and
school-board candidates is apparently good for Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   In what's being described as ``an effort to maintain a high
degree of fairness and dignity'' in the Academy Awards process, the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences is requiring filmmakers
to stop unfair and overly aggressive ``campaigning'' to win Oscar
nominations and awards.
</P>
<P>
   Academy executive administrator Ric Robertson said in a
statement that the guidelines are similar to last year's and are
primarily designed to clarify existing regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In the new guidelines, set forth in a July 9 letter to film
marketers, the Academy's board of governors orders a ban on
``letters of any kind that extol the merits of a film or an
achievement,'' letters to Academy members that contain critics'
blurbs, and the inclusion of photographs or ``extraneous''
advertising copy in printed screening schedules for eligible films.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines also put restrictions on the packaging and
submission of videocassettes of eligible films, recordings and
sheet music, and on descriptions of submitted screenplays. One
specific change from last year is that the mailing of video
excerpts from eligible films in order to spotlight particular songs
or musical scores is now prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines also forbid telephone solicitations of voting
members and ``receptions, dinners or other events to which Academy
members are invited and which are connected to the promotion of a
film or achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter warns that companies guilty of infractions may lose
their allotment of tickets to the awards presentation. More serious
violations involving the solicitation of votes may result in a film
losing its eligibility for awards consideration. &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
