<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-CORRUPTION-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN MEDIA TYCOON CONVICTED AGAIN ON CORRUPTION CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Silvio Berlusconi, the flamboyant media tycoon and former
prime minister, was convicted by a Milan jury on Monday of making
illegal political donations and was given a sentence of two years
and four months, as well as a $5.6 million fine.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time this month that Berlusconi, 61, who heads
the center-right opposition group in Parliament, was convicted on
corruption charges. Last week, he was convicted of bribing tax
inspectors and sentenced to a term of two years and nine months. He
was also convicted of accounting fraud in a separate trial in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his three strikes, Berlusconi does not appear to be out.
The tycoon, one of Italy's richest businessmen, is in no immediate
danger of going to jail. As an elected member of Parliament, he has
immunity. Even if Parliament voted to waive his immunity, Italian
law guarantees him at least two appeals before the convictions take
force.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a measure of the baroque complexities of Italian
politics that Monday's long-awaited decision was in some ways less
awkward for Berlusconi than for the administration he accuses of
persecuting him for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an Anglo-Saxon point of view, three preliminary
convictions on separate corruption charges might raise ethical
questions about a politician's qualifications to serve the
public,'' said Massimo Pavarini, a professor of law at the
University of Bologna. ``But in a more Latin, Machiavellian
culture, three convictions can be made to look like a political
conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi, whose Forza Italia party won a series of mayoral
elections in May, is not acting like a fugitive in disgrace. He has
instead turned his multiple legal troubles into a political
campaign, accusing left-leaning prosecutors of singling him out for
political persecution. A little like a player in the card game
Hearts, who decides to amass bad cards to shoot the moon,
Berlusconi is hoarding his convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi, who denies all the charges, was found guilty Monday
of having been involved in a scheme to channel $12 million dollars
to a former prime minister, Bettino Craxi, and his Socialist Party
in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Craxi, whose conviction on one of many corruption charges was
upheld by the Italian Supreme Court in 1996, is a fugitive in
Tunisia. Monday's ruling gave him a four-year sentence and a $10
million fine for having been on the receiving end of the political
payoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely evident that this is not about justice, but
about destruction,'' Berlusconi's media company, Fininvest, said in
a press release. ``The sentence was in the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is an obvious self-serving streak to Berlusconi's
theme, Italian society is nonetheless asking itself painful
questions about the power of its magistrates and the entire
judicial system, turning one prominent politician's travails into a
more widespread social and political tempest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The storm not only affects the immediate future of the strained
center-left government of Prime Minister Romano Prodi, but it also
clouds the past. Berlusconi is seeking to recast and darken one of
Italy's most crucial recent turning-points _ the 1992-1993
investigations into the complex web of political and financial
corruption known as Tangentopoli, or Bribesville, when Milan
prosecutors toppled an entire political class and put more than
2,500 businessmen in jail.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the Tangentopoli investigations, magistrates
were viewed by most Italians as heroes, dedicated public servants
who dared to probe the deep collusion between politics and business
that was at the heart of the Italian system. Five years later, some
of those magistrates have come under scrutiny themselves, and so
have the broad powers of their office.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, shortly after Berlusconi was convicted on charges
that one of his companies, Fininvest, bribed tax officials, his
coalition proposed the creation of a parliamentary commission to
investigate Tangentopoli. The mere suggestion unleashed a bitter
political debate.
</P>
<P>
   While the commission was described as an inquiry into the nature
and breadth of political corruption in the Italian system, many,
including most magistrates, viewed such a commission as a
politically charged effort to investigate the investigators.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Parliament is expected to debate the scope and
purpose of the commission. It is a sensitive issue for the Prodi
government, which has repeatedly called for reform of the political
and judicial system, but does not want to inadvertently help
Berlusconi's cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course there is a problem,'' Prodi said, referring to the
inadequacies of the justice system. ``We need a solution, but the
solution cannot be reached by silencing the magistrates. We must
let the magistrates do their job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
