<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2991 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     07-13 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKER'S BRAIN TAKES NAP ON SLEEPING QUESTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken LLoyd, Ph.D., is a specialist in organizational behavior.
Questions can be sent by electronic mail to lloydonjob(at)aol.com,
or they can be mailed to P.O. Box 260057, Encino, CA 91426. Names
will be withheld upon request.) 
BY KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (LOS ANGELES) _ Q: I was taking a brief nap at my desk after
lunch, and my manager walked in and said I will be terminated if
this ever happens again. I'm a good employee, and I believe my
manager overreacted. I've even heard that in some companies, taking
a nap is acceptable and even has some benefits. What do you think?
D.N.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's time to wake up and smell the reality. Although naps can
have beneficial results and they are permitted in some companies,
you obviously work for a company that prefers to have the employees
remain awake on the job.
</P>
<P>
   In most companies, employees are subject to swift discipline for
sleeping, all the way up to termination. The best way to understand
your manager's reaction is to review your company's policy in this
area, as well as review the kinds of problems that can develop as a
result of your catnap. For example, if you are in a position in
which inattention can lead to serious accidents, injury or
production problems, your manager may have actually underreacted.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, rather than trying to change the culture and
sleeping habits of the company, you are better advised to look at
yourself and see if there may be any physical problems wearing you
down. It will also be helpful to look at your job and see if there
is anything about it that may be putting you to sleep. Since sleep
is a way to psychologically withdraw from work, perhaps your body
is trying to tell you something.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several employees who report to me have been coming to me for
advice on personal matters, and I am not equipped to help them. I
am a good listener with a lot of common sense, but I am not trained
as a counselor and I am not comfortable advising employees in areas
I know little about. But I do not want to abandon them. What can
you suggest? C.T.
</P>
<P>
   A: As a person with a good deal of common sense, you need to
apply it to yourself in this situation. If your common sense tells
you that a particular issue that an employee raises can be easily
remedied with basic horse sense, you can certainly render some
words of wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   However, your good judgment should also tell you when you are
out of your league. For example, when the questions start to focus
on issues like depression, serious problems at home or feelings of
rage, the best strategy is to refer the person to the company's
human resources staff, a health care professional or a religious
adviser. This is not abandoning the employee. In fact, you are
giving him or her excellent advice: Get some professional help.
</P>
<P>
   As a manager, it is also important to be sure that you are not
spending too much time advising your employees on personal matters
and too little time advising them on job-related matters. While
professional counselors often play the role of best friend, it is
appropriate for a manager to be friendly, but not best friends,
with the troops.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been with the company for 15 years, but now there is a
merger in progress and talk about severance pay for those who will
be let go. I want to know if or how a person can negotiate this
package. P.D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Many strategists believe that it pays to negotiate severance
pay. However, one concern is that many companies have specific
formulas in this area, such as so much pay for so many months
worked and they are often reluctant to deviate from them.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there is often some wiggle room, particularly if
you envision your severance as a package and not just a cash
payout. In this regard, you can try to negotiate for longer medical
coverage as well as outplacement support, such as a desk, phone,
secretarial help and career counseling while you search for a job.
</P>
<P>
   If the cash payout is less than what you desire, another
negotiating approach is to try to remain on the payroll longer
while you are doing your job search. This may appeal to the company
because it does not set a precedent in the way that the severance
itself is calculated. Do not be afraid to tell management about
your financial situation and the hardship the current severance
arrangement will cause.
</P>
<P>
   Some strategists also suggest that you look for leverage. For
example, if the company wants you to sign an agreement regarding
your right to sue or compete in the future, the suggested strategy
is to consider rejecting the first offer and holding out until they
sweeten the package for you to the point that parting is more
likely to be sweetened sorrow. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
