</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Berman was taken to Winfield's Restaurant in Greenwich,
Conn., for a Father's Day brunch.
</P>
<P>
   As the party was seated, he noticed a printed, filled-in form on
the table:
</P>
<P>
   Mr./Mrs./Ms. Berman Kenneth
</P>
<P>
   Number of Guests: 3
</P>
<P>
   Adult (CHECKMARK)
</P>
<P>
   Children
</P>
<P>
   Other
</P>
<P>
   That was followed by a table number, date and manager's name.
</P>
<P>
   What Berman wants to know is who or what is ``other''?
</P>
<P>
   The young man walking near Arlene Cohen in Central Park
observed, with a somewhat jaundiced eye, a woman jogging by. He
turned to Mrs. Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spandex is a privilege, not a right,'' he said and went on his
way.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Mai and Tiffany Otto were in a SoHo boutique when they
were approached by an eager salesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies,'' he said, ``if there's anything you need, I'm Nick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And if we don't need anything, who are you then?'' one of the
``ladies'' asked.
</P>
<P>
   I was riding the subway recently and noticed the following
advertising placard placed by the New York City Board of Education
for a teacher recruitment program: ``Our schools need certified
bilingual professionals qualified in the areas of'' _ and it then
proceeded to list a number of educational areas.
</P>
<P>
   Six out of 10, including English as a second language, had a
little star next to them. At the bottom, there was a note stating
that the star meant ``Qualified applicants need not be bilingual.''
</P>
<P>
   What is wrong with this picture?
</P>
<P>
   MARK A. BIENSTOCK
</P>
<P>
   Scene: A recent evening at Chicago's O'Hare Airport. Anne
Ritchie and other tired passengers waiting out a two-hour delay for
a flight to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Next gate: More tired passengers waiting out a delayed flight to
St. Louis. The St. Louis flight announcement rings out _ they will
be boarding in 10 minutes. Applause, laughter, cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, the New York flight is announced, boarding in 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A lone voice cuts the silence. ``So, they want we should jump
for joy?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ritchie knew then that she was almost home.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Marks was sitting near the front of a downtown Lexington
Avenue bus when a woman, obviously in a hurry, managed to get on
the lower step and prevent the door from closing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this an express?'' she gasped.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the driver replied.
</P>
<P>
   She remained on the step, pondering her predicament aloud:
Should she board the bus or wait for a limited? The passengers
became impatient.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she stepped up and, as she deposited her fare, said to
the driver, ``Well, will you drive fast?''
</P>
<P>
   There was a line at a bank on Madison Avenue, and waiting his
turn was a man holding the hand of his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, who appeared to be about 5 or 6 years old, looked
around and asked, ``What is this place?'' Her father explained that
it was a bank. ``What is a bank?'' was the next question.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right, you've never been in a bank before,'' he
replied. ``A bank is what they had before there were money
machines.''
</P>
<P>
   She nodded, satisfied. It now all made sense.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three summers, our family, former New Yorkers, have
spent a week on the Outer Banks of North Carolina. Our
daughter-in-law, Betsy Nicholas, loves to try out new recipes and
one, for yellow-fin tuna, called for a marinade using wasabi, the
Japanese herb. Our son, Paul Kessler, drove to the local
supermarket to search for it. After three unsuccessful attempts, he
found a cheerful clerk near the spice department and tried again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where can I find wasabi?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' the clerk replied, ``I don't live around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The wasabi was at the top of the spice rack, and the tuna
steaks were delicious.
</P>
<P>
   _ETHEL AND LEN KESSLER
</P>
<P>
   After enjoying lunch in the financial district, Sharon Druck and
her friends walked along West Broadway toward Battery Park. Along
the way, they noticed a commotion at the corner _ four police
officers were crowded around a police cruiser. A small crowd had
gathered and Ms. Druck and friends thought perhaps a suspect was
being arrested. As they got closer, they realized that the only
suspects were the keys to the police car, which had been locked
inside.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this story _ it doesn't only happen to you.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Adams was walking behind two women, and as they were
about to pass the Methodist Church of St. Paul and St. Andrew at
86th Street and West End Avenue, they noticed a discarded pair of
new-looking crutches in the gutter.
</P>
<P>
   One of the women paused, pointed toward the church and said
``Well, they seem to be getting results.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Marshman reports that his wife, Ann, was sitting on a
park bench when she noticed an elegant woman slowly parading an
equally elegant French poodle. The poodle had a dazzling white
coat, legs and hindquarters clipped to the skin except for fluffy
pompoms at ankles and tail and, on each ear, long combed-out locks
tied with red bows.
</P>
<P>
   A little girl approached the dog's owner and asked if she might
pet him, politely adding, ``It is a he, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's a he all right,'' was the response. ``The groomer
just likes to cross-dress him.''
</P>
<P>
   The place: Eighth Avenue in the 40s.
</P>
<P>
   The time: Saturday afternoon; curtains still up on matinee
performances.
</P>
<P>
   The scene: Charter bus waiting for returning theatergoers.
</P>
<P>
   The observer: Linda Cohen
</P>
<P>
   The action: Bus driver relaxing, arms behind his head in a
hammock he has hung between the side-view mirror of the bus and a
lamppost.
</P>
<P>
   Make that inaction.
</P>
