<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KHOBAR-GENERAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-OFFICER DEFENDS HANDLING OF SECURITY AT SAUDI BASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ With every crack of a hammer and the daylong whine
of power saws slicing into wood, Terryl Schwalier moves closer to
building a new home. And he edges ever farther from a distant
desert community known as Khobar Towers.
</P>
<P>
   But the former Air Force brigadier general never truly can
escape Khobar, a 180-building Saudi Arabian dorm complex rocked
June 25, 1996, by a terrorist blast that killed 19 Americans and
wounded 345 others, many seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't done the things that we did, if we had not acted
aggressively and practically with the information that we knew,
then it would be much more difficult,'' Schwalier, 51, said. ``But
I know we were acting responsibly, taking care of the people who
were put in my charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I was acting responsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on who is talking, Schwalier is a hero or a scapegoat,
a commander who went above and beyond the call of duty to protect
those he led, or fell well short of the standard for American
generals.
</P>
<P>
   Then a brigadier general on his way to a second star and a
coveted Pentagon post, Schwalier's bright career crumbled like the
buildings closest to Khobar's blast center. Defense Secretary
William Cohen laid the bulk of the blame on Schwalier, saying in a
June 25, 1997, Pentagon news conference that Schwalier failed to do
everything possible to protect his forces against the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I clearly believe that it was politically motivated,''
Schwalier said of Cohen's decision. ``I do not believe it was the
right decision. But I respect his right to make that decision. I
think it was the wrong one.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's conclusions didn't just bring down Schwalier. His
assessment prompted Air Force Chief of Staff Ronald Fogleman to
quit his post in protest _ an unprecedented event in Air Force
history. It exposed strained relations between the Saudis and the
United States, and sparked profound changes in the way America
protects the oil-rich desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has spent $122.6 million moving its troops
from Dhahran to Prince Sultan Air Base in the Saudi desert, where
adversaries now face winding roads, night vision devices and sensor
networks. The Air Force's Security Forces Center, a relatively
obscure anti-terrorist operation, opened in the wake of the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. Richard A. Coleman, commander of the Security Forces
Center, sees the improvements as ``formidable steps'' intended to
foil attacks like the one at Khobar.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's claim that Schwalier stumbled while trying to protect
his wing draws defenders and detractors in and out of uniform.
</P>
<P>
   In his first speech since quitting the joint chiefs, Fogleman
last fall told a group in Austin, Texas, that Schwalier took around
130 actions to prevent the blast. David Winn, consul general in
Dhahran during Schwalier's year in the desert kingdom, said
``extraordinary measures'' were taken that included car and body
searches at the compound's gate, and placing sharpshooters on dorm
roofs.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabian authorities, as recently as the day before the
bombing, had repeatedly assured the Americans there were no
indications of a terrorist attack and ``even gently chided us for
worrying too much,'' Winn said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen said intelligence reports indicated a terrorist attack
on Dhahran was to be expected. Like Cohen, retired Army Gen. Wayne
Downing said Schwalier didn't prevent terrorists from setting off a
bomb on the complex's perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said there were other failings, Downing _ who headed
an influential task force that found fault with Schwalier's efforts
_ is quick to say that Schwalier's bosses erred, too. He said those
in the command chain ``were let off rather easily,'' but couldn't
explain why Schwalier was singled out.
</P>
<P>
   Downing's report identifies the leadership of the U.S. Central
Command, which was responsible for the Persian Gulf region, and Air
Force Central Command as failing to have done more to protect
Khobar.
</P>
<P>
   Fran Heiser, a Palm Coast, Fla., real estate company owner who
lost her only son, Air Force Master Sgt. Michael Heiser, 35, in the
blast, said Schwalier must take responsibility as commander at
Khobar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been labeled a scapegoat,'' Heiser said. ``But isn't
losing a star a small price to pay for 19 lives?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A sympathetic Downing praises Schwalier for boosting defenses at
Khobar and preventing the worst attack _ a bomb that could
penetrate the complex.
</P>
<P>
   But both his report and the one later issued by Cohen dovetail
on issues ranging from the need for alarm systems at Khobar to
alerting superiors to problems beyond Schwalier's control.
</P>
<P>
   Downing shares Cohen's view that Schwalier had served well, but
as wing commander was ``ultimately responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwalier said he believes Sens. Arlen Specter and Joseph
Lieberman helped launch a search for a fall guy. Specter, R-Pa.,
said in a June 30, 1996, appearance on NBC's ``Meet The Press''
that there's ``a real need to shake up'' the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   In a July 9 Senate hearing, Lieberman, D-Conn., said: ``The
obvious fact is they didn't do enough because 19 Americans are
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter's office did not return a phone call. A spokesman with
Lieberman's office, speaking on condition of anonymity, said: ``I
can tell you Sen. Lieberman never wanted any witch-hunting to occur
and he never called for that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   For Schwalier, there is one great, unstated but obvious truth:
America has moved its troops to the desert, a decision that implies
commanders can't protect their forces in Saudi urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reported to my location, I didn't choose it. I tried to make
it better and I tried to make it safe. That was my job,'' Schwalier
said. ``I was dealt a deck and that's the one I worked with,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was a personal failing, why have we changed
everything?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
