<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. NOT AIMING TO MEDIATE CHIAPAS CONFLICT, ANNAN SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANTHONY DEPALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan denied Monday that
the United Nations was looking to mediate the conflict in Chiapas,
even though he expressed concern over the fragile state of peace in
Mexico's southernmost state.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, in Brazil on the first leg of a 10-day visit to Latin
America, said some of his statements last week at a news conference
in New York had been misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Annan had apparently not realized how Mexican officials would
react when he broadly suggested, in response to a reporter's
question, that the possibility of U.N. involvement in resolving the
four-and-a-half-year standoff in Chiapas would depend on what
government leaders told him when he visited Mexico later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   That was widely reported in Mexico as an offer to mediate, and
Mexican officials rejected it outright.
</P>
<P>
   Annan made it clear Monday that although Mexican officials had
sent him reports about Chiapas, which he will study, they had not
formally sought U.N. help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a role could only be considered under certain conditions,
among them an official request by the Mexican government,'' said a
statement Monday morning from Annan's office in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely considered highly unlikely that Mexico would make
such a request. The government has moved to bar some international
observers from Chiapas, and even the hint of foreign involvement is
usually enough to evoke the tragedies caused by interventions and
invasions here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can sort out our problems amongst ourselves,'' Interior
Minister Francisco Labastida Ochoa told reporters over the weekend.
He said the documents on Chiapas had been sent to New York simply
to inform the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not consider it appropriate to internationalize the
conflict,'' Labastida said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roberto Albores Guillen of Chiapas was more direct, telling
reporters that Annan would be welcome in Chiapas ``as a tourist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Annan's concern has encouraged church leaders and human
rights groups in Mexico, setting off a broad discussion over
whether international efforts are needed to bring permanent peace
to Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having the United Nations take an interest in Chiapas has been
a very important advance,'' said the Rev. Edgar Cortez, director of
the Miguel Agustin Center for Human Rights in Mexico City, which
has long monitored Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   Cortez said he doubted that the government or the Zapatista
National Liberation Army rebels would accept direct U.N. mediation.
But he said by simply monitoring human rights the group could calm
tensions and help set the stage for a resumption of peace talks,
which broke off in September 1996, mostly over granting autonomy to
Indian communities.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Chiapas government proposed a plan that offers to
recognize the autonomy of Indian-run communities designated by the
Zapatista rebels. But its chances of success are considered
minimal, because the rebels demand that the federal government pull
back its troops, while the government refuses to do so and insists
that Zapatista sympathizers surrender their arms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
