<HEADLINE>
CRASH SNAPS BOARDMAN'S WRIST -- AND LEADING EFFORT  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The leader's yellow jersey in the Tour de France is never easy
to keep, but it's usually the steep mountain rides or the strenuous
grind of three weeks of racing that bring a rider down.
</P>
<P>
   Not in Chris Boardman's case. The British rider who had worn the
jersey for the first two days, crashed Monday and fractured his
left wrist. So now he's not just out of the leader's spot, he's out
of the race.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 minutes away from the finish of the 127-mile stage in
Cork, Ireland, Boardman crashed after his front wheel clipped the
rear wheel of his teammate, Frederic Moncassin of France.
Boardman's helmet hit a stone fence by the roadside, cutting his
forehead. Tour doctor David Curtis said Boardman had a fractured
left wrist, as well as cuts and bruises to his face. His arm was
put in a cast and he was to spend the night in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Svorada of the Czech Republic won the stage, which was the
Tour's final day in Ireland, while Germany's Erik Zabel finished
17th and took over the yellow jersey as the overall leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour has not been kind to Boardman, 29, who was the gold
medalist in the 1992 Olympics in the pursuit race. He won the
prologue in his Tour debut in 1994, but he broke his ankle in the
1995 prologue and was eliminated. He went on to finish 39th in the
1996 Tour, and in 1997 again won the prologue but was forced to
withdraw two weeks later because of crash injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The 189 riders began Monday's race at Enniscorthy, a market town
near the ancestral home of the Kennedy political dynasty. About
one-third of the way along the route, the riders reached
Carrick-on-Suir, the hometown of Sean Kelly, who won the sprinter's
green jersey a record four times during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The riders stuck together and set a leisurely pace through most
of the stage along Ireland's flat southern coast.
</P>
<P>
   But then the crash occurred and set up a new race for the yellow
jersey. Two of Boardman's Gan teammates, Frenchmen Eddy Seigneur
and Francois Simon, broke away from the pack and pulled ahead by
more than a minute until the race reached the outskirts of Cork.
</P>
<P>
   A second pileup 7 miles from the end caused more than a dozen
cyclists to topple over and others to veer onto the grassy banks to
avoid the collision. That crash injured another Gan rider, Francois
Simon of France, who received four stitches in his heel after
finishing the race in 184th place. But crashes aside, the race went
on.
</P>
<P>
   Czech rider Svorada won the sprint finish, while Zabel took over
the yellow jersey as overall leader with a cumulative time of 10
hours 21 minutes 16 seconds. He is now 7 seconds ahead of Tom
Steels, winner of Sunday's stage. American Bobby Julich is in sixth
place, just 9 seconds back.
</P>
<P>
   The riders flew to France Monday night, to resume the race
Tuesday _ Bastille Day _ in the host country. The 106-mile stage
goes from Roscoff to Lorient in the northwestern Brittany region of
France.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
