<HEADLINE>
KOOL-AID WEEK IN NEBRASKA  
 HEALTH ADVISORY FOR TRAVELERS TO TAIWAN  
 ABORIGINAL AUSTRALIA  
 GAY GAMES IN THE NETHERLANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 19)  
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kool-Aid was formulated and first produced in Hastings, Neb. To
recognize this momentous fact, Gov. Ben Nelson recently proclaimed
it the official state soft drink, and Nebraskans will celebrate
Kool-Aid Week from Aug. 9-15. Travelers who find themselves in
Nebraska during that time can partake of the neon-bright beverage
(the original six flavors will be offered free) at rest stops along
Interstate 80, the state's main east-west thoroughfare.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 15, the Hastings Museum, in conjunction with the town of
Hastings, is planning an extravaganza called Kool-Aid Days. The
town is in south-central Nebraska 16 miles south of I-80 on U.S.
Highway 281. Activities will include a Kool-Aid recipe cook-off, a
contest to choose the most creative Kool-Aid stand, and races for
roller-skating waiters and waitresses (who carry a tray of glasses
filled with Kool-Aid). Exhibits about Kool-Aid and its inventor,
Edwin Perkins (1889-1961), will be on display.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins' first foray into drink concentrates was a product
called Fruit Smack. It was sold as a liquid in glass bottles, but
shipping proved expensive and precarious (the bottles broke). In
1927 he figured out a way to dehydrate the liquid and sell the
powder in little envelopes. He called it Kool-Ade, shortly changed
to Kool-Aid. The drink proved to be wildly popular; because it was
also affordable, Perkins' business flourished during the
Depression. Perkins Product Co. moved to Chicago in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call the Hastings Museum at (800) 508-4629 or
(402) 461-2399. The museum is open daily. Admission is $5.
</P>
<P>
   CDC Issues Warning on Virus in Taiwan
</P>
<P>
   A widespread viral illness on Taiwan that can be fatal to
infants and young children poses some risk to international
travelers, according to the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention. The virus causes a hand, foot and mouth disease that is
identified by sores in the mouth and rashes on the palm of the hand
and soles of the feet. Meningitis, encephalitis or a poliolike
paralysis may follow. Sixty children under 3 years of age on Taiwan
had died by July 7. The risk of death to visitors was described as
``very small''; the death rate in the age group in Taiwan was one
in 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is described as moderately contagious; it is not
spread by airborne transmission, and is unlikely to be spread by
food or water. It is spread by direct contact with a sick person's
saliva, mucus or stool. The government recommends that travelers
avoid prolonged direct contact with infected people and take
hygienic steps: Wash hands frequently, especially after diaper
changes; disinfect contaminated surfaces, and wash soiled clothing.
The government asked travel agencies and airlines to notify their
clients of the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Tours and Museum Focus on Aborigines
</P>
<P>
   Travelers interested in Australia's aboriginal heritage can view
traditional dances at the new National Aboriginal Cultural Center,
scheduled to open in early August in the Darling Harbor section of
Sydney. The center houses the most extensive collection of
artifacts of the country's 200 aboriginal tribes, including some of
the earliest rock art dating back at least 50,000 years. Other
relics include masks, boomerangs, dancing sticks, fishing spears
and colorfully painted didgeridoos, flute-like instruments made of
eucalyptus wood.
</P>
<P>
   Artists and craftsmen from various tribal nations work at the
center, open from 9:30 a.m. to 8 p.m. daily. Dance performances
take place at 11 a.m. and 1, 4 and 6 p.m. Admission, which includes
performances, is $18.
</P>
<P>
   More knowledge of the aborigines can be gained by taking tours
offered by organizations like Tobwabba Arts and Aboriginal Cultural
Tours in the Forster region of New South Wales, a three-hour drive
north of Sydney, and Harry Nanya Tours in Wentworth in the Outback.
Participants often sample aboriginal food, called bush tucker,
which can include emu, kangaroo, roots, flowers, leaves and
insects, and view paintings and decorative wares. The Tobwabba tour
costs $21 a person with lunch; the Harry Nanya tour is $27.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Aussie Helpline, (805) 775-2000; Tourism New South
Wales, (310) 301-1903, or www.tourism.nsw.gov.au.
</P>
<P>
   Sports and the Arts at Gay Games in Amsterdam
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam, Netherlands, one of Europe's gay capitals, is
anticipating an influx of more than 200,000 people for the fifth
Gay Games _ the first to be held outside North America. From Aug.
1-8, 15,000 participants from 64 countries will compete in 29
sports events and take part in 14 artist's workshops.
</P>
<P>
   Badminton, ice hockey, volleyball, wheelchair dancing and a
marathon along the route of the 1928 Olympic race in Amsterdam are
among the competitions to be held throughout the city and also in
Amersfoort, a town east of Amsterdam, which will be the site of the
swimming events.
</P>
<P>
   According to Paul van Yperen, a spokesman for the Games, the
competition will be open to both homosexuals and heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to government subsidies and contributions from 38
private sponsors, including KLM Royal Dutch Airlines and Kodak, the
Games are also the recipient of the first contribution (about
$55,000) from the European Commission to a gay event.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Ministry of Defense is helping out with 3,000 cots to
be set up for athletes in schools and campgrounds, although there
is still hotel availability.
</P>
<P>
   Three thousand volunteers are being trained to help organize the
events and manage crowds. Central Amsterdam is expected to be the
busiest during the games, particularly the area around Dam Square,
Friendship Village and gay centers such as the
Reguliersdwarsstraat.
</P>
<P>
   When this event was first held in 1982 in San Francisco, the
U.S. Olympic Committee sued to forbid the use of the name Gay
Olympics; the organization subsequently changed the name. The event
was last held in 1994 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the usual gold, silver and bronze medals,
commissioned by the municipal Amsterdam Fund for the Arts and
designed by Marcel Wanders, there is a fourth medal that all
participants will receive.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural events _ including some 40 exhibitions _ will
complement the games. At the Rijksmuseum, ``Olympic Gods'' will
feature prints and drawings of Jupiter, Adonis, Diana and other
mythological beings, and at the Stedelijk Museum for Modern Art,
lesbian and gay artists will display their sculptures, paintings,
photographs and other works.
</P>
<P>
   Many theaters are putting on special shows, among them two
performances on Aug. 3 and 4 by Harvey Fierstein in the Municipal
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   There will be free concerts on Dam Square, open-air theater in
the Vondelpark, and presentations of recent gay-themed films on an
outdoor screen every evening after 10 on Nieuwmarkt Square. The
opening ceremony in Amsterdam Arena, on Aug. 1 at 8 p.m., will
include performances by Dana International, the Israeli transsexual
who won this year's Eurovision song contest, and the Weather Girls
accompanied by a hundred dancers in sailor outfits.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the sports events are free; the swimming, dancing,
body-building and ice hockey competitions and a number of finals
will cost between about $6 and $12.
</P>
<P>
   For tickets, call (31-20) 420 0200; for accommodations, call
(31-20) 427- 1998 or (31-35) 542-9333.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.gaygames.nl.
</P>
</TEXT>
