   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   NEW-YORKER-EDITOR (New York) _ David Remnick, a Pulitzer
Prize-winning author who has spent the last six years writing for
The New Yorker on topics from Alexander Solzhenitsyn to Mike Tyson,
is named the fifth editor in the magazine's seven-decade history.
By Robin Pogrebin. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news
file.) With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-ISOLATION (Whittier, Alaska) _ On rare days when the
clouds lift, it is still hard to see why anyone would want to live
in this toenail of a port at the foot of a glacier on Prince
William Sound. But when the train departs, leaving Whittier alone
at the edge of the world, it is evident why 250 or so people have
chosen to live in a bombproof tower in a town that is an asterisk
in World War II history. Surrounded by mountains on three sides and
the sea on the other, Whittier is that rare American town with no
road connecting it to the rest of the world. By Timothy Egan.
(Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) With map and
photo. 1,000 words.
</P>
