<P>
   NEW-YORKER-EDITOR (New York) _ David Remnick, a Pulitzer
Prize-winning author who has spent the last six years writing for
The New Yorker on topics from Alexander Solzhenitsyn to Mike Tyson,
was named the fifth editor in the magazine's seven-decade history
Monday. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Top display)
</P>
<P>
   REMANUFACTURE (Undated) _ Once the purview of myriad small
companies that eked out a living refurbishing carburetors, printer
cartridges and other used parts, re-manufacturing _ a method of
re-using old parts in new machines _ has hit corporate America in a
big way. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom)
</P>
<P>
   MCI-INTERNET (Undated) _ MCI Communications Corp. is close to
determining the future of its Internet business. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   CENDANT-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ More is at stake than just the
vast sum that vanished in the blink of an eye for Cendant
investors. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's financial stories.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 10 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are tonight's columns:
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ A brighter earnings outlook for several
leading technology companies propelled the technology-laden Nasdaq
composite index to its fourth consecutive new high. By Sharon R.
King.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Treasury securities suffered their worst
one-day losses in more than a month Monday on suggestions that
Japan and Russia would overcome their economic crises, which
diminished the allure of U.S.bonds as a safe-haven investment. By
Robert Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   NFL-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ The annual advertising offensive to
stimulate interest in National Football League games will begin
almost two months earlier than usual and involve almost four times
as many promotional commercials as before. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET.)
