<SLUG> BC-CAR-LOUDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUDON LANDS LATE-AUGUST WINSTON CUP DATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeff Burton and his winning team were off to Indianapolis to
test for the upcoming Brickyard 400. Bob Bahre was back in his
office in Oxford, Maine. And stragglers in motor homes continued to
stream off the grounds of New Hampshire International Speedway
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Things were just about back to normal in Loudon, N.H., a day
after 90,000 filled the speedway's 83,000 seats and luxury suites,
infield, and hillside on the backstretch for the running of the
Winston Cup Jiffy Lube 300.
</P>
<P>
   Burton and Bahre and thousands of fans in recreational vehicles
and thousands more coming for the day will all reconvene again late
next month.
</P>
<P>
   The speedway landed a second date on the Winston Cup tour and
ran its first CMT (for Country Music Television) 300 last year,
which was won by Jeff Gordon. The second race will be held the last
weekend of August, and will most likely switch to mid-September for
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Having the next Cup weekend go as well as this one would suit
Bahre fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think things went very well, to be honest with you,'' he
said. ``We had everyone on the grounds in plenty of time, an hour
or an hour and a half before the race. People seemed to be happy. I
was walking around and people were thanking me and I told them I
should be thanking them. Where would we be without them? You've got
to have fans.''
</P>
<P>
   By the nature of the business, traffic was slower leaving the
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between coming in and getting out is that some
people wnat to be here at 5, some want to be here at 7, some at 9,
and some at 11,'' said Gary Bahre, Bob's son and NHIS president.
``And everyone plans to leave when the checkered flag falls.
Although we were pleased with the way we got people out, we didn't
get them out as fast as they came in.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the crowd stayed around an extra hour or so for a
postrace auto show.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all practical purposes, the parking lots were cleared by
8:45, 8:30,'' said Gary Bahre.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think things went very well,'' said Capt. David McCarthy of
the New Hampshire State Police. ``The only real slowdowns we
noticed were because it was the first real good weather weekend of
the summer, and a lot of the resort traffic from the north came
down and led to some delays. Interstate 93 got extremely heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Sunday's race, the second Cup race is once again sold out.
The speedway drew an estimated 19,000 last Friday for Cup
qualifying and practice and 40,000 Saturday for the final
qualifying and more practice and a pair of NASCAR-sanctioned
support races _ the Featherlite Modified Tour race and a Busch
Grand National North race. The schedule for the Cup weekend in
August is the same, and the Bahres hope to draw similar crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Burton would love to match his result.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Cuppers have this weekend off, head to Pocono and
then the Brickyard 400 Aug. 1, and return here in the middle of a
grueling stretch run of races on 16 consecutive weekends to finish
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who defended his Jiffy Lube title Sunday, has now won
two of the last three Cup races here. His team was good in
practice, good in the early stages of the race, and kept getting
better as he and crew chief Frank Stoddard kept adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   Burton has won three races and was fourth in the points last
year. Now, the team has its first win of the season and is eighth
in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stuck to our game plan,'' he said about some problems the
team had earlier in the season. ``We kept working and we still have
work to do. Just because we won today it doesn't mean the world's
gonna be great from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is a little better than it was a week ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
