<SLUG> BC-BIOLOGIAL-THREAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS SEEKING BIOLOGICAL AGENTS IN ARRESTS OF THREE TEXAS MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Federal agents were hunting for containers of
HIV-infected blood, the rabies virus and anthrax spores earlier
this month when they arrested three men on charges of threatening
government officials and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also searched for written threats, instruction
manuals and tools to turn disposable lighters into mechanisms for
using biological weapons, according to search warrants unsealed
Monday a federal magistrate in Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   Three men were arrested July 1 and accused of using e-mail to
relay threats of biological and chemical attacks on the heads of
the FBI and the Internal Revenue Service, as well as state and
local officials.
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie Wise, 72, of Olmito; Jack Abbott Grebe Jr., 43, of Los
Fresnos; and Oliver Dean Emigh, 63, of Harlingen, remained in
custody at the Cameron County Jail Monday on charges of conspiring
to use weapons of mass destruction and using weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, the IRS, Secret Service and the Cameron County
Sheriff's Department searched three Rio Grande Valley residences
about the time of the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Officials seized chemistry and electronics books, photographs,
notebooks and assorted other material, according to a search
warrant signed by an FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   However, no chemicals are specifically mentioned in the
inventory sheets of items that agents seized from the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Anthrax is an infectious cattle and sheep disease that can be
transmitted to humans.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials declined to comment on the seized items.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate John Black ordered the search warrants unsealed
at the request of defense attorneys who argued that they were
unable to defend their clients without knowing more about the
government's case.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing is set for Thursday at the federal courthouse in
Brownsville. At the hearing, defense attorneys are expected to have
an opportunity to question at least one government witness.
</P>
<P>
   During a hearing earlier this month, Assistant U.S. Attorney
Rick Lara told Black that the men not only conspired to use the
weapons, but discussed how to use them and who would be targets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
