</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONSBANK-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NationsBank tops forecast for second quarter
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Buoyed by a 31 percent increase in non-interest
income, NationsBank reported a 23 percent rise in second-quarter
operating earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte-based banking company logged operating income of
$1.13 billion, or $1.15 per share, compared to $919 million, or 94
cents, a year ago. Net income, which included a $430 million
pre-tax gain from the sale of 67 Florida offices, was $1.41
billion, or $1.43 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Per share earnings were a penny above a 20-analyst consensus,
according to the First Call service.
</P>
<P>
   Non-interest income was $1.86 billion, which represented 42
percent of revenue, up from $1.42 billion and 37 percent a year
ago. Traditional lines of business appeared to be flattish, with
net interest income at $2.53 billion versus $2.44 billion a year
ago. Net interest margin _ the difference between what it cost a
bank for money and what it makes on money_ declined 0.24 percentage
points to 3.81 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, Robinson-Humphrey analyst John W. Coffey said, ``The
reported numbers belied what was really going on in the loan
portfolio. If you exclude the effects of Florida divestitures of
over $1.4 billion in loans'' and another $2 billion in other loan
sales, ``the loan portfolio grew about 8 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, revenue rose 14 percent to $4.42 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Non-interest expense was up 12 percent to $2.51 billion from
$2.23 billion. On a cash basis, which excludes accounting for
intangibles, it cost NationsBank about 53.6 cents, down from 54
cents last year, to bring in a dollar of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping expense growth lower than revenue growth accounts for
the higher earnings gain, said NationsBank spokesman Robert
Stickler.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real significance of their success'' in turning in this
kind of quarter while absorbing Barnett Banks ``is that it bodes
well for their upcoming merger with BankAmerica,'' said Coffey.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported return on assets of 1.45 percent and return
on equity of 18.3 percent compared to 1.3 percent and 15.7 percent
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The provision for possible loan losses was $265 million, or 0.47
percent of assets, versus $225 million, or 0.53 percent, a year
ago. Net charge offs were $276 million, or 0.61 percent of average
loans, compared to $220 million, or 0.49 percent, a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the six months, operating earnings totaled $2.27 billion, or
$2.32 per share, versus $1.77 billion, or $1.81 per share.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank had assets of $307.99 billion at quarter's end. Its
stock closed at $87, down 18 3/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
