A3019 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-CANDIDATE-BOS &LR;      07-13 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-CANDIDATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING A REPLACEMENT FOR HASHIMOTO A TOUGH TASK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Whoever replaces Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto will
have his work cut out for him. Unfortunately, say analysts and
voters, there may not be a politician in Japan who is up to the
task.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation has focused on Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi, 60, a
12-term member of the Lower House who has held several top party
posts. Obuchi heads the largest faction in the LDP and, based on
party politics, is the leading candidate for the job.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the colorless politician could be a liability
for the LDP. A recent survey of pundits by the leading business
magazine Toyo Keizai ranked Obuchi next to last among politicians
in his grasp of economics. More disturbingly, last place went to
Finance Minister Hikari Matsunaga.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi ``is not charismatic, he's extremely ignorant of
economics and he's not popular with the public...Most Japanese
wouldn't even recognize him,'' said Garry Evans, a strategist for
HSBC Securities in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Young, head of economic analysis in Japan at Salomon
Smith Barney, said with Obuchi's ``lack of policy experience and
the LDP's weak position in parliament, it's going to be an uphill
battle'' for him to take decisive action.
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate is former chief Cabinet secretary Seiroku
Kajiyama, 71, the markets' favored choice. Kajiyama advocates
letting insolvent banks fail, a radical stance in Japan, and is
considered a free-marketeer. But he also supports higher interest
rates, a policy many economists call wrongheaded in a time of weak
consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much more outspoken and bold than most politicians in
this country,'' Evans said. ``The problem is he's a bit populist _
he swings whichever way he thinks the public mood is going. He
wants to raise interest rates, which would be disastrous, to
satisfy people who live off their savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation has also turned to former Prime Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa, 78, who was in charge in 1993 when the LDP was thrown out
of power for the first time in 38 years. Last December, Miyazawa
helped forge a 30 trillion yen ($2.1 billion) bank bailout. He also
pushed his party to move faster on economic stimulus and a ``bridge
bank'' plan for failed banks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Evans, ``Miyazawa was the cause of the end of LDP
rule. The economy at that stage was in bad shape, too. But now he's
seen as a safe pair of hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Another option is Yohei Kono, 61, former party leader when the
LDP was out of power following Miyazawa's ouster. Kono later lost
the party leadership to Hashimoto, and became the only LDP chief
not to serve as prime minister. Having lost the top job once, he
may not want to stand again.
</P>
<P>
   The dark horse candidate is Health and Welfare Minister
Junichiro Koizumi, 56, an outspoken fiscal policy specialist who in
a previous job pushed for selling off the government's postal
savings fund, a move that investors supported, but which the LDP,
bureaucrats and unions opposed.
</P>
<P>
   With his longish hair, he stands apart from the standard LDP
conservative politician lineup, and in a time of voter discontent,
Koizumi is probably the best electoral draw the party has got.
</P>
<P>
   One LDP faction, including Koizumi, may back party General
Council Chairman Yoshiro Mori, according to today's Daily Yomiuri
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, opposition groups are discussing joining
forces behind Democratic Party of Japan leader Naoto Kan for prime
minister, but it's unlikely they could succeed, given the LDP
majority in the Lower House of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Given the uninspiring field of LDP contenders, Evans said, ``I
could imagine in six months time that we might look back with
nostalgia on Hashimoto.''
</P>
</TEXT>
