<SLUG> BC-IMF-STABILITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF DIPS INTO EMERGENCY FUND TO AID RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The International Monetary Fund plans to use
emergency reserves to help fund $22.6 billion in loans to Russia, a
move that places new pressure on Congress to provide more money for
the lending agency.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF has used its emergency fund only nine times since it
established the reserve account in 1962. The last time the account
was used was in 1978, when the United States withdrew money in a
bid to stop the declining value of the dollar, and in 1977 to aid
the United Kingdom and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the IMF has warned that its regular reserves
are low because of the financial crisis in Southeast Asia, which
the agency has tried to ease by offering tens of billion of dollars
in loans to South Korea, Indonesia, Thailand and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   IMF officials recently said that $15 billion or less is left in
their regular accounts. But borrowers such as Indonesia are calling
for even more loans, and the IMF has committed $11 billion as its
share of the Russian bailout package.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF and its supporters, including the Clinton adminstration,
say the agency needs new funding to continue its mission of
promoting a stable global economy. The IMF acts as a lender of last
resort to troubled nations.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has called on Congress to transfer $18 billion
to the IMF as part of an international program to boost its
reserves. The proposal has passed the Senate, but it is stalled in
the House, where some lawmakers are complaining that IMF operations
are too secretive. They also argue that IMF loans carry strict
economic terms that can close businesses, raise prices and leave
workers unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IMF bailout of Russia is an enormous scam that will not
only not help the Russian people, but will continue the
destabilization of their economy, causing increased poverty and
misery,'' Representative Bernie Sanders, Independent of Vermont,
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said the IMF loans merely funnel US tax money to Russia,
which uses it to repay ``large banks and speculators who have made
risky loans to Russia at high interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michael McCurry, the White House, said the IMF's loan offer
to Russia shows that Congress should ``stop fooling around, stop
the politics'' and approve the administration's request for new
funds for the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have ample evidence in today's developments that the
Republican Congress is being very short sighted in not moving
forward on the funding commitments we need to deal with these
international economic issues,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in the House are generally united behind a bill that
funds the IMF but includes new protections for foreign workers and
the environment, said Representative Barney Frank, Democrat of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said he and some other Democrats are finding it easier to
support the IMF funding because a major stumbling block -- IMF
support for President Suharto of Indonesia -- has been removed.
Suharto has stepped down, replaced by a new government that may
ease up on repression in East Timor and which has released a
prominent labor leader from jail.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF issue is a tricky one for Republican leaders. One wing
of the party supports corporate America, which generally backs the
IMF efforts to bring stability to the world economy. But other
Republicans believe the IMF uses tax money to support international
lenders who have made reckless loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``IMF bailouts encourage investors to assume additional risk in
pursuit of extra-normal returns, in the expectation that losses may
be absorbed by the IMF,'' Representative Jim Saxton, a New Jersey
Republican who is co-chairman of the Joint Economic Committee, has
said.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton also calls the IMF a ``secretive organization'' that
should release more information about its inner workings in order
to receive new US tax money.
</P>
<P>
   Another political problem for the IMF bill could arise as social
conservatives try to attach an anti-abortion measure to it, which
would be unacceptable to Democrats and the White House. But at the
same time, support for the IMF is building among lawmakers from
farm states, who believe IMF loans help US farmers sell their
products overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping the IMF emergency fund to aid Russia requires permission
from the United States and 10 other industrialized nations, but all
are considered likely to approve the withdrawl. The United States
is the largest contributor to the IMF, and holds 18 percent of the
votes, the largest share of any nation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
