<HEADER>
A3026 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRISH-PARADE-BOS &LR;      07-13 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-PARADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE DEATHS CLOUD PROTESTANT MARCH PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ By mid-afternoon Monday, even as
police held two men for questioning in the arson attack on Sunday
that killed three boys, the conspiracy theory had worked its way
through the crowd that was standing around Drumcree Church.
</P>
<P>
   According to this theory, the Quinn brothers who were burned to
death in their beds early Sunday were not the victims of Protestant
extremists who targeted their Catholic mother, as the police have
said, but were killed in a domestic dispute. The police, this
theory holds, are trying to smear the loyal people of Ulster, those
camped out on the hillside next to Drumcree Church.
</P>
<P>
   That such a story, no more than rumor, could be spread and
embellished by those who describe themselves as upstanding,
God-fearing men and women speaks volumes about the denial at work
here, and how divided this society remains.
</P>
<P>
   Some have suggested the appalling deaths of the Quinn brothers
-- 8-year-old Jason, 9-year-old Mark, and 11-year-old Richard --
marked a turning point in Northern Ireland, that even the
recalcitrant minority that refuses to accept the new spirit of
accommodation and cooperation would be marginalized.
</P>
<P>
   There has long been a propensity here to claim that the latest
atrocity would be the key that unchains Northern Ireland from its
past. But while some hardline loyalists were moved by the deaths of
the three boys, many others were not. There were gestures of
compassion from some Orangemen, so named for King William of
Orange, whose 1690 victory over Catholic forces was celebrated
Monday. But many others ignored pleas from their own political and
religious leaders that they curtail celebrations and end the
standoff here at Drumcree.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of people here, both Protestant unionists and
Catholic nationalists, are sick of the violence and voted
overwhelmingly to endorse new political arrangements two months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But some 29 percent of the electorate voted against the Good
Friday agreement, and within that minority is a smaller minority
who want to foment the hatred and bigotry that has defined Northern
Ireland to the outside world for so long.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of hatred and bigotry, the police say, that led
someone to firebomb the Quinn house and incinerate three little
boys in the pre-dawn hours of Sunday. Police sources said the men
being questioned Monday have links to Protestant loyalist
paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fields of Drumcree, those who ignored pleas to end
their standoff were irritated when asked whether they were being
disrespectful by carrying on their protest against being barred
from marching down the Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's disgusting what happened to those three little
boys, but I think it's equally disgusting that we're being blamed
for it,'' said Stephen McKinney, an Orangeman from Lurgan who
brought his wife and young son to Drumcree.
</P>
<P>
   By day, Drumcree is full of families like the McKinneys, and it
has a benign, almost carnival-like atmosphere. But as night falls,
a sinister element takes over, taunting the security forces on the
other side of the barbed wire. Shots have been fired and bombs
thrown at the security forces from the Orangemen's side, a sight
that has shaken many Orangemen.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. William Bingham, an Orange Order chaplain who wept when
he learned of the boys' deaths, spoke from his pulpit Sunday,
asking the Orangemen to call off their protest because they could
not control their violent sympathizers. Monday, Bingham was heckled
by some fellow Orangemen who called him a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You betrayed your country!'' screamed Joel Patton, leader of
the hardline Spirit of Drumcree group.
</P>
<P>
   As other Orangemen asked Patton not to make a public spectacle
of the split within the Orange Order, scuffles broke out.
</P>
<P>
   The horrific deaths of the Quinn boys may signal the end of the
Orange Order as a potent political force. Founded 203 years ago,
the Protestant fraternal organization has over the last 30 years
been nearly halved in size, to about 70,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   Its reputation for always getting its way has taken a beating as
the British government has made it clear that British soldiers and
the Royal Ulster Constabulary will not allow Orangemen to defy the
Northern Ireland Parades Commission ban against it marching down
the Catholic Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   The determination of some Orangemen to carry on the protest that
began 10 days ago when the authorities barred them from marching
through a Catholic neighborhood has bitterly divided the Orange
Order, especially in the wake of the deaths of the three boys. Many
Orangemen take their religion seriously, and consider it Christian
to show respect to the dead boys.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night only a few thousand people showed up here to show
solidarity with the Orangemen. Last week Orange leaders predicted
they would have 100,000 people in the fields with them. They
explained the discrepancy by saying they asked other lodges to stay
home.
</P>
<P>
   Some Orange lodges were unmoved by the deaths of the Quinn
brothers. An Orange parade was held in Ballymoney, the town where
the boys died. Some people had asked the Orangemen to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   In Rasharkin, the village where the boys' bodies were being
waked at their grandmother's house, another Orange parade passed,
playing loud music that celebrated military victories over
Catholics some 300 years ago. Some passersby made obscene gestures
at the Quinn family.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Quinn, the dead boys' grandmother, said the booming drums
and music could be heard in her house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought today would've been different,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Intransigence is not confined to hardline Protestants. A
Protestant parade in Belfast was held up Monday for over an hour
after the Irish National Liberation Army, a small Catholic
republican splinter group that refuses to call a cease-fire, said
it had planted two bombs on the route. A car bomb, believed left by
republican dissidents, was defused outside the Newry courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   There were, however, hopeful signs Monday. In several villages,
nationalists called off protests out of respect for the Quinn
brothers. In Dunloy, Orangemen did not challenge a ban from
marching through the Catholic village. Many Orange leaders began
speeches with sympathetic words for the Quinns.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite the bomb threats that delayed it for an hour, an
Orange parade passed without acrimony down the Lower Ormeau Road in
South Belfast, which besides the Portadown parade is the most
controversial, disputed route in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   In a place where peaceful protest has been rare since 1972, when
14 Catholics were shot dead by British soldiers at a civil rights
march, there was proof Monday that it can work, on both sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
