<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMANUFACTURE-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANUFACTURERS AND CONSUMERS NOW CHOOSE REUSE OVER RECYCLING
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., N.C., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dig inside Xerox Corp.'s newest stand-alone digital copier and
the nuts and bolts of a big shift in manufacturing swing into view.
</P>
<P>
   Parts that were welded are now fastened, and easy to take apart.
Components that were scattered throughout the machine are arranged
on subassemblies that can easily be lifted out. The fuser roll,
which fixes the toner to the paper, is no longer made of an
aluminum core that is tossed out when its rubberized coating wears
off; the core is now a combination of aluminum and steel that can
be re-coated again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the changes _ particularly since some of the new parts
are more expensive to make? Because they add a re-use option to the
recycle-or-dump-it choice for disposing of used or obsolete
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, it is cheaper to re-use a part than to
recycle it,'' said Jack Azar, Xerox's director of environment,
health and safety.
</P>
<P>
   Once the purview of myriad small companies that eked out a
living refurbishing carburetors, printer cartridges and other used
parts, re-manufacturing _ a method of re-using old parts in new
machines _ has hit corporate America in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   From Xerox to Saturn, from Lucent to DuPont, from Kodak to
Steelcase, companies of all types and technologies are looking to
re-manufacturing as a premier way to hold costs down and keep
products out of landfills. No longer happy to let their
small-company forebears breathe new life into their discarded
machines, many are stepping up their collection methods and re-use
technologies to bring older products home.
</P>
<P>
   But they are not content just to salvage parts from old
products. Now, they are beginning to design products with eventual
re-manufacturing in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finally convincing designers that it doesn't matter if a
part is twice as expensive if you can use it again and again,''
said Cavan Kelsey, manager of design for health, safety and
environment at Eastman Kodak Co., which recently replaced some
plastic parts in its high-speed copiers with more expensive, but
reusable, stainless steel.
</P>
<P>
   Designers are not the only converts. The Federal Trade
Commission, the Environmental Protection Agency, and even Congress
have recently embraced re-manufacturing, with money, technological
support and new rules. And numerous universities are studying it
and teaching it.
</P>
<P>
   Interest is running so high that some manufacturers are using
design changes and sometimes lawsuits to keep the independent
re-manufacturers at bay. Some are fearful that the re-manufactured
versions of their products will eat too deeply into sales of new
ones. Others just want to do the re-manufacturing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have similar environmental goals, recycling and
re-manufacturing are not at all alike. Recycling generally involves
destroying something so that its materials can be re-used.
Re-manufacturers remove parts, test them, refurbish them and re-use
them.
</P>
<P>
   Recycling methods _ melting down steel, or dissolving paper _
can be energy-intensive and polluting, and often yield lower-grade
materials. And they do not recapture the value that was added
through processing or assembling.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ``re-manufacturing is an affordable way to get the
highest value out of parts,'' said Nabil Nasr, director of the
Rochester Institute of Technology's National Center for
Re-manufacturing and Resource Recovery. That realization, said
Stuart Hart, professor of strategic management at the University of
North Carolina's Kenan-Flagler Business School, is yielding
``tremendous corporate interest in, and sophistication about,
re-manufacturing.''
</P>
<P>
   Universities are fanning the embers. Kenan-Flagler just hired a
professor of ``reverse logistics'' _ getting products back and
re-manufacturing them. The Rochester Institute sponsored a
conference on re-manufacturing in June. Gary Davis, director of the
University of Tennessee's Center for Clean Products and Clean
Technology, said his group was about to study re-manufacturing for
the automobile industry ``because it is infinitely superior to any
type of recycling.''
</P>
<P>
   And numerous schools now preach re-manufacturing in industrial
design courses. ``We are teaching students that it is silly to
think one-time use when they design products,'' said Steven Derby,
associate professor of mechanical engineering at the Rensselaer
Polytechnic Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Re-manufacturing is no panacea. The logistics of getting
products back can be daunting. So can putting in tracking systems
to insure that a part with a 10-use life is not on its 11th
go-round. And some customers eschew re-manufactured products, no
matter how rigorously tested and warrantied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people will always believe that if something isn't brand
new, it isn't high quality,'' said Michael Best, a product manager
for Steelcase Inc., which makes new and re-manufactured furniture.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
