<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REMANUFACTURE-ART-2ND     07-13 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMANUFACTURE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: re-manufactured furniture. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still, a growing number of manufacturers think the pluses
outweigh the drawbacks. Computer companies, including IBM, are
retrieving chips from old machines. Telecommunications equipment
companies, including Lucent Technologies, are re-manufacturing
switching equipment. Lexmark International, which re-manufactures
its own printer cartridges, is looking ``on a test basis'' at
whether it should use re-manufactured parts in printers, said a
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp.'s Saturn division is working with the
University of Tennessee to develop a software program that tracks
the energy and environmental impact of every part of a car, from
manufacture to disposal. One major use for the program: let
designers run ``what if'' scenarios to see whether tinkering with
certain parts will make them easier to recycle or re-manufacture.
``We want designers to look at the environmental component of all
their decisions,'' said William Miller III, Saturn's manager of
environmental affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Even chemical companies, which deal with vats of materials
rather than discrete parts, are learning to re-manufacture. Instead
of melting down old polyester film _ which degrades the fiber _ or
burning it for fuel, DuPont now ``unzips'' the polyester molecule
down to its atoms, and re-manufactures the polyester. DuPont is
``scouting around for a similar chemistry for nylon,'' said John
Carberry, director of environmental technology. ``Billions of
pounds of nylon carpeting is going into landfill that we should be
able to re-use.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins &AMP; Aikman Floor Coverings Inc. has noticed that, too. It
has a new technology, which falls between recycling and
re-manufacturing, for grinding up old carpets and, without any
chemical processing, using them as backing for new ones. ``You can
do this forever, without the fiber degrading in any way,'' said Lee
Schilling, senior vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Re-manufacturing as a separate industry has been around for more
than 50 years. Re-manufactured parts dominate the aftermarket for
cars and trucks. Re-manufactured office furniture and printer
cartridges have also been available for years.
</P>
<P>
   The United States military, the largest re-manufacturer in the
world, routinely uses re-manufactured parts in vehicles and
weapons. And ``disposable'' cameras are a misnomer: since the early
1990s, Fuji and Kodak have retrieved them from photofinishers and
re-used the flash and other parts in new cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't take long to realize how much value was left in
those so-called throwaways,'' said Stephen Rumsey, Kodak's
manufacturing manager for single-use cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Re-manufacturing is a good-sized industry in its own right.
Robert Lund, a professor of manufacturing engineering at Boston
University, said that in 1996, the last year for which he gathered
figures, companies that rebuild parts comprised a $53 billion
business employing 480,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   But until recently, manufacturers and regulators barely
acknowledged them. ``This industry has grown and grown, yet it's
been completely overlooked,'' Lund said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, re-manufacturing is being promoted by its proponents _
including several state legislators in New York, which is home to
many cartridge re-manufacturers _ as the answer to everything from
global warming (it requires less energy, and thus reduces
greenhouse gases) to welfare reform (it provides jobs for
low-skilled workers). Congress just granted the Rochester
Institute's re-manufacturing center $10 million over five years to
develop new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC, whose Green Guide to products with recycled content is
widely followed by corporate and government procurement
departments, amended its guidelines in May to embrace
re-manufactured products. The Environmental Protection Agency is
financing some studies on re-manufacturing. ``It's an
environmentally friendly solution for businesses looking to hold
down costs,'' said Jane Bare, a chemical engineer in the EPA's
office of research and development.
</P>
<P>
   Re-manufacturing companies are trying to capitalize on their new
fame. Last year they formed the Re-manufacturing Industries Council
International, which is lobbying Congress to make re-manufacturing
equipment eligible for a 25 percent capital investment tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``As George Burns used to say, `Hang around long enough, and
you'll get discovered,' '' said William Gager, chairman of both the
Automotive Parts Rebuilders Association and the new council.
</P>
<P>
   But what may be old hat for Gager is brand new for primary
manufacturers. Many are under pressure from shareholders to meet
environmental goals, and from customers who, facing their own
environmental pressures and leery of rising landfill charges, want
them to take back used items.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of technology and the robust economy together encourage
companies to upgrade old equipment, creating a steady flow of
products to be re-manufactured. And the pressure to keep costs
down, combined with the growing number of start-up businesses that
cannot afford all-new products, has created a growing market for
re-manufactured goods like office furniture or cartridges which,
unlike re-manufactured copiers or cameras, are generally sold at a
discount.
</P>
<P>
   The battle lines between primary manufacturers and the
independent re-manufacturers are being drawn. Several printer
companies have redesigned their cartridges to make them harder to
refill. And they have aggressively sued re-manufacturers _ and
sometimes each other _ for trademark infringements when the
packaging on the re-manufactured cartridges looks too much like
that on their new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture manufacturers may be playing hardball, too. Bill
Davies, owner of Davies Office Refurbishing in Albany, N.Y., says
it used to be simple to remove fabric from the frames of office
panels; now, he says, Steelcase and other manufacturers are
laminating the fabrics ``solely to make them hard to
re-manufacture.''
</P>
<P>
   Steelcase's Best says that is nonsense _ particularly since his
company has a thriving re-manufacturing business of its own. ``The
new design makes it easier to route cable through the panels,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But it also brings more of the panels home to
Steelcase itself for re-manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
