<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-JAPAN-0714-COX     07-13 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-JAPAN-0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HASHIMOTO RESIGNATION, JAPANESE ECONOMY HAS U.S., OTHERS ASKING,
'WHAT NEXT?'
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With American jobs, profits and stock prices at
stake, the White House moved quickly Monday to stress that whoever
replaces Ryutaro Hashimoto as prime minister of Japan must
prescribe the tough medicine needed to prevent the country's
sagging economy from dragging down global growth.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear, however, whether Hashimoto's replacement,
as yet unchosen, would have the motivation or the means to carry
out reforms the United States has sought, and Japan has promised,
for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   All that was certain was that the prospect of dealing with yet
another Japanese prime minister -- Hashimoto's replacement will be
the seventh person to lead Japan's government since President
Clinton took office five years ago -- added yet another layer of
uncertainty to the future of the world's second-largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Japan's recovery is now in doubt,'' said Robert DiClemente,
chief economist for the New York investment house Salomon Smith
Barney. ''Who's going to lead them out?''
</P>
<P>
   By early Monday morning, the White House and U.S. State and
Treasury departments had cobbled together a single policy line
meant to display a veil of public confidence in Japan's ability to
pick a new leader that would carry out long-promised, though
ill-defined, measures to cut taxes, shore up Japan's ailing banks
and invigorate consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is very important for the new government, as it forms
itself, to move quickly to implement concrete fiscal and banking
measures, to achieve strong domestic, demand-led growth in Japan,''
said White House spokesman Michael McCurry. ''The president
believes that a healthy Japanese economy is critical for the entire
Asia region, that it's critical to the global economy and thus to
the people of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   It was largely the ailing economy that prompted Japanese voters
to deal a punishing drubbing in Sunday's elections to Hashimoto's
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP). The party dropped from 61 seats to
44 seats in the 252-member Upper House of Japan's legislature,
called the Diet.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto announced Monday that he would resign in two weeks --
he cancelled his White House visit scheduled for next week -- to
take responsibility for the harsh judgment by voters fed up with
nearly a decade of lackluster growth and, most recently, a
full-blown recession, in a country that had, for two generations,
led the way to stunning economic vitality across much of East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts predicted that Sunday's election results would
provide a wake-up call to the LDP, which remains in control of the
more powerful legislative wing, the Lower House. Japanese
politicians, much like their American counterparts, have often
avoided painful change until a crisis makes it impossible to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ''This may be the crisis,'' said Edward Lincoln, former economic
adviser in the U.S. Embassy in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is actually a mildly encouraging development, because the
election results leave the LDP frightened,'' said Lincoln, now a
senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, a Washington think
tank. ''They might start coming up with some new policies, or
different policies, than what they've done up to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout nearly a decade of nearly-flat economic performance,
Japan's government has been loathe to reject the formula that
carried the country from the ashes of post World War II destruction
to prosperity over the course of three decades.
</P>
<P>
   That formula boils down to easy money for industry, low interest
rates for savers and policies that protect domestic industry from
competition, largely at the expense of consumers, so that huge
corporations can use lucrative domestic markets as a springboard
for global exports.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement has long been a bone of contention for U.S.
policymakers, which have complained for two decades now that Japan
doesn't import as much as might be expected for an economy its
size.
</P>
<P>
   One result: a chronic U.S.-Japan trade gap that has averaged $50
billion, in Japan's favor, for more than 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's figure was $55.7 billion, and this year's deficit is
already on target to top $62 billion.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim. Story can end here.)
</P>
<P>
   That, American critics say, results in the loss of tens of
thousands of American jobs that might be supported by exports to
Japan, were the two-way trade flow closer to balanced. It also
affects profits of many U.S. corporations which rely on exports for
a growing portion of their sales. That, in turn, has a dampening
effect on stock prices. Wall Street, which has struggled for the
past two months in the face of deepening worries about Japan,
drifted downward on Monday, with the closely watched Dow Jones
Industrial Average falling 9.53 points to close at 9096.21.
</P>
<P>
   What's fueling the increase in the trade deficit is Japan's
economic weakness, combined with a precipitous drop in the value of
the Japanese currency. The yen has lost some 80 percent of its
value against the dollar over the past three years, as investors
flee the yen as a show of no-faith in the future of the economy
more broadly.
</P>
<P>
   A weak yen makes Japanese products cheaper, in dollar terms, in
the United States, providing an incentive for Americans to increase
their purchases of Japanese imports. It has the opposite effect on
U.S. exports to Japan, making American goods most costly to
Japanese consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The weakening yen also puts pressure on other Asian currencies,
such as those of South Korea, Indonesia and Thailand, which have
already plummeted some 40 percent against the dollar over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular concern is China, which has resisted devaluing its
currency but has hinted that a continuing slide in the yen could
force a devaluation of the Chinese yuan, a move that analysts fear
would trigger further declines in currencies regionwide.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's sagging economy, moreover, denies the region, and the
world, an economic locomotive that, in healthier times, might be
stimulating growth worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   To try to get Japan's economy moving again, and to shore up the
addled yen, Hashimoto had vowed a permanent tax cut -- as yet
undefined -- and a program to try to consolidate and deal with bad
bank loans valued at some $600 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The loans have crippled many of Japan's largest banks, crimping
credit and putting a drag on economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto also reluctantly talked of reforming Japan's economy
more generally to promote consumption, and of stimulating growth by
spending billions of dollars on public works.
</P>
<P>
   One problem politically, however, is that Hashimoto's policies
remained so vague that it's hard to draw a clear mandate from
Sunday's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''People were just kind of mad that the government's letting the
economy slip,'' Lincoln said. ''Virtually nothing they have done
for the past nine months has been encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Sunday's humbling of the LDP leads to change remains the
central question for analysts trying to piece together the future
of Japan's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have to remain somewhat skeptical,'' said
DiClemente. ''This was already a very dramatic challenge for the
authorities there. Now, suddenly, the means to do all that itself
is up in the air. Who among the (LDP) party leadership is capable
of really taking charge?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
