the Japanese currency. The yen has lost some 80 percent of its
value against the dollar over the past three years, as investors
flee the yen as a show of no-faith in the future of the economy
more broadly.
</P>
<P>
   A weak yen makes Japanese products cheaper, in dollar terms, in
the United States, providing an incentive for Americans to increase
their purchases of Japanese imports. It has the opposite effect on
U.S. exports to Japan, making American goods most costly to
Japanese consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The weakening yen also puts pressure on other Asian currencies,
such as those of South Korea, Indonesia and Thailand, which have
already plummeted some 40 percent against the dollar over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular concern is China, which has resisted devaluing its
currency but has hinted that a continuing slide in the yen could
force a devaluation of the Chinese yuan, a move that analysts fear
would trigger further declines in currencies regionwide.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's sagging economy, moreover, denies the region, and the
world, an economic locomotive that, in healthier times, might be
stimulating growth worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   To try to get Japan's economy moving again, and to shore up the
addled yen, Hashimoto had vowed a permanent tax cut -- as yet
undefined -- and a program to try to consolidate and deal with bad
bank loans valued at some $600 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The loans have crippled many of Japan's largest banks, crimping
credit and putting a drag on economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto also reluctantly talked of reforming Japan's economy
more generally to promote consumption, and of stimulating growth by
spending billions of dollars on public works.
</P>
<P>
   One problem politically, however, is that Hashimoto's policies
remained so vague that it's hard to draw a clear mandate from
Sunday's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''People were just kind of mad that the government's letting the
economy slip,'' Lincoln said. ''Virtually nothing they have done
for the past nine months has been encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Sunday's humbling of the LDP leads to change remains the
central question for analysts trying to piece together the future
of Japan's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have to remain somewhat skeptical,'' said
DiClemente. ''This was already a very dramatic challenge for the
authorities there. Now, suddenly, the means to do all that itself
is up in the air. Who among the (LDP) party leadership is capable
of really taking charge?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
