<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3038 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-HASHIMOTO-BOS &LR;      07-13 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-HASHIMOTO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASHIMOTO DEPARTURE LEAVES MOUNTAIN OF PROBLEMS FOR JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Edgy financial markets and disgruntled voters cheered
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's resignation Monday after his
party's hammering at the polls, hopeful that his replacement would
succeed in reviving Japan's sluggish economy where Hashimoto had
failed.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems facing Japan are monumental _ from fixing a
banking system strapped with $550 billion in problem loans to
appeasing a population suffering the worst unemployment in postwar
history. Hashimoto's departure has set off a scramble to replace
him, but has failed to turn up a shining contender. The jockeying
within a weakened ruling party could also delay essential financial
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   But even if his notoriously snail-paced party finally makes a
commitment to consistent economic policies following its stunning
electoral defeat Sunday, passing legislation to tackle the mess may
be harder now.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Democratic Party will retain its hold on power
through its dominance of the Lower House, but the party lacks a
majority in the Upper House. Rival parties picked up 17 seats the
LDP lost in the Upper House elections. It must now work feverishly
to find allies _ at a time when the opposition wants to distance
itself from a discredited establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread corruption and pork-barrelling by the LDP had primed
voter discontent over the last decade. But Hashimoto's ultimate
downfall was indecisiveness and frequent reversals on economic
policy that undermined his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The question for Japan is whether _ and how fast _ Hashimoto's
successor will commit to measures that many economists say are
needed: letting insolvent banks fail and cutting taxes to spur
demand while managing a colossal deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Investors hope a fresh face will instill confidence and shake
things up. But skeptics say there is no credible leader in the
wings, and that whoever fills Hashimoto's shoes may be no more than
a transitional figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to change the people at the top to create change in
this country, and it's got to start today,'' declared Kenzo Uchida,
a politics professor at Tokai University in Kanagawa. ``But there
is nobody to replace Hashimoto and no political party to take the
LDP's place...so it will be difficult to achieve change. That is
the tragedy of Japanese politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, a sell-off in shares followed news of the LDP's dramatic
defeat, but the benchmark Nikkei index rebounded after Hashimoto
stepped down, closing 1.7 percent up. The yen also recovered after
his resignation to hit 142.42 to the dollar by the end of the day
in Tokyo, up 1.09 yen from late Friday here.
</P>
<P>
   A newly strengthened opposition could thwart the LDP in order to
boost its own position. Conversely, it could force the LDP to adopt
more dramatic reforms than the conservative party might otherwise
support. For example, the Democratic Party of Japan wants at least
6 trillion yen ($42 billion) in tax cuts _ one-third more than the
LDP has proposed. If the LDP goes begging for allies in parliament,
it might have to bend to the opposition's will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people have repudiated Mr. Hashimoto, the LDP and the
long-standing system of government by bureaucrats,'' said DPJ
leader Naoto Kan. ``The people have lent an ear to what we said,
and they are giving us a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The depth of voters' anger against the LDP can hardly be
underestimated, but what will follow the upset at the polls is
still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Tokashi Imai, chairman of Keidanren, the Japanese Federation of
Economic Organizations, an industry group traditionally allied with
the LDP, said: ``Voters believed voting against the LDP would be
the fastest and most extreme way to resolve the economic crisis.''
Hashimoto had no choice but to step down, he added, but ``we cannot
afford to have a vacuum in government.''
</P>
<P>
   When a moist-eyed Hashimoto announced Monday he would step aside
to take responsibility for the electoral drubbing, it was with
humility and barely restrained emotion, but without an explanation
for his policy flip-flops that so angered voters, nor with news of
who would replace him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything rests on my shoulders and I was powerless to do
anything about it,'' he told reporters in a question-and-answer
session. ``(But) it is very necessary to try to tackle these
(economic) problems...There will not be a setback in the approach
to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   The LDP hopes to nominate a candidate for prime minister with a
vote July 21 _ but Parliament is not expected to reconvene to
approve the nominee until after July 26, along with a new Cabinet
if Hashimoto's team steps down, as they are expected to. Hashimoto
cancelled a July 21 trip to Washington to discuss economic reform
efforts with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The top candidates to succeed Hashimoto appear to be Foreign
Minister Keizo Obuchi, head of the largest faction in the LDP, and
former cabinet chief Seiroku Kajiyama, a free-market advocate and
the markets' favored choice.
</P>
<P>
   One strong faction of the LDP is backing party General Council
Chairman Yoshiro Mori for the job, according to Tuesday editions of
The Daily Yomiuri.
</P>
<P>
   Also mentioned have been former Prime Minister Kiichi Miyazawa,
who has taken a lead role in economic reform, and Yohei Kono, a
former LDP chief. An underdog is Health and Welfare Minister
Junichiro Koizumi, who saved social security from the axe when
other ministries endured deep cuts.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the elections, the once stunningly-popular
Hashimoto had dropped to a 28.5 percent approval rating. In the
end, his waffling over the economy overshadowed his
accomplishments, a sign of rising public anger over Japan's first
recession in 23 years. As in Indonesia, Thailand and South Korea,
where leaders or ruling parties were ousted in the last year amid
financial meltdowns, it was a sorry economy that ended Hashimoto's
2 1/2 years in power.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto did manage to bring about several significant reforms
during his tenure, including a ``Big Bang'' plan to open financial
markets by 2001. He also downsized the bureaucracy by cutting 22
ministries to 12, a near-miracle in a nation run by bureaucrats. He
also managed to stifle opposition to US military bases on Okinawa
by returning US-leased land to the local government.
</P>
<P>
   But Hashimoto also instituted a series of unpopular policies,
including hiking the sales tax, cutting spending drastically and
bailing out failed loan companies in what was seen as favoritism
for cronies. In a reversal this year, he proposed a $127 billion
tax cut and spending package _ Japan's largest ever _ and a
``bridge bank'' plan that would allow weak banks to fail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
