<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3042 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAFTA-SUIT-BOS &LR;      07-13 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAFTA-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEELWORKERS SUIT ASSAILS NAFTA AS UNCONSTITUTIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United Steelworkers of America filed a lawsuit
against the federal government Monday, charging that the North
American Free Trade Agreement is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The steelworkers, along with the Made in the USA Foundation,
charge that NAFTA is a treaty and needed a two-thirds vote of the
Senate when it was passed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   George Becker, president of the Pittsburgh-based union, said
NAFTA must be retracted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to do is to wipe NAFTA off the books clean,''
Becker said at a news conference. ``It was not constitutionally
adopted. Then let's negotiate trade agreements, but let's do it
with the understanding that we'll have input for the workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The groups filed the lawsuit in the US District Court in
Northern Alabama, because, Becker said, workers there have been
hurt by NAFTA. A Steelworkers local that represents employees from
Goodyear Tire and Rubber Co. in Gadsden, Ala., is also a plaintiff
in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit asks the court to decide whether NAFTA is a treaty,
and if it is, to retract the trade accord with Mexico and Canada
because it did not pass the Senate with the two-thirds vote needed
for treaties.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the Senate voted 61-38 to adopt NAFTA, and the House
approved it with a 234-200 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NAFTA is not a treaty, we can't imagine what would qualify
as a treaty,'' Becker said. ``NAFTA is a failed treaty. It has not
expanded the economy of the US, Canada, or Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA has turned out to ``betray the trust of workers and
families who bought into the dream of an improved economy,'' Becker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Becker said the Labor Department has certified that more than
180,000 US workers, including 7,400 from the Steelworkers union,
have been displaced by NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit attacks only the constitutionality of NAFTA, not
whether it is effective, said Carl Frankel, the union's general
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not in the lawsuit debate whether the treaty is good
or bad except to show we have been injured as a result of NAFTA,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Becker cited the loss of American jobs to cheaper
Mexican labor and unimproved conditions for Mexican workers.
</P>
<P>
   Joel D. Joseph, chairman of the Made in the USA Foundation, said
the nonprofit group promoting American products joined in the
lawsuit because NAFTA ``has not helped workers or consumers in the
United States, Canada, or Mexico, and because it was not enacted as
a treaty by the Constitution of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The groups pointed to an article by Laurence H. Tribe, professor
of constitutional law at Harvard Law School, stating that NAFTA is
a treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short of creating a government for the Western Hemisphere,
NAFTA does everything else a treaty could do,'' Tribe said Monday
in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokeswoman, Chris Watney, said, ``The
government has not yet seen that suit. We will be reviewing it as
soon as possible, and we will comment after we review it.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker said the steelworkers union waited five years after NAFTA
was passed to file the lawsuit because the group wanted to see how
the agreement would work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was, maybe, a way of hoping things were going to get
better, but they don't,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
