<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      07-13 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The possibility of two fashion weeks in New York, one
of which might pre-empt the European shows, has taken on serious
proportions as Donna Karan, John Bartlett and Ralph Lauren say they
are considering showing their spring 1999 women's lines in New York
in September.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Helmut Lang announced that he would show on Sept. 17
rather than during the regular New York shows, most of which are
scheduled for Oct. 31 through Nov. 6 in the tents in Bryant Park.
His announcement was followed the next day by Calvin Klein's saying
that he, too, would show early.
</P>
<P>
   The declarations seemed like the work of two titans going head
to head, with Klein having been stung by comments that he has been
unduly influenced by Lang's work. But now several American
designers are considering moving their dates forward. The benefits
would mean more attention _ and, they hope, more money _ from
retailers who tend to be most influenced by the Europeans, whom
they normally see first. There is also a matter of pride, as
American designers have been considered followers of European
trends since the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely looking at it,'' said Patti Cohen, a senior
vice president for Donna Karan International. Ms. Cohen was in
meetings Monday trying to figure out whether the move is feasible.
``There's the mills, the fabrics that are due in. Each division is
now looking into what everyone would be responsible for.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett arrived in Italy Monday to check whether his samples
would be ready for an early showing.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Tesoro, a spokeswoman for Lauren, said that the designer
would consider changing if there is enough support for the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, it is likely that the tents in Bryant Park
will go up as scheduled. But Fern Mallis, the executive director of
Seventh on Sixth, the shows' producer, is concerned about the
impact two show weeks could have on the organization and the
industry. To move the shows would require coordination with their
sponsors and the Bryant Park Restoration Corp., which manages the
park. ``We sent out a letter last week, and the general consensus
is most people appreciate and like the idea, but it just can't be
done this quickly for most of the industry,'' Ms. Mallis said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Finley, the publisher of the New York Fashion Calendar,
which began more than 40 years ago, recalled that American
designers tried to show earlier about 10 years ago. ``A group of
designers pushed to have it to get the money,'' she said. ``Mollie
Parnis was one of the leaders. And it didn't work. The buyers
didn't want to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsey Johnson in London
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Betsey Johnson plans to take her wares to London and
show during the ready-to-wear shows at the end of September. Ms.
Johnson opened her first store in England in April, at 106 Draycott
Ave. in the Knightsbridge section of London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Londoner at heart,'' Ms. Johnson said. ``It's a much
more frivolous, creative and personal design approach. I'm not the
only crazy one on the runway.''
</P>
<P>
   English designers are known for their eclectic approach to
design, and last season Ms. Johnson's fall show in New York, a
bawdy runway romp of lingerie-inspired clothes, was but another
chapter in her madcap runway book.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnson has not yet nailed down a time and location for the
show.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the excursion into London is to raise her
visibility throughout Europe in preparation for a more
mass-oriented collection than her popular Betsey Johnson and
higher-priced Ultra lines. She would not disclose the nature of the
venture, but there has been talk for some time that the designer
was in negotiations to introduce a jeans collection. Jeans would be
a natural next step for Ms. Johnson, whose body-conscious designs
are popular with the young and the youthful.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnson said that she would return her show to New York next
year and that she supported the move by some designers to show
before the European designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our collections are open in the showroom three months before
we show them, so our English sales reps can have them to show
around in time in Europe,'' Ms. Johnson said. ``New York should
absolutely open early.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
