<HEADER>
A3051 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-robertsoncolumn-HNS &LR;      07-13 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-robertson </SLUG>
 column -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   French impeccable &QL; 
as World Cup hosts
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ With all due respect to Les Bleus, the real French heroes
are les verts.
</P>
<P>
   Beating Brazil to win France's first World Cup is one thing.
Cleaning up the mess after Brazil has been beaten and that first
World Cup won, however, is quite another.
</P>
<P>
   All I know is when I went to bed in the wee hours Monday
morning, the party of this half-century raged on unabated. Yet in
the final victory of this emotional Coupe du Monde, by 7:30 a.m.
the boulevards and avenues where millions had swarmed were already
trash-free. I swear to goodness, there wasn't a piece of litter to
be seen anywhere, and it was drizzling to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the men in green, Paris' hard-working garbage collectors,
had trumped the Blues. And to think they'll just have to start all
over again Wednesday morning, following today's Bastille Day bash.
Allez, verts!
</P>
<P>
   This World Cup, then, would be a start-to-finish triumph for the
home team. On every front, victory can be declared, from critical
acclaim for the Stade de France _ the planet's most beautiful
sports stadium _ to France's breakthrough on the soccer pitch to
the massive tidying-up effort afterward.
</P>
<P>
   No real trace of danger
</P>
<P>
   Despite the many dire warnings about France's scary
vulnerability to terrorist actions, none materialized. The closest
thing to trouble I saw was when the CRS, France's national police,
blew up an unattended bag at Charles De Gaulle Airport one Saturday
morning. Even that had the feel of a fete to it.
</P>
<P>
   And the imposing, occasionally ominous CRS presence
notwithstanding, the cops were always quick to give advice or
directions. The only really foul behavior, not surprisingly, was
the result of the idiots barging in from across (and under) the
English Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, a mob of a million-plus delirious fans taking to the
streets late Sunday night didn't produce a body count or do
irreparable harm to the local monuments. A comparable number of
Yankees fans would have torn down the Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   So the French people, as underrated as their rubbish collectors,
came through in smashing style, actually surpassing the efforts of
the footballers representing them. And while, no, not everyone was
polite, not everyone is polite in New York, either.
</P>
<P>
   Or Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle's John P. Lopez was hopelessly lost in Bordeaux
late one night. Seeking help in getting to his hotel, he found only
one place open, a small bar on a narrow, deserted street where a
half-dozen surly-looking men were still drinking. Madam bartender
had the obligatory tattoo and only the slightest comprehension of
the English language.
</P>
<P>
   Yet within half an hour, Lopez had seven new friends and a taxi
waiting at the door.
</P>
<P>
   George Vecsey of the New York Times misplaced his press pass, an
almost insurmountable faux pas given FIFA's ponderous and arrogant
bureaucracy. One of the aforementioned street sweepers, however,
found it lying amid the refuse and immediately phoned the Times'
office here to inquire how he might return it.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. inferior, but that's OK
</P>
<P>
   Memo to you tourists planning a visit to Paris, or anywhere in
France: Forget everything you've heard about how difficult the
French are. They're terrific, save for the cigarette smoke. Be
polite _ deferential won't hurt; smile when smiled at; and always
stay patient if the natives don't understand you.
</P>
<P>
   As the guest, you are obliged to find a way to understand them.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is what befell the U.S.'s long-vanquished soccer
team. Our lads just didn't get it either, and, as I have noted
previously, they probably never will. The demographics of the
current team, which performed at a level inferior to any of the
other 31 to reach France, suggest our being competitive in, never
mind winning, the Japan-South Korea World Cup in 2002 is only a
remote possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Which is perfectly OK, as I have previously noted. We don't need
soccer, and soccer doesn't need us. We can get enough kicks from
the Super Bowl, the World Series, et al., and let the rest of the
planet have the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Although we would like to believe the approval of the almighty
U.S. market is essential for anything to be judged significant, the
delirious mobs that partied down all night long on the Champs
Elyses would seem to suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Brazil's Ronaldo is 21 years old and earns the equivalent
of $10 million per year already. France's 25-year-old superstar
Zinedine Zidane, among others, isn't way behind. You think they're
worried about selling soccer to the American people?
</P>
<P>
   It's a great game. It just isn't our game. No biggie. Vive la
diffrence!
</P>
<P>
   And again, vive les verts! I could use a few of those guys
around my house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
