<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PORN-INTERNET (Washington) _ It isn't exactly ``Star Wars,'' but
an intense battle in cyberspace is being waged in the suburbs of
the nation's capital. At issue is the decision by the public
library board of Loudoun County, Va., to install so-called blocking
software to deny library patrons access to computer Internet sites
featuring ``child pornography,'' ``hardcore pornography'' and
``material deemed harmful to juveniles.'' By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already
filed)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S. (Washington) _ The Clinton administration says it
hopes the resignation of Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
will not derail economic reforms in that country. Experts say the
defeat of Hashimoto's party could lead to quicker reforms. By MARK
HELM. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   HISTORIC-TREASURES (Washington) _ Buoyed by the pledge of a $10
million corporate gift to help restore the nation's tattered
Star-Spangled Banner in the Smithsonian Institution, First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton begins a four-day tour to promote the
preservation of America's historic treasures. By NICOLE TSONG.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BIOLOGICAL-THREAT (Laredo, Texas) _ Federal agents were hunting
for containers of HIV-infected blood, the rabies virus and anthrax
spores earlier this month when they arrested three men on charges
of threatening government officials and their families. By DANE
SCHILLER. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HEAT (Dallas) _ The heat in Texas has been blamed for the
deaths of 15 people in Dallas alone, and another day of
temperatures over the 110-degree mark is forecast for Tuesday. The
heat wave is approaching the deadly effects of 1980's overheated
drought. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOAK-THE-RICH (Paris) _ France's Socialist-led government is
extending a wealth tax, introduced a decade ago, to include the
estimated value of individuals' art collections and antiques. The
rich also will no longer be able to write off bad loans against
their wealth-tax liability. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed)
</P>
