<TEXT>
<P>
   `Dirty bits' included in Showtime's `Lolita'
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: Georg is cq)
</P>
<P>
   By Lyle V. Harris
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Oscar winner Jeremy Irons remembers the first
time he read ``Lolita,'' the 1954 Vladimir Nabokov novel about a
middle-aged professor's sexual obsession with a 12-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read it when I was 18 and I was looking for the dirty
bits,'' Irons recalled via satellite from England during a press
interview before the nation's TV critics meeting here to preview
the upcoming fall season. ``But there are no dirty bits in this
novel, and that's what's surprising about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The same can't be said, however, for director Adrian Lyne's
adaptation of ``Lolita,'' which premieres Aug. 2 on Showtime. (The
film is being shown before that in a New York theater to qualify it
for possible Oscar nominations.) For that and other reasons,
``Lolita'' has become one of the biggest, and most controversial,
movies of the new television season.
</P>
<P>
   Made for theatrical release, the movie was held up two years
because of concerns it might offend moviegoers. Its $58 million
price tag makes it the most expensive film ever made for cable, and
director Lyne's reputation raised concerns that he would turn the
classic novel about a complex and disturbing relationship into an
exploitative sex romp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie in places is erotic,'' said Lyne, whose films
include ``9 1/2 Weeks,'' ``Flashdance'' and ``Fatal Attraction.''
``But for a movie to be erotic, it doesn't have to have acres of
flesh. I think some people will be judging me rather than the
movie. But it's not the salacious piece of work they expect it to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Irons says he wasn't worried about Lyne, but had doubts about
the subject matter. When Lyne asked him to play Lolita's older
lover, Humbert Humbert, he turned him down _ twice.
</P>
<P>
   Irons said he realized that his decision was based on trying to
be ``politically correct'' and he eventually changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer Dominique Swain, 17, who stars in the title role, said
she never felt uncomfortable on the set of ``Lolita,'' especially
since her mother was always nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Swain, a high school senior who resembles Marcia of ``The Brady
Bunch'' and talks like a total Valley Girl, said, ``I think Adrian
did a pretty good job of keeping me from being corrupted by this
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Showtime programming chief Jerry Offsay said he hasn't been
inundated by complaints about ``Lolita'' _ nor is he expecting
many. Offsay said another movie about child sexual abuse, ``Bastard
Out of Carolina,'' was far more disturbing. Showtime aired
``Bastard'' last season after TNT (and reportedly then-owner Ted
Turner) deemed some scenes too graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got five phone calls (about 'Lolita'). One person asked
me why I'm promoting pedophilia and another woman said she was
praying for me,'' Offsay said. ``I'm sure there will be some people
who will be unhappy. But we invite people who are criticizing the
movie to first see the film. It's a responsible, intelligent
treatment of a difficult subject.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Reid sets up bar again
</P>
<P>
   The new Showtime sitcom ``Lincs'' is set in a big-city bar where
everybody knows your name, the waitress is sassy and the owner has
a raffish charm. But no matter what you do, don't ask producer Tim
Reid if he's is trying for the black ``Cheers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want do do is explode the myths that blacks are
monolithic, that we're either in prison or in Princeton,'' says
Reid of the show set in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Williams (Mr. X on ``The X-Files'') stars in the title
role as outspoken black conservative Russell Lincoln, Pam Grier as
lusciously liberal children's rights activist Eleanor Winthrop and
Georg Stanford Brown as Johnnie B. Good, a morally challenged
lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Grier said she was excited to be reunited with Reid, who cast
her on his critically acclaimed but long-defunct CBS sitcom
``Frank's Place.'' Reid admitted that he also played favorites when
looking for actors to star in his new half-hour sitcom, which
debuts Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife (Daphne) plays the hooker on the show, and yes, she
slept with me to get the part.''
</P>
<P>
   Jodie does `Baby Dance'
</P>
<P>
   A very pregnant Jodie Foster waddled into the convention to
promote ``Baby Dance,'' a Showtime movie about a wealthy infertile
couple trying to adopt a baby from a pair living in a trailer park.
Foster called her imminent motherhood (she's due in September) and
her decision to produce the movie ``a coincidence.'' But she says
the movie made her ``obsess a little bit more'' about parenthood.
Commenting on her success as a director, producer and Oscar-winning
actress, Foster called herself ``the luckiest white girl in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Lust in the dust
</P>
<P>
   Proving again that kids say the darnedest things, ``Lolita''
star Dominique Swain dissed El Paso, Texas, which experienced
severe weather while the movie was filming there. Swain described
the event that delayed shooting as a ``dust storm in the hick
bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The gang's all here
</P>
<P>
   Ray Liotta stars as Frank Sinatra in HBO's unauthorized biopic
``The Rat Pack,'' about the coolest cats America has ever known,
scheduled for August. Don Cheadle plays Sammy Davis Jr. with Joe
Montegna as Dean Martin and William Petersen as John F. Kennedy.
Asked what qualified him to play ``The Voice,'' Liotta paused for a
few seconds and said, ``I've got blue eyes and I'm from New Jersey.
That seemed to be enough.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
