<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-POLITICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia air waves polluted with political commercials
 &HT;    By Charles Walston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is making TV stations rich, giving campaign
strategists headaches, and driving some viewers crazy.
</P>
<P>
   It's political ad clutter, and it has become a nightly feature
on local TV newscasts across Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   One week before the July 21 primary elections, a record number
of candidates are relying on TV to get their messages to voters.
The main reasons are the increased strength of the Republican
party, resulting in heated GOP primaries, and an explosion of TV
advertising by candidates for lieutenant governor and other
``down-ballot'' offices.
</P>
<P>
   One media strategist said the glut of political ads is unusual
for a major TV market like Atlanta, where a 30-second spot on an
evening newscast can cost as much as $1,800.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clutter will rival any state's clutter, any time,'' said
Raymond Strother, a consultant who produced his first political ad
three decades ago and is working in Georgia this year for Rep. Roy
Barnes, a Democratic candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as bad as I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   There are seven Republican and Democratic candidates for
lieutenant governor trying to reach voters on TV this week,
compared to just three Democrats before the 1990 primary, the last
time an incumbent wasn't running.
</P>
<P>
   Six gubernatorial hopefuls from both parties are also on TV,
along with candidates for attorney general, labor commissioner and
the state Supreme Court. Michael Coles, a Democratic candidate for
U.S. Senate, also launched a 60-second biographical ad this week.
</P>
<P>
   The clutter is thickest on the local evening news shows, where
as many as five 30-second political ads can be jammed together
during a commercial break.
</P>
<P>
   TV news is normally considered a good advertising slot for
political campaigns, because people who watch the news are more
likely to vote than those who don't. But with so many ads on the
air this year, campaigns fear that their messages are getting lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much stuff on TV, people are learning not to
notice information,'' U.S. House Speaker Newt Gingrich said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with voters around the state, several said they
were turned off by the barrage of ads this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm almost at the point of throwing a shoe at the TV, it's
that bad,'' said Rowena Wall of Warner Robins.
</P>
<P>
   If the sheer number of ads wasn't confusing enough, the
similarities in the messages would be. Because there has been very
little negative advertising so far, most of the ads have stuck to
themes such as improving education, slashing taxes or cracking down
on criminals. After watching several in a row, it's hard for many
voters to remember which candidate said what.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so confusing, there's nobody that really stands out,''
said Charles Wise, a retiree who lives near Blue Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason why Republican gubernatorial candidate Mike
Bowers decided to launch his broadcast ad campaign by attacking
racial quotas and preferences, according to his campaign spokesman,
Bill Crane. Bowers also will debut a new ad Tuesday featuring his
wife, Bette Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers had produced commercials dealing with crime, taxes and
education, Crane said. But by the time he was able to buy TV time,
other candidates including his GOP rival Guy Millner had already
been talking about those issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an arena where you have a half-dozen candidates for
governor, and even more for lieutenant governor, trying to reach
voters in a 10-day window, you have to do things a little
differently to break out of the pack,'' said Crane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that we needed to speak to issues that were outside
of the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
