<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia court gives OK to link violent films, acts
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ultra-violent movies like ``Natural Born Killers'' and
``Menace II Society'' may be shown during murder trials to prove
defendants were inspired by Hollywood to commit real mayhem, the
Georgia Supreme Court ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidence of a movie in a criminal defendant's possession which
depicts the conduct with which the defendant is charged may be
admissible to show the defendant's bent of mind,'' Justice Harris
Hines wrote in a 4-3 decision upholding a Worth County murder
conviction and dismissing claims the movie prejudiced the jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this decision is not unprecedented, it's certainly
unusual,'' said professor Robert Pugsley from Southwestern
University School of Law in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In the Worth County case, jurors watched the grisly opening
sequence of ``Menace II Society,'' a film that defendant Gerald
Nathaniel Rushin watched at least five times. The film opens with
character ``O-dog'' fatally shooting two convenience store clerks
and taking the store's surveillance videotape. Rushin shot and
killed a store clerk in 1995 and took the surveillance tape.
</P>
<P>
   The court also upheld Ronnie Jack Beasley Jr.'s murder
conviction in Toombs County. Beasley and his girlfriend had watched
``Natural Born Killers'' an estimated 20 times. In the movie, 52
people are killed by a man and woman on a three-month crime spree.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley sometimes referred to himself as ``the Natural.'' The
jury watched the entire movie during his trial for a murder
committed in a 1995 robbery. ``The visceral impact that one
experiences in seeing a mindless, blood-thirsty film like 'Natural
Born Killers' can have a far-reaching, inflammatory impact,'' said
Pugsley. ``You're also taking a truly monstrous example, a
caricature, and showing this person kill 52 while asking the jury
to convict the defendant of killing only one. This constitutes, no
pun intended, overkill.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Torre, director of the Georgia Film and Video Commission,
said, ``This ruling doesn't sit well with me. If an individual is
going to commit a crime, I don't think it takes a movie to do it.
The same can be said for books and video games.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Norman Fletcher wrote dissents to both rulings, saying
the violence in the movies was prejudicial and unnecessary in light
of corroborating evidence. ``The movie thus served as a dramatic
state witness who blurred fact and fiction but who was not subject
to cross-examination,'' Fletcher wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In Rushin's case, the store surveillance film was recovered and
used to rebut his contention that the killing was accidental. For
this reason, ``The real purpose of the movie was to provide a more
explicit visual picture of the state's theory that Rushin committed
crimes similar to the movie's crimes,'' Fletcher said. ``In
contrast to the store videotape, which had only fuzzy black images
and ended before the shooting, the movie presented a clear and
colorful image of two senseless murders.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
