<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-STROHMEYER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK STROHMEYER, ACCOUNTANT, AMATEUR ARCHEOLOGIST; AT 45 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Allen Strohmeyer of Watertown, Mass., an accountant and
amateur archeologist who found meaning in stoneworks he claimed
were constructed by Native Americans, died of liver failure
Saturday in Mount Auburn Hospital in Cambridge, Mass. He was 45.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Strohmeyer was born in Boston and raised in Bethlehem, Pa.
He graduated from Boston University in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Active in Boston public-housing circles, he was a teacher at
Casa del Sol, an agency serving Latinos in the South End; and an
accountant for the Justice Resource Institute and the Committee for
Boston Public Housing.
</P>
<P>
   Though most archeologists discounted his theories, he spent much
time exploring local rock formations and discussing his findings
with local historical groups.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn of the winter solstice on Dec. 21, 1996, Mr. Strohmeyer
was hunkered down in the potato cave in Acton, Mass., a slab-roofed
chamber set into the hillside above Nashoba Brook, studying what he
thought was an ancient astronomical observatory. ``Every time I
come in here, I'm still in awe of these huge slabs,'' he said in a
story published in the Globe on Jan. 5, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The potato cave is entered through a long crawl space that opens
into a chamber large enough to stand in. It is supported on one
side by a column of stones that has a small crevice opening to the
morning sun. At dawn on Dec. 21, Mr. Strohmeyer said, a beam of
light shone through the crevice and illuminated a spot just below a
large stone of quartz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the shortest day of the year; then the sun comes back and
the light comes back,'' he said. ``It's an event that's observed
throughout the world, and the Indians here saw the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He also studied a network of stone rows, mounds, and chambers
from Billerica, Mass. to Boxborough, Mass., which he believed
native people constructed to celebrate the earth. ``There are
stoneworks that are staggering in their beauty and their
construction,'' he said. ``It's right in your back yard. The whole
question is seeing it.''
</P>
<P>
   He also found meaning in certain large boulders and outcroppings
in Great Brook State Park in Carlisle, Mass. At Mr. Strohmeyer's
prodding, the Massachusetts Department of Environmental Management
commissioned a study of the site in 1995. The study found no
evidence that Native Americans constructed anything on the site.
However, Native American consultants told the study's authors that
a large boulder on the site that is shaped like a turtle _ the
Native American symbol of creation _ and topped with a pine tree _
the Native American symbol of peace _ was considered sacred.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves two sons, Fernando Vitol and Andres Colby, both of
Watertown; his parents, John and Nancy (Jordan) Strohmeyer of
Anchorage; a brother, John of Bloomfield, Mich.; a sister, Sarah
Strohmeyer Merriman of Middlesex, Vt.; and his former wife, Beatriz
McConnie Zapater of Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
