<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-ART-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS OF PROTESTANTS MARCH PEACEFULLY IN ULSTER
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Tens of thousands of Orange Order
Protestants walked peacefully Monday in several hundred parades
throughout Northern Ireland, after a week of Protestant violence
over patriotic marches in Catholic neighborhoods and the death of
three young Catholic brothers in an arson attack.
</P>
<P>
   In what was taken to be a reaction to the killing of the boys on
Sunday, the level of violence in the British province on Sunday
night and Monday was low, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear yesterday, after those murders, an awful lot of
people did reflect on what is happening, and it is absolutely
appalling that it should take that to make some people see where
they potentially were heading,'' a spokesman for Prime Minister
Tony Blair said in London. ``The vast majority are making it clear
they will not tolerate violence, that that is the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The violence had threatened the peace pact approved in May.
</P>
<P>
   The situation grew tenser after the boys had been killed in a
fire that the police said was the work of Protestants in the
predominantly Protestant town of Ballymoney, 40 miles north of
Belfast. Today, as the boys became virtual martyrs in the eyes of
Catholics, and some Protestants, the tension seemed to ebb. But
they could rise again in nighttime demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   A march that led to violence in the past passed calmly through a
Catholic area in Belfast this morning. To honor the dead boys,
Catholics did not resist. One leader, John Gormley, said, ``We
thought it would be a good tactic, as well as good behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orange parades, held annually to celebrate the victory in
1690 of the Protestant William of Orange over his Catholic
father-in-law, King James II, had threatened to cause further
disturbances. The Protestant violence began after a British
government commission had forbade Orangemen to march through a
Catholic area in Portadown, 35 miles west of here.
</P>
<P>
   For a week protesters in the Drumcree area of Portadown attacked
with gasoline bombs, rocks and ball-bearings hurled from
slingshots. Hundreds of police officers and British troops blocked
the Protestants and kept them from Catholic Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters across the province also hijacked and burned dozens
of cars and blocked scores of major roads. But the Orange Order's
case seemed substantially weakened, as public support, even among
Protestants, seemed to drop after the arson attack.
</P>
<P>
   An Orange leader, the Rev. William Bingham, chaplain of the
Portadown unit, urged an end to the protest at Drumcree, saying,
``No road is worth a life.'' Some Orangemen denounced him as a
traitor.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop Robin Eames, the Protestant Primate of the Church of
Ireland, said, ``What is being done in the name of Protestantism is
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The churchmen's view was echoed by other prominent Orangemen,
including David Trimble, the First Minister of the new Northern
Ireland Assembly, which is supposed to enact changes to give the
Catholic minority added power.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago Trimble, head of the Ulster Unionist Party,
raised his arm in triumph after joining the Drumcree march. The
gesture enhanced his image among Protestants and led, ultimately,
to his post as First Minister. In that post he is committed to
cooperate with Catholic officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen at Drumcree said that they were not responsible
for the killings or the widespread Protestant mob violence and that
they would continue their protest until they were allowed to march
through the Catholic area.
</P>
<P>
   The police in Ballymoney arrested two men, whom they did not
identify, for questioning in the arson that killed the Quinns _
Richard, 10; Mark, 9, and Jason, 7 _ as they slept.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Monday afternoon at Drumcree, about 1,500 Orangemen and
supporters continued to face the police and soldiers across the
barbed-wire and concrete barriers blocking the way to the Catholic
area.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 500 parades Monday, only one was considered highly
volatile, along a Catholic stretch of Lower Ormeau Road in Belfast.
The march, after a delay caused by bomb hoaxes, began in heavy rain
at about 8:40 a.m. A government parade commission authorized the
march after having banned it for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Lower Ormeau Road has been a flash point since the 1992 march,
when Orangemen passing the Catholics raised their hands with five
fingers spread wide at the crowd. The gesture was a brutal,
gloating reminder that several months earlier Protestant gunmen had
shot dead five Catholics in front of a bookmaker's shop on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   This morning 200 quiet men, most in black suits and orange
stoles, many wearing black bowlers, marched briskly to the beat of
a large drum. The fife-and-drum band, which traditionally played
martial music that angers Catholics, was silent by order of the
parade commission.
</P>
<P>
   But the Catholics did not, as they have in the past, sit down in
the road, confront the police separating them from the parade or
hurl rocks and bottles at the marchers.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the Quinn family said although the three brothers
would be buried Tuesday in a Catholic cemetery after a funeral
Mass, they had not been raised as practicing Catholics. Their
mother, Christine, the friends said, had sent them to a
predominantly Protestant school so that they would be assimilated
with the largely Protestant population.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were raised both Catholic and Protestant,'' said an
uncle, Robert Patton, a Protestant. Their father, John Dillon, who
is estranged from their mother, arrived from England, where he
lives, for the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon was quoted by The Irish News, a respected Belfast
newspaper favored by Catholics, as having said that Protestant
militants ``chased me to England.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys and their mother came back last year,'' he added. ``I
still live in England. So they go after the wee ones.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3058 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-ART-60     07-13 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-ART-600&AMP;ADDS(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN BEGINS SEARCH FOR NEW PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: see related JAPAN-REACT) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(HLW) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Politicians began jockeying on Monday for the chance to
play chief surgeon to the world's second-largest economy after
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto resigned, saying he was
responsible for his party's disastrous finish in parliamentary
elections on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto's resignation left a political vacuum at the economic
heart of Asia, sending stocks and currencies reeling across the
continent and triggering fears that another chapter could be
beginning in the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden and unexpected nature of the political upheaval here
was underscored when Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko of Russia
arrived in Tokyo on Monday morning for a visit with Hashimoto. It
was the first such visit ever by a Russian prime minister, and it
seemed sensible enough when Kiriyenko left Moscow, but by the time
he stepped off the plane in Tokyo, Hashimoto was history.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto also had to cancel plans for a state visit to the
United States later this month.
</P>
<P>
   A new prime minister is expected to be chosen in the next week
and installed on about July 30, after intensive horse-trading in
the governing Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   But the election has left some wondering whether Japan is on a
transition toward a two-party system that will change the character
not just of the party but also of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   That is subject to debate, but there seems little doubt that the
election has already left the party with a reduced ability to
govern and with a handful of prime ministerial candidates who
represent precisely the old school of politics that the voters
decisively rejected on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hashimoto is one of the best that the LDP can produce,'' said
Takashi Inoguchi, a political scientist at Tokyo University.
``Unless someone terribly fresh and surprising comes along, it's
hard to see how the next prime minister can handle the issues head
on and fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``To handle the problems efficiently, you need a fresh, strong
and decisive leader, but they are very hard to find. So we'll have
to muddle through with less than competent political leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of a new prime minister for Japan is of intense
interest around Asia, for Japan is seen as the key to overcoming
the region's crisis. Its economy is eight times as big as China's
and twice as big as all the rest of Asia's put together, and it has
contributed far more to bail-out packages than the United States or
any other country.
</P>
<P>
   Handicapping the race is a bit difficult, however, for the last
thing candidates do is express interest in the job. Instead, if one
is asked if one is interested, it is deemed polite to assume a
pained expression and rush away without answering _ which is
precisely what the front-runner, Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi, did
on Monday when reporters raised the issue outside his home.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While in the United States the metaphor for becoming a candidate
is to toss one's hat into the ring, in Japanese it is to be an
omikoshi, a portable shrine. Just as throngs of revelers together
carry an omikoshi on their shoulders in exuberant street festivals,
so the candidate is supposed to be carried by supporters into the
fray.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, of course, the candidates are a bit different from
other omikoshi: they desperately scramble for shoulders to carry
them, and in some cases they even pay party officials huge sums in
exchange for support.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi, 61, is the leading candidate largely because he heads
the largest faction in the party and is respected for his
affability. But critics say that while he may not have enemies, he
also has no policies or initiatives, and it would be difficult to
find someone less charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   Another contender is Seiroku Kajiyama, 72, a much more outspoken
and controversial party elder. He has some support, because he has
consistently urged a more aggressive posture in tackling Japan's
economic problems, but he has also made missteps over the years.
</P>
<P>
   A possible compromise is Kiichi Miyazawa, 78, a former prime
minister who is respected for his command of financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto, in announcing his resignation, declined to endorse a
successor. His face grim and his eyes moist, he urged his
successors to continue his policies of rectifying Japan's finances
and restructuring government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have proposed a number of reforms that are painful to
people,'' Hashimoto said, apparently referring to such measures as
his increase of the national sales tax. ``I realize that there are
various objections to this. But I did my best on these matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the biggest reason was for his defeat, Hashimoto
scarcely paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally my fault,'' he said. ``I lacked ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto will remain a caretaker prime minister until his
successor is chosen.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the new leader's central tasks will be to shore up not
only the country but also his party. The elections on Sunday for
the upper house of Parliament were a major blow to the party, as it
won only 44 seats out of the 126 contested.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most worrying for the Liberal Democrats were the hints
that Japan might be moving toward a Western-style system in which
two political parties alternately hold power. For decades, Japan
has been a multiparty democracy in form, but the reality has been
something closer to a one-party state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is surely changing,'' Takao Toshikawa, publisher of a
political newsletter in Tokyo. ``We're moving toward a two-party
party system.''
</P>
<P>
   Commentators have been saying that for a number of years, and it
never came true in the past, even in similar circumstances. In the
1989 elections for the upper house, for instance, the Liberal
Democrats suffered an even worse defeat, which was widely seen as a
sign of fundamental change. Then tides quickly shifted again.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the latest result also indicated that a two-party system may
be emerging. The main opposition group, the Democratic Party,
consolidated its status by winning big in the election, gaining
respectability and legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in the proportional representation part of the ballot,
the Democrats won 22 percent of the vote, only just behind the
Liberal Democrats, who got 25 percent. The balance was divided
among a profusion of small opposition parties, and if some of them
join forces with the Democrats _ as the Democrats hope _ then the
opposition would be theoretically able to outvote the Liberal
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party is poorly organized. Its greatest asset is
Naoto Kan, a dynamic former Cabinet minister who is by far the most
popular politician in the country. The Liberal Democrats are
fretting that they have no one with close to the appeal of Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Another key factor is that disaffected citizens once simply did
not bother to vote. But this time, exit polls indicate, the
disaffected turned up at the polls _ and voted against the Liberal
Democrats. Voter turnout surged from 44 percent in the last
election for the upper house to 59 percent this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time is extremely different from past elections, both
upper house and lower house elections,'' Toshikawa said. ``This
time, people were motivated to vote because of the economic
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the election suggests that the Liberal Democrats
are relying on a dwindling power base. They won their seats
primarily in the rural areas that are losing population and
influence, and they were demolished in the urban areas, failing to
win a single district in Tokyo, Osaka, Kobe or Nagano. In urban
areas, even the Communists did better than the Liberal Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Kazuyuki Hamada, a political commentator in Tokyo, said that the
challenge will be for the Democratic Party to unite the fragmented
opposition, but that if this happens, the impact on Japan will be
historic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to put aside their differences and work together,''
Hamada said of the opposition parties. ``It's a life-or-death
moment for Japan. If they fail, in the 21st century Japan will
drift along and we will have no hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese and Western analysts, even those in the Liberal
Democratic Party, often emphasize the importance of a nurturing a
two-party system as the best way to create a responsive political
structure to lead the nation. For now, Japan in some respects
resembles a one-party state, with a familiar pattern of political
corruption and stagnation.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many say that it would be difficult to restructure the
Liberal Democratic Party and make it more forward-looking unless it
is evicted and kept from power for some time. Just as the best
thing that happened to the British Labor Party was the
introspection and change triggered by its years in the political
wilderness, the thinking goes, the only way to refocus the Liberal
Democratic Party may be to exile it from power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
