<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAPRUDER-KENNEDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAPRUDER FILM RELEASED TO STORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ They are 26 seconds of infamy, the rolling film
of a national nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   For 35 years, Dallas dressmaker Abraham Zapruder's horrific home
movie of President John F. Kennedy's assassination has been locked
in the National Archives, off limits to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   But to the anguish of Kennedy supporters and the anticipation of
conspiracy buffs, thousands of digitally enhanced videtapes of
Zapruder's historic recording of Kennedy's slaying are bound this
week for the ``new release'' shelves of the nation's video stores.
</P>
<P>
   An American tragedy for sale: $19.98 a copy.
</P>
<P>
   Billed by Zapruder's heirs as a public service to satisfy
unrelenting demand for the film, the videotapes will make widely
available for the first time the most gruesome image of the
assassination: the instant when Lee Harvey Oswald's bullet struck
the president's head.
</P>
<P>
   The impact, captured on frame 313 of the 500-frame film, has
rarely, if ever, been shown by television networks, although it has
been available for years on illegal, bootleg copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when you think US culture cannot be degraded any further,
something like this comes along,'' said Frank Mankiewicz, a
long-time Kennedy ally who was Robert F. Kennedy's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Zapruder, who died in 1970, was hoping to capture an image of
Kennedy for his grandchildren when he raised his Bell &AMP; Howell
movie camera in Dealey Plaza in Dallas on Nov. 22, 1963, as the
presidential motorcade approached. His hands shaking, Zapruder
recorded the closest and most vivid film of the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   The footage was scrutinized by the Warren Commission, whose 1964
report concluded that Oswald acted alone when he shot Kennedy from
the sixth floor of the Texas School Book Depository building.
</P>
<P>
   That finding has long been challenged by many conspiracy
theorists, and the newly released videotapes could become the stuff
of a new wave of assassination questions. The footage, digitally
enhanced at an estimated cost of $500,000, provides a fuller
picture of the killing than has been available before, including
images between the original film's sprocket holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see images no one ever saw before, like extra people in
the motorcade and extra movement by the Secret Service,'' said
Natalie Olinger, a spokesman for MPI Home Video of Orland Park,
Ill., which collaborated with Zapruder's heirs on the project.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-minute video, titled ``Image of an Assassination: A New
Look at the Zapruder Film,'' includes a 40-minute documentary about
the ``preservation and restoration'' of the Zapruder film and shows
numerous images of the bullet striking Kennedy's head. Olinger said
the production company, which will split the proceeds equally with
Zapruder's heirs, hopes to sell 200,000 copies of the video.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Senator Edward M. Kennedy said, ``The Kennedy
family has chosen not to comment'' on the video release.
</P>
<P>
   However, family supporters said the development was deeply
painful to the Kennedys and expressed dismay at the prospect of the
grisly footage becoming a form of mass entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing but titillation,'' Mankiewicz said. ``I'm
surprised they don't get the film of Jack Ruby shooting Lee Harvey
Oswald and run it as a second feature.''
</P>
<P>
   Olinger defended the video release. ``The story is not meant to
hurt the Kennedy family in any way,'' she said, ``but John F.
Kennedy was our president and people have a right to see what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Zapruder sold Life magazine the rights to the footage
in 1963 for $50,000, he made clear before he died that he did not
want to use the film to exploit Kennedy's death commercially. James
L. Silverberg, a lawyer for Zapruder's heirs, including his son and
daughter, Henry and Myrna, said they share that desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was done with the expectation that the Zapruder family
would have invested a substantial amount of money in order to
answer a public need,'' Silverberg said, referring to demand for
the footage.
</P>
<P>
   The Assassination Record Review Board ruled last year that the
original Zapruder film should be part of its permanent records.
Since then, the Zapruder family, which maintains copyrights to the
film, has been negotiating how much the government will compensate
them for the footage.
</P>
<P>
   The government has offered $3 million. But the Zapruders, citing
appraisals as high as $70 million, are asking for $18 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
