<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRI-LAYOFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRI AUTOMATION TO LAY OFF 180 WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asia's economic problems and a worldwide slowdown in orders for
computer chip equipment took a further toll in Massachusetts as PRI
Automation Inc. of Billerica said Monday it planned to lay off
about 180 employees, or 15 percent of its work force.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the layoffs will be in Massachusetts and range from
production to sales and management positions, including ``a couple
at the highest levels,'' chief financial officer Stephen D. Allison
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it also expects to report up to a 20 percent
decline in sales for its most recent quarter from the previous
three-month period, along with a net loss for the quarter of
between 12 cents and 16 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   PRI makes robotic equipment and software bought and used by
semiconductor manufacturers, and the company's announcement was the
latest round of gloom from an industry that, a year ago, had
expected big gains from an ongoing changeover in technology that
would increase computer chip production.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, thousands of workers around the world, including
hundreds in Massachusetts, have been pink-slipped as customers
postpone orders for new machines or request a delay in shipments.
Many Asia-based chip makers are cutting back on equipment purchases
in wake of the financial crisis that has swept the region; US chip
suppliers are slowing production as Asian customers, such as
computer makers, reduce spending.
</P>
<P>
   Offering an optimistic note, Allison said, ``Some start out as
cancellations but then turn around to become postponements.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nasdaq trading, PRI shares fell 1 to close at 15 1/16 after
dropping earlier in the day to 14. The company's 52-week peak share
price was 58 1/2, last Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Allison said that as part of PRI's restructuring, two small
sales offices will be closed and manufacturing space in Lowell
leased earlier this year will remain empty.
</P>
<P>
   This is PRI's second round of layoffs this year. The first
involved 60 employees, most of them temporary workers, who were
furloughed last January.
</P>
<P>
   The current dismissals will be more costly. PRI said that
severance and other payments are expected to bring between $5
million and $7 million in extraordinary charges when it posts
financial results for the most recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The steps we are taking will help make PRI a stronger and more
competitively positioned company once the upturn comes,'' chairman
and chief executive Mord Wiesler said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   PRI uses a fiscal year ending Sept. 30; the upcoming report will
cover the third quarter of that year, which ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The company said sales for the most recent quarter are likely to
be down between 15 percent and 20 percent from the $47.1 million
posted for the second quarter, which ended March 30. The projected
quarterly loss did not include extraordinary charges for
restructuring and writeoff of excess assets.
</P>
<P>
   One of Masschusetts' fastest growing companies, PRI was on its
way to a record of $200 million-plus in annual sales through the
first half of its fiscal year, although the company suffered a
22-cent &UR;  &LR; per &UR;  &LR; share net loss for that period.
</P>
<P>
   For fiscal 1997, PRI chalked up $17.08 million in earnings on
$169.5 million in sales, for a fourth straight profitable year
since its stock went public in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
