<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3072 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-FCC-COX     07-13 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-FCC-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Turner critical media, congress at NAACP convention
</P>
<P>
   By Shelia M. Poole
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No one was safe from media mogul Ted Turner Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Not media conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Not Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who spoke during a telecommunications forum at the 89th
Annual NAACP Convention at the Georgia World Congress Center,
criticized both for making it more difficult for small businessmen
to get into _ and stay in _ the business.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, drawing laughs from the audience of about 300, recalled
when he was a small businessman and had difficulty getting capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really tough,'' said Turner, vice chairman of Time
Warner Inc., and one of the world's wealthiest individuals.
</P>
<P>
   It's even worse today, he said, because television and radio
``prices have been bid up so high. Quite frankly, America is run by
the Golden Rule to the extent that he who has the gold, rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, in his ``just folks'' style, accused media conglomerates
of swaying Congress with hefty campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the big boys shoveling the big dough,'' said Turner, who
peppered his speech with calls for campaign reform. Congressmen
``vote where the money comes from.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner also said he could understand what women and blacks have
gone through because he, too, faced discrimination _ as a
Southerner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to have an education, you just have to have
smarts, Bubba,'' he said. ``You've got to find out what's coming
next and you'd better be right. If you bet on the wrong horse you
can end up with nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on the panel were Federal Communications Commission chief
William Kennard; Percy Sutton, chairman of African Continental
Telecommunications; and Eddie Edwards, president and chief
executive officer of Glencairn Ltd. Broadcast Properties.
</P>
<P>
   Minority ownership of media properties has long been an issue
among civil rights groups. But concerns intensified with the
passage of the Telecommunications Act of 1996, which eased media
ownership rules, allowing chains to buy out smaller operators.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 1 percent of all television and radio stations are
owned by minorities, down from a peak of 3 percent in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues affecting minority ownership include access to
capital, and the launching later this year of digital TV, which
will offer better pictures but take up more airwaves. Low-power TV
stations, including many that are minority-owned, could go off the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard, the first black chairman of the FCC, said the
Information Age is having a profound impact on the U.S. and the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The civil rights challenge of the next decade and the next
century is to make sure African-Americans share in the benefits of
the Information Age,'' through access to technology, employment
opportunities and ownership, Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of employment, Kennard said the FCC plans to continue
to fight a court ruling in the Lutheran Church v. FCC case that
struck a blow at the agency's efforts to promote equal employment
opportunities for women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a cold wind blowing through Washington,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
