u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-NOTES14-COX     07-13 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-NOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAACP notes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Boyd, president of the National Black Farmers
Association, plans to stage a rally here Wednesday before a speech
by Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman to the NAACP convention on
the black farmer issue. Boyd, who has been a leader in the effort
by hundreds of black farmers to win compensation for years of past
discrimination by the Agriculture Department, is also scheduled to
speak during the convention. The Baskerville, Va., man provided The
Associated Press on Monday with a copy of an Agriculture Department
letter stating the investigation into Boyd's complaint that an
agency lawyer referred to him with a racial epithet during a
telephone conference call has ended.
</P>
<P>
   In a formal complaint, Boyd claimed that Teresa Gruber, counsel
to August Schumacher, undersecretary for farm and foreign
agriculture services, used the word ``nigger'' in referring to the
farmer at the end of a May 27 conference call. Schumacher and
Gruber both denied it.
</P>
<P>
   The letter dated Friday from John Sparks, special civil rights
assistant to Glickman, said the USDA inspector general's own
interviews of those involved ``do not provide sufficient evidence
to support the allegation.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurel Green, 22, said she's glad the NAACP's Annual Diversity
Job Fair lasts two days. Otherwise, she said she'd never get
through it in a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought 30 resumes with me. I have no idea how many I've
handed out today,'' she said on Monday, day one of the job fair. A
recent Shaw University graduate, Green said the fair is much more
diverse than the others she's attended this year. She said she is
looking for a job in computers.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Wakefield, a recruiter from the Georgia-based American
Family Life Assurance Company of Columbus (AFLAC), said she was
impressed with the candidates she had seen on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very pleased,'' Wakefield said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 120 companies attended the Diversity Job Fair
sponsored by the NAACP National Labor Department. The fair runs
from noon to 6:30 p.m. today in the Georgia World Congress Center.
The job fair is free and open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Bernice King, daughter of The Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr., addressed her own struggles in an address Monday to the youth
NAACP members.
</P>
<P>
   King said she had become increasingly angry and
``self-destructive'' over the years while trying to deal with the
deaths of her father and other relatives who were close to her. She
said the culmination came when she considered suicide when she
landed in academic trouble after her first year of law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I saw before me was failure. I said, `my God, if don't
come out of this then, the whole world would know that Dr. King's
daughter is a failure,''' she said. ``God really, literally came
into my home and told me to put that knife down because I had a
reason and a purpose for living.''
</P>
<P>
   King encouraged the audience to recognize that they are destined
for greatness as well and that their family or academic
circumstances do not have to dictate their fates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, today, is the beginning of your new life regardless of
what happened yesterday,'' she said. ``Stop replaying the tape.
Live in the present.''
</P>
<P>
   An NAACP leader died of a heart attack en route to the group's
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Dogan, head of the Stark County, Ohio, NAACP branch,
collapsed and died Saturday during a stopover in his hometown of
Greenville, S.C. He was 58.
</P>
<P>
   Dogan was a longtime member of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People and had been chapter president since
1987.
</P>
<P>
   He was a critic of the Canton, Ohio, Police Department and once
tried to get the Department of Justice and FBI to investigate the
department on allegations of racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral is planned for Wednesday in Massillon, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff and its wire services
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
