<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3080 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-REACT-NYT &LR;      07-13 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEF IS FELT IN TOKYO THAT THE MESSAGE HAS FINALLY GOTTEN
ACROSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: see related JAPAN-POLITICS.) 
(HLW) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ While investors are worrying that the prime minister's
resignation on Monday has left a political vacuum that may lead to
economic paralysis, voters are sighing in relief that their
political message may have finally gotten through to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Some people want to teach a lesson to the governing Liberal
Democratic Party and its departing Prime Minister, Ryutaro
Hashimoto. Others want to vent their anger. Some voters want a big
tax cut, while others fear that a tax cut now will bring high tax
bills later on.
</P>
<P>
   But the one message that many people seem to have in common is
that they want stronger leadership and economic change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a good thing that Hashimoto is resigning,'' said
Shinichi Miyagi, 61, an electronics consultant who runs his own
company. ``He is not a leader. People began to feel a sense of
urgency that if they did nothing, Japan would end in failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a big factor was the lack of vision for the future,
the absence of someone saying, `Follow us because the future will
be bright if you put up with this period of pain.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto's resignation sent markets tumbling throughout Asia,
and fears rose that weakness in the Japanese economy, the
second-largest in the world, could pummel the yen and provoke a
recessionary backlash in the region.
</P>
<P>
   But to some voters the resignation was almost cathartic,
offering new hope that there may be opportunity for economic
revival. At the very least, some say, things could not get much
worse than they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people wanted to change the trend and they felt that
the recession would not go away unless they took some drastic
measure,'' said Yoshitoyo Nakano, 54, an electrician, who took his
entire family together to vote on Sunday _ and not for Hashimoto's
candidates. ``I hope that as a result of this election, the Liberal
Democratic Party will reflect on its inability to deal with the
economy and then concentrate its energies on reviving it.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese have long shown an uncanny ability to endure an unhappy
situation, and one consequence is that there has not been a deep
sense of crisis among the leadership, or even among the people,
until now. Indeed, the political scrambling after Hashimoto's
resignation may finally lead to a sense of urgency among the
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   That was not necessarily clear before the election. Japan is a
deceptively affluent society, and that may have made it hard for
the leadership to appreciate the overwhelming sense of malaise.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese are still buying presents for friends during the
traditional summer gift-giving season. They still go out to golf,
and they still plan summer vacations. And soon, a $117-billion
fiscal stimulus package will begin trickling through the economy,
lifting many companies out of their misery.
</P>
<P>
   But just now, the brutal defeat of the Liberal Democrats at
least sends a message to voters as well: that other people think
the same way they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel that something is wrong, but they don't really
feel it,'' said Masao Miyamoto, a social psychologist and author of
``The Straightjacket Society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The restaurants are full of people,'' he said. ``People take
cabs. They don't express their anger. These things have to come
out, and for that to come out, we need bigger crises to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, perhaps for a lack of a crisis, the leadership has been
slow to address problems in the financial system. It took eight
years after the speculative economic bubble burst and the stock
market crashed for the Liberal Democratic Party to come up with its
``Total Plan'' to mop up the nation's $540 billion in bad and
doubtful loans.
</P>
<P>
   Now the election may cause the Total Plan to face even more
delays, and political bickering between a weakened governing party
and emboldened opposition parties could also whittle away at the
plan. But even among those who acknowledge that there may be a
period of economic disarray, the trade-offs may be well worth it,
at least emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about time,'' said Hideaki Kato, 50, a banker at a small
financial institution, who still voted for the Liberal Democratic
Party's candidate in his district.
</P>
<P>
   He added about Hashimoto: ``He could not solve the economic
problems and the financial industry is in chaos, and he only acts
when the Americans tell him to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results of the election are a real scolding to the LDP. It
does not show that people are totally abandoning the party. But it
turns out that the scolding was a bit too effective, and now the
economy may become even less stable. That is unfortunate for
Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto and other government officials on Monday tried to
assure the markets that economic policy would not change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a single day of political vacuum can be allowed, given the
current economic situation,'' said Chief Cabinet Secretary Kanezo
Muraoka.
</P>
<P>
   But emotions ran high this morning, with Taku Yamasaki, the
Liberal Democrats' top policy maker, suggesting concern about a
political void if there is a sudden bank failure. Finance Ministry
officials denied that there would be disruptions in the financial
system but acknowledged a possible delay in carrying out the Total
Plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be no distinction between the opposition and the
ruling side, because we are in a crisis period,'' Deputy Finance
Minister Yasuhisa Shiozaki said in an interview. ``We should
coordinate and cooperate together to overcome this rather
historically important and serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A benchmark stock index, the Nikkei average, rose on Monday,
hitting a peak just after Hashimoto's resignation. Some analysts
said the government might have poured money into the stock market
to prevent a protracted sell-off. Other investors went hunting for
bargains after prices fell in the early morning, and their buying
helped buoy the market in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Nikkei ended on Monday at 16,360.39, up 270.33 points, or
1.68 percent from Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
   Though a successor to the prime minister has not yet been named,
several candidates from the Liberal Democratic Party have emerged,
nearly all of whom are unlikely to veer too far from the current
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think that the worst-case scenario is more of the
same,'' said Kathy Matsui, strategist at Goldman Sachs Japan.
``They don't see anything different if they're just picking someone
from the LDP pot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
