<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RBI dearth starts with Weiss
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ The Braves No. 3 and 4 hitters go into the two-game
Mets series with just two RBIs in the second half. Before anyone
indicts Chipper Jones and Andres Galarraga for the three losses in
Florida, consider this:
</P>
<P>
   Lead-off hitter Walt Weiss is 4-for-32 this month, and his
average (.295) just dipped below .300 for the first time this
season. No. 2 hitter Keith Lockhart went 1-for-10 against the
Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   That means RBIs become harder to generate with no one on base.
Jones' two RBIs came on solo home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves scored only 13 runs in four games against Florida.
Houston is the only club to hold down the Braves like that in a
four-game series. The Astros limited Atlanta to 10 runs on May
15-18. Rarely is the Astros' pitching staff mistaken for Florida's.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you say? Talk them out of not hitting?'' manager Bobby
Cox said. ``You have to have some luck. Look at Lockhart. The first
night (last Thursday), he has three balls right on the button and
didn't get any hits. All line drives.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said he is not considering changes in the order, although
his club is getting a first glimpse of what can happen when Weiss
doesn't get on base. Even after hitting .280 in June and getting
through his family crisis with his son, Brody, Weiss still took a
.323 average into July. But he was hitless against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two games, I've felt real good at the plate and I
didn't get anything either game,'' said Weiss, who had two hits in
the All-Star game. ``But that's the way it goes sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Charting Chipper
</P>
<P>
   Jones reached 23 home runs on Sunday in his 348th at-bat of the
season. He needed all of his 597 at-bats in 1997 to reach 23. He
currently is projected to reach 40. His career-high is 30, which he
hit in 1996. With five homers in nine games this month, Jones
trails club leader Galarraga by three.
</P>
<P>
   Tending the fields
</P>
<P>
   It is going to take weeks before New York's outfield situation
plays out. For now, converted catcher Todd Hundley is being given
top priority in left field because his power gives clean-up hitter
Mike Piazza the best protection in the order. That leaves Butch
Huskey and Bernard Gilkey to share right field. Gilkey has started
in right field five times in his career. Huskey is a converted
infielder the Mets switched to outfield in order to get him more
playing time. Both are right-handed, both ideally are No. 5 hitters
and who starts tonight against the Braves is anyone guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that you've got four players who have been around the
game makes it easier,'' said Gilkey. ``We just want to win. I know
people don't want to hear that. They want to get on the radio and
just talk their heads off.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
