<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR-COX     07-13 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood sitting on 10 wins
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kevin Millwood won't be the Braves' starter tonight,
even though it's his turn to pitch. In most cities, any man who
wins 10 times before the All-Star break can call his own tune.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood instead sits in the bullpen and waits for a kinder
calendar. John Smoltz opens a two-game series tonight with the New
York Mets, and Millwood, who has made one start in the last 14
games, parks the cars, scrubs the pots and waits for the phone to
ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the season started, I told myself this was something I
was going to have to do and have to do it all year long,'' he said.
``It's not like I wasn't ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox used his underemployed fifth starter in his first
relief appearance of the season Sunday at Florida, and with two
more scoreless innings, Millwood pushed his total to 10 innings
without allowing a run. But Cox is forced by Monday's off day to
pass Millwood by for the fourth time this season to keep the rest
of the rotation on a five-day work program. Millwood has pitched 14
2/3 innings since June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had to do it, so I have no clue what it's like,''
said Smoltz, who is 2-1 in four starts since last coming off the
disabled list. ``But you need to have patience and know in time
that it's not going to be like this. In thinking with him, it sure
beats the alternative in my mind. You get to learn from the best.
Although you might not get to pitch as much, I think it's going to
prolong his career, personally, with all the knowledge he gains and
knowing what it's like to win at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my first time I've ever come out of the bullpen,''
Millwood said. ``It won't be the last. Whatever they want me to do,
I guess that's part of my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood is one of eight National League pitchers with 10 or
more victories. He knows what separates him from more steady work.
Four times this year, he has been hit for five or more runs. Five
times in 16 starts, he hasn't lasted into the sixth inning. At
first, he found the heart of the plate instead of the corners. Then
his change-up, his newest pitch learned from Greg Maddux, went
haywire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my change-up just about where I want it now,''
Millwood said. ``All my pitches are fine. I just want to be a
little more consistent with them. And I think that's what separates
me from the other four starters.''
</P>
<P>
   And from starting tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
