<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HEAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT WAVE KILLS 15 IN DALLAS AREA SINCE JUNE 1 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The blistering heat that has wrapped itself around
north Texas for the past six weeks loosened its grip slightly
Monday, but the death toll continued to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 1, the Dallas County Medical Examiner's office has
attributed 15 deaths to the heat wave, eight of them in the past
two days. Seven additional deaths are being investigated and
autopsies may show they also were heat-related.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the victims have been elderly and lived in homes with no
air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't pretty,'' said an investigator for the medical
examiner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures at Dallas-Fort Worth Airport reached 110 Sunday,
the third-hottest day on record. Fort Worth's Meacham Field
reported 112 degrees Sunday, but a city health department
spokeswoman said there have been no confirmed heat-related deaths
there.
</P>
<P>
   The north Texas weather is beginning to rival the summer of
1980, when Dallas recorded 69 days _ 42 of them consecutive _ with
temperatures of 100 degrees or above. The high that summer was 113
degrees, reached June 26.
</P>
<P>
   So far this summer, there have been 21 100-degree days, and no
end is in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's high at DFW was 101 degrees, and the forecast called
for more of the same throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff House, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service in
Fort Worth, said Monday's respite was the result of a dissipating
high-pressure ridge that had been parked over Texas. As that system
shifted to the west, temperatures in north Texas fell, but only
enough to provide moderate relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a weird summer,'' said Teresa Rehfeld, who has
worked the past five years for America Ice Co. in Dallas. ``We're
going nonstop, 24 hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals have increased their ice stocks to treat hyperthermia
victims, but ice suppliers have also seen a surge in demand from
individuals. Deliveries of 800 to 1,000 pounds to cool residential
swimming pools is not uncommon when temperatures linger in three
digits, but Rehfeld said this year's weather has pushed some
customers a step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people try to buy one or two tons of snowcone ice so
they can have snowball fights,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Dallas residents are combating the heat simply by
staying indoors under the air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Schein, a spokesman for TU electric, said the record for
usage, 208 million kilowatts, was actually set last Tuesday, when
the temperatures only reached 105 degrees. Because the 110-degree
mark was reached on a Sunday, when many businesses are closed, the
demand that day was 19.7 million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
   Water consumption in Dallas hit a record 664 million gallons
Saturday but declined Sunday to 650 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths that have been attributed to the heat, according to
the medical examiner's office, follow the typical pattern. Five of
the 15 victims were older than 80 and all but two were older than
50.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Monday's victims, an 88-year-old woman and an 83-year-old
man, were found in overheated residences. The woman's home had air
conditioning, but it was turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the victims were found outside, where they apparently
had been engaged in strenuous activities. The season's first heat
death was Jason Stogsdill, a 23-year-old Arlington man, who died of
hyperthermia June 1 while riding a bicycle in Cedar Hill State
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Gonzales, 83, was found dead July 10 after he had walked
about 100 yards from his van, which was crippled by two flat tires.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
