u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      07-13 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ SETS RECORD ON GAINS FROM TECHNOLOGY ISSUES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHARON R. KING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A brighter earnings outlook for several leading
technology companies propelled the technology-laden Nasdaq
composite index to its fourth consecutive new high Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the gains among technology issues, stocks were mixed,
as investors pondered how the unexpected resignation of Japan's
prime minister would affect American companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite rose 22.49 points, to 1,965.53, led by
gains among some of its bellwether issues such as Microsoft, Intel
and Dell Computer.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in the index reflected renewed enthusiasm by investors
for computer-related issues, which have largely been the
torchbearers of this year's bull market. Many investors are now
betting that earnings and sales of these companies _ which have
taken a hit this year, in part due to slowing demand from Asia _
will rebound in the second half of 1998, as a worldwide glut of
personal computers abates. Once that happens, personal computer
manufacturers like Dell and Compaq will increase production and
purchases of computer chips, improving the lot of chip makers like
Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Intel rose 2|, to 82], on expectations that sales for
the world's largest semiconductor maker will soon improve. While
Intel is expected to report weak second-quarter earnings later this
week, investors are optimistic the company will signal a sales
improvement in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft gained 4], to 117 9/16, on optimism it would report
better-than-expected fiscal fourth-quarter earnings Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 9.53 points, to 9,096.21.
General Motors, Exxon, Sears, Roebuck and Procter &AMP; Gamble were the
leading decliners among the blue chips.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index inched up 0.86 points, to
1,165.19, just 1.18 points shy of its July 8 record close.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, Japan's benchmark Nikkei index rose 1.68 percent, but
most equity markets were lower. The prime minister of Japan,
Ryutaro Hashimoto resigned, accepting responsibility for the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party's dismal showing in weekend elections.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the news, the dollar fell against the Japanese yen
Monday and Treasury bond prices dropped, suffering their largest
declines in more than a month. The retreat indicated that the
strong gains among the dollar and bonds recently, much of which was
attributed to safe-haven buying by foreign investors, may end.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, analysts offered mixed views of how domestic stock
markets will fare as a result of the latest Japanese development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just breathing a sigh of relief that they got off the
ground,'' said Peter Canelo, a U.S. investment strategist at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. ``I wasn't expecting a resignation, but that's
even better. It's an even stronger signal that they're going to do
something right.''
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts remain skeptical that the resignation signals
that the Japanese government is ready to take quick action and
implement major economic reforms to pull the economy out of
recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors around the world are looking for concrete steps,''
said Douglas Cliggott, United States equity strategist at J.P.
Morgan Securities in New York. ``There've been a lot of false
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's change. I think people are hoping there will be change
in the right direction, but I don't know if there's anything to
support'' that conclusion, Cliggott added.
</P>
<P>
   While technology shares led the market higher Monday, declines
among issues like Applied Materials indicated that aside from
global economic news, quarterly corporate earnings reports are
still a focus.
</P>
<P>
   Applied Materials closed at 28 9/16, down 15/16. Shares declined
after the computer chip equipment manufacturer warned that fiscal
third-quarter earnings would fall below analysts' forecasts,
weakened by order delays and spending cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the stock really didn't cascade'' the way other shares
have done after forecasting earnings disappointments, said Anthony
Conroy, a managing director for Bankers Trust Global Investment
Management. He attributed the stock's limited slide to investors'
belief that ``we're close to a bottom'' and the sector is ready to
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
