A3088 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUERTO-RICO14-COX     07-13 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTO-RICO14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PUERTO RICO TARGETS GOP IN QUEST FOR REFERENDUM
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It comes as no surprise that Puerto Rico would wage
a multimillion-dollar lobbying campaign to push for congressional
backing of a vote on its political status.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing between statehood, becoming an independent country or
remaining a U.S. commonwealth has been at the top of the island's
legislative agenda for the better part of the last century.
</P>
<P>
   What is so unusual about Puerto Rico's quest these days is where
the island is getting its support: from the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., has supported allowing
Puerto Ricans the right to vote on statehood, a stand that recently
drew cheers at a speaking engagement in Dallas where the speaker
was reaching out to Hispanic voters. And other key Senate
Republicans are backing the measure as hearings start Tuesday in
the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are a potential voting pool of 3.8 million voters,
which would translate to as many as seven House seats and two
Senate seats if Puerto Rico became the 51st state.
</P>
<P>
   And contrary to the commonly held belief that most of those
seats would be held by Democrats, Puerto Rican officials say the
Democrats should not be so confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assumption that Puerto Rico is a liberal Democratic
community is wrong,'' said Xavier Romeu, executive director and
general counsel for the Puerto Rico Federal Affairs Administration
in Washington. ``Everyone thinks that, but it is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Puerto Rico's political agenda echoes the GOP agenda,
Romeu said. For example, Puerto Ricans are largely against
abortion, they support school vouchers, they mandate a five-minute
reflection or ``prayer time'' at the start of each school day, and
they want to reduce the capital gains tax to spur economic
development, Romeu said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the speaker (Gingrich) is to be commended for reaching
out,'' Romeu said. ``He realizes that the Republican Party will be
the minority party unless they reach out to Hispanics.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is just what the Republican Party wants to
hear. The party has been actively courting Hispanic and other
minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been voting Democratic; that's a habit we'd like to
break,'' said Tim Fitzpatrick, deputy press secretary at the
Republican National Committee. ``On a lot of issues we are closely
aligned with Hispanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the Democrats concerned about the GOP edging in on the
Hispanic voting pool by supporting popular Hispanic issues such as
granting Puerto Rico the right to vote on its political status?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supporting any type of initiative that the Puerto Rican
population would like to take,'' said Lina Garcia, deputy press
secretary at the Democratic National Committee. ``I don't think the
Republicans are genuinely trying to reach out to help Hispanics. I
think the record shows that the Democratic Party is much stronger
on issues that matter to the Hispanic community.''
</P>
<P>
   The referendum issue is expected to be a thorny one as it moves
to the Senate chamber, closely mirroring the struggle in the House,
where the measure barely passed by a 209-208 vote.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this is a test of both political parties, said
Romeu.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Democrats are not careful, they will lose our vote,''
Romeu said. ``The Republicans also stand to lose if they validate
the perception in the community at large that the Republican Party
is anti-Hispanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
