<HEADER>
A3091 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLD-CUP-HNS &LR;      07-13 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-CUP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
State of euphoria 
envelops France
<TEXT>
<P>
   World Cup champs feel vindicated
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ The street sweepers went rumbling through Paris on Monday
morning, up the avenues and down the boulevards, like they do every
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But business was good this time. Very good. Better than ever, in
fact.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's jubilant World Cup championship celebration in
France left behind piles of champagne bottles, streamers and
confetti. The streets were stained with the remnants of red, white
and Les Bleus face paint and shoe polish.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as the aftermath of the party was washed and cleaned
away nice and neatly, the memories of France's thrilling 3-0 World
Cup victory over Brazil likely never will be swept away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after saying it 10 times, we can't believe it _ we're
world champions,'' France forward Christophe Dugarry said. ``We
could have won that game 5-0 or 6-0. We played fantastic football.
It's incredible to believe that we put on that kind of show.''
</P>
<P>
   It was indeed quite a show and definitely worthy of lifting the
Cup. It led to more than 1 million people flooding the Paris
streets in the kind of all-night celebration not seen in France
since the Liberation and the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   And for this marvelous team, liberation definitely was the key
word to the World Cup victory. So many players, along with coach
Aime Jacquet, felt liberated, vindicated or finally fulfilled with
the victory. France is an also-ran no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved that French teams can play good football and win
championships,'' midfielder Emmanuel Petit said. ``That's something
that we have wanted to prove as a nation for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is still mixed up in my head. It all feels unreal.
The best thing is that we have brought pleasure to the French
people, and that is something that they have deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, French soccer fans felt betrayed by the national
team when it was eliminated from USA '94 on the final day of
qualifying. Four years before that, France also failed to qualify
despite being a world-ranked contender.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the disappointment of 1986, when a Michel
Platini-led French team eliminated Brazil in the quarterfinals but
then stumbled in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our dreams have come true, finally,'' France's Alain
Boghossian said. ``We really deserved this victory and to finally
win the Cup. We won this for everyone in France, especially the
supporters and the players before. We felt enormous pressure, but
now we've got good times.''
</P>
<P>
   Individual demons seemed to vanish in the revelry, too.
</P>
<P>
   For Jacquet, who was harshly criticized throughout qualification
and early Cup games, the relief was clear in his face after
Sunday's game. During his official news conference after the
victory, Jacquet scolded certain French publications for not
believing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of France saw the kind of team we were and how we play,''
Jacquet said. ``The people judged for themselves, and they saw the
best team in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Jacquet did, in fact, often struggle trying to find
offense in this team, the defense proved to be among the toughest
in World Cup history. And the three goals in the final against
Brazil proved offense ultimately was no big problem, either.
</P>
<P>
   The camaraderie and close-knit nature of this team was evident,
too, especially after defender and popular star Laurent Blanc was
red-carded in the semifinal against Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   The popular opinion was that Brazil would be able to slice
through a French defense that didn't have Blanc. Instead, the team
rallied around replacement Frank Leboeuf, and Blanc was an
inspiration on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``After each victory, the atmosphere in the dressing room was
wonderful with this team,'' Petit said. ``This team possessed a
wonderful joie de vivre and a will to win as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bixente Lizarazu: ``We were rewarded for several years of
working together and months of preparation together for this
tournament. It's incredible how this team came together. It was a
destiny. We played the perfect game. We're world champions. It
sounds so strange to say that.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's true. Just ask the street sweepers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
