<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3092 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-1     07-13 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN FINANCE INQUIRY SAID TO BE MAKING SCANT PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-INDICT) 
(mk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Twenty-one months after accusations of illegal fund
raising arose from President Clinton's re-election campaign, law
enforcement officials concede they have no big cases to show for
their effort and express doubts that they will obtain evidence to
warrant prosecution of senior White House or Democratic Party
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say they are increasingly pessimistic that they will
ever answer questions at the heart of the inquiry; that is, whether
there was a plot by the Chinese military behind contributions to
the Democratic Party that may have been intended to help Beijing
gain easier access to American space technology, and whether any
Democratic Party or White House officials knew of the Chinese
effort. Thus far investigators have been stymied in their efforts
to obtain the cooperation of witnesses in China.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there are still people being investigated, and
conceivably a witness with crucial evidence could decide to
cooperate, breaking open the investigation. And it is even
conceivable that an independent counsel could be named to
investigate top officials. But the cases brought so far by the
Justice Department's campaign-finance unit have centered on
relatively low-level fund-raisers charged with illegally disguising
overseas contributions through straw donors.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment Monday of the Thai businesswoman Pauline
Kanchanalak and her sister-in-law brings to eight the number of
people who have been charged, and officials expect more will be
charged with similar crimes in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials said that despite hundreds of subpoenas and
thousands of hours of grand jury testimony, they have no evidence
that White House officials, their aides or Democratic Party leaders
broke the law, even though some investigators, from the inquiry's
early days, have sought evidence that higher-ups knew or encouraged
the acceptance of illegal contributions. Now, whether such cases
will be brought depends on the willingness of the fund-raisers to
plead guilty and testify against their superiors, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The evidentiary value of that cooperation could prove only
marginally useful. So far, only one defendant, the California
businessman Johnny Chung, has cooperated with authorities. Although
he provided what was apparently a link between the Chinese military
and the Democratic Party, the officials said, it remained uncertain
whether his information would implicate any officials at the
Democratic National Committee or in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Justice Department officials are prepared to concede
that their investigative leads are drying up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This task force is on a roll with four new charges in the last
six days,'' said Bert Brandenburg, a spokesman for the Justice
Department, referring to tax charges brought last week against the
California fund-raiser Maria Hsia and fund-raising charges against
Howard Glicken of Miami, as well as the indictments Monday of Ms.
Kanchanalak and her sister-in-law, Duangnet Georgie Kronenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``White-collar cases take longer than any other types of
cases,'' Brandenburg said. ``But through aggressive investigation
and prosecution, we have brought charges in mere months that
usually take years to bring. This continues to be the department's
largest criminal investigation, with more than 120 task-force
members, offices on two coasts and resources drawn from around the
country. And we are not done yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Republicans pass scathing judgment on the inquiry
and continue to demand the appointment of an independent
prosecutor, saying that the Justice Department, under Attorney
General Janet Reno, will never be able to credibly investigate the
fund-raising practices of the president's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people running this thing are people of
integrity,'' said Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., who was chairman of
the Senate hearings on campaign finance abuses. ``But they refuse
to acknowledge the hopelessly conflicted situation they are in. If
they continue to travel down this road and wind up where it looks
like they are headed, it's going to look a lot like a cover-up.''
</P>
<P>
   A telling measure of the low fortunes of the campaign-finance
inquiry was illustrated after its top prosecutor, Charles Labella,
announced in May that he would resign to become the acting U.S.
attorney in San Diego. In trying to fill Labella's job, Reno found
few prosecutors willing to take on the challenge of leading the
inquiry already under way.
</P>
<P>
   Under different circumstances, such an assignment might be
considered a high-profile, career-making plum. But at least two
prominent federal prosecutors refused the offer. ``It's a loser,''
one prosecutor said. ``And it's going nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno picked David Vicinanzo, an assistant U.S. attorney from New
Hampshire, to take command of an inquiry that critics insisted was
never given the top priority or the prosecutorial mandate that it
deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigation can only be described as a total disaster,''
said Michael Madigan, the former chief counsel to the Senate
committee that investigated campaign-finance abuses. He is now a
partner at Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld, the Washington law
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Madigan and leading congressional Republicans said that
prosecutors have only themselves to blame. They said members of the
campaign finance team had moved lethargically, failed to dig for
evidence against powerful Democrats and concentrated mainly on
lower-echelon fund-raisers like Ms. Hsia, Chung and Yah Lin Trie.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hsia and Trie have pleaded not guilty to the charges against
them and are scheduled to go on trial this fall. Chung pleaded
guilty in March to campaign-related bank and tax fraud. He is the
first defendant to cooperate with authorities; he is scheduled to
be sentenced later this year.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Republicans complained that the most vivid
example of the task force's failure was prosecutors' not taking
action against John Huang, the former Commerce Department official
and Democratic fund-raiser. He raised $1.6 million in contributions
that the Democratic Party later returned after questions were
raised about the origins of the money.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said that investigators were actively
reviewing Huang's activities, including fund-raising solicitations
made while he was an official at the Commerce Department and his
role in funneling overseas contributions to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Huang, who lives in California, has denied through his lawyers
any wrongdoing, but he refused to testify before Senate or House
committees by invoking the Fifth Amendment, the constitutional
guarantee against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the White House is stonewalling and you're having
hearings that are overtly partisan,'' Thompson said, ``it's
absolutely vital to have an aggressive prosecution going on
downtown. It was that way during Watergate. It was that way during
Iran-Contra. That was the big missing element we have seen in this
investigation. There was no pressure brought to bear on any of
these key people. So they either fled the country or refused to
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews last week, Justice Department and other law
enforcement officials said that the investigation's failure to meet
the early expectations and perceptions of ineptitude were the
result of several factors, including investigators' own missteps
and changes in the leadership of the campaign- finance unit.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry was first assigned to the Justice Department's
public integrity unit, which prosecutes official corruption. But
Reno, prodded by complaints from the FBI, brought in a fresh team
in October 1997, led by Labella, the federal prosecutor from San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Labella is planning to leave later this month to return to San
Diego and the U.S. attorney's office. James Desarno, the lead FBI
investigator assigned to the inquiry, was planning to accept a
promotion at his agency until the FBI director, Louis Freeh,
ordered him to remain in place indefinitely after news reports
about the move.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some prosecutors acknowledge that a battle-weariness has
slowed the pace of day-to-day operations, fed by the lack of
cooperative witnesses and the difficulty of conducting an inquiry
that must decipher the muddled and arcane laws involving campaign
finance. The House's campaign-finance investigation, led by Rep.
Dan Burton, R-Ind., has also been stymied by a lack of cooperation
from many of its 108 witnesses, who have either left the country,
refused to be interviewed or invoked the Fifth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials also acknowledged that the inquiry was
hamstrung by sporadic feuding within the Justice Department over
the investigation's direction.
</P>
<P>
   For example, FBI officials and investigators continue to openly
question Reno's refusal to seek an independent prosecutor to
examine the vast swirl of accusations. Reno's repeated refusals
have been used to attack her image as a fair and objective law
enforcement official. Some say her obstinacy has drained the
campaign-finance investigation of its credibility.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Reno will most likely face new questions about the
inquiry's status when she appears before the Senate Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
