A3095 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-IMMUNIZATION-BOS &LR;      07-13 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-IMMUNIZATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS TOPS LIST IN CHILD IMMUNIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. SANCHEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston and Massachusetts lead the country in immunizing
children against disease, a new report shows.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the city immunized 88 percent of children two years
of age or under, compared to the national average of 78 percent;
and the state inoculated 87 percent, according to a report
published by Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The report, called the National Immunization Survey, tracked
immunization rates for diphtheria, polio, measles, mumps, and
rubella.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we were tied with another locality,'' said Dr. Anita
Barry, director of communicable disease control for the Boston
Health Commission. ``This year we're just out ahead of the pack.''
The CDC tracks only large cities for its statistics.
</P>
<P>
   City officials credit the rankings to a tracking and recall
system in place since 1993 that helps disseminate recommendations
to health care professionals, aids in distributing vaccines to
where they are needed most, and coordinates the activities of
various groups such as community health centers, hospitals,
physicians, and schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some good partnerships throughout the city,'' Barry
said. ``And people are very interested in the health of children.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, many of these activities have also expanded
throughout the state using the same federal funding source.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immunization is one of the most cost effective public health
things that we do,'' Barry said. ``For every dollar you spend in
immunity, you save $10 in subsequent health care costs that you
would incur from disease occurring.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the Bay State and Boston have come in near or at
the top in immunizing children. But a proposed 35 percent cut in
the federal budget for 1999 threatens the progress made here. The
result would be major program cuts, Barry said, and fewer
immunizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3096 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS &LR;      07-13 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
British layout 
taxing players, 
ball supplies
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SOUTHPORT, England _ Golfers got a blustery welcome to the 127th
Open Championship, with gusting winds, bouts of rain and chilly
temperatures making golf at Royal Birkdale Golf Club on Monday a
major challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure this suits anybody's game,'' said Tom Lehman. ``I
would not say the course is unplayable, but it is awfully
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Golfers who arrived early in Southport, hoping to get in some
extra practice time before the championship begins Thursday, ended
up spending much of Sunday and Monday searching for more than just
their games.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Sunday, I took my driver and the 5-iron and the putter with
six golf balls,'' Lehman said. ``By the time I got to the eighth
tee, I was out of golf balls. It was blowing 45 mph. On the second
hole, which was 410 yards, I hit two drivers and didn't get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to keep going. But it was my first time seeing the
course, and I did not know where to aim. With the wind blowing, I
ended up hitting it everywhere. Somebody in one of the galleries is
going to find six brand-new Titleists with my mark on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather forecasters said the gusts were as strong as 55 mph at
times Sunday. The wind was almost as bad Monday, gusting to 30 to
35 mph and the temperature hovering in the low 60s.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to leave U.S. Open champion Lee Janzen longing for
the comforts of the treacherous greens at the Olympic Club in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get some occasionally bad weather, but we do not play on
golf courses like this with this kind of bad weather,'' Janzen
said. ``It is extremely tough out there. I cannot think of a time
I've lost more golf balls without hitting the water than I have in
the last two days.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Janzen lost five Sunday. He managed to hold on
to most of them Monday but not without a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've only made two birdies in two rounds of golf, and
that did not come until the 17th hole today,'' Janzen said. ``The
downwind holes, it's tough to hit the ball straight. If you do, it
is tough to keep the right distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot see anybody shooting under par for four days if it
stays like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the golfers in the Open Championship, Mother
Nature is expected to lighten up a little bit. The extended outlook
was calling for warmer temperatures and sunny skies for the next
few days at least. And a high-pressure system moving out of the
area is likely to calm the wind as well.
</P>
<P>
   That was good news for everyone, including those golfers much
more accustomed to such nasty conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see a little bit of a breeze, but I don't call
that a breeze out here, I don't think,'' Ernie Els said. ``Today, I
think I shot 74 or 75. And I would say 72 would have been a really
good score. It is really blowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those golfers trying to qualify for the British Open at one
of four open qualifying sites had their share of problems with the
wind. Korean Young Woo Nam, playing at West Lancashire, was forced
to quit in the second round when he lost his last golf ball on the
18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only had four this morning in the bag, and at 18, I could
not find the last one,'' Nam said.
</P>
<P>
   Nam was 11-over on the round and 25-over for the two days at the
time after an 86 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the expected improvement in weather, it is likely that
this week's contest at Royal Birkdale will be a difficult one.
Anyone having trouble hitting it straight might as well not tee it
up at all, and putting will be at a premium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the best players will rise to the top,'' Lehman said.
``When it is blowing hard, you just have to hit the ball solid, and
that is the end of the story. If you do not hit it solid, you have
no chance whatsoever of winning, I don't care how good you play.
The best ball-strikers definitely have an advantage at Birkdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best players will come to the top for sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
