<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3103 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMF-ART-2TAKES     07-13 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S FINANCIAL CRISIS EASED BY NEW LOAN AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-U.S.) 
(ART ADV.: a graphic giving details of the IMF loan to Russia is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling 212 556-4204.) 
(HLW) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian government and international lenders
concluded a landmark agreement on Monday aimed at easing Russia's
financial crisis and restoring confidence in its economy.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would provide $17.1 billion in additional loans
over the next two years. About $12.6 billion would be delivered
this year and another $4.5 billion would be available in 1999.
Combined with existing international assistance, the new pact would
bring total lending to Russia to $22.6 billion over this year and
next.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of the new money will be lent by the
International Monetary Fund, which came under pressure from the
Clinton administration to increase the amount of money it was
willing to loan to Russia and to quickly wrap up negotiations that
had dragged on for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   To finance the Russian bailout, the United States agreed to loan
the fund $2.1 billion. Other countries making loans include Japan,
Germany, France and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Anatoly Chubais, the lead Russian negotiator, described the
round-the-clock talks as the most difficult ever held between the
Yeltsin government and the IMF. ``The decisions taken today signify
a restoration of faith in Russia's ability to overcome its
difficulties,'' Chubais said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the process -- and the endless drama here -- is far
from over. Russia still has to take a number of important steps
before any of the money will be distributed. On Wednesday and
Thursday, the Russian government will attempt a crucial hurdle when
the lower house of Parliament is expected to vote in extraordinary
session on the Kremlin's plan for ending the financial crisis. That
plan reflects several demands made by the monetary fund as
conditions for further loans.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for lower tax rates and laws to stimulate
investment as well as a new law on budgeting procedures, all
considered vital by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   John Odling-Smee, the chief negotiator for the fund, said that
the fund would decide on July 20 whether to start distributing its
new loan to Russia. He added that the actions of the Parliament
would heavily influence the IMF's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Parliament has already balked at measures to reform the
personal income tax and to change procedures for determining
value-added taxes. If the legislature also rejects additional
proposals, Yeltsin can impose some of his measures by decree. But
that could plunge the nation into a legal and political quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, Monday's announcement provided a badly needed boost to
Russia's financial markets, which has been waiting for the IMF to
throw its support behind the Russians. Russia's stock market rose
10 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, Russia suffered from the general unease
Western investors had over emerging markets following the economic
turmoil in Asia. But Russia has also been vulnerable to a global
currency crisis because it depends on foreign investors to finance
so much of its deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the IMF said that new loans were not needed. It
wanted to husband its limited resources and insisted that the
Kremlin could weather the financial storm by taking its own
corrective measures.
</P>
<P>
   But as interest rates on Russian Treasury bills soared, reaching
120 percent recently, and Russia's bond markets weakened, investors
began to worry about the ruble and whether the government would be
able to avoid a devaluation of the currency as a means to lower
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   With Central Bank reserves of dollars and other foreign
currencies at about $15 billion, and foreign investors owning $20
billion in treasury bills, there was a widespread concern among
investors that an investor panic might drain Russia's slender cash
reserve. Of the $15 billion, $5 billion of that is in gold, which
cannot readily be spent.
</P>
<P>
   The worry was that a foreign panic might set off a stampede in
the treasury bill market in which investors would convert their
rubles into dollars. Without adequate reserves, the Central Bank
would be unable to support the value of the ruble by purchasing it
in the currency markets, and a devaluation might soon follow.
</P>
<P>
   The concern was that a devaluation of the ruble would not only
lead to a round of inflation but might also shake the nation's
political establishment. Yeltsin has even gone so far as suggest
that ``extremists'' might attempt to launch a coup.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's financial markets shuddered in May and June, the IMF
began to consider additional financing. IMF officials initially
proposed only $5.6 billion in new loans. But after President
Clinton returned from his trip to China, the United States began to
focus on Russia's economy with new intensity.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration considers Sergei Kiriyenko, the
Russian prime minister, and his team of aides the most
reform-minded government Russia has had in years.
</P>
<P>
   American officials argued that assistance had to be large enough
to impress the world's financial markets and give Kiriyenko the
breathing space he needed to try to turn the country's economy
around.
</P>
<P>
   The American pressure bore fruit last weekend when the IMF
doubled its financial package and sought to wrap up the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   To come up with the additional funds, the IMF was forced to use
the General Arrangements to Borrow, a little-used loan fund
established in 1962 to stabilize the world monetary system.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with the lure of additional funds, the monetary fund
and Russia had to work hard to overcome their differences.
</P>
<P>
   A major issue in the talks, for example, has been the pace at
which Russia should cut its budget deficit. The two sides now agree
that the deficit should be reduced to 2.8 percent of Russia's
economy in 1999 from about 5 percent currently, a huge step that
will require raising billions of dollars in new revenue.
</P>
<P>
   To reasure investors, Chubais emphasized on Monday that Russia
will receive $22.6 billion in loans during the last half of 1998
and in 1999. That figure, however, combined old loans that were
worked out before the financial crisis and the new rescue package.
</P>
<P>
   The actual amount of new financing is somewhat less, though
still substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Russia will receive $12.6 in additional financing during the
rest of 1998. Those loans include $11.2 billion from the IMF, $800
million by the World Bank, and $600 million lent from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Some $2.2 billion in previously agreed IMF and World Bank loans
is also to be disbursed, bringing the total for this year to $14.8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Russia will receive $7.8 billion in new aid,
including $4.5 in new loans and $3.3 in previously agreed
financing.
</P>
<P>
   There may be even more loans in the future, as the fund
indicated it is willing to negotiate a further three year loan if
the government stays on the reform track. That would provide an
additional $2.6 billion a year in new financing.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a loan package, Russia agreed to stop issuing short-term
treasury bills, which have been sold at high interest rates in
auctions that have occurred every week or 10 days. Instead, it will
now offer investors an opportunity to convert their ruble
denominated treasury bills into longer-term dollar denominated
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone applauded the new loans.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom, the huge natural gas monopoly, complained about
provisions that would require it to make its transport pipeline
system available to other gas producers. The World Bank insisted
that the pipeline be opened to limit Gazprom's dominance and
introduce more competition.
</P>
<P>
   While the the Russian government was breathing a sigh of relief,
the toughest part lies ahead. The Yeltsin government has to win
parliamentary approval of its anti-crisis take-other measures to
qualify for the new loans. Then it has to try to stay the course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
