</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-GOALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP TO FOCUS ON ATTACKS ON AFFIRMATIVE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NAACP President Kweisi Mfume conceded Monday that the
organization was caught flat-footed during last year's fight over
Proposition 209, the ballot measure approved by California voters
to end state affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   But now the group has shifted into overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   At the NAACP's 89th annual convention, its leaders have
strenuously defended affirmative action and belittled its critics,
and have pledged to defeat any effort to curtail it in Washington
state, which looms this fall as the latest battleground for a
California-style initiative.
</P>
<P>
   And in a shift in strategy, the leadership of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People has also
ratcheted up its rhetoric against Supreme Court justices who oppose
affirmative action _ seeking to challenge their decisions in the
court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proposition 209 got past us. We are absolutely certain nothing
will get past us again,'' Mfume told reporters after a hard-hitting
speech to the convention in which he called the justices
``hyprocrites'' for making decisions on affirmative action when, he
said, they have never promoted diversity among their own office
staff.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a single native America among the 397 law clerks who
work for Supreme Court justices and only seven are of African
ancestry, Mfume said. ``You have to hunt to find any'' minority law
clerks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In major back-to-back speeches over the last two days, Mfume and
board chairman Julian Bond have singled out Supreme Court justices
for harsh criticism. They have sought to make the case that the
NAACP is still relevant because discrimination remains rampant in
America and that ultimately, as in years gone by, the battle will
be fought in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night Bond referred to Clarence Thomas, the only black
Supreme Court justice and a conservative, as ``affirmative action's
poster child.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even he says that affirmative action makes black people feel
bad,'' Bond said. ``But Thomas may be right. Ever since he got his
most recent affirmative action job, he has been in a foul and nasty
mood,'' he said. The remark moved the more than 3,500 delegates to
a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Mfume singled out Justice Antonin Scalia for criticism
saying he has never found it in his ``heart of hearts to employ one
black person'' while on the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Mfume defended the name-calling to reporters, saying
it was necessary to ``use the law of reason and the law of shame,''
to convince the court to change its ways.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington state conservative activists, bolstered by the
success of the California effort, are pushihg Initiative 200, which
would curtail if not end most affirmative action programs. The
NAACP has set aside $50,000 to help to defeat the measure.
Officials hope to double that amount by the time the association's
board of directors holds its quarterly meeting in Seattle in
October. It says the donation has spurred other organizations to
become active as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bond has twice visited Washington state to drum up opposition to
the measure, and Mfume is planning a visit. The NAACP plans to use
the money to buy ads on cable television and erect billboards. They
are also planning marches and demonstrations to try to convince
voters not to approve the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The measure has galvanized NAACP officials, but they also stress
other priorities. Among them: urging the Census Bureau to get an
accurate count of minorities, opposing school tuition vouchers, and
pushing for a proportionate share of any funds distributed from a
national tobacco settlement to be spent on groups that promote
minority health.
</P>
<P>
   But along with crafting their agenda, NAACP officials have also
sought to spotlight the persistent presence of racial
discrimination in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discrimination is not an article of the past, it is an article
of the present,'' Mfume said. ``People of African ancestry in this
country, unless anyone forgets it, are not going to silently sit by
and let these years of progress be taken away without a fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
