<HEADER>
A3109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-NYT &LR;      07-13 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP OFFICIAL CRITICIZES SUPREME COURT ON AFFIRMATIVE ACTION
DECISIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The nation's oldest civil rights organization stood
firmly behind affirmative action on Monday, publicly scorning
compromise on the issue and attacking its critics, including the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of accommodation was in short supply in speeches at the
convention of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, and speakers defended granting special breaks for
minorities in employment, college admission and government
contracting.
</P>
<P>
   Kweisi Mfume, the organization's president and chief executive
officer, castigated the justices on Monday for limiting the
government's ability to run affirmative action programs, and for
the court's own lack of minority law clerks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court finds itself as hypocrites, particularly on
diversity and affirmative action issues,'' Mfume said. He added
that ``this Supreme Court ought to be ashamed of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong convention here marks the first gathering of the
NAACP since it selected veteran civil rights advocate Julian Bond
as chairman of the board of directors in February. Under the new
leadership team of Bond and Mfume, who was elected to his post in
1996, the internal squabbling that has marked the organization in
recent years appears to have been muted and its financial problems
lessened. As a result, the group appears poised to direct its
energies toward political and legal fights.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action is a particular battleground. Programs that
grant preferences to minorities have been under intense legal and
political scrutiny. Washington state, for example, will hold a
referendum in November on whether to outlaw government programs
that extend preferences based on race or sex. Voters in Houston
defeated a similar ballot initiative last November.
</P>
<P>
   The enrollment of minorities in the top schools in the
University of California system has dropped sharply in the wake of
passage of a similar ballot initiative in the state in 1996. And in
recent months, the Clinton administration, responding to Supreme
Court rulings, has scaled back the affirmative action efforts in
federal contracting.
</P>
<P>
   In this climate, affirmative action has dominated the first days
of this year's convention. And, in public speeches, NAACP officials
have struck a defiant tone when it comes to support for programs,
even those that the courts have found to be illegal or
constitutionally suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of mealy-mouthed statements about
affirmative action,'' Bill Campbell, Atlanta's mayor, told the
delegates Sunday night. ``I want you to know I'm here for
affirmative action. I'm for quotas. I'm for set-asides. I'm for
whatever gets us back to where we ought to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Mfume suggested that his organization would be willing to try to
work out some compromises on affirmative action, and that some
programs should be examined closely to insure that the benefits do
not go to people who do not deserve them. But he also insisted that
black civil rights organizations be consulted when changes in
policy are made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to sit down and have discussion and debate,''
he said. ``We are prepared to hear the other side. We're prepared
to make our case. We're prepared to negotiate. But we are not
prepared to have policy imposed upon us, when we have no input into
that policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mfume was critical, however, of a number of federal agencies,
specifically the Defense Department, for what he said was ``going
too far'' in scaling back their affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   But he saved his harshest criticism for the Supreme Court, which
in recent years has imposed strict constitutional tests on when a
program that gives special aid to minorities or women can be
legally justified.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a report by USA TODAY in March that noted the court had
only seven black law clerks among the 394 appointed since 1971,
Mfume said the justices were not getting enough diverse opinions
when they deal with affirmative action issues.
</P>
<P>
   Out of all the law clerks ``who read the initial briefs, who
decide what goes forward and what goes back; who help to write
those decisions, who have the ear of those judges; who partake in
much of the process, seven are African-American,'' Mfume said. ``So
don't sit around, fellow justices, and tell us about affirmative
action and there is no need for it, until you practice it on your
own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
