</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-EDUCATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pierce wants NAACP to insist on higher educational standards
 &HT;    By Kimberly H. Byrd
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Go ahead, raise the educational standards for students
in public schools and watch black children rise to the occasion.
But make sure they have the resources necessary to excel.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Pierce, deputy assistant secretary of education for the
U.S. Department of Education's Office of Civil Rights, delivered
that message Monday to NAACP convention participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who think that when we push high standards,
that equity, fairness, will necessarily suffer and that is not
true,'' Pierce said. ``Too often when we receive complaints about
inappropriate use of tests _ when tests are designed for one
purpose and being used for another with an obvious disparate impact
upon minority students _ the only correction (taken by educators)
is to water down the tests, to lower the standards.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not necessary, he said. The key is to set high standards
and hold educators accountable. If they fail to produce, replace
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that sounds rather harsh, but we're losing too many
generations of our children not to take a serious look at the
process by which they're being educated,'' Pierce explained. ``Our
children should not be able to leave third grade and not read
independently. Our children should be able to master basic
mathematical skills by the end of eighth grade. At the same time,
we must make sure that the schools our children attend have the
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   By resources, he meant supplies, safe and clean buildings and
teachers instructing within their professions.
</P>
<P>
   As for schools that continually fall short of the mark, Edith
Bond of the American Federation of Teachers said closing and
restructuring them with a new educational focus is an option.
</P>
<P>
   But when discrimination issues are involved, Brian Kintisch of
the Center for Children and Education encouraged communities to
mobilize, get the facts straight and come up with a plan for
reforming bad policies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
