<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-SPOTLIGHT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students tackle tough question
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because the theme of this year's NAACP convention is ``Preparing
tomorrow's leaders today,'' The Atlanta Journal-Constitution asked
the national organization to identify college students considered
to be up-and-coming leaders. Some are regional youth
representatives to the national NAACP board; others are members of
the National Youth Work Committee, which consists of a youth
national board member, and a youth and adult representative from
each region; some were members or officers of local organizations.
The committee serves as a liaison between the youth and college
chapters and the national organization.
</P>
<P>
   Each was asked the question: How can you have an impact on the
civil rights movement as a student leader?
</P>
<P>
   Taj Brown, 19, Lock Haven University of Pennsylvania, Lock
Haven, Pa., sophomore:``I think that history reveals most
revolutionary movements are ignited with young people. An advocate
for civil rights is a proactive person. It is important for me to
be proactive... My responsibility/challenge would be to effectively
represent the young people of my region and at large when it comes
to top-level decision making in the NAACP. That is a challenge
because I think that all too often our parents or generations prior
tend to forget what it means to be a young person. If that is the
case, it is unfair for me to expect our seniors to effectively
advocate the youth cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Gaulden, 20, University of Colorado at Colorado Springs,
junior: ``I can help by raising awareness and by getting youths and
students to mobilize. Understanding that strength is in numbers
will get us far.''
</P>
<P>
   La'Keitha Daniels, 18, Clark Atlanta University, senior:``We are
seen as role models for the younger people. The youths coming up in
the organization see me as a leader. As a leader, I provide a venue
for other unheard youths across the nation. Every year I grow more
and more as I continue to learn the background and workings that
have sustained us as the oldest and strongest civil rights
organization. I can keep the struggle alive with the help of other
youth leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamont Ross, 19, University of Texas at Austin, junior: ``(I can
help) by helping to motivate other people. We need to lose the
apathy. We have a lot of sleepwalkers among us, and a wake-up call
is long overdue. I look at myself as an implementer and a motivator
to help other people 'get on the bus' as we drive toward the goal
of true political independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomeka Berry, 22, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill,
graduate student: ``(I can help) by being active and letting people
be informed about the issues that affect them. I can help by being
active in the struggle to assist with protests, boycotts and
marches.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Smith, 19, Morehouse College, junior: ``Being that the
struggle started in the youth-college division, we're the ones to
begin the revolution again. We know firsthand of where injustice is
going on. As youths, a fighting spirit is instilled in us so we can
continue. We're the ones able to march and fight the long battles.
We're the ones who will have to continue the battle. Our older
freedom fighters have done it and they're getting tired. The
youth-college division is training leaders for the future. We hold
our destiny in our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Tabari Baker, 19, Morehouse College, junior: ``I can get other
students to become involved in the NAACP and take a bigger stand in
things that are going on not just locally but throughout the state
of Georgia and nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
