<HEADER>
A3118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-COX     07-13 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM looks to conserve cash
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ General Motors Corp. stepped up its search for
ways to conserve cash after failing to settle two crippling strikes
in Michigan over the weekend as it had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Top-level talks in Flint foundered yesterday, largely over GM's
demand that the union agree not to strike elsewhere once the Flint
strikes ended. GM's top negotiator, Vice President Gerald Knechtel,
returned to Detroit and didn't meet with his UAW counterpart, Vice
President Richard Shoemaker, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With a two-week vacation shutdown over, GM resumed absorbing
losses of $80 million a day from the dispute, now in its sixth
week. GM today will report a strike-caused plunge in second-quarter
earnings and probably will use the occasion to restate its
determination to stand fast, an analyst said.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM needs to find a resolution that will enable the company to
improve its labor productivity to competitive levels and avoid the
union going on strike every three months,'' said Morgan Stanley
analyst Stephen Girsky, who predicted the strikes will last until
mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes have now idled 165,000 workers nationwide and nearly
8,000 GM workers in the Miami Valley. Those workers idled at local
plants include 3,900 at the Moraine truck assembly plant; 1,300 at
the Delphi Harrison Thermal Systems plant; 1,100 at the Kettering
suspension part plant; 550 at the Moraine engine plant; 500 at the
Vandalia air bag plant; and 420 at the Delphi Chassis parts plant
on Home Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Despite local layoffs, about 3,400 workers at two Dayton brake
plants went to work Monday. More than 1,000 brake plant workers on
Needmore Road and Wisconsin Boulevard were idled before the
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the future of the brake plants remain in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   UAW Local 696 in Dayton, which represents workers at the brake
plants, continued talks with GM officials Monday in hopes of
settling several issues that have split the company and union for
over two years. Like the Flint disputes, the Dayton talks center on
outsourcing issues, work rules and health and safety regulations.
</P>
<P>
   No progress was reported in the Dayton talks on Monday. UAW
officials have threatened to call a strike in Dayton after a
settlement in Flint, but the union has not served GM with a
five-day strike notice.
</P>
<P>
   GM shares fell 2 5/16 to 68 7/8, their biggest decline in more
than a month, reflecting investor disappointment in GM's failure to
reach a weekend settlement after raising expectations that it
would. The shares have dropped 8.7 percent since the strikes began,
while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index has risen 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest automaker is expected to cut benefits for
about 100,000 UAW members in the U.S. laid off because of the
walkouts, in an effort to spread the strike costs to the union. The
union, which maintains such a move is illegal, would pick up the
benefits from its $800 million strike fund.
</P>
<P>
   Knechtel also said the company would continue to push a
grievance it filed earlier alleging that the strike is illegal.
It's also considering whether to seek a court order forcing workers
back to the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
