<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. HOPES JAPAN CAN RESTORE CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: see related JAPAN-POLITICS, JAPAN-REACT) 
(HLW) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1995 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House on Monday urged Japan's next
government to move quickly to ``restore confidence in Japan's
financial system,'' even while administration officials said they
feared that political paralysis in Tokyo greatly complicated
efforts to ignite a recovery in Asia and ease pressure on other
countries, including Russia.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials on Monday spent little time mourning the
departure of Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, whose slowness to
act on economic reforms had been a continuing source of frustration
here.
</P>
<P>
   But several administration officials wondered aloud whether any
of Hashimoto's likely successors would be able to piece together a
coalition strong enough to bail out the Japanese banking system and
provide a sharp stimulus to the economy _ and to do so before the
deterioration in the Japanese currency does greater damage to the
world economy.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative, said in an
interview: ``One can hope that this vote will be seen by the new
administration in Japan as a definitive wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   But colleagues of hers in the administration said that it was
too early to determine whether Hashimoto's party would interpret
its electoral loss on Sunday as a signal to accelerate reforms or a
sign that it should be cautious about causing economic pain.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts on Japan say the election could stimulate action.
``Up to now, the main pressure to get the house in order was from
the U.S. and from the markets,'' said Michael Mochizuki, a senior
fellow at the Brookings Institution. ``That was big pressure. But
still, what you read from Japan was that no one wanted to make any
hard choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there is domestic political pressure. The question is
whether that translates into action.''
</P>
<P>
   How the markets interpret the politics will reverberate beyond
Japan. Just a few weeks ago, for example, a Treasury Department
study found a ``surprisingly strong correlation'' between the fall
of the yen and the flight of investors from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other financial contagions that have swept through Asia
and beyond in the last year, no one can entirely explain this
phenomenon, beyond citing the psychology of increasingly wary
investors who are nervous about emerging markets of all kinds,
including Russia's.
</P>
<P>
   But the link was one more factor in the race to put together the
$22.6-billion package for Russia that was announced on Monday by
the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   It was this same concern about Russia, and the growing pressure
on China to devalue its own currency, that led President Clinton
and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin to order an intervention in the
currency markets a month ago to strengthen the yen.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's election could unwind that effort. If the political
turmoil in Japan is prolonged, one result could be another panicky
sell-off of the yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to soak up time that Japan doesn't have, and
that the rest of Asia doesn't have,'' one administration official
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the Liberal Democrats' drubbing clearly took the
administration by surprise. At White House meetings last week, the
consensus was that the party would garner at least 54 or 55 seats
in the upper house of Parliament. It won only 44.
</P>
<P>
   But in public on Monday, administration and Japanese officials
aimed their public comments at forestalling a sharp reaction in the
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever the new prime minister is, he will try to implement
the economic plans formulated by the Hashimoto government,''
Japan's ambassador to the United States, Kunihiko Saito, said as he
sipped green tea in his office along Embassy Row.
</P>
<P>
   Saito is a veteran of managing relations with Washington during
times of upheaval: he was the country's top career diplomat,
running the day-to-day operations of the Foreign Ministry, when the
Liberal Democrats were thrown out of power in 1993. Then, it was
because of corruption, not ineptitude in handling the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But while Sunday's defeat was less dramatic, in some ways it is
more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   There was little international cost to the political chaos that
followed the 1993 upset; the issues of political reform were
entirely domestic. This time, they ripple daily through the
international markets.
</P>
<P>
   So now, though the party retains the prime ministership, it must
convince Washington, the markets and Asia that a weaker governing
party will push through painful reforms that a stronger government,
under Hashimoto, shied away from.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
