<SLUG> BC-PROPERTY-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE EFFECTIVELY KILLS GOP-BACKED BILL ON PROPERTY RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Blocking a conservative drive to make it easier for
developers to challenge zoning and environmental laws in federal
courts, the Senate on Monday effectively killed a property rights
bill supported by Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 52-42, with the leadership falling well short of
the 60 needed to prevent a filibuster, the Senate refused to limit
debate on the measure, and signaled that the legislation probably
cannot survive this Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation passed the House last year by a wide margin,
but even if the Senate had concurred, the proposal faced a
presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   With a series of environmental votes pending before Congress
adjourns for elections, the Senate's action on Monday may reflect a
distaste in Congress for proposals weakening environmental
protections.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, favored by home builders and agricultural groups but
opposed by environmental advocates and local governments, would
broaden the powers of two specialized courts, the Court of Federal
Claims and the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in
Washington, to review federal, state and local restrictions on how
property may be used.
</P>
<P>
   Its sponsors, led by Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, the chairman of
the Judiciary Committee, argued that landowners face too many legal
roadblocks when they claim that environmental regulations violate
their rights under the Fifth Amendment, which prohibits taking
private property without just compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, joined
those who argued that environmental regulations can amount to the
unfair seizure of property.
</P>
<P>
   ``What value does a piece of property have in Kansas, or in
Connecticut, or in Mississippi, if you have been told, `Yes, it is
your land, we won't take it, but by the way, you can't use it the
way that you had intended,''' he said. ``What value does it have if
you can't use it?''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow developers to move swiftly to challenge
state and local zoning rules in the federal courts, overturning a
legal doctrine that allows federal courts to defer to state courts
on many such issues and making federal claims ripe for review even
before local challenges are exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   While conservatives in Congress have offered property rights
proposals before, this attempt was unusual because it would have
affected state and local regulations as well as federal rules. The
legislation has been opposed by the national organizations that
represent state governors, state legislators, mayors and county
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Chafee of Rhode Island, a leading Republican
environmentalist, called it ``strange to me that this is being
brought up by Republicans, who are always concerned about activist
federal judges. This puts everything in the lap of activist federal
judges.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters argued that the constitutional rights of property
owners were at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that every day in America, private property is
being taken without just compensation,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas. ``We all know in the name of endangered species, in the
name of wetlands, in the name of numerous other public purposes,
that private property is being trampled on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
