</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITTAKER-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO 
</HEADLINE>
 
Whittaker   investor   confident   of future 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a sign that Whittaker Corp.'s future continues
to brighten, Century City-based Tennenbaum &AMP; Co. LLC recently
bumped up its stake in the Simi Valley, Calif.-based developer of
aircraft fluid control and fire safety systems from 3 percent to
about 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Managing member Michael Tennenbaum said Monday his company first
invested in Whittaker about 15 months ago. Earlier this month,
Tennenbaum &AMP; Co. bought the additional shares on the strength of
the improvements spearheaded by Whittaker Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer Joseph Alibrandi.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning to the helm in 1996 after a brief retirement,
Alibrandi has shed several ``problem businesses'' and reduced debt,
leaving a strong core business that has helped return the company
to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The businesses they have are excellent and they have been
excellent,'' Tennenbaum said. ``The bad businesses were obscuring
the good ones and threatening them financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Whittaker has a tax loss to carry forward for the next
three years that will save the company from paying taxes during
that time, which will boost cash flow and help the company whittle
down its approximately $71.5 million debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the company will be totally out of debt in
three years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker officials did not return telephone calls Monday to
discuss Tennenbaum's investment. Whittaker shares closed up 0.875
at 15 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies or investment groups of late also have increased
existing stakes or bought into Whittaker, in some cases picking up
stock that was sold off by larger corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, for example, Beverly Hills-based investment group
Canpartners Investments IV LLC purchased 1.97 million Whittaker
shares from electronics giant Raytheon Co., giving Canpartners
one-fourth ownership of Whittaker. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
