<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-GAYS-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE JOURNAL: MUGABE ATTACKS, AND GAY ZIMBABWEANS FIGHT BACK  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Nearly three years ago, in a dispute over a
small stand at an obscure book fair, President Robert Mugabe
suddenly lashed out against gay men and lesbians, making remarks
that echoed around the world. He said they were ``worse than pigs
and dogs'' and had no civil rights in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Although gay organizations overseas were shocked and angry, gay
Zimbabweans largely did what white Zimbabweans had done 10 years
before, when Mugabe began attacking them: ducked their heads and
tried to get on with life.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed. Both sides have now dug in, and a state
of undeclared war exists between gay Zimbabweans and the president.
</P>
<P>
   Activists recently thwarted a plan by California State
Polytechnic University at Pomona to award the president an honorary
doctorate, and have asked foreign human rights groups to picket his
overseas trips.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe, for his part, repeatedly takes gratuitous slaps at gay
men and lesbians. At a news conference on another topic in another
country in May, for example, he told foreign reporters, ``In
Zimbabwe, all the freedoms you get elsewhere _ except that of gays
_ are allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   He recently told journalists at an editor's funeral to ``report
negatively'' on homosexuality. He has even suggested, gay activists
said, that women not attend baby showers, saying that talk about
sex and libidinous kwasa-kwasa dance music led to lesbian affairs.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the press and society in general have become
homophobic in a country that was once indifferent to or tolerant of
gay men and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   When the controversy began in 1995, many people were ignorant of
homosexuality. Rural Zimbabweans said some heterosexual friends had
asked if gay people had both male and female sex organs.
</P>
<P>
   Because African men commonly hold hands and share bedrooms, gay
men said, the police used not to recognize them as gay.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they say, the police sneer at them and refuse to
investigate gay-bashing incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't accept us anymore,'' said Tina Machida, a leader
of Gays and Lesbians of Zimbabwe, a gay rights group known as Galz.
``The bouncers from the bar next door to a club where we held our
last party tore down our decorations and got violent. They were
saying, `The president doesn't like people like you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Street boys who sell sexual favors to older white men now harass
black gay men. ``They see us as a threat,'' said Chesterfield
Samba, another activist. ``They start yelling to the police: `How
come you're not arresting them? They're homosexuals mincing
around!'''
</P>
<P>
   Galz recently opened a headquarters in a suburban house, and the
government-owned Sunday Mail promptly called it a whorehouse for
white foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The group used to meet with the police to press for fairer
treatment. ``We thought we were getting somewhere,'' Ms. Machida
said. ``But they were looking over the members, then finding their
parents and saying, `Do you know your child is gay?'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The battle got nastier recently when the World Council of
Churches, which is to meet here in December, invited Galz to join
its human rights session. Conservative local churches and the
government have objected.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle is all the more awkward for Zimbabwe's public image
because two prominent court cases about gay sex crimes are under
way, too.
</P>
<P>
   The first case concerns the Rev. Canaan Banana, 62, who was
president from 1980 to 1987, when Mugabe absorbed his largely
ceremonial post. He is charged with sodomy and indecent assault.
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses _ most of them his youthful police bodyguards or
cooks between 1983 and 1986 _ described a pattern in which he would
ask them to play cards, offer them a drink, put on some music and
then insist on teaching them to dance. While dancing, they said, he
would kiss or fondle them, in one case squeezing one's buttocks
appreciatively, saying, ``This is the food of the elders.'' Most
fled in confusion. One jumped out a window. Another screamed so
loudly that the president's wife appeared. A third said he pushed
the president into a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   The key state witness, Jefta Dube, was sentenced in 1995 to 10
years for killing another policeman. His defense was that he had
been driven to do it because the man tauntingly called him
``Banana's wife.''
</P>
<P>
   He testified that he was drugged, and later woke up with his
pants off and a smiling president saying, ``We helped ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   He became, he testified, a reluctant sex slave. When he finally
resisted, he said, Banana jailed him.
</P>
<P>
   Banana, a Methodist minister with four children, has called the
accusations ``a mortuary of pathological lies and a malicious
vendetta.'' The defense said the acts never took place. But if the
court found that sodomy took place, his lawyer argued, it was
consensual, and consensual sodomy ought not to be a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Some Zimbabweans suspect that the charges were brought now to
destroy Banana as a possible successor to Mugabe, who is under
pressure to step down. Mugabe has never commented on the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, a Galz leader, Keith Goddard, was accused of
sodomy. The charge was brought, he said, by a 20-year-old man he
had never met who wrote him letters recalling a night they had
supposedly spent together and demanding $500, a color television, a
stereo, an electric burner, a kettle and an iron. In the final
letter, the man threatened to have him arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Goddard, 38, said he gave the letters to the police as evidence
of extortion. At a lineup, he recognized the author as someone who
had once visited the Galz office. Although Goddard is short,
stooped and frail, the man first accused him of overpowering him,
then said Goddard had a gun. The police searched Goddard's house
but found only toy guns still in their packages, which were
intended for his maid's children.
</P>
<P>
   Galz activists said the young man admitted extortion but was
pushed by the judge to change his plea to not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has become a pattern _ the police bringing prosecutions
against victims,'' said Iden Wetherell, a columnist who frequently
criticizes the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
