<HEADER>
A3135 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-ART-2NDTAKE     07-13 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 FLINT, Mich.: come back.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soon after the strike began, both sides began alternating
serious negotiations with moves to escalate the dispute further.
</P>
<P>
   GM and the UAW made a strenuous effort to solve after just six
days the strike at an auto body parts factory in Flint that makes
hoods, fenders and engine mountings. GM even made the important
concession on June 11 of promising to return parts-making equipment
removed from the factory before the strike. But when those talks
broke down, the UAW ordered a walkout at a nearby spark plug and
speedometer factory that is losing jobs to Mexico and East Asia,
where wages are lower.
</P>
<P>
   The second walkout raised the difficult question of GM's steady
push to build factories overseas while slowing investment in its
low-profit American operations.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the auto body parts factory, the spark plug and
speedometer factory is part of GM's inefficient Delphi Automotive
Systems subsidiary, which makes mostly small, low-technology auto
parts. GM wants to sell part or all of Delphi and the UAW does not
want it sold, so the second walkout dragged in this long-festering
issue.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the second walkout, GM began threatening to
close assembly plants and terminate the production of some
slow-selling car models if the UAW did not compromise. The threats
angered the UAW, and raised the contentious question of how many
workers GM would employ in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the UAW threatened further walkouts later this year
at other parts factories here and in Indianapolis and Dayton, Ohio.
GM responded last week by insisting that long-simmering disputes at
those factories be resolved before any agreement is reached here
</P>
<P>
   The entire morass of issues has left bargainers saying that
while GM and the UAW have labored through more than a dozen local
strikes in the last five years, not one of those disputes has
approached the complexity of the current mess. ``It's complex
enough. These are sufficiently complicated, I'm not sure you could
make them more,'' said Richard Shoemaker, the UAW's vice president
for GM issues.
</P>
<P>
   Yet both sides say that the broader questions are unlikely to be
settled by any deal here. Gerald Knechtel, GM's vice president for
North American personnel, said on Sunday that the main issue
remained a union insistence that GM invest more money in the auto
body parts factory here despite its low productivity. Improving
that productivity will require changes in union work rules and a
company investment in new equipment - the local issues here 39 days
ago before either side began bringing up other problems.
</P>
<P>
   And Hackworth warned Monday night that, ``it appears as though
we have a long haul before settlement is reached.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
