<SLUG> BC-PRADA-FASHION-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S AT STAKE AS PRADA TOYS WITH GUCCI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Patrizio Bertelli, the chairman of Prada, made his purchase
early last month of 5.5 percent of Gucci stock, he met with
Domenico De Sole, the chief executive of Gucci, to tell him so.
</P>
<P>
   What else the two might have discussed is not known, but a few
weeks later, Bertelli announced that he and his wife, the designer
Miuccia Prada, had increased their stake to 9.5 percent. The
Gucci-Prada relationship has quickly taken on the plot twists,
grand ambitions and personal intrigues of an Italian opera.
</P>
<P>
   Though sewing machines will be still next month, when Italians
take their annual summer vacation, lips will be atwitter about what
the Gucci-Prada attachment means. For many Milanese, the raid is
indicative of the way the Italian fashion business will change in
the next five years: a phalanx of generational family businesses
giving way to family-controlled public enterprises that can compete
globally.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction has not only exposed Gucci's weakness _
vulnerability to takeover _ but also laid bare Prada's uncertain
future. Will the company be able to evolve from its revolutionary
nylon handbags and jackets, which are now a part of the fashion
vocabulary?
</P>
<P>
   Aligning Prada with the much larger, debt-free Gucci, which in
1997 had sales of $975 million compared with Prada's $480 million,
would certainly benefit the privately held Prada. Both companies
have suffered loss of business, including 40 percent in the
deteriorating Asian market.
</P>
<P>
   Under Dutch law _ like many international companies, Gucci is
based in the Netherlands to take advantage of favorable tax laws _
a 10 percent stake would allow Bertelli to have the right to demand
a seat on the Gucci board. That request would be subject to
shareholders' approval. Among the shareholders are De Sole and Tom
Ford, the creative director of Gucci. But Bertelli has not yet
stated his intentions, a state of affairs that is confounding De
Sole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we are monitoring the situation and we're very
thoughtful about it for the shareholders,'' De Sole said. ``And
obviously we don't want to be distracted because Asia is a very
sensitive situation and we want to be on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The psychodrama aspects of the purchase by Prada seem rooted in
the personal nature of the Italian fashion business and the rumors
and speculation the purchase has engendered. On Monday, HDP, a vast
Italian luxury goods holding company, denied reports that it was
negotiating a deal with Prada to take over Gucci. As reported in
the Italian press, the denial included the biting twist that if the
company wanted to take over Gucci, it would do so itself.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, several Italian business leaders said they were
shocked by Bertelli's actions. They now believe it indicates the
shadow of changes crossing over Italian fashion, one that will see
more family companies go public to remain competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange,'' said Paolo Gerani, vice president of Gilmar
S.p.A., a second-generation fashion house owned by the Geranis.
``But that's life. That's business. Even if it's Italian. It's a
huge amount of money to put into a company without control or even
without asking for a seat on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Gucci is one of a handful of Italian fashion companies that are
public. Others include Bulgari and Marzotto. But Bertelli's move,
coupled with the many companies, including Giorgio Armani and
Gianni Versace, which have indicated an interest in going public,
point to a growing sense of how Italian fashion executives see
their future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger would be positive for Italian industry because it
guarantees continuity,'' Massimo Ferragamo, president of Ferragamo
USA, said. ``Italy has learned takeovers and mergers from the U.S.
And we've noticed it with the French groups. It protects both
companies because you're part of bigger things.'' It was Ferragamo
last year that purchased Emanuel Ungaro's company. In January, HDP
bought Valentino. Both purchases were solicited and welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci's Achilles' heel is that it is a public company without a
family dynasty exerting control. In fact, when referring to Gucci,
it is ``Dynasty,'' the television show, that comes to mind.
Patrizia Gucci now awaits trial on charges that she arranged the
murder of her husband Maurizio Gucci, one of the scions of the
founders of Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   If there does not seem to be much sentiment either way for the
company's stewards, De Sole and Ford, it is because neither has
deep roots in the Italian fashion world, where Bertelli and Ms.
Prada have transformed a family business. They took it from being a
small respected luggage company to a global fashion arbiter. And in
one sense, fashion observers believe that Gucci, leaving itself
vulnerable, got what was coming to it.
</P>
<P>
   Vendome, the French luxury company that once owned Karl
Lagerfeld, was interested in buying Gucci before it went public.
Since then, LVMH Moet Hennessy-Louis Vuitton has expressed
interest, but nothing has come of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Neither De Sole nor Ford would comment on steps being taken to
fend off a takeover by Prada. Gucci has already bought back some
outstanding shares. To an extent, their hands are tied, as De Sole
must do what is best for shareholders, like maximizing the stock
price. On Monday, Gucci closed at 54 15/16. Its low in the last
year was 28}, reflecting troubles in Asia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
