<HEADER>
A3138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRADA-FASHION-ART-2ND     07-13 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRADA-FASHION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: in Asia. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Born in Italy, De Sole, now a U.S. citizen, was once a partner
in Patton &AMP; Boggs, the Washington law firm. He has worked with
Gucci for 14 years. Ford is an American who left Perry Ellis to
become the designer for Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Malkin, director of equity research for Warburg Dillon
Read and a specialist in apparel, said a Gucci-Prada merger would
ultimately cut costs for both companies as they would pool
production, distribution and influence with retailers. Bertelli's
next step, she said, is to begin negotiations with Gucci. ``It
would be too expensive to keep buying shares on the open market,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The rub in any such deal might be the grudge factor. It is
unlikely that De Sole or Ford would stay on with Bertelli. A few
years ago, Bertelli accused Gucci of copying his wife's designs.
Back then he must have taken satisfaction that everyone was copying
Ms. Prada's designs.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot be lost on Bertelli that the man who stopped that
practice was Ford when he exploded onto the scene in 1994. Almost
overnight, Gucci became Prada's No. 1 competitor. Sales jumped from
$263.5 million in 1994 to $500 million the next year. Gucci surged
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prada has to find some definitive direction for its
ready-to-wear,'' said Gloria Gelfand, a director at Marketing
Management Group, a fashion consulting company. ``Where they're
great is those accessories that took over the market completely. I
guess I know who their customer is for ready-to-wear, but I don't
know that they're so many. Gucci has been able to get their message
out to a discerning customer.''
</P>
<P>
   In stores like Neiman Marcus, Prada and Gucci sometimes vie for
the same trendy fashion customer. But Gucci's coin of the realm is
easily understandable: sex. Ms. Prada's clothes are more cerebral.
The men's spring 1999 shows in Milan two weeks ago were
illustrations of the differing approaches. Ford chose a vibrantly
casual motif that drew on 70's pop culture and hip-hop; Ms. Prada
created her concept around stripped-down sleeveless suits with
subtle details like laser-cut collars.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ford nor Ms. Prada returned telephone calls seeking
comment about the situation. Both designers, along with Bertelli
and De Sole, run into each other at industry functions, and it is
an uncomfortable situation among them and others in the Milan
fashion whirl. ``Tuscany is a very small place,'' one fashion
executive said in reference to the region where Gucci and Prada
operate offices and factories.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt it will get smaller still as Prada, Gucci and other
Italian companies confront the unpleasant realities of global
business.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
