<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF SAYS IT WILL BORROW FROM MEMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: see related RUSSIA-IMF) 
(HLW) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Its financial strength depleted by the Asian
crisis, the International Monetary Fund said on Monday that it
would have to borrow from its richest members to pay for the
bailout of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The $11.2 billion in new loans being provided by the fund to
Russia this year, plus the possibility of an additional $2.6
billion next year, would just about wipe out the money available
from the fund's main financing pool, IMF officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Michel Camdessus, the managing director of the
fund, said that the loan package to Russia will largely tap a
backup credit line from 11 of the largest industrial countries,
including the United States. The American share is expected to be
$2.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The fund has not had to use the credit line _ described by a
senior American official on Monday as a ``spare fuel tank'' _ since
1978. With Japan in political and economic flux and other economies
throughout Asia moving downward, analysts and American officials
said that the IMF and the other multilateral lending institutions
faced a real possibility of being caught short should another major
crisis erupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts them pretty close to the bottom of the barrel,''
said Morris Goldstein, a former IMF official who is now with the
Institute for International Economics, in Washington. ``If a big
case comes in, or maybe a couple of medium-sized cases, then you're
stuck. Your alternative then is to go around hat in hand and try to
put it together bilaterally.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said that the situation added
urgency to their request that Congress provide new money for the
IMF. The Senate has approved a White House request for $18 billion
for the fund.
</P>
<P>
   But the House has balked at providing the money without
conditions that the White House has considered unacceptable,
including limits on family planning.
</P>
<P>
   Any congressional approval would not have direct effects on the
Russia bailout. But it could help the fund if it needed additional
money to deal with a further spreading of the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``With each of these developments, it becomes ever more
important that Congress act quickly to approve IMF funding,'' a
senior American official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A House Appropriations subcommittee is scheduled to take up the
issue on Wednesday. But Republican aides said on Monday that the
party leadership has not decided whether to seek the full $18
billion or to limit the bill to one part of the financing, $3.5
billion that would go to an expanded version of the backup credit
line.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave open the question of the other $14.5 billion.
That money would be the American contribution to an increase in the
monetary fund's main financing pool, which is financed by quotas _
or membership dues _ levied on each of the 182 member countries.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Congress said that they would push the Republicans
to act quickly to approve the new appropriation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We no longer have the luxury of simply waiting for something
to happen,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic
leader, said after meeting President Clinton at the White House on
Monday. ``It's happened. We've got to act soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Fund officials said that they plan to raise $8.4 billion for the
Russia bailout from the credit line, known as the General
Arrangements to Borrow. The United States, which provides 25
percent of the money under the credit line, expects the fund's
request to be approved quickly by the big industrial countries, the
senior American official said. American participation would not
require congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   Under the credit line, the United States and its major allies
can provide the fund with up to $23 billion, which has to be repaid
at market interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The quotas paid into the fund by its members total $195 billion.
But of that, the fund has $30 billion available. Half of that has
to be kept in reserve in case any member countries decide to
withdraw part of their quotas, which they are free to do, much like
a depositor at a bank.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that without tapping the backup credit line,
the fund has no more than $15 billion available. By the end of the
year, fund officials said, its available funds will have declined
to worrisomely low levels, even including the backup credit line.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans in Congress said the fund was exaggerating the
crisis it faces. They said the fund has $30 billion in gold
reserves, plus the ability to borrow on the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials said the fund badly needed the
flexibility that would accompany the pending quota increase and the
increased backup credit line. The increases were proposed by the
fund after the financial crisis in Mexico in 1995. That crisis
showed international lending institutions how quickly global
financial markets could overwhelm entire economies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
