<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-AREA-HOMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME SALES JUMP IN LOS ANGELES VALLEYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the first sign of a broad-based recovery for
the housing market this decade, sales of single-family homes in the
San Fernando and Santa Clarita valleys soared in June, thanks to
brisk movement in homes of all prices, a trade association has
reported.
</P>
<P>
   For years, first-time home buyers drove the market with their
purchases of entry-level houses, while sales of costlier residences
remained sluggish. But lately, the recovery has spread to include
higher-end homes, including many that cost more than $1 million,
according to a Southland Regional Association of Realtors report
Monday. Together with tight inventory, home prices have rocketed to
recent highs as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular market upturn is in all areas,'' said Jim
Link, executive vice president of the Realtors group. ``Sales of
homes costing $300,000 and up are strong. It was dead in the
mid-1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   Fueling demand is a strong economy, a healthy job market and
long-term interest rates that are hovering at a low 7 percent, he
said. Link expects these factors to continue to drive home sales
and prices for the near term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is going to remain strong for the rest of the
year,'' he said. ``We're very confident that by the end of the
year, we'll greatly outpace last year and it will probably be the
best year we'll have since 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   In the San Fernando Valley last month, sales of existing
single-family homes rose 31 percent more than a year ago _ to 1,315
closed escrows. That is the most closed escrows since May 1989, the
Realtors group reported.
</P>
<P>
   In the Santa Clarita Valley, sales of single-family homes rose
37 percent last month to a record high of 269 closed escrows.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of stronger sales among higher-priced homes, the
median price of single-family residences in the San Fernando Valley
closing escrow last month rose 26.1 percent to $208,000, the
highest since January 1993. The percentage increase was the largest
since June 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six of the San Fernando Valley escrows were priced at
more than $1 million, including a few sales at $2 million or more,
the Realtors group said.
</P>
<P>
   Median prices in the Santa Clarita Valley rose 10.8 percent to
$205,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Homeowners) have recouped a good bit of the equity they
lost,'' Link said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is tighter inventory: There were 10.8 percent fewer
existing homes listed for sale last month in the San Fernando
Valley _ or 4,623 _ compared with a year ago. In the Santa Clarita
Valley, active listings dipped 21 percent to 799.
</P>
<P>
   The brisk housing market also brought out new sellers, with new
listings up 14.6 percent to 1,935 homes in the San Fernando Valley
and up 20 percent to 306 residences in the Santa Clarita Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Zicarelli, president of Style Realty and Investments in
Tarzana, said it's a seller's market and that buyers don't have the
luxury of waiting to make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   He knew of a potential buyer who waited through a weekend to
offer $30,000 below the asking price of a house he wanted. However,
the home seller got another offer for the full price in the
meantime and made a deal, Zicarelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for homes costing $500,000 and higher is healthy, with
many selling in a month, Zicarelli said. In 1993, it would have
taken three to six months.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is different for San Fernando Valley condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   In June, sales dropped by 0.3 percent to 307 closing escrow. But
median prices rose 40 percent to $125,500. Active listings dropped
by 10.8 percent to 921 and new listings rose 1.3 percent to 400.
</P>
<P>
   Condominium sales slowed down after the number of units priced
under $100,000 dwindled, Link said. With available condos now
priced between $110,000 and $125,000, they became less attractive
to buyers since they're much closer in cost to single-family homes.
</P>
<P>
   However, Santa Clarita Valley condo sales rose 24.6 percent to
81 closing escrow last month. The median price rose 12 percent to
$124,500. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
