<HEADLINE>
CHRYSLER POSTS STRONG SECOND-QUARTER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also GM-STRIKE)  
(lh) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Zipping smoothly past Wall Street's projections,
Chrysler Corp. reported second-quarter earnings Monday that were
more than double the strike-ridden second quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler said that cost-cutting, strong sales, and the growing
popularity of high-margin products like the Dodge Durango sports
utility vehicle combined to overcome much of the financial damage
of high levels of rebates and discounting. Total revenue topped $17
billion, a Chrysler record for a second quarter that would have
been more impressive if it did not cost the company $1,485 a car in
sweeteners to secure buyers. That was up more than 20 percent from
$1,230 in the first quarter and 50 percent from $980 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been getting better every quarter at offsetting the
costs of incentives, even though they are going up,'' said Wendy
Beale Needham, an auto industry analyst for Donaldson Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, summing up how Chrysler beat Wall Street's projections by
about 10 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The cost-cutting included reductions in advertising, lower raw
materials costs and about $100 million from more efficient
manufacturing, for a total of between $400 million and $500 million
in total savings, the company said. Chrysler said it is ahead of
its plans for meeting its previously announced goal of shaving $1.5
billion off of annual spending during the course of the year. And
the company's North American market share reached 16.1 percent, up
from 15.5 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler earned $1 billion, or $1.51 a fully diluted share,
compared with $483 million, or 70 cents a share in the quarter a
year earlier. In the 1997 quarter, a monthlong strike at a Detroit
engine plant cut deeply into sales of its high-margin trucks. As a
result, after tax profits of $1,040 a vehicle in the recent quarter
were nearly double those of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were initially pleased, bidding Chrysler shares up
more than $1 on the New York Stock Exchange in early trading, but
the stock closed unchanged at $56.1875. Shares have been moving in
tandem with Daimler-Benz, the German carmaker Chrysler is planning
to merge with this fall, adjusting for currency fluctuations.
Daimler shares fell 2.85 marks, to 175.65 marks on the Frankfurt,
Germany, stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Valade, Chrysler's chief financial officer, said in a
conference call with reporters that the company expected the
rebating and other discounting to subside enough to return the
average cost to first quarter levels for the rest of the year.
Robert J. Eaton, Chrysler's chairman, said in a statement that the
outlook for the industry remained favorable given high consumer
confidence and low unemployment but that growth is slowing and the
uncertain Asian economic situation merits close attention.
</P>
<P>
   Valade also said that the company had not benefited in the
second quarter from the General Motors strike and had not factored
in any strike-related gains in its projections for the current
quarter. He said Chrysler had already received inquiries from
rental car companies that normally buy from GM, but analysts noted
that automakers rarely find it profitable to pursue such business
when rivals are being struck because it can evaporate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The profits reported Monday helped swell Chrysler's cash
reserves to a record $9.2 billion, compared with $7 billion a year
ago. The company halted its share repurchase program when it
reached its agreement in May to merge with Daimler-Benz. Valade
said the cash would continue to accumulate for the next four or
five quarters and could be deployed in new products, or, at least
in part, returned to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The news was not uniformly good. Total vehicle shipments rose
almost 15 percent to just over 849,000 but sales outside North
America tumbled 12 percent to 53,342 vehicles
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Chrysler said that the heavy discounting had
probably moved some sales forward into the second quarter. The
company expects output to decline to 631,000 units in the current
quarter, which is still up 10 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors is planning to release its earnings on Tuesday,
followed by Ford on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
