<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3152 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-670&AMP;     07-13 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY SAYS SHARPTON, TWO ADVISERS DEFAMED FORMER PROSECUTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Ten years after a white former assistant
district attorney filed a lawsuit to clear his name, a jury
declared Monday that he was defamed when three advisers to a black
teen-ager named Tawana Brawley accused him of kidnapping and rape,
creating a racial storm that roiled the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff, Steven Pagones, called the verdict a bittersweet
victory, for all the pain it had revived. But for the advisers, who
vowed to appeal, it was clear the verdict was just another chapter
in a case with its own life that has come to symbolize the
complexities of race relations in New York and the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a battle that obviously is not over,'' said Michael
Hardy, the lawyer for the Rev. Al Sharpton, the best known of Miss
Brawley's advisers.
</P>
<P>
   After a nearly eight-month trial, the verdict was an endorsement
of a 1988 grand jury report that discredited Miss Brawley's account
and suggested that her advisers had participated in a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict was also a rebuke to the advisers, Sharpton, C.
Vernon Mason and Alton H. Maddox Jr., whose critics have long said
represented a brand of ardent cynicism that twisted civil rights
advocacy into a vehicle for self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   A separate part of the trial to set damages with the same
six-person jury is to begin Tuesday. Pagones, 37, is seeking $395
million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are still to deliberate on the case, the jurors did
not speak about the verdict Monday. But there appeared to be some
division on the panel, with one unidentified juror refusing to sign
the verdict sheet. The jury includes two blacks and four whites.
Because Pagones' suit is civil, only five of the six votes were
required to find liability on each of the statements the advisers
made years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones has always described his decade-long fight against the
advisers as a battle to establish accountability. As he claimed
victory Monday, he repeated that theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Mason, Maddox and Sharpton did hurt a lot of people. They
hurt race relations,'' he said, encircled by reporters from most of
the New York City news organizations outside the courthouse in this
Hudson Valley city, a two-hour drive north from Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones' wife, Niki, who married him surrounded by armed guards
because of the threats he was receiving in the midst of the Brawley
confrontation, leaned against him. ``It's been a long 10 years,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones may have trouble collecting any money from the advisers.
Maddox, 52, is a suspended lawyer. Mason, 51, is a disbarred lawyer
who is now a theological student. Sharpton, 43, says he owns no
home or other substantial property and is paid an annual salary of
about $60,000 by his organization, the National Action Network.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Brawley, who was 15 at the time, was found apparently
dazed, with excrement and racial epithets etched on her body after
she disappeared for four days in November 1987. The grand jury
report suggested that she had concocted the story to avoid
punishment from her stepfather for being out without permission.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury also suggested that the advisers had permitted
the case to spiral into a national cause despite indications that
Miss Brawley's account was not what it appeared.
</P>
<P>
   With seven findings of defamation against Sharpton, including
two that he had made statements about Pagones that he knew were
false, the verdict presented a new challenge in Sharpton's widely
chronicled effort to give himself a broader base as he attempts to
forge a mainstream political career.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, who has attended the trial only intermittently, was
not here for Monday's verdict. As recently as last week, however,
he ridiculed the suggestion that his political ambitions could be
affected ``one iota'' by the verdict, saying his base of supporters
would always stand by his actions on behalf of Miss Brawley a
decade ago.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The jurors found that Maddox defamed Pagones twice and that
Mason defamed him once. But the jurors did not find defamation in
12 of the 22 statements upon which Pagones based his suit. The
jurors also rejected a contention by Pagones that the three
advisers, who are black, engaged in a conspiracy against him.
</P>
<P>
   After years of saying they would prove their allegations against
Pagones in court, the advisers never presented anything resembling
hard evidence that he was guilty of assaulting Miss Brawley or, as
they asserted 10 years ago, that he had killed a friend who they
said was also involved in an attack on Miss Brawley. The 1988 grand
jury concluded that the friend, Harry Crist, had committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   At the trial, Maddox, who represented himself, and Stephen
Jackson, Mason's lawyer, often said they still believed Pagones was
one of Miss Brawley's attackers. Hardy, though, walked a delicate
line, never saying he believed Pagones had been guilty. Instead, he
argued that, as Miss Brawley's spokesman, Sharpton had a duty to
represent her zealously and that he did not behave with reckless
disregard for the truth and did not know any of the assertions he
was making were false.
</P>
<P>
   Because Pagones was an assistant district attorney, a judge
ruled early in the case that he would be viewed as a ``public
official.'' Under the law of defamation, a public official must
prove not only that derogatory and false things were said about
him, but also that the speaker either knew the statements were
false or spoke with reckless disregard of whether they were true or
not.
</P>
<P>
   One statement the jurors found Sharpton made with reckless
disregard for the truth was made on a television talk show on March
31, 1988: ``We stated openly, that Steven Pagones, the Assistant
District Attorney, did it. His lawyers say he may or may not sue
us. If we're lying, sue us, so we can go into court with you and
prove you did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pagones sued after the grand jury concluded that there was no
evidence he had committed any crime.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox said that by finding no defamation in 12 of the
statements upon which Pagones sued, the jurors had agreed with the
advisers that something had happened to Miss Brawley. ``The main
thing here, was that this was not a hoax,'' Maddox said.
</P>
<P>
   In their verdict Monday, jurors seemed to focus on when some
statements were made. They found, for example, that nothing Mason
said during the most intense months of the Brawley confrontation
was defamatory. But they found that remarks by Mason in a talk at
Harvard Law School in March 1989, five months after the release of
the grand jury report, were defamatory and that Mason knew they
were false.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
