<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IF NICKLAUS ISN THERE, IS IT GOLF?  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time since 1962, when he was a rookie touring pro,
Jack Nicklaus won't be teeing off in the British Open when it
begins Thursday at Royal Birkdale in Southport, England.
</P>
<P>
   After 146 consecutive major tournaments, he decided not to
enter. And Monday, he announced he would retire from the PGA Tour
after the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate the Nicklaus time span, consider that in 1962,
both Michael Jordan and Mark McGwire had not yet been born.
</P>
<P>
   Also consider that only two years ago, when Nicklaus was 56, he
was only one stroke off the British Open lead after a second-round
66.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you come here for; that's what you play 40 years
for,'' he said that day, then he laughed. ``Maybe I'll shoot 150
for two days.''
</P>
<P>
   He did just that, finishing with a 77 and a 73.
</P>
<P>
   But as Nicklaus approached the final green two years ago at
Royal Lytham and St. Annes and again last year at Royal Troon, a
waterfall of admiring applause engulfed the golfer who has played
Scotland's game better than anyone else. At the British Open, they
know their golf. And their golfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aye,'' a ruddy-faced Scotsman once said while watching
Nicklaus play at Muirfield, ``he's something to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Scots like to say, ``If it's nae wind, it's nae golf.'' And if
the British Open is nae Nicklaus, isn't it nae golf?
</P>
<P>
   From 1966 to 1979, he finished first three times, second or tied
for second six times, and third or tied for third twice. Over those
14 tournaments, he had 11 top three finishes. Something to beat
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his seconds, to Lee Trevino in 1972 at Muirfield and to
Tom Watson in 1977 at Turnberry, are as memorable as his three
victories.
</P>
<P>
   When Nicklaus won at Muirfield in 1966, he used his driver only
17 times. When he returned there in 1972 with a Grand Slam alive
after having won the Masters and the United States Open, he was
cautious again, hitting his 3-wood or 1-iron off most of the tees.
He also had awakened early in the week with a crick in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``My neck wasn't very good,'' he acknowledged years later,
``until halfway through the third round.''
</P>
<P>
   After 54 holes, Nicklaus was six shots back. Hitting his driver
in the final round, he took the lead after 11 holes, but on the
16th he missed a 6-foot downhill putt. Bogey. His 66 wasn't enough.
Trevino won by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always believe I played the course the right way and
didn't play well,'' Nicklaus said, alluding to his caution in the
first three rounds. ``What can I do about a guy who holes it out of
bunkers and across greens?''
</P>
<P>
   Trevino holed it four times from off the putting surface, twice
with a sand wedge he had found in a pro-shop barrel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not winning that British Open was a very big disappointment,''
Nicklaus said later. ``And it seems to have become bigger as the
years go by.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Nicklaus finished 65-66 but lost to Watson's 65-65 at
Turnberry in what is considered golf's classic medal-play duel.
</P>
<P>
   After being two shots behind with six holes remaining, Watson
holed a 60-foot putt from off the 15th green to tie, then birdied
the long 17th for the lead. On the 18th, he had a 3-footer for
another birdie, but suddenly Nicklaus holed a 40-foot birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my caddie Jack was going to make that putt,'' Watson
said later. ``I just knew he would.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson now needed his putt, and made it. Nicklaus was second,
again.
</P>
<P>
   But the next year, Nicklaus won at St. Andrews for the second
time. He had won there in 1970 in an 18-hole playoff with Doug
Sanders, who had missed a 3-footer on the final hole of the fourth
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Andrews, to me, is the home of golf and where it all
began,'' Nicklaus said that day. ``It's my favorite place, and
where I most want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the 14th hole at St. Andrews in 1995, the golfer who has
played Scotland's game better than anyone else hit a 3-wood into
the notorious Hell bunker. After a slash with his pitching wedge
and two more with his sand wedge, he was still in it. Another sand
wedge and he was finally out. He chipped on, then three putted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made many 10s,'' he said later.
</P>
<P>
   But when the British Open returns to St. Andrews in 2000, Jack
Nicklaus intends to play. He'll be 60 then, but don't bet he won't
shoot at least one round in the 60s. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
