<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH KNOCKS BOARDMAN, TOUR'S LEADER, FROM RACE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORK, Ireland _ What started as a festival day in the Tour de
France to celebrate a hero of the past, Sean Kelly, ended in
disaster Monday for a hero of the present, Chris Boardman, the man
in the leader's yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Boardman, a Briton who is the top rider for the Gan team, was
injured about 35 miles from the finish of the race's second daily
stage after he seemed to brush the back wheel of a teammate,
Frederic Moncassin, and crashed, sliding along the shoulder of a
wide highway.
</P>
<P>
   Boardman was hospitalized with a broken bone in his left wrist
and a cut to his forehead. Boardman, 30, was wearing a helmet when
he struck his head in the fall. He was unconscious for a few
minutes before the race's ambulance arrived to treat him.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second time that Boardman has been injured and
forced to withdraw from the Tour. In 1995, he crashed as he took a
curve in the rain during the prologue and broke his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Crashes are common in the Tour, especially in the early, nervous
stages. Another crash Monday decked Laurent Jalabert, the Frenchman
who is ranked No. 1 in the world; Laurent Brochard, the Frenchman
who is the world road-race champion, and Abraham Olano, a Spaniard
who is among the overall favorites. All were quickly up and back
riding.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after the crash and 5 hours 45 minutes 10 seconds after
the pack set off in Enniscorthy for the 127.7-mile run to Cork, Jan
Svorada, a Czech with the Mapei team, won a mass sprint by a
bicycle length.
</P>
<P>
   Second was Robbie McEwen, an Australian with Rabobank, who is in
splendid form since he was third in the sprint on Sunday. Third in
the field of 186 men was Mario Cipollini, an Italian with Saeco,
who lost 3 minutes 40 seconds Sunday after he and several other
riders crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Moving into the vacated yellow jersey because of time bonuses
along the route was Erik Zabel, a German with Telekom. Second was
another sprinter, Tom Steels, a Belgian with Mapei, and third was
Moncassin.
</P>
<P>
   The field dropped from its original 189 riders when, in addition
to the loss of Boardman, Ludovic Auger of the Big Mat team did not
start and Erik Dekker of Rabobank had to quit partway through
because of injuries sustained in the Cipollini crash on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Kelly too had to pull out of the Tour once because of a
crash, in 1987, that left him with a broken collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   King Kelly he was then, winning every bicycle race in sight
except the Tour de France, and King Kelly he remains: This was
unofficially Sean Kelly Day in the 85th Tour. Until Boardman's
crash, it was, as they say in Ireland, brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who retired four years ago at the age of 38, rode in 14
Tours and finished 12 of them. He captured the green points jersey
a record four times, won five daily stages and for a day, in 1983,
wore the yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   A farmer's son, he still lives in his hometown of Carrick on
Suir, which he said in an interview before the stage is a strong
cycling town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call it the home of cycling in Ireland,'' he said,
adding: ``They're very enthusiastic down there in the countryside,
more so than in Dublin. They're decorating all the shop windows,
and there's a lot of flags and banners. They're really making a big
thing about it. Of course, it's fabulous, a dream come true, that
the Tour has come to Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowds were indeed huge and enthusiastic along the route despite
a cold wind and occasional showers on the Tour's final day of
racing in Ireland. French flags mingled with Irish ones, and
posters acclaiming Kelly hung from many a pole and window.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1985, a main area in Carrick on Suir, a village of 5,000,
has been called Sean Kelly Square, and through there the pack
streamed near noon as a crowd estimated at several times the
population cheered. Originally, the Tour was to have bypassed the
square because it was considered too narrow for safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tight part of the street,'' Kelly called it. ``They wanted
to route the race just at the outskirts of town, and the people
down there weren't too happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Local officials met with Jean-Marie Leblanc, the director of the
race, , and persuaded him to alter the route.
</P>
<P>
   A limestone boulder, called a jostling stone, at the end of the
square next to Jack Savage's butcher stop was uprooted from the
spot where it had rested since the 17th century. A few telephone
poles were removed, the sidewalk cut back.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Kelly was standing on a podium to watch as the Tour
passed through his square. An explosion of cheers rang out for all
the riders and for King Kelly, then, now and forever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
