<SLUG> BC-NEW-YORKER-EDITOR-ART-420(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMNICK APPOINTED EDITOR OF NEW YORKER
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
By ROBIN POGREBIN  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Remnick, a Pulitzer Prize-winning author who
has spent the last six years writing for The New Yorker on topics
from Alexander Solzhenitsyn to Mike Tyson, was named the fifth
editor of the magazine in its 73-year history on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment, which becomes effective immediately, was
announced by S.I. Newhouse Jr., the chairman of Advance
Publications. The announcement came just a few days after The New
Yorker's current editor, Tina Brown, resigned to start her own
media company in affiliation with Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was the best man for the job,'' Newhouse said in
an interview on Monday. ``I think he has a combination of skills
both as a writer and conceptually as a magazine person.''
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse's announcement _ made Monday morning in a meeting at
the magazine in the presence of Remnick and Ms. Brown _ was met
with sustained applause by members of the staff, many of whom later
described their feelings as profound relief. ``It seldom happens
that the absolute best person on the face of the earth for a given
position gets that position,'' Hendrik Hertzberg, the senior editor
at the magazine, said.
</P>
<P>
   Remnick's appointment comes after months of tension over the
magazine's financial losses, which came to a head this month with
the expiration of Ms. Brown's contract. Despite award-winning
editorial content, considerable _ if sometimes controversial _
publicity and increased circulation, the magazine has continued to
lose money in its 13 years under Newhouse. Although losses have
decreased from $30 million in 1992 to $11 million last year, recent
changes on the magazine's business side suggested that Newhouse had
had enough.
</P>
<P>
   Remnick was by no means an obvious choice to succeed Ms. Brown.
There had been speculation that Newhouse might select someone with
a tested mass-market track record, such as Graydon Carter, the
editor of Vanity Fair, who one Conde Nast executive said was
offered the job but turned it down. Such a choice would have seemed
in keeping with the style of Ms. Brown, 44. She was a glamorous
magnet for the gossip columns who many say created _ for better or
worse _ the era of the magazine editor as celebrity and pointed up
the importance of ``buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   Remnick, 39, promises to be a significant change of pace. With a
gentle and pensive manner, he is more likely to be found sitting at
a seminar at the Council on Foreign Relations than running the
gauntlet of paparazzi on his way into some black-tie benefit.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
