<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH WATCH: HEART ATTACKS SURGE IN AFTERNOONS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting up can be hard on a body, Monday mornings remind us. But
why should leaving work be just as hard on the heart?
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have long known that heart attacks occur more
frequently in the morning, a surge suspected to be a result of the
complicated chemical changes in the blood associated with the end
of sleep and return of activity. So when statisticians and
cardiologists at the University of Washington in Seattle combed
records of 3,690 heart attacks compiled by that city's paramedics
over 23 years, they were not expecting to find what they uncovered,
which was a similar surge of heart attacks in the late afternoon
beginning at 4 p.m. and peaking at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Though medication may be to blame _ heart medication, which is
most often taken in the morning, may be wearing off by late
afternoon _ Dr. Alfred Hallstrom is more interested in stress as an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more likely the result of what we do,'' he said. ``Most
of us are relatively sedentary at work during the day, and then
rush off, whether to drive home and make dinner or whatever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
