<SLUG> BC-ATCITTY-NAVAJO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVAJO COUNCIL RULES TRIBAL PRESIDENT MUST STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL DONOVAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. _ The Ethics and Rules Committee of the
Navajo Nation Council ruled Monday that Tribal President Thomas
Atcitty must resign for violating tribal ethics laws by accepting
corporate gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The panel decision is only advisory, and must be approved by the
full council. It comes five months after former President Albert
Hale stepped down for similar reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Rex Morris, acting chairman of the ethics panel, said Monday
``the law is the law,'' and that Atcitty, while vice president,
should have known he was violating tribal laws when he permitted
off-reservation businesses on at least 10 occasions to pay for
golfing trips between 1995 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Atcitty, 64, on Monday reaffirmed that he will fight an ouster,
but will cooperate with the Tribal Council while the issue is being
decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to emphasize to the people, as well as all
federal, state and local governments and the private sector, that
any interest you may have vested in the Navajo Nation is not
adversely affected,'' Atcitty said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Atcitty took over as tribal president Feb. 19 after Hale
resigned to avoid removal from office for also allowing companies
doing business with the tribe _ or wanting to _ to pay his
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   At an ethics panel hearing last week, Atcitty said he wasn't
aware that allowing companies to pay for golfing trips violated
tribal anti-gift laws.
</P>
<P>
   He told the committee that when he thought of taking gifts, he
thought of things like rugs and not of something ``intangible''
like a golfing trip.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's recommendation now goes to the full Tribal
Council, whose summer session begins Monday. But Bob French,
director of the tribe's ethics office, said that, even if the
council refuses to go along, tribal law would require Atcitty to
step down.
</P>
<P>
   Atcitty's only hope, he said, is for 59 of the 88 council
members to agree to waive the law and allow him to stay on as
president.
</P>
<P>
   If Atcitty steps down, tribal law says that speaker of the
council Kelsey Begaye will step in as acting president for up to a
month, so that a special election can be held.
</P>
<P>
   But this may be revised since the tribe's primary is scheduled
for Aug. 4. The council could allow the top vote-getter in the
primary to take office in an interim capacity _ or allow Begaye to
remain in both positions _ until November's general election.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics committee also has recommended that Atcitty not be
allowed to run for a tribal elective position for five years. If
upheld, this would remove him as the front-runner in the coming
election and throw it open to the other eight candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe's special prosecutor has said Navajo Nation law holds
that tribal officials cannot accept anything worth more than $100
from anyone doing business or planning to do business with the
tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Atcitty has claimed that the law was intended to prevent
companies from persuading tribal officials to use their influence
to provide a favor. He said the presidency largely isn't in a
position to do so since the passage of new laws in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Those laws were passed after the then-leader of the tribe, Peter
MacDonald, was suspended as a result of allegations that he took
bribes. He was convicted later in tribal and federal courts and is
serving a 14-year term in a federal prison. &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
