<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUSTERY WELCOME FOR OPEN  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ The wind was howling at Royal Birkdale Golf
Club Monday, with players wearing ski caps and layered clothing to
try to stay warm during practice rounds.
</P>
<P>
   It was a cold, fitting reminder that the British Open has a
different feel from the other major championships. The year's third
major, which begins on Thursday, is synonymous with unpredictable
weather, and it is played on golf courses that require creativity
and resiliency.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, in mid-July, many of the world's greatest players were
shivering, dealing with temperatures in the 50s and wind gusts of
around 35 miles per hour. That is part of what makes the British
Open special. And if the weather stays chilly and windy, it will
help those who cope successfully with the elements stay in
contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the best players will come to the top,'' said Tom
Lehman, the 1996 British Open champion. ``If you're not hitting the
ball solid, you have no chance whatsoever, I don't care how you
putt. How do you practice for stuff like this? If you live in
Scottsdale, Ariz., where it's 110 degrees, how do you practice for
this?''
</P>
<P>
   To many players, the British Open is the major that best tests
all-around skill, because with changing conditions, the same course
can require dramatically different shots from one day to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Birkdale, a par-70, 7,018-yard course on England's
northwest coast, last held a British Open in 1991, when Ian
Baker-Finch defeated Mike Harwood by two strokes. But many great
players have won here, including Arnold Palmer (1961), Peter
Thomson (1954 and '65), Lee Trevino (1971), Johnny Miller (1976)
and Tom Watson (1983).
</P>
<P>
   As usual, a long list of contenders will tee off on Thursday
with a legitimate chance to win. Lee Westwood of England has
surpassed Colin Montgomerie as Europe's best player at the moment,
winning seven tournaments in the last nine months, including last
week's Loch Lomond Invitational in Scotland. Justin Leonard, the
defending champion, cannot be overlooked. Jesper Parnevik has
finished second or tied for second in two of the last four British
Opens. And David Duval and Fred Couples are having outstanding
years and will have as much confidence as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The last three British Opens have been won by U.S. players _
John Daly in 1995, followed by Lehman and Leonard. Most American
players arrive in Europe the week before the British Open to combat
the jet lag, either playing in the Loch Lomond tournament or
practicing elsewhere. Tiger Woods, Mark O'Meara and Payne Stewart
played several courses in Ireland last week.
</P>
<P>
   The British Open has been a difficult tournament for Woods, who
has not finished higher than 22d in three attempts. Perhaps the
biggest challenge for Woods, along with everyone else in the field,
will be to keep tee shots in Birkdale's narrow fairways, avoiding
the double-bogey and triple-bogey holes that can ruin a round.
</P>
<P>
   The last 15 majors have been won by 15 different players, making
it difficult for anyone to predict what will happen. And the more
players who prove themselves capable of winning majors, the harder
it will be for anyone to dominate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win a major, a little more is expected of you,''
Lehman said. ``Maybe you put a little more pressure on yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo, a three-time winner of the British Open, will be
putting a different kind of pressure on himself this week. Forced
to withdraw from the Loch Lomond tournament because of sharp pain
in his right elbow, Faldo still hopes to tee off on Thursday, which
would extend his streak to 45 consecutive majors, the longest
current streak. Jack Nicklaus, who has played in 146 consecutive
majors, will not play in the British Open or in the PGA
Championship next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inflammation has gone down seriously,'' Faldo said. ``I am
still undergoing intensive treatment and will be doing so right up
until the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Another player who is ailing this week is Els, who said Monday
that his injured back had not completely healed and that he might
be forced to take time off after the Open.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
