<SLUG> BC-MENACE-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13.) 
`DENNIS' SEQUEL BYPASSING BIG SCREEN IN GROWING INDUSTRY TREND
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: ``Today'' in story refers to Tuesday, July(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Warner Bros., becoming the latest studio to opt
for the small screen over the big one, is rolling out a
direct-to-video sequel of ``Dennis the Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   The project _ ``Dennis the Menace Strikes Again'' _ is Warner's
fourth direct to video release (following ``Pippi Longstocking,''
``Shiloh'' and ``Batman and Mr. Freeze: Subzero'') and underscores
the growing trend among studios to bypass the risky theater
business with video versions of easy to recognize properties for
families.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the live-action video, to be released today, is a
sequel to the studio's 1994 release of ``Dennis the Menace,'' a
solid money maker that grossed $51 million domestically and sold
more than 4 million video copies. Justin Cooper, who starred
opposite Jim Carrey in ``Liar Liar,'' plays the title character in
the sequel with supporting roles by Don Rickles, Betty White and
George Kennedy, among others. It carries a suggested price of
$19.94.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Alexander, head of industry tracker Alexander &AMP;
Associates, said Warner's move should work, given the success that
rivals The Walt Disney Co., Universal and 20th Century Fox have
found so far with similar products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Direct to video has become a real market,'' Alexander said.
``There are a lot of people on the theatrical side of the business
that still don't give it the credibility it deserves, but consumers
will pay for the product.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney kick-started the direct to video market four years ago
with ``The Return of Jafar,'' an ``Aladdin'' sequel that stunned
the industry by selling more than 10 million copies. Until then,
direct to video had been a catchall for titles not good enough for
theatrical release.
</P>
<P>
   Why direct to video? Studios save significantly since production
costs typically amount to less than $10 million and promotions cost
about $5 million, Alexander noted. Last year's average production
cost for a film from a major studio was nearly $40 million, while
promotional costs were almost $20 million each, according to the
Motion Picture Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``With direct to video, you're not battling for screens because
the key outlets like Wal-Mart, Target and Kmart are going to put
you on the shelf if you're one of the top names like Disney and
Warner,'' he said. ``With a franchise product, you have an
excellent chance of making back your costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the relatively inexpensive costs of tape production
and distribution, studios can make as much as a $10 profit for each
video sold. Thomas Adams of Adams Media Research estimates that
last year's direct to video titles _ including Disney's ``Beauty
and the Beast: The Enchanted Christmas'' and Fox's ``Casper: A New
Beginning'' _ generated $380 million in revenue or nearly double
the 1996 total.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to see more direct to video even though no
individual title is blowing the socks off anyone,'' Adams said.
``It makes perfect sense for studios, since these are produced on
an economic model that allows them to make a good profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney is the dominant player in direct to video titles, with
sequels coming later this year for ``Pocahontas'' and ``The Lion
King,'' and four titles per year planned under the Disney Premieres
nameplate. Universal has sold 20 million copies of four ``Land
Before Time'' videos, and Fox sold an estimated 5 million copies of
the ``Casper'' video last year.
</P>
<P>
   As for Warner, it has three more direct to video projects due by
the end of the year: ``Scooby Doo on Zombie Island,'' ``Addams
Family Reunion'' and ``Richie Rich's Christmas Wish.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
