<SLUG> BC-NAMAN-SHOOTING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMELESS MAN SENTENCED TO 15 YEARS IN SHOOTING OF COUNTY
SUPERVISOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A delusional homeless man called himself a ``leader''
in court Monday, saying he ended a ``dictatorship'' when he shot a
county supervisor who voted in favor of a baseball stadium tax.
</P>
<P>
   Before being sentenced to 15 years in prison for attempted
murder in the shooting, Naman said he accomplished what he set out
to do: stop shady politicians from thwarting the will of the
people.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he had no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech directed mostly at his victim, Maricopa County
Supervisor Mary Rose Wilcox, Naman predicted it will be a long time
before a political board tries to implement a sales tax without
going to the voters first.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my way I tried to be a leader here. I still am,'' said
Naman, who has spent the past 20 years of his life living along
riverbanks, collecting aluminum cans and digging through dumpsters
for food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   When Wilcox and the other supervisors approved the county-wide
baseball stadium tax instead of taking it to a vote of the people
more than three years ago, it was tantamount to violence, Naman
said in a voice barely audible in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the people who have sincere faith in democracy. It's
these people who really got hurt,'' said Naman, appearing pale and
thin in oversized jail pants. ``They were the victims of
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   He refused to apologize to Wilcox until she admits she was wrong
and fights ``to tear down the Bank One Ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized the judge and jury for not standing up
against the stadium tax.
</P>
<P>
   During his 50-minute speech, Naman raised his voice at one point
and spewed obscenities at Wilcox. Wilcox stood up and walked out of
the courtroom on the verge of tears.
</P>
<P>
   Naman, who acted as his own attorney, said he never intended to
kill Wilcox, just maim her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have tracked you down, Mrs. Wilcox - you or another
leader - tracked you down at night and shot you and left before the
cops came and made a clear getaway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Dave Powell asked the judge to give Naman the
stiffest sentence possible, saying Wilcox endured extreme emotional
and physical injury after Naman snuck a .357 into a supervisors
meeting in August 1997 and shot Wilcox in the leg. The weapon was
loaded with deadly hollow point bullets that explode on impact.
Wilcox had to undergo two surgeries, including one to clean out a
potentially fatal infection caused by the bullet fragments.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox also made a brief statement at the sentencing. Naman's
actions were premeditated and that he intended to kill her, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   He is a dangerous man who targeted others to shoot including
ballpark construction workers, radio personalities and Jerry
Colangelo, Wilcox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man should not be allowed to go back into society for a
very, very long time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Michael Wilkinson listened intently and politely
throughout the proceedings and did not register any expression when
when Naman criticized the judge for not taking a ``leadership
role'' against the ballpark tax.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining his reasons for a lengthy sentence, Wilkinson said
Naman used a deadly weapon and endangered the lives of others
besides Wilcox.
</P>
<P>
   His ``complete lack of remorse'' also contributed to his
decision, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   When Naman used violence to try and change government, it was an
act of anarchy and cannot be tolerated in our society, Wilkinson
said. He added that Naman did exactly what he accused Wilcox of
doing: an act of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an incredible twisting of logic in your mind,''
Wilkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not take into consideration Naman's history of mental
problems because Naman was found not to be mentally ill and to be
legally competent to stand trial and act as his own attorney.
</P>
<P>
   A court appointed psychiatrist testified Monday that Naman is
``somewhat delusional'' but knows the difference between right and
wrong. He said Naman could be a danger to himself and others in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a throw of the dice,'' the psychiatrist said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
