<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GILKEY-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILKEY'S SLUMP CONFOUNDS THE METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like any other baseball player in the hours before a
game, Bernard Gilkey performs a daily routine in front of his
clubhouse stall. He puts on his uniform and cap, laces up his
spikes, grabs a glove and makes his way out to the dugout with a
couple of bats tucked beneath his arm.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one piece of equipment, not of standard issue, that
the Mets left fielder chooses to leave behind: his contact lenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to wear them, period,'' Gilkey said. ``I'm not
far enough from the pitcher where I can't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But the Mets apparently do not see the issue as
clearly. What they have seen is a once-dangerous hitter who is
batting .237, one season after his average was hovering in the low
.200s through mid-August before it finally ended up at .249.
</P>
<P>
   The question of Gilkey's vision is just one of the possible
explanations the organization has considered as it searches for
clues to his decline at the plate over the last year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey said he still sees occasional flashes in his left eye,
the result of a frightening beaning in Miami on June 12. He has
undergone numerous eye examinations since, at least one coming
after he had been cleared to play on June 21.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even before the beaning, Gilkey said, eye doctors suggested
that he try glasses or contacts. He said he is just not comfortable
wearing them and rarely puts the lenses in, on the field or off.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey may not believe that his vision is the primary reason for
his struggles, but he does not offer any other explanation. He is
just as confounded by what has happened to him as everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mets signed him to a guaranteed four-year, $20.4
million deal in December 1996, Gilkey was coming off the season of
his life: a .317 batting average, 30 homers and 117 runs batted in
_ all career highs.
</P>
<P>
   But in the season and a half since, there has been nothing but
frustration and unanswered questions. This season he has only three
home runs and 25 runs batted in, and since 1996, he has batted .245
with 21 homers and 103 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   When asked recently whether this was the real Bernard Gilkey,
the 31-year-old just shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``And it is, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey's lack of production is a problem for the Mets, who begin
a two-game series against the Atlanta Braves Tuesday night at Shea
Stadium. There are those who believe that had Gilkey approached an
average season last year, the Mets would not have fallen four games
short of the National League wild card. And it seems equally
apparent that the Mets need Gilkey to produce behind Mike Piazza
and Todd Hundley for the team to have a realistic chance at the
wild card this year. Piazza said as much after Sunday's 5-2 victory
over the Montreal Expos gave the Mets two victories in two games
since Hundley, who is Gilkey's best friend, rejoined the club.
</P>
<P>
   Entering this season, Gilkey's career batting average was .283.
But since April 25, when he went on the disabled list with an elbow
injury, he has hit just .203 (32-for-158). Despite a three-hit game
on Friday night, his batting average has dropped 77 points. Manager
Bobby Valentine said his biggest mistake of the first half of the
season was allowing both Gilkey, who returned on May 12, and
Edgardo Alfonzo to come back too soon from stays on the disabled
list. And now that Hundley is back, Gilkey's playing time figures
to be further reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to go through trials and tribulations,''
Gilkey said. ``It's easy to judge somebody when they're doing
well.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is much more difficult to ascertain why Gilkey is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was able to drive the ball then, and he is not able to
drive the ball now,'' Valentine said. ``It is my opinion that his
swing is kind of upside-down. He leads with his top instead of his
bottom. He is rotating too soon with his upper body. And he
therefore leaves himself hitting the ball out in front too much,
which causes bloops to right and grounders to left. It shouldn't be
that tough mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Another theory, one that Valentine does not adhere to, is that
Gilkey has not been the same since Tom Robson replaced Tom McCraw
as the team's hitting coach after the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey, who has hit the ball better the last few days after
working with Robson on using his entire body, doesn't entirely
agree. ``I've had a few hitting instructors in my day,'' he said.
``It's easy to have a good relationship with a guy when you're
having the best year of your career. But it's not like we went out
together, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey dismisses suggestions that he may have grown complacent
because of his big contract, as well as criticism that he is
resistant to suggestions about his stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't look back and wonder why,'' Gilkey said. ``Not now.
It's not how you start, it's how you finish. And for me, it's not
over yet. Not by far.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Mets General Manager Steve Phillips said last week:
``He was one of the most productive left fielders in the game, when
you break down the numbers. And he's not doing it now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
