<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXSIDE-LADN(Goes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXING'S POPULARITY FUELED BY LATINOS
</HEADLINE>
 with Boxing) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The popularity of boxing doesn't rival that of
America's favorite sports.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it has its moments.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Oscar De La Hoya drew more than 50,000 fans to
the Sun Bowl for a fight he had no chance of losing last month in
El Paso, Texas, against unknown Patrick Charpentier of France.
</P>
<P>
   The second Mike Tyson-Evander Holyfield fight, in June of 1997,
had a record pay-per-view buy rate of 1.95 million, which, at $50 a
pop, translates to almost $100 million from domestic television
revenue alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Tyson-Buster Mathis fight in 1995, on FOX, was watched in
more than 15 million homes across the nation _ almost 1 million in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   And networks report solid ratings on regular shows. For example,
HBO has had double-digit ratings for many of its biggest fights.
</P>
<P>
   Many credit a fiercely loyal core of boxing fans _ largely
Latino _ for the sport's viability but bemoan the fact they don't
seem to be reaching a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``If only 2 million people watched the Super Bowl, it'd be
financial disaster,'' said Nigel Collins, editor of The Ring
magazine, referring specifically to the Tyson-Holyfield
pay-per-view success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange situation. A tremendous amount of money is
being generated by a relatively small audience willing to pay
exorbitant fees for big events.''
</P>
<P>
   About 68 percent of Latino males watch boxing on television at
least once a week, according to a marketing study cited by HBO
executive Mark Taffet. Taffet, as well as several other observers,
estimate Latinos account for more than 50 percent of pay-per-view
buys.
</P>
<P>
   That growing ethnic group could fuel the sport indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news. The bad news is boxing officials believe
they're failing to reach non-Latinos and young people, which
precludes boxing from challenging bigger sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there has been a tremendous erosion of Anglo fans. We
don't have younger men watching boxing the way they did 20 years
ago because we don't see enough compelling fights,'' promoter Bob
Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   The television networks certainly aren't giving up on the sport.
</P>
<P>
   USA's decision to drop it's Tuesday night shows, the most
consistent in boxing in recent years, was a blow to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   However, the move wasn't made because of ratings, which were
solid. The move had more to do with the network's across-the-board
decision to target a younger audience.
</P>
<P>
   And other networks have stepped in to fill at least part of the
void. Among them, FOX's FX and TNT are making forays into the
sport, an indication it continues to have a pulse.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's up to those who control the sport to take the next
step.
</P>
<P>
   Said Taffet: ``We have to adapt to a changing marketplace on a
regular basis or be left behind. That's the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   WISH LIST
</P>
<P>
   Boxing has had a pathetic dearth of compelling bouts because the
sport's biggest stars tend to avoid one another. If these 10 fights
could be made in the next year and half, it would give boxing a
blast of momentum going into the year 2000. &QL; 
1. Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis: The two best heavyweights in the
world would provide the ultimate show. &QL; 
2. Oscar De La Hoya-Felix Trinidad: Oscar needs a test. This could
kick off a Leonard-Duran-Hearns-Hagler-like welterweight series. &QL; 
3. Holyfield-Mike Tyson III: OK, Tyson is no longer Tyson. Still,
the interest in this one would be overwhelming. &QL; 
4. Roy Jones Jr.-David Reid: The best pound-for-pound fighter vs.
the Olympic champion. A sure winner. &QL; 
5. Naseem Hamed-Arturo Gatti: Half the fans want to see Hamed's
antics. The other half wants to see him lose. &QL; 
6. Tyson-George Foreman (at 50): No typo here. Think about it: Who
wouldn't want to see this? &QL; 
7. De La Hoya-Ike Quartey: This could be Part II in De La Hoya's
riveting road to immortality. &QL; 
8. Roy Jones Jr.-Holyfield (or another top heavyweight): Yes, this
is a stretch but an intriguing prospect. &QL; 
9. Shane Mosley-Arturo Gatti: The classic boxer-puncher vs. the
classic brawler is a can't-miss lightweight hit. &QL; 
10. Fernando Vargas-David Reid: For a change, how about a matchup
of two future greats while they're on the rise? &QL; 
Others: Lewis-Michael Grant; Hamed-Angel Manfredy; Hamed-Johnny
Tapia; Tapia-Mark Johnson; Tyson-Andrew Golota; Mosley-Floyd
Mayweather; De La Hoya-Vargas; De La Hoya-Reid. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
