A3185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAY2CHEAP-COX     07-13 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAY2CHEAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Way2Cheap bankruptcy shows debt of $1 million
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Four months after closing its doors, Way2Cheap
Inc. has gone to bankruptcy court to dispose of its assets.
</P>
<P>
   In its bankruptcy filing, Way2Cheap listed debts of more than $1
million owed to 359 creditors, including banks, parts suppliers and
former employees. Assets were $90,694, according to the filing.
</P>
<P>
   Others with a claim against Way2Cheap can file it with the
bankruptcy court, said Harry Hobbs, a trustee for the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``A trustee will be appointed and will go out and see what
assets, if any, there are to liquidate for creditors,'' Hobbs said.
``Once that's done, they'll file through all the claims. At this
point, all the claims against Way2Cheap would be resolved in the
bankruptcy court.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobbs said that with such steep debts and so few assets, it's
unlikely most claimants will get their money back.
</P>
<P>
   Once one of Austin's fastest growing small computer companies
with revenues of about $7 million in 1996, the company ran into
problems when sales were too weak to meet rising debts. In March,
the company closed its two Austin stores without warning.
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown left dozens of customers without computers. Some
ordered and paid for PCs, which they never got. Others had
computers in the stores for service and had to wait weeks to get
them back. Way2Cheap owner Chris Lott and his wife, Beth, filed for
personal bankruptcy last month, citing debts of more than $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Lotts' attorney, William Peckham, said the
couple had run up mostly credit-card debt _ some personal, some
business-related.
</P>
<P>
   The delay in the filings came from sorting out the debts and
liabilities for the personal and business bankruptcies and putting
together the list of creditors, Peckham said.
</P>
<P>
   Way2Cheap had built a reputation with good reviews for its
systems in Windows magazine. In addition to store sales, the
company also sold PCs by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
