<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE MEETS LIKE ABOARD SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 19)  
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are some pretty small niches in the cruise business, I
thought on receiving a flier from Bare Necessities, which sells
travel to clothing-optional fans, a k a nudists or naturists. But
when officials of this company said that their charter cruises had
been selling out their 800 to 1,100 places, I had to think again.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When I asked how these clients were found, Bare Necessities
referred me to a major U.S. nudist group, the American Association
for Nude Recreation in Kissimmee, Fla., which has 50,000 members
and 230 clubs. The spokeswoman for the group, Georgia Brown, says
that only a small proportion of those who take clothing-optional
cruises are ideological nudists. Most are travelers who relax by
going without clothes, and 30 percent are first-timers. So while
the brochure startled me a bit, the concept seems the same as
creating cruise charters for others with particular focuses:
golfers, for example, or people in 12-step recovery programs. I
took a look and found many new things.
</P>
<P>
   CLOTHING-OPTIONAL CRUISES: Bare Necessities Tour and Travel of
Austin, Texas, was established by Tom and Nancy Tiemann in 1990.
They have done charter cruises since, working with Holland America,
Cunard, Regal and other lines. As would be expected, the company
takes the whole ship. The 1998 Caribbean cruise was aboard the
Regal Empress in February. The big attraction was the eclipse of
the sun, but there were shore excursions to Curacao, Aruba and
Jamaica.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the coming year, the Caribbean cruise will be aboard
Carnival's Tropicale, leaving from Tampa, Fla., on Feb. 27 and
returning March 4. The prices range from $639 to $1,564 for one of
two people, plus taxes of $147.25 each.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Mediterranean cruise is scheduled for July 31-Aug. 6
aboard the Star Clipper, a 360-foot sailing vessel that takes 174
passengers. It leaves from Cannes, France, with calls at Corsica;
Sardinia; the island of Giglio and the village of Portovenere, both
in Italy; and Monte Carlo. The prices, without air fare, for one of
two people in a cabin range from $1,359 to $2,395, plus port taxes
estimated at $210. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bare Necessities Tour and Travel, 1802 W. Sixth St., Suite B,
Austin, TX 78703; (800) 743-0405; Web site:
www.bare-necessities.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Association for Nude Recreation, 1703 North Main St.,
Suite E, Kissimmee, FL 34744; (800) 879-6833; www.aanr.com.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christie Musick, owner of Travel au Naturel in Florida, books
smaller cruises aboard sailing vessels in the Caribbean for
male-female couples only. She says her October cruise out of
Grenada is sold out, and she is now well into the 1999 version
aboard the Yankee Clipper, a schooner. ``Some people wear all their
clothes, some wear a T-shirt, some just pants, some nothing,'' she
said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the '99 cruise, the Yankee Clipper will sail the Southern
Grenadines from Oct. 24 to 30; about half of the 64 berths are
gone. The price for one person in a cabin with two bunks is $1,195;
in a cabin with a lower bunk that will accommodate two people, the
price is $1,395 a person. All meals and an open bar, plus tips and
port charges are included, but not air fare to Grenada. Ms. Musick
books the October date because it includes a Halloween party.
Travel au Naturel, P.O. Box 890, Land o' Lakes, FL 34639; (800)
728-0185.
</P>
<P>
   SOBRIETY CRUISES: Steve Abrams and Guy Grand, brothers who own
Sober Vacations International in California, have two cruises
scheduled for people in recovery programs. Alcoholics Anonymous
operates no tours or trips, and does not endorse any, and ``AA'' is
not supposed to be used in any advertising, according to a
spokeswoman for the General Service Office of AA in New York. But
the words ``recovering'' and ``sober'' are enough to inform
potential travelers. Abrams and Grand, in recovery from different
addictions, say that 12-step meetings are scheduled, with speakers
like Clancy I. and Dr. Paul.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The brothers have been offering trips for 10 years, and have had
particular success working with Club Med to offer Sober Villages.
Their first Caribbean cruise, aboard Carnival's Fascination from
Jan. 23 to 30, leaves from San Juan, Puerto Rico. The price for one
of two people in a cabin ranges from $799 to $1,099, plus port
taxes of $121.50.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Their big coup, Abrams said, is the chartering of the new
American Queen river boat, with a capacity of 400, for a six-day
trip in 2000. It will leave the Twin Cities and cruise to St. Louis
after the close of the AA World Convention in Minneapolis on July
2, 2000. The itinerary is exotic in a different way: Winona,
Prairie du Chien, Dubuque and Hannibal, and the trip is already
half sold. The prices start at $1,590.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sober Vacation finds that New York and California each
contributes 15 percent of the company's business, and that single
people form 51 percent of the clientele. The rest are families and
couples. Sober Vacations International, 31368 Via Colinas, Suite
113, Westlake Village, CA 91362; (800) 762-3738; www.
sobervacations.com.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF CRUISES: Considering the lack of turf aboard ship, it may
seem odd, but the golfing cruise is a burgeoning niche. Wide World
of Golf in Carmel, Calif., is offering a big program through
Seabourn Cruise Line, which is now merged with Cunard, both of them
part of Carnival.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, Wide World of Golf has a dozen cruises to Southeast
Asia, the Caribbean, the Mediterranean, Europe, the East Coast and
Mexico. Lessons and lectures are given on board, and the cruises
make landfalls in places with notable links where the participants
get to play. The golfing has a price in addition to the cruise
price. For example, a cruise from Barbados to St. Thomas on the
Seabourn Legend from Feb. 13 to 20 provides chances to play at the
Mullet Bay club on St. Martin and Carambola on St. Croix. With two
rounds of golf plus the classes, the golf price is $850 each if 12
or more participate; the cruise price, for one of two people in a
cabin, ranges from $3,790 to $7,290, plus port fees of $185. Wide
World of Golf, Post Office Box 5217, Carmel, Calif. 93921; (408)
624-6667. Seabourn Cruise Line, 55 Francisco St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94133; (800) 929-9595. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The golf promoters are also looking to the millennium. Scotia
Travel, a Glasgow company, says it has chartered the QE2 for a
cruise from Southampton, England, to St. Andrews, Scotland, in time
for the British Open from July 20 to 23, 2000. The golfers will be
able to go ashore in the regular tenders, ``setting foot virtually
on the first tee.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scotia Travel said 200 of the 1,700 berths had been sold. The
price for the seven days _ the trans-Atlantic trip is not included
but will be available, the organizers say _ ranges from $2,999 for
one of two people in a cabin to $12,999. Tips and port and handling
fees are included, but not drinks. The fee to attend the match at
St. Andrews Old Course is definitely included. After the golf
tournament, the travelers will themselves be able to play St.
Andrews.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scotia Golf, 57 Bothwell St., Glasgow G2 6RF, Scotland; (44-141)
305-5050, fax (44-141) 305-5051; www.scotiatravel.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
