<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHRYSLER PROFITS DOUBLE, TOPPING ANALYSTS' FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler reported second-quarter earnings of $1.51 a share,
surpassing Wall Street's projections by about 10 cents a share. The
automaker's profits were more than double the strike-ridden second
quarter of last year, attributing the sound performance to strong
sales, cost- cutting and the growing popularity of high-margin
products like the Dodge Durango sports utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   TURMOIL IN JAPAN CAUSES NEW FEARS
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto of Japan
left a political vacuum at the economic heart of Asia, sending
stocks and currencies reeling across the continent and touching off
fears that another chapter could be beginning in the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN LOANS PACKAGE APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government and international lenders concluded an
agreement to ease Russia's financial crisis. The deal provides
$17.1 billion in additional loans in the next two years with most
of the money provided by the International Monetary Fund. The IMF
said it would have to borrow from its richest members to pay for
the bailout of Russia. The American share is expected to be $2.1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL RESPONDS TO ANTITRUST SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Intel said it acted lawfully in withholding some technology from
three computer companies and seeking to retrieve other technology
from them. It was Intel's first formal response to a Federal Trade
Commission antitrust lawsuit against the top computer-chip maker.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ SETS A RECORD; DOW FALLS
</P>
<P>
   A brighter earnings outlook for several leading technology
companies propelled the technology-laden Nasdaq composite index to
its fourth consecutive high. Other stock gauges were mixed. The Dow
Jones industrial average fell 9.53 points, to 9,096.21.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHER EARNINGS AT TWO BIG BANKS
</P>
<P>
   Nationsbank's quarterly earnings rose 53 percent on stronger
loan growth and improved investment banking and brokerage revenue.
First Chicago NBD earnings rose 8 percent on higher income from
bank fees that offset declines in loan income. The results at both
banks exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   TENNECO WAS NEAR DEAL FOR ITT UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Tenneco halted talks to buy the European brakes division of ITT
Industries, but two other bidders, the German tire maker
Continental A.G. and Ford Motor Company's Visteon Automotive
Systems, are said to be interested in the concern.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS RISE 39 PERCENT AT PAINE WEBBER
</P>
<P>
   Paine Webber Group said second-quarter earnings jumped 39
percent, to $129.5 million, or 82 cents a diluted share, from $93
million, or 58 cents, beating Wall Street forecasts of 78 cents.
Sales rose to $1.2 billion from $976 million. The record earnings
and revenues were attributed to strong asset management and
investment banking fees.
</P>
<P>
   MILAN JURY CONVICTS MEDIA TYCOON
</P>
<P>
   Silvio Berlusconi, the flamboyant media tycoon and former prime
minister of Italy, was convicted by a Milan jury of making illegal
political donations and was given a sentence of two years and four
months, as well as a $5.6 million fine. Mr. Berlusconi, 61, was
convicted last week of bribing tax inspectors and sentenced to a
term of two years and nine months. He was also convicted of
accounting fraud in a separate trial in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
