</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IND-BAYH-PROFILE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN INDIANA, A LESS LIBERAL BAYH SEEKS THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ When Birch Evans Bayh Jr., the notable Democratic
U.S. senator of the 1960s and '70s, first learned that his son
wanted to run for public office, the elder Bayh was wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my first thought was, was that something he really
wanted to do or is that something he wanted to do just because his
father wanted to do it?'' Bayh recalled recently.
</P>
<P>
   And during the son's first campaign _ for Indiana secretary of
state in 1986 _ the father said he wanted his son to make his own
way. ``If he said, `Dad, can you call so-and-so?' I would say,
`Yes, I can call so-and-so, but are you sure that's what you want
to have happen?'''
</P>
<P>
   The son, Birch Evans Bayh III, who prefers to be called Evan
Bayh, won that race and went on to be governor of Indiana. And now,
Bayh, 42, is running for the Senate seat that his father lost in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   He is favored to win back his father's seat for the Democrats.
But Evan Bayh is not a carbon copy.
</P>
<P>
   While his father, now 70, spent 18 years in office as a
prominent Great Society liberal, Evan Bayh is a fiscal conservative
who takes credit for balancing his state's budget, implementing
welfare reform and cutting taxes. While his father wrote
constitutional amendments, including the one lowering the voting
age to 18, and helped block two of President Nixon's Supreme Court
nominees, Evan Bayh has practiced what he describes as a politics
of ``pragmatic,'' incremental change, an approach that supporters
praise as savvy and critics consider overly cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes making progress a step at a time is better than no
progress at all,'' Bayh said in an interview at the Democratic
Party's campaign headquarters across from the state Capitol. ``If
by demanding revolutionary change, I run the risk of accomplishing
nothing on behalf of the public, then I'm not sure that's a
responsible course of action.''
</P>
<P>
   Bayh is enormously popular in Indiana, with his famous name, his
earnest manner, his good looks and his risk-averse governing style
in a state dominated by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   He has also been mentioned as a prospect for higher office. Held
up as the embodiment of President Clinton's ``New Democrat''
policies, Bayh gave the keynote speech at the 1996 Democratic
National Convention. While he was edged out of prime-time airplay
by other speakers, and pundits said his performance lacked
excitement, Bayh came across as a good sport, appearing on stage
with his wife, Susan, a lawyer, and their twins, Nicholas and Beau,
then 9 months old.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of boy the people in Indiana would like their
daughters to bring home,'' said Brian Vargus, a political science
professor at Indiana University-Purdue University at Indianapolis.
``Mr. Clean, crisp, Boy Wonder, young, attractive, articulate,
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Bayh gets chided by more liberal Democrats, who, Vargus said,
privately ``refer to him as a Republicrat.''
</P>
<P>
   While Republican leaders consider the race for this seat,
vacated by Sen. Dan Coats, to be their toughest senatorial election
this year, they are running a well-credentialed candidate, Paul
Helmke, 49, the three-term mayor of Fort Wayne, Indiana's
second-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evan still comes across a little the empty suit,'' said
Helmke, a moderate Republican who won a three-way primary and has
achieved some national prominence of his own, as a former president
of the U.S. Conference of Mayors. ``He looks good. He sounds good.
But there's a sense that he's trying to be all things to all
people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Born on Dec. 26, 1955, in Terre Haute, Ind., Evan Bayh was
swaddled in politics. His mother, Marvella Bayh, was the daughter
of an Indiana governor, Matthew Welsh. His father ran twice for the
Democratic nomination for president, dropping out in 1972 because
his wife was stricken with cancer, which took her life in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   When Evan Bayh was 6, he accompanied his parents to the home of
former President Truman, where his father was seeking advice about
his first Senate race. He remembers that Truman gave him a silver
dollar and that sometime in the political discussion he blurted
out, ``I have to go to the bathroom.'' Truman rescued him from his
mother's mortified looks by saying, ``You know, son, I have to go
the bathroom, too,'' and taking him there.
</P>
<P>
   At a White House dinner with his mother and father, Evan saw
President Johnson put his feet up on the table and was escorted by
Lady Bird Johnson into the Lincoln Bedroom to watch television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evan grew up in a very public home,'' said his father, now
practicing law in Washington. Bayh said Evan was aware that his
father was controversial because of the judicial appointments and
other liberal stances, and once heard a phone caller threaten to
kill the senator.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Bayh helped run his father's unsuccessful last Senate
campaign, against Dan Quayle in 1980, and the loss ``probably hurt
him more than it hurt me,'' the elder Bayh said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, at age 32, the son was elected the nation's
youngest governor and served the maximum two terms. Bayh, who
contended with Republican-dominated Legislatures during his tenure
but benefited from a robust economy, said his accomplishments
included creation of 350,000 jobs and doubling the state surplus,
to $1.6 billion, the largest in state history. He trimmed a deficit
in state pension plans and sliced Medicaid spending to restore the
state's fiscal health.
</P>
<P>
   There were no tax increases. He did try to raise taxes on
hospitals and cigarettes, but was blocked by Republican
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts say Bayh, who has been practicing corporate
law since 1996, made few major advances on issues like education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of his governorship time was devoted to dollars-and-cents
kinds of issues,'' said Jay McCann, associate professor of
political science at Purdue University.
</P>
<P>
   Although a polished spinner of phrases, Bayh said he resisted
``generalizations'' and ``buzzwords,'' believing that most issues
were complex. He gets ideas from reading history and biographies
that he orders from a history book club. He just started Theodore
White's ``Thunder Out of China,'' because he is ``trying to learn
more about foreign policy and defense policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bayh said that as senator he would work to raise educational
standards and support ``a flatter, fairer tax.'' While government
should help the disadvantaged, he said, ``personal responsibility
has to go hand in hand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to find the sensible center,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
