</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-STANDOFF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas mother jailed after holding knife to daughters' throats
 &HT;    By Bob Banta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A woman fighting eviction from her home was
arrested Monday after she kept police at bay for more than five
hours by holding a knife to the throats of her two 13-year-old
daughters, officers said.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff, which began about 9 a.m. Monday in central East
Austin, ended about 2:15 p.m. Monday when Nailah Sankofa's
daughters left the home under a police escort and Sankofa
surrendered shortly afterward. No one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The incident started when Travis County Constable Jesse
Villalovos went to the home to serve an eviction notice, and
Sankofa picked up a kitchen knife. ``She held it at their (the
daughters' )throats and moved the knife back and forth in her hands
between them,'' Villalovos said.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Police Department SWAT team officers surrounded the home,
sending in a hostage negotiator to talk to the woman, who had
barricaded herself in a bathroom with the two girls.
</P>
<P>
   Among those neighbors who observed the situation was Pam Wade,
vice president of the Robertson Hill Neighborhood Association.
</P>
<P>
   Wade said Sankofa, 37, was public relations coordinator for the
neighborhood group. ``She does a wonderful job,'' Wade said. ``She
is a talented writer and is trying to go back to school to get her
Ph.D. She is just down on her luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade said police should have allowed Sankofa to talk with
friends. ``I don't think Anglo police understand the situation of a
black, single mom who is down on her luck,'' Wade said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Police Chief Michael McDonald said the police
negotiators did a good job. ``The lines of communication between
the lady and the negotiator were always open,'' McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   Sankofa was taken to the Austin State Hospital for a
psychological evaluation and then booked into the Travis County
Jail, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The girls were examined by Emergency Medical Services paramedics
and then placed in a foster home, according to Marla Sheely of the
Texas Department of Protective and Regulatory Services.
</P>
<P>
   Sheely said her agency will investigate the possibility of
placing the teen-agers with family or friends. She said the girls
will be given counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
