</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge meets with tobacco lawyers
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEXARKANA, Texas _ U.S. District Judge David Folsom divided
lawyers representing opposing sides into two negotiating groups
Monday in a push get the $15.3 billion Texas tobacco settlement
finished, once and maybe for all.
</P>
<P>
   In what might be called state line diplomacy, Folsom scattered
the lawyers among three floors of the U.S. Courthouse astride the
Texas-Arkansas line. The lawyers and the judge shuttled between the
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that the parties are here to try to work out all their
differences,'' Folsom said before the closed-door meetings began.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom had summoned the lawyers to Texarkana for a status report
on negotiations that have been ongoing since shortly after the
state and the tobacco industry settled the case in January. The
judge said he was not seeking to mediate the dispute himself but
clearly he was pressing the parties to resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dan Morales, who participated in the talks,
said ``the court is serious about wanting to encourage resolution
of this this week. And I think we're on track to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Two principal issues are stalling the tobacco settlement, the
largest recovery from a lawsuit in U.S. history. One issue involves
a challenge Gov. George W. Bush and seven Texas legislators to the
amount Folsom awarded for legal fees to private lawyers Morales
hired to sue cigarette manufacturers. Folsom awarded 15 percent of
the recovery _ as much as $2.3 billion _ to the lawyers. That
reflected their 15 percent contingency fee contract with Morales,
an arrangement the judge analyzed for its reasonableness.
</P>
<P>
   The second issue challenges how the $15.3 billion recovery will
be divided. Seven large counties and public hospital districts sued
to share the money and more than 100 smaller counties want part of
it too.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said the county hospital issue was complex, but declared
``substantial progress made on all issues'' late Monday. The
governor's general counsel, Margaret Wilson, involved in resolving
the legal fees dispute, seemed more reserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not make as much progress today as we had hoped,''
Wilson said, ``but we are still going to work on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, addressing the tobacco talks with reporters in Austin,
said his representatives had ``fleshed out'' an agreement he
accepted. ``As you know, I'm only involved with the lawsuit
regarding the legal fees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Travis County state District Judge Jim Myer mediated the
major block to the settlement, the county hospital issue.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers involved in the meetings said privately that Folsom
clearly was pushing for resolution of the remaining disputes, but
none was willing to predict he would get one this week. Morales
left Texarkana late Monday to go to New York for renewed
negotiations for yet another settlement with the tobacco companies
that could enhance Texas' recovery by $2 billion or so. Morales
said he would return to Texarkana on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even if an agreement is reached in principle with the counties
and hospital districts, Morales said, a final agreement would take
at least several days to get approval from the commissioners courts
and district boards involved.
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from Osler McCarthy and Ken
Herman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
