the raid is indicative of the way the Italian fashion business will
change in the next five years: a phalanx of generational family
businesses giving way to family-controlled public enterprises that
can compete globally.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- July 13, 1998 -- NEW-YORKER-EDITOR, 7-13 --
Pulitzer Prize-winning author David Remnick, whom Tina Brown
personally recruited to The New Yorker as a staff writer, is named
Monday to succeed her as editor of the magazine. Remnick, 39, who
has written more than 100 articles for the magazine, will take over
when Ms. Brown leaves Aug. 1. Remnick says his top priority will be
``to edit a magazine of hilarity, deep reporting, literary quality
and moral seriousness.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- July 13, 1998 -- NY-MIMEO, 7-13 -- ``A Secret
Location on the Lower East Side: Adventures in Writing,
1960-1980,'' at the main branch of the New York Public Library
through July 25, documents the rich, four-decade-long indie
phenomenon in American literature, often called the ``mimeograph
revolution.'' The show encompasses some 400 publications, from
quick-and-dirty pamphlets to elegantly designed books. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BATAVIA, Ill. -- July 13, 1998 -- SCI-LEDERMAN-Q&AMP;A, 7-13
-- Dr. Leon Lederman at the center named for him at Fermilab in
Batavia. Since his retirement from Fermilab, Lederman has become an
advocate for improved science education. He is the chairman of the
board of the Teachers Academy for Mathematics and Science, an
organization that shows primary school teachers how to teach modern
mathematics and science. ``Teaching is show business,'' he says.
(Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- July 13, 1998 -- MARITAL-BLITZ-BOS,
7-13 -- Dan Zevin, an author and humorist, poses with a photo taken
at his wedding of his wife, Megan, and himself. Zevin, 33, first
book, ``Entry Level Life,'' is a tongue-in-cheek, how-to book for
recent college graduates about surviving in the real world. His
most recent work is ``The Nearly-Wed Handbook - How to Survive the
Happiest Day of Your Life'' (Avon Books), a spoof of
wedding-planning guides. (Tom Herde/New York Times Photo)
</P>
