<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980713.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3219 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCTIC-ANIMAL-GUARDIA     07-13 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCTIC-ANIMAL-GUARDIAN-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENGUIN KEEPER'S EDEN NO TUXEDO JUNCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you're looking for someone who knows penguins, you
could do worse than have a chat with Celia Ackerman, a zoo keeper
at the Central Park Zoo. She knows the names of the 38 birds in the
penguin building and can tell you where their immigrant ancestors
came from. (They were collected, as eggs in the Antarctic, by the
people at Sea World, and shipped, after hatching, to New York.)
</P>
<P>
   Why do people seem to like penguins so much?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the cutesy-cutesy,'' says Ms. Ackerman, who has the
wholesome, patient, competent-in-the-wild style every mother would
want for her child's camp counselor, but with this question sounds
a little exasperated.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Ohhh, they look like they're wearing little
tuxedos.' As an animal person, I don't care for it. I would rather
see respect for the animal. They look the way they do for a
particular reason. When they swim in the ocean, for the predators,
looking up, white is hard to see. Looking down from above, the
black is camouflage.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hot outside. Want to meet somebody who works where the
temperature is 34 degrees? That was the invitation from the public
relations people at the Wildlife Conservation Society, which runs
the Central Park Zoo, and what kind of fool would decline? The
flower gardens are thick and scented; the sea lions, whom Ms.
Ackerman also cares for, perform obligingly. In the penguin house,
behind a glass wall, the adult penguins and a few newly hatched
chicks trundle and dive (actually, plop).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ackerman, 35, is a zoo keeper in the Polar Zone. She arrives
at 7:30 in the morning and often works an 11-hour day, washing the
habitats, thawing the fish (some of which are vitamin-packed),
caring for the animals.
</P>
<P>
   The questions of a reporter, regarding her personal life, make
Ms. Ackerman wary. Ms. Ackerman seems to have a strong bond with
the animals: Is she a religious person? Ms. Ackerman knits her brow
suspiciously. Is there anyone in her personal life? Ms. Ackerman
would rather not say.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Ms. Ackerman is not squeamish.
</P>
<P>
   How does a vitamin-packed fish get that way?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ackerman picks up a deceased herring, gets a vitamin B
tablet and shoves it into the fish's gill. Minutes later,
accompanied by another keeper, James Ayala, Ms. Ackerman puts on
her down jacket, opens a thick refrigerator door and goes into the
manmade Arctic. When she enters, a young penguin rubs its head
against her leg. The rest wait their turn to eat. Some are eager.
With others, Ms. Ackerman has to open their bills and ease the fish
down their gullets.
</P>
<P>
   It brings to mind the food chain. The vitamins are shoved into
the fish, the fish are stuffed into the penguins and the reluctant
Ms. Ackerman has been offered up to the reporter. It takes the
penguins 40 minutes to dine, after which Ms. Ackerman turns to the
next feeding.
</P>
<P>
   She was brought up in the Flatbush area of Brooklyn, Ms.
Ackerman says; her father owned a diner, her mother was a
housewife. As a child, Ms. Ackerman watched Jacques Cousteau and
``Flipper'' and wildlife shows. A scene she found particularly
upsetting showed a pack of wolves trying to get away from people
who were shooting at them from a helicopter. The snow was deep, the
wolves floundered. Ms. Ackerman decided then, ``there were not
enough people in the world taking care of animals.''
</P>
<P>
   While in high school, she worked as a volunteer at the aquarium
and left Brooklyn College after one year, when a full-time job at
the aquarium came through.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ackerman has worked in Central Park, where she earns
approximately $30,000, for 10 years. She says she still finds every
day exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Is Ms. Ackerman a spiritual person?
</P>
<P>
   ``In my own way I am,'' Ms. Ackerman says. ``The Native
Americans, when they hunted a deer, gave thanks to the spirit of
the deer for sacrificing itself. They called the animals `brother'
and `sister.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Ackerman pauses, concerned about coming off as a New Age
flake, revering animals and their skins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't thank my shoes,'' Ms. Ackerman says. ``I don't go that
far. I don't give thanks at every meal, but I do give thanks
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   It would seem on a day like today, when the weather is fine and
the Zoo is Eden, that Ms. Ackerman has the best job in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Ms. Ackerman. ``On days like this, everybody wants a
zoo job. But there's also winter. We had one winter when for two
weeks it didn't get out of the teens.''
</P>
<P>
   That cold? So did Ms. Ackerman ever have a yen to take a few of
the penguins out for a stroll?
</P>
<P>
   A look from Ms. Ackerman suggests you might as well ask them to
read Sartre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you want to do that?'' Ms. Ackerman asks. ``There's
nothing out there that would interest them. Our penguins have
everything they need. They're happy.''
</P>
<P>
   A day later, after the visit by the note-taking mammal, Ms.
Ackerman calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep asking me what I get from the animals,'' Ms. Ackerman
says. ``When I go inside the penguin cage and clean, sometimes they
exhibit bowing behavior. They bow down to the ground and spread
their wings. It's like a greeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a bird's been away from the nest, some times they do it.
`Hello, I'm here.' Sometimes you see birds bowing down together. It
makes me feel honored, you know, when they do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
