<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMELESS-CARTS-NYT &LR;      07-13 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-CARTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE HOMELESS IN L.A., A NEW SET OF WHEELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the homeless on the streets of Skid Row here,
just a couple of blocks from the glass towers of downtown, a
shopping cart is much more than a basket on squeaky wheels. It is
also a rolling closet, a hope chest and an office, and sometimes a
ticket to jail since the carts are typically the property of
grocery stores and other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people who have spent 30 days in jail for pushing a
shopping cart down the street,'' said Jeff Dietrich of the Los
Angeles Catholic Worker, a group that feeds the poor of the Row.
``It's a scandal that people are forced to push their few
possessions in shopping carts. It is far more scandalous for people
to be arrested for being poor.''
</P>
<P>
   So Monday, in front of the Central City East police station
downtown, the Catholic Worker, with two lawyers on hand, began
distributing 100 brand-new black shopping carts to the homeless.
The group had bought the carts _ $100 apiece, Dietrich said _ and
affixed a sign to each saying that it belonged to the Catholic
Worker and that the homeless were authorized to use it ``within the
County of Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Dietrich said the distribution was helping not only the homeless
but also the authorities, by ``alleviating the police from having
to worry so much about shopping carts and harassing the poor.'' He
said that right in front of the Catholic Worker soup kitchen, he
had watched police officers give people tickets for having shopping
carts, make them dump their belongings out of the carts and then
give them tickets for littering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that as issues go, this isn't the most important,'' he
said. ``But harassing people over shopping carts is just part of
the continuum of mistreating the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   As several homeless people claimed their carts Monday, a group
of police officers, including Capt. Richard Bonneau, watched from
the steps of the police station.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholic Worker people are well intentioned, but misguided
on this issue,'' Bonneau said. Many of the people who wander the
streets day and night pushing shopping carts, he said, use them for
criminal activity, ``as ladders to break into buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonneau said his officers confiscated 20 to 50 carts a week from
homeless people downtown. ``But I suspect we'll be powerless to do
anything about these,'' he said, pointing to the long line of new
carts parked in front of the station.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Mathis, 36, who took one of the carts, said she was
``tired of getting tickets from the police.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a perfect idea,'' Ms. Mathis said. ``You can have 100
pounds of stuff in your cart, and the police say, `Get it out.' You
say, `I can't carry all this.' But they don't care. Now they have
to care.''
</P>
<P>
   When Robert Hosey, 59, was handed a new cart Monday, he said:
``Wow! This is a Cadillac.'' He gave a shove to his old shopping
cart _ one of those that had earned him tickets _ and added, ``Now
I got to get rid of this Chevy before it gets me in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Hosey said he used a cart to make a meager living on the street,
collecting bottles and cans and anything else that could fetch him
a few nickels and dimes. On one occasion, he said, he had a cart
full of glass that he was pushing toward a recycling center when he
was stopped by police and ordered to dump his cargo onto the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying the police were wrong,'' Hosey said. ``It's the
law and all. But a guy has to do something. You can't carry a
hundred pounds of glass on your back. I just thank God I got my own
cart now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
