<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BRAWLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE BRAWLEY VERDICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, July 14:
</P>
<P>
   Monday's verdict in the case against Tawana Brawley's former
advisers was a healthy one. Freedom of speech would not have been
well served if Americans got the impression that it protects the
systematic defamation the Rev. Al Sharpton, C. Vernon Mason and
Alton Maddox directed at Steven Pagones. Sharpton's decade-old dare
that if Pagones was unhappy he could ``sue us so we can go into
court with you'' has boomeranged.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Miss Brawley's former advisers, the jury appeared to have
been trying to make its judgments carefully. Although the three men
appeared bent on muddying every issue by withholding Miss Brawley
from investigators, and failing to even question her themselves
about what had happened, the jury decided they had not been engaged
in a conspiracy to defame Pagones. Rather it found that Sharpton,
Mason and Maddox had willfully ignored the reality that was right
in front of them, in a manner so blatant as to fit the high
threshold of defamation law. They also found that Sharpton made two
statements about Pagones he knew were false.
</P>
<P>
   The figure upon whom the verdict will fall hardest is Sharpton,
who has evolved into a well-known figure in New York politics at
the same time his former associates were fading from view.
Ironically, his talents as a public speaker got him into the
deepest trouble. Having spoken much more on television and in press
interviews than have his co-defendants, he had more to answer for,
and the jury found him guilty on seven different counts.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton has become a different sort of public figure over the
last decade, far more moderate and inclusive than in his Brawley
days. He has argued that New York voters should put that episode
behind them, and acknowledge the good things he has done since,
including publicly forgiving a white man who stabbed him after a
civil rights march.
</P>
<P>
   The Tawana Brawley episode took place at a time when some
activists, Sharpton included, seemed to believe that past
injustices gave them a right to mold the truth in any way that
served their political ends. But this verdict supports the view
that a decent respect for facts is essential to healing racial
dialogue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
