<HEADLINE>
UNROLLING THE NFL'S PRESEASON AD CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The annual advertising offensive to stimulate interest in
National Football League games will begin almost two months earlier
than usual and involve almost four times as many promotional
commercials as before.
</P>
<P>
   The fast start and increased exposure for the NFL's sales pitch
are a result of the league's most lucrative contracts ever with the
broadcast and cable television networks, covering the 1998-99
season. ABC, CBS, ESPN and Fox will run more than 2,200 NFL spots,
which are scheduled to begin appearing Wednesday, in all parts of
their schedules, including early morning, daytime and prime time.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, about 600 league promotional spots ran for the
1997-98 season and did not begin until Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our network partners are giving us a significant amount of
additional time'' to help ``manage an ongoing dialogue with our fan
base,'' said Howard Handler, senior vice president for marketing
and fan development at NFL Properties in New York. NFL Properties
is the in-house unit of the league responsible for the campaign
along with NFL Films in Mount Laurel, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL barrage will run in addition to the myriad commercials
that each network will run for its own game coverage. CBS, for
example, has a campaign carrying the theme ``The NFL on CBS ... The
way it should be!''
</P>
<P>
   The ratcheting up of the football spiel is indicative of the
intensifying effort to sell sports programming to viewers even
when, in the case of football, surveys show that fans continue to
anticipate coming seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the competition for people's time,'' Handler said,
``it's important for us to reach out to as broad an audience as
possible to draw them into our games.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998-99 campaign, like its two predecessors, is aimed at
reinforcing ties with so-called core fans, most of whom are men, as
well as generating attention from what are known as casual fans,
many of whom are women, children, teen-agers and twentysomethings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to build the connection with the players, the clubs,
the game,'' Handler said, ``so fans spend more time watching games,
visiting stadiums, playing football.''
</P>
<P>
   Trade publications have reported that the NFL is most concerned
about addressing fans ages 18-34 to stem an erosion in support
among them. But Handler said that in communicating with casual
fans, the various components ``share equal importance,'' adding,
``If I had to choose, it would be the kids, because that's where
the seeds of commitment are being sown.''
</P>
<P>
   That explains the quite youthful tone and tenor of the 1998-99
campaign, which will again carry the theme ``Feel the power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The message we want to send through everything is that the NFL
provides a thrill ride,'' Handler said, ``an adrenaline-charged
roller coaster ride.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One completed television commercial and several that he
presented in preliminary form are infused with hip, contemporary
argot and attitude, much of it with roots in black culture.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said Bruce W. Burke, vice president and creative
director at NFL Properties, one component of the campaign,
conveying ``the emotions of the game,'' is called ``Rhythm,'' and
another, about star players, is called ``Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, announcers use phrases like ``you getting
phatter'' and ``gives his props.'' Two spots focused on preseason
practice are set to a funk version of ``Summertime'' and a rap
tune.
</P>
<P>
   Those who welcome a touch of tradition with their football will
find it, too. Many of the spots feature the measured intonation and
rolling cadence of John Facenda, the longtime narrator of NFL game
footage who was described by Tripp Dixon, a director at NFL Films,
as ``the voice of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon said the NFL Films archives were being canvassed for work
by the narrator, who died in 1984, that could be matched to
contemporary footage for the commercials. The preseason rap spot,
for example, includes Facenda-speak about ``the legions of the
sun'' and ``Super Bowl dreams that glow in the sunshine.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the television commercials, there will be print
advertisements for the Pro Line of apparel licensed by NFL
Properties, which will run in sports magazines like Sports
Illustrated, Sport and ESPN Magazine as well as in music magazines
like Spin, The Source and Vibe.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's major marketing partners are also drawing up ambitious
plans for the 1998-99 season. Visa USA, for one, will embark on an
advertising and promotional program that includes sponsorship of
the halftime report on the football games covered by the Fox
Broadcasting Company, part of News Corp.; a ``Kickoff '98'' retail
promotion at 131 shopping malls around the country, and two
30-second commercials during Super Bowl XXXIII on Fox on Jan. 31,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Two other spots, set to appear in late August, will be centered
on two teammates on the San Francisco 49ers, quarterback Steve
Young and wide receiver Jerry Rice. The Visa ad agency is BBDO New
York, a unit of Omnicom Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
