<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC WORKERS ACCUSE L.I. COMPANY OF DISCRIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Charging that they were the target of a litany
of ethnic slurs and numerous instances of employment discrimination
based on race, 21 Hispanic workers have filed a civil rights suit
against a Long Island paper products company formed by immigrants
from Iran.
</P>
<P>
   In court documents filed in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn and
served Monday on officials of the American Tissue Company in
Hauppauge, the 21 workers, immigrants from El Salvador, Guatemala
and Ecuador, said that as Hispanics they had been subjected over
the last several years to a hostile work environment and that
non-Hispanic employees had been given preferred treatment in
promotions and conditions of employment. When the Hispanic
employees complained, they contended, they were fired.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the plaintiffs said they had been subjected to
epithets and insults such as ``stupid Spanish'' and ``Spanish
animals.'' They also said that supervisors had called members of
their families ``dogs,'' ``dirt'' and ``mentally retarded.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the company denied the charges, saying that as
refugees and entrepreneurs, the company's Iranian founders had
sought to hire minority workers, including Hispanics, as part of
their belief in the ``American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This dispute has nothing to do with race and human rights,''
the lawyer, George Isaacson, said, ``but everything to do with a
failed effort by a group of Latino workers to unionize the company.
They lost that battle and are suing out of frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Chavez, an immigrant from El Salvador who worked for the
company for five and a half years and was a union organizer, said
that American Tissue had denied him and other workers training and
advancement and had forced them to work overtime, up to 17 hours a
day, and sometimes seven days a week. Their average salary was $5
an hour, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The supervisor treated everyone very badly,'' Chavez said.
``For example, when workers did overtime on July 4, 1996, the
company did not pay in the right way. When I complained, I was
called into the office and was accused of being an agitator.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said that he and the other plaintiffs had been dismissed
after employees had voted 80-29 against joining Local 707 of the
International Brotherhood of Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs took their complaint to the New York state
Division of Human Rights, which after an investigation supported
their claim that they had been victims of discrimination. The New
York-based Center for Constitutional Rights put their complaint
into the form of a lawsuit, which seeks back wages and overtime and
an end to discriminatory practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suit is important,'' said Barbara J. Olshansky, a lawyer
for the Center for Constitutional Rights, ``not only to vindicate
the plaintiffs' rights but also to send a message to employers that
such egregious violations of workers' basic rights will not be
tolerated.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Isaacson said he had not received a copy of the lawsuit Monday,
but denied all of the charges against the company. ``This dispute
has been going on for the last two years, and I doubt there is
anything new,'' he said. ``This company has been an American
success story for its Iranian founder, Mehdi Gabayzadeh, who came
here as a refugee. He has hired a large contingent of Latino
Americans, also immigrants from India, Afghanistan and Poland. All
the immigrants have helped to make the company a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadia Marin, a lawyer for the Workplace Project, a nonprofit
organization serving Hispanic workers in Nassau and Suffolk
Counties, described discriminatory employment practices against
Hispanics on Long Island as commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them cannot speak English, are fearful of losing their
jobs and are taken advantage of,'' she said. ``They are not aware
that they have rights. What's different about this incident is that
there were people who were willing to speak out and willing to file
a lawsuit. That takes a lot of courage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
