<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-GAYS-FAMILYRATE-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GAY MEN FIGHT TOWN HALL FOR A FAMILY POOL PASS DISCOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HARTFORD, Conn. _ What Mark Melanson loves about living in
the suburbs with his gay partner, he says, is that they have a lot
in common with everybody else in their suburban neighborhood,
including the elderly woman who lives next door and the nuclear
family down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're professionals,'' Melanson said. ``We take good care of
our property. The fact that we're gay doesn't even factor into the
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps that is why Melanson expected to be treated no
differently from anyone else last winter when he asked for a family
discount at the town-run pools for himself and his partner, Michael
P. Antisdale.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the gay couple's request was rejected in June by the
Town Council, whose leaders say they believe the pool may lose
money if the town gives family discounts to any groups of people
who live in the same household, including siblings, roommates and
gay couples. Melanson and Antisdale have found themselves at the
center of a townwide debate.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, the Town Council is expected to consider a
proposal for an expanded discount that would apply to gay couples
and other types of households, but the measure's supporters are not
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   In this Hartford suburb, usually known for its liberalism, about
100 people showed up at a Town Council meeting last month to
support the couple. Republican members, who took control of the
Council in November for the first time in more than a decade, said
they were being unfairly labeled homophobic.
</P>
<P>
   Colin McEnroe, a radio talk show host who grew up in town and
moved back here about five years ago, said that the debate
reflected a failure by some residents to understand ``the changing
nature of suburban life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Which is not to say the traditional nuclear family is gone,''
he said. ``But the idea of one house after the other of Cleaver
families _ it doesn't really work like that anymore.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Melanson, 36, and Antisdale, 40, wrote to the Town Council last
winter, after managers of the town-owned Cornerstone Aquatic Center
refused to give them a family membership. An individual membership
was $345 a year at the time. A family membership is $395.
</P>
<P>
   Both men, who have lived in town 10 years, said the fees seemed
blatantly unfair. They said they did not understand why they should
pay more than a married couple.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Republicans on the Council, who control the board 6-3,
reduced the individual membership fee by $50. ``They just made
discrimination more affordable,'' Melanson said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Robert Bouvier, a Republican who serves on the Council,
said that the town did its best to accommodate the men's request.
He said he is not biased against gay and lesbian people. He
compared a husband, wife and three children living on one income
with a gay couple living on two incomes and asked, ``Who's better
able to handle the fees at the pool?'' The rationale for the
longstanding family rate, he added, is to encourage children to
learn to swim. If the town gives gay couples the same rate, Bouvier
said, ``You're putting them on par with traditional families.''
</P>
<P>
   Council Democrats support either a household rate equal to the
family rate or further study of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Conaty, communications director for the National Gay and
Lesbian Task Force, said that the issue reflects the discrimination
that gay and lesbian families face nationwide, but that conditions
are improving. About 350 corporations and 60 municipalities,
including West Hartford, now offer partner benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Antisdale, director of marketing for Raytel Medical Corp. in
Windsor, said that he and Melanson, a senior business analyst for
Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Connecticut, crossed a line in
speaking out about this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no problems as a gay couple,'' Antisdale said. ``But as
soon as we raised our hands and said, `We want the same things you
want,' the answer was `No.' And the response from some Town Council
members was even like, `How dare you ask.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the men said they have been encouraged by support from
neighbors, friends and even strangers. Antisdale and Melanson said
they plan to stay in West Hartford, where they still feel they
belong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were both raised in middle-class families,'' Antisdale
said, ``where the expectation was we would go to college, we would
become educated, we'd get a nice white-collar job, we'd move up and
own a nice house in the suburbs. And that's exactly what we've
done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
