<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHER-FIRED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRED TEACHER TO GET 2 WEEKS' BACK PAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MACARENA HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A city teacher who was fired a month ago for asking
her sixth- graders if they wanted to accept Jesus Christ as their
saviour will receive two weeks' back pay, Board of Education
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, Mildred Rosario, 43, of Manhattan, will be
compensated for the two weeks that remained in the school year
after her dismissal on June 12, said David Galarza, a board
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Rosario filed a grievance with her union, the United
Federation of Teachers, challenging her dismissal and seeking the
back pay. ``They took away those last two weeks with my students,''
she said Monday. ``They can't take back all the suffering my
students and I have been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. Rosario will not get her job back as a bilingual
teacher at Intermediate School 74 in the Bronx, she is free to
apply for a job with any other city school district, Galarza said.
Mrs. Rosario said she met with her lawyers Monday to discuss what
to do next.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy began on June 8, when Mrs. Rosario led her
pupils in prayer and laid her hands on their foreheads after the
children asked about a classmate who had recently drowned. The next
day, a sister-in-law of one of the pupils complained to the
principal.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education ruled that her actions violated the
constitutional separation of church and state and fired her four
days later.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Rosario's dismissal has attracted national support from
groups like the Religious Freedom Coalition and from some
Republicans in Congress, including the House majority whip, Tom
DeLay of Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-98 2302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
