<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BRAWLEY-PAGONES-AR     07-13 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-PAGONES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFAMED LAWYER SAYS LIFE WON'T SUDDENLY RETURN TO NORMAL
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Steven Pagones is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(With NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL, NY-BRAWLEY-SHARPTON, NY-BRAWLEY-CHRONO.) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Their life together has never been normal,
Steven and Niki Pagones were saying Monday, just hours after the
verdict had come in. Their wedding, their first child, the birth of
identical twin girls _ not a blessed event has gone by untainted by
a thought or mention of the Tawana Brawley affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lies,'' Pagones said again, this time with the force of
law.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife say they cannot wake up in the morning without
stepping past a home office in their bedroom that overflows with
the articles, videotapes and legal detritus of 10 difficult years.
The ``Tawana junk,'' Mrs. Pagones calls it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be more than happy to just shove it in the garbage,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   They know, of course, that putting it all behind them will take
much more than a wastebasket. ``It'll take time, I guess,'' Pagones
said. ``As time goes on, hopefully, I'll be able to almost put this
aside, into a part of my life where I don't have to think about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, he said. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe five or 10 years,'' his wife suggested, laughing a
little.
</P>
<P>
   A jury had just vindicated Pagones, saying that Miss Brawley's
three former advisers, C. Vernon Mason, Alton Maddox and the Rev.
Al Sharpton had defamed him a decade ago when they accused him of
raping and kidnapping the 15-year-old black teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Pagones showed little joy to the friends and well-wishers
who came up to slap him on the shoulder and kiss his wife as they
sipped drinks together in a tavern down a hill from the Dutchess
County Courthouse. He managed a smile and a sincere thanks. But he
kept getting up and excusing himself, finding a corner to collect
himself, to wipe his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he had heard his wife's voice crack as she spoke to
reporters. ``You'd think I'd be elated, but I'm saddened,'' she had
said, her lips quavering. Standing behind her, Pagones gently
touched his head to hers. She bucked up.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones said he was afraid he would break down, too, but years
of concealing his emotions kicked in. ``If I became emotional about
this over the past eight months, I probably wouldn't be able to see
it through,'' he said. ``I built up this protective wall, which
enabled me to deal with the press, the threats, the rude
statements. But as soon as I came home, that wall went down.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Pagones could not talk about the case with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   He would retreat to a darkened room and unwind in a chair, or
listen to the TV news out of earshot of her and the children. Mrs.
Pagones, a lawyer at her father-in-law's firm, would ask her boss
about the case to keep up, or listen while her husband spoke on the
phone about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She left it alone,'' Pagones said. ``She did that for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Pagones said, he has been having nightmares about
the case, waking his wife with terrifying screams.
</P>
<P>
   It might not have just been from the stress, he said. At home,
he and his family still feel vulnerable. ``We still get death
threats,'' he said. ``We've had people come to the house. Just last
week, some guy stalked me from New York City, a homeless guy who
told me he was going to kill me. He told me he was a pedophile.
It's very scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Pagones mulled over what the lawsuit had accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm recognized as the person who held Mason, Maddox and
Sharpton accountable,'' he said. ``I think a lot of people will
remember this for a long time. These men have hurt a lot of
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
