<HEADER>
A3353 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BRAWLEY-SHARPTON-6     07-13 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-SHARPTON-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BLOW FROM THE PAST CLOUDS SHARPTON'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL, NY-BRAWLEY-PAGONES, NY-BRAWLEY-CHRONO.) 
(nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The defamation finding against the Rev. Al Sharpton in the
Tawana Brawley case Monday struck at the heart of what is surely
the longest-lasting of the many campaigns that Sharpton has waged
in New York over the last 10 years: The campaign to establish
himself as a mainstream force in state and city politics.
</P>
<P>
   For Sharpton, the jury's finding could hardly have been worse.
Not only did it reprise and validate one of the more troublesome
accusations in his career, it did so at a time when Sharpton has
been trying, with considerable success, to erase his reputation as
a rabble-rouser and emerge as a sober influence in New York
politics. Last year he played a major role in the Democratic
mayoral primary, and he says he plans to run again for mayor in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, an unusually agile politician, argued in an interview
Monday night that the jury's finding would help him among his
supporters _ blacks, mainly _ the way similarly adverse encounters
with the legal system lifted other famous black politicians in
American history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will do for me what the indictment did for Adam Powell:
People came out for him 5-to-1,'' he said, referring to the late
Harlem congressman charged with misusing congressional funds.
``It's not going to be an upstate jury next time; it's going to be
here in the city. I just have to sit back here and wait and take my
vitamin pills.''
</P>
<P>
   But that assessment, while echoed by many political analysts
Monday, misses the point of the way Sharpton's career has developed
in recent years. Starting with his run for the Senate in 1992, and
continuing with his mayoral campaign last year, Sharpton has been
trying to present himself as resolutely mainstream, and as the
pre-eminent black politician in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   He has clipped his hair and trimmed back his rhetoric. In both
the Senate race and the mayoral one, he often took advantage of
squabbles among his rivals to present himself as the most dignified
candidate in the contest. And he has done that with the knowledge
that the 130,000 votes that he has been able to count on drawing in
any citywide election is not quite enough to put him in Gracie
Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's jury finding may make that effort more difficult,
several analysts said. ``There's a serious problem with him
becoming a crossover candidate as a function of this verdict,''
said Hank Sheinkopf, a Democratic consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Sal Albanese, a former city councilman who ran against Sharpton
in last year's mayoral primary, said the finding ensured that even
after a decade, Sharpton will continue to pay a price for his role
on the Brawley case. ``Had he not been involved in that incident, I
think his ability to have a broader appeal would have certainly
been enhanced,'' Albanese said.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a mistake to write Sharpton off completely, no
matter the final outcome of the lawsuit brought by Steven Pagones,
the former Dutchess County assistant district attorney whom Miss
Brawley accused of rape.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Sharpton has already accomplished a level of
political resurrection that no politician in New York City would
have thought possible at the height of the Brawley case. He is a
talented speaker, with an uncommon understanding of the New York
media and an exceptional command of politics.
</P>
<P>
   And, as his friends said Monday, this is a 10-year-old case, and
the voters whom Sharpton has been appealing to in trying to widen
his influence appreciate his emotional evolution
</P>
<P>
   ``People will look and see those statements that they found the
verdict on were made 10 years ago, and Al Sharpton is not the same
person that he was 10 years ago,''' said state Sen. Larry Seabrook,
D-Bronx. ``He has moved on with his political life. And he has
matured.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sharpton argued Monday that the verdict had less political force
both because he was not found guilty of conspiracy and because the
jury could ultimately decide on a small financial penalty, which
Sharpton argued would undercut the import of the guilty finding
itself. ``This thing could end up boomeranging on him,'' Sharpton
said of Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But as of now, several analysts said Monday, it seems
more likely that Sharpton will be the one to feel the sting of the
boomerang. For one thing, as he has throughout the defamation
trial, Sharpton said Monday that he had no apologies for the
statements that got him in trouble, a position that his critics
will surely use against him. For another, Sharpton was found liable
by the jury for making more defamatory statements than any of the
other defendants. It is noteworthy, the analysts said, that
Sharpton was absent from Poughkeepsie when the verdict was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, as even Sharpton acknowledged, his best ally in
riding out the political fallout of this case may be the clock. The
next race on Sharpton's political calendar is not until 2001. ``If
Marion Barry can come back _ I mean, what are we talking about
here?'' Sharpton asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a three-year-old story,'' Sharpton said. ``And if I
appeal, and the appellate court comes out against me in two years,
and then it's 2001 _ I couldn't ask for a better commercial. I win
either way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
