r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     07-13 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCCER GAINS A CONVERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As France Sunday stormed to its most epic triumph since Napoleon
was carving up Europe in the early stages of the 19th century, I
must admit I felt a sense of both embarrassment and enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   I felt like a person who had just awokened from the darkness of
a lifelong slumber to discover the glorious joy of living.
</P>
<P>
   I felt like I had been struck by a divine epiphany that gave me
a sudden understanding of the greatness of a sport I had always
pettily ridiculed.
</P>
<P>
   I felt like the classic Ugly American.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer of ignorance is hatred, and I must sheepishly admit
that this football-basketball-baseball-boxing reared, red, white
and blue blood American born citizen had just such an emotion
toward soccer for most of his myopic life.
</P>
<P>
   But no more.
</P>
<P>
   Not after the past month of watching so many of the World Cup
matches on television with a growing fascination that, at the
dramatic conclusion, had me totally enraptured.
</P>
<P>
   What I discovered about soccer is that it mirrored life in all
its agonizing fickleness, in its judicial injustices, in its tragic
disappointments, in its celebratory triumphs, in its infinite
unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   I became entrapped into its web by its mesmerizing tentacles
after actually sitting and watching the entire 120-minute
Argentina-England overtime epic that was decided in Argentina's
favor by penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   I found myself afterward detesting the way the outcome came
about, but also found myself engrossed by the intoxicating drama of
the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   And so after that, I started observing a lot more World Cup
matches Italy-France, Croatia-Germany, Holland-Argentina,
France-Croatia, Brazil-Holland, and, finally, France-Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   I found myself entranced by the action and its total lack of
pre-game form.
</P>
<P>
   I also found myself shaking my head in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   I had spent almost an entire journalistic career mocking a sport
simply because I had been too cavalier about ever taking the time
to actually watch and understand it.
</P>
<P>
   I still have not the faintest grasp of its esoteric nuances and
its maddening subtleties.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a charm to it that can become addicting.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike hockey, it does not give a winking affirmation to violent
fist fights. Unlike football, it is not a Roman gladiator theatre
of frightening blindside blocks and sledgehammer tackles. Unlike
basketball, it is not a non-stop carnival of cloyingly repetitive
goals. Unlike baseball, it is not a slow-motion skit too often
dragged out interminably by its haughty participants. Unlike
boxing, it does not sanction homicide.
</P>
<P>
   What I've come to savor most about soccer is that you simply
never know for sure what will unfold in one of its matches, as
France's shocking 3-0 win over Brazil graphically reflected.
</P>
<P>
   In the golden land that gave us Poussin, Voltaire, Flaubert,
Hugo, Zola and, of course, Bardot, France wasn't expected to emerge
victorious against the mighty defending World Cup champion
Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   But the World Cup isn't the NBA finals that always belong to
Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls, come rain, shine or Karl
Malone's ominous presence.
</P>
<P>
   There are no preordained scripts, and thus Sunday Zinedine
Zidane, Fabien Barthez, Marcel Desailly, Emmanuel Petit and Didier
Deschamps and the other Frenchmen totally upstaged Ronaldo,
Rivaldo, Dunga, Bebeto, Denilson and the other men from Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   I actually found myself caught up in the spectacle of the event,
and idly kept wondering to myself how I had spent an entire life
blithely, if not stupidly remaining unaware of its uniqueness and
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   I've never thought soccer would make the impact in this country
that our major sports have, but it won't surprise me if it does
sometimes during the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   The young kids in school are now playing it, and new leagues are
surfacing all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   There still are spoilsports like I too long was who will
cynically continue to put the sport down simply because they refuse
to take the time to watch it and learn it.
</P>
<P>
   If they did, they just might come to appreciate the masterful
foot artistry of its athletes, or even the physical prowess they
show with their heads, which Zidane certainly did on two occasions
against the stunned Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   They might come to realize what I have that there are compelling
reasons for soccer being the most popular on the planet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
