<HEADLINE>
RICHTER STILL HOPING TO MAKE A DEAL WITH RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While the Rangers remained close to an agreement with
the free-agent goaltender Curtis Joseph Monday, Mike Richter and
his agent expressed hope that a deal to keep Richter in New York
could still be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have been negotiating with Joseph, who played most
recently for the Edmonton Oilers, since last Friday and were
apparently closing in on a deal, according to people involved in
the negotiations. But as of late Monday, an agreement had not been
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Richter, meanwhile, has been in contact with other teams, but
his agent, Herb Pinder, said Monday that Richter would like to
continue talking to the Rangers. Pinder said that talks with the
Rangers had not broken off, and that he expected to hear from the
team again. Richter, who had not returned telephone messages Monday
night, is believed to be seeking a deal worth about $7 million a
season.
</P>
<P>
   Pinder also denied that Richter rejected the Rangers' offer last
week of three years and $15 million. ``I told Neil Smith that Mike
was not wildly enthusiastic about his offer,'' Pinder said. ``But I
would not call that a rejection.'' Pinder added that the Rangers
did not call it a final offer. Smith, the Rangers' general manager,
has said that he will not comment on negotiations with Joseph or
Richter until an agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Richter did reject a five-year, $27 million offer from the
Rangers. But that was before the free-agent signing period began on
July 1, and before John Vanbiesbrouck signed with the Philadelphia
Flyers, reducing Richter's leverage with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been out of it,'' Pinder said. ``I told Neil Smith
that Mike was not wildly enthusiastic about their offer. He said
that he needed to check his other options, and I told him I thought
that was a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has explored other options, and as of Monday, Joseph
appeared to be it. ``We had positive talks with the Rangers again
today,'' Joseph's agent, Don Meehan, said. ``But nothing is going
to happen tonight. It's a long process and a complicated process.
We'll speak again tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   While Meehan would not reveal details of the negotiations, and
what areas of disagreement there still were, it appeared that
Joseph had not backed down from his original asking price of $6
million a year. The four-year deal Joseph is seeking is longer, and
would pay him considerably more, than the Rangers appear ready to
spend.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he thought a deal would be made, Meehan said: ``I
don't know. We've had some good discussions with Neil Smith, and as
always, the negotiations have been in good faith.''
</P>
</TEXT>
