 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Whisper-Light Speaker/Microphone Says an Earful   By Jonathan Marshall  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In yellow, green or red, it looks a little like one of my kids'
chewable Gummi Bears. But the Jabra EarSet is a unique combination
of speaker and microphone  that fits in your ear and connects by a
thin wire to a cellular phone or PC.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The EarSet permits hands-free communication without the
encumbrance of a headband and boom microphone common to other
headsets. It's easy to forget you even have it on because it weighs
less than an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny microphone and speaker fit into a colored gel earpiece
molded to fit most ears. The package comes with 6 washable
earpieces _ small, medium and large sizes for left and right ears.
</P>
<P>
   The directional microphone, although placed at your ear, picks
up sounds from your mouth. Because it stays fixed, it's not subject
to the sound variations that plague boom microphones when you jar
or misadjust them.
</P>
<P>
   I tried the EarSet on a demanding application _ Dragon Naturally
Speaking, a PC dictation program that comes with its own,
traditional headset.
</P>
<P>
   I plugged the earpiece's wire into the microphone and speaker
jacks of my PC sound card. I had to adjust the microphone gain on
my sound card because Jabra's earpiece had lower output than the
boom microphone, but it performed just as accurately as Dragon's
mike.
</P>
<P>
   I also used the earpiece to hold a phone conversation over the
Internet, using my PC to encode and decode speech. Again, it worked
flawlessly _ more than I can say for the Internet, which sometimes
broke up the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Jabra soon will start bundling its earpiece with Internet
telephony software from Net2Phone, a division of New Jersey-based
IDT Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Jabra Corp., based in San Diego, came out with an earpiece
several years ago for the Macintosh. But the company reorganized
last year, revamped the microphone and circuitry and added the gel
earpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between (the old) product and today's is a
little like the difference between a Commodore 64 and a Pentium
II,'' said Jabra spokeswoman Julie Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   The PC version of the EarSet is available from some mail-order
retailers, such as TigerDirect, for $49.95. PC and Mac versions
also are available from CompUSA.
</P>
<P>
   A separate model for cellular phones _ great for talking in the
car while keeping both hands on the steering wheel _ costs $39.95,
if your phone accepts a 2.5 millimeter jack.
</P>
<P>
   The price jumps to $79.99 if you need a special connector set
for nonstandard jacks with such phones as the Motorola Flip Phone.
</P>
<P>
   More information is available from Jabra's Web site, at
 &LR; www.jabra.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
