<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Semiconductor Equipment-Makers May Feel the Urge to Merge   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The semiconductor equipment industry is the pits, but that could be
good news for investment bankers like Tim Sullivan _ and maybe for
bottom-fishing investors.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Semi equipment vendors sell the multimillion-dollar machines
that run chip assembly lines.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, who works in Morgan Stanley's M&AMP;A practice in Menlo
Park, explained why equipment-makers, who are holding a trade
show &UR;  &LR; this week in San Francisco, may be getting the urge to merge.
</P>
<P>
   In short, after two years of overly ambitious factory expansion,
the chip market is glutted. Chipmakers like Intel are cutting jobs,
idling assembly lines _ and canceling orders for new equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a situation like this, there is a tendency for smaller or
weaker (equipment-makers) to decide they need to be part of a
bigger company,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent report predicting more semi-equipment mergers,
analyst Tia-min Pang of Cowen &AMP; Co. in San Francisco named
potential buyers and sellers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, stronger vendors like Applied
Materials, Photronics and Kulicke &AMP; Soffa might use the slump to
gobble up smaller firms like Credence Systems, GaSonics,
Nanometrics and Tegal.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a word to the wise. The semi equipment industry is so
complex, even insiders like Sullivan struggle to keep up with the
science behind these complex machines that can create perfect
vacuums or spray on layers of metal a mere 50 atoms thick.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Sullivan warns that shares of semi equipment
stocks could fall even further before any potential mergers pull
them out of the dumps.
</P>
<P>
   What investors need to know is something that puzzles insiders:
Has the industry hit bottom?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard to say,'' said Bill McIlvaine, managing editor of
Semiconductor Business News. ``But I can tell you it's already as
bad as 1985,'' the last time equipment-makers fell this far into
the trough.
</P>
<P>
   To study up before investing, start with  &LR; www.semi.org &LR;  and
 &LR; www.seminews.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Leaden parachutes? &LR;  The tech industry seems on the verge of
steamrolling organized labor's opposition, and persuading Congress
to increase the quota of foreign workers who can be ``imported'' to
the United States under the H-1B visa program.
</P>
<P>
   That irritates Mike Schilling, a programmer in Oakland who
thinks the H-1B issue has been cooked up by execs to hold down the
wages of software serfs like himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anyone in the world whose wages are inflated, it's
CEOs,'' Schilling complained in an e-mail that has been working its
way around the Net.
</P>
<P>
   As Schilling sees it, even CEOs who send their firms into
nose-dives float away on golden parachutes. And with Silicon Valley
headhunters talking about an ``executive shortage,'' odds are that
even bungling CEOs will get a shot at running another firm into the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   So in tongue-in-cheek fashion, Schilling proposes creating a
special H-1B visa category for top brass. ``What America needs is a
CEO who's willing to work 12 hours a day for a reasonable wage and
can be cheaply deported should he not perform acceptably,'' he
writes.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Squeaky wheel? &LR;  It took a letter to 3Com Chairman Eric
Benhamou _ with a copy to the media _ but Donna Bernett finally got
reimbursed for $191.30 in expenses she incurred before being laid
off four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   What made the long wait particularly annoying was that Bernett
worked for 3Com for only 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   The Wheeling, Ill., woman started on January 19 as a
$3,750-a-month print advertising supervisor. On March 16, she was
fired, as part of a 7 percent layoff in 3Com's US Robotics
division.
</P>
<P>
   She promptly filed a request to be paid for 552 miles in travel
expenses and tolls. But her chit apparently got stalled in the 3Com
network until Friday, when her letter to Benhamou, and the threat
of media exposure, prompted the company to cut a check.
</P>
<P>
   3Com spokeswoman Sara Powers said she wasn't sure what caused
the delay. But she noted that 3Com tried to ease the pain of
Bernett's layoff with a severance package that included an extra
two months pay.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Eastward, ho? &LR;  Every state in the Union is trying to grab a
piece of California's tech action. The latest wannabe is Oklahoma,
which styles itself the ``Silicon Frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   Touting tax incentives, fast permits and low ($150,000) housing
prices, Gary Miller, director of Oklahoma's Department of Commerce,
will be prospecting for relocation clients at this week's
semiconductor equipment trade shows in San Francisco and San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   So if your evening commute sends you east over Highway 580, you
might expect a little extra delay ... as all those covered wagons
full of California refugees slow down to &UR;  &LR; climb Altamont Pass.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Cobol, Fortran speakers &LR; : The Department of Labor will open a
new site today, advertising jobs for Year 2000 programmers. See
 &LR; www.dol.gov &LR;  for details.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail ( &LR; abate(at
sign)sfgate.com &LR; ). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
