<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH-COMMENTARY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIDANE HEADS THE BEST FROM THE WORLD CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Four years ago, Romario doing what Romario does best
declared that the summer belonged to him. ``This is,'' the
Brazilian star boasted, ``the World Cup of Romario.''
</P>
<P>
   Zinedine Zidane would never claim anything like that. He's far
too reserved, too shy, more apt to flash a bashful smile eyes
averted, of course and mumble a few humble words than brag about
what he could, and would, do once the whistle blew.
</P>
<P>
   And Zidane didn't need to say a thing: Every movement, every
inspired step even the one, his staunchest supporters claim, that
forced him to the sidelines for two matches stamped the 1998 World
Cup, beyond any rational doubt, as his.
</P>
<P>
   Matserful with the ball at his feet, surprisingly deadly with
his head, ``Zizou'' was responsible for everything France
accomplished the past month: the mesmerizing triumph, sure, but
also the strides Les Bleus took in unifying this diverse,
too-often-divided nation, and in demonstrating to many, many French
just how valuable their diversity truly is.
</P>
<P>
   Zidane, the son of Algerian immigrants who grew up poor in
Marseille's rough La Castellane district, proved to be a symbol of
so many things although that wasn't the least part of his aim. All
he wanted was to play soccer, but the way he played the ease with
which he did the most extraordinary things meant so much more to so
many.
</P>
<P>
   He had a superb supporting cast Didier Deschamps, Marcel
Desailly, Lilian Thuram, Emmanuel Petit, Laurent Blanc, Thierry
Henry, at last a half-dozen others without whose efforts France's
greatest sporting achievement would have been impossible. But
Zidane was the heart, the soul, the magic of Les Bleus
</P>
<P>
   ; it is to him the greatest slice of glory shoul go.
</P>
<P>
   The manner with which he demolished foes with a serpentine run,
always twisting the ball to where defenders' legs weren't, or with
the incisive pass nobody else on the field could have imagined was
pure wizardry. In a World Cup in which magic was in short supply,
his was a welcome presence.
</P>
<P>
   Zidane's Cup was defined by two moments, one bleak, the other
sublime. With two emphatic headers in Sunday's 3-0 rout of Brazil
in the final, he took full responsibility for an attack that had
faltered during the knockout phase; it was a heroic display that
bolstered French confidence while destroying the Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   The other action, stamping on an opponent during a first-round
romp over Saudi Arabia an action that gained Zidane a red card and
a two-game suspension, jeopardizing France's prospects to reach the
quarterfinals also was seen as heroic by some. Most of the 3
million Algerians in France are opposed to the African nation's
Islamic regime; many of them are from the oppressed Berber-speaking
peoples of Algeria's mountains.
</P>
<P>
   To them, Zidane was making a political statement. It was the
``Revenge of Zizou,'' according to an Algerian newspaper: By
stomping on a Saudi a devout Muslim Zidane was striking a blow
against the extemists.
</P>
<P>
   But it was that kind of Cup for Zidane. No matter what he did,
it was seen as the best. Most of it was.
</P>
<P>
   Other '98 bests:
</P>
<P>
   Best defender:
</P>
<P>
   Easy. Desailly was a rock for a French defense that surrendered
just two goals and shutout five opponents, including the defending
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Best goalkeeper:
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay's Jose Luis Chilavert was much more than a shot
blocker. Through sheer will and force of personality, he carried
Paraguay within six minutes of a possible upset over the French. He
was, in the purest sense of the term, the Cup's most valuable
player.
</P>
<P>
   Best newcomer:
</P>
<P>
   If England's Michael Owen had grown up in America, he'd have
just graduated from high school. Instead, the 18-year-old striker
is a burgeoning international star, the most exciting player to
step foot on a French field this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Best coach:
</P>
<P>
   Miroslav Blazevic took a decent Croatian squad that had lost its
best player injured Alen Boksic and gave it the confidence to
believe anything was possible. As it turned out, anything was.
</P>
<P>
   Best game:
</P>
<P>
   Several to choose from, but the Spain-Nigeria thriller from the
Group of Death still stands tallest.
</P>
<P>
   Best goal:
</P>
<P>
   Many great goals this Cup. Tops was Sunday Oliseh's half-volley
bullet off the post that gave Nigeria a 3-2 win in the tournament's
best game.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest disappointment:
</P>
<P>
   Among teams, it has to be Spain. The Spaniards were thought to
be genuine contenders but choked, like always. Among players, there
were many. A tossup among Spanish goalkeeper Andoni Zubizaretta,
whose horrendous display on Nigeria's second goal sealed Spain's
fate; Colombian forward Faustino Asprilla, whose big mouth earned
him an early trip home; and Italian striker Alessandro Del Piero,
the superstar-in-waiting who kept everyone waiting all Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Best quote:
</P>
<P>
   We'll leave it to Bora Milutinovic, the former U.S. coach, who
made Nigeria the fourth team he'd taken to the World Cup final
rounds. Asked whom he'd be guiding in 2002, he replied: ``I am
soccer coach I don't know where I am tomorrow morning. How do I
know where I be in four years?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
