<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Specialty Internet search engines allow users to cut through 
 clutter   By Amy Doan  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Say you want to locate a news group on swing dancing, a shop in
Northern California that will do custom embroidery, or a sheet
metal supplier in the Midwest.
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could go to one of the main search engines, such as Yahoo or
Excite, and sort through mountains of information that may or may
not be relevant. Or you could take a shortcut and go to one of a
growing number of specialty search engines.
</P>
<P>
   As the amount of data clogging the Internet continues to grow,
it's ``just harder and harder'' for traditional automated search
engine technology to return focused data, said Danny Sullivan,
editor of the ``Search Engine Watch'' newsletter, based in London.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``the number of specialty engines has been growing
wherever you look, especially in the past year,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Thomas Regional Directory Co., best known for its
industrial supply books, recently created regional search engines
on a wide variety of industrial products, services and trade
associations.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Disney started a site for kids called Dig.com that
features individual search engines for topics such as comic books
and dinosaur trivia.
</P>
<P>
   Most search engines create their listings automatically by
having software ``agents'' crawl the Web and constantly update a
directory of site information, which is matched against the
keywords typed in by users.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Yahoo, also rely on teams of editors to manually
review sites and descriptions that are submitted by site owners.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty search engines work much the same way, but because
their focus is so narrow, they can eliminate more ``clutter.''
</P>
<P>
   You can find specialty search engines by looking in hobby and
trade magazines.
</P>
<P>
   You also can find them on standard search engines. The home
pages for the major search engines, including Excite and Lycos,
produce fairly comprehensive specialty search engine listings in
their ``computers'' category.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm looking for a Viper 330 video card, it just makes no
sense whatsoever to start out with Yahoo,'' said Charlie Woods, a
Dallas engineer. ``Digging through the sites that come up just
takes too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods uses niche engines to find computer components for work
and, on weekends, to locate parts for his Honda ST1100 motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually find the exact information I'm looking for within
the first 20 or 30 listings, instead of the hundreds of listings it
took before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Gettinger, who runs a glass manufacturing company in
Hayward, also uses specialty engines for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sick of typing in `glass' and getting tons of
information on artistic glass or glass plants in Canada, but
nothing I could use,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of specialty search engines is that they are
sometimes no more than glorified commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Because they get fewer advertising dollars than traditional
search engines, specialty search engines often charge sites for
prominent positions in their search results.
</P>
<P>
   And some only are referral sites for companies looking for sales
leads.
</P>
<P>
   Web surfers should find out how a search engine makes money
before relying on it exclusively, say analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Users should always be on the lookout for clues as to how
commercially biased the listings are,'' said Mark Mooradian, a
director with Jupiter Communications, a research firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites that purport to be search engines don't even refer
visitors to other Web sites. For example, Jewelry-Search.com only
refers visitors to local jewelers who have paid a fee to be
included. When you're checking out a specialty search engine, pay
attention to the kinds of sites that show up on search results. If
they include a mix of commercial and noncommercial sites and news
groups, they're more likely give you less-biased information.
</P>
<P>
   ``But just because sites are paying to be included in the
results doesn't mean a site isn't useful,'' Mooradian said.
</P>
<P>
   And many generic, advertising- &QL; 
supported search engines also charge Web sites for premium
listings, he added.
</P>
<P>
   For example, mainstream search engines often have exclusive
licensing deals with online retailers. When users type in popular
keywords like ``books'' or ``music,'' sites like Amazon.com or
Barnes &AMP; Noble.com usually will be listed first.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said many users of traditional search engines don't know
that when a logo flashes ``try this first'' above a search result,
it's likely that a company has paid for top billing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Lycos instructs users to ``check this out,'' with
``this'' being a link to business partner Barnes and Noble.com.
When someone jumps to the Barnes and Noble site from Lycos, the
search engine gets a commission.
</P>
<P>
   One search engine company has chosen to be up-front about its
commercial ties.
</P>
<P>
   Goto.com, launched in 1997, tells users exactly how much a site
has paid for placement on the Goto search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Goto even shows visitors how much sites are paying per click.
Most companies pay between one and 12 cents for every person who
clicks onto to their sites from Goto.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Goto search results are organized via competitive bidding:
Those that pay more get higher billing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
