<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN ASSEMBLYMAN ACQUITTED OF CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dov Hikind, a Democratic assemblyman from Brooklyn
who is known for his maverick politics and outspoken manner, was
acquitted Monday of charges that he took tens of thousands of
dollars in illegal payoffs from officials of a social services
group.
</P>
<P>
   But a former official of the group, Rabbi Elimelech Naiman, was
convicted of making corrupt payments to Hikind, a veteran state
legislator from Borough Park. And the rabbi was convicted of fraud
charges stemming from his activities with the group that did not
involve Hikind.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors declined to speak with reporters to explain their
decision to acquit Hikind and convict Naiman, but prosecutors and
defense lawyers said the two verdicts were not necessarily
contradictory.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, they said, could have accepted the prosecutors'
contention that the rabbi made the payments with the intent to
influence Hikind corruptly in order to help the group obtain state
funds, but that Hikind did not receive the payments with corrupt
intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intent is the key,'' Hikind's lawyer, Gustave Newman, told
reporters after the verdicts were announced in U.S. District Court
in Brooklyn after five and a half days of deliberations in a
two-month trial.
</P>
<P>
   As the verdict was announced, Hikind, 48, gasped loudly, then
put his head on the table and began to cry. He then embraced
Newman. Later, standing outside the courtroom with his sobbing
wife, Shoshana, Hikind thanked God, his lawyer and the jury of six
men and six women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am in a yarmulke, an Orthodox Jew, and a jury made up
of a cross section of New York, including four black people and a
Pakistani person, and I got justice today,'' he said. ``What a
great country for someone whose parents survived Auschwitz.''
</P>
<P>
   Hikind had been charged with two counts: the corrupt
solicitation and acceptance of funds and the misapplication of
funds, each of which could have produced a sentence of up to 10
years in prison. In addition, a conviction would have meant
immediate expulsion of Hikind from the Assembly, where for 16 years
he has represented Borough Park and surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary Carter, the U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, whose office
prosecuted the case, said later that he was satisfied with the
verdict to the extent that Naiman's conviction supported the
prosecution argument that government funds, which had been given to
the social services group for charitable uses, ``were diverted for
purposes that were not intended.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury apparently did not conclude beyond a reasonable doubt
that Assemblyman Hikind accepted the benefits conferred upon him
with the same corrupt intent with which they were conferred,''
Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors, Jason Brown and Elisa Liang, assistant U.S.
attorneys in Brooklyn, told the jury that between 1991 and 1994,
Hikind corruptly received about $40,000 of the council's funds in
return for obtaining hundreds of thousands of dollars in state
money for the group and its affiliates. The payoffs, they held,
were in the form of payments for items like yeshiva tuition for
Hikind's children, family trips to Israel and France, and expenses
for political campaigns and fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Naiman, 44, exhibited no reaction as he heard the jury pronounce
him guilty of corrupt payment of funds, misapplication of funds and
a half dozen mail fraud counts. He faces a term of up to 10 years
in prison when Judge Charles Sifton of U.S. District Court
sentences him on Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi's lawyer, Benjamin Brafman, said, ``I'm confident this
verdict against Rabbi Naiman will not withstand appellate review.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The rabbi was the employment and training director of the social
services group involved in the case, the Council of Jewish
Organizations of Borough Park. Until the investigation that led to
the trial, the council was an influential and politically connected
group that ran programs like job training and aid to the elderly
and to children, receiving millions of dollars a year in federal,
state and city funds. Candidates for public offices from president
on down courted the council, widely known as COJO, because they
believed it was instrumental in winning tens of thousands of
Orthodox Jewish votes.
</P>
<P>
   A third defendant in the case, Paul Chernick, COJO's former
operations director, pleaded guilty in April to stealing from the
group's government grants and said he had used some of the money to
make illegal payoffs to Hikind. But the jurors at the assemblyman's
trial were not told of the plea and statement, and Chernick did not
testify because his plea deal did not require him to do so, for
reasons Carter declined Monday to disclose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
