<SLUG> BC-PACIFIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 The Chicago Option   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The Pacific Exchange and Chicago Board Options Exchange confirmed
yesterday that they are holding preliminary talks to form a
``strategic alliance.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The boards of directors of both exchanges meet next week and
could agree to a merger between the Chicago exchange, which trades
nearly two-thirds of all stock and stock-index options, and the
Pacific, the third largest options exchange in the country.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are not only 487 jobs at the Pacific Exchange, 80
percent of them in San Francisco, but about 1,900 other jobs at
member firms.
</P>
<P>
   The two exchanges reportedly have agreed to a ``lockup
agreement'' that requires them to negotiate exclusively with each
other for a month.
</P>
<P>
   The move to consolidate isn't surprising. Like the companies
whose stocks and stock options they trade, exchanges &UR;  &LR; are combining
to cut costs, share technology and gain other economies of scale to
better compete in the rapidly changing financial services world.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago exchange has had the urge to merge before. The
exchange, which revolutionized options trading by creating
standardized, listed options in 1973, bid unsuccessfully earlier
this year for the options business of the Philadelphia Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But the Philadelphia exchange decided to merge with the American
Stock Exchange and National Association of Securities Dealers. That
deal presumably put additional pressure on Chicago and Pacific to
work out a merger agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific has been talking about alliances and mergers for the
past decade, according to Vice President Dale Carlson. ``But these
are very difficult to pull off because you're dealing with member
organizations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After reporting record trading volume and profits for three
years, Carlson said ``our board members have said we have the
wherewithal to remain independent indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   One non-negotiable point in the current discussions, he said, is
keeping an options trading floor in San Francisco. Members also
want a long-term guarantee rather than a five-year commitment which
is all the Philadelphia exchange received in its deal with Amex.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike shareholders of public companies like BankAmerica, who
may favor a merger that stipulates moving operations and
headquarters, the 552 members who own the Pacific and predominantly
work in San Francisco must vote in favor of a merger by a
two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't get membership support unless an options floor
remains in San Francisco,'' said Don Abramson, a director of
Kessler-Asher, a San Francisco stock options clearing firm.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, business leaders and politicians supported what they
knew about Chicago-Pacific discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident there will be no job loss in San Francisco
and we are equally confident there will be a stock options and
exchange floor in the city,'' said Kandace Bender, a spokeswoman
for Mayor Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are also hoping that there will be no changes in the plans
to construct a new 17-story headquarters and trading floor on
Folsom Street,'' said San Francisco Supervisor Mark Leno.
</P>
<P>
   Since no agreement has been reached, there are many more
questions than answers. Some observers question the long-term
viability of regional stock exchanges in an era of global markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens to the equities side of the business is bothering
a lot of us,'' said Dennis LoPresti, senior vice president of
Wedbush Morgan Securities in Los Angeles and a former director of
the Pacific Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recently expanded from seven to 10 equities trading
specialists so we are concerned if the exchange plans to spin off
its equities trading operations or merge them with someone else
like the Cincinnati or Boston exchanges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific trades the most active stocks and bonds on the New
York and American stock exchanges but its options trading business
has been growing at more than double the pace of its stock trading.
</P>
<P>
   Investors can use options to lessen the risks of owning stocks.
An option contract gives the purchaser the right to buy or sell the
underlying security at a prespecified price by a certain date.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Pacific trading in Microsoft, Compaq, Sun Microsystem
and about 800 other equity options jumped 38 percent. Options now
account for more than half the exchange's business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
