<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-CHRONO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAWANA BRAWLEY CASE CHRONOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL, NY-BRAWLEY-SHARPTON, NY-BRAWLEY-PAGONES.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A chronology of the Tawana Brawley case:
</P>
<P>
   NOV. 28, 1987: Tawana Brawley, a 15-year-old high school
student, is found curled in a fetal position inside a plastic bag
behind an apartment house in Wappingers Falls, six miles south of
Poughkeepsie, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that she had been beaten; ``nigger'' and ``KKK''
written on her torso; feces smeared across her body, and her hair
chopped off. She later told her family and law enforcement
authorities that she had been abducted and sexually assaulted by
six white men, one of whom wore a police badge.
</P>
<P>
   DECEMBER 1987: The Brawley family hires Alton Maddox and C.
Vernon Mason as its lawyers. The Rev. Al Sharpton, who has worked
with the civil rights lawyers in the past, assumes the role of
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   JAN. 26, 1988: After two local prosecutors disqualify themselves
and Maddox continues to advise Miss Brawley to remain silent and
uncooperative with investigators, Gov. Mario Cuomo orders State
Attorney General Robert Abrams to act as a special prosecutor in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   FEB. 29, 1988: State Supreme Court Justice Angelo Ingrassia
empanels a grand jury of 11 women and 12 men (2 blacks and 21
whites) to determine the facts of the case.
</P>
<P>
   MARCH 13, 1988: Without citing evidence, Maddox and Mason say
Assistant District Attorney Steven Pagones was one of a group of
white men who abducted Miss Brawley and sexually abused her.
Pagones denies the allegation, and his lawyer, Gerald Hayes, says:
``I can assure you that Steve Pagones will not only defend himself
against these liars, but we will certainly see them in court. If
there's any doubt about what I mean by that last statement, it
means that we fully intend to sue them for slander.''
</P>
<P>
   OCT. 6, 1988: Concluding a seven-month investigation, the grand
jury concludes that Miss Brawley had fabricated her tale of
abduction and sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   These were among the conclusions:
</P>
<P>
   _Miss Brawley decided not to return to her home in Wappingers
Falls on Nov. 24 and spent much of the ensuing four days in an
apartment from which her family had recently been evicted.
</P>
<P>
   _Miss Brawley, alone or with an accomplice, concocted the
degrading condition in which she was found by smearing herself with
dog feces, writing racial slurs on her body, tearing and scorching
her clothes and crawling into a garbage bag and pretending to be in
a traumatized state.
</P>
<P>
   _Miss Brawley tried for weeks to mislead doctors, social
workers, the police, reporters and community residents with faked
medical complaints and fragmentary accounts of an attack by a band
of white racists.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Brawley's lawyers and adviser, in a four-hour broadcast
over New York radio station WLIB, denounced the grand jury's report
as a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   OCT. 31, 1988: Pagones files a lawsuit against Maddox, Mason,
Sharpton and Miss Brawley.
</P>
<P>
   MAY 21, 1990: Maddox is suspended from practicing law in New
York state because of his refusal to cooperate with an ethics panel
looking into his conduct in the Brawley case.
</P>
<P>
   MAY 7, 1991: Judge rules that Pagones wins his case against Miss
Brawley by default after she fails to answer legal papers. Damages
against her will be tallied after the trial is completed.
</P>
<P>
   SEPT. 13, 1994: Sharpton receives 26 percent of the vote in the
statewide Democratic primary for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   JAN. 26, 1995: Mason is disbarred by a state appellate court,
which cited him for ``a pattern of professional misconduct''
spanning at least six years.
</P>
<P>
   SEPT. 9, 1997: Sharpton receives 32 percent of the vote in the
Democratic mayoral primary in New York City, nearly forcing a
runoff with Ruth Messinger.
</P>
<P>
   NOV. 18, 1997: Pagones' defamation suit against against Miss
Brawley's three advisers begins, 10 years after it was filed. The
trial is expected to last about a month.
</P>
<P>
   JULY 8, 1998: The case goes to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   JULY 13, 1998: The jury reaches a verdict, finding Mason, Maddox
and Sharpton liable for defaming Pagones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
