<HEADLINE>
ESPN WEST PLANS SHELVED BEFORE DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Three months before its intended launch, the ESPN
West mission has quietly been scrubbed.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Fox announced a 10-year cable agreement to continue
regional coverage of the Angels and Mighty Ducks _ the two teams
that were to be the foundation of ESPN's first foray into the
regional-cable business this October.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which announced the intention to create ESPN West at the
Western Cable Show last December, ran into problems that many
industry analysts anticipated _ it had trouble making any headway
with local cable operators finding space for the channel on their
systems.
</P>
<P>
   To date, only DDS systems DirecTV and EchoStar had committed to
ESPN West because of 500-channel capacities on their small
satellite dish distribution. Systems in Orange County were ones
that ESPN West would have focused on most, but channel space for
that has recently been given, in some cases, to Fox Sports West 2.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said that several months ago, Fox received a call from
Disney representatives, who run both ESPN as well as the two teams,
and asked if they'd entertain an offer to continue their current
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, which understands the frustration of lining up cable
systems considering the pains it went through the last two years to
launch Fox Sports West 2 even with the Dodgers as its star
attraction, was understandably ecstatic about locking in the Angels
and Ducks as programming for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Even though both the Angels and Ducks had filed suit against Fox
Sports West and Fox Sports West 2 to have their contracts revoked _
in both cases, agreements were reached to allow the teams to leave
Fox _ the Disney-owned teams are content with this new Fox
alignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We approach this as a long-term alliance,'' Tim Mead, vice
president of communications for Anaheim Sports Inc., said of the
team in a statement. ``Unique provisions ensure that both companies
will be working toward a common goal in the years ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   With the extended Fox deal, the Ducks will have 40 games a
season (home and road) live on Fox Sports West 2 while the Angels
will have 50 games (most at home) live on Fox Sports West.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports West reaches 4.8 million viewers in Southern
California, Nevada and Hawaii; Fox Sports West 2 is in 2.8 million
homes in Southern California and Nevada. FSW2 has not been picked
up by several cable systems in the San Fernando Valley and nearby
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this announcement, we fully expect Fox Sports West 2 to
have 100 percent distribution in the coming months,'' Kitty Cohen,
general manager of FSW and FSW2, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN spokesman Chris LaPlaca said channel-capacity issues that
affect all new networks were a large part of why ESPN West could
not meet its October launch goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this time line, the startup needs of ESPN West didn't meet
the immediate needs of the teams, and we support the decision''
said LaPlaca. ``Disney is all about doing what helps every one of
its entities.''
</P>
<P>
   LaPlaca did not rule out a future launch of ESPN West, although
having the Angels and Ducks locked in for 10 years with the
network's chief competition should preclude any movement on ESPN
trying to go regional in Southern California market. ESPN continues
to look into regional channels in other parts of the country,
LaPlaca said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, which owns the Dodgers, also has the Lakers and Kings
locked into agreements until 2010, and have three more years on a
deal with the Clippers. Fox also has USC and UCLA sports rights _
leaving little to no inventory for an ESPN West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
