</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES NOTEBOOK: WILLIAMS SET TO REJOIN LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Bernie Williams, out for more than a month after
suffering a sprained knee, will probably rejoin the Yankees' lineup
on Friday in Toronto, according to manager Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie's feeling really good,'' Torre said Monday. ``To me, it
looks good for the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams will join the Yankees' Class AA affiliate Norwich on
Tuesday, as the Navigators begin a three-game series in Portland,
Maine. Williams is expected to play two games, and if all goes
well, Torre said, he could rejoin the team on Thursday in Detroit
and then play on Friday. But don't rule out the possibility that
Williams could talk his way back into the lineup for Thursday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams sprained his knee sliding on June 10 and was placed on
the 15-day disabled list the next day. He progressed rather quickly
in his rehabilitation through June, and the Yankees thought he
would be ready to play last week at Tampa Bay. But in the first
game of a minor league rehabilitation assignment on July 6,
Williams felt pain in his knee as he made a throw. However, doctors
think the pain stemmed from scar tissue, rather than any structural
problem, and on Sunday, Williams was given the clearance to resume
full batting practice and outfield drills.
</P>
<P>
   As well as the Yankees have been playing _ they have a 65-21
record, and are 19-8 without Williams _ he is needed to bolster a
sagging offense.
</P>
<P>
   Since Williams suffered his injury, the Yankees' batting average
has dropped from .300 to .283, and other members of the lineup have
started to sputter. Paul O'Neill, swinging more aggressively
without Williams in the lineup, has seen his average sink 15
points, and he has drawn only two walks in his last 14 games. With
the switch-hitting Williams, Torre can separate the
left-handed-hitting O'Neill and Tino Martinez in the lineup, making
it more difficult for opposing managers to use left-handed
relievers late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis, who has done a solid job in center field, could use
a rest, Torre said on Sunday. Before he got three hits on Sunday,
Curtis' batting average had dropped 26 points.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams is activated, the Yankees are expected to send
Ricky Ledee back to Class AAA Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Has a Relapse
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had hoped to activate the reliever Jeff Nelson for
Tuesday's game, but Nelson's back, the reason he was placed on the
disabled list in June, began bothering him again after he threw
batting practice on Sunday. Now Torre is wondering if it would be
better to send Nelson on a minor league rehabilitation assignment _
perhaps sometime at the end of the week _ before activating him.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis, the third player on the Yankees' disabled list, may
begin his rehabilitation assignment on or around July 23 and be
activated in the following week. Tim Raines and Darryl Strawberry
have been semi-regular players in Davis' absence, but once Davis
returns, Torre said, he will be given the bulk of the at-bats, so
that he can regain his timing quickly enough to be a factor in the
final weeks of the regular season and in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much invested in him to not do that,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Gout Is Out, Says Wells
</P>
<P>
   David Wells, hobbled by a bruised right big toe, says he does
not have gout. ``If I did, I would tell you,'' said Wells, who
expects to make his next scheduled start on Friday in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Homer Bush has been a sometimes valuable tool for the Yankees,
pinch-running in close games; on Sunday, he scored the decisive run
in the ninth inning. But the Yankees will probably trade Bush in
the days leading up to the July 31 deadline, because, barring
injuries, the Yankees will not have room for Bush once Chili Davis
returns from the disabled list in August. Brian Cashman, the
Yankees' general manager, says eight teams have demonstrated
interest in Bush. Among those: St. Louis, Detroit, Toronto and
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Dyed blonde hair is a growing fad around the big leagues, Roger
Clemens of Toronto and Charles Nagy of Cleveland being among those
who have gone platinum. Torre said the Yankees have a rule against
facial hair. But if someone wanted to go blond, ``What can I do
about it?'' Torre asked rhetorically, smiling. ``I don't run these
guys' lives.'' The Yankees least likely to dye their hair,
according to Torre: Joe Girardi and Paul O'Neill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
