A3375 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-D'AMATO-POLITICS-4     07-13 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-D'AMATO-POLITICS-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTING D'AMATO ON A SHOESTRING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The letter was handwritten on lined dime-store
paper, suggesting a homespun spontaneity. ``Entire forests are
dying from disease,'' a Long Island teacher wrote. ``If you press
hard for acid rain legislation in this session of Congress, I may
never have to teach anything more than the beauty and wonders of
nature!''
</P>
<P>
   But the note was actually one of thousands written quite
unspontaneously at the behest of environmental groups last spring.
And like the paper plates bearing messages from immigrants, the
postcards from people with AIDS and the phone calls from opponents
of smoking, they were part of well-coordinated efforts to influence
one man: Sen &UR; . &LR;  Alfonse D'Amato, the New York Republican.
</P>
<P>
   No stranger to the high-priced lobbying of powerful interest
groups, D'Amato opens himself to less-familiar pressure groups come
election time. He has been getting an earful of low-budget advocacy
these days from nonprofit organizations representing immigrants,
environmentalists, tenants, gay people and a bevy of other
constituencies better known for their ties to New York Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   With phone and letter campaigns, news conferences and
newsletters, the groups are training laserlike attention on D'Amato
this year, hoping that election-year pressures will cause him to
push harder and shout louder on issues he might have ignored or
opposed were he not seeking votes. D'Amato, considered one of the
Senate's most vulnerable incumbents, is seeking his fourth term
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who I've talked to who knows him said, `You know,
this is your best year,''' said William Cooke, legislative director
for the Citizens Campaign for the Environment, which is urging
D'Amato to push acid rain legislation. ``Every six years, he's an
environmentalist.''
</P>
<P>
   It might seem pointless for groups with traditionally liberal
agendas to focus on a man who revels in labeling challengers
``hopelessly liberal.'' But such organizations have clearly reaped
some benefits from their efforts. With his bloodhound's nose for
populist themes, D'Amato is more moderate, and malleable, near
election time than his hard-edge campaign oratory suggests,
officials with several groups said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much more amenable at election time,'' said a Washington
lobbyist for a civil rights group, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``People joke that in an election year, D'Amato is
better than most Democrats. He'll be there, because he's seeking
votes.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His ties to centrist and liberal pressure groups have also been
useful to D'Amato. Such alliances have allowed him to say he is
fighting against conservative Republicans for regular New Yorkers,
and not just for wealthy campaign contributors or big companies.
</P>
<P>
   But his critics and Democratic rivals accuse D'Amato of
opportunism, saying he champions liberal and centrist causes solely
to court swing voters and to whitewash what they consider a
distinctly conservative voting record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's masquerading as a new-found environmentalist,'' said
Chris Ballantyne, Northeast regional director for the Sierra Club,
which has run television advertisements criticizing D'Amato this
year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, D'Amato bridled at suggestions that he has
shifted leftward this year, insisting that most of his current
positions are not new. ``They are matters of conscience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged feeling additional pressure from grass-roots
lobbyists in recent months. ``Some groups become impatient,'' he
said. ``They think that because there is an election, they will get
you to do more or less. But I work as hard as I can all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, pressure tactics may have influenced the senator more
than he admits. In one case, D'Amato voted in May for a Democratic
amendment to raise cigarette taxes by $1.50 a pack after fierce
lobbying from health care and consumer groups. In the past, he has
voted against such tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a significant effort to focus on D'Amato,'' said Joan
Mulhern, co-chairwoman of the Save Lives, Not Tobacco Coalition.
``Tobacco control is a big issue for some of his Democratic
opponents, so we thought it was an issue he would be sensitive
on.''
</P>
<P>
   In part because they knew he would be embroiled in a tough
re-election campaign, advocates for immigrants also made D'Amato a
major target this year in their fight to reinstate food stamp
benefits for legal immigrants. The groups mailed hundreds of paper
plates containing scribbled messages from immigrants to D'Amato _
who often supports immigrants on other issues _ hoping that the
appeal of potential Hispanic and Asian voters would turn his head.
</P>
<P>
   Though he did not press this issue as hard as some groups hoped,
D'Amato spoke in favor of the measure and joined a bipartisan group
that helped break a Senate deadlock, paving the way for the bill's
passage.
</P>
<P>
   For similar reasons, patient advocates are planning to lobby
D'Amato later this summer on legislation intended to increase
consumer protections in managed-care plans. Though D'Amato has
sponsored such legislation, he has not pushed hard enough for its
passage, the groups say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps that there are three Democrats who are actively
campaigning on this,'' said Richard Kirsch, executive director of
Citizen Action of New York, a nonprofit government watchdog group
active in health care issues.
</P>
<P>
   The three Democrats seeking the nomination to challenge D'Amato
are Geraldine Ferraro, the former candidate for vice president;
Mark Green, the New York City public advocate, and Rep. Charles
Schumer of Brooklyn and Queens.
</P>
<P>
   For D'Amato, there are some obvious risks in advocating
legislation that other Republicans strongly oppose. Success can
annoy his Senate allies, while failure can disappoint and anger the
grass-roots groups he is courting.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, at the urging of environmental groups, D'Amato and
his Democratic counterpart, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
introduced legislation last year intended to curb the airborne
pollutants that cause acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   The groups cheered him at the time, and D'Amato began
broadcasting television advertisements just weeks later touting his
environmentalism. But the bill has been stuck in committee, and the
environmentalists have begun complaining loudly that D'Amato is
doing nothing to advance it. ``We had been hoping that his campaign
would make a difference,'' said John F. Sheehan, a spokesman for
the Adirondack Council.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato said fierce opposition to the bill from Midwestern
senators has made passage all but impossible this year. But he
pledged that the bill would be enacted eventually. ``You don't win
every one of these battles overnight,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
