<HEADLINE>
ROWLAND OPENS RE-ELECTION EFFORT WITH A PLEDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORWICH, Conn. _ Formally starting a re-election campaign that
has been under way for a year, Gov. John Rowland of Connecticut
declared on Monday that his top priority in a second term would be
helping to rebuild the decaying cores of the state's largest
cities.
</P>
<P>
   That choice as a campaign centerpiece is part of a continuing
effort by Rowland, a Republican, to chart a course that he calls
``fiscally conservative and socially inclusive.'' It also reflects
the evolution of the ever-more-moderate Rowland, 41, who went to
Congress in 1985 as a brash right-winger and won the gubernatorial
race in 1994, a year of big Republican gains.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 3, Rowland will face a former colleague on Capitol Hill,
Rep. Barbara Kennelly, 62, a Democrat who has championed women's
and children's issues during her 16 years in Washington. Rowland
has built a wide lead in polls and has set a state record for a
governor's race by raising $4.3 million, or more than twice as much
as Mrs. Kennelly.
</P>
<P>
   Basking in the state's rebounding economy and showing a deep tan
after nine days at the beach, Rowland cut a confident and casual
figure as he led a caravan across the state for four rallies
featuring Boy Scouts, Dixieland bands and all the other patriotic
trimmings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked the bad times in the eye and we've turned things
around,'' Rowland said, sporting a gold elephant in his lapel.
``More jobs, higher wages, health care for children, better
schools, safer streets.'' Pausing for applause, he said, ``I
promise you that we are just getting started.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland began running television ads nine months ago, so
Monday's rallies were hardly a surprise. But his campaign tried to
pump up supporters by sending star-spangled postcards urging:
``Don't miss out. It's the tour that makes it official.''
</P>
<P>
   He began the day under a white tent on a wharf in this mill town
in eastern Connecticut, drove 100 miles west to the office towers
in the New York suburb of Stamford, then doubled back to West
Hartford and finished the night at an amusement park near his
hometown of Waterbury, where he once worked in his family's
insurance business.
</P>
<P>
   In his speeches, Rowland said that he would continue to try to
cut taxes, and he hailed the state's efforts to move welfare
recipients into jobs as ``tough love.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he was making the cities his top priority because
the state as a whole is in such good economic shape. ``All of our
cities are on the way back to an economic renaissance that we've
never seen before, because of our hard work,'' he said. ``But we
can do so much more.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After his address in Stamford, Rowland said he wanted to follow
through on economic development plans that had been announced for
the downtown areas of Hartford, New Haven, Bridgeport and
Waterbury.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said he wanted to promote similar projects in other
cities and urban towns, but would like them to rely on local and
private money rather than state financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a combination of universities, colleges,
private investment, federal dollars in some cases, city dollars in
some cases, waterfront development,'' he said. ``So I want to kind
of stick around for a few more years to see that come to
fruition.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding later to Rowland's plans, the chairman of the state
Democratic Party, Edward Marcus, pointed to Rowland's
long-abandoned promise of the last campaign, to repeal the state
income tax, and asserted that today's pledges were no different.
</P>
<P>
   ``He takes positions as they become convenient,'' Marcus said.
``He ignored the cities and education and the environment for three
years. Now in an election year, he's for all of the above.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland brushed off questions about whether he would commit to
serve out a second term before seeking a higher office, or whether
he might seek a third term. (Connecticut has no term limits for
governors.)
</P>
<P>
   In his speeches, Rowland made only the vaguest reference to Mrs.
Kennelly or the Democratic Party. But he said he would stand by his
challenge to debate Mrs. Kennelly six to eight times before
Election Day. A spokeswoman for Mrs. Kennelly said the
congresswoman wanted to participate in debates, but said it was too
soon to discuss how many.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, Mrs. Kennelly held a news conference outside a
recycling plant in New Haven to accuse Rowland of ``putting
polluters before people,'' a charge she planned to make repeatedly
through the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly had expressed frustration and even defeatism at
several recent appearances, but aides said Monday that she was
upbeat. ``The state of Connecticut will be better for this race,
and I intend to win this race,'' Mrs. Kennelly said. ``I'm going to
work so hard, you won't believe it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
