<HEADLINE>
THREAT TO KYL NETS HOUSE ARREST, PROBATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Angelo Schubert's letter last year to U.S. Sen. Jon
Kyl was a desperate plea for help in bringing his Filipino wife to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the 50-year-old Bullhead City man went too far. On Monday he
was sentenced to 120 days' house arrest and two years' probation
for threatening to kill the senator.
</P>
<P>
   Schubert, a food service worker in Laughlin, Nev., wrote the
letter in December from his home in Bullhead City. He had been
married for two years to a Filipino woman but was unable to get
permission for her to immigrate to the United States, court records
show.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Schubert wrote that he ``cannot take this Pain
much longer being seperated from my wife.'' He said he was
suffering from eating and sleeping disorders, a nerve condition, an
ulcer and suicidal depression.
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``If my wife is not with me by Dec. 31, 12
midnight . . . I will be forced to lay down my Life for her . . .
but I will not Die alone I will take with me all those responsible
for my Suffering . . . and especially the creators of you're
Inhuman Laws . . . one life for each day of Pain!''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which also included a pledge that ``January 1998
will go down in the History of the United States,'' sparked an
investigation by the FBI and the U.S. Attorney's Office in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 4, two days after Kyl's office received the letter,
Schubert was taken into custody by FBI agents from Kingman. In a
later plea agreement, prosecutors reported that a search of his
residence ``disclosed no evidence that Angelo Schubert intended to
follow through with his threat to Senator Kyl.''
</P>
<P>
   In imposing the sentence, which followed a plea agreement
between Schubert and prosecutors, U.S. District Judge Earl Carroll
allowed him to leave his residence ``for work and daily
necessities.'' Schubert was also ordered to perform 150 hours of
community service. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
