<HEADLINE>
TENNECO SAID TO HALT TALKS ON ITT UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tenneco Inc., a leading maker of car mufflers and shock
absorbers, has halted talks to buy the European brakes division of
ITT Industries Inc., a person close to the company said late
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Two other bidders, including the German tire maker Continental
AG and Ford Motor Co.'s Visteon Automotive Systems, are still
interested in the concern and may make an announcement sometime
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday afternoon, Tenneco's board met to discuss the
acquisition of ITT Automotive Europe, which is based in Frankfurt,
Germany. But after the meeting ended, ``the deal was dead,'' the
person close to the company said. Tenneco had been expected to make
an announcement early Tuesday that it was aquiring the division for
around $2 billion, this person said. Several people close to the
companies who were reached for comment expressed surprise that the
transaction was not completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no deal with ITT,'' Barbara Posner, the vice
president of communications for Tenneco, said last night. ``We are
not acquiring their brake and chassis unit as rumored.'' She
declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the companies had been in talks for more than a
month.
</P>
<P>
   ITT Industries, based in White Plains, N.Y., designs and
manufactures automobile products, including brake and chassis
systems and electronics for the military market. The European
automotive division has been on the auction block since March. It
is estimated that the division employs 16,700 people and has annual
sales of about $2.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, several companies were said to be interested in
buying all or part of the European operations, including Delphi
Automotive Systems, Visteon Automotive Systems, Siemens AG and
Tenneco. Several companies took plant tours to inspect the
operations then.
</P>
<P>
   The unit would have been a significant addition to Tenneco's
automotive line. Tenneco entered the auto parts business with the
acquisition of Walker Manufacturing, a muffler maker, in 1967. The
Tenneco Automotive division, which is based in Lake Forest, Ill.,
had 1997 sales of $3.2 billion. It not only sells mufflers, but
Monroe brand shock absorbers, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
