<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DUNNE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE DUNNE, PROMINENT JESUIT, DIES AT 92 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. George H. Dunne, a Jesuit priest who was an impassioned
critic of racial segregation and prominent in ecumenical efforts to
combat poverty and foster peace, died on June 3 in a hospital in
Los Gatos, Calif., outside San Jose, near the Jesuit retirement
community where he had been living. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne was also a student of Chinese theology and language, a
playwright and an author. But he was best known for his criticism
in the 1940s of racial segregation, particularly in Roman Catholic
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was basically a prophetic voice for social justice long
before his time,'' said the Rev. Paul Locatelli, president of Santa
Clara University, a Jesuit institution in Santa Clara, Calif. ``He
talked about racism back in the 1940s. He predicted in 1933 that if
we did not develop democratic leaders in China, it would fall to
the Communists within 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunne made that prediction after spending a year as a missionary
in China.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after receiving a doctorate in international relations in
1944 from the University of Chicago, he went to work at the
Institute of Social Order, a new program at St. Louis University,
another Jesuit institution, that was meant to respond to social
problems and increase Jesuits' awareness of them.
</P>
<P>
   But as things turned out, he was transferred to California after
strongly expressing his opposition to racial discrimination at the
university. In 1946, in an article published in the influential
Catholic lay magazine Commonweal, he branded segregation a sin. (He
was later called one of the first prominent Roman Catholics to have
done so.) In that article, he contended, among other things, that
segregation constituted a breach of justice.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier he had written a play, ``Trial by Fire,'' that
described the bombing of a black family that had moved into a Los
Angeles neighborhood restricted to whites. The play was performed
in 1947 and 1948 in Los Angeles and Chicago and at the Blackfriars
Theater in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne spent much time and energy combating prejudice: writing
articles, making speeches and taking part in numerous civil rights
demonstrations, including several led by the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther
King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Pope Paul VI and the Rev. Eugene Carson Blake, the
general secretary of the World Council of Churches, named him the
first director of the Committee on Society, Development and Peace,
an ecumenical group based in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne wrote later in ``The King's Pawn: The Memoirs of George
Dunne, S.J.'' (Loyola Press, 1990) that the committee's ``stated
purpose was to focus attention upon the problems of poverty,
especially in the third world, and upon the imperatives of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the churches,'' he added, ``it proposed to quicken the
consciences first of Christians, and then of all men and women, to
their moral responsibility to concern themselves with the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other members of the committee traveled widely and held
conferences in Lebanon, Japan, South Korea and elsewhere. At a
conference in 1968 in the mountains above Beirut, participants
blamed a lack of political will, among rich and poor nations alike,
for inadequate economic growth in most emerging nations.
</P>
<P>
   Pope Paul VI sent a special blessing to that gathering, and
messages from him and leaders of the World Council of Churches
emphasized the importance of joint Christian action in the sphere
of international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   After four years as director of the committee, Dunne retired
from the post. The panel expired not long afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne's chief literary work was ``Generation of Giants'' (1962),
about Matteo Ricci and other Jesuit missionaries who worked in
China during the Ming and Manchu dynasties. His view was that those
missionaries' lives had provided a lesson for the present day by
adapting Christianity and humanism to the culture of China and not
imposing Western ways on the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   A relative of the American humorist and journalist Finley Peter
Dunne and the author Dominick Dunne, Dunne was born in St. Louis,
grew up in Los Angeles and studied at various institutions,
receiving a bachelor's degree from Loyola College in Los Angeles
and a master's from Gonzaga University in Spokane, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, his activities included teaching at Loyola and
at Santa Clara and serving as the president's assistant for
international programs at Geogetown University.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne is survived by six nieces and two nephews.
</P>
</TEXT>
